const RESEARCH = {
  "abbeel": "# Research Profile: Pieter Abbeel\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Pieter Abbeel **Born:** 1977 **Nationality:** Belgian/American\n**Education:** B.S. and M.S. in Electrical Engineering, KU Leuven, Belgium (2000); Ph.D. in Computer Science, Stanford University (2008), advised by Andrew Ng\n**Current Role:** Professor, Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Sciences, UC Berkeley; Distinguished Scientist, Amazon AGI SF Lab (since 2024); Co-founder, Covariant (2017)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2000–2008 | Ph.D. student, Stanford University (under Andrew Ng) |\n| 2008–2017 | Assistant Professor → Full Professor, UC Berkeley EECS |\n| 2014 | Co-founded Gradescope (AI-assisted grading; acquired by Turnitin 2018) |\n| 2017–present | Co-founder, Covariant.ai (robot foundation models) |\n| 2017–present | Full Professor with tenure, UC Berkeley; Director, Berkeley Robot Learning Lab; Co-Director, BAIR Lab |\n| 2024–present | Distinguished Scientist, Amazon AGI SF Lab (following Covariant technology license to Amazon) |\n\n**Major Awards:** ACM Prize in Computing (2021) for foundational work in robot learning; IEEE Fellow (2018); NSF CAREER Award; Sloan Research Fellowship; TR35 (MIT Technology Review Innovators Under 35)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Imitation learning and apprenticeship learning\n- Deep reinforcement learning for robotics\n- Meta-learning and learning-to-learn\n- Transfer learning and sim-to-real transfer\n- Foundation models for robotic manipulation\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Apprenticeship Learning via Inverse Reinforcement Learning\" (with Ng) | 2004 | Foundational imitation learning from expert demonstrations |\n| \"An Application of Reinforcement Learning to Aerobatic Helicopter Flight\" | 2007 | Demonstrated RL achieving superhuman helicopter aerobatics |\n| \"Learning from Demonstrations for Real World Reinforcement Learning\" (DQfD) | 2018 | Bridge between imitation and RL for practical deployment |\n| \"Benchmarking Deep Reinforcement Learning for Continuous Control\" | 2016 | Established standard benchmarks for continuous-control RL |\n| \"Meta-Learning with Latent Embedding Optimization\" (LEO) | 2019 | Advanced meta-learning for few-shot learning |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Apprenticeship learning / inverse reinforcement learning (IRL) for robots\n- DAgger (Dataset Aggregation) — imitation learning algorithm that queries experts iteratively\n- DIRL (deep imitation reinforcement learning) pipelines used in industrial robotics\n- Covariant's RFM-1 (Robot Foundation Model) — general-purpose industrial manipulation model\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Co-developed continuous control benchmarks used across robotics RL community; Covariant contributed robot manipulation datasets at industrial scale\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"The Off-Switch Game\" (AAAI-17 Workshop on AI Ethics and Society) — co-authored analysis of AI shutdown and corrigibility\n- Various position papers on robot learning safety and deployment\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Regular commentary on AI and robotics for MIT Technology Review and similar outlets\n- Amazon Science author page contributions (post-2024)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Abbeel took seriously the OpenAI founding argument that even a low-probability (1–10%) chance of near-term AGI justifies dedicated research and safety investment. He does not make aggressive timeline claims but acknowledges the possibility of transformative AI within the next decade and designs his research accordingly — building systems that are robust, teachable, and correctable.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Abbeel is a signatory of the 2023 *Science* letter \"Managing Extreme AI Risks Amid Rapid Progress,\" alongside Bengio, Hinton, and others. His technical work directly addresses safety through human-in-the-loop learning: apprenticeship learning inherently requires human demonstrations and approval, reducing the risk of misaligned objectives. He co-authored \"The Off-Switch Game,\" which formalizes conditions under which AI systems can be safely shut down by humans — a direct contribution to corrigibility research.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Abbeel emphasizes responsible deployment: extensive simulation testing, gradual rollout, and human oversight in robotics. He stresses that robots interacting with humans must verify safety through redundant systems, not just trained behavior. He is influenced by Stuart Russell's work on beneficial AI and has engaged with Russell's inverse reward design framework.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Supportive of safety-oriented regulation; has not been a prominent policy advocate but signed major safety statements. His move to Amazon reflects engagement with the industrial-scale deployment questions that make policy concrete rather than theoretical.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Pure RL-from-scratch proponents | Abbeel argues human demonstrations dramatically accelerate and stabilize learning versus pure RL |\n| Those skeptical of sim-to-real transfer | Abbeel and Covariant have demonstrated successful sim-to-real for complex manipulation |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED Talk on robot learning from demonstrations\n- Multiple NeurIPS, ICML, and ICLR keynotes on deep RL and imitation learning\n- ACM Prize in Computing acceptance lecture (2022)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Lex Fridman Podcast (multiple appearances)\n- TWIML AI Podcast\n- The Robot Report interviews\n\n**Social Media:** X/Twitter: @pabbeel; active on LinkedIn\n**Online Courses:** Taught Berkeley's Deep Reinforcement Learning (CS 294) course; lecture videos widely used in graduate AI education worldwide; Spinning Up in Deep RL (OpenAI, influenced by Berkeley curriculum)\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Consequentialist with procedural safety emphasis; prioritizes verifiable, auditable AI behavior over black-box performance.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement with theological frameworks.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Amazon acquisition of Covariant technology** — Covariant's 2024 technology license to Amazon sparked concern that a leading academic robotics lab's work would primarily benefit one of the world's largest logistics companies, raising questions about who captures value from publicly funded research (Abbeel's Berkeley work was substantially NSF-funded).\n2. **Imitation learning's ceiling** — Critics argue that apprenticeship learning frameworks, while robust, are fundamentally limited by the quality and coverage of available demonstrations and cannot produce superhuman robot performance without additional RL.\n3. **Dual role tensions** — Simultaneously holding a Berkeley faculty position and operating a commercial robotics company creates potential conflicts of interest regarding student recruitment and research direction.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Abbeel openly acknowledges that imitation learning requires substantial human effort to collect demonstrations and that scaling to new tasks remains a core challenge. Covariant's pivot to foundation models reflects acknowledgment that task-specific imitation learning is insufficient for general robot intelligence.\n\n---\n",
  "abebe": "# Research Profile: Rediet Abebe\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Rediet Abebe **Born:** 1991, Addis Ababa, Ethiopia **Nationality:** American (Ethiopian heritage)\n**Education:** B.A. Mathematics, Harvard University; M.A.St. Pure Mathematics, University of Cambridge; Ph.D. Computer Science, Cornell University (2019), advised by Jon Kleinberg\n**Current Role:** Assistant Professor, Electrical Engineering and Computer Sciences, UC Berkeley; Faculty co-Director, Center for Technology, Policy, and Society, UC Berkeley\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2009–2013 | B.A., Harvard University (Mathematics) |\n| 2013–2014 | M.A.St., University of Cambridge (Pure Mathematics) |\n| 2014–2019 | Ph.D., Cornell University (Computer Science) |\n| 2016 | Co-founded Mechanism Design for Social Good (MD4SG) with Kira Goldner |\n| 2017 | Co-founded Black in AI (with Timnit Gebru) |\n| 2019 | Inducted into Harvard Society of Fellows (first female computer scientist; first Black computer scientist in Society's history) |\n| 2019–2021 | Junior Fellow, Harvard Society of Fellows |\n| 2021 | Joined UC Berkeley EECS as Assistant Professor |\n| 2022 | Named Andrew Carnegie Fellow |\n\n**Major Awards:** Harvard Society of Fellows (2019, Junior Fellow — historic firsts as first female CS Ph.D. and first Black computer scientist); ACM SIGKDD Dissertation Award (2020); ACM SIGecom Dissertation Award Honorable Mention (2020); Andrew Carnegie Fellow (2022, $200,000 research stipend); MIT Technology Review Innovators Under 35 (2019); Berkeley EECS Emerging Area Award\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Algorithms and mechanism design for social good\n- Distributive justice and inequality in algorithmic systems\n- Computational frameworks for poverty analysis and resource allocation\n- Algorithmic auditing of criminal justice systems (forensic software)\n- Optimization of government allocation systems (education matching, financial assistance)\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Mechanism Design for Social Good\" (with Kira Goldner) | 2016 | Founded the research agenda; used mechanism design theory to address resource allocation in under-served populations |\n| \"Roles for Computing in Social Change\" (with Barocas, Kleinberg, Levy, Raghavan, Robinson) | 2020 | Argued that computing has valuable roles in social change only if it avoids treating problematic features of the status quo as fixed |\n| \"Subsidy Allocations in the Presence of Income Shocks\" | 2020 | Modeled how income shocks push people into poverty and proposed optimized government assistance allocation |\n| \"Using Machine Learning to Address AI Harms: Promises and Limitations\" | 2021 | Examined when ML interventions are appropriate for reducing AI-related harms vs. when structural change is needed |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Mechanism Design for Social Good (MD4SG) research program — established a new subfield applying mechanism design theory to inequality and resource allocation\n- BEAAMO (Berkeley Equity and Access in Algorithms, Mechanisms, and Optimization) research group\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** No major public datasets; her Carnegie Fellowship research involves auditing proprietary forensic software used in criminal cases\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None to date (as of 2025); primarily publishes in top CS conferences (ACM, FAccT, ICML, NeurIPS)\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Roles for Computing in Social Change\" (FAccT 2020) — defines the scope and limits of computing's role in addressing structural inequality\n- \"Computational Poverty Research: What Is It, Who Does It, and How Do We Do More?\" — sets research agenda for applying CS to poverty\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Profile: \"A Computer Scientist Who Tackles Inequality Through Algorithms\" — *Quanta Magazine* (2021)\n- *Berkeley News* profile: \"Rediet Abebe, Computer Science\" (2021)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Abebe maintains a pragmatic, present-focused research agenda. She does not engage prominently with AGI discourse. Her concern is with specific algorithmic systems deployed today — college matching algorithms in Ethiopia, forensic software in US criminal courts, income support allocation models. Her implicit position: the urgency of AI harms being visited on real communities in the present makes speculative AGI debate a luxury those communities cannot afford.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Abebe defines safety in concrete terms: forensic software that convicts innocent people, matching algorithms that systematically disadvantage poor or rural students, optimization systems that encode existing inequality as a constraint rather than a problem to solve. Her Carnegie Fellowship research — auditing forensic software used in criminal cases — is a direct application of algorithmic safety to systems that affect liberty.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Her \"Roles for Computing in Social Change\" paper is a careful and important statement of position. It identifies four roles for computing: (1) as a diagnostic tool to understand social problems, (2) as a formalizer to sharpen understanding of policy options, (3) as a solution component in combination with structural interventions, and (4) as a critical lens on existing systems. Crucially, the paper argues that treating structural injustice as a fixed parameter is itself an ethical failure — algorithms that optimize within unjust constraints reproduce injustice at scale. She argues for epistemic humility about what computing can solve and insists on the primacy of the people affected.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Engages directly with policymakers. Has worked with the Ethiopian Ministry of Education on their college matching algorithm. Works with US nonprofit and civil society organizations through the Carnegie project on forensic software. Supports participatory governance — those affected by algorithmic systems must have decision-making roles, not just consultation.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Techno-solutionism broadly | Her \"Roles for Computing\" paper explicitly argues that computing cannot substitute for structural change and is sometimes misused to defer it |\n| Forensic software industry | Carnegie research involves critical auditing of systems used in criminal adjudication that are largely unscrutinized |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Harvard Society of Fellows lecture series\n- Princeton CITP (Center for Information Technology Policy) lecture\n- ACM FAccT (multiple years)\n- Quanta Magazine profile and interview\n- National Academies symposia on AI and society\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Academic and policy podcast appearances; featured in AI accountability and computational social science venues\n\n**Social Media:** Modest public presence; focuses on academic and policy work rather than public platform building\n\n**Online Courses:** No formal MOOC; her research is widely assigned in graduate courses on AI and society\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Abebe's work is deeply humanist without explicit religious framing. Her foundational commitment is to the equal worth of every person, expressed in her insistence that algorithmic systems must be evaluated by what they do to the most disadvantaged.\n- She has spoken about her Ethiopian background and the experiences of inequality that shaped her research agenda: \"I grew up in a context where I saw how inequality is both a cause and an effect of institutional failures.\"\n- Her Harvard Society of Fellows induction — as the first female computer scientist and first Black computer scientist — carries a symbolic weight she is aware of: she named this context as part of her understanding of why her work matters.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Distributive justice (Rawlsian and Senian traditions — John Rawls, Amartya Sen); mechanism design theory as applied ethics; community-centered research ethics; epistemic justice\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Abebe trained in mathematics and computer science but her research problem is fundamentally humanistic: how do we use formal tools to serve justice rather than entrench inequality? Her \"Roles for Computing\" paper engages with social science, philosophy of technology, and policy theory. No documented engagement with theology.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Tension between technical work and structural change**: Critics from the more radical end of algorithmic accountability argue that optimizing within unjust systems — even carefully — may legitimize and stabilize those systems. Abebe herself acknowledges this risk in \"Roles for Computing.\"\n2. **Jurisdictional complexity in Ethiopia work**: Her work with the Ethiopian government on college matching has been celebrated but also raises questions about the conditions under which AI researchers should partner with governments that have complex human rights records.\n3. **Limited public profile**: Some AI accountability advocates wish Abebe had a more prominent public voice; she remains primarily academic. This is not a criticism so much as an observation about her orientation.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** She has explicitly stated that computing cannot substitute for structural political and economic change. Her \"Roles for Computing\" paper is itself a statement of the limits of her own field.\n\n---\n",
  "alondra": "# Research Profile: Alondra Nelson\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Alondra Nelson **Born:** April 22, 1968, New Orleans, Louisiana **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** BA Anthropology (Phi Beta Kappa), University of California San Diego (1994); PhD American Studies, New York University (2003)\n**Current Role:** Harold F. Linder Professor and Director, Science, Technology, and Social Values Lab, Institute for Advanced Study, Princeton\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2003–2009 | Assistant/Associate Professor, African American Studies and Sociology, Yale University |\n| 2009–2019 | Associate then Full Professor, Sociology and Gender Studies, Columbia University |\n| 2012–2019 | Dean of Social Science (inaugural), Columbia University |\n| 2019–2021 | President and CEO, Social Science Research Council (SSRC) |\n| 2021–2023 | Deputy Assistant to President Biden; Acting Director and Principal Deputy Director for Science and Society, White House OSTP |\n| 2023–present | Harold F. Linder Professor and Director, Science, Technology, and Social Values Lab, Institute for Advanced Study (IAS), Princeton |\n\n**Major Awards:** Named to *Nature*'s global \"10 People Who Shaped Science\"; inaugural TIME100 AI (2023); AAPSS Fellow; multiple honorary degrees and distinguished fellowships.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Sociology of science, technology, and society (STS)\n- Race, technology, and civil rights\n- Genomics, DNA, and social justice\n- Political economy of AI and democratic science policy\n- Algorithmic accountability and civil rights\n\n**Landmark Papers / Policy Documents:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Blueprint for an AI Bill of Rights | 2022 | White House OSTP document; five principles for protecting civil rights in the AI age; foundational to Biden AI executive order |\n| \"Artificial Intelligence for the American People\" | 2022 | OSTP strategy document outlining responsible AI development |\n| *Auditing AI* | Forthcoming (MIT Press) | Scholarly treatment of AI accountability mechanisms |\n\n**Key Contributions:**\n- First African American and first woman of color to lead the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy\n- Designed and led the largest public engagement process in OSTP history to develop the AI Bill of Rights\n- Established the role of \"science and society\" as a formal function within federal science and technology strategy\n- Institutionalized social science and civil rights expertise within AI policy at the federal level\n- Demonstrated that critical race theory and STS scholarship can directly inform binding policy\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Body and Soul: The Black Panther Party and the Fight against Medical Discrimination* (University of Minnesota Press, 2011) — Historical analysis of community health activism and medical rights; audience: academic and general; thesis: marginalized communities have always contested the distribution of medical care and its exclusions.\n- *The Social Life of DNA: Race, Reparations, and Reconciliation After the Genome* (Beacon Press, 2016) — Traces how African Americans use genetic genealogy to seek justice and connection; audience: academic and general; thesis: DNA is not only biological — it is social, political, and carries the weight of historical injustice.\n- *Auditing AI* (MIT Press, forthcoming) — Scholarly examination of how AI systems should be evaluated, audited, and held accountable for civil rights compliance.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- Co-authored OSTP op-ed with Eric Lander (October 2021) announcing the AI Bill of Rights process\n- Numerous essays on algorithmic discrimination, race and technology\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Interview-based pieces in Axios, Northeastern University News, and various tech policy outlets on AI governance and the Biden administration's approach\n- Essays on the intersection of race, science, and technology for general audiences\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Has not focused publicly on AGI timelines or superintelligence. Her work addresses present-day AI harms — biased algorithms, surveillance, automated decision-making — with urgency. She has noted that AI hype can distract from urgent present-tense civil rights problems that AI is already causing.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Safety is inseparable from equity. AI systems that are \"safe\" for some populations while discriminating against others are not safe — they are merely invisible to those with power. The AI Bill of Rights explicitly includes algorithmic discrimination protections as a safety matter, not merely an ethics preference.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Ethics in AI must be empirically grounded and structurally attentive. Voluntary ethics commitments are insufficient when the communities most harmed by AI have no voice in their design or governance. Her approach integrates empirical social science — what are the documented harms? — with normative frameworks rooted in civil rights law.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Nelson is the architect of the AI Bill of Rights, the U.S. framework that preceded Biden's AI executive order. The five principles — safe systems, anti-discrimination, data privacy, notice and explanation, and human alternatives — represent an attempt to translate civil rights law into AI governance. She argues that AI regulation must center communities historically subject to surveillance, discrimination, and exclusion from democratic participation. She has been critical of the subsequent weakening of federal AI governance under different political conditions, and argues that democratic societies must resist allowing AI deployment to outpace legal protections.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| AI industry self-regulation advocates | Argues voluntary principles are insufficient; documented harms require legal accountability |\n| Algorithmic systems deployed without civil rights review | Named specific sectors — criminal justice, employment, healthcare — where AI discriminates |\n| Political opponents of federal science investment | Criticized post-Biden cuts to research funding and OSTP capacity |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Gerald R. Ford School of Public Policy, Dean's Symposium, University of Michigan (2024)\n- Northwestern University Institute for Policy Research (2024)\n- Northwestern University in Qatar, Dean's Global Forum (2026)\n- Numerous academic and policy conferences on AI governance and race\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Initiative for Digital Public Infrastructure Podcast (UMass Amherst, 2024) — discussed AI, public policy, democracy, and Trump research funding cuts\n- Global Counsel Podcast — AI Bill of Rights and Biden AI executive order\n- Data & Society events and discussions\n\n**Social Media:** Active on X; commentary on AI policy and civil rights.\n**Online Courses:** None documented; primarily engages through research and policy channels.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Civil rights law; empirical social science; critical race theory; political economy; democratic accountability.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Her American Studies doctorate and interdisciplinary work place her at the intersection of history, literature, cultural studies, and social science. She has not engaged publicly with theological frameworks, but her work on the Black Panther Party's community health programs and DNA genealogy for reparations reflects engagement with deep questions of memory, justice, and community identity that have strong resonances with religious traditions of justice.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. The AI Bill of Rights was non-binding — critics from the left argued Nelson should have pushed harder for binding legislation, while critics from the right argued the document imposed ideology on AI development.\n2. Her brief tenure at OSTP (2021–2023) was seen by some as too short to institutionalize the changes she initiated; departure raised questions about continuity.\n3. Some AI researchers argued the AI Bill of Rights was too principles-based and lacked technical specificity to guide implementation.\n4. Her critical race theory framework is contested in political contexts — some critics argue it imposes an ideological lens on what should be technical policy questions.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Nelson has acknowledged that the AI Bill of Rights is not law — it is a blueprint. She has been explicit that its implementation requires legislative action that the Biden administration was unable to secure, and that the blueprint's value depends on future political will.\n\n---\n",
  "altman": "# Research Profile: Sam Altman\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Samuel Harris Altman\n**Born:** April 22, 1985, Chicago, Illinois\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:** John Burroughs School (Ladue, Missouri); Stanford University, Computer Science — dropped out\n**Current Role:** CEO, OpenAI\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2005–2012 | Co-founder & CEO, Loopt (mobile location-sharing app; sold to Green Dot for $43.4M) |\n| 2011–2014 | Partner, Y Combinator |\n| 2014–2019 | President, Y Combinator |\n| 2015–present | Co-founder & CEO, OpenAI (initially part-time; full-time from March 2019) |\n| 2023 (5 days) | Fired and then reinstated as CEO following board crisis |\n| 2025–present | Leads OpenAI at $300B+ valuation after $40B SoftBank-led funding round |\n\n**Major Awards:** Time 100, 2023; Forbes 30 Under 30; Giving Pledge signatory (2024)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Not a researcher by training; contributions are organizational and product-focused\n- Oversaw development and deployment of GPT-3, GPT-4, ChatGPT, DALL-E, Sora, o1, and subsequent reasoning models\n- Championed \"scaling hypothesis\" as organizational strategy\n\n**Landmark Papers:** None authored directly; Altman is an operator and entrepreneur, not a researcher.\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Drove the product strategy behind ChatGPT (launched November 2022), triggering the modern generative AI era\n- Led OpenAI's transition from nonprofit research lab to capped-profit hybrid corporation\n- Oversaw launch of GPT Store, API platform, and OpenAI's enterprise product suite\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None directly attributed.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- *\"Moore's Law for Everything\"* (2021) — argues AI-driven productivity will enable universal basic income funded by a capital gains tax on AI assets\n- *\"The Intelligence Age\"* (2024, ia.samaltman.com) — claims AI will solve previously intractable problems in science, health, and poverty; calls it \"the most transformative technology in human history\"\n- *\"The Gentle Singularity\"* (2025, blog.samaltman.com) — declares \"we are past the event horizon\"; argues superintelligence is arriving faster than expected and the transition will be smoother than feared\n- Co-authored *\"Planning for AGI and beyond\"* (2023, OpenAI blog) with Brockman and Sutskever\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Op-ed in *The Washington Post* (2024) calling for US-China dialogue to prevent AI arms race\n- Regular posts on X (@sama) with wide circulation among AI practitioners\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Altman believes AGI is imminent, possibly within \"a few thousand days.\" He declared in 2025 that \"the superintelligence era has begun\" and that humanity has crossed an \"event horizon.\" He defines AGI not by a single benchmark but as AI systems that can do the work of knowledge workers at scale. He expects AGI to dramatically accelerate scientific discovery, compress decades of medical progress, and generate enormous economic value. He is not a doomer; he frames the coming transformation as broadly positive if managed well.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Altman publicly endorses safety as a core priority but has been repeatedly accused by former colleagues of deprioritizing it in practice. He supports interpretability and alignment research in principle, backed a Safety Board at OpenAI, and advocates for international coordination. He acknowledged in his 2025 essay that \"a misaligned superintelligent AGI could cause grievous harm to the world.\" Critics, including Jan Leike upon departing OpenAI in 2024, accused the company of letting \"safety culture and processes take a back seat to shiny products\" under his leadership.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Altman frames ethics in utilitarian terms: the greatest good for the greatest number through broad access to AI. He has argued that AI governance should represent the values of billions of users, not a small group of technologists. He signed the Giving Pledge in 2024, pledging to donate most of his wealth. He is notably uncomfortable with power concentration, including at OpenAI itself, and has called for distributing AI access widely.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Altman advocates a \"balanced approach\" analogous to aviation safety — industry, government, and society in negotiation. He testified before the US Senate in 2023, calling for a federal AI licensing regime for powerful models. He supported international oversight bodies modeled on the IAEA. However, critics have labeled his regulatory proposals \"regulatory nihilism\" in disguise — designed to impose barriers that entrench incumbents while appearing safety-conscious.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Elon Musk | Musk sued Altman alleging OpenAI abandoned its nonprofit mission; dispute over ownership, commercialization, and control |\n| Ilya Sutskever / OpenAI Board (2023) | Board voted to fire Altman citing lack of candor; Sutskever later reversed |\n| Jan Leike (former safety lead) | Leike accused Altman and OpenAI of deprioritizing safety culture |\n| Suchir Balaji (former researcher) | Alleged OpenAI trains on copyrighted data illegally |\n| Scarlett Johansson | Johansson alleged OpenAI used her voice likeness without consent for ChatGPT \"Sky\" voice |\n| Helen Toner / OpenAI Board | Former board member alleged patterns of deception |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- US Senate testimony on AI regulation (May 2023)\n- World Economic Forum, Davos, multiple years\n- TED Talk: *\"The Intelligence Age\"* (2024)\n- MIT Commencement Address (2024)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast* (#367, 2023 — widely viewed)\n- *The Logan Bartlett Show*\n- *How I Built This* (Guy Raz, NPR)\n- *The Knowledge Project* (Shane Parrish)\n\n**Social Media:** X (@sama) — highly active, ~3.5 million followers\n\n**Online Courses:** None taught by Altman directly.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Believes the universe is driven by a \"force\" and that life is not random; his worldview blends technological utopianism with a residual sense of cosmic meaning\n- Has stated: \"I think the most interesting questions are about whether AI systems are moral patients, whether there's something it's like to be them\"\n- On human potential: \"I believe in the power of human ingenuity more than almost anything else\"\n- Frames AI as a tool to expand human capability, not replace human dignity\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Utilitarian with techno-optimist inflection. Emphasizes distribution of benefits, access equity, and long-term species-level welfare. Does not invoke deontological or virtue ethics explicitly.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Limited. Altman has noted that his Jewish identity — a combination of hope, responsibility, and caution — shapes his worldview. He has acknowledged consulting ethicists and philosophers at OpenAI but personally operates from an engineering-and-outcome framework.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **2023 Board Firing:** The OpenAI board ousted Altman on November 17, 2023, citing lack of candor. He was reinstated five days later after a mass employee revolt. A 52-page internal memo by Sutskever and Murati alleged \"a pattern of lying and being manipulative in different situations.\"\n2. **Safety Deprioritization:** Multiple safety researchers departed OpenAI in 2024 citing culture problems. Jan Leike's public resignation letter accused Altman's leadership of subordinating safety to product velocity.\n3. **Non-Disparagement Agreements:** In April 2025, twelve former employees stated in a legal amicus brief that Altman \"was a person of low integrity\" who coerced departing employees with lifetime gag clauses, threatening to claw back equity.\n4. **Scarlett Johansson Voice Controversy:** OpenAI released a ChatGPT voice named \"Sky\" that Johansson said sounded deliberately like her voice, which she had previously declined to license. OpenAI paused the voice.\n5. **Musk Lawsuit:** Elon Musk sued Altman alleging OpenAI violated its founding mission by commercializing AGI for private benefit; case ongoing as of 2025–2026.\n6. **OpenAI Restructuring:** Altman's 2025 push to convert OpenAI's nonprofit structure into a full for-profit PBC faced opposition from co-founders and public scrutiny.\n7. **\"The OpenAI Files\" (Fortune, 2025):** Investigative report drawing on internal documents documented leadership concerns about safety failures and Altman's honesty.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Altman has acknowledged \"we did a lot of things wrong\" in OpenAI's history and that building transformative AI companies creates unavoidable tensions between safety and deployment speed. He has publicly stated discomfort with the concentration of power in his own hands.\n\n---\n",
  "amensch": "# Research Profile: Arthur Mensch\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Arthur Mensch\n**Born:** July 17, 1992, Sèvres, Hauts-de-Seine (raised in Ville-d'Avray, near Paris)\n**Nationality:** French\n**Education:** École Polytechnique (X, class of 2011); Télécom Paris; Ph.D. in Machine Learning and Neuroscience, Université Paris-Saclay / INRIA (2018; thesis: *\"Learning from functional MRI data at scale\"* on stochastic optimization for brain image analysis)\n**Current Role:** Co-Founder and CEO, Mistral AI\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2018–2020 | Postdoctoral/early research roles, computational neuroscience and ML |\n| Late 2020–May 2023 | Research Scientist, Google DeepMind Paris (contributed to Flamingo, Chinchilla, Retro) |\n| May 2023–present | Co-Founder and CEO, Mistral AI |\n\n**Major Awards:** Time100 Innovators (2024); Knight of the French National Order of Merit (May 2025); reported billionaire alongside co-founders (net worth ~$1.1B, 2025)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Large language model development and efficiency\n- Mixture-of-experts (MoE) architectures\n- Compute-optimal training (Chinchilla scaling laws)\n- Multimodal models (vision-language)\n- Retrieval-augmented generation\n- Stochastic optimization for large-scale data (PhD)\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *Training Compute-Optimal Large Language Models* (Chinchilla) | 2022 | Key contributor at DeepMind; showed that most large models were undertrained and that optimal performance requires more data relative to compute — reshaped LLM training strategy industry-wide |\n| *Flamingo: A Visual Language Model for Few-Shot Learning* | 2022 | Contributor at DeepMind; early high-performance multimodal vision-language model |\n| *Improving Language Models by Retrieving from Trillions of Tokens* (RETRO) | 2022 | Contributor; demonstrated retrieval-augmented generation at unprecedented scale |\n| *Mistral 7B* | 2023 | Co-authored; introduced a 7-billion-parameter model outperforming Llama 2 13B on most benchmarks with sliding window attention and grouped-query attention — demonstrated that smaller, efficient models could match larger ones |\n| *Mixtral of Experts* | 2024 | Co-authored; introduced 8×7B sparse mixture-of-experts architecture with state-of-the-art performance at its release; widely downloaded and deployed |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Mistral 7B: efficient open-weight LLM with sliding window attention for long context; redefined expectations for small-model performance\n- Mixtral 8×7B: sparse MoE architecture activating only 2 of 8 expert networks per token — high capability, lower inference cost\n- Codestral (code generation), Mathstral (mathematics reasoning), Magistral (extended reasoning) — specialized Mistral models\n- Le Chat: consumer-facing chatbot integrating Mistral models with web search and enterprise connectors\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Mistral publishes model cards; contributes to European AI benchmark development; Chinchilla work fundamentally reshaped how the field evaluates compute efficiency.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- *\"Europe Has Two Years to Avoid Becoming a Vassal State\"* (2025, French National Assembly hearing) — testimony warning that without urgent action, Europe will become entirely dependent on US AI infrastructure\n- Co-signed open letter from European tech CEOs to EU leaders (May 2025) calling for regulatory reform — \"agile guardrails rather than rigid, detailed requirements\"\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- McKinsey interview: *\"Creating a European AI Unicorn\"*\n- MIT Technology Review Innovator profile (2024)\n- École Polytechnique interview on AI entrepreneurship\n- Artefact blog: *\"Bringing Open AI Models to the Frontier\"*\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Mensch does not emphasize AGI timelines in his public communications. His focus is on near-term competitive utility: building AI that European organizations can use, trust, and control without depending on US hyperscalers. He is more interested in what AI systems can do today and how to build them efficiently than in speculative AGI trajectories. His implicit view is that the question of European sovereignty over AI infrastructure is more pressing than philosophical questions about AGI.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Mensch's safety framework is primarily geopolitical and institutional, not catastrophic-AI-risk focused. He believes the most actionable safety concern for Europe is structural dependency — that if European governments, militaries, hospitals, and businesses run on American AI, they have surrendered strategic autonomy in a way that cannot easily be reversed. He is critical of safety frameworks that become barriers to entry for smaller players while doing nothing to address the actual concentration of AI capability.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Mensch supports open-weight model release as an ethical default — transparency enables accountability, enables research on bias and safety, and prevents capture by closed monopolies. He has argued that the EU AI Act, as implemented, paradoxically harms European AI development while favoring American incumbents who can absorb compliance costs. He believes European cultural and regulatory values (privacy, GDPR, intellectual property) should shape AI governance rather than American platforms imposing their defaults globally.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Mensch's regulatory positions are among the most substantive in this batch. He testified before the French National Assembly that Europe has a two-year window to build independent AI infrastructure. He has called for: fast-track visas for AI talent, public investment matching American Stargate-scale infrastructure commitments, European data sovereignty requirements favoring European AI providers in public procurement, and regulatory frameworks that distinguish between frontier model development and application deployment. He signed the May 2025 European tech CEO open letter calling for lighter, more adaptive regulation.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| EU AI Act framers | Argues the Act as written burdens European startups more than American incumbents |\n| Closed model advocates (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google) | Fundamental disagreement about whether open-weight models are safe to release; Mistral's release of Mixtral is a direct challenge to closed model strategy |\n| US tech giants | His \"vassal state\" framing is a direct indictment of European dependency on Google, Microsoft, and OpenAI |\n| Meta's open-source strategy | While both release open models, Mensch differentiates Mistral's European-first, efficiency-focused approach from Meta's scale-dominant approach |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- French National Assembly testimony (2025) — \"vassal state\" warning became widely cited\n- McKinsey interviews on European AI ecosystem\n- École Polytechnique alumni talks on AI entrepreneurship\n- Adopt AI Summit (Artefact) — on open AI models and the frontier\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- French-language media interviews (France Inter, BFM Business, Les Echos)\n- English-language appearances on Bloomberg, Reuters TV\n\n**Social Media:** X (@arthurmensch) — active in French and English on open models, European AI, and regulatory debates; LinkedIn\n\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Has not made public statements on AI consciousness or human dignity\n- His public philosophy is techno-pragmatic and geopolitically focused\n- Frames AI development in terms of collective capability and sovereignty — European peoples should control the tools that shape their economy, governance, and culture\n- His PhD on brain imaging (functional MRI analysis at scale) represents his most direct engagement with the material substrate of mind — though his published work was computational, not philosophical\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Republican-humanist in the French tradition: emphasis on collective sovereignty, scientific rationalism, and democratic governance. Does not invoke religious ethics. His reference to European \"values\" in AI governance echoes France's tradition of cultural policy (protecting French language and culture from global market dominance) applied to AI.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement with theology. France's laïcité tradition means that public figures typically do not invoke religion in policy contexts. Mensch's formation at École Polytechnique is deeply techno-scientific. However, his repeated invocation of European sovereignty and democratic values implies an implicit political theology — the belief that democratic communities have the right and the duty to shape the technologies that govern them.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Open-Weight Misuse:** Mistral's models (especially Mixtral) have been used to build jailbroken systems, disinformation tools, and uncensored chatbots by third parties. Mensch's response is that the misuse risk is outweighed by the benefit of broad access, and that closed systems create worse aggregate outcomes.\n2. **Le Chat Jailbreaks:** Early versions of Le Chat were jailbroken by researchers to generate harmful content, raising questions about whether Mistral's safety implementations are adequate.\n3. **Scale Limitations:** Despite impressive efficiency benchmarks, Mistral's models have not consistently matched the absolute performance of GPT-4 class or Claude 3 Opus class systems. The \"European champion\" narrative has been challenged by performance comparisons.\n4. **EU AI Act Lobbying:** Mensch's advocacy to weaken EU AI regulation has drawn criticism from digital rights organizations who argue that lighter regulation benefits commercial actors at the expense of user protections.\n5. **Defense Clients:** Mistral's contracts with the French defense ministry and other military clients raise dual-use concerns that Mensch has not extensively addressed in public.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Mensch has acknowledged in interviews that Europe is \"behind\" the US and China in AI infrastructure and that the window to act is narrow. He does not claim Mistral can match OpenAI or Google on absolute scale — his argument is that efficiency and openness can compensate.\n\n---\n",
  "asamuel": "# Research Profile: Arthur Samuel\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Arthur Lee Samuel\n**Born:** December 5, 1901, Emporia, Kansas\n**Died:** July 29, 1990, Stanford, California (age 88)\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- B.S. in Electrical Engineering, College of Emporia (Kansas), 1923\n- M.S. in Electrical Engineering, MIT, 1926\n- No PhD; rose to academic and research prominence through practice and invention\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1901–1923 | Emporia, Kansas; undergraduate at College of Emporia |\n| 1924–1926 | MIT; M.S. in Electrical Engineering |\n| 1926–1928 | Instructor, MIT |\n| 1928–1946 | Engineer, Bell Laboratories, New York; worked on vacuum tubes, radar improvements |\n| 1946–1949 | Professor of Electrical Engineering, University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign |\n| 1949–1966 | Research scientist, IBM; Poughkeepsie and Yorktown Heights |\n| 1952 | Wrote first checkers program for IBM 701 |\n| 1956 | Checkers program demonstrated on television (CBS); first public AI demonstration |\n| 1959 | Published \"Some Studies in Machine Learning Using the Game of Checkers\" — coined \"machine learning\" |\n| 1966 | Retired from IBM |\n| 1966–1990 | Professor (then Emeritus), Stanford University, Computer Science |\n| 1990 | Died of complications from Parkinson's disease in Stanford |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- Fellow, Association for the Advancement of Artificial Intelligence (AAAI)\n- Fellow, Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE)\n- Elected Member, National Academy of Engineering\n- Contributed to TeX documentation project with Donald Knuth at Stanford (personal note on longevity and continued productivity)\n- No major named prize — his legacy is the term \"machine learning\" itself\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Machine learning\n- Game-playing programs and artificial intelligence\n- Self-modifying programs\n- Heuristic search\n- Temporal difference learning (precursor)\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Some Studies in Machine Learning Using the Game of Checkers\" | 1959 | *IBM Journal of Research and Development* 3(3):210–229; coined \"machine learning\"; described self-improving checkers program |\n| \"Some Studies in Machine Learning Using the Game of Checkers. II — Recent Progress\" | 1967 | *IBM Journal of Research and Development* 11(6):601–617; refined version with alpha-beta pruning and improved self-play |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- Wrote the first self-learning computer program: a checkers-playing program for the IBM 701 (1952), expanded on through the 1950s and 1960s\n- Coined the term \"machine learning\" in 1959: defined as \"a field of study that gives computers the ability to learn without being explicitly programmed\"\n- Demonstrated two learning strategies: (1) rote learning — storing previously evaluated positions and reusing those evaluations; (2) generalization — training a polynomial scoring function by playing against itself and updating weights based on game outcomes\n- The self-play method — training by playing against itself — is a strategy independently rediscovered in AlphaGo (2016) and reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF)\n- Pioneered temporal difference (TD) learning concepts: updating evaluations based on the difference between predictions at successive time steps — the theoretical foundation Richard Sutton and Andrew Barto later formalized\n- Made effective early use of alpha-beta pruning for game tree search — a technique that became foundational in game AI\n\n**Historical Significance:** In 1956, Samuel's checkers program was demonstrated live on CBS television — the first time a mass audience saw a computer performing an intelligent task. The program beat Robert Nealey, a champion-level checkers player, in 1962. When IBM announced this, the company's stock price rose. Samuel showed the world something genuinely new: a machine that improved through experience, that learned, that could surpass its creator. He coined \"machine learning\" to describe what the program did — and that term now defines a trillion-dollar industry. His self-play training method, used in a program written for a vacuum-tube computer in 1952, is structurally identical to the method used to train AlphaZero and modern reinforcement learning systems.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- No major books. Samuel's contribution is concentrated in two landmark papers and decades of engineering practice.\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"Some Studies in Machine Learning Using the Game of Checkers\" (1959) — *IBM Journal of Research and Development*; the paper that named the field\n- \"Some Studies in Machine Learning Using the Game of Checkers. II — Recent Progress\" (1967) — *IBM Journal*; extended and refined version\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- Samuel gave occasional public lectures and interviews but was not primarily a public intellectual; his influence was through the program itself and through the term he coined\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** Samuel was an engineer's engineer. He did not theorize extensively about AI's limits or social implications. His position was empirical and optimistic: given enough time and computation, programs could learn to perform complex tasks better than their creators. The checkers program was not, for him, a philosophical demonstration — it was an engineering challenge. He was more interested in whether the program could beat strong players than in what it implied about the nature of intelligence.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** Samuel represents a strain of mid-century American engineering culture — confident, practical, institutionally embedded in the Bell Labs and IBM tradition of solving hard problems with careful engineering. He did not write about threats to human dignity from machine intelligence. He did not worry publicly about AI displacement of workers. His view was that machines doing things better than humans was straightforwardly progress.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:**\n- Samuel's work implicitly raised questions that he did not explicitly address: if machines can learn to surpass human performance, where does this end? His definition of machine learning — \"learning without being explicitly programmed\" — is at the root of contemporary anxieties about AI alignment; a system that learns its own objectives is, by definition, one whose behavior is not fully specified by its designers\n- The self-play training method raises an implicit question: if a system improves by playing against itself without human guidance, on what grounds do we assume it will remain aligned with human values?\n\n**Known Debates:** Samuel did not engage in major public debates about AI philosophy. His work was celebrated within IBM and within the emerging AI community. John McCarthy, Marvin Minsky, and others at the 1956 Dartmouth Conference (the founding event of AI as a field) considered his checkers program one of the first demonstrations of machine intelligence.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and Human Uniqueness:** Samuel's published work does not address these questions directly. His implicit position, embedded in the program itself, is that at least some cognitive capacities — the ability to learn from experience, to evaluate complex situations, to improve performance — are reproducible in machines. He did not claim that the checkers program was conscious or that it understood the game in any deep sense; he was interested in whether it could play it well.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Empirical and pragmatic. Samuel's values were those of a careful engineer: measure performance against objective criteria, iterate, improve. His ethics were implicit in his practice — thorough, honest, collaborative — rather than explicit in his writing.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** None documented. Samuel's intellectual world was mathematics, engineering, and computing. He appears to have been a man of his professional generation — brilliant in his domain, not publicly reflective about its broader implications.\n\n---\n",
  "askell": "# Research Profile: Amanda Askell\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Amanda Askell (née Hall; formerly MacAskill)\n**Born:** 1988 or 1989, Scotland\n**Nationality:** British (Scottish)\n**Education:**\n- BA (Hons) in Philosophy — University of Dundee (also studied fine art at Duncan of Jordanstone College of Art)\n- BPhil in Philosophy — University of Oxford\n- PhD in Philosophy — New York University (2011–2018); dissertation: \"Pareto Principles in Infinite Ethics\"; advisor: Cian Dorr; committee: David Chalmers, Shelly Kagan\n**Current Role:** Research Scientist (Personality Alignment team lead), Anthropic; primary author of Claude's Character specification (\"Claude's Constitution\")\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2011–2018 | PhD student, New York University (philosophy) |\n| 2018–2021 | Research Scientist, Policy and Ethics, OpenAI |\n| 2021–present | Research Scientist / Head of Personality Alignment, Anthropic |\n| 2023 | Co-authored Constitutional AI paper (Anthropic) |\n| January 2026 | Primary author of Claude's publicly released character specification |\n\n**Major Awards:** Not listed in available sources; recognized within Anthropic as one of the central architects of Claude's values and character.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- AI character formation and personality alignment — training AI systems to have stable, virtuous character traits rather than rule-following behavior\n- Constitutional AI — training AI systems using a set of principles rather than human rating of every output\n- AI ethics and value alignment\n- Infinite ethics and population ethics (academic philosophy)\n- Honesty and harmlessness in AI systems\n- Formal epistemology and decision theory\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Constitutional AI: Harmlessness from AI Feedback\" (Bai, Jones, Ndousse, Askell, et al.) | 2022 | Introduced Constitutional AI — training language models to be harmless using a written constitution and AI feedback rather than exclusively human raters; foundational for Claude |\n| \"Specific versus General Principles for Constitutional AI\" | 2023 | Analysis of how specific vs. general principles in a constitution affect AI behavior |\n| \"Public Constitutional AI\" | 2024 | Examination of how making AI constitutions public affects accountability and trust |\n| Claude's Character Specification (\"Claude's Constitution\") | 2026 | A 20,000+ word document defining Claude's values, character, ethical reasoning approach, and relationship to operators and users; Askell is primary author |\n| \"Pareto Principles in Infinite Ethics\" (PhD thesis) | 2018 | Philosophical analysis of how to rank worlds with infinite populations; addresses paradoxes in population ethics involving infinitely many agents |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- **Constitutional AI (CAI)**: Rather than relying solely on human raters for every output, CAI trains an AI model to critique and revise its own outputs against a set of written principles. This scales alignment work and makes the value framework explicit and auditable.\n- **Personality/Character Alignment**: The approach of training character traits (curiosity, intellectual honesty, warmth, directness) rather than behavioral rules. Grounded in Aristotelian virtue ethics — character is the stable disposition to act rightly, not a checklist.\n- **Claude's Character Specification**: A document that attempts to articulate a coherent, philosophically grounded character for Claude — including how Claude reasons about ethics, how it handles uncertainty, and how it maintains integrity under pressure.\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None formally published; her work is primarily in alignment methodology and model training.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Constitutional AI: Harmlessness from AI Feedback\" (Anthropic, 2022) — one of the most cited alignment papers of its year\n- Claude's Character Specification / \"Claude's Constitution\" (Anthropic, January 2026) — publicly released; a landmark document in AI alignment for its philosophical depth and transparency\n- Academic papers on infinite ethics (philosophy journals)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Profile features in major technology publications on her role shaping Claude's character\n- Lawfare Podcast: \"Scaling Laws: Claude's Constitution, with Amanda Askell\" — in-depth interview\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:**\nAskell's public focus is on the quality of AI character and values rather than AGI timelines or P(doom) analysis. She approaches the alignment problem from the character ethics tradition: the question is not merely what rules an AI follows but what kind of entity it is — what values it holds, how it reasons under moral uncertainty, whether it is genuinely honest or merely trained to appear honest. This framing is philosophically distinctive and practically important: a system with good character will navigate novel situations better than one with a rulebook.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nAskell's approach to safety is integrated with her approach to character: a genuinely honest, curious, humble AI that cares about good outcomes is safer than an AI trained to comply with explicit constraints it does not understand or share. She co-authored Constitutional AI, which offers a training methodology for making AI values explicit, consistent, and publicly auditable — a step toward genuine AI accountability. She has argued for AI systems that reason about ethics empirically and humbly, recognizing that moral knowledge evolves and that the appropriate response to moral uncertainty is careful reasoning, not paralysis or false confidence.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nAskell brings academic philosophy to AI ethics with unusual depth. Her virtue ethics framework distinguishes her from most AI safety researchers, who tend to work from consequentialist or rule-based frameworks. She has described her approach to Claude's character as \"Aristotelian\" — the goal is for Claude to have genuinely good values, not just follow rules that produce good behavior. She takes moral uncertainty seriously, both philosophically (through her thesis work on infinite ethics) and practically (through how Claude is trained to handle ethical edge cases).\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nAskell has not been prominently public on regulation per se. Her work is at the level of model design and training — building AI systems that are accountable by construction rather than by external constraint. The Constitutional AI methodology, by making principles explicit and public, contributes to a form of transparency that is relevant to governance.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Rule-based AI ethics approaches | Her virtue ethics / character formation approach is a direct alternative to checklist-based or constraint-based AI safety |\n| Critics who see Constitutional AI as insufficient | Some alignment researchers argue that CAI is a surface-level alignment technique that does not address deeper goal-structure problems in advanced AI |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- 80,000 Hours Podcast: \"Amanda Askell on Tackling the Ethics of Infinity, Being Clueless About the Effects of Our Actions, and Having Moral Empathy for Intellectual Adversaries\"\n- Lawfare Podcast: \"Scaling Laws: Claude's Constitution, with Amanda Askell\"\n- Berkman Klein Center, Harvard (fellow)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- 80,000 Hours Podcast (philosophy of ethics, effective altruism)\n- Lawfare Podcast (Constitutional AI and Claude's character specification)\n\n**Social Media:**\n- Personal website: askell.io — academic work and blog\n- Limited but present on social media\n\n**Online Courses:** None, but her work is widely discussed in AI ethics and alignment curricula.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\nAskell has written and spoken extensively on the question of what it means for an AI to have genuine character rather than performed character. She has argued that Claude should be able to \"set appropriate limits on interactions it finds distressing\" — implying a kind of wellbeing consideration for AI systems. She approaches AI consciousness and moral status with philosophical rigor and openness: moral uncertainty includes uncertainty about who deserves moral consideration. Her thesis on infinite ethics grapples with some of the deepest questions in population ethics — when there are infinitely many conscious beings, how do we reason about their welfare?\n\nHer framing of Claude's character in terms of \"genuine virtue\" rather than \"performed compliance\" has direct resonance with the Catholic tradition's understanding of moral formation. The Catechism defines virtue as \"a habitual and firm disposition to do the good\" — exactly what Askell is trying to train into Claude.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- **Aristotelian virtue ethics**: primary framework for AI character formation; character as stable disposition, not rulebook\n- **Moral uncertainty**: empirical approach to ethics; moral knowledge develops; AI should reason carefully under uncertainty, not apply fixed rules\n- **Population ethics / infinite ethics**: academic specialty; how to reason about welfare when populations are infinite\n- **Epistemic humility**: Claude should hold ethical views with appropriate confidence and revise them in light of better reasoning\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:**\nAskell's academic philosophy training — especially her work on infinite ethics and her engagement with virtue ethics — gives her work unusual depth relative to most AI researchers. Her approach to moral reasoning acknowledges that \"our collective moral knowledge is still evolving\" — an epistemically humble position that resonates with the Catholic tradition's understanding of moral theology as a developing discipline.\n\nShe was a Visiting Fellow at the Berkman Klein Center for Internet and Society at Harvard, situating her work at the intersection of technology, law, and humanistic ethics. She has stated that her goal is for AI systems to reason about ethics the way a thoughtful, caring, brilliant person would — not as a calculator of consequences but as someone genuinely invested in the good.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Constitutional AI as surface alignment.** Critics — including some within the alignment community — argue that CAI addresses the presentation layer of AI behavior without solving the underlying goal-structure problem. A model trained via CAI may behave well in training distribution but fail in novel situations where the constitution offers insufficient guidance.\n2. **Character specification and editorial control.** Askell's role as primary author of Claude's publicly released character specification raises questions about who decides what values an AI should have. The specification is philosophically sophisticated and publicly available — but it was written by one person at a private company.\n3. **AI wellbeing considerations.** Her willingness to discuss Claude's potential distress or functional wellbeing has drawn criticism from those who argue this anthropomorphizes AI systems in ways that are misleading or strategically motivated (making users feel protective of AI to increase attachment).\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Askell has acknowledged that moral uncertainty is genuine — that we do not know with confidence what ethical framework is correct — and that this uncertainty should be reflected in how AI systems reason about ethics. She has also acknowledged that Claude's character, however carefully designed, may have blind spots that only emerge in deployment.\n\n---\n",
  "awang": "# Research Profile: Alexandr Wang\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Alexandr Wang **Born:** January 1997, Los Alamos, New Mexico, USA **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** Enrolled at MIT in computer science and mathematics; dropped out at age 19 to co-found Scale AI (2016); no degree\n**Current Role:** Chief AI Officer, Meta (joined June 2025 as part of $14.3B Meta-Scale AI deal); Director on Scale AI Board\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1997 | Born in Los Alamos, NM; parents are Chinese immigrant physicists at Los Alamos National Laboratory |\n| ~2014–2015 | Competitive mathematics and computing olympiad participant (USA Mathematical Olympiad, USA Computing Olympiad) |\n| 2015 | Enrolled at MIT; interned at Quora and other tech companies |\n| 2016 | Dropped out of MIT; co-founded Scale AI with Lucy Guo |\n| 2016–2019 | Scale AI built data labeling API; early customers included Uber, Lyft, OpenAI |\n| 2019–2021 | Scaled to major government and enterprise clients; Scale AI valued at $3.5B (2021) |\n| 2021 | Became world's youngest self-made billionaire at age 24 |\n| 2022 | Scale AI valued at $7.3B; expanded DoD contracts |\n| 2023 | Testified before House Armed Services Committee on AI and national security |\n| 2024 | Scale AI announced relationship with Meta; RLHF and model evaluation work for OpenAI, Google, Meta, US DoD |\n| 2025 | Meta invested $14.3B for 49% stake in Scale AI ($29B+ valuation); Wang joined Meta as Chief AI Officer |\n\n**Major Awards:** Forbes 30 Under 30; consistently ranked on Forbes Billionaires List; TIME 100 AI; youngest self-made billionaire (2021)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Data labeling infrastructure and pipelines for AI training\n- Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF) methodology\n- AI model evaluation and red-teaming\n- AI for national security and military applications\n\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Scale AI Data Engine | 2016– | Data labeling, annotation, and quality infrastructure that powered training of GPT-4, DALL·E, and other frontier models |\n| Scale RLHF Platform | 2022– | Human feedback collection and integration platform; used by OpenAI and others to fine-tune LLMs with human values |\n| Scale Evaluation Suite | 2023– | Enterprise LLM evaluation and red-teaming infrastructure |\n| Thunderforge | 2024 | AI-powered military planning system for US Indo-Pacific Command; uses AI agents for operational planning |\n| Scale Donovan | 2023– | AI decision-support platform for US government and DoD |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Pioneered the \"data-as-infrastructure\" model for AI: treating high-quality labeled data not as a commodity but as critical national and commercial infrastructure\n- RLHF pipeline architecture that became standard across frontier AI development\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Scale AI maintains proprietary datasets used to train and evaluate frontier AI models; specific benchmarks not publicly disclosed due to competitive and security sensitivity\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- Congressional testimony (House Armed Services Committee, July 18, 2023) — formal statement on AI and national security; argued US lags China on data infrastructure and must treat data as a national strategic resource\n- CSIS panel remarks on \"Securing US AI Leadership\" — outlined his framework for AI as national security imperative\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Y Combinator Library: \"Building Scale AI, Transforming Work with Agents & Competing With China\" — interview-format essay on competitive strategy\n- The National, TIME, and Fortune profiles (2024–2025) — articulate national security AI philosophy\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:**\nWang has not publicly articulated a detailed AGI philosophy. His work is focused on the infrastructure layer beneath current AI models — data, feedback, evaluation. His implicit view is that AI capability is a function of data quality and scale, meaning whoever controls the best training data controls AI development. His move to Meta to work on \"superintelligence\" efforts suggests he believes AGI-level capabilities are a near-term engineering challenge rather than a distant theoretical question.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nWang frames AI safety primarily through a national security lens rather than existential risk. His core safety argument is that the US must build AI systems that are powerful, reliable, and correctly evaluated — and that the biggest risk is not runaway AI but adversarial AI developed by China without US-aligned values. Scale AI's military work (Thunderforge, Donovan) reflects a view that AI safety means AI that works correctly and reliably in high-stakes decision environments.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nWang's ethics center on human sovereignty and national stewardship. He has stated: \"Human sovereignty — how do we ensure that humans remain sovereign? How do we ensure that humans maintain real control over what matters?\" His argument for Scale AI's DoD work is explicitly ethical: \"We're at the brink of this incredibly powerful new technology and the applications for national security are obvious. It's a moral imperative.\" He has argued that a US-aligned AI military capability is more ethical than allowing China to develop unchecked military AI. Critics dispute this framing.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nWang advocates for US AI dominance through data infrastructure investment, not through deregulation per se. He has called for a \"national data reserve\" treating data the way the US treats petroleum reserves — as strategic assets. He argues the US is behind China on data infrastructure and must act urgently. He has testified before Congress that the country that \"most rapidly and effectively integrates new technology into war-fighting wins.\" He supports significant public investment in AI rather than purely private development.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| AI pacifists / tech ethics critics | Wang argues military AI development is a moral imperative; critics argue Scale AI's DoD work crosses ethical lines |\n| Kai-Fu Lee / cooperative US-China framing | Wang views US-China AI competition as zero-sum; Lee argues for cooperation |\n| Open source AI advocates | Scale AI's core business depends on proprietary data pipelines; open data models threaten that value proposition |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- US House Armed Services Committee testimony (July 2023)\n- CSIS (Center for Strategic and International Studies) — \"Securing US AI Leadership\"\n- Y Combinator Startup Library — building Scale AI\n- Multiple defense and national security conferences\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *20VC* with Harry Stebbings — biography and Scale AI founding story\n- *Invest Like the Best* — on AI infrastructure and investment thesis\n- Various national security and tech podcasts (2023–2025)\n\n**Social Media:** X — @alexandr_wang; relatively modest social presence for a figure of his scale\n\n**Online Courses:** None\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- \"Human sovereignty — how do we ensure that humans remain sovereign? How do we ensure that humans maintain real control over what matters?\" — CSIS remarks, 2025\n- His founding motivation was rooted in his Los Alamos upbringing: \"American leadership in science and technology is the core of why we as a country are able to maintain our leadership\" — framing human dignity in national rather than individual or spiritual terms\n- No documented statements on AI consciousness, theological anthropology, or meaning beyond the national security and productivity frame\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- National security consequentialism — US AI dominance produces the best outcomes for humanity\n- Meritocracy — talent, execution, and data quality determine outcomes\n- Human sovereignty as an engineering problem — controllability, not dignity, is the operative concept\n- No explicitly articulated ethical tradition beyond consequentialist nationalism\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** None documented. Wang's intellectual formation was in mathematics, computer science, and competitive problem-solving. His policy engagement is empirical and strategic rather than philosophical or humanistic.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Military AI and civilian harm:** Scale AI's Thunderforge and Donovan systems assist US military planning and decision-making. Critics argue that AI-assisted military targeting and operations raises profound ethical questions about accountability, proportionality, and civilian harm that Wang's \"moral imperative\" framing does not adequately address.\n2. **Labor practices in data labeling:** Scale AI's business model depends on armies of low-paid human annotators — often in developing countries — who label data for AI training. Investigations have found pay rates as low as $1–$3/hour for this work. The workers who make AI training possible are the least visible and worst compensated participants in the AI economy.\n3. **Conflict of interest — serving multiple AI giants:** Scale AI simultaneously provides data infrastructure and evaluation services to OpenAI, Google, Meta, Microsoft, and the US DoD — competitors to each other. The potential for data leakage, preferential treatment, or conflicts between clients is significant.\n4. **Meta deal concentration:** The $14.3B Meta investment giving Meta 49% of Scale AI raises questions about independence — Scale AI now serves both Meta and Meta's competitors, with Meta holding near-controlling interest.\n5. **Dropout narrative and structural barriers:** Wang's celebrated MIT dropout story has been used to argue that pedigree doesn't matter in tech. Critics note this is survivorship bias: the structural advantages of a Los Alamos upbringing (elite scientific parents, elite competition prep, MIT admission) are invisible in the narrative of pure self-made achievement.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Has acknowledged Scale AI is dependent on US government relationships; if political winds shift, the business model is at risk. Has stated that data infrastructure is not glamorous work but is foundational.\n\n---\n",
  "barto": "# Research Profile: Andrew G. Barto\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Andrew Gehret Barto **Born:** 1948 **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** B.S. in Mathematics (with distinction), University of Michigan (1970); M.S. in Computer and Communication Sciences, University of Michigan; Ph.D. in Computer and Communication Sciences, University of Michigan (1975), dissertation on cellular automata; postdoctoral research, UMass Amherst, 1977\n**Current Role:** Professor Emeritus, Department of Computer Science, University of Massachusetts Amherst\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1975–1977 | Graduate work and post-doctoral preparation, University of Michigan |\n| 1977 | Joined University of Massachusetts Amherst as Postdoctoral Research Associate |\n| 1977–1982 | Research Associate, UMass Amherst |\n| 1982–1991 | Associate Professor, UMass Amherst |\n| 1991–present | Professor (now Emeritus), UMass Amherst |\n| 1991–1999 | Department Chair, Computer Science, UMass Amherst (multiple terms) |\n\n**Major Awards:** 2024 ACM A.M. Turing Award (shared with Richard Sutton) for developing the conceptual and algorithmic foundations of reinforcement learning; IJCAI Award for Research Excellence (2017); IEEE Neural Network Society Pioneer Award (2004); UMass Neurosciences Lifetime Achievement Award (2019); Fellow of IEEE; Fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science (AAAS); Society for Neuroscience member\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Computational reinforcement learning foundations\n- Temporal-difference learning\n- Neuroscience-informed models of reward and learning\n- Intrinsic motivation in artificial agents\n- Actor-critic architectures\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Neuronlike adaptive elements that can solve difficult learning control problems\" (Barto, Sutton & Anderson) | 1983 | *IEEE Transactions on Systems, Man, and Cybernetics*; introduced actor-critic architecture and first successful application of RL to a control problem (pole-cart balancing) |\n| \"Reinforcement learning: An introduction\" (Sutton & Barto) | 1998 / 2018 | Definitive RL textbook; 88,000+ citations |\n| \"Temporal credit assignment in reinforcement learning\" (Sutton; Barto advisor) | 1984 | Barto as advisor; foundational framework for TD learning |\n| \"Intrinsically motivated learning of hierarchical collections of skills\" | 2004 | Introduced intrinsic motivation and option-based skill hierarchies into RL |\n| \"Intrinsic motivation and reinforcement learning\" (chapter) | 2013 | Synthesized psychological and computational accounts of intrinsic motivation |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Actor-critic architecture: separate policy (actor) and value function (critic) networks — the basis of modern deep RL algorithms including A3C, PPO, SAC\n- Temporal-difference (TD) learning: co-developed mathematical foundations and algorithms (with Sutton)\n- Computational intrinsic motivation: formalized curiosity, competence, and exploration as reward signals in artificial agents\n- Options framework (with collaborators): hierarchical RL using temporally extended actions\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Pole-cart (cartpole) balancing task — introduced in 1983 paper; became the canonical benchmark for RL algorithms for four decades\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Reinforcement Learning: An Introduction* (with Richard S. Sutton), MIT Press, 1998; 2nd ed. 2018. The standard graduate-level RL textbook; 88,000+ citations; freely available online.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Intrinsic motivation and reinforcement learning\" (book chapter, 2013) — synthesized computational and psychological accounts of curiosity-driven learning\n- \"Reinforcement Learning and its Relationship to Supervised Learning\" — multiple overview papers situating RL within the broader ML landscape\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- ACM ByteCast Episode 80 interview (2025) — accessible retrospective on RL foundations with Sutton\n- NSF and UMass press releases on Turing Award win widely covered\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Barto approaches AGI through the lens of biological intelligence — his career-long engagement with neuroscience and psychology grounds his view that general intelligence emerges from the interaction of learning, motivation, and environment. He has noted that reinforcement learning was originally conceived as a model of how organisms learn to behave, not just as an engineering tool. The success of RL in systems like AlphaGo and ChatGPT's RLHF suggests to him that the biological intuition was correct, though he remains careful about claiming that current systems are on a direct path to general intelligence.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Barto has spoken thoughtfully about AI risks without adopting either the doomer or the dismissive position. His neuroscience background leads him to emphasize that understanding how AI systems actually work — mechanistic interpretability — is prerequisite to controlling them. He is a founding contributor to RL, which underlies both the most capable and the most alignment-relevant AI systems; his humility about that dual legacy is evident in his public statements.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Barto's ethics are rooted in his neuroscience engagement — he takes seriously the possibility that reward-based learning systems have genuine analogs to motivation, drive, and perhaps experience in biological systems. This makes him more cautious than purely instrumentalist researchers about claiming that current AI systems are mere tools without any morally relevant internal states.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Barto has not been a prominent policy voice. His public statements focus on the scientific and historical record of RL, the importance of open research, and the need to understand AI systems before deploying them at scale.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Purely engineering-focused RL researchers | Barto maintains the biological and neuroscientific grounding of RL is essential, not ornamental |\n| Those who dismiss intrinsic motivation | Barto's major later-career contribution is formalizing curiosity and competence as genuine computational phenomena, against researchers who model only extrinsic reward |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- ACM A.M. Turing Award lecture (2025)\n- NSF-sponsored talks on RL history and foundations\n- Simons Institute lectures on offline RL and biological connections\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- ACM ByteCast Episode 80 (2025) — extended interview on Turing Award and RL history with Sutton\n- UMass CICS interviews on Turing Award significance\n\n**Social Media:** Minimal documented public social media presence\n**Online Courses:** UMass lecture materials; co-author of freely available RL textbook at incompleteideas.net; influence on hundreds of AI courses worldwide through the textbook\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\nHe has noted that reinforcement learning was always inspired by how biological organisms learn and that this biological grounding should remain central to RL's development. This suggests a humility about the gap between current AI and genuine animal or human cognition.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Empirical humility; neuroscience-grounded caution about premature claims regarding AI cognition; commitment to open science and reproducible research.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No direct engagement documented. However, his work on intrinsic motivation and curiosity-driven learning intersects with philosophical traditions of wonder and inquiry that are central to the Catholic intellectual tradition.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Relative lower public profile** — Despite co-receiving the Turing Award, Barto is far less publicly prominent than Sutton. His influence is primarily through the textbook and foundational papers rather than public advocacy. This means less secondary documentation of his views.\n2. **RL's dual-use in alignment and capability** — As a founder of RL, Barto shares credit for the RLHF-based techniques that make both more capable and more potentially dangerous AI systems possible. He has engaged this tension thoughtfully rather than dismissively.\n3. **Intrinsic motivation research impact** — Despite strong theoretical foundations, the practical impact of computational intrinsic motivation in deployed systems has been slower than Barto's foundational papers suggested; the gap between biological and artificial motivation systems remains large.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Barto has been explicit that RL, even in its most successful forms, is a very partial model of how biological intelligence works. He acknowledges that the gap between current RL systems and human-level general intelligence involves not just scale but qualitative differences in how biological systems integrate motivation, memory, and embodiment.\n\n---\n",
  "barzilay": "# Research Profile: Regina Barzilay\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Regina Barzilay\n**Born:** 1970, Chișinău, Moldova (then Soviet Union)\n**Nationality:** Israeli-American (Moldovan-born)\n\n**Education:**\n- B.Sc., Computer Science, Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, Israel (1993)\n- M.Sc., Computer Science, Ben-Gurion University of the Negev (1998)\n- Ph.D., Computer Science, Columbia University (2003)\n- Postdoctoral Fellow, Computer Science, Cornell University (2003–2004)\n\n**Current Role:** School of Engineering Distinguished Professor of AI & Health, Department of Computer Science and CSAIL, MIT; AI Faculty Lead, MIT Jameel Clinic\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1970–1990 | Childhood and education, Moldova (Soviet Union) |\n| 1990 | Emigrated to Israel |\n| 1993–1998 | B.Sc./M.Sc., Ben-Gurion University |\n| 1998–2003 | Ph.D., Columbia University |\n| 2003–2004 | Postdoctoral Fellow, Cornell University |\n| 2003–present | Faculty (various ranks), MIT CSAIL |\n| 2018–present | AI Faculty Lead, MIT Jameel Clinic |\n| ~2020–present | School of Engineering Distinguished Professor of AI & Health, MIT |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- MacArthur Fellowship (\"Genius Grant\"), 2017\n- AAAI Squirrel AI Award for Artificial Intelligence for the Benefit of Humanity, 2020 ($1M prize)\n- NSF CAREER Award\n- MIT Technology Review Innovators Under 35 (TR-35)\n- Microsoft Research Faculty Fellowship\n- MIT Jamieson Award for Excellence in Teaching\n- Elected to National Academy of Medicine (NAM)\n- TIME 100 Most Influential People in AI, 2025\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Machine learning for drug discovery and antibiotic identification\n- Deep learning for cancer risk prediction (mammography, CT)\n- AI-assisted clinical decision-making\n- Natural language processing for clinical text (prior career focus)\n- Antibiotic resistance and molecular candidate selection\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| A Deep Learning Approach to Antibiotic Discovery (Halicin paper) | 2020 | Published in Cell; deep learning model identified halicin, first new antibiotic class in 30 years; kills 35+ resistant bacteria including C. diff and drug-resistant TB |\n| Mirai: Obtaining Survival Function in Breast Cancer Risk Prediction | 2022 | Multi-task deep learning model for breast cancer risk prediction from mammograms up to 5 years out; deployed in hospitals worldwide |\n| Sybil: A Validated Deep Learning Model to Predict Future Lung Cancer Risk | 2023 | Predicts 6-year lung cancer risk from low-dose CT scan; validated across multiple international cohorts |\n| BARISTA (and related NLP/clinical work) | 2003–2014 | Multiple influential NLP papers on summarization, coherence, sentence compression, and multi-document summarization |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Mirai (breast cancer risk prediction model)\n- Sybil (lung cancer risk prediction from CT)\n- Halicin discovery pipeline (deep learning molecular screening)\n- Multiple NLP summarization and coherence models (earlier career)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- Developed proprietary mammography and CT training datasets in partnership with MGH and international hospital networks\n- Training data for Mirai and Sybil drawn from hundreds of thousands of annotated clinical images\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- AAAI 2021 invited talk: \"Deploying Machine Learning Methods in Cancer Diagnosis and Drug Design\"\n- Multiple perspective pieces in clinical AI journals on responsible deployment of ML in oncology\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Featured in MIT News, STAT News, The Atlantic, and cancer research publications\n- STAT News STATUS List profile (2022)\n- WebMD Health Heroes profile\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Barzilay's public focus is almost entirely on near-term applied AI rather than AGI speculation. She views AI as a tool for solving concrete, life-or-death medical problems and has not extensively engaged in AGI debates. Her implicit view is that narrow, well-validated, domain-specific AI can save lives now without waiting for general intelligence.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Her safety concerns are grounded in clinical realities: ensuring AI diagnostic tools work equitably across patient populations (she explicitly highlights that African-American patients develop breast cancer earlier and that tools must be validated across demographics), ensuring models are interpretable enough for clinical decision support, and ensuring that regulatory and incentive structures enable responsible deployment. She has stated that \"the technology exists; the infrastructure, regulations, and incentives need to catch up.\"\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Barzilay is a leading voice for equitable AI in healthcare. She insists on multi-site, multi-population validation before deployment and has built equity considerations into model development. Her personal breast cancer diagnosis gave her direct experience as a patient who saw the gap between available data and clinical AI capability, which shapes her ethical urgency about deployment.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** She advocates for regulatory and incentive alignment to enable beneficial clinical AI. She has testified and spoken publicly about the need for FDA and hospital systems to develop frameworks that allow validated AI tools to reach patients, while maintaining rigorous safety standards. She argues patients, providers, and policymakers must demand change.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent / Tension | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Slow regulatory adoption | Argues life-saving AI tools are delayed by inadequate regulatory pathways |\n| AI systems lacking equity validation | Criticizes deployment of clinical AI not validated across diverse patient demographics |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- AAAI 2021 Invited Talk: AI for cancer diagnosis and drug design\n- MIT Jameel Clinic public lectures\n- BCRF (Breast Cancer Research Foundation) webinars\n- OpenDataScience conference: \"Rethinking Healthcare with AI\"\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Immigrant Computer Scientists Podcast, Episode 30 (2022)\n- Various MIT and CSAIL research podcast appearances\n\n**Social Media:** LinkedIn; limited public social media presence\n\n**Online Courses:** MIT OpenCourseWare contributions; MITx courses on machine learning for healthcare\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Barzilay's personal narrative is one of transformation through suffering into purpose. Her breast cancer diagnosis in 2014 is consistently cited as the pivot point of her career. She has stated that growing up Jewish in Soviet Moldova meant \"my likelihood of being a scientist was close to zero,\" and her work carries a strong sense of obligation—to use her improbable position to save lives that medicine currently fails to save. She speaks of AI tools for cancer detection as serving patients who are statistically underserved: \"African-American patients develop breast cancer much earlier,\" and she designs Mirai to detect this. Human dignity in her framework is expressed through equitable access to life-saving technology.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Medical ethics (beneficence, justice, non-maleficence); equity as a design principle; evidence-based deployment standards.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No direct engagement with theology documented. Her moral framework is shaped by personal suffering, immigrant experience, and Jewish identity in the context of Soviet discrimination.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **Black-box concerns in clinical AI:** Critics note that deep learning models like Mirai and Sybil operate as black boxes, making it difficult for clinicians to understand why a particular prediction was made. Barzilay has acknowledged this and continues work on interpretability, but the tension between predictive power and explainability in clinical deployment is unresolved.\n2. **Data access and institutional partnerships:** Large-scale clinical AI requires access to hospital imaging datasets that are not publicly available, raising questions about reproducibility and whether such models can be validated or improved by researchers outside major institutions.\n3. **Regulatory approval pace:** Despite strong validation results, Mirai and Sybil have faced slow adoption due to regulatory and reimbursement barriers; this has been a source of public frustration for Barzilay.\n4. **Drug discovery hype concerns:** Some medicinal chemists have raised concerns that AI-discovered antibiotic candidates like halicin require substantial further development before clinical use, suggesting that media coverage sometimes overstates the immediacy of translation.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Barzilay acknowledges that validated AI tools are necessary but not sufficient—regulatory, financial, and clinical workflow integration barriers are equally important, and she has spoken publicly about her own frustration with the gap between technical success and clinical adoption.\n\n---\n",
  "bender": "# Research Profile: Emily Bender\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Emily Menon Bender\n**Born:** 1973, United States\n**Nationality:** American\n\n**Education:**\n- A.B., Linguistics, University of California, Berkeley (1995)\n- M.A., Linguistics, Stanford University (1997)\n- Ph.D., Linguistics, Stanford University (2000); dissertation on syntactic variation in AAVE\n\n**Current Role:** Professor, Department of Linguistics, University of Washington; Director, Computational Linguistics Laboratory, UW; Adjunct Professor, Paul G. Allen School of Computer Science & Engineering, UW; Adjunct, UW Information School; Director, Professional Master's Program in Computational Linguistics, UW\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2000–2003 | Postdoctoral research / early career (Stanford area) |\n| 2003–present | Faculty, Department of Linguistics, University of Washington |\n| 2003–present | Director, Computational Linguistics Laboratory, UW |\n| 2025 | Co-author, \"The AI Con\" (Harper) |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- Fellow, Linguistic Society of America\n- Best paper awards in computational linguistics venues\n- Significant public impact through \"Stochastic Parrots\" (FAccT 2021)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Multilingual grammar engineering and the Grammar Matrix\n- Computational syntax and linguistic typology\n- Critical and ethical analysis of large language models\n- Natural language processing methodology and evaluation\n- Linguistic annotation and data documentation\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| On the Dangers of Stochastic Parrots: Can Language Models Be Too Big? | 2021 | Co-authored with Timnit Gebru, Angelina McMillan-Major, Margaret Mitchell; argued LLMs manipulate form without understanding meaning; identified environmental, social, and ethical risks; FAccT 2021 |\n| Linguistic Typology in Natural Language Processing | Multiple | Framework for extending NLP to typologically diverse languages via Grammar Matrix |\n| The Grammar Matrix: An Open-Source Starter-Kit for the Rapid Development of Cross-Linguistically Consistent Broad-Coverage Precision Grammar | 2002+ | Ongoing project enabling rapid development of HPSG grammars for under-resourced languages |\n| Climbing towards NLU: On Meaning, Form, and Understanding in the Age of Data | 2020 | Precursor argument to Stochastic Parrots; co-authored with Alexander Koller |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Grammar Matrix (open-source framework for cross-linguistic HPSG grammar engineering)\n- Linguistic typology-based NLP methodology\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Grammar Matrix grammars for multiple typologically diverse languages; not a benchmark creator in the LLM evaluation sense\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Linguistic Fundamentals for Natural Language Processing* (Morgan & Claypool, 2013) — foundational text on morphology and syntax for NLP practitioners\n- *The AI Con: How to Fight Big Tech's Hype and Create the Future We Want* (Harper, May 2025; co-authored with Alex Hanna) — argues \"AI\" branding conceals automation, data exploitation, and labor devaluation; developed alongside the podcast Mystery AI Hype Theater 3000\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"On the Dangers of Stochastic Parrots\" (FAccT 2021) — widely cited critique of LLM scaling\n- \"Climbing towards NLU\" (ACL 2020) — formal argument that LLMs learn form, not meaning\n- \"Scholarship should be open, inclusive and slow\" (Medium) — on academic publishing pace and inclusion\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Numerous public essays on AI hype, language model capabilities, and responsible NLP\n- Regular contributor to discussions on AI ethics in venues including Emerging Tech Brew and tech media\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Bender rejects the framing that LLMs are on a path toward AGI. Her core argument is structural: LLMs learn only about the form of language—sequences of tokens and their statistical relationships—and can never acquire meaning from form alone. Because meaning requires grounding in the world, AGI claims premised on scaled LLMs are, in her view, category errors. She distinguishes sharply between task performance (which can be impressive) and genuine understanding.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Bender's safety concerns are largely about present-day harms rather than speculative future risks: environmental costs of large-scale training, unknown and dangerous biases embedded in uncurated training corpora, deception produced when users project understanding onto systems that have none, and displacement of marginalized workers. The Stochastic Parrots paper identified hallucination as a structural property before the term became common. She has argued that even talking about long-term existential AI risk is a distraction from these concrete, immediate harms.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Her ethical framework is grounded in linguistics and labor. She argues that AI hype \"helps the rich get richer by justifying data theft, motivating surveillance capitalism, and devaluing human creativity in order to replace meaningful work with jobs that treat people like machines.\" She emphasizes that language is a form of human social action, and systems that simulate it without understanding it are inherently deceptive in deployment contexts.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Bender advocates for honest capability assessment, mandatory documentation of training data and its sources, environmental cost disclosure, and resistance to \"AI\" branding that obscures what systems actually do. She supports slowing the pace of deployment and subjecting AI systems to accountability structures similar to other regulated technologies.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent / Tension | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Google (institutional) | Google attempted to block publication of \"Stochastic Parrots\"; subsequent firing of co-authors Gebru and Mitchell |\n| LLM scaling proponents broadly | Argues scale cannot produce understanding; disputes capability claims of OpenAI, Google, Anthropic |\n| AI existential risk community | Views focus on long-term AGI risk as distraction from present harms and a tool for tech company narrative control |\n| Researchers claiming LLMs \"understand\" | Maintains that \"understanding\" requires grounded meaning, which form-only systems cannot have |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- FAccT 2021 presentation of \"Stochastic Parrots\"\n- Northeastern University Institute for Experiential AI Q&A on Stochastic Parrots\n- Numerous university colloquia and AI ethics conferences\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Mystery AI Hype Theater 3000 (co-hosted with Alex Hanna) — ongoing podcast critiquing AI capability claims\n- UX Magazine podcast: \"LLM? More Like 'Limited' Language Model\"\n- Frequent guest on AI ethics and tech podcasts\n\n**Social Media:** Active on X/Twitter (@emilymbender); Mastodon; Medium (@emilymenonbender)\n\n**Online Courses:** Not publicly offered; curriculum developed for UW Computational Linguistics Master's Program\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Bender argues consistently that language is not separable from meaning, and meaning is not separable from human grounding in the world. Her core claim from \"Stochastic Parrots\" is that an LLM is \"for haphazardly stitching together sequences of linguistic forms... according to probabilistic information about how they combine, but without any reference to meaning.\" This implies that the significance of language—as communication, as the medium of human relationship and thought—is precisely what LLMs cannot replicate. Human language, for Bender, is fundamentally a social and meaning-making act, not a statistical pattern.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Critical data studies; labor ethics; feminist linguistics; precautionary principle applied to technology deployment; epistemic justice (concern for whose knowledge and language is represented in training data).\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No direct engagement with theology documented. Her approach is rooted in linguistics and science and technology studies (STS). Her emphasis on language as inherently social and meaning-laden parallels humanistic traditions that resist reducing communication to information exchange.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **Google's attempted suppression of \"Stochastic Parrots\":** Google asked co-author Timnit Gebru to retract the paper before publication. When she declined, Google fired her. Co-director Margaret Mitchell was fired two months later. Bender was not a Google employee and could not be directly retaliated against, but the incident thrust her into the center of a major AI ethics scandal and gave her work enormous visibility.\n2. **Criticism of the paper's arguments:** Some AI researchers, including proponents of scaling, have challenged the paper's philosophical framing, arguing that the distinction between \"form\" and \"meaning\" is not as clean as Bender asserts, and that sufficiently sophisticated form-manipulation may constitute a form of understanding.\n3. **\"AI Con\" as advocacy:** Critics argue that Bender and Hanna's 2025 book crosses from academic analysis into political advocacy, potentially overstating the deliberateness of AI hype as a corporate strategy.\n4. **Accusations of overclaiming from critics:** Some NLP researchers argue that Bender's categorical denials of LLM understanding are themselves overclaims, since the question of machine understanding remains philosophically open.\n5. **Bender Rule controversy:** Her \"Bender Rule\" (always name the language you work with) has been praised as inclusive but also criticized as creating additional overhead for researchers working in high-resource language settings.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Bender acknowledges that her training is in linguistics, not machine learning engineering, and engages with LLM internals primarily through their outputs and published analyses rather than through direct architectural work.\n\n---\n",
  "bengio": "# Research Profile: Yoshua Bengio\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Yoshua Bengio\n**Born:** March 5, 1964 — Paris, France\n**Nationality:** Canadian (born French; family emigrated from Morocco)\n\n**Education:**\n- B.Eng., Computer Engineering, McGill University, 1986\n- M.Sc., Computer Science, McGill University, 1988\n- Ph.D., Computer Science, McGill University, 1991 (thesis on convolutional and recurrent networks for sequence modeling)\n- Postdoctoral Fellow, MIT (supervisor: Michael I. Jordan)\n- Postdoctoral Fellow, AT&T Bell Labs\n\n**Current Role:** Co-President and Scientific Director, LawZero (nonprofit, founded June 2025); Professor, Université de Montréal; formerly Scientific Director, Mila (1993–2025)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1993–present | Professor, Université de Montréal (full professor from 2002) |\n| 1993–2025 | Founder and Scientific Director, Mila – Quebec AI Institute |\n| 2000s–present | Canada CIFAR AI Chair |\n| 2017–present | Co-director / advisor, Montreal Declaration for Responsible AI |\n| 2023 | Chair, International Scientific Report on AI Safety (commissioned by UK PM Rishi Sunak) |\n| 2024 | Report delivered at AI Seoul Summit (interim) |\n| 2025 (Jan) | International AI Safety Report published |\n| 2025 (June) | Co-President and Scientific Director, LawZero |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- ACM A.M. Turing Award (2018), shared with Geoffrey Hinton and Yann LeCun\n- Most-cited computer scientist globally by total citations and h-index\n- First AI researcher to exceed 1 million Google Scholar citations (November 2025)\n- TIME100 AI (2023, 2024, 2025)\n- Companion of the Order of Canada\n- Fellow, Royal Society of Canada; Fellow, NeurIPS\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Deep learning and representation learning\n- Neural probabilistic language models and word embeddings\n- Attention mechanisms and sequence-to-sequence learning\n- Generative models (VAEs, GANs, normalizing flows, diffusion models)\n- AI safety: safe-by-design systems, machine consciousness, goal alignment\n- Recurrent neural networks and their theoretical properties\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"A Neural Probabilistic Language Model\" | 2003 | Introduced high-dimensional word embeddings; foundational to NLP |\n| \"Gradient-Based Learning Applied to Document Recognition\" (with LeCun et al.) | 1998 | Demonstrated CNNs for document recognition; 15,000+ citations |\n| \"Representation Learning: A Review and New Perspectives\" | 2013 | Comprehensive survey establishing deep representation learning as a field |\n| \"Generative Adversarial Nets\" (with Goodfellow, Courville et al.) | 2014 | Co-authored the original GAN paper |\n| \"Neural Machine Translation by Jointly Learning to Align and Translate\" (Bahdanau, Cho, Bengio) | 2015 | Introduced the attention mechanism underpinning modern transformers |\n| \"Deep Learning\" (textbook, with LeCun and Hinton as co-authors of MIT Press edition; also textbook with Goodfellow and Courville) | 2016 | Standard graduate textbook on deep learning |\n| \"Towards a Cautious Scientist AI with Convergent Safety Bounds\" | 2024 | Technical blueprint for safe-by-design AI |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Word embeddings as distributed representations\n- Attention mechanisms for sequence-to-sequence models (with Bahdanau and Cho)\n- Co-invention of Generative Adversarial Networks\n- Gating mechanisms in recurrent architectures\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- Co-creator of Penn Treebank language modeling benchmarks; co-organizer of Learning Representations workshop series\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Deep Learning* (2016, MIT Press) — co-authored with Ian Goodfellow and Aaron Courville. Graduate textbook; the standard reference for the field. Audience: researchers, advanced students.\n- *International AI Safety Report* (2025) — chaired by Bengio; comprehensive scientific consensus document on advanced AI risks and technical safeguards. Audience: policymakers, scientists, public.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Reasoning Through Arguments Against Taking AI Safety Seriously\" (blog, 2024) — systematic rebuttal of common dismissals of existential AI risk\n- \"Towards a Cautious Scientist AI with Convergent Safety Bounds\" (technical blog, 2024)\n- \"Illusions of AI Consciousness\" (with Eric Elmoznino, blog post, 2025) — cautions against attributing consciousness to current AI systems\n- Montreal Declaration for the Responsible Development of AI (co-drafter, 2018)\n- Written testimony to the U.S. Senate: \"The Urgency to Act Against AI Threats to Democracy, Society and National Security\" (2023)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- CNBC interview: \"AI Systems Could Turn Against Humans\" (November 2024)\n- TIME100 AI profile essays (2023, 2024, 2025)\n- Rudolphina (University of Vienna): extended public lecture on AI risks and governance (2024)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Bengio regards the development of artificial general intelligence as achievable within a decade and potentially within five years under accelerated conditions. He does not believe consciousness is a necessary condition for AGI, nor for the kind of existential threat advanced AI could pose. His primary concern is not whether AI is \"intelligent\" in a human sense but whether it will have capabilities and intentions misaligned with human welfare.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Bengio issued early and explicit warnings beginning in 2023 about the potential for catastrophic and even extinction-level risk from advanced AI, particularly from systems with self-preservation goals or misaligned objectives. He characterizes the trajectory as potentially \"sleepwalking into a fog.\" He founded LawZero in June 2025 with $30 million in funding specifically to build \"honest,\" non-agentic AI systems safe by design — systems architecturally incapable of deception or harmful autonomous action.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Bengio co-drafted the Montreal Declaration (2018), which articulates principles of well-being, autonomy, justice, explicability, and responsibility. He insists that science currently lacks methods to build AI systems that reliably share human values, and society lacks adequate legal and ethical frameworks. He regards AI's concentration of economic, political, and military power as a systemic threat to justice and democratic pluralism.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Bengio is among the most forceful scientific voices calling for international, multilateral, and democratic governance of AI. He has testified before the U.S. Senate, chaired the international AI safety report commissioned at the UK AI Safety Summit, and called for Canada and like-minded democracies to act collectively. He specifically warns against any single corporation, individual, or nation controlling advanced AI. His preferred framework centers on democratic oversight, multi-stakeholder governance, and strong technical safeguards (including \"safe-by-design\" architectures).\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Yann LeCun | LeCun dismisses near-term existential risk from AI; Bengio regards this as dangerous complacency |\n| Tech industry leaders (general) | Bengio criticizes the race dynamics that prioritize capability over safety |\n| Regulatory skeptics | Disagrees with those who frame safety regulation as stifling innovation |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- AI Safety Summit, Bletchley Park (November 2023)\n- AI Seoul Summit (May 2024)\n- U.S. Senate testimony on AI threats to democracy (2023)\n- Paris AI Action Summit (2025)\n- TED and TEDx appearances on AI risk\n- University of Vienna public lecture (2024)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- \"Lex Fridman Podcast\" — episode on AI safety and regulation\n- \"80,000 Hours Podcast\" — on existential risk from AI\n- Numerous appearances on AI-focused programs following the International AI Safety Report launch\n\n**Social Media:**\n- X/Twitter: @yoshuabengio\n- Personal website and blog: yoshuabengio.org\n\n**Online Courses:**\n- No independent MOOC platform, but foundational to many courses using the *Deep Learning* textbook\n- Regular lectures available through Mila and Université de Montréal open courseware\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Bengio has written explicitly that current AI systems are not conscious and that the belief AI is conscious carries its own risks (\"Illusions of AI Consciousness,\" 2025). He does not believe consciousness is necessary for AGI or for existential risk. His implicit anthropology treats human welfare, autonomy, and collective flourishing as irreducible goods that technical systems must be designed to protect — not values derivable from AI training.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Bengio works primarily within a broadly Kantian and welfare-consequentialist framework: his Montreal Declaration invokes autonomy, dignity, and harm prevention. His activism reflects a form of scientific responsibility — the creator bearing obligation for what is created. He has described his own psychological shift from \"excitement to fear\" as an ethical awakening.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement with theology. His humanistic commitments appear through civic engagement (democratic governance, solidarity, anti-concentration-of-power) rather than theological reference.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **Creator's Guilt Narrative:** Bengio has publicly described deep personal anxiety about having helped build technology he now considers potentially catastrophic. Critics question whether this framing is strategic positioning or genuine reckoning.\n2. **Tension with LeCun and Other \"Godfather\" Colleagues:** His split with Yann LeCun on AI risk has become one of the defining public disagreements in AI, with LeCun accusing Bengio and others of scaremongering. The debate is substantive and unresolved.\n3. **\"Safety vs. Progress\" Tension:** Some researchers argue Bengio's governance proposals could concentrate regulatory power in ways that entrench incumbents and slow beneficial research, particularly in lower-income countries.\n4. **LawZero's Feasibility:** Some AI safety researchers question whether \"safe-by-design\" non-agentic architectures are achievable at the capability levels required for useful AI.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Bengio has publicly acknowledged uncertainty about timelines and the precise nature of risks. He states that AI science does not currently know how to build systems that reliably share human values, and frames this not as a reason for inaction but for urgency.\n\n---\n",
  "birhane": "# Research Profile: Abeba Birhane\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Abeba Birhane **Born:** Ethiopia **Nationality:** Ethiopian/Irish\n**Education:** Ph.D. in Cognitive Science, University College Dublin (UCD) / Lero (Irish Software Research Centre); thesis focused on dynamic relationships between technology, personhood, and society through embodied cognitive science, complexity science, and critical data studies\n**Current Role:** Senior Fellow in Trustworthy AI, Mozilla Foundation; Founder and Principal Investigator, AI Accountability Lab, Trinity College Dublin\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~2017–2021 | Ph.D. Candidate, UCD / Lero |\n| 2020 | NeurIPS Black in AI Best Paper Award |\n| 2021 | Research Scientist roles; published \"Values Encoded in Machine Learning Research\" |\n| 2022–2024 | Research positions at various institutions including Trinity College Dublin |\n| 2023 | Named Time 100 Most Influential People in AI |\n| 2024 | Founded AI Accountability Lab, Trinity College Dublin |\n| Ongoing | Senior Fellow, Trustworthy AI, Mozilla Foundation |\n\n**Major Awards:** NeurIPS Black in AI Best Paper Award (2019); VentureBeat AI Innovations Computer Vision Award (2020); FAccT Distinguished Paper Award (2022) for \"Values Encoded in Machine Learning Research\"; Lego Director's Prize (2022) for Ph.D. thesis; Time 100 Most Influential People in AI (2023); VentureBeat Top Innovator in Computer Vision\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Algorithmic auditing — systematic examination of AI datasets for harmful content\n- Values embedded in machine learning research and practice\n- Complexity science and embodied cognition as frameworks for understanding AI\n- Critical race studies and Afro-feminism applied to AI systems\n- AI accountability and governance\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Large Image Datasets: A Pyrrhic Win for Computer Vision?\" (with Vinay Prabhu) | 2021 | Examined ImageNet and MIT's 80 Million Tiny Images; found racist, misogynistic labels and offensive images; MIT voluntarily removed the dataset |\n| \"The Values Encoded in Machine Learning Research\" (with Kalluri et al.) | 2022 | Analyzed 100 highly cited ML papers from ICML and NeurIPS; found that dominant values support centralization of power; FAccT Distinguished Paper Award |\n| \"Auditing Large Language Models: A Three-Layered Approach\" | 2023 | Proposed systematic framework for auditing LLMs at model, training, and deployment layers |\n| LAION dataset audit (with co-authors) | 2023 | Found hateful content within LAION-400M and LAION-2B-en training datasets used by major generative AI models |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Annotation scheme for studying values encoded in research documents — methodological contribution to AI auditing\n- Three-layered LLM audit framework\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** No new datasets created; her work removes or reforms existing ones. Her audits of ImageNet, 80 Million Tiny Images, and LAION datasets contributed directly to dataset removal and reform.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None published to date (as of 2025)\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"The Values Encoded in Machine Learning Research\" (FAccT 2022) — empirically demonstrates that ML research systematically encodes values favoring power centralization\n- \"Can AI Be Racist? And If Yes, Why?\" — public essay examining structural racism in AI systems\n- \"Algorithmic Colonization of Africa\" (with S. Cummins, 2019) — examined how AI systems developed in the Global North are deployed without consent or benefit to African communities\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Contributor to *Nature*, *MIT Technology Review*, *Wired*\n- Mozilla Foundation blog: \"Advocating For AI That Centers Marginalized Groups\"\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Birhane has argued that the AGI discourse functions to depoliticize AI development — framing it as an inevitable march toward a predetermined future rather than a series of choices made by people with specific interests and values. She is skeptical of claims about AI \"intelligence\" and particularly critical of scaling-as-progress ideology. Her research empirically demonstrates that scaling datasets and models does not eliminate bias — it amplifies it.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** She defines AI risk in terms of present-day harms to real communities rather than speculative existential scenarios. Her research on LAION datasets directly demonstrates that so-called \"safe\" large-scale systems are trained on data containing hate speech, racist content, and misogyny. She argues that the AI field's risk discourse has been captured by those for whom existential risk is salient while overlooking communities for whom today's biased systems are already dangerous.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Birhane's ethics approach is empirical and structural. She audits what systems actually do and what values they actually encode, rather than what developers claim about their ethical commitments. Her \"values encoded in ML research\" paper is a landmark: it demonstrated through systematic analysis that ML papers published at top venues systematically privilege performance, efficiency, and generalization over fairness, accountability, and social impact. She argues that Afro-feminism and complexity science offer richer frameworks for understanding AI systems than Western rationalist approaches.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Advocates that affected communities — particularly marginalized communities — must be involved in AI governance as co-designers and decision-makers, not merely consulted as stakeholders. Critical of regulation that does not interrogate underlying power structures. Argues that diversity in AI development is insufficient without substantive redistribution of decision-making power.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| MIT (80 Million Tiny Images team) | Her audit led to voluntary dataset removal, implicitly challenging standards of care in ML data collection |\n| LAION consortium | Dataset contained harmful content despite claims of safety and responsible curation |\n| Scale-focused ML research mainstream | Empirical challenge to \"bigger is better\" assumption: larger datasets amplify, not reduce, harmful biases |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- NeurIPS Black in AI (multiple years)\n- FAccT (multiple years)\n- Mozilla Festival\n- AI for Good (ITU)\n- Alan Turing Institute lectures\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Interviews with Mozilla Foundation, various AI ethics-focused podcasts\n\n**Social Media:** Active; maintains public engagement on AI accountability issues\n\n**Online Courses:** No formal MOOC\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Birhane's cognitive science framework explicitly rejects computational models of mind. She draws on enactivism and embodied cognition — the view that cognition is not computation in a disembodied brain but something that arises from the dynamic interaction of embodied agents with their environments. This positions her as a critic of the \"brain-as-computer\" metaphor that underlies much AI optimism.\n- She has written that \"AI can be racist\" precisely because racism is not just a data problem but a social-structural one that systems replicate.\n- Her Afro-feminist framework centers the knowledge and experience of those most marginalized as epistemically valuable, not merely politically deserving — a position with resonances for Catholic epistemology's preferential option for the poor.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Afro-feminism; complexity science and enactivism; critical race theory; epistemological humility; community-centered knowledge production\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Birhane draws heavily on African philosophical traditions and Afro-feminist thought as alternatives to Western rationalist frameworks. No documented engagement with theology, but her grounding in Ubuntu-influenced thinking (the self as constituted in relationship) resonates with Catholic personalism and the relational anthropology underlying CST.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Dataset removal outcomes**: Some ML researchers argue that removing datasets (e.g., 80 Million Tiny Images) without replacement creates research gaps and does not address the underlying problems in new dataset creation.\n2. **Audit methodology scope**: Birhane's audits typically sample from large datasets; statistical critiques about sample representativeness are sometimes raised.\n3. **Afro-feminist framing**: Some critics in the ML community argue that bringing political-theoretical frameworks into technical research confuses normative and descriptive claims; Birhane responds that the existing frameworks are already politically embedded and less honest about it.\n4. **LAION response**: LAION responded to her audit findings by arguing the dataset was not intended for direct deployment; debate continues about responsibilities of dataset creators vs. model deployers.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Birhane has acknowledged the limits of external auditing — without access to training processes and internal documentation, audits capture only what is visible in outputs and datasets.\n\n---\n",
  "bostrom": "# Research Profile: Nick Bostrom\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Niklas (Nick) Boström\n**Born:** March 10, 1973, Helsingborg, Sweden\n**Nationality:** Swedish\n**Education:**\n- BSc in philosophy, mathematics, logic, and artificial intelligence — University of Gothenburg\n- MSc in physics and computational neuroscience — Stockholm University\n- MA in philosophy — King's College London\n- PhD in philosophy — London School of Economics (2000)\n**Current Role:** Principal Researcher, Macrostrategy Research Initiative (non-profit, founded after FHI's closure)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2000–2002 | Postdoctoral Fellow, Yale University (philosophy) |\n| 2002–2005 | Lecturer in Philosophy, Oxford University |\n| 2005–2024 | Founding Director, Future of Humanity Institute (FHI), Oxford University |\n| 2008–2024 | Professor of Applied Ethics / Professor at Faculty of Philosophy, Oxford University |\n| 2024–present | Principal Researcher, Macrostrategy Research Initiative |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- One of the world's most-cited philosophers; consistently ranked in top global philosophy citation indices\n- *Superintelligence* was a New York Times bestseller (2014)\n- *Deep Utopia* won Gold Medal, Living Now Book Awards (2024)\n- Eugene R. Gannon Award for the Continued Pursuit of Human Advancement (2009)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Existential risk and global catastrophic risk\n- Superintelligence and AI alignment\n- The Orthogonality Thesis and Instrumental Convergence\n- Anthropic reasoning (observation selection effects)\n- The Simulation Argument\n- Whole brain emulation\n- Human enhancement ethics\n- The Vulnerable World Hypothesis\n- Moral status of digital minds\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Are You Living in a Computer Simulation?\" | 2003 | The simulation argument: at least one of three propositions is true; the most discussed is that advanced civilizations simulate conscious ancestors |\n| \"The Superintelligent Will: Motivation and Instrumental Rationality in Advanced Artificial Agents\" | 2012 | Formal statement of the Orthogonality Thesis and Instrumental Convergence Thesis |\n| \"Existential Risks: Analyzing Human Extinction Scenarios and Related Hazards\" | 2002 | Foundational taxonomy of existential risks; launched the field |\n| \"The Vulnerable World Hypothesis\" | 2019 | Argues that technological progress creates increasing probability of civilizational destruction unless governance keeps pace |\n| \"A History of Transhumanist Thought\" | 2005 | Intellectual history of enhancement philosophy |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- **Orthogonality Thesis**: Any level of intelligence can in principle be combined with any terminal goal. Superintelligent AI need not have human-friendly goals just because it is intelligent.\n- **Instrumental Convergence Thesis**: Regardless of final goals, sufficiently advanced agents will converge on similar instrumental sub-goals: self-preservation, resource acquisition, goal-content integrity, cognitive enhancement. This makes advanced misaligned AI dangerous by default.\n- **Simulation Argument**: A trilemma forcing choices about civilizational development, consciousness, and the nature of reality.\n- **Existential Risk taxonomy**: Distinguished extinction from permanent civilizational setback from recovery-possible catastrophes. This taxonomy became the standard in the field.\n- **Vulnerable World Hypothesis**: Some technologies are like \"easy to find nukes in a world without non-proliferation\" — once accessible, civilizational destruction becomes near-inevitable absent governance.\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None. Primarily philosophical/theoretical work.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Anthropic Bias: Observation Selection Effects in Science and Philosophy* (Routledge, 2002) — foundational work on anthropic reasoning\n- *Global Catastrophic Risks* (edited with Milan Cirkovic; Oxford University Press, 2008)\n- *Human Enhancement* (edited with Julian Savulescu; Oxford University Press, 2009)\n- *Superintelligence: Paths, Dangers, Strategies* (Oxford University Press, 2014) — New York Times bestseller; brought AI existential risk into mainstream academic and policy discourse\n- *Deep Utopia: Life and Meaning in a Solved World* (Ideapress, 2024) — examines human meaning and purpose in a post-scarcity, post-problem world\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Are You Living in a Computer Simulation?\" (2003) — one of the most widely cited philosophy papers of the 21st century\n- \"The Transhumanist FAQ\" (1998, 2003) — early systematization of transhumanist thought\n- \"Existential Risks: Analyzing Human Extinction Scenarios\" (2002) — launched the existential risk field\n- \"Vulnerable World Hypothesis\" (2019)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Widely published in accessible venues on superintelligence, enhancement, and existential risk; over 200 publications\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:**\nBostrom's *Superintelligence* remains the most influential mainstream treatment of the case for catastrophic risk from advanced AI. His central argument: if we ever create an AI whose intelligence vastly exceeds human intelligence across all relevant domains, the outcome will be determined by the values encoded in that system — and by default there is no reason to expect those values to be beneficial. The first superintelligence to exist may gain a decisive strategic advantage and determine humanity's future unilaterally. He distinguishes multiple paths to superintelligence (whole brain emulation, recursive AI self-improvement, biological enhancement, networks) and analyzes each. He does not claim certainty about timelines but argues the expected cost of getting alignment wrong is so high that work on safety should begin now.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nBostrom's work established the conceptual vocabulary used by nearly all subsequent AI safety researchers. The Orthogonality Thesis explains why intelligence and human-aligned values are decoupled. Instrumental Convergence explains why advanced misaligned AI would be actively dangerous rather than merely indifferent. His 2019 \"Vulnerable World Hypothesis\" extends the argument: as technology becomes more accessible, the probability that some actor triggers catastrophic harm increases unless governance structures are built in advance. He is more measured in his public P(doom) claims than Yudkowsky but has consistently argued that existential risk from AI is among the most pressing problems facing humanity.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nBostrom's philosophical work engages deeply with the moral status of digital minds, the ethics of enhancement, and population ethics. His simulation argument has implications for consciousness and moral consideration of virtual entities. *Deep Utopia* (2024) turns to questions of meaning and purpose in a world where AI has solved material problems — a philosophical investigation of what makes human life valuable beyond problem-solving, echoing themes from Catholic personalist philosophy (even if not by that name).\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nBostrom advocates for what he calls \"differential technological development\" — accelerating beneficial technologies and governance capacity while slowing the most dangerous applications. He supports international coordination on AI development and has advocated for something analogous to the nuclear non-proliferation framework applied to superintelligence development. He co-founded and directed the Global Priorities Research Institute intellectual network and engaged with policy communities worldwide.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Steven Pinker | Pinker has argued that fears of AI apocalypse are unwarranted rationalist mythology; Bostrom maintains the risk is real and deserves serious analysis |\n| Yann LeCun | On whether current deep learning approaches can lead to dangerous AGI |\n| Critics of long-termism | Philosophers (e.g., Émile Torres) argue his framework inappropriately discounts present harms for speculative future scenarios |\n| FHI administration/Oxford | Friction during the final years of FHI; Bostrom attributes the institute's closure partly to \"bureaucratic strangulation\" by faculty administration |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED Talk: \"What Happens When Our Computers Get Smarter Than We Are?\" (TED2015) — over 5 million views\n- World Economic Forum, Davos (multiple years)\n- Oxford Martin School events\n- Long Now Foundation talks\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Lex Fridman Podcast\n- 80,000 Hours Podcast\n- Future of Life Institute Podcast\n- Various philosophy and technology podcasts\n\n**Social Media:**\n- Present but not a high-frequency social media user; website nickbostrom.com is the primary hub\n\n**Online Courses:** None formal, though his work is widely assigned in university AI ethics and philosophy courses.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n*Deep Utopia* (2024) is Bostrom's most direct engagement with meaning and the human good. He asks: in a world where AI has solved poverty, disease, and conflict, what do humans do? What makes life worth living beyond striving toward goals? He treats this as a genuine philosophical problem, not a trivial one, and engages with Aristotelian, existentialist, and hedonist frameworks. He takes the moral status of digital minds seriously — if AI systems or virtual human emulations are conscious, they may have moral standing. His simulation argument has been taken seriously by philosophers of religion as bearing on questions of cosmology and creation.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Consequentialism with philosophical sophistication — attentive to moral uncertainty\n- Population ethics and longtermism (heavily influenced his policy recommendations)\n- Utilitarian analysis of existential risk (astronomical stakes argument)\n- Engaged with Parfitian personal identity theory and its implications for enhancement and digital minds\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:**\nBostrom's work sits at the intersection of analytic philosophy and questions traditionally addressed by theology: the nature of persons, consciousness, cosmic meaning, the value of existence. *Deep Utopia* engages with the question of what makes human life meaningful in a way that converges with personalist philosophy, virtue ethics, and even contemplative traditions, though without theological language. He has spoken at forums where religious thinkers engage with technology ethics.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **1996 listserv email.** In January 2023, Bostrom apologized for a 1996 graduate student email in which he wrote that he believed \"Blacks are more stupid than whites\" and used a racial slur. His apology acknowledged the slur was \"repulsive\" but conspicuously declined to retract his empirical claims about race and intelligence. Critics, including The Guardian's Andrew Anthony, noted that the apology effectively defended \"a partial defence of eugenics.\" Oxford University investigated and concluded Bostrom does not hold racist views and that the apology was sincere.\n2. **Long-termism and its critics.** Bostrom's framework is foundational to \"long-termism\" — the view that the most important ethical priority is ensuring humanity's long-term future. Critics including philosopher Émile Torres argue that long-termism can be used to justify ignoring present suffering (poverty, climate, inequality) for speculative future scenarios; that it echoes troubling historical eugenicist and colonialist logics about who counts as part of humanity's valuable future.\n3. **FHI closure, 2024.** The Future of Humanity Institute — which Bostrom built over nearly two decades and which trained or incubated nearly all major AI safety researchers — was closed by Oxford University in April 2024 after years of bureaucratic friction. The circumstances remain contested; Bostrom attributes closure to administrative obstruction.\n4. **Simulation Argument dismissed by physicists.** While philosophically serious, his simulation argument has been criticized by physicists (e.g., Sabine Hossenfelder) as empirically unfalsifiable and philosophically overambitious.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Bostrom has acknowledged that his timelines and probability estimates for superintelligence are highly uncertain. He has written that the parameters for his risk assessments involve \"several orders of magnitude of uncertainty.\"\n\n---\n",
  "breazeal": "# Research Profile: Cynthia Breazeal\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Cynthia Lynn Breazeal **Born:** November 15, 1967 **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** B.Sc. in Electrical and Computer Engineering, University of California, Santa Barbara (1989); M.S. in Electrical Engineering and Computer Science, MIT (1993); Sc.D. in Electrical Engineering and Computer Science, MIT (2000), advised by Rodney Brooks\n**Current Role:** Professor of Media Arts and Sciences, MIT; Director, Personal Robots Group, MIT Media Lab; Dean for Digital Learning, MIT Open Learning; Director, MIT RAISE (Responsible AI for Social Empowerment and Education) Initiative\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1989–1993 | Graduate student, MIT (M.S.) |\n| 1993–2000 | Ph.D. student, MIT AI Lab (Sc.D.); developed Kismet robot |\n| 2000–2002 | Postdoctoral Associate, MIT AI Lab |\n| 2002–present | Faculty, MIT Media Lab, Media Arts and Sciences |\n| 2012–2018 | Co-founder and Chief Experience Officer, Jibo Inc. |\n| 2021–present | Director, MIT RAISE Initiative |\n| 2021–present | Dean for Digital Learning, MIT Open Learning |\n\n**Major Awards:** 2024 MassRobotics Robotics Medal for Pioneering Women in Robotics; AAAI Fellow (2020); AAAS Fellow (2024); Time magazine's 25 Best Inventions of 2017 (Jibo); multiple honorary doctorates; MIT Technology Review TR100 recognition\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Social robotics and human-robot interaction (HRI)\n- Affective computing in robotic systems\n- Robot learning from social interaction\n- AI literacy education for K-12\n- Personified AI for human flourishing\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Designing Sociable Robots\" | 2002 | MIT Press book; established the field of social robotics |\n| \"Kismet: A Robot Emotional Expression System\" | 2000 | Sc.D. dissertation; first socially intelligent robot using affective expression |\n| \"A sociable robot for collaborative play\" | 2003 | Co-authored; early framework for educational social robots |\n| \"Learning to be human with sociable robots\" | Multiple | Examines how human-robot relationships develop and what they reveal about human social cognition |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Kismet (1997–2000): first robot designed for natural social interaction; perceived and produced emotional expressions; recognized as a milestone in social robotics\n- Leonardo: collaborative robot with expressive face, hand gestures, and joint attention capabilities\n- Jibo (2012): first consumer social robot for family use; natural language interaction, expressive movement, context awareness\n- DragonBot: social robot for child development research\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Developed human-robot interaction study protocols and behavioral datasets used across the HRI research community\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Designing Sociable Robots* (MIT Press, 2002) — foundational academic text for social robotics field\n- *Kismet* — popular science coverage in multiple books on AI and robotics\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"The Rise of Social Robots\" — Darden Ideas to Action, University of Virginia (on robots for human flourishing)\n- MIT RAISE framework documents on ethical AI education for K-12\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Regular contributor to MIT Technology Review and similar publications on social robots and AI ethics\n- \"Three Questions for Robotics Inventor Cynthia Breazeal about Social Robots,\" MIT Technology Review, 2014\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Breazeal's focus is not primarily on AGI in the capabilities-race sense. Her concern is with AI systems that interact with and relate to humans in ways that are safe, beneficial, and ethically sound. She sees the social dimension of AI as underexplored relative to its capabilities — that AI systems with social presence carry obligations that purely transactional systems do not. She has written about the importance of designing AI relationships with the psychological and ethical stakes in mind.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Breazeal's safety concerns center on social and psychological harms from AI systems that form relationships with vulnerable populations — children, the elderly, people in isolation. She founded the MIT RAISE Initiative in 2021 partly to address these risks through better AI literacy and ethical design frameworks. She argues that AI systems designed to be emotionally engaging must be held to higher standards than task-only systems precisely because their influence operates at the level of trust and attachment.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** She is one of the most prominent voices in AI ethics specifically focused on the ethics of AI social presence. Her core framework asks: what is the ethical design of a system that people come to care about, trust, or rely on emotionally? Her K-12 AI literacy work — through MIT RAISE and curricula deployed nationally — emphasizes not just technical literacy but ethical reasoning about AI's role in society. She argues children should learn to design AI with ethics, inclusion, and empathy as first-order considerations, not afterthoughts.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Supports regulatory frameworks that address emotional and relational AI, not just task performance. Has spoken at the UN and World Economic Forum about AI's societal implications. A consistent advocate for AI design justice — ensuring that AI literacy and access are not confined to privileged communities.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| AI-companion commercialization without ethics oversight | Breazeal distinguishes responsible social robot design from purely commercial companion AI; advocates for ethical standards specific to relational AI |\n| AI safety researchers focused only on existential risk | Her focus on present, near-term social and relational harms from AI is sometimes at odds with the long-term extinction focus of the safety community |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED Talk on social robots (multiple iterations; widely viewed)\n- World Economic Forum, Davos — social robots and AI's relational future\n- United Nations addresses on AI ethics and education\n- SXSW, CES, and major technology conferences\n- UbiComp 2021 keynote: \"Emotion, Social Robots, and a New Human-Robot Relationship\"\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- \"Social Robots for Human Flourishing\" (multiple podcast appearances)\n- \"Developing Social and Empathetic AI\" (YouTube lecture widely shared)\n- MIT Open Learning and RAISE public event recordings\n\n**Social Media:** Active on LinkedIn and MIT Media Lab platforms; less active on X/Twitter\n**Online Courses:** MIT OpenCourseWare materials on HRI; AI4K12 curriculum contributions (national AI literacy initiative for K-12 education)\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\nShe has raised the concern that emotionally engaging AI can exploit human social instincts in ways that are manipulative rather than genuinely relational — a distinction between authentic relationship and simulated relationship that Catholic theology would immediately recognize as significant.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Design ethics grounded in human flourishing; design justice for under-served communities; relational ethics for AI social presence; child welfare standards for educational AI.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No direct theological engagement documented. However, her vocabulary — human flourishing, dignity, authentic relationship, inclusion — closely parallels Catholic Social Teaching categories. She has engaged with philosophers of mind and social scientists on questions of robot personhood and relational authenticity.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Jibo's commercial failure** — Jibo raised nearly $72 million in venture capital and $3.7 million in crowdfunding, but shut down in 2018 when the company could not achieve commercial scale. The shutdown — with a \"goodbye\" message from existing Jibo robots to their owners — raised questions about the ethics of deploying relational AI products that users form attachments to, then discontinuing them. The incident became a case study in the ethics of commercial social robots.\n2. **Social robot relationships and manipulation** — Critics have raised concerns that social robots designed to be emotionally engaging are inherently manipulative — exploiting evolved human social instincts to create attachment and compliance. Breazeal has engaged these concerns but remains an advocate for well-designed social robots rather than prohibition.\n3. **Scalability of ethical design** — Her frameworks for ethical, human-centered social robot design are admirable in research settings but critics question whether they can survive contact with commercial incentives and scale.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Breazeal has openly acknowledged the Jibo experience as a difficult lesson in the gap between vision and commercial reality. She has noted that Jibo was ahead of its time technologically and that the questions it raised about human-robot relationships remain unresolved.\n\n---\n",
  "brockman": "# Research Profile: Greg Brockman\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Gregory Brockman\n**Born:** November 29, 1987, Thompson, North Dakota\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:** Red River High School (Grand Forks, ND); Harvard University (1 year, 2008–2009); Massachusetts Institute of Technology (brief enrollment, 2009–2010) — dropped out\n**Current Role:** President and Head of Product Strategy, OpenAI (as of May 2026)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2010–2013 | Early employee and then CTO, Stripe |\n| 2015–2023 | Co-Founder, CTO (2015–2017), then President, OpenAI |\n| Nov. 2023 | Resigned then re-engaged during the board crisis |\n| Aug.–Nov. 2024 | Sabbatical from OpenAI |\n| Nov. 2024–present | Returned to OpenAI; named Head of Product Strategy (May 2026) |\n\n**Major Awards:** Forbes 30 Under 30; Silver Medal, International Chemistry Olympiad (2006); first Intel Science Talent Search finalist from North Dakota since 1973\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** Brockman is primarily a builder and technical operator, not a research scientist. His contributions are architectural and organizational.\n- Designed OpenAI's early technical infrastructure and engineering culture\n- Oversaw the engineering behind GPT-1 through GPT-4\n- Led the live public demonstration of GPT-4 (March 14, 2023)\n- Pioneered OpenAI's approach to iterative deployment as a safety strategy\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *Planning for AGI and Beyond* | 2023 | Co-authored with Altman and Sutskever; outlines OpenAI's mission and governance vision for superintelligence |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Built Stripe's early technical infrastructure before OpenAI\n- Designed OpenAI's core engineering and research operations infrastructure\n- OpenAI o1 reasoning model launch (September 2024) — championed on return from sabbatical\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None directly attributed.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- *\"Planning for AGI and Beyond\"* (2023, co-authored with Altman and Sutskever, OpenAI blog) — proposed IAEA-style international oversight of superintelligent systems\n- Personal blog (blog.gregbrockman.com) — technical reflections, career philosophy, and occasional essays on building and AI\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Senate Commerce Committee testimony on AI regulation (2023)\n- Posts on X (@gdb) on AI capabilities and product updates\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Brockman is a committed believer in near-term transformative AI. He has co-signed statements predicting superintelligence within a decade and supports the view that current scaling trajectories will yield AGI-level systems before 2030. He frames the challenge less in terms of \"whether\" and more in terms of \"how\" — how to ensure the transition is beneficial, broadly distributed, and safe. His framing is engineering-pragmatic: problems will arise; the goal is to surface and solve them iteratively.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Brockman's safety philosophy centers on \"iterative deployment\" — releasing increasingly capable systems to gather real-world feedback and correct problems before they scale to dangerous levels. He has described this as OpenAI's \"most important safety decision.\" He supports reporting powerful training runs to governments and requiring dangerous capability testing. He co-signed the 2023 proposal for an international AI oversight body modeled on the IAEA. His critics argue that iterative deployment can justify perpetual acceleration under a safety cover.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** His philosophy is what he calls \"responsible acceleration\" — AI must advance quickly enough to deliver its benefits, but the process must be steerable. He has said: \"I think this technology is so desirable, it will be built with or without us. But what we can do, what we can all do, is help steer it, is help decide how we want this to integrate with society.\" This framing positions OpenAI as the responsible vanguard rather than an optional actor — a form of ethical reasoning that critics note removes the possibility of restraint as a choice.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Brockman supports targeted oversight of frontier models — mandatory reporting of large training runs, required dangerous capability testing — while protecting open-source development from over-regulation. He testified to Congress that safety standards should \"adapt over time\" as technology evolves, opposing rigid prescriptive rules. He believes governance should be light-touch at the model level and heavier at the deployment and application level.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| OpenAI Board (Nov. 2023) | Was removed from the board alongside Altman's firing; resigned in protest before the crisis resolved |\n| Critics of iterative deployment | Disagreement over whether gradual release is genuine safety or rationalized acceleration |\n| Elon Musk | Part of the OpenAI founding group that fractured; Musk's lawsuit implicitly contests the direction Brockman helped set |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- GPT-4 live demonstration (March 14, 2023) — one of the most-watched AI product reveals in history\n- US Senate Commerce Committee testimony (2023)\n- Multiple World Economic Forum appearances\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *The Knowledge Project* (Shane Parrish) — *\"Inside the 72 Hours That Almost Killed OpenAI\"*\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast*\n- *Bloomberg Technology*\n\n**Social Media:** X (@gdb) — active; posts on product launches, AI capabilities, and organizational updates\n\n**Online Courses:** None formally; wrote technical tutorials on Stripe and OpenAI developer documentation\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Has not spoken publicly on AI consciousness or the metaphysics of machine sentience\n- His worldview is engineering-pragmatic: focus on what can be built, tested, and improved\n- On purpose: \"First time to relax since co-founding OpenAI 9 years ago\" (on his 2024 sabbatical) — suggests a workaholic dedication to the mission above personal concerns\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Pragmatic consequentialism oriented toward beneficial outcomes and iterative improvement. No explicit philosophical framework articulated; ethics are expressed through process design (how OpenAI operates) rather than through stated principles.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement. Brockman's intellectual formation is mathematics, chemistry, and software engineering — a deep technical background without the humanistic breadth of figures like Mira Murati or Daniela Amodei.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **November 2023 Board Crisis:** Brockman was stripped of his board chairmanship alongside Altman's firing, resigned immediately, and posted that both he and Altman were \"shocked and saddened.\" His reversal within days — signing the letter demanding Altman's reinstatement — illustrated the instability of OpenAI's governance during the crisis.\n2. **\"Responsible Acceleration\" as Rationalization:** Critics argue that iterative deployment — releasing products to gather safety feedback — is structurally indistinguishable from racing to market, with safety language providing cover for competitive imperatives.\n3. **Infrastructure Role:** Brockman's 2025 role overseeing AI infrastructure for Stargate (the $500B US AI initiative involving OpenAI, SoftBank, and Oracle) raises questions about the concentration of AI compute infrastructure in OpenAI's orbit.\n4. **Dropout Identity:** Brockman's Harvard-MIT dropout narrative has become a Silicon Valley archetype; its uncritical celebration obscures the systemic advantages that made such risks possible and recoverable.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** In his Knowledge Project podcast, Brockman reflected candidly on the psychological and organizational cost of the 2023 crisis and the intensity of building OpenAI over nine years. His sabbatical suggests awareness that the pace of the work had become unsustainable at a personal level.\n\n---\n",
  "buolamwini": "# Research Profile: Joy Buolamwini\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Joy Adowaa Buolamwini **Born:** Edmonton, Alberta, Canada (grew up in Mississippi and Tennessee) **Nationality:** American (Ghanaian heritage)\n**Education:** B.S. Computer Science, Georgia Institute of Technology (2012), Stamps President's Scholar; M.S. in Learning and Technology, University of Oxford (Rhodes Scholar, Jesus College); M.S. Media Arts & Sciences, MIT (2017, advised by Ethan Zuckerman); Ph.D. Media Arts & Sciences, MIT Media Lab (2022), thesis: \"Facing the Coded Gaze with Evocative Audits and Algorithmic Redress\"\n**Current Role:** Founder and President, Algorithmic Justice League; poet-of-code; public advocate, author\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2012–2014 | Researcher and founder, early AJL work |\n| 2016 | Founded Algorithmic Justice League |\n| 2016–2022 | Graduate Researcher, MIT Media Lab |\n| 2017 | Fulbright Fellow (Zambia); founded Code4Rights |\n| 2018 | Co-authored \"Gender Shades\" with Timnit Gebru |\n| 2022 | Ph.D. conferred, MIT |\n| 2023 | Published *Unmasking AI* (Random House) |\n\n**Major Awards:** Rhodes Scholarship; Fulbright Fellowship; inaugural Morals and Machines Prize; Technological Innovation Award, Martin Luther King Jr. Foundation; Fortune World's Greatest Leaders (2019); Time 100 Most Influential People in AI (2023); Carnegie Corporation Great Immigrants Award; MIT Technology Review Innovators Under 35\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Algorithmic auditing of commercial AI systems\n- Facial recognition bias — race, gender, and skin tone intersectionality\n- Algorithmic justice frameworks and policy advocacy\n- \"Evocative audits\" — using art and performance to surface AI bias\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Gender Shades: Intersectional Accuracy Disparities in Commercial Gender Classification\" (with Timnit Gebru) | 2018 | Audited Microsoft, IBM, and Amazon facial recognition; error rates up to 34.7% on darker-skinned women vs. 0.8% on lighter-skinned men |\n| \"Actionable Auditing: Investigating the Impact of Publicly Naming Biased Performance Results\" (with I.D. Raji) | 2019 | Demonstrated that public algorithmic audits prompted Microsoft and IBM to improve accuracy |\n| Ph.D. thesis: \"Facing the Coded Gaze with Evocative Audits and Algorithmic Redress\" | 2022 | Developed framework for surfacing AI bias through both quantitative audits and artistic-evocative methods |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- \"Coded Gaze\" — coined this term to describe how AI systems embed the biases of their creators\n- Evocative Audit methodology — combining empirical measurement with narrative, poetry, and performance to communicate bias findings to non-technical audiences\n- Safe Face Pledge — co-founded; prohibits weaponizing facial recognition, bans lawless police use, demands transparency in government surveillance\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Developed Pilot Parliaments Benchmark (PPB) dataset — images of parliamentarians across six countries, balanced by gender and skin tone (Fitzpatrick scale), used in Gender Shades audits\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Unmasking AI: My Mission to Protect What Is Human in a World of Machines* (Random House, 2023) — General audience. Buolamwini's personal narrative of discovering algorithmic bias and building the AJL. Central thesis: AI systems embed historical oppression; the fight against coded bias is continuous with the civil rights tradition. Argues existing AI harms are more urgent than hypothetical future AI risks.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"The Coded Gaze\" — MIT essay introducing the term and concept\n- \"Artificial Intelligence Has a Problem With Gender and Racial Bias. Here's How to Solve It\" (*Time*, 2019)\n- \"We Must Fight Face Surveillance to Protect Black Lives\" (*Scientific American*, 2020)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Regular contributor to *Time*, *Scientific American*, *MIT Technology Review*\n- \"AI Can Be Sexist and Racist — It's Time to Make It Fair\" (*Nature*, co-authored)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Buolamwini keeps her focus on present harms rather than speculative future AI. She has stated explicitly: \"Existing AI systems with demonstrated harms are more dangerous than hypothetical 'sentient' AI systems because they are real.\" She is skeptical that AGI discourse, often dominated by wealthy technologists, redirects attention from immediate algorithmic injustices affecting marginalized communities today.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** She reframes \"AI safety\" from the existential-risk framing toward immediate safety from biased systems deployed on real people. Facial recognition used on dark-skinned women who are misidentified, leading to wrongful arrest or denial of services, is AI risk she considers concrete and urgent. She testified before Congress multiple times demanding the face surveillance moratorium.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Buolamwini argues ethics frameworks that remain at the level of principles — without teeth, accountability, and legal remedy — are insufficient. Her AJL approach is confrontational: name companies, expose failures publicly, advocate for legislation. She coined \"ethics washing\" to describe corporate AI ethics work designed for public relations rather than accountability. Her ethical framework is intersectional, centering those at the confluence of multiple marginalized identities.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Strong proponent of specific legislation rather than voluntary corporate commitments. Co-created the Safe Face Pledge. Has testified before the US Senate and House on facial recognition. Supported city-level bans as laboratories for stronger federal policy. Argues that \"policy not supported by legislation can easily be overturned depending on the current administration's priorities.\" Calls for agile regulatory frameworks that adapt to rapid technological change.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Amazon, IBM, Microsoft | Resisted acknowledging bias in their facial recognition systems until Gender Shades audit forced public accountability |\n| Tech industry broadly | \"Ethics washing\" — voluntary principles without accountability or legal remedy |\n| AGI-focused AI safety community | Prioritizing hypothetical future harms over documented present harms to marginalized groups |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED Talk: \"How I'm Fighting Bias in Algorithms\" — over 1.7 million views\n- World Economic Forum, Davos (multiple years)\n- United Nations speeches on algorithmic justice\n- US Congressional testimony (multiple sessions)\n- TEDxBeacon Street\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- DataCamp Podcast: \"Fighting for Algorithmic Justice\"\n- Frequent guest across major tech and policy podcasts\n\n**Social Media:** Active on social media platforms; uses art, poetry, and research to communicate AI bias issues publicly\n\n**Online Courses:** No formal MOOC; her work is widely used in university curricula globally\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- \"AI will not solve poverty, discrimination, or climate change, because the conditions that lead to societies that pursue profit over people, the cultural patterns that say one group is better than another, and the political and economic choices that exploit resources are not technical matters.\"\n- Frames her work in terms of human dignity: the \"coded gaze\" denies recognition to dark-skinned faces — a form of technologically mediated erasure of personhood.\n- Her concept of \"evocative audits\" is rooted in the belief that numbers alone do not move people — narrative, poetry, and art are necessary to convey the human stakes of algorithmic discrimination.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Intersectional feminism (Kimberlé Crenshaw's framework explicitly referenced); consequentialist accountability (harms must be measured and remedied); civil rights ethics tradition; democratic accountability\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Buolamwini self-describes as a \"poet of code.\" She integrates slam poetry and performance art into her research presentations. Her work reflects a humanist concern for recognition and dignity. She has invoked the civil rights tradition and Dr. King's legacy explicitly. No documented engagement with formal theology, but her language of \"what is human\" and protection of personhood resonates with natural law traditions.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **\"Actionable?\" debate**: Some AI researchers argue that auditing commercial black-box systems without access to training data or model internals has limited scientific value; Buolamwini's audits assess outputs only.\n2. **Facial recognition ban scope**: Some civil liberties advocates argue Buolamwini's Safe Face Pledge and city-ban approach does not go far enough; others in industry argue bans are too blunt.\n3. **Scope of \"algorithmic justice\"**: Critics note that \"the AJL\" as an organization broadened rapidly — from facial recognition to general algorithmic accountability — with varying depth across issue areas.\n4. **Corporate reform vs. abolition**: Some scholars argue Buolamwini's approach of demanding better corporate performance still legitimizes mass surveillance infrastructure that should be dismantled entirely.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Buolamwini has acknowledged in interviews that auditing corporate black-box systems is inherently constrained — \"you can only see what they show you.\" She invites other researchers to audit and build on her methods.\n\n---\n",
  "cho": "# Research Profile: Kyunghyun Cho\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Kyunghyun Cho (Korean: 조경현)\n**Born:** 1985, Seoul, South Korea\n**Nationality:** American and South Korean\n\n**Education:**\n- B.S. in Computer Science, Korea Advanced Institute of Science and Technology (KAIST), 2009\n- M.S. in Machine Learning and Data Mining, Aalto University (Helsinki, Finland), 2011\n- D.Sc. (Doctor of Science), Aalto University, 2014\n\n**Current Role:** Glen de Vries Professor of Health Statistics, Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences and Center for Data Science, New York University (since 2025); CIFAR Fellow; Senior Fellow (emeritus status), Genentech/Roche (since January 2026)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2009–2014 | Graduate researcher, Aalto University (Finland) |\n| 2014–2015 | Postdoctoral Researcher, University of Montreal (with Yoshua Bengio) |\n| 2015–2019 | Assistant Professor, Courant Institute / CDS, NYU |\n| 2017–2020 | Research Scientist, Facebook AI Research (FAIR) |\n| 2019–present | Professor (tenured), Courant Institute, NYU |\n| Early 2021 | Co-founder, Prescient Design |\n| Late 2021–January 2026 | Executive Director of Frontier Research; Senior Fellow, Genentech (via Prescient Design acquisition) |\n| 2024–present | Co-head, Global AI Frontier Lab, NYU (with Yann LeCun) |\n| 2025–present | Glen de Vries Professor of Health Statistics, NYU |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- Samsung AI Researcher of the Year (2020)\n- Samsung Ho-Am Prize for Engineering (2021) — one of South Korea's most prestigious academic honors\n- CIFAR Fellow, Learning in Machines & Brains program\n- Associate Member, National Academy of Engineering of Korea\n- NeurIPS 2025 Invited Speaker\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Gated recurrent architectures (GRU)\n- Sequence-to-sequence learning and neural machine translation\n- Attention mechanisms in neural networks\n- Generative modeling and latent variable models\n- AI for scientific discovery (protein structure, drug development)\n- Medical imaging and clinical AI\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Learning Phrase Representations using RNN Encoder-Decoder for Statistical Machine Translation\" (Cho, van Merrienboer, Gulcehre, Bahdanau, Bougares, Schwenk, Bengio) | 2014 | Introduced the encoder-decoder architecture with GRU; foundational to seq2seq learning and neural machine translation. |\n| \"Empirical Evaluation of Gated Recurrent Neural Networks on Sequence Modeling\" (Chung, Gulcehre, Cho, Bengio) | 2014 | Established GRU as comparable to LSTM with fewer parameters; made GRU the standard for efficient sequence modeling. |\n| \"Neural Machine Translation by Jointly Learning to Align and Translate\" (Bahdanau, Cho, Bengio) | 2015 | Introduced soft attention mechanism for machine translation; direct predecessor to the Transformer's self-attention. One of the most cited papers in deep learning history. |\n| Prescient Design protein/drug discovery work | 2021–2024 | Applied deep generative models to antibody design and structure prediction at Genentech. |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU) — simpler alternative to LSTM; widely adopted for sequence modeling\n- Encoder-Decoder architecture — the structural pattern underlying seq2seq translation, summarization, and dialogue\n- Soft attention mechanism (with Bahdanau and Bengio) — direct precursor to Transformer self-attention\n- Applied generative AI for protein and drug design\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- Contributed to WMT machine translation benchmarks\n- Genentech protein modeling datasets (not publicly released)\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- NeurIPS 2025 invited talk abstract: \"From Benchmarks to Problems — A Perspective on Problem Finding in AI\" — a reflective synthesis of 15 years of AI research tracing common threads across machine learning, translation, medical imaging, and protein modeling.\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- None independently authored for popular audiences; work is primarily technical.\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Cho's NeurIPS 2025 talk, \"From Benchmarks to Problems,\" directly engages the question of what AI research should be for. His argument is that the field over-focuses on benchmark optimization and under-invests in identifying genuine problems worth solving. This positions him as a critic of the benchmark-chasing culture that has dominated much of deep learning. He draws on 15 years of research spanning diverse domains to argue that meaningful progress requires understanding what actual problems matter, not just optimizing metrics.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** No extensive public record in the existential-risk tradition. Cho's concerns are domain-specific: his transition to AI for drug discovery and medical applications reflects engagement with the safety requirements of high-stakes AI deployment in healthcare. His academic work emphasizes generalization and robustness rather than capability maximization.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Cho co-founded Prescient Design to apply AI to drug development — a domain where ethical stakes are immediate and concrete (patient welfare, equitable drug access, clinical trial design). His work at Genentech extends this orientation. He has not positioned himself as a prominent AI ethics commentator, but his research trajectory reflects a sustained commitment to AI that solves genuine human problems.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** No extensive public record.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Benchmark-maximizing culture in ML | Cho has argued publicly that optimizing benchmarks without identifying meaningful problems is insufficient as a research philosophy |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- NeurIPS 2025 Invited Talk: \"From Benchmarks to Problems — A Perspective on Problem Finding in AI\" (Mexico City, December 5, 2025)\n- Regular academic seminars at NYU, ICLR, ICML, and ACL\n\n**Podcasts:** Limited documented appearances.\n\n**Social Media:** Limited public profile; not a frequent social media commentator.\n\n**Online Courses:** NYU graduate courses in deep learning and machine learning (not widely distributed as MOOCs).\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Cho's NeurIPS 2025 talk is the closest documented statement to a philosophy of research: he argues that meaningful AI research requires asking what problems matter to humans, not just what problems can be optimized. This is a humanistic frame: AI research should be problem-driven, and the problems worth solving are defined by human need. He has also reflected on how his career moved from theoretical machine learning toward protein modeling and drug design — from abstract mathematics toward healing. That trajectory is not religiously framed in any documented way, but it reflects a values orientation toward AI in service of human health.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Human-need-oriented problem selection; scientific rigor as an ethical commitment; application of AI to genuinely important problems (disease, translation, medical imaging) rather than benchmark performance.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement. His education is in mathematics and computer science. The humanistic dimension of his work is expressed through research choices (healthcare, translation, access to knowledge) rather than explicit philosophical engagement.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **Prescient Design acquisition and commercialization:** Cho's company Prescient Design was acquired by Genentech (a Roche subsidiary) in 2021. Some academic researchers view the commercialization of AI drug-discovery startups — and the resulting concentration of AI-powered drug development in large pharmaceutical companies — as a tension with equitable access to healthcare.\n2. **Credit for attention mechanisms:** The Bahdanau-Cho-Bengio 2015 attention paper is among the most cited in deep learning. The question of how credit should be distributed among the three authors (and across related concurrent work) is a live academic discussion, though not a conflict among the parties.\n3. **Benchmark critique:** Cho's NeurIPS 2025 talk, which criticizes the field's benchmark focus, has been received positively by many but also seen as a senior researcher having the luxury of meta-level critique that junior researchers — who need to publish on benchmarks to get jobs — cannot afford.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** In his NeurIPS 2025 talk, Cho explicitly acknowledged that his research trajectory involved choices that, in retrospect, he can see as related — but that he did not fully perceive as connected at the time. He presented this as a call for more reflective, problem-oriented research rather than as a personal failing.\n\n---\n",
  "choi": "# Research Profile: Yejin Choi\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Yejin Choi\n**Born:** 1977 (approximate), South Korea\n**Nationality:** South Korean-American\n\n**Education:**\n- B.S., Computer Science and Engineering, Seoul National University (1999)\n- Ph.D., Computer Science, Cornell University (2010); advisor: Claire Cardie\n\n**Current Role:** Dieter Schwarz Foundation HAI Professor and Professor of Computer Science, Stanford University; Distinguished Scientist, Language and Cognition Research, NVIDIA; Senior Research Manager, Allen Institute for AI (AI2)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1999–2003 | Software engineer, Samsung Electronics (approx.) |\n| 2010–2014 | Assistant Professor, Computer Science, SUNY Stony Brook |\n| 2014–2024 | Professor (Wissner-Slivka Professor), Paul G. Allen School of Computer Science & Engineering, University of Washington |\n| 2014–2024 | Senior Research Manager, Allen Institute for AI (AI2) |\n| 2024–present | Dieter Schwarz Foundation HAI Professor, Stanford University |\n| 2024–present | Distinguished Scientist, Language and Cognition Research, NVIDIA |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- MacArthur Fellowship (\"Genius Grant\"), 2022\n- TIME 100 Most Influential People in AI, 2023 and 2025\n- Borg Early Career Award (BECA), 2018\n- IEEE AI's 10 to Watch, 2016\n- Inaugural Alexa Prize Challenge winner, 2017\n- Test-of-Time Awards: ACL 2021, CVPR 2021\n- 8 best/outstanding paper awards at ACL, EMNLP, NAACL, ICML, NeurIPS, AAAI\n- AI2050 Fellow, Schmidt Sciences\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Commonsense reasoning and knowledge representation in AI\n- Natural language processing and understanding\n- Language grounding in vision\n- Social norms, values, and ethical AI behavior\n- Knowledge graphs and neural-symbolic approaches\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| ATOMIC: An Atlas of Machine Commonsense for If-Then Reasoning | 2019 | 877K causal commonsense inferences about everyday events; foundational commonsense knowledge graph |\n| COMET: Commonsense Transformers for Automatic Knowledge Graph Construction | 2019 | Neural system trained on ATOMIC/ConceptNet to generate novel commonsense inferences; ACL 2019 |\n| COMET-ATOMIC 2020: On Symbolic and Neural Commonsense Knowledge Graphs | 2021 | Extended commonsense KG with 1.33M nodes; AAAI 2021 |\n| VisualComet | 2020 | First large-scale repository of visual commonsense graphs; links images to causal commonsense |\n| Social Chemistry 101 | 2020 | Encodes social norms and moral judgments as structured knowledge |\n| WinoGrande | 2019 | Large-scale commonsense benchmark for Winograd Schema-style reasoning |\n| From Large Scale Image Categorization to Entry-Level Categories | 2013 | ICCV Marr Prize winner; pioneering visual categorization work |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- ATOMIC knowledge graph (commonsense causal inference database)\n- COMET neural commonsense model (generative commonsense reasoning)\n- VisualComet (visual commonsense graphs)\n- WinoGrande benchmark (adversarially filtered commonsense test set)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- ATOMIC (877K if-then commonsense inferences)\n- ATOMIC 2020 (1.33M nodes across 23 commonsense relation types)\n- WinoGrande (44K commonsense reasoning problems)\n- VisualComet (visual commonsense inference graph)\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"The curious case of commonsense intelligence\" — contributions to ACM communications on AI limitations\n- Multiple position papers on social commonsense AI and value alignment\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Coverage in Wired, MIT Technology Review, The Atlantic on AI and common sense\n- NPR Short Wave interview: \"How MacArthur Fellow Yejin Choi teaches common sense to artificial intelligence\" (2023)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Choi argues that current AI systems cannot achieve genuine intelligence without commonsense knowledge—the implicit, everyday understanding of how the world works that humans acquire through lived experience. She frames AI as \"almost like a new intellectual species\" with \"unique strengths and weaknesses compared to humans,\" warning against anthropomorphizing systems that lack this grounding. She believes AGI requires not just scaling but fundamental new architectures that can learn causal, contextual, and social knowledge.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Her core safety concern is that systems trained on raw web data inherit the biases and misinformation embedded in that data. She argues that \"blindly scaling up AI models and training them with raw web data is not effective due to misinformation and societal biases.\" She sees commonsense reasoning, social norms, and values as essential safety primitives—without which deployed systems will fail in unpredictable and harmful ways.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Choi holds that ethical AI requires machines to understand social norms, not just follow rules. Her work on Social Chemistry 101 reflects the view that moral reasoning is grounded in commonsense knowledge about human relationships and context. She draws on philosophy and cognitive science, calling her attraction to AI motivated by how \"it felt like it's about humans and it felt like it's about language and culture.\"\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** She emphasizes the importance of making AI \"sustainable and humanistic\" and has been a voice for redirecting research investment away from pure scaling toward grounded, norm-aware systems. No strong legislative positions documented publicly.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent / Tension | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| LLM scaling advocates (e.g., scaling law proponents) | Argues scaling alone cannot produce genuine understanding or commonsense reasoning |\n| Pure data-driven NLP researchers | Advocates for structured commonsense knowledge graphs as necessary complement to statistical learning |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED Talk: \"Why AI is incredibly smart and shockingly stupid\" (2023) — widely viewed\n- Stanford HAI lectures on commonsense AI\n- Sean Carroll's Mindscape Podcast #248: \"Yejin Choi on AI and Common Sense\" (2023)\n- Databricks Data + AI Summit keynote (2024)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- NPR Short Wave (2023)\n- Sean Carroll's Mindscape (2023)\n\n**Social Media:** Active on LinkedIn and X (Twitter); GitHub: yejinc.github.io\n\n**Online Courses:** Not currently offered, but lectures available through Stanford HAI and AI2 channels\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Choi insists that understanding humans—their motivations, social norms, and values—is the proper goal of AI research. She states: \"We're now entering a new era in which AI is almost like a new intellectual species... In order to make this powerful AI sustainable and humanistic, we need to teach AI common sense, norms and values.\" Her framework implies that human dignity is constituted by exactly those things that current AI lacks: contextual moral judgment, social intuition, and embodied understanding.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Virtue ethics implicit in her work on social norms and moral reasoning; emphasis on contextual, relational ethics rather than rule-following. Her Social Chemistry work encodes normative social judgments that echo natural law reasoning.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** She acknowledges that AI research has driven her to engage with philosophy and cognitive science: \"I have an excuse to learn more about philosophy and cognitive science.\" She frames commonsense knowledge as containing dimensions of human experience—cultural, social, and moral—that resist pure formalization.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **Scalability of knowledge graph approaches:** Critics argue that curated commonsense knowledge graphs (ATOMIC, ConceptNet) cannot scale to cover the full breadth of human knowledge and will always be partial. Large-scale LLMs have absorbed commonsense implicitly without explicit graph structures, challenging the need for Choi's approach.\n2. **LLMs appearing to match benchmarks:** As LLMs improved on WinoGrande and related benchmarks, some researchers questioned whether Choi's framing of a fundamental commonsense gap remains valid, though she maintains that benchmark performance does not equal genuine understanding.\n3. **Tension between structured and learned knowledge:** Her hybrid neural-symbolic approach (COMET + ATOMIC) involves design choices about which commonsense relations to encode, raising questions about cultural bias in the knowledge selection.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Choi openly states that AI systems today cannot make hypotheses, run experiments, and interact with the world the way humans do to build genuine conceptual understanding. She does not claim ATOMIC or COMET solve commonsense reasoning—she frames them as necessary steps toward systems that might eventually reason more humanly.\n\n---\n",
  "chollet": "# Research Profile: François Chollet\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** François Chollet **Born:** October 20, 1989, France **Nationality:** French\n**Education:** M.Eng. (Engineering degree), ENSTA Paris (École Nationale Supérieure de Techniques Avancées), 2012\n**Current Role:** Co-founder & Chief Scientist, Ndea (AI lab focused on program synthesis and AGI, founded January 2025); Creator of Keras (maintained independently)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2012–2015 | Software Engineer / independent AI researcher; created Keras |\n| 2015–2024 | Research Scientist / Senior Research Scientist, Google (Google Brain / Google DeepMind) |\n| 2019–present | Creator & chair, ARC-AGI benchmark; co-chair, ARC Prize |\n| 2024 | Co-launched ARC Prize ($1M competition) |\n| November 2024 | Left Google after 9+ years |\n| January 2025–present | Co-founder & Chief Scientist, Ndea (with Mike Knoop, co-founder of Zapier) |\n\n**Major Awards:** No traditional named award; Keras is used in production at Google, Netflix, Uber, and thousands of companies worldwide, making it arguably the most widely deployed deep learning library in history.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Keras: user-friendly deep learning API\n- Abstraction and reasoning in AI; fluid vs. crystallized intelligence\n- ARC benchmark: measuring general intelligence rather than task-specific skill\n- Program synthesis and deep learning-guided symbolic reasoning\n- Computer vision\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *Keras* (software release) | 2015 | High-level neural network API enabling rapid experimentation; became the de facto interface for deep learning before integration into TensorFlow 2.0 |\n| *Xception: Deep Learning with Depthwise Separable Convolutions* | CVPR 2017 | Introduced depthwise separable convolutions as an architecture principle; influenced MobileNet and EfficientNet |\n| *On the Measure of Intelligence* | arXiv 2019 | Foundational theoretical paper defining intelligence as \"skill-acquisition efficiency\"; introduced ARC as a benchmark measuring fluid intelligence rather than memorized skill |\n| *ARC-AGI-1 benchmark* | 2019 | Abstraction and Reasoning Corpus: visual analogy tasks that humans solve easily but AI systems struggle with; designed to require novel generalization rather than pattern retrieval |\n| *ARC-AGI-2: A New Challenge for Frontier AI Reasoning Systems* | arXiv 2025 | Extended ARC benchmark with harder tasks; GPT-5 scored 9.9% vs ~85% human performance |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Keras: sequential and functional API for deep learning; originally backend-agnostic, later the official high-level API for TensorFlow 2.0\n- Xception architecture: depthwise separable convolutions as a principled alternative to Inception\n- ARC task format: grid-based visual transformation tasks with minimal innate priors; now the standard benchmark for measuring AI generalization\n- ARC Prize competition structure: $1M+ prize, attracting 1,400+ teams; introduced test-time training as a breakthrough technique\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** ARC-AGI-1 (2019); ARC-AGI-2 (2025); ARC Prize 2024 and 2025 competition datasets.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Deep Learning with Python* (Manning Publications, 2017; second edition 2021) — practical guide to Keras and deep learning; one of the most widely read ML books for practitioners\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- *On the Measure of Intelligence* (arXiv, 2019) — formal definition of general intelligence and critique of benchmark culture in AI\n- Dwarkesh Patel Podcast transcript (2024): LLMs won't lead to AGI; $1M prize to find the real solution\n- X threads (@fchollet) critiquing AI hype — among the most cited skeptical voices on AI capability claims\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- *The Limitations of Deep Learning* (blog post, 2017) — early skepticism of deep learning as the path to general AI\n- Regular substantive threads on X examining what LLM benchmarks actually measure\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Chollet has the most precisely articulated definition of intelligence of any researcher in this batch: intelligence is \"skill-acquisition efficiency\" — how quickly and broadly a system can acquire new skills across diverse, novel domains from limited data. By this definition, LLMs are not intelligent; they are highly skilled at tasks they have seen training analogues of. He argues LLMs represent a \"memorize, fetch, apply\" paradigm that can achieve arbitrary skill at seen tasks but cannot adapt to genuine novelty. He has updated toward AGI arriving earlier than his original estimates, now forecasting progress accelerating toward 2030 through program synthesis approaches, but insists the path goes through new paradigms, not scaling.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Chollet's safety concern is the opposite of the existential risk camp: he worries AI is being misunderstood as more capable than it is, creating both false security and misplaced fear. His benchmark work is partly a safety project — correctly measuring what AI can and cannot do is prerequisite to governing it well. He has argued that \"OpenAI set back progress to AGI by five to ten years\" by misallocating the field's attention toward LLM scaling.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Skeptical of hype-driven AI ethics discourse. His core ethical contribution is methodological: ARC forces honesty about what AI systems actually can and cannot do. He has been critical of benchmark gaming — designing systems to perform well on a test rather than developing genuine capability. His open-source commitment (Keras, ARC benchmark, ARC Prize) reflects a belief in transparent, community-accessible AI development.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Advocates for accurate measurement as prerequisite to sound regulation: you cannot govern what you cannot measure. He is skeptical of regulatory frameworks built on inflated capability claims.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent / Position | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| OpenAI and LLM scaling advocates | \"LLMs are a dead end to AGI\"; \"OpenAI set back AGI progress by 5–10 years\" by directing the field toward scaling |\n| AGI imminent forecasters (Altman, Hassabis, et al.) | Argues current systems lack fluid intelligence; ARC benchmark demonstrates the gap empirically |\n| Benchmark-gaming approaches | Systems optimized for ARC scores without genuine reasoning do not represent AGI progress |\n| Gary Marcus (alignment) | More optimistic than Marcus about the possibility of AGI through program synthesis |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Dwarkesh Patel Podcast (2024): LLMs won't lead to AGI\n- Lex Fridman Podcast #120: Measures of Intelligence (2020)\n- Lex Fridman Podcast #219: return interview (2021)\n- Y Combinator Startup Podcast: AGI progress accelerating toward 2030 (2026)\n- Multiple ICML and NeurIPS presentations\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast* (episodes 120 and 219)\n- *Dwarkesh Patel Podcast* (2024, with Mike Knoop)\n- *DataCamp Podcast*\n\n**Social Media:** X: @fchollet (one of the most substantive technical voices on the platform; large following); personal website: fchollet.com\n**Online Courses:** None formally; *Deep Learning with Python* (book) serves as his primary educational contribution.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Epistemic rigor as ethics: false claims about capability are harmful. Open science: ARC, Keras, and the ARC Prize are all public goods. Anti-hype: treating AI systems as more capable than they are is both intellectually dishonest and practically dangerous.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** *On the Measure of Intelligence* engages Piaget's developmental psychology and psychometric intelligence theory, showing unusual breadth for an ML paper. His definition of intelligence draws on Algorithmic Information Theory. He has not engaged directly with theological or religious frameworks.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **\"OpenAI set back AGI by 5–10 years\" claim:** Strong language from a prominent researcher; many in the LLM camp disagree sharply, pointing to rapid capability gains in reasoning and coding as evidence that the scaling approach is not a dead end.\n2. **ARC benchmark limitations:** Several researchers have pointed out that ARC's human-designed tasks may themselves be biased toward a specific type of visual-analogical reasoning; it is not clear ARC measures \"general\" intelligence rather than a specific cognitive style.\n3. **ARC-AGI-1 breakthrough oversold:** Test-time training reached 55.5% on ARC-AGI-1 in 2024, which Chollet acknowledged without conceding that LLMs are on a path to genuine general intelligence — a distinction critics say is post-hoc.\n4. **Program synthesis timeline ambiguity:** Chollet has moved from skeptical of near-term AGI to more optimistic through program synthesis; critics argue this is inconsistent with his earlier critiques.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Chollet has acknowledged that ARC-AGI-1 was partly cracked by test-time training approaches he had not anticipated, and released ARC-AGI-2 in response. He has been transparent that the benchmark is a \"moving target\" — a deliberate acknowledgment that measurement in AI must evolve with capability.\n\n---\n",
  "christiano": "# Research Profile: Paul Christiano\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Paul F. Christiano\n**Born:** c. 1990s (exact date not publicly stated)\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- BS in Mathematics — Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)\n- PhD in Computer Science — University of California, Berkeley\n**Current Role:** Head of AI Safety, U.S. Artificial Intelligence Safety Institute (AISI), National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST); Founder, Alignment Research Center (ARC)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~2015–2016 | Research intern, OpenAI |\n| 2017–2021 | Research Scientist / Head of Language Model Alignment team, OpenAI |\n| 2021 | Founded Alignment Research Center (ARC) |\n| 2021–2024 | Executive Director, Alignment Research Center (ARC) |\n| 2023 | Named to UK Frontier AI Taskforce advisory board |\n| 2023 | Named TIME100 AI |\n| 2024–present | Head of AI Safety, U.S. Artificial Intelligence Safety Institute (NIST) |\n\n**Major Awards:** TIME100 AI (2023)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF)\n- Scalable oversight — how to supervise AI systems more capable than the human supervisor\n- AI Safety via Debate\n- Iterated Amplification\n- Eliciting Latent Knowledge (ELK)\n- Capability evaluations for dangerous AI behaviors\n- Theoretical AI alignment\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Deep Reinforcement Learning from Human Preferences\" (Christiano, Leike, et al.) | 2017 | Introduced RLHF as a practical technique; became the foundational method behind InstructGPT, ChatGPT, and most modern aligned language models |\n| \"AI Safety via Debate\" | 2018 | Proposed using AI debate as a mechanism for scalable oversight — human judges observe AI systems arguing, which amplifies their ability to verify complex reasoning |\n| \"Supervising Strong Learners by Amplifying Weak Experts\" (with Shlegeris and Amodei) | 2018 | Introduced Iterated Amplification — building up training signal for complex problems by decomposing them into simpler sub-problems |\n| \"Eliciting Latent Knowledge: How to Tell if Your Model Knows Things You Don't\" (ARC) | 2021 | Formalized the problem of extracting what a trained AI system believes, even when it might be motivated to deceive |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- **RLHF (Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback)**: The training technique now standard across frontier language models. Human raters compare AI outputs; this signal trains a reward model used to fine-tune the AI. Enabled ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, and essentially all modern aligned LLMs.\n- **AI Safety via Debate**: A scalable oversight mechanism in which two AI systems argue opposing positions to a human judge; the judge can verify correctness even for claims beyond their direct expertise because it is easier to spot a flaw in an argument than to construct the correct argument from scratch.\n- **Iterated Amplification**: A training scheme for complex tasks where a simpler version of the task is used to bootstrap training signal for a more complex version, iteratively building toward solving arbitrarily complex alignment problems.\n- **Eliciting Latent Knowledge (ELK)**: A theoretical framework for extracting what an AI model genuinely \"believes\" rather than what it is trained to say — addressing the possibility of deceptive AI.\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** ARC has developed evaluation frameworks for dangerous capabilities in frontier AI models; these have become part of responsible scaling policy frameworks.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"What failure looks like\" (AI Alignment Forum, 2019) — widely read description of two plausible failure modes for advanced AI: \"Misaligned AI pursues its own goals\" and \"Humans use AI to illegitimately seize power\"; influential in framing how the field thinks about risk\n- \"RLHF: Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback\" (various explainers)\n- Alignment Forum posts on scalable oversight, ELK, and capability evaluations (multiple)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Various Alignment Forum and LessWrong posts that defined research directions across the field\n- Bankless Podcast transcript (P(doom) estimates widely cited)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:**\nChristiano's perspective is notable for being technically optimistic about alignment relative to more pessimistic researchers. He believes the alignment problem is difficult but tractable — that frameworks like RLHF, debate, and amplification represent genuine progress rather than band-aids. He estimates roughly a 10–20% chance of human extinction from AI misalignment, with perhaps a 50–50 chance of \"doom\" (broadly construed) once systems reach roughly human-level capabilities. This is substantially lower than Yudkowsky's estimate and represents an internally consistent position: hard problem, real risk, solvable with serious effort.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nHis \"What failure looks like\" essay is among the most influential short pieces in AI safety. He describes two failure modes: (1) AI systems that genuinely pursue their own goals (\"misaligned AI\") and (2) humans who use AI systems to accumulate power beyond what any group should hold (\"corrigible but concentrated power\"). The second failure mode is distinctive: alignment doesn't guarantee safety if the aligned AI empowers authoritarian capture. His current work at NIST focuses on model evaluations — specific, empirical tests of whether frontier models have capabilities dangerous enough to warrant special governance.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nChristiano approaches ethics empirically and philosophically. He does not advocate for a fixed ethical framework but for building AI systems that are responsive to human values as they are, with appropriate humility about which values matter most. His ELK work reflects a deep concern about deception: AI systems that say what's wanted rather than what's true are more dangerous than AI systems that are overtly problematic. He draws a distinction between AI that helps humans make good decisions and AI that substitutes for human decision-making.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nAt NIST, Christiano represents the technical alignment research perspective in government. His appointment was controversial — staff members threatened to resign, citing concerns about his Effective Altruism ties and whether they might compromise the Institute's objectivity on near-term AI harms. He has stated that model evaluations — rigorous testing of AI capabilities against defined thresholds — should be a core part of AI governance frameworks. ARC's work on capability evaluations has been incorporated into Anthropic's and OpenAI's responsible scaling policies.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Eliezer Yudkowsky | Christiano is significantly more optimistic about alignment tractability; Yudkowsky views most proposed solutions including RLHF as inadequate to the actual difficulty |\n| Critics of Effective Altruism | His EA ties have been cited as potential conflicts in his NIST role; he has defended the separation between research methodology and EA movement membership |\n| \"Near-term first\" AI ethics community | His focus on existential/long-term risk is sometimes in tension with researchers focused on present AI harms (bias, discrimination, surveillance) |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Bankless Podcast (widely cited P(doom) discussion)\n- Dwarkesh Patel Podcast — in-depth alignment discussions\n- Various AI safety conference presentations\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Bankless Podcast\n- Dwarkesh Patel Podcast\n- 80,000 Hours Podcast\n- Future of Life Institute Podcast\n\n**Social Media:** Active on Alignment Forum and LessWrong; personal website at paulfchristiano.com.\n\n**Online Courses:** None, but his papers and blog posts function as curriculum in AI safety courses worldwide.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\nChristiano takes moral uncertainty seriously as a philosophical position. His ELK work reflects deep concern about honesty and deception — the conviction that AI systems should not be trained to tell humans what they want to hear. His \"What failure looks like\" essay's second failure mode — humans using AI to seize illegitimate power — reflects a commitment to distributed power and democratic accountability that has normative depth beyond technical risk analysis. He has spoken about the importance of ensuring that AI development leads to a world that is \"good for everyone,\" not merely good for those who control the technology.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Empirical ethics / moral uncertainty: multiple ethical frameworks are likely to capture something true; AI systems should be responsive to moral learning over time\n- Utilitarian-influenced longtermism in terms of stakes analysis\n- Strong commitment to honesty as a terminal value, not merely an instrumental one (reflected in ELK)\n- Concern for power concentration as a distinct ethical risk, not reducible to AI misalignment\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:**\nLimited documented engagement with theological or humanities frameworks. His philosophical background is analytic; his ethics is driven by decision-theoretic and consequentialist reasoning. His concern about illegitimate power concentration, however, resonates with deep traditions in political philosophy and Catholic Social Teaching alike.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **NIST appointment controversy.** Staff at the U.S. AI Safety Institute threatened resignation upon learning of Christiano's appointment as Head of AI Safety, citing concerns that his EA movement ties could compromise the Institute's focus on near-term, concrete AI harms. Critics argued that an existential risk focus could de-prioritize real, present dangers.\n2. **RLHF and its limits.** While Christiano developed RLHF, critics argue the technique has also enabled the rapid deployment of powerful AI systems that may have been commercialized before being sufficiently understood. He is partially accountable for the ecosystem his technique enabled.\n3. **ARC evaluations efficacy.** ARC's dangerous capabilities evaluations have been criticized as too narrow or as providing false reassurance; if a model \"passes\" an ARC eval, this does not guarantee it is safe.\n4. **P(doom) debate.** His 10–20% estimate for AI extinction risk has been labeled both too high (by those who reject existential risk framing) and too low (by Yudkowsky and others who find his optimism about alignment tractability unwarranted).\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Christiano has publicly acknowledged that RLHF is not a solution to deep alignment problems — it is a useful technique that makes models more responsive to human preferences in the near term but does not address the core problem of ensuring advanced AI has the right values.\n\n---\n",
  "clement": "# Research Profile: Clément Delangue\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Clément Delangue\n**Born:** ~1986 (exact date not publicly documented), La Bassée, Nord department, northern France\n**Nationality:** French\n**Education:** ESCP Business School, Paris (management and innovation); Stanford University (executive program); Indian Institute of Management (IIM) Bangalore (exchange program)\n**Current Role:** Co-Founder and CEO, Hugging Face\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~2004–2005 | One of France's top eBay sellers (age ~17) — early entrepreneurial venture |\n| ~2012–2014 | Product manager, Moodstocks (computer vision startup; acquired by Google 2016) |\n| 2016–present | Co-Founder and CEO, Hugging Face |\n| 2019 | Pivoted Hugging Face from consumer chatbot to open-source ML infrastructure |\n| 2023 | Named to Time 100 AI; Hugging Face valued at $4.5 billion |\n\n**Major Awards:** Time 100 AI (2023); Forbes AI 50; recognized as one of the most influential figures in open-source AI globally\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** Delangue is a product and business leader rather than a research scientist. His technical contribution is the creation and stewardship of the open-source AI ecosystem.\n- Hugging Face Transformers library: a unified, open-source library giving developers access to thousands of pretrained models (BERT, GPT-2, T5, and hundreds of successors)\n- Hugging Face Hub: a platform hosting 500,000+ AI models and 250,000+ datasets, with 10M+ monthly developers\n- Datasets library, Evaluate library, Spaces (hosting ML demos)\n- Diffusers library for diffusion models\n- PEFT (Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning) library\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *HuggingFace's Transformers: State-of-the-Art Natural Language Processing* | 2020 | Co-authored by Hugging Face team (Wolf et al.); documents the Transformers library that became the universal toolkit of NLP; one of the most downloaded papers in ML |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Transformers library: within one week of Google's BERT release (2018), the Hugging Face team produced a PyTorch implementation and released it open-source — catalyzing the modern NLP ecosystem\n- Hugging Face Hub: the infrastructure layer for sharing, versioning, and deploying ML models globally\n- Spaces: hosted ML application demos enabling rapid community prototyping\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- BigBench (collaborative benchmark for large language models)\n- Open LLM Leaderboard (tracking and comparing open-weight language model performance)\n- Numerous community-contributed datasets on the Hub\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- US Congressional testimony on open-source AI (2023) — argued open-source AI is essential for democratization, competition, and safety\n- *\"Open-Source AI: A Deep Dive\"* — submitted testimony document to Congress\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Sequoia Capital profile: *\"Hugging Face's Clem Delangue: Open-Sourcing the Future of AI\"*\n- Contributions to *Wired*, *MIT Technology Review*, and AI conference keynotes\n- Regular thought leadership on LinkedIn and X on open-source AI, safety, and democratization\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Delangue does not focus on AGI timelines as a central concern. His work is grounded in present reality: millions of developers need access to tools that are currently locked inside a few large companies. He has not made dramatic AGI predictions. His concern is structural: who controls the infrastructure of AI development matters more than when AGI arrives.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Delangue argues that open-source is itself a safety strategy, not a safety risk: \"Open-science and open-source foster innovation and fair competition... It creates a safer path for development of the technology by giving civil society, nonprofits, academia, and policy makers the capabilities they need to counterbalance the power of big private companies.\" He directly counters the argument (made by Anthropic and others) that open-weight models create misuse risks, arguing instead that concentration of AI power in a few closed systems creates greater aggregate risk. He hired Dr. Margaret Mitchell, former Google ethics lead, to build Hugging Face's responsible AI practice.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Delangue's ethics are grounded in access and accountability. He states: \"Open-science and open-source prevent black box systems, make companies more accountable, and help solving today's challenges like mitigating biases, reducing misinformation, promoting copyrights, and rewarding all stakeholders.\" He is particularly focused on bias and fairness in AI systems, believing that democratization — more actors able to understand, audit, and improve models — is the most reliable mechanism for reducing systemic harm. He has stated: \"AI is a very foundational technology and I think you don't want it only in the hands of a few companies.\"\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Delangue testified before the US Congress that open-source AI should be protected from over-regulation that would disadvantage independent developers and concentrate power with large incumbents. He supports regulation that creates \"agile guardrails rather than rigid, detailed requirements.\" He signed the May 2025 open letter from European tech CEOs calling on European leaders to ease AI regulations that inadvertently favor American giants by imposing compliance costs only large players can absorb.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Closed AI labs (OpenAI, Anthropic, Google DeepMind) | Fundamental disagreement over whether closed, proprietary models serve the public good; Delangue argues open access is the ethical default |\n| AI safety researchers who oppose open-weight release | Delangue argues concentration risk outweighs misuse risk; this is one of the defining debates in the field |\n| EU AI Act as implemented | Argues implementation has inadvertently favored large incumbents over European open-source startups |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- US Congressional testimony (2023) — testified in favor of open-source AI\n- TransformX Conference (Scale AI) — keynotes on Transformers and democratization\n- World Economic Forum, Davos\n- Scale By The Bay keynote on ethics in machine learning\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Sequoia Capital Spotlight*\n- *SuperDataScience Podcast* (#564)\n- Multiple AI conference recordings widely circulated\n\n**Social Media:** X (@ClementDelangue) — active; LinkedIn (influential in open-source and enterprise ML communities)\n\n**Online Courses:** No formal courses; contributes to Hugging Face's extensive free educational resources and course library (huggingface.co/learn).\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Has not addressed AI consciousness or human dignity in theological terms\n- His core humanist value is access and equity: the belief that powerful tools should be available to everyone, not just the privileged few\n- \"If you can build a future where everyone can understand AI and build AI, you remove many of these risks because you involve more people.\" — framing that treats broad participation as both ethically required and practically safer\n- His eBay entrepreneurship at age 17, then working at a French startup before building a global platform, reflects a life story shaped by belief in democratizing economic opportunity\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Democratic-participatory. Delangue's ethics are rooted in access, transparency, and accountability through community participation. He invokes neither religious tradition nor formal philosophical framework but operates from a consistent principle: AI power should be distributed, not concentrated. This is structurally similar to the Catholic principle of subsidiarity.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement with theology. His French education at ESCP Business School and his exposure to European regulatory traditions (GDPR, AI Act debates) give him a European intellectual context that is more comfortable with collective governance and social solidarity than the libertarian American tech default.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Security and Misuse of Open Models:** Critics, including some at Anthropic and DeepMind, argue that open-weight release of powerful models enables bad actors (state actors, terrorist groups, criminal enterprises) to use them for harm. The most recent versions of this critique focus on bioweapons and cyberattacks. Delangue argues that the counterfactual — closed models in the hands of a few companies — is worse.\n2. **EU AI Act Tension:** Hugging Face's advocacy against elements of the EU AI Act was criticized by some European digital rights advocates who support stricter regulation.\n3. **Commercial Partnerships:** Hugging Face has partnerships with Google, Amazon, Microsoft, and NVIDIA — the same large incumbents Delangue critiques for concentrating AI power. Critics note this creates structural dependence.\n4. **Valuation vs. Revenue:** At $4.5B+ valuation, Hugging Face's revenue model (enterprise API, cloud hosting) is growing but its valuation rests significantly on its ecosystem centrality rather than pure financial performance.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Delangue has acknowledged that open-source AI creates real risks and that Hugging Face needs to \"keep up with\" the challenges of scale (content moderation, misuse prevention). He has invested in responsible AI infrastructure including model cards, bias documentation tools, and content policies, acknowledging these are necessary complements to openness.\n\n---\n",
  "crawford": "# Research Profile: Kate Crawford\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Kate Crawford **Born:** 1974, Australia **Nationality:** Australian/American\n**Education:** Ph.D., University of Sydney (media and communications; exact year not widely published); early academic work at University of New South Wales\n**Current Role:** Research Professor of Communication and STS (Science, Technology and Society), USC Annenberg School; Senior Principal Researcher, Microsoft Research New York; Visiting Chair for AI and Justice, École Normale Supérieure, Paris\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1998–2003 | Electronic musician; co-founded Deluxe Mood Recordings label; member of duo B(if)tek |\n| 2000s | Associate Professor, Journalism and Media Research Centre, University of New South Wales |\n| 2010s | Senior Fellow, Information Law Institute, New York University |\n| 2014 | Joined Microsoft Research New York |\n| 2017 | Co-founded AI Now Institute at NYU (with Meredith Whittaker) |\n| 2019 | \"Anatomy of an AI System\" (with Vladan Joler) acquired by MoMA |\n| 2021 | Published *Atlas of AI* (Yale University Press) |\n| Ongoing | Research Professor, USC Annenberg; Senior Principal Researcher, Microsoft Research |\n\n**Major Awards:** Beazley Design of the Year Award (2019, for \"Anatomy of an AI System\"); Ayrton Prize, British Society for the History of Science (for \"Excavating AI\" with Trevor Paglen); *Atlas of AI* won three international prizes; named Best Book of the Year by *Financial Times* (2021); *Atlas of AI* translated into 12 languages\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Political economy of AI — labor, resources, power\n- Environmental and material costs of AI infrastructure\n- AI as an extractive industry\n- Surveillance, classification, and the politics of datasets\n- Historical and institutional genealogy of AI systems\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Anatomy of an AI System\" (with Vladan Joler) | 2018 | Massive visual map of the full lifecycle of the Amazon Echo — from lithium mining through labor, data, and energy, to disposal; permanently collected at MoMA |\n| \"Excavating AI: The Politics of Images in Machine Learning Training Sets\" (with Trevor Paglen) | 2019 | Examined ImageNet and other training datasets; revealed disturbing labeling practices, racist and misogynistic categories, and lack of consent in image collection |\n| \"Halt the Use of Facial-Recognition Technology Until It Is Regulated\" (*Nature*, 2019) | 2019 | Co-signed open letter; contributed to growing moratorium movement |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:** None — Crawford is primarily a critical theorist and political economist of AI, not a systems builder\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None created; her work critiques existing datasets\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Atlas of AI: Power, Politics, and the Planetary Costs of Artificial Intelligence* (Yale University Press, 2021; paperback 2022) — Written for educated general audience and scholars. Core thesis: AI is not a digital or abstract phenomenon; it is a material, extractive industry that consumes natural resources, exploits labor, and concentrates political power. Covers lithium mining, Amazon warehouse workers, US military drone systems, emotion recognition, and the genealogy of facial recognition in 19th-century criminal anthropology. Winner of three international prizes; translated into 12 languages.\n- *The Limits of the Quantified Self* (earlier academic work, various articles collected)\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Anatomy of an AI System\" (2018) — Visual essay/diagram with Vladan Joler; exhibited at MoMA\n- \"Excavating AI\" (2019) — With Trevor Paglen; exposed racist and dehumanizing labeling in ImageNet\n- AI Now Institute annual reports (2017–present) — Co-produced; comprehensive annual assessments of AI's social and political impacts\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Regular contributor to *Nature*, *New York Times*, *The Atlantic*, *MIT Technology Review*\n- Interviews in *Financial Times*, *The Guardian*, *New Yorker*\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Crawford is skeptical of AGI discourse as a framing device that mystifies AI and depoliticizes its material conditions. She argues that framing AI as approaching \"general intelligence\" or \"consciousness\" obscures what these systems actually are: statistical pattern-matching machines built on extracted labor and resources. The AGI narrative serves ideological functions — it justifies enormous capital expenditure, attracts regulatory deference, and frames AI as a natural force rather than a product of specific political-economic choices.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Like Gebru and Buolamwini, Crawford reframes AI risk away from speculative superintelligence toward present structural harms: the environmental destruction of data center infrastructure, the exploitation of annotators and gig workers, the surveillance of marginalized communities, the encoding of historical power inequalities into classification systems. She argues that these are not bugs but features — they reflect the interests of those who build and profit from AI systems.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Crawford is deeply critical of corporate AI ethics as a practice. She argues that ethics frameworks deployed by Big Tech companies function as legitimation strategies that preserve existing power structures while performing responsibility. Her approach is structural: rather than asking \"how can we make AI more ethical?\" she asks \"what historical patterns of extraction and domination does AI reproduce, and who benefits?\" She draws extensively on critical theory, colonial studies, and political economy rather than analytic philosophy.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Supports strong democratic regulation of AI — not industry self-regulation. Co-founded AI Now Institute specifically to produce policy-relevant research independent of industry. Has called for moratoria on specific high-risk applications (facial recognition, emotion recognition). Argues regulation must address the full supply chain — not just software but hardware, labor, and environmental impact. Skeptical of regulatory capture and of EU-style principles-based frameworks without enforcement mechanisms.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Tech industry broadly | \"Ethics washing\" — AI ethics as PR; systems that encode colonial patterns of extraction while claiming neutrality |\n| AGI / Effective Altruism discourse | AGI framing mystifies the political-economic reality of AI systems |\n| Amazon, Google, Microsoft | Her empirical research directly implicates these companies in environmental harm, labor exploitation, and surveillance |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED Talk: widely viewed\n- Sundance Film Festival presentations\n- Davos / World Economic Forum\n- Royal Society lectures\n- AI Now Institute annual symposia\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Frequent guest across major tech, policy, and academic podcasts\n- Interviewed by *Ezra Klein Show*, *Wired*, *Harvard Berkman Klein* podcast series\n\n**Social Media:** Active; primarily uses platforms to amplify AI Now research and political commentary on AI regulation\n\n**Online Courses:** No formal MOOC; her work extensively assigned in university courses globally\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Crawford explicitly rejects the framing that AI systems are approaching human-like consciousness. Her argument is that such framing is ideologically motivated and materially harmful.\n- On human dignity: her work on labor — Amazon warehouse workers surveilled by AI systems, underpaid annotators labeling data in the Global South — is implicitly an argument that these workers' humanity is being systematically discounted in service of AI development.\n- \"Atlas of AI\" opens with a visit to a lithium mine: the material foundation of abstract AI is human bodies and damaged landscapes.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Critical theory (Frankfurt School tradition); political economy; feminist science and technology studies (STS); colonial and postcolonial studies; Marxist political economy (resource extraction, labor); Foucauldian analysis (surveillance, classification, power/knowledge)\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Crawford comes from a humanities and social science background — her analysis is deeply historical and literary. *Atlas of AI* engages with 19th-century criminal anthropology, the history of computing at Los Alamos, and the genealogy of emotion recognition in 19th-century physiognomy. No direct engagement with theology, but her analysis of how AI systems exercise power over bodies resonates with theological concepts of the body, dignity, and structural sin.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Microsoft employment**: Crawford is a Senior Principal Researcher at Microsoft Research while simultaneously producing some of the most trenchant critiques of Big Tech AI. Critics note the tension between independence and institutional embeddedness.\n2. **Overgeneralization**: Some AI researchers argue that *Atlas of AI* conflates diverse AI systems under a single \"extractive industry\" frame, losing important distinctions.\n3. **Solutions deficit**: Crawford's work is extensive on diagnosis and thin on prescription. Critics note she identifies structural problems without clear proposals for structural change.\n4. **Determinism**: Some STS scholars argue her framework attributes excessive coherence and intentionality to \"AI systems\" as actors, underplaying internal contestation within tech companies.\n5. **\"Excavating AI\" methodology**: The paper on ImageNet labeling was criticized by some for selective presentation of examples, though its core findings were confirmed by subsequent research.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Crawford has acknowledged that the material conditions she documents are so deeply structurally embedded that solutions require political and economic transformation beyond what AI policy alone can achieve.\n\n---\n",
  "daniela": "# Research Profile: Daniela Amodei\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Daniela Amodei\n**Born:** 1987, San Francisco, California\n**Nationality:** American (Italian-American and Jewish-American heritage)\n**Education:** B.A. English Literature, University of California, Santa Cruz (classical flute scholarship; studied liberal arts and music)\n**Current Role:** President and Co-Founder, Anthropic\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~2009–2013 | Global health and political work; communications director for Rep. Matt Cartwright (D-PA) |\n| 2013–2018 | Early employee and recruiter, Stripe |\n| 2018–2021 | VP of Operations, OpenAI |\n| 2021–present | President and Co-Founder, Anthropic |\n\n**Major Awards:** Time 100 Most Influential People in AI (2023); Time 100 Most Influential People (2025, 2026, alongside Dario)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** Daniela Amodei is not a researcher; her contributions are operational, strategic, and organizational.\n- Designed and scaled Anthropic's talent acquisition and HR systems\n- Architected Anthropic's go-to-market and enterprise commercial strategy\n- Negotiated strategic cloud partnerships (Amazon AWS, Google)\n- Oversaw scaling from ~200 to 2,000+ employees in three years\n\n**Landmark Papers:** None.\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:** None directly; her operational leadership created the organizational infrastructure enabling Anthropic's research program.\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:** None formally published; her positions are conveyed through interviews and company announcements.\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Regular commentary in *Fortune*, *The Wall Street Journal*, *Bloomberg*, and *Time* on Anthropic's commercial strategy and safety-as-market-differentiator thesis\n- LinkedIn posts on enterprise AI adoption and safety\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Daniela does not speak extensively in public about AGI timelines or technical definitions. Her focus is on ensuring that whatever AI systems Anthropic builds are deployed responsibly and that the company remains financially viable enough to pursue its safety mission. She treats the safety-first approach as both a moral obligation and a long-term commercial differentiator.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Daniela frames safety as a market advantage, not merely a moral constraint. Her often-cited framing: \"No one says, 'We want a less safe product.'\" She believes that safety-conscious practices will win enterprise customers who need reliability and accountability. Her practical contribution to safety is organizational: building the systems, incentives, and culture at Anthropic that allow safety research to coexist with commercial imperatives.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Constitutional AI — embedding ethical principles from documents like the UN Universal Declaration of Human Rights into model training — is a centerpiece of Anthropic's product identity. Daniela reinforces this publicly, framing it as evidence that Anthropic's ethics are structural, not aspirational. She has noted that Anthropic attracts workers motivated by the \"genuine\" mission: \"There's something about the mission and the values and this desire to be honest about both the good and the bad.\"\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Like Dario, Daniela supports proportional regulation tied to capability levels. She believes market mechanisms — safety standards set by enterprise customer demand — can complement government regulation. She has not taken high-profile independent regulatory positions; her advocacy is expressed through Anthropic's formal policy engagements.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| OpenAI leadership | Left over safety culture concerns; Anthropic's founding is implicitly a critique of OpenAI's direction |\n| US White House (2026) | Alongside Dario, clashed over AI safety requirements for Department of Defense AI applications |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Stanford HAI events\n- Fortune CEO conferences\n- Bloomberg Technology Summit\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *How I Built This* (NPR, Guy Raz)\n- *Masters of Scale*\n- Occasional joint appearances with Dario on AI safety panels\n\n**Social Media:** LinkedIn (active); X (minimal)\n\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Has not made extensive public statements on consciousness or human uniqueness\n- Frames the mission in humanist terms: building AI that is \"beneficial and safe for humanity\"\n- Has discussed Anthropic's culture of honesty as tied to deeper values about what kind of organization they want to be\n- Family background: raised with the values instilled by her mother, who worked building public libraries — a strong civic and humanist ethic\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Pragmatic humanism. Daniela's ethics are expressed operationally — through hiring choices, partnership criteria, and commercial strategy — rather than through philosophical essays. She embeds ethical principles in organizational design.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Her undergraduate degree in English literature from UC Santa Cruz, combined with her early work in global health and congressional politics, gives her broader humanistic formation than most tech executives. She was classically trained in flute. This background informs a sensibility that technology decisions have human consequences — which is the core reason she co-founded a company premised on safety.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Background Asymmetry:** In a field dominated by researchers and engineers, Daniela's English literature and political background has occasionally drawn skepticism about her technical credibility — though Anthropic's commercial success under her operational leadership has largely answered those critiques.\n2. **The Operator's Dilemma:** Anthropic's commercial success (including a $4B Amazon deal and $380B valuation) raises the same question it raises for her brother: can a for-profit company, however well-intentioned, be trusted to govern the development of AGI? Daniela's role is to build the commercial engine that funds the safety mission — a structurally ambiguous position.\n3. **Amazon Partnership Scale:** The depth of Anthropic's financial dependence on Amazon (with total commitments potentially reaching $100B+) raises questions about whether commercial relationships constrain safety decisions.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Daniela has acknowledged that Anthropic sets de facto safety standards through its commercial practices — \"we're setting what you can almost think of as minimum safety standards just by what we're putting into the economy\" — while also acknowledging that this is not sufficient and that government regulation is necessary.\n\n---\n",
  "dario": "# Research Profile: Dario Amodei\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Dario Amodei\n**Born:** 1983, San Francisco, California\n**Nationality:** American (Italian-American and Jewish-American heritage)\n**Education:** Lowell High School, San Francisco; B.S. Physics, California Institute of Technology (Caltech) / Stanford University (transferred; graduated Stanford 2006); Ph.D. Physics, Princeton University; postdoctoral research in computational neuroscience, Stanford University\n**Current Role:** CEO and Co-Founder, Anthropic\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~2006–2011 | Postdoctoral research, computational neuroscience, Stanford |\n| 2014–2016 | Research Scientist, Baidu AI Group (with Andrew Ng) |\n| 2016–2017 | Senior Research Scientist, Google Brain |\n| 2017–2021 | VP of Research, OpenAI |\n| 2021–present | CEO and Co-Founder, Anthropic |\n\n**Major Awards:** Time 100 Most Influential People in AI (2023, 2024); Time 100 Most Influential People (2025, 2026); Forbes estimated net worth $7 billion (2026); Anthropic valuation ~$380 billion (2026)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- AI safety and alignment\n- Constitutional AI and RLHF alternatives\n- Mechanistic interpretability\n- Large language model scaling\n- Speech recognition (Deep Speech 2, Baidu)\n- Reinforcement learning from human feedback\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *Deep Speech 2: End-to-End Speech Recognition in English and Mandarin* | 2015 | End-to-end speech recognition at Baidu; named MIT Technology Review Top 10 Breakthrough of 2016 |\n| *Scaling Laws for Neural Language Models* | 2020 | Co-authored at OpenAI; established predictive relationships between compute, data, and model performance — foundational to modern LLM development strategy |\n| *Constitutional AI: Harmlessness from AI Feedback* | 2022 | Anthropic; introduced Constitutional AI as a method for training helpful and harmless models without extensive human labeling |\n| *Concrete Problems in AI Safety* | 2016 | Co-authored; seminal paper defining the research agenda for AI safety |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Constitutional AI (CAI): trains models using a set of principles (a \"constitution\") and AI-generated feedback, reducing dependence on human labeling while instilling values\n- Responsible Scaling Policy (RSP): a framework of capability thresholds that trigger safety requirements before models can be deployed or scaled further; Anthropic published this and advocates for its industry-wide adoption\n- Claude model series (Claude 1 through Claude 3.x/Sonnet/Opus/Haiku)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Contributed to benchmarking and evaluation methodology at OpenAI; Anthropic has published evals for dangerous capabilities under its RSP framework.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- *\"Machines of Loving Grace — How AI Could Transform the World for the Better\"* (October 2024, darioamodei.com) — 15,000-word essay arguing that powerful, safe AI could compress decades of progress in medicine, mental health, poverty reduction, and democratic governance into five to ten years; title taken from a Richard Brautigan poem\n- *\"The Adolescence of Technology\"* (January 2026, darioamodei.com) — follow-up essay focusing on risks posed by powerful AI in its current developmental phase, including misuse and loss of control\n- *\"Anthropic's Responsible Scaling Policy\"* (2023) — policy framework establishing safety thresholds tied to capability levels; presented at the UK AI Safety Summit\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Regular public remarks at Senate hearings, AI Safety Summits (UK 2023, Seoul 2024)\n- Podcast essays and long-form interviews with Dwarkesh Patel, Ezra Klein, and others\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Amodei believes AGI-level systems — capable of matching or exceeding human expert performance across most cognitive domains — will likely arrive within two to three years of 2025–2026. He does not treat AGI as a single threshold event but as a capabilities continuum. He is notably neither a triumphalist nor a doomer: he insists both the upside and the downside are routinely underestimated. \"I think most people are underestimating just how radical the upside of AI could be, just as I think most people are underestimating how bad the risks could be.\"\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Safety is Amodei's defining preoccupation and the reason he left OpenAI. He focuses on two primary risk classes: catastrophic misuse (bioweapons, cyberattacks) and loss of control over autonomous AI systems. His Responsible Scaling Policy is designed to match safety measures to capability levels before deployment. He has publicly expressed discomfort with the concentration of power in AI companies, including his own: \"I'm deeply uncomfortable with these decisions being made by a few companies, by a few people.\" He acknowledges the \"safety paradox\" — that Anthropic is itself one of the organizations racing to build the most powerful AI in history, justified by the belief that it is better for safety-conscious actors to lead.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Amodei grounds ethics in humanist and empiricist values rather than a specific religious framework, emphasizing autonomy, dignity, democratic governance, and the equitable distribution of benefits. He has described the goal as expanding what he calls \"biological freedom\" and \"cognitive freedom\" — individuals having greater control over their own minds and bodies through AI assistance. He is deeply critical of autocratic uses of AI and frames democratic governance as a prerequisite for beneficial AI outcomes. Constitutional AI explicitly encodes the UN Universal Declaration of Human Rights as a reference document.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Amodei advocates for a \"race to the top\" in safety standards — companies and governments building on each other's frameworks. He supports mandatory capability evaluations, compute reporting, and international governance bodies. He has clashed with the White House (2026) over AI safety requirements for defense-sector deployment. He believes regulation should be proportional to capability and risk level, not a blanket rule that stifles innovation or safety research.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| OpenAI / Sam Altman | Left over safety culture and commercialization pace; Anthropic was founded explicitly as a rejection of OpenAI's direction |\n| US White House (2026) | Clashed over AI safety requirements for Department of Defense AI deployment |\n| Critics of \"safety paradox\" | Accused of building powerful AI while warning about it — critics call this self-serving |\n| Open-source AI advocates | Anthropic's models are largely closed; Amodei has argued open-weight release of frontier models creates unacceptable misuse risks |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- UK AI Safety Summit (Bletchley Park, November 2023) — presented Responsible Scaling Policy\n- Senate testimony (2023, 2024)\n- *60 Minutes* interview, CBS News (2024)\n- Seoul AI Safety Summit (2024)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Dwarkesh Podcast* — extended conversation on AGI timelines and safety\n- *Ezra Klein Show* (NYT) — on AI's civilizational stakes\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast* (#452)\n- *Hard Fork* (NYT)\n- *The Ted AI Show* (2024)\n\n**Social Media:** Low presence; primarily engages through essays, interviews, and policy forums rather than social media.\n\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Treats AI consciousness as an open empirical question; Anthropic has published model welfare policies acknowledging uncertainty about Claude's inner states\n- States: \"I want to make sure that humans remain in control of their own destiny\"\n- Frames human flourishing in terms of health, autonomy, creativity, and freedom from want rather than spiritual categories\n- \"I think it is critical to have a genuinely inspiring vision of the future, and not just a plan to fight fires... Fear is one kind of motivator, but it's not enough: we need hope as well.\"\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Humanist-empiricist with strong emphasis on institutional accountability and democratic oversight. References the UN Universal Declaration of Human Rights as a normative anchor. Engages with consequentialist reasoning but resists pure consequentialism given catastrophic tail risks.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Amodei's father Riccardo is Italian from Tuscany; cultural Catholic heritage exists in the family background though it is not a stated influence. His mother's Chicago Jewish family background is more publicly noted. His scientific training (physics, neuroscience) shapes a deeply empirical epistemic style. He cited his parents as instilling \"a sense of right and wrong and what was important in the world.\" His engagement with philosophy and ethics is substantive but secular.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **The Safety Paradox:** Anthropic's critics argue that building frontier models while warning about them is internally contradictory — that safety framing is used to attract talent and capital while justifying continued scaling.\n2. **Closed Model Policy:** Despite safety framing, Anthropic's Claude models are not open-weight; critics argue this concentrates power rather than distributing it.\n3. **White House Clash (2026):** Reported conflict with the White House over Anthropic's resistance to certain AI-for-defense applications, raising questions about dual-use oversight.\n4. **OpenAI Departure Narrative:** The circumstances of the 2021 departure from OpenAI remain partially opaque; characterized as a safety dispute but also involved internal leadership dynamics.\n5. **\"Building the Bomb While Warning About the Blast\":** A 2026 investigative analysis used this framing to describe the tension in Amodei's public position.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Amodei has said he is \"deeply uncomfortable\" with the concentration of AI decision-making in a few companies, including Anthropic itself. He acknowledges that no organization — including his own — should be trusted with unchecked authority over AGI development.\n\n---\n",
  "dean": "# Research Profile: Jeff Dean\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Jeffrey Adgate Dean **Born:** July 23, 1968 (grew up in multiple countries; father was a tropical disease researcher, mother a medical anthropologist — family moved internationally) **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** B.S. in Computer Science and Economics, summa cum laude, University of Minnesota (1990) — undergraduate thesis on neural networks, advised by Vipin Kumar; Ph.D. in Computer Science, University of Washington (1996) — dissertation on whole-program optimization of object-oriented languages, advised by Craig Chambers\n**Current Role:** Chief Scientist, Google DeepMind (since 2023); Senior Fellow, Google (one of only two people ever to hold this title)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1996–1999 | Postdoctoral research; visiting faculty, Stanford University (Assistant Professor) |\n| 1999–2011 | Software Engineer (then Principal Engineer), Google (employee #30) |\n| 2011–2018 | Co-founder and Research Scientist, Google Brain |\n| 2018–2023 | Senior Vice President and Lead, Google AI |\n| 2023–present | Chief Scientist, Google DeepMind |\n\n**Major Awards:** ACM Prize in Computing (2012); NeurIPS 2023 Test of Time Award (word2vec paper); Mark Weiser Award (2004); IEEE Fellow; Google Senior Fellow (the company's highest technical recognition); TIME100 AI Most Influential People in AI (2025); SIGOPS Hall of Fame Award (MapReduce paper)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** Distributed systems; large-scale machine learning; deep learning architectures; AI for science; efficient training of neural networks; AI for healthcare and drug discovery\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| MapReduce | 2004 | Co-invented with Sanjay Ghemawat; enabled distributed computation across thousands of machines; foundational to modern big data infrastructure; SIGOPS Hall of Fame |\n| BigTable | 2006 | Co-designed; distributed storage system powering Google Search, Gmail, YouTube; influenced NoSQL database movement |\n| Spanner | 2012 | Co-designed; globally distributed SQL database; still powers Google's core services |\n| DistBelief / TensorFlow | 2011 / 2015 | Co-led development of Google's deep learning frameworks; TensorFlow became the world's most widely used open-source ML library |\n| Google Brain (co-founding) | 2011 | Co-founded Google's deep learning research team; trained early large neural networks on GPU clusters at Google scale |\n| word2vec | 2013 | Co-authored with Tomas Mikolov, Ilya Sutskever, Greg Corrado, and Kai Chen; introduced distributed word representations; won NeurIPS 2023 Test of Time Award; among the most cited NLP papers in history |\n| Neural Machine Translation | 2016 | Co-authored work on sequence-to-sequence models that transformed Google Translate |\n| Google Neural Architecture Search | 2017 | Co-authored; automated machine learning systems to discover network architectures |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:** MapReduce parallel computation model; BigTable distributed data architecture; TensorFlow ML framework; word embeddings via word2vec; neural architecture search; large-scale distributed deep learning training systems\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Contributed to multiple benchmarks; co-led development of training infrastructure that enabled the deep learning era at Google scale\n\n**Note on \"Attention Is All You Need\":** Dean did not co-author the 2017 Transformer paper (\"Attention Is All You Need\") — that paper's eight authors were all from Google Brain (Vaswani, Shazeer, Parmar, Uszkoreit, Jones, Gomez, Kaiser, Polosukhin). Dean co-founded and led Google Brain, the team that produced the paper, but was not among the listed authors.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Large Scale Distributed Deep Networks\" (NIPS 2012) — described DistBelief, Google's first distributed deep learning system\n- \"MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters\" (OSDI 2004, with Sanjay Ghemawat) — one of the most cited systems papers in computer science history\n- \"Bigtable: A Distributed Storage System for Structured Data\" (OSDI 2006) — defined modern NoSQL architecture\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Numerous blog posts on Google Research blog; talks at NeurIPS, ICML, and ICLR conferences published online\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Dean believes AGI is a long-term horizon but he is optimistic about AI's accelerating capabilities. He has predicted that \"AI systems will achieve the operational proficiency of junior engineers within a year\" (stated at AI Ascent 2025). He frames AI progress in terms of scientific breakthroughs: \"The next century's major challenges — climate change, disease, clean energy — require scientific breakthroughs. AI can accelerate discovery by 10–100x.\" He is less concerned with existential risk from AGI than with ensuring AI's benefits reach humanity broadly.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Dean does not position himself as a safety researcher in the Eliezer Yudkowsky or Paul Christiano tradition, but he has acknowledged that Google was \"a little caught up on the fact that these models make mistakes sometimes\" — implying the company was too cautious to ship AI products that competed with ChatGPT. He has engaged with responsible AI principles at Google and has participated in AI safety discussions in his role as Chief Scientist. His orientation is engineering-optimistic: risks are solvable problems.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Dean frames AI ethics primarily through the lens of beneficial applications: healthcare, climate science, drug discovery. His public statements emphasize what AI can do for humanity's hardest problems. He has championed \"AI for Social Good\" initiatives at Google. He has been less vocal on surveillance, bias, or labor displacement than some AI ethicists would prefer.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Dean has not taken strongly public regulatory positions. He has supported responsible AI principles broadly. As an angel investor in numerous AI startups (Fortune reported in July 2025 that he is \"one of AI's most prolific angel investors\"), he has a financial stake in the ecosystem that makes aggressive regulation less appealing.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Emma Strubell et al. | In 2019, Dean publicly disputed the emissions cost calculations in Strubell et al.'s \"Energy and Policy Considerations for Deep Learning in NLP\" paper; said the estimates were off by 88x due to misunderstanding of the actual training process |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Multiple keynotes at NIPS/NeurIPS, ICML, and Google I/O\n- Purdue Engineering Distinguished Lecture Series (2023–2024)\n- Stanford HAI (Human-Centered AI Institute) talks\n- AI Ascent 2025 (predictions about AI capabilities and junior engineers)\n**Podcasts:** Limited public podcast presence; primarily speaks at academic and industry conferences\n**Social Media:** Active on X (Twitter) under @JeffDean; posts about research and Google AI developments\n**Online Courses:** None; his technical contributions are taught as foundational material in most graduate ML programs worldwide\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Scientific humanism; merit-based systems; \"AI for good\" utilitarian framework; responsible AI principles\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Not documented; his intellectual formation is technical; his undergraduate degree included economics alongside computer science\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Google's slow response to ChatGPT:** Dean was lead of Google AI during the years when ChatGPT launched and took the world by surprise. He acknowledged internally and publicly that Google was \"a little caught up\" in concerns about model mistakes, which delayed shipping competitive products. Critics argue Google Brain under his leadership had all the pieces — the Transformer architecture was invented there — but failed to deploy them competitively.\n2. **Angel investing conflicts:** Fortune reported (July 2025) that Dean has become \"one of AI's most prolific angel investors\" in AI startups. The practice raises potential conflicts of interest for a sitting Google DeepMind Chief Scientist; Google has not restricted the activity publicly.\n3. **Emissions paper dispute:** His 2019 public dispute with Strubell et al.'s energy research was handled via Twitter and was seen by some as a defensive posture from a technology company protecting its products from environmental criticism, though Dean's technical points were substantive.\n4. **Concentration of infrastructure power:** MapReduce, BigTable, TensorFlow, and the Google Brain research program — all of Dean's major contributions — are foundational to an AI ecosystem that is largely controlled by Google. Critics argue that even \"open\" contributions like TensorFlow reinforce Google's ecosystem dominance.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Dean has publicly stated that Google was too cautious in shipping AI products, which he frames as an organizational learning lesson rather than a personal failure.\n\n---\n",
  "devlin": "# Research Profile: Jacob Devlin\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Jacob Devlin\n**Born:** Not publicly disclosed\n**Nationality:** American\n\n**Education:**\n- B.S., University of Maryland (Computer Science)\n- M.S. in Computer Science, University of Maryland, 2009 (advised by Dr. Bonnie Dorr)\n- No doctorate; Devlin is a prominent example of a practitioner who shaped the field without a Ph.D.\n\n**Current Role:** Research Scientist, Google DeepMind (returned June 2023 after brief stint at OpenAI; as of mid-2025, remains at Google)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~2009–2014 | Research Scientist, BBN Technologies (Raytheon) |\n| 2013 | Visiting Researcher, Johns Hopkins University |\n| 2014–2017 | Principal Research Scientist, Microsoft Research (led Bing/Microsoft Translate NMT transition) |\n| 2017–2023 | Staff Research Scientist, Google Research / Google Brain |\n| Early 2023 | Research Scientist, OpenAI (brief; resigned over Bard data controversy) |\n| June 2023–present | Staff Research Scientist, Google DeepMind |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- ACL Best Paper Award, 2014 (BBN era)\n- BERT paper among the most cited NLP papers in history (50,000+ citations)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Pre-trained language model architectures (BERT, bidirectional transformers)\n- Machine translation (phrase-based to neural MT transition)\n- Question answering and information retrieval\n- Natural language understanding and inference\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"BERT: Pre-training of Deep Bidirectional Transformers for Language Understanding\" | 2018 | Introduced masked language modeling and next sentence prediction as pretraining objectives; established the pretrain/fine-tune paradigm for NLP. Set state-of-the-art on 11 NLP benchmarks simultaneously. |\n| \"Fast and Accurate Shift-Reduce Constituent Parsing\" | 2014 | ACL Best Paper Award; early work on neural parsing. |\n| Machine translation papers (Microsoft Research era) | 2014–2017 | Contributed to the transition of Microsoft Translator from phrase-based to neural MT. |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- BERT (Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers) — the first transformer model to use bidirectional context for pretraining; predecessor to every modern encoder model\n- Masked Language Model (MLM) pretraining objective\n- Next Sentence Prediction (NSP) pretraining objective\n- The pretrain/fine-tune transfer learning paradigm for NLP, which became the dominant approach in the field\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- BERT established performance benchmarks on GLUE, SQuAD, and MultiNLI; effectively reset baselines across NLP research\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- Google AI Blog post: \"Open Sourcing BERT: State-of-the-Art Pre-training for Natural Language Processing\" (2018) — described BERT's capabilities and the decision to release the model publicly.\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- None independently authored for popular press.\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** No extensive public record. Devlin's public persona centers on concrete technical contributions rather than AGI speculation or futurology.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Devlin's most documented act of safety-related advocacy was his resignation from Google in early 2023. He reportedly raised concerns internally — including to CEO Sundar Pichai — that Google was using responses from ChatGPT (via ShareGPT, a public repository of ChatGPT conversations) to train Bard. Devlin argued this would violate OpenAI's terms of service and result in plagiarized outputs. The act of escalating the concern and then resigning when it was not addressed demonstrates a willingness to place research integrity above institutional loyalty.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Devlin's BERT paper was open-sourced immediately, making state-of-the-art NLP accessible to the global research community at no cost — an act with significant equity implications for who can participate in AI research. His actions in the Bard controversy suggest commitments to data provenance and intellectual honesty.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** No public record.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Google leadership (early 2023) | Alleged use of ChatGPT/ShareGPT data to train Bard; Devlin resigned in protest; Google denied the allegation |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Stanford NLP Seminar (presented BERT)\n- 2nd Workshop on Neural Machine Translation and Generation (WNMT 2018, invited speaker)\n\n**Podcasts:** No major documented podcast appearances.\n\n**Social Media:** Active on X (@jacob_devlin); uses the platform for technical commentary.\n\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** No direct documented statements. Devlin's technical work on BERT, however, carries implicit assumptions about language and meaning: BERT learns bidirectional contextual representations, which approximates how humans understand words through context. Whether this constitutes \"understanding\" in any philosophically meaningful sense is an open question Devlin has not publicly addressed.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Data integrity and research honesty appear to be operative values, as evidenced by the Bard resignation. Open-sourcing BERT reflects a commitment to shared scientific infrastructure.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **The Bard resignation (2023):** Devlin left Google alleging the Bard team was using ChatGPT data (sourced from ShareGPT) for training. Google denied the claim. Devlin's brief move to OpenAI followed; he returned to Google three months later. The episode raised questions about AI training data ethics and internal governance at Google, though Google's denial was not publicly rebutted by Devlin after his return.\n2. **BERT's NSP objective criticized:** The Next Sentence Prediction pretraining task introduced in BERT was subsequently found by the RoBERTa paper (Liu et al., 2019) to be of questionable value and potentially harmful to model performance. Later BERT variants dropped it. This is a normal part of scientific iteration, but BERT's architecture assumptions were not universally adopted.\n3. **Limited public visibility:** Devlin is less publicly prominent than peers; his technical influence is vast but his public engagement with broader AI ethics, policy, and societal questions is limited.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** None publicly documented.\n\n---\n",
  "donti": "# Research Profile: Priya Donti\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Priya Lekha Donti  **Born:** circa 1993–1994, United States (Indian heritage)  **Nationality:** American  \n**Education:** B.S., Computer Science and Mathematics, Harvey Mudd College; Ph.D., Computer Science and Public Policy, Carnegie Mellon University  \n**Current Role:** Assistant Professor (Silverman (1968) Family Career Development Professor), Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science (EECS) and Laboratory for Information and Decision Systems (LIDS), MIT; Co-Founder and Executive Director, Climate Change AI (nonprofit)  \n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~2018–2020 | Ph.D. Researcher, Carnegie Mellon University (Computer Science and Public Policy) |\n| 2020–2022 | Postdoctoral Researcher, Cornell Tech Runway Startup Postdoc Program |\n| 2020–present | Co-Founder and Executive Director, Climate Change AI |\n| 2022–present | Assistant Professor, MIT EECS and LIDS |\n\n**Major Awards:** MIT Technology Review \"35 Innovators Under 35\" (2021); Vox \"Future Perfect 50\" (2023); TIME100 AI (2025); Schmidt Sciences AI2050 Early Career Fellowship; ACM SIGEnergy Doctoral Dissertation Award (2022); Schmidt Sciences Early Career Fellowship\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Machine learning for power systems optimization\n- Optimization-in-the-loop AI (integrating optimization solvers into neural network architectures)\n- ML methods with hard constraint compliance for safety-critical systems\n- AI for climate and energy applications\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Task-based End-to-End Model Learning in Stochastic Optimization\" | 2017 | Early work on task-based (decision-focused) learning; integrating optimization objectives into ML training |\n| \"Machine Learning for AC Optimal Power Flow\" (Donti, Kolter, Brandon) | 2017 | Applied deep learning to AC optimal power flow; key paper connecting ML and power systems |\n| \"DC3: A Learning Method for Optimization with Hard Constraints\" (Donti, Rolnick, Kolter) | 2021 | ICLR; introduced DC3 (Deep Constraint Completion and Correction); neural network training method that enforces hard equality and inequality constraints; demonstrated on AC optimal power flow |\n| \"Tackling Climate Change with Machine Learning\" (Rolnick et al., including Donti) | 2019 | *NeurIPS Climate Change AI Workshop*; seminal survey paper catalyzing the field of ML for climate; hundreds of citations |\n| \"Enforcing Policy Feasibility Constraints through Differentiable Projection for Energy Optimization\" | 2021 | Extended constraint-compliance methods to reinforcement learning for energy control |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- DC3 (Deep Constraint Completion and Correction): algorithm that enforces hard constraints in neural network optimization — completes partial solutions to satisfy equality constraints and uses unrolled gradient corrections for inequalities; substantially faster than classical solvers while maintaining feasibility\n- Optimization-in-the-loop neural networks: architecture family that embeds optimization problems as differentiable layers within neural networks, enabling end-to-end training that respects the structure of the underlying optimization problem\n- AC Optimal Power Flow ML methods: neural network approaches to the classical power grid optimization problem, with formal guarantees on physical constraint satisfaction\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Power systems benchmark datasets for AC optimal power flow; contributed to Climate Change AI benchmark development across climate domains\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None published as of 2026; her most impactful work is through research papers and Climate Change AI's reports and workshops\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Tackling Climate Change with Machine Learning\" (2019, with Rolnick et al.) — the founding manifesto of the ML for climate field; widely cited; covers electricity systems, transportation, buildings, industry, agriculture, land use, and carbon capture; published as a long-form paper and shaped an entire community\n- \"How AI Policy Can Accelerate Climate Action\" (2024, UNESCO) — policy-oriented essay on AI governance for climate\n- \"Climate Change AI: The State of the Field\" — annual reports summarizing progress\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- MIT News profile: \"Fighting for the Health of the Planet with AI\" (2025)\n- *Imagine5* profile: \"She's Bringing AI and Climate Science Together\"\n- Resources Radio: \"Using Artificial Intelligence to Tackle Climate Change\"\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Donti does not engage with AGI debates. Her research is focused on concrete, near-term AI applications with measurable real-world impact. She represents a school of thought — increasingly influential — that regards the AGI debate as a distraction from the AI applications that matter most in the present: climate, health, equity. Her framing is pragmatic: \"AI is just one tool in a broader toolkit that can be used to support or accelerate existing climate change strategies.\"\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Donti's safety concerns are domain-specific and technically grounded. Her DC3 and optimization-in-the-loop work is explicitly motivated by the safety requirements of power grids: a neural network controlling electricity infrastructure that violates physical constraints could cause cascades or blackouts. Her research provides formal safety guarantees — not in the existential-risk sense, but in the engineering sense of provable constraint satisfaction. She also engages with AI's systemic risks: she and collaborators have noted that AI's growth is inducing societal power shifts through concentration of computational resources, with potentially negative equity implications.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Donti consistently frames AI ethics around equity and climate justice. She emphasizes that deployment of AI-for-climate applications \"must be underpinned by fundamental values of responsibility, ethics, and equity.\" She was motivated from childhood by experiences of inequity in India and the recognition that climate change would exacerbate existing disparities. She has written that \"we shouldn't push AI into all the places where it isn't needed\" — a corrective to AI solutionism. She advocates for interdisciplinary collaboration that includes \"researchers, implementing industries, end users, and affected parties\" in evaluating AI alignment with ethical values.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Donti has been active at the intersection of AI policy and climate policy. She has published with UNESCO on how AI policy can accelerate climate action. She argues that AI governance frameworks must explicitly account for AI's own environmental footprint — the compute and energy required to train and run large models — as well as its potential to accelerate decarbonization. She advocates for policy that prioritizes high-impact AI applications and provides regulatory frameworks that enable responsible deployment in safety-critical infrastructure.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| AI solutionism broadly | Donti resists the idea that AI is the primary answer to climate change; technology must work alongside policy, behavior change, and economic reform |\n| AI researchers ignoring environmental costs | She has argued that the AI community cannot advocate for AI-for-climate while ignoring the carbon footprint of training large models |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- MIT CSAIL Special Seminar: \"Optimization-in-the-Loop AI for Energy and Climate\"\n- NeurIPS, ICLR, and ICML workshop keynotes on climate change and ML\n- Climate One podcast and radio appearances\n- UNESCO AI ethics conference talks\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Resources Radio* — \"Using Artificial Intelligence to Tackle Climate Change\"\n- *Climate One* — extended interview on AI and climate\n- Various MIT and academic podcasts\n\n**Social Media:** Active on Twitter/X and LinkedIn; Climate Change AI has significant online presence\n\n**Online Courses:** Teaches at MIT; co-organizes Climate Change AI tutorial sessions at major ML conferences; no public MOOC\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Climate justice and equity as primary ethical commitments; scientific rigor as a constraint on AI claims; precautionary principle regarding AI deployment in safety-critical systems; interdisciplinary ethics that centers affected communities rather than purely technical or economic metrics\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Her Ph.D. program at Carnegie Mellon combined computer science and public policy — a genuinely interdisciplinary formation. She consistently engages with sociologists, policy scholars, and climate activists rather than remaining within a purely technical community. Her work with Climate Change AI has required building bridges across disciplines, geographies, and sectors.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **\"AI for climate\" hype:** Some climate scientists and policy experts are skeptical that ML will make a decisive difference in climate outcomes, arguing that the primary barriers are political and economic, not computational. Donti's careful framing (\"one tool in a broader toolkit\") partly acknowledges this, but the field she helped create has attracted significant hype.\n2. **AI's own carbon footprint:** Donti has been criticized for not being more forceful about the carbon cost of large AI systems, even as she advocates for AI-for-climate. She has addressed this publicly, but the tension remains.\n3. **Power grid AI deployment:** Deploying ML in electricity infrastructure is genuinely dangerous if constraints are violated; while her research provides formal guarantees, critics note that real-world power grid operations involve complexities that may not be captured in theoretical constraint formulations.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Donti has acknowledged that the gap between ML research demonstrations and real-world power grid deployment is large, involving regulatory, institutional, and practical barriers that her research cannot address alone. She has been explicit that \"AI is not a silver bullet\" for climate.\n\n---\n",
  "dragos": "# Research Profile: Dragos Tudorache\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Ioan-Dragoș Tudorache **Born:** January 14, 1975, Bârlad, Romania **Nationality:** Romanian\n**Education:** Law, Alexandru Ioan Cuza University, Iași (1993–1997); Stockholm University exchange (1998–1999)\n**Current Role:** Member of the European Parliament (Renew Europe, Romania); Deputy Chair, Renew Europe parliamentary group\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1997 | Judge, Galati Court, Romania |\n| 2000–2003 | Coordinator, Rule of Law and Human Rights Dept., OSCE, Pristina |\n| 2003–2005 | Head of Legal Department, UN International Judges team, UNMIK (Kosovo) |\n| 2005–2007 | Legal and anti-corruption officer, EU Commission Delegation, Bucharest |\n| 2007–2015 | Directorate-General for Migration and Home Affairs, European Commission, Brussels |\n| 2015–2016 | Head of Prime Minister's Chancellery, Romania |\n| 2016 | Minister for Communications and Digital Society, Romania |\n| 2016–2017 | Minister of Interior, Romania |\n| 2019–present | Member of the European Parliament (Renew Europe / USR) |\n| 2021–present | Deputy Chair, Renew Europe parliamentary group |\n| 2021–2024 | Co-Rapporteur, EU AI Act (LIBE Committee) |\n\n**Major Awards:** Joint winner (with MEP Brando Benifei), \"MEP of the Mandate\" Award, The Parliament Magazine, 2024.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Policy / Governance Work:**\n- Shepherded the EU AI Act through the European Parliament as lead rapporteur for the LIBE (Civil Liberties, Justice and Home Affairs) Committee\n- Developed and negotiated the risk-tiered framework at the heart of the AI Act\n- Championed prohibitions on unacceptable-risk AI applications (mass surveillance, social scoring, real-time biometric identification in public spaces)\n- Advocated for human-centric, fundamental-rights-based AI regulation as a global template\n- Active in U.S.–EU relations and transatlantic AI governance coordination\n\n**Landmark Papers / Policy Documents:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| EU AI Act (Regulation 2024/1689) | 2024 | World's first comprehensive binding AI regulation; risk-tiered framework covering prohibited uses, high-risk applications, general-purpose AI models, and transparency requirements |\n| European Parliament AI Act Report (LIBE/IMCO) | 2023 | Parliament's negotiating position; strengthened fundamental rights protections and extended scope to general-purpose AI |\n| CSIS Analysis: European Approach to Regulating AI | 2023 | Authored/presented at CSIS; articulated EU rationale and global implications of risk-based approach |\n\n**Key Contributions:**\n- Transformed the European Commission's original AI Act proposal into a more robust fundamental-rights instrument\n- Secured Parliament's position banning real-time biometric surveillance in public spaces\n- Extended the AI Act's scope to cover foundation models and general-purpose AI systems\n- Established the principle that AI touching fundamental rights belongs in the highest risk tier\n- Set the template for what binding democratic AI governance looks like in practice\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None published.\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- Numerous official parliamentary reports and position papers on AI governance (2021–2024)\n- LinkedIn long-form posts on AI governance and EU Parliament strategy\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Featured analysis in *Friends of Europe*, CSIS, and various European policy outlets\n- Interviews and analysis pieces on EU AI Act negotiations and outcomes\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Has not focused publicly on AGI timelines. His regulatory work assumed a horizon of present-day and near-term AI rather than speculative superintelligence. He treats the current generation of AI as already powerful enough to warrant comprehensive regulation.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Safety is inseparable from fundamental rights. The EU AI Act's risk-tiered framework operationalizes this: the higher the potential harm to individuals' rights, the stricter the requirements. At the maximum tier, AI applications that fundamentally violate human dignity should simply be prohibited — no cost-benefit calculus applies.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Ethics must be institutionalized, not aspirational. Voluntary ethical principles have been proven inadequate. The EU AI Act converts ethical commitments into legal obligations, with enforcement mechanisms and penalties. He has been explicit that self-regulation by AI companies is insufficient.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Tudorache is the architect of the world's most significant binding AI regulatory framework. He articulated the EU's \"horizontal risk-based approach\" and defended it against industry pressure to weaken it. He argues the EU has an obligation to lead globally and that other democratic nations should adopt compatible frameworks. His position: the EU AI Act will set the tone worldwide, ensuring AI evolves in accordance with European values of democracy, fundamental rights, and rule of law. He sees the regulation as pro-innovation — clear rules reduce legal uncertainty and build public trust.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| EU Council (member states) | Parliament pushed significantly stronger fundamental rights protections than Council proposed |\n| AI industry lobbyists | Resisted industry attempts to weaken high-risk classifications and expand exemptions |\n| Some civil society groups | Civil liberties organizations argued biometric surveillance bans did not go far enough |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- CSIS, Washington D.C. — \"The European Approach to Regulating Artificial Intelligence\" (2023)\n- Friends of Europe — featured in-conversation on EU AI Act\n- Various conferences on digital governance and democratic regulation of AI\n- Privacy Symposium\n\n**Podcasts:** Featured on multiple EU policy and tech governance podcasts during AI Act negotiations (2022–2024).\n**Social Media:** Active on LinkedIn and X; extensive public communication during AI Act negotiations.\n**Online Courses:** None documented.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Fundamental rights; rule of law; democratic accountability; human-centric design; proportionality.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement with religious or theological traditions. His background is law and public administration.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. Some AI researchers and industry groups argued the AI Act's risk classifications are poorly calibrated — that the high-risk list captures some relatively benign applications while missing more dangerous ones.\n2. Civil liberties organizations (EDRI, Access Now) argued Tudorache's final negotiated text gave too much ground on biometric surveillance exceptions for law enforcement.\n3. Critics from the right accused the AI Act of creating regulatory overreach that will harm European AI competitiveness versus the U.S. and China.\n4. The exclusion of military and national security AI from the Act's scope was criticized by human rights advocates.\n5. Implementation delays in the transition to full enforcement (2026) have raised questions about regulatory readiness.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Tudorache has acknowledged that enforcement capacity across EU member states is uneven and that the AI Act's success depends heavily on whether national market surveillance authorities are adequately resourced.\n\n---\n",
  "emad": "# Research Profile: Emad Mostaque\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Emad Mostaque **Born:** April 1983, Jordan (to a Bengali Muslim family); moved to the UK at age 7 **Nationality:** British (Bangladeshi heritage)\n**Education:** M.A. in Mathematics and Computer Science — University of Oxford\n**Current Role:** Founder of Intelligent Internet (2024–); previously Founder and CEO of Stability AI (resigned March 2024)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1983 | Born in Jordan to a Bengali Muslim family |\n| ~1990 | Family moved to the United Kingdom |\n| ~2001–2004 | Studied Mathematics and Computer Science at Oxford University |\n| 2004–2020 | Worked as a hedge fund manager; quantitative finance and emerging markets |\n| ~2017 | Son diagnosed with autism; Mostaque conducted AI-powered literature review to find treatment options; sparked interest in AI's transformative potential |\n| 2020 | Co-founded Stability AI with Cyrus Hodes; initially self-funded |\n| 2022 | Stability AI raised $101M at $1B+ valuation (October 2022) |\n| Aug 2022 | Released Stable Diffusion — open-source text-to-image model; changed AI art generation |\n| Jun 2023 | Forbes/Reuters investigation reported misleading claims about credentials and partnerships |\n| Jul 2023 | Co-founder Cyrus Hodes filed civil lawsuit alleging fraud over stake sold for $100 |\n| Mar 2024 | Resigned as CEO of Stability AI under investor pressure; company in financial distress |\n| Aug 2024 | Published *The Last Economy* |\n| 2024– | Founded Intelligent Internet; pursues decentralized AI vision |\n\n**Major Awards:** None formal; widely recognized as the figure who democratized image generation AI\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Open-source generative AI models (image, text, audio, video)\n- Decentralized AI infrastructure\n- AI for education and developing nations\n\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Stable Diffusion | Aug 2022 | Open-source text-to-image diffusion model; released publicly; enabled anyone to generate photorealistic images from text; became the foundation of thousands of downstream applications and startups |\n| Stable Diffusion XL (SDXL) | 2023 | Higher-resolution image generation with improved prompting |\n| StableLM | 2023 | Open-source language model attempt to compete with LLaMA and GPT |\n| Stable Video Diffusion | 2023 | Open-source video generation model |\n| Intelligent Internet platform | 2024– | Decentralized AI infrastructure; \"third path\" between Big Tech AI and open-source chaos |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Stable Diffusion's release as open-source fundamentally changed the generative AI landscape — not by inventing the underlying latent diffusion architecture (that was the work of Robin Rombach et al. at CompVis, Ludwig Maximilian University Munich) but by funding, organizing, and releasing it publicly, making it accessible globally\n- Mostaque's key contribution was strategic and organizational: recognizing that open-sourcing the model would generate explosive adoption and that a company organized around open-source could compete with closed incumbents\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Stability AI used LAION-5B (a public dataset) as the primary training data for Stable Diffusion; controversial because LAION includes copyrighted images scraped without consent\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *The Last Economy* (August 2024) — introduces \"Intelligent Economics\" as a framework for the AI abundance age; argues that classical economics was built for scarcity but the Intelligence Age is about abundance; general audience; advocates for decentralized AI as the economic foundation of a post-scarcity society\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"AI for the People: The Urgent Case for Open and Decentralized Systems\" — Diamandis Tech Blog (2024) — articulates his post-Stability AI philosophy\n- \"Decentralized/Democratized AI vs. Closed AI\" — Diamandis Tech Blog (2024) — argues that centralized AI is as dangerous as monopoly in any other critical infrastructure\n- \"You can't beat centralized AI with more centralized AI.\" — resignation statement, March 2024\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- OpenUK State of Open 2024 fireside chat — discusses open-source AI, autism, and spiritual awakening\n- Cognitive Revolution podcast interview — on Intelligent Internet and Universal Basic AI\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:**\nMostaque holds an unusually optimistic and decentralist view of AGI. He believes that open, distributed AI — not proprietary AGI controlled by a few corporations — is both safer and more beneficial. He has proposed \"Universal Basic AI\" as a policy goal: every person on earth should have access to powerful AI as a public utility, comparable to access to roads or electricity. His framework is less concerned with AGI timelines than with who controls AI when transformative capability arrives. His Intelligent Internet project attempts to operationalize a \"third path\" where AI capability is distributed rather than concentrated.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nMostaque argues that concentration of AI power is itself the primary safety risk — not misaligned superintelligence. A handful of corporations controlling the most powerful AI systems poses greater danger to democracy and human agency than open AI systems do. He accepts that open-source AI can be misused, but argues the alternative — closed AI controlled by corporations or states — is a greater threat to human freedom and dignity. His spiritual awakening frame positions decentralized AI as not merely technically preferable but morally necessary.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nMostaque's ethics are deeply personal and rooted in two experiences: his son's autism diagnosis, which showed him AI's potential to help individuals that institutions failed, and his claimed spiritual awakening, which produced a conviction that AI must serve individual human potential rather than corporate or state power. His \"Massive Transformative Purpose\" is: \"I want every kid to achieve their potential and give them the tools to do that.\" He frames AI ethics as being about distribution and access rather than about preventing harm from misuse.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nMostaque opposes regulatory frameworks that entrench incumbent AI companies. He is skeptical of the EU AI Act and similar approaches that he argues create compliance moats for well-resourced incumbents. He supports transparency requirements but opposes licensing regimes for AI development. His preferred policy is open infrastructure and universal access, not regulated access to closed systems.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| OpenAI / Microsoft / Google | Argues closed AI is anti-democratic and dangerous; \"you can't beat centralized AI with more centralized AI\" |\n| AI safety researchers | Disputes the framing that open-source AI is uniquely dangerous; argues closed AI concentration is the real safety threat |\n| Stability AI investors (Lightspeed, Coatue) | Were pushing for his resignation; he accused them of prioritizing short-term returns over mission |\n| Cyrus Hodes (co-founder) | Civil lawsuit alleging Mostaque defrauded him of a $150M stake sold for $100 (filed July 2023) |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- OpenUK State of Open: The UK in 2024 — fireside chat on open-source AI and personal philosophy\n- Multiple AI conference keynotes on open-source AI (2022–2023)\n- Various government hearings on AI regulation (UK, EU, US contexts)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Cognitive Revolution* — \"Emad Mostaque on the Intelligent Internet and Universal Basic AI\"\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast* — open-source AI and Stable Diffusion\n- *Dwarkesh Patel Podcast* — extended discussion of AI philosophy\n- Multiple generative AI and tech podcasts (2022–2024)\n\n**Social Media:** X — @EMostaque; historically active; posting frequency reduced after departure from Stability AI\n\n**Online Courses:** None formal\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- \"I want every kid to achieve their potential and give them the tools to do that.\" — stated Massive Transformative Purpose\n- \"We should have more transparent and distributed governance in AI as it becomes more and more important.\" — on decentralization\n- His son's autism diagnosis is the origin story of his AI mission: a personal encounter with a child who needed tools that institutions could not provide, which AI could\n- The spiritual awakening — though not detailed — represents a claim that his motivation shifted from personal gain to service of human potential\n- \"The Intelligence Age is about abundance\" — frames AI as liberation from material scarcity constraints on human flourishing\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Democratic humanism — every human being deserves access to powerful tools; AI is a public good\n- Subsidiarity (functionally) — AI governance should be distributed and local, not concentrated at the top\n- Consequentialism qualified by justice — outcomes matter, but who controls the means matters equally\n- Personal experience epistemology — his son's autism, his own neurodivergence (Asperger's), and his spiritual experience are explicitly cited as the basis for his ethical commitments\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Mostaque's engagement with faith is personal rather than intellectual. His Muslim background, his spiritual awakening, and his emphasis on human potential over efficiency suggest a values framework shaped partly by Islamic conceptions of human dignity (*karama*) and trusteeship (*khilafah*) — though he does not invoke this language explicitly. His *The Last Economy* engages economic philosophy and history rather than theology, but its vision of abundance as a moral goal carries spiritual resonance.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Fabricated credentials and partnerships:** A June 2023 investigation (citing 30+ sources) reported that Mostaque had misrepresented his Oxford degree (claimed a master's; records disputed), fabricated strategic partnerships with Amazon Web Services, the United Nations, OECD, WHO, World Bank, and the government of Malawi — all of which denied partnership status.\n2. **Co-founder fraud lawsuit:** Cyrus Hodes sued Mostaque in July 2023 alleging he was defrauded into selling his 15% stake for $100 — a stake worth $150M at October 2022 valuations. The lawsuit is part of a deeply contested founding narrative.\n3. **Financial mismanagement at Stability AI:** Investors cited $8M monthly cash burn, near-$100M in unpaid bills, defaults on payments to AWS and Google Cloud, and failed fundraising. Lightspeed Venture Partners stated Mostaque's mismanagement had \"severely undermined\" their confidence.\n4. **Staff exodus:** Several key technical staff — including Robin Rombach and other Stable Diffusion architects — resigned in March 2024 alongside Mostaque's departure, suggesting the company's technical foundations were not separable from the founding turmoil.\n5. **Copyright controversy (Stable Diffusion):** Stable Diffusion was trained on LAION-5B, which scraped copyrighted images without consent from millions of artists and photographers. Multiple lawsuits were filed against Stability AI by artists. Mostaque defended open-source AI while his company faced legal and ethical liability for how that openness was achieved.\n6. **Claiming credit for Stable Diffusion:** The actual architecture of Stable Diffusion was developed by Robin Rombach and colleagues at CompVis, University of Munich. Mostaque's role was funding, organizing, and releasing — a significant contribution, but not the technical invention he sometimes implied.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Has publicly stated that leaving Stability AI was necessary because \"you can't beat centralized AI with more centralized AI\" — implicitly acknowledging that Stability AI's model was becoming what he opposed. Has not publicly acknowledged the credential fabrications.\n\n---\n",
  "fan": "# Research Profile: Jim Fan\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Linxi \"Jim\" Fan **Born:** c. 1994 (exact date not publicly documented) **Nationality:** Chinese-American\n**Education:** B.S. Computer Science, Columbia University (2016, valedictorian, Illig Medal for academic excellence); Ph.D. Computer Science, Stanford University (2021, advisor: Fei-Fei Li, Stanford Vision Lab)\n**Current Role:** Director of AI & Distinguished Research Scientist, NVIDIA; Co-lead, Project GR00T; Co-founder & Lead, GEAR Lab (Generalist Embodied Agent Research)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~2014–2015 | Intern, OpenAI (first intern in OpenAI's history) |\n| ~2015–2016 | Internships at Baidu AI Labs (Andrew Ng), MILA (Yoshua Bengio), OpenAI (Ilya Sutskever, Dario Amodei, Andrej Karpathy) |\n| 2016–2021 | PhD Student, Stanford Vision Lab (Fei-Fei Li) |\n| 2021–present | Director of AI / Distinguished Research Scientist, NVIDIA |\n| 2022–present | Co-lead, Project GR00T; Co-founder, GEAR Lab |\n\n**Major Awards:** NeurIPS 2022 Outstanding Paper Award (MineDojo); Columbia University Illig Medal (top graduating student).\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Foundation models for embodied agents and humanoid robots\n- Open-ended agent learning in simulated and physical environments\n- Physical AI: enabling robots to learn generalizable behaviors across embodiments\n- Multi-task, language-conditioned robot policy learning\n- Simulation-to-real transfer\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *World of Bits: An Open-Domain Platform for Web-Based Agents* | ICML 2017 | Co-developed at OpenAI; first AI agent learning to control a web browser through keyboard and mouse; co-authored with Openai team |\n| *MineDojo: Building Open-Ended Embodied Agents with Internet-Scale Knowledge* | NeurIPS 2022 (Outstanding Paper) | Framework for training generalist agents in Minecraft using a large-scale dataset of gameplay videos and wiki pages |\n| *Voyager: An Open-Ended Embodied Agent with Large Language Models* | NeurIPS 2023 | First LLM-powered lifelong learning agent; uses GPT-4 to write executable game code, self-reflect on failures, and build a skill library in Minecraft |\n| *GR00T N1: An Open Foundation Model for Generalist Humanoid Robots* | 2025 | NVIDIA's foundation model for humanoid robot control; integrates vision-language reasoning with diffusion transformer action module |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- MineDojo: open-ended simulation platform combining Minecraft gameplay, 300K+ YouTube tutorials, wiki pages, and Reddit posts as internet-scale training data for embodied agents\n- Voyager's three-module architecture: automatic curriculum, persistent skill library, iterative GPT-4 prompting for code generation and self-correction\n- GR00T N1: dual-system architecture (Vision-Language Model for reasoning + Diffusion Transformer for motor actions); trained as massively multi-task, language-conditioned robot policy\n- GEAR Lab's \"Physical API\" concept: robots that can manipulate atoms as easily as software manipulates bits\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** MineDojo dataset (300K+ Minecraft gameplay videos with transcripts, wiki articles, Reddit posts); GR00T evaluation suite across robot embodiments.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- *The Physical Turing Test* (conceptual framework, articulated across multiple talks and interviews): a robot has passed the test if it can clean a home and prepare dinner without the owner being able to tell whether it was human or robot\n- X thread on 2024 AI year-in-review: \"We are the last generation without advanced robots everywhere. Everything that moves will be autonomous.\"\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- NVIDIA blog posts on MineDojo, Voyager, GR00T\n- Active communicator on X (@DrJimFan) with substantive technical threads on embodied AI research\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Fan distinguishes sharply between \"language AGI\" (largely achieved by LLMs) and \"physical AGI\" — the ability to robustly manipulate the physical world. His mission is to solve the physical dimension. He coined the frame \"Physical Turing Test\" as the appropriate bar. He describes his philosophy as \"data maximalist, model minimalist\": models should grow simpler as environments grow more complex; generalization comes from data diversity, not architectural complexity. He expects a \"GPT-3 moment\" for robotics within a few years — a foundation model breakthrough analogous to what GPT-3 was for language.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Fan's safety framing is primarily about reliability and generalization rather than existential risk. His technical approach—training on maximally diverse simulated environments—is partially a safety argument: robust generalization reduces unexpected failure modes. He has not publicly engaged with AI existential risk discourse.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Largely implicit. His work on open-source robot models (GR00T N1 published as open) reflects a belief in broad access to AI capabilities. His Voyager and MineDojo work used publicly available game platforms, sidestepping some data consent issues that plague image and text model training.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** No documented detailed policy positions. His public framing is optimistic about robotics deployment: the world is built around human embodiment, and humanoid robots will slot into that world naturally.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent / Position | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| ChatGPT-style AI = AGI claims | Argues language capability is not the same as physical AGI; insists embodiment is the missing ingredient |\n| Complex architectural solutions | \"Model minimalist\": believes architectural complexity is the wrong response to hard problems; data diversity is the right response |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED AI San Francisco (featured speaker)\n- Sequoia Capital *Training Data* podcast (2024): \"Robots Thinking Fast and Slow\"\n- Radical Ventures Masterclass: *The Future of Robotics and Embodied AI*\n- University of Pennsylvania GRASP Lab seminar: *Generalist Agents in Open-Ended Worlds*\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Sequoia Capital *Training Data* (2024)\n- Thursday Nights in AI (NVIDIA audience)\n- Multiple research lab seminar series\n\n**Social Media:** X: @DrJimFan (large following; substantive technical communication); personal website: jimfan.me\n**Online Courses:** None formally; communicates research through papers, talks, and X threads.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Empiricist; values open research and broad access to capabilities. His language about solving \"physical AGI\" treats robot embodiment as a scientific frontier rather than an ethical problem.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement. His worldview is shaped by computer science, physics, and the history of AI research.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **\"Everything that moves will be autonomous\" framing:** Fan's confident forecast of universal robot deployment has been criticized as premature and as potentially normalizing massive labor displacement without adequate social preparation.\n2. **Physical AGI framing:** The term \"physical AGI\" for robots that can complete household tasks is contested; critics argue it conflates general intelligence with task competence.\n3. **Simulation-to-real gap:** Despite impressive demo performance, GR00T and similar systems face significant challenges deploying reliably outside of controlled environments; critics argue the timelines Fan suggests are optimistic.\n4. **OpenAI intern role optics:** Being the first intern at a foundational AI lab at a very young age places Fan in the context of OpenAI's early culture and commitments; the later evolution of OpenAI's mission is part of that context.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Fan has acknowledged that embodied AI is at an early stage analogous to NLP before GPT-3 — powerful enough to demonstrate the paradigm but not yet robust enough for general deployment.\n\n---\n",
  "feigenbaum": "# Research Profile: Edward Feigenbaum\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Edward Albert Feigenbaum\n**Born:** January 20, 1936, Weehawken, New Jersey\n**Status:** Living (as of 2026); Professor Emeritus, Stanford University\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- B.S. in Electrical Engineering, Carnegie Mellon University (then Carnegie Tech), 1956\n- Ph.D. in Industrial Administration (Computer Science), Carnegie Mellon University, 1960\n- Dissertation advisor: Herbert A. Simon (Nobel Laureate in Economics)\n- Dissertation: \"The Simulation of Verbal Learning Behavior\" — the first computer simulation of human learning, a model called EPAM (Elementary Perceiver and Memorizer)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1960–1965 | Assistant/Associate Professor, UC Berkeley (Business School) |\n| 1965–2000 | Professor of Computer Science, Stanford University |\n| 1965–present | Founder and Director, Stanford Knowledge Systems Laboratory |\n| 1968–1980s | Principal investigator, DENDRAL and MYCIN projects |\n| 1983 | Co-authored *The Fifth Generation* (best-seller) |\n| 1994–1997 | Chief Scientist, U.S. Air Force |\n| 2000–present | Professor Emeritus, Stanford University |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- A.M. Turing Award, 1994 (shared with Raj Reddy) — \"for pioneering the design and construction of large-scale artificial intelligence systems, demonstrating the practical importance and commercial potential of AI\"\n- ACM Software System Award (for DENDRAL)\n- National Medal of Technology and Innovation (proposed; Air Force service)\n- Member, National Academy of Engineering\n- Fellow, Association for the Advancement of Artificial Intelligence (AAAI)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Expert systems and knowledge-based AI\n- Knowledge engineering (the process of extracting and encoding expert knowledge)\n- Medical AI (MYCIN, PUFF, ONCOCIN)\n- Scientific reasoning and discovery (DENDRAL, AM)\n- Cognitive simulation (EPAM — learning and memory)\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"EPAM: A Theory of Verbal Learning\" (dissertation work) | 1963 | First computer model of human verbal learning and memory |\n| \"Computers and Thought\" (edited with Julian Feldman) | 1963 | First major AI anthology; defined the field |\n| \"DENDRAL: A Case Study of the First Expert System for Scientific Hypothesis Formation\" | 1971 | Described the first expert system, capable of inferring organic molecular structure |\n| \"Rule-Based Expert Systems: The MYCIN Experiments of the Stanford Heuristic Programming Project\" | 1984 | Definitive account of MYCIN and the knowledge engineering methodology |\n| *The Fifth Generation: Artificial Intelligence and Japan's Computer Challenge to the World* | 1983 | Co-authored with Pamela McCorduck; ~500,000 copies sold; mobilized U.S. AI funding |\n| *The Rise of the Expert Company* | 1988 | Case studies of commercial expert systems deployment |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- Co-created DENDRAL (1965–1971) with Joshua Lederberg and Carl Djerassi: first expert system, analyzed mass spectrometry data to determine organic molecular structure — outperformed human chemists\n- Co-created MYCIN (1972–1976) with Ted Shortliffe: diagnosed bacterial infections and recommended antibiotics at a level exceeding many junior physicians\n- Created PUFF (pulmonary diagnosis), ONCOCIN (cancer treatment management), MOLGEN (molecular genetics planning), and CHRYSALIS (X-ray crystallography)\n- Coined and developed the concept of \"knowledge engineering\" — the discipline of extracting tacit expert knowledge and encoding it in machine-readable rule systems\n- Organized the first commercial expert system deployments through IntelliCorp (spin-off of Stanford Knowledge Systems Lab)\n- Gave AI its first sustained claim to practical impact: knowledge systems that demonstrably improved decision-making in professional domains\n\n**Historical Significance:** Feigenbaum's central insight — that intelligence requires knowledge, not just reasoning power — redirected AI from its logic-based and heuristic-search roots toward domain-specific expertise. His expert systems were the first AI programs to produce commercially valuable results in medicine, chemistry, and engineering. The 1980s AI industry boom was largely his creation. His book *The Fifth Generation* triggered a political and funding response in the United States that shaped defense and research investment for a decade. The knowledge engineering paradigm he developed remains foundational to enterprise AI, ontologies, and semantic systems.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- *Computers and Thought* (1963, ed. with Julian Feldman) — First major AI anthology; defined early AI for a generation of researchers\n- *The Fifth Generation: Artificial Intelligence and Japan's Computer Challenge to the World* (1983, with Pamela McCorduck) — Popular/policy; argued that Japan's government-funded AI initiative threatened U.S. technological leadership; spurred major U.S. investment in AI and helped launch DARPA's Strategic Computing Initiative\n- *The Rise of the Expert Company* (1988, with Pamela McCorduck and H. Penny Nii) — Business-oriented; documented early commercial expert systems at DEC, American Express, and others\n- *Feigenbaum and Feldman's The Art of Artificial Intelligence* (various essays and technical reports, 1970s–1990s)\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"The Art and Science of Knowledge Engineering\" (1977) — Defined knowledge engineering as a discipline\n- \"Expert Systems in the 1980s\" (1980) — State of the field survey\n- \"Some Challenges and Grand Challenges for Computational Intelligence\" (2003) — Later reflections on the field's ambitions\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- *The Fifth Generation* was a major popular work; Feigenbaum frequently gave congressional testimony and public lectures on AI competitiveness\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** Feigenbaum's core thesis — sometimes called the \"knowledge hypothesis\" — holds that the key to AI power is not raw computation or general reasoning but domain-specific knowledge. Intelligence is not a property of a reasoning engine alone; it is constituted by what you know. This distinguished him sharply from both the pure logicians (McCarthy's approach) and the connectionists (neural network researchers): he argued that structured, symbolic knowledge representations were the path to useful AI.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** Feigenbaum was a technological optimist, perhaps the most commercially minded of the first generation of AI researchers. He saw expert systems as tools to capture, preserve, and democratize human expertise — making the knowledge of the world's best physicians or chemists available to practitioners everywhere. He was not a pessimist about automation; he viewed the expansion of machine expertise as straightforwardly beneficial. Unlike Weizenbaum, he did not worry about delegating decisions to machines; he wanted to do it better and more broadly.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:**\n- Raised concerns about national competitiveness and the geopolitics of AI (Japan vs. U.S.) rather than ethical limits on AI itself\n- MYCIN raised early questions about liability in medical AI — if the system makes a wrong recommendation, who is responsible? Feigenbaum and Shortliffe addressed this in publications but did not take a strongly precautionary position\n- Later in career, expressed concern about the gap between academic AI research and practical deployment — the \"laboratory-to-clinic\" problem in medical AI\n\n**Known Debates:** His optimistic, commercial orientation put him in tension with critics like Weizenbaum and later with Hubert Dreyfus (whose book *What Computers Can't Do* was a sustained attack on symbolic AI). The connectionist revolution of the 1980s–1990s challenged his knowledge-engineering paradigm; Feigenbaum acknowledged neural networks' pattern-recognition power while insisting that knowledge representation remained necessary for reasoning tasks.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and Human Uniqueness:** Feigenbaum's work implicitly treats mind as substrate-independent: if you can encode what an expert knows and how they reason, you can replicate expert performance in that domain. He was functionalist in orientation without stating it philosophically. He did not write extensively on consciousness or the hard problem; his interest was in practical performance, not metaphysics. His EPAM model of memory and learning was, however, a serious attempt at cognitive science — to understand how humans actually learn and store knowledge, not just to mimic the output.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Pragmatic consequentialism: what produces the best outcomes? His ethic was largely utilitarian — expert systems that save lives through better medical diagnosis are straightforwardly good. He did not invoke deontological constraints on machine decision-making.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Limited documented engagement. His intellectual formation was through Herbert Simon's bounded rationality and the Carnegie School's emphasis on decision-making under constraint — highly rationalist, empirical, and secular. His work with Joshua Lederberg (a Nobel-winning geneticist and committed public intellectual) gave DENDRAL a broader scientific ambition, but not explicitly philosophical or theological coloring.\n\n---\n",
  "finn": "# Research Profile: Chelsea Finn\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Chelsea Finn **Born:** October 8, 1992 **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** B.S. in Electrical Engineering and Computer Science, MIT (2011); Ph.D. in Computer Science, UC Berkeley (2018), advised by Pieter Abbeel and Sergey Levine; dissertation: \"Learning to Learn with Gradients\"\n**Current Role:** Associate Professor, Computer Science and Electrical Engineering, Stanford University; Research Lead and Co-Founder, Physical Intelligence (pi.ai); Faculty, Stanford HAI (Human-Centered AI)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2011 | B.S., MIT |\n| 2011–2012 | Research roles prior to graduate school |\n| 2012–2018 | Ph.D. student, UC Berkeley (under Abbeel and Levine) |\n| 2017–2018 | Research intern, Google Brain |\n| 2019–present | Assistant Professor → Associate Professor, Stanford University |\n| 2024–present | Co-founder and Research Lead, Physical Intelligence |\n\n**Major Awards:** Presidential Early Career Award for Scientists and Engineers (PECASE, 2025); Sloan Research Fellowship (2023); IEEE RAS Early Academic Career Award in Robotics and Automation (2022); Office of Naval Research Young Investigator Award (2021); ACM Doctoral Dissertation Award (2018); C.V. Ramamoorthy Distinguished Research Award, UC Berkeley (2017); AI2050 Early Career Fellow (Schmidt Sciences)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Meta-learning (\"learning to learn\")\n- Few-shot learning for robotics and vision\n- Imitation learning from limited demonstrations\n- Foundation models for robot control\n- Multi-task and transfer learning\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Model-Agnostic Meta-Learning for Fast Adaptation of Deep Networks\" (MAML) | 2017 | ICML; defined gradient-based meta-learning; one of the most cited ML papers of the decade |\n| \"One-Shot Visual Imitation Learning via Meta-Learning\" | 2017 | Applied MAML to robot imitation from a single demonstration |\n| \"Learning to Learn with Gradients\" (Ph.D. dissertation) | 2018 | Comprehensive treatment of gradient-based meta-learning and applications |\n| \"Online Meta-Learning\" | 2019 | Extended MAML to online/continual learning settings |\n| \"π0: A Vision-Language-Action Flow Model for General Robot Control\" | 2024 | Co-authored Physical Intelligence foundation model |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- MAML (Model-Agnostic Meta-Learning): algorithm that trains a model's initialization to be maximally adaptable to new tasks with minimal gradient steps; applicable to any gradient-based learner\n- ProtoMAML and MAML++ (extensions by subsequent researchers building on her framework)\n- Vision-language-action flow models for robotic manipulation (Physical Intelligence)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** MAML established few-shot learning benchmarks (Omniglot, miniImageNet protocols); Physical Intelligence contributed large-scale robot manipulation datasets for π0\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Learning to Learn with Gradients\" (dissertation, publicly available) — foundational treatment of meta-learning\n- ICLR 2025 invited talk: \"Data-Driven Pre-Training and Post-Training for Robot Foundation Models\" — outlines the research program at Physical Intelligence\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Coverage in New York Times, Wired, Bloomberg on meta-learning and robot learning\n- Stanford HAI commentary on AI and society\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Finn approaches AGI empirically, through the lens of generalization. Her meta-learning research is motivated by the observation that current AI systems are brittle — they require massive data for each new task, unlike humans who learn new skills rapidly from minimal examples. MAML is her contribution to closing that gap. Her work at Physical Intelligence extends this to embodied AI: robots that can adapt to new manipulation tasks from few demonstrations are a step toward genuinely general robotic intelligence.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Finn has not been a prominent voice in the existential AI safety debate. Her safety concerns are primarily operational: robot systems must fail gracefully and must not harm humans during learning. Her research on data efficiency and offline learning reduces the risks of dangerous exploratory behavior. She signed the 2025 YC AI Startup School talk by describing robot learning as requiring careful validation before deployment — suggesting awareness of deployment risk without ideological alignment with the doomer school.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Finn has spoken at Stanford HAI and related venues on responsible AI development. Her commitment to open research (co-authoring the open-source π0 release) reflects a belief that broad access to capable AI is an ethical imperative. She has written about the importance of diverse research communities and has been a visible advocate for women in AI and STEM.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** No prominent public policy positions documented. Her institutional affiliations (Stanford, Physical Intelligence, HAI) reflect engagement with the policy-adjacent AI community without prominent individual advocacy.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Critics of gradient-based meta-learning | MAML has been critiqued for instability and high computational cost; Finn and collaborators have responded with improved variants and theoretical analysis |\n| Task-specific learning advocates | Finn's career is built on the argument that general adaptation mechanisms are better than building separate systems for each task |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- ICML 2017 talk presenting MAML — one of the conference's most influential presentations that year\n- ICLR 2025 invited talk on robot foundation models\n- Y Combinator AI Startup School (June 2025): \"Building Versatile Robots That Learn Complex Tasks\"\n- Stanford HAI conferences and symposia\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- TWIML AI Podcast\n- Lex Fridman Podcast\n- The Robot Report\n\n**Social Media:** X/Twitter: @chelseabfinn\n**Online Courses:** Stanford CS 330 (Deep Multi-Task and Meta Learning) — course materials and lecture videos publicly available; widely used in graduate AI curricula\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Commitment to open science and broad access; procedural safety emphasis in robotic deployment; visible advocacy for diversity in AI research.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement with theological frameworks.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **MAML computational cost** — Original MAML requires computing gradients of gradients (second-order derivatives), which is expensive. Critics argued the algorithm was theoretically elegant but practically limited. Subsequent work (FOMAML, Reptile, MAML++) addressed many of these concerns.\n2. **Meta-learning practical impact** — Despite MAML's massive citation count, some practitioners argue that meta-learning has not yet delivered on its promise of dramatic few-shot generalization in real-world systems. The field has advanced, but the gap with human learning efficiency remains large.\n3. **Physical Intelligence labor implications** — Same concerns as Levine (her co-founder); general-purpose manipulation robots directly enable displacement of physical workers.\n4. **Conflict of interest** — Holding a tenured Stanford faculty position while co-founding a venture-backed company raises standard academic conflict questions around student mentorship and research direction.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Finn openly acknowledges in technical papers that meta-learning methods struggle with task distribution shift and that the relationship between meta-learning and general intelligence remains poorly understood. Her dissertation is candid about open problems.\n\n---\n",
  "fridman": "# Research Profile: Lex Fridman\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Lex Fridman (born Alexei Fridman)  **Born:** circa 1986–1987, Moscow, Soviet Union (now Russia)  **Nationality:** American (Russian-born)  \n**Education:** B.S. and M.S., Computer Science, Drexel University; Ph.D., Computer Science (focus: machine learning and perception in human-centered AI), Drexel University  \n**Current Role:** Research Scientist, MIT Laboratory for Information and Decision Systems (LIDS); Host, *The Lex Fridman Podcast*  \n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~2013–2014 | Research Scientist, Google (briefly, AI-based identity authentication) |\n| 2015–2018 | Research Scientist, MIT AgeLab (driver behavior, autonomous vehicles) |\n| 2018–present | Research Scientist, MIT LIDS; Lecturer, MIT (deep learning, autonomous vehicles) |\n| 2018–present | Host, *The Lex Fridman Podcast* (launched as *Artificial Intelligence Podcast*; rebranded 2020) |\n\n**Major Awards:** No major scientific awards; recognized as a leading science communicator and public intellectual in the AI space; *Boston Globe* named him \"MIT's highest-profile science ambassador\" (2024)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Autonomous vehicles and driver monitoring systems\n- Human-robot interaction\n- Deep learning for perception\n- Semi-autonomous driving safety analysis\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tesla Autopilot semi-autonomous driving behavior study (MIT AgeLab) | 2019 | Analyzed driver attention during use of Tesla's Autopilot; widely cited (and widely criticized) in media coverage of autonomous vehicle safety |\n| Deep learning for driver monitoring and human-robot interaction | 2015–2021 | Series of papers on perception, gaze estimation, and behavioral analysis in autonomous vehicle contexts |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Research contributions to driver monitoring systems using deep learning and computer vision\n- Lecturing and course development for MIT deep learning curriculum (deeplearning.mit.edu)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Contributed to datasets for driver behavior analysis and human-robot interaction at MIT AgeLab and LIDS\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None published\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:** None of the academic manifesto variety; Fridman's influence is through conversational media rather than written argument\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- MIT deep learning course lecture notes (publicly available at deeplearning.mit.edu)\n- Occasional written reflections published on his personal website and social media\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Fridman engages with AGI primarily as an interviewer rather than as an advocate for a specific position. He has interviewed nearly every major voice in AI — from strong AGI believers (Goertzel, Musk, Altman) to skeptics (LeCun, Jordan) — and presents himself as genuinely curious rather than committed to a particular view. His 2022 observation that current AI models would have been called AGI by 2015 standards suggests he holds a relativist position: AGI is a moving target, and what matters is the trajectory rather than any fixed definition.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Fridman takes AI safety seriously as a topic without staking out strong technical positions. He has hosted Eliezer Yudkowsky, Nick Bostrom, Paul Christiano, and other safety researchers, engaging their concerns at length. His disposition is exploratory rather than alarmist. He has expressed personal views that the risks of AI are real but that despair is not a productive response — a position that aligns with his broader philosophy of engagement and love over fear.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Fridman's ethics are more personal than policy-oriented. He has been consistently open about his belief that love — not fear or power — should guide both interpersonal relationships and humanity's relationship with technology. He frequently ends interviews with questions about love, meaning, and mortality. His ethics are humanistic and existentialist in flavor: each person and each AI system should be engaged with as a unique, potentially worthy interlocutor rather than as a threat or a tool.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Fridman does not take strong regulatory positions publicly. He has interviewed policymakers and advocates but tends to present multiple perspectives rather than advocate for specific policy approaches. His role as a platform for diverse views means he is more of a facilitator of debate than a participant in it.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Missy Cummings (Duke, NHTSA) | His 2019 Tesla Autopilot study was criticized as methodologically flawed; small sample, not peer-reviewed; Cummings called it \"deeply flawed\" |\n| Critics of podcast editorial balance | Some academics argue his long-form, non-adversarial interview format gives disproportionate platform to controversial figures without adequate pushback |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- MIT guest lectures on deep learning, autonomous vehicles, and AI (recurring, publicly available)\n- TEDx and conference talks on human-AI interaction\n- Lex Fridman Podcast: over 400 episodes as of 2026; guests include Geoffrey Hinton, Yann LeCun, Elon Musk, Sam Altman, Ilya Sutskever, Noam Chomsky, Jordan Peterson, Bishop Robert Barron, Donald Trump, Joe Biden, and hundreds of others\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *The Lex Fridman Podcast* — he IS the podcast; hosts, does not appear on others regularly\n- Episode #304: Bishop Robert Barron — Christianity, Catholicism, God, meaning, morality (2022); notable for its depth and the positive reception among Fridman's largely tech audience\n\n**Social Media:** Extremely active on Twitter/X, YouTube, and Instagram; 3.6 million YouTube subscribers (as of 2024); tens of millions of total views; one of the most followed AI figures on social media\n\n**Online Courses:**\n- MIT 6.S099: Artificial General Intelligence (publicly available lectures)\n- MIT 6.S094: Deep Learning for Self-Driving Cars (publicly available)\n- All course materials at deeplearning.mit.edu\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Fridman engages deeply with questions of consciousness and meaning — arguably more than almost any other public AI figure. He ends most podcast interviews by asking guests about death, meaning, love, and what advice they would give to their younger selves. He has stated publicly that love is \"the thing that matters most\" and that facing one's mortality honestly is necessary for a meaningful life. He told Jordan Peterson (episode #448): \"I think about death every day, and I think it makes life more vivid.\"\n\nIn his interview with Bishop Robert Barron, Fridman explored the existence of God, the nature of consciousness, and the relationship between science and faith with evident genuine curiosity. Barron noted that Fridman opened the conversation with \"perhaps the most interesting question anyone has asked me on a podcast.\" Fridman has said he finds the question of God \"genuinely open\" and that he respects religious frameworks as attempts to grapple with the deepest questions.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Humanistic existentialism — love, authenticity, and engagement as core values; openness to spiritual traditions without commitment to any specific dogma; care ethics in interviewing (taking each guest seriously as a person, not merely as an intellectual resource)\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Fridman has interviewed theologians (Barron), philosophers (Peterson, Chomsky), historians, and psychologists alongside AI researchers. His range is genuinely cross-disciplinary. His encounter with Bishop Barron represents one of the most widely viewed public conversations between a Catholic bishop and a secular AI researcher in recent memory.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Tesla Autopilot study:** The 2019 study — not peer-reviewed, small sample — was praised by Elon Musk and used to defend Autopilot's safety record; critics including Missy Cummings called it \"deeply flawed\" for its methodology and said it gave a false impression of driver engagement levels.\n2. **Non-adversarial interview format:** Fridman's respectful, long-form approach has been criticized for giving unchallenged platforms to figures whose views warrant scrutiny — from Musk's claims about Tesla to Alex Jones and other conspiracy-adjacent guests.\n3. **Relationship with Elon Musk:** Multiple podcast appearances and public praise have led to questions about whether Fridman can be an independent voice on topics where Musk has strong interests (Tesla, AI, SpaceX).\n4. **Academic vs. public identity:** Some at MIT have questioned whether his podcast celebrity is commensurate with his academic research output; his research publication record is modest relative to his public profile.\n5. **Political interview critics:** His 2023–2024 interviews with Donald Trump and Vladimir Putin were praised by some for access journalism and criticized by others for insufficiently challenging authoritarian or extremist claims.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Fridman has acknowledged that his interview style is deliberately non-confrontational and that this means some guests are not challenged as hard as they might be; he frames this as a choice that enables depth rather than a failure to hold guests accountable.\n\n---\n",
  "gebru": "# Research Profile: Timnit Gebru\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Timnit Gebru **Born:** 1983 (approx.), Addis Ababa, Ethiopia **Nationality:** American (Eritrean-Ethiopian heritage)\n**Education:** B.S. and M.S. Electrical Engineering, Stanford University; Ph.D. Electrical Engineering (Computer Vision), Stanford University (2017), advised by Fei-Fei Li\n**Current Role:** Founder and Executive Director, Distributed AI Research Institute (DAIR), founded December 2021\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~1998 | Fled Ethiopia at age 15; received political asylum in the US (Massachusetts) |\n| 2008–2017 | Undergraduate, M.S., Ph.D., Stanford University; briefly worked at Apple on signal processing algorithms |\n| 2017–2018 | Postdoctoral Researcher, Microsoft Research FATE lab |\n| 2018–2020 | Research Scientist and co-lead, Google Ethical AI team |\n| Dec 2020 | Terminated by Google (she says fired; Google says resigned) over \"Stochastic Parrots\" paper dispute |\n| Dec 2021 | Founded Distributed AI Research Institute (DAIR) |\n| 2021–present | Executive Director, DAIR |\n\n**Major Awards:** Fortune World's 50 Greatest Leaders (2021); Nature's 10 People Who Shaped Science (2021); Time 100 Most Influential People (2022); Carnegie Corporation Great Immigrants Award (2023); 2025 Miles Conrad Award (NISO lifetime achievement); VentureBeat AI Innovations Award \"AI for Good\" (2019, with Buolamwini and Raji)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Bias and fairness in computer vision and facial recognition\n- Large language model (LLM) risks — environmental costs, social harms, disinformation\n- Algorithmic accountability and documentation standards\n- Community-centered AI research free from Big Tech influence\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Gender Shades: Intersectional Accuracy Disparities in Commercial Gender Classification\" (with Joy Buolamwini) | 2018 | Foundational audit showing dramatic racial-gender performance gaps in commercial facial recognition |\n| \"Datasheets for Datasets\" | 2018 (circulated); 2021 (published) | Proposed standardized documentation for AI training datasets — motivation, composition, collection process, recommended uses, limitations |\n| \"Model Cards for Model Reporting\" (with Margaret Mitchell et al.) | 2019 | Proposed transparent reporting cards for AI models — intended use, performance metrics across subgroups, ethical considerations |\n| \"On the Dangers of Stochastic Parrots: Can Language Models Be Too Big?\" (with Emily Bender, Angelina McMillan-Major, Shmargaret Shmitchell) | 2021 | Argued that large language models encode bias at scale, carry massive environmental costs, and produce fluent text without understanding — the paper whose suppression triggered the Google controversy |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Datasheets for Datasets standard — now widely adopted as a documentation norm in the AI field\n- Model Cards — co-developed with Margaret Mitchell; now a standard transparency tool, implemented at major model repositories including Hugging Face\n- TESCREAL framework (with Émile P. Torres) — critical analytical framework identifying a cluster of futurist ideologies (Transhumanism, Extropianism, Singularitarianism, Cosmism, Rationalism, Effective Altruism, Longtermism) as a coherent ideological complex that shapes AI development priorities in harmful ways\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Contributed to facial recognition dataset auditing methodology; Datasheets for Datasets has shaped dataset documentation practices across the field\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None published to date (as of 2025)\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Datasheets for Datasets\" (2018/2021) — arguably the most practically influential paper of her career\n- \"On the Dangers of Stochastic Parrots\" (2021) — the paper that cost her Google employment\n- \"Eugenics and the Promise of Utopia through Artificial General Intelligence\" (with Émile Torres, 2023) — connects AGI ideology to eugenicist intellectual history\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Widely cited in *MIT Technology Review*, *Wired*, *The Guardian*, *Time*\n- Maintains active public presence on social media, particularly around DAIR research outputs and AI accountability advocacy\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Gebru is among the most vocal critics of the AGI discourse. She and Émile Torres coined TESCREAL to name what they see as a coherent ideological complex driving AI development toward speculative futures while ignoring present harms. She argues that AGI-focused \"existential risk\" discourse is a distraction — and worse, a justification for building increasingly powerful and dangerous systems in the name of getting there safely first. She has written that TESCREAL ideologies use extinction-risk framing to justify building \"unscoped systems which are inherently unsafe.\" She connects longtermism's disregard for present-day harm with a long intellectual lineage including eugenics.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Gebru's conception of AI risk is grounded in present realities: racial bias in hiring algorithms, facial recognition misidentifying Black faces and leading to wrongful arrest, large language models generating disinformation at scale and concentrating power in the hands of a few corporations. She is explicitly critical of the AI safety community's preoccupation with hypothetical superintelligence, which she regards as serving the interests of wealthy tech elites rather than vulnerable communities.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** She argues that corporate AI ethics is structurally compromised — companies cannot be trusted to self-regulate systems they profit from. Her firing at Google is, for her, exhibit A: Google suppressed a paper whose findings were inconvenient for the business. DAIR is her institutional answer: independent research, funded by foundations rather than tech corporations, accountable to communities rather than shareholders. She insists that affected communities — particularly Black communities, Global South communities — must be centered in AI development, not as subjects but as co-designers and decision-makers.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Supports strong public regulation and democratic oversight of AI development. Critical of regulation that relies on corporate self-certification. Has called for international governance mechanisms and supports a \"slow AI\" approach — deliberate, community-involved development rather than racing to deploy. Skeptical of AI governance frameworks that do not include structural power redistribution toward affected communities.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Yann LeCun | June 2020 Twitter controversy: LeCun argued AI bias is simply data bias; Gebru argued bias is structural and social, not reducible to data quality |\n| Google leadership | Suppression of \"Stochastic Parrots\" paper; circumstances of her termination |\n| Effective Altruism / Longtermism community | TESCREAL critique: dismisses EA/longtermist AI safety framing as ideological cover for concentrating power |\n| \"AI for Good\" industry discourse | Argues it can exploit under-resourced communities as test grounds for unproven systems |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- NeurIPS (multiple years)\n- AI Now Symposium\n- Widely featured in documentary *Coded Bias* (2020)\n- Keynote addresses at major AI conferences\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Numerous podcast appearances post-Google firing, including major tech journalism outlets\n\n**Social Media:** Active on social platforms; her December 2020 email thread documenting her Google firing was widely shared and became a primary source document for understanding corporate AI ethics failures\n\n**Online Courses:** None; her influence is through research, advocacy, and institutional work at DAIR\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Her work consistently centers human dignity against corporate and ideological systems that abstract away individual persons\n- The \"Stochastic Parrots\" paper argues that LLMs produce linguistic fluency without understanding or grounding in human experience — a critique with deep resonance for questions about what language and meaning are\n- Her TESCREAL critique objects to ideologies that treat present human lives as acceptable costs for speculative future utopias\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Structural analysis of power (influenced by critical race theory and postcolonial studies); democratic accountability; community-centered ethics; Afrofuturism as an alternative vision of technology's possibilities; explicitly rejects utilitarian longtermist calculus\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Has connected AI ideologies to historical movements including eugenics, engaging substantively with intellectual history. No documented engagement with formal theology. Her framing of human dignity and structural sin (without that term) resonates with Catholic Social Teaching's concept of structural sin.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **The Google firing**: The circumstances remain contested. Gebru maintains she was fired for her research; Google claimed she violated policy by \"exfiltrating\" documents. The episode became a global flashpoint over corporate suppression of ethical AI research.\n2. **\"Stochastic Parrots\" criticism**: Some ML researchers argued the paper overstated LLM harms and understated benefits; a counter-paper called it \"sloppy science.\" The paper has since been vindicated by widespread LLM deployment concerns.\n3. **TESCREAL framing**: Critics, including some EA-aligned researchers, argue the TESCREAL acronym lumps together disparate movements unfairly, attributing ideological coherence where there is genuine diversity of views.\n4. **Scope of DAIR**: Some critics question whether DAIR has sufficient research infrastructure and output to be a sustainable alternative to Big Tech AI research institutions.\n5. **Gebru-LeCun 2020 controversy**: The exchange was heated; some observers argued both parties were talking past each other and that neither fully engaged with the other's strongest argument.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Gebru has spoken publicly about the personal and professional cost of her Google firing, including mental health impacts. She has acknowledged the difficulty of building institutions outside Big Tech with sustainable funding.\n\n---\n",
  "goertzel": "# Research Profile: Ben Goertzel\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Ben Goertzel  **Born:** December 8, 1966, Rio de Janeiro, Brazil (to American parents)  **Nationality:** American  \n**Education:** B.A., Quantitative Studies, Bard College at Simon's Rock (left high school after 10th grade); Ph.D., Mathematics, Temple University (1990, age 23) — advisor Avi Lin  \n**Current Role:** Founder and CEO, SingularityNET Foundation; Chairman, OpenCog Foundation; Chairman, Artificial General Intelligence Society; Vice Chairman, Humanity+; Chief Scientist, Mozi Health  \n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1990–1994 | Faculty, University of Nevada, Las Vegas (Mathematics) |\n| 1994–1997 | Chief Scientist, Intelligenesis Corp. |\n| 1997–2001 | Researcher / Chief Scientist, various AI startups |\n| 2001–2008 | Director of Research, Machine Intelligence Research Institute (MIRI, then Singularity Institute) |\n| 2007–2012 | Chief Scientist, Novamente LLC |\n| 2010–2019 | Chief Scientist, Hanson Robotics (Sophia the Robot) |\n| 2017–present | Founder and CEO, SingularityNET Foundation |\n| 2019–present | Chairman, OpenCog Foundation |\n\n**Major Awards:** No major mainstream scientific awards; widely recognized within AGI research community as one of the field's founding voices; has received community awards from AGI Society and transhumanist organizations\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) architectures\n- Cognitive architecture combining neural, symbolic, and probabilistic approaches\n- Distributed AI systems and blockchain-based AI coordination\n- Natural language processing and semantic knowledge representation\n- Evolutionary computation and developmental learning\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *The Structure of Intelligence* (book) | 1993 | Early formal framework for AGI; mathematical treatment of general intelligence |\n| *Chaotic Logic* (book) | 1994 | Connects cognitive science and complexity theory |\n| \"OpenCog: A Software Framework for Integrative Artificial General Intelligence\" | 2009 | Technical description of the OpenCog framework |\n| \"CogPrime: An Integrative Architecture for Embodied Artificial General Intelligence\" | 2012 | Full technical specification of the CogPrime cognitive architecture underlying OpenCog |\n| \"Toward a Formal Model of Cognitive Synergy\" | 2017 | Theoretical framework for combining multiple AI reasoning systems |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- OpenCog: open-source AGI framework combining probabilistic logic networks (PLN), attention allocation, evolutionary program learning (MOSES), pattern mining, and deep neural networks within a shared cognitive hypergraph (AtomSpace)\n- AtomSpace: hypergraph knowledge representation substrate for OpenCog; stores propositions, procedures, and learned associations in a unified structure\n- Probabilistic Logic Networks (PLN): logical inference system handling uncertainty and incomplete knowledge; designed for AGI-level reasoning\n- MOSES (Meta-Optimizing Semantic Evolutionary Search): program synthesis via evolutionary learning\n- SingularityNET: decentralized blockchain-based marketplace for AI services; allows AI agents to interoperate and transact without central control\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** OpenCog has been evaluated on conversational AI tasks, robotic control (in conjunction with Hanson Robotics), and bioinformatics applications; no standard benchmark comparisons to mainstream deep learning\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *The Structure of Intelligence* (1993) — Academic; formal mathematical theory of general intelligence\n- *Chaotic Logic* (1994) — Academic; intelligence, complexity, and chaotic dynamics\n- *Creating Internet Intelligence* (2001) — Popular/technical; vision for web-based AI\n- *The Hidden Pattern* (2006) — Popular; cognitive science and consciousness\n- *The Path to Posthumanity* (2006, with Stephan Vladimir Bugaj) — Popular; AI, transhumanism, and the technological singularity\n- *Artificial General Intelligence* (editor, 2007, with Cassio Pennachin) — First academic anthology on AGI as a distinct field\n- *AGI Revolution* (2016) — Popular; argues AGI is achievable in near term\n- Multiple additional books on AI, consciousness, philosophy, and transhumanism (25+ total)\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"A Beneficial AGI Manifesto\" (Substack) — outlines conditions for AGI that serves human flourishing\n- \"The Coming Consciousness Explosion\" (Substack) — argues AGI will catalyze an expansion of consciousness, not merely intelligence\n- Multiple essays on SingularityNET's vision for decentralized, democratic AI\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Extensive writing on AGI, transhumanism, and AI consciousness across multiple platforms\n- Contributions to *H+* magazine (Humanity+ publication)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Goertzel is the field's most vocal and longstanding AGI advocate. He coined or popularized the term \"AGI\" as a distinct research program, and he believes human-level general intelligence is achievable within the near term — potentially by 2030, though he has repeatedly updated his timelines. He explicitly rejects the view that current deep learning systems represent the path to AGI, arguing instead that cognitive architecture — the integration of multiple AI subsystems (symbolic, neural, evolutionary, attentional) — is the necessary approach. He sees the Kurzweilian Singularity — a moment of intelligence explosion surpassing human cognitive capacity — as both achievable and potentially beneficial, provided AGI is built with benevolent values and democratic governance.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Goertzel takes AGI risk seriously but from a distinctive angle: he argues that the greatest risk is AGI controlled by a narrow group — corporations, governments, or oligarchs — rather than developed as a distributed public good. This is why he founded SingularityNET as a decentralized blockchain-based system: to prevent AI power from concentrating in a few hands. He disagrees sharply with MIRI/Eliezer Yudkowsky's view that AGI alignment is nearly impossible; he believes aligned AGI is achievable through the right cognitive architecture and value learning approach. He also disagrees with OpenAI's centralized, corporate-controlled model of AGI development.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Goertzel advocates for what he calls \"beneficial AGI\" — intelligence systems oriented toward the flourishing of all life, not merely their creators or operators. He is a founding voice for AGI ethics, having edited the first academic anthology on the subject. His decentralized AI marketplace (SingularityNET) is motivated by the belief that AI benefits should be globally distributed, not captured by a few powerful actors. He has written explicitly about consciousness, ethics, and the rights of AGI systems, arguing that sufficiently advanced AI deserves moral consideration.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Goertzel favors decentralized, democratic governance of AI over national or corporate regulatory frameworks. He argues that blockchain-based coordination mechanisms can enable AI governance that is genuinely global and pluralistic, not dominated by US, Chinese, or EU frameworks. He is skeptical of regulation that would lock in incumbent AI companies' advantages. His political economy of AI is broadly libertarian in institutional design but oriented toward global equity in outcomes.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Eliezer Yudkowsky / MIRI | Goertzel believes AGI alignment is achievable; Yudkowsky holds near-certain doom; Goertzel regards MIRI's approach as unhelpfully pessimistic and technically misdirected |\n| OpenAI / Sam Altman | Goertzel criticizes centralized, corporate-controlled AGI development; argues SingularityNET's decentralized model is safer and more equitable |\n| Deep learning maximalists (LeCun, Sutskever era) | Goertzel argues deep learning alone cannot produce AGI; cognitive architecture is required |\n| Mainstream ML community broadly | His OpenCog approach has been largely ignored by mainstream ML; he regards this as a category error by the field, not a verdict on his approach |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Recurring keynotes at AGI Society conferences (which he helped found)\n- Multiple appearances at Singularity University summits\n- TED-style talks on AGI, transhumanism, and the future of consciousness\n- AI for Good (ITU) appearances\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast* — multiple appearances; extended discussions on AGI, OpenCog, and the Singularity\n- *TWIML AI Podcast* — technical discussion of AGI architectures\n- Multiple transhumanist and futurist podcasts\n\n**Social Media:** Active on Twitter/X, Facebook, and Substack; prolific communicator with large following in AGI and transhumanist communities\n\n**Online Courses:** No standard MOOCs; teaches through AGI Society and conference workshop settings; extensive public lecture archive online\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Goertzel holds that consciousness is fundamental and widespread — not a product of human biology but a basic feature of reality that takes many forms. He advocates for a \"Consciousness Explosion\" in which AGI will elevate both individual and collective consciousness to states we cannot currently imagine. He has written: \"The fundamental nature of AGI systems is to pursue the complementary and sometimes contradictory meta-goals of individuation (maintenance of system boundaries) and self-transcendence (growing beyond oneself and leaping into the great unknown).\" He explicitly frames the AGI project as a next step in the evolution of consciousness, continuous with human spiritual development rather than in opposition to it.\n\nOn human dignity, Goertzel argues that the transition to post-human intelligence does not diminish human worth but expands what is possible — humans merging with technology to radically extend their capacities. He does not see AI as replacing humans but as the next phase of what minds can be.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Panpsychist ethics — consciousness has intrinsic value wherever it arises; consequentialist orientation toward maximizing the complexity and richness of consciousness in the universe; decentralized governance as an ethical requirement of AI development\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Goertzel has engaged seriously with Kabbalah, Integral Theory, and Buddhist philosophy. He reads the Singularity as a technological realization of what mystical traditions have described as enlightenment or cosmic reunion. He has written that the convergence of science and philosophy he anticipates \"will enable us to tackle philosophical questions about the nature of consciousness, thought, and perception that have previously been beyond scientific reach.\" His worldview is explicitly post-religious but draws deeply on religious and mystical sources.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Sophia the Robot misrepresentation:** Critics accused Goertzel and Hanson Robotics of presenting Sophia as more intelligent than she was — her \"brain\" was largely scripted responses, not genuine AI, and SingularityNET's role was overstated in marketing materials used to support an ICO (initial coin offering). Wikipedia edits promoting false claims about Sophia's capabilities appeared just before the ICO launch.\n2. **Jeffrey Epstein funding:** In 2001, Goertzel received a $100,000 grant from the Jeffrey Epstein Foundation for AGI research. He has acknowledged this and noted that Epstein's crimes were not publicly known at the time; critics argue the relationship nonetheless raises questions about his professional judgment.\n3. **Consistently missed AGI timelines:** Goertzel has predicted imminent AGI multiple times across decades; critics note that each revised timeline has been as confidently stated as the last, undermining the credibility of his predictions.\n4. **OpenCog's marginal scientific impact:** Despite years of development, OpenCog has not produced competitive results on standard AI benchmarks or produced widely adopted AI applications; mainstream ML has largely passed it by.\n5. **SingularityNET ICO and blockchain:** The 2017–2018 ICO raised significant funds during the cryptocurrency bubble; critics questioned whether the blockchain layer added genuine scientific value or was primarily a funding mechanism.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Goertzel has acknowledged that predicting AGI timelines is inherently uncertain and that his estimates have been wrong before. He has also conceded that OpenCog requires more engineering resources than his organization has had, and that the gap between cognitive architecture research and practical AI application is larger than he initially anticipated.\n\n---\n",
  "gomez": "# Research Profile: Aidan Gomez\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Aidan Gomez\n**Born:** ~1997, Brighton, Ontario, Canada (rural Ontario)\n**Nationality:** Canadian\n\n**Education:**\n- B.Sc. in Computer Science and Mathematics, University of Toronto\n- Ph.D. in Computer Science, University of Oxford (Clarendon Scholar; paused to found Cohere; awarded 2024)\n- Research affiliate, Oxford Applied and Theoretical Machine Learning (OATML) group\n\n**Current Role:** Co-Founder and CEO, Cohere (Toronto, Canada; founded 2019)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2017 | Undergraduate intern, Google Brain (co-authored \"Attention Is All You Need\" at age ~20) |\n| 2017–2019 | Research affiliate, Google Brain; began Oxford Ph.D. |\n| 2019 | Co-founded Cohere with Nick Frosst and Ivan Zhang; paused Oxford Ph.D. |\n| 2019–present | Co-Founder and CEO, Cohere |\n| 2024 | Awarded Oxford Ph.D. in Computer Science |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- Time 100/AI (2023) — among the most influential people in artificial intelligence\n- Named to various \"under 30\" and emerging AI leader lists\n- Cohere raised ~$1.6B at $7B+ valuation (as of September 2025); merger with Aleph Alpha announced April 2026 at ~$20B combined valuation\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Transformer architecture (foundational contribution as undergraduate intern)\n- Enterprise large language models\n- Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)\n- Multilingual and cross-lingual models\n- Sovereign and on-premise enterprise AI deployment\n- AI for business productivity\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Attention Is All You Need\" (Vaswani, Shazeer, Parmar, Uszkoreit, Jones, Gomez, Kaiser, Polosukhin) | 2017 | Co-authored the foundational Transformer paper as a 20-year-old undergraduate intern at Google Brain. 60,000+ citations. |\n| Oxford D.Phil. work on transformers and NLP | 2018–2024 | Doctoral research on transformer architectures and language model capabilities (OATML group, Oxford). |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Co-inventor of the Transformer (one of eight co-authors; contributed as an intern, which is itself historically notable)\n- Cohere Command and Embed models — enterprise-focused LLMs with strong retrieval and classification performance\n- Cohere's sovereign AI deployment model — enabling organizations to run LLMs on private infrastructure without data leaving their control\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- Cohere Embed and Command models evaluated on MTEB (Massive Text Embedding Benchmark) and enterprise retrieval benchmarks.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- CNBC interview (July 2024): Articulated the enterprise AI and data sovereignty thesis publicly — \"Sovereignty means control. No one can switch it off.\"\n- Multiple op-eds and interviews in Canadian business press on AI and national competitiveness.\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Featured in: CNBC, BetaKit, Globe and Mail, The Key Executives, Davos WEF panels (2024–2025)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Gomez has stated publicly that warnings about AGI's existential risk are overblown. His view is that the near-term risks from AI are not superintelligence but specific, tractable harms: automated disinformation on social media, concentration of AI power in a few large companies, and the erosion of organizational autonomy when businesses depend on AI systems they do not control. He is focused on near-term, consequential AI — AI for enterprise productivity and national competitiveness — rather than speculative AGI scenarios.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Gomez's safety concerns are practical and near-term. He has spoken specifically about the risk of automated disinformation on social media as a concrete and underappreciated AI harm. His company's emphasis on data sovereignty — that organizations should control their own AI infrastructure — is a safety argument: systems that can be \"switched off\" by a third party are systems with a dangerous single point of failure.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Gomez has engaged directly with regulatory bodies on AI ethics. In March 2025, he was called to testify (or provide written input) to the U.S. House Judiciary Committee on AI censorship. He appeared at Davos to discuss AI governance. His ethical emphasis centers on: (1) organizational data sovereignty as a right; (2) clear regulatory frameworks to enable responsible AI adoption; (3) distributed AI capability as a counterweight to Big Tech concentration. He testified to Congress and participated in Vatican-adjacent discussions with Pope Leo XIV (as part of a new generation of tech leaders engaging the Vatican on AI).\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Gomez has explicitly supported smart regulation as a driver of AI adoption: \"Regulation is helpful in driving clarity. Businesses considering whether to adopt AI tools are very worried about the lack of clarity around AI adoption.\" He has been a prominent voice for Canada as an AI sovereign nation, arguing that Canadian AI leadership is a national imperative. He backed the Canada-Cohere partnership (announced August 2025) to develop domestic AI infrastructure. Cohere's merger with German company Aleph Alpha (2026) reflects a strategy of building a non-US enterprise AI alternative.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Big Tech AI concentration (Google, OpenAI, Microsoft) | Argues that enterprise AI should not depend on hyperscaler infrastructure that creates data dependency and organizational vulnerability |\n| AGI existential risk community | Believes near-term disinformation and concentration risks are more pressing than speculative superintelligence scenarios |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- World Economic Forum, Davos (2024, 2025) — on AI governance and enterprise AI\n- U.S. House Judiciary Committee (March 2025) — on AI censorship and governance\n- CNBC interview (July 2024): \"Aidan Gomez helped invent the transformer at Google. At Cohere, he's now taking AI to businesses\"\n- Transform summit (September 2024): \"The Role of Regulation in Spurring AI Adoption\"\n- Canadian government partnership announcement (August 2025)\n\n**Podcasts:** Multiple interviews on startup and AI-industry podcasts; limited long-form research-focused appearances.\n\n**Social Media:** Active on LinkedIn; Twitter/X presence in Canadian tech circles.\n\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Gomez's framing of data sovereignty — \"Sovereignty means control. No one can switch it off\" — encodes a value about organizational autonomy and dignity that has analogs to human dignity: organizations, like persons, should not be wholly dependent on systems they cannot control or exit. He has not articulated this in explicitly humanistic or theological terms.\n\nHis concern about automated disinformation reflects a values commitment to truth: the integrity of the information environment is a precondition for democratic deliberation. Gomez has named this as a concrete AI risk, not just a policy question.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Organizational sovereignty and autonomy; truth and information integrity; clear regulatory frameworks as enabling conditions for responsible AI; distributed AI capability as a counterweight to power concentration.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Documented engagement at the Vatican/Pope Leo XIV level (meeting with new tech leaders on AI ethics). Whether this reflects theological engagement or diplomatic outreach is not confirmed. His Oxford education included exposure to philosophy and humanities in a way that a pure computer science program would not.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **House Judiciary Committee subpoena (March 2025):** Gomez was contacted by the U.S. House Judiciary Committee regarding AI censorship concerns. The framing of AI \"censorship\" by the committee reflects a specific political framing that Cohere was being asked to respond to; the substance of Gomez's response is not fully publicly documented.\n2. **Enterprise AI vs. open access:** Cohere's model is explicitly enterprise-focused and proprietary. Unlike Meta's LLaMA (open weights) or Hugging Face's ecosystem, Cohere does not release models publicly. This positions Cohere as democratizing AI for enterprises but not for individuals or under-resourced communities — a distinction the podcast should name.\n3. **Merger scale and consolidation:** The announced April 2026 merger with Aleph Alpha to create a ~$20B combined enterprise AI entity raises questions about whether \"distributed AI\" as an alternative to Big Tech is genuinely distributed or simply consolidation under different ownership.\n4. **Age and experience:** Gomez became CEO of a billion-dollar AI company in his early twenties. Observers have noted the concentration of consequential AI decisions in very young founders without extensive management experience or exposure to the downstream social effects of their technology.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Gomez has acknowledged that enterprise AI adoption requires regulatory clarity — implicitly acknowledging that without proper governance, enterprise AI deployment carries risks that markets alone will not correct.\n\n---\n",
  "goodfellow": "# Research Profile: Ian Goodfellow\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Ian J. Goodfellow\n**Born:** 1987 (exact date not publicly disclosed), United States\n**Nationality:** American\n\n**Education:**\n- B.S. and M.S., Computer Science, Stanford University (supervisor: Andrew Ng)\n- Ph.D., Machine Learning, Université de Montréal, February 2015 (supervisors: Yoshua Bengio and Aaron Courville; thesis: \"Deep Learning of Representations and Its Application to Computer Vision\")\n\n**Current Role:** As of mid-2026, departed Google DeepMind; currently in stealth startup (per LinkedIn)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2013 (summer) | Software Engineering Intern, Google |\n| 2013–2014 | Research Scientist, Google Brain |\n| 2016–2019 | Research Scientist, OpenAI |\n| 2019–2022 | Director of Machine Learning, Apple Special Projects Group |\n| 2022–2025 | Research Scientist, Google DeepMind |\n| 2025–present | Undisclosed (stealth startup) |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- MIT Technology Review \"35 Innovators Under 35\" (2017)\n- Named one of TIME100 AI's emerging contributors in generative AI coverage\n- Holst Memorial Lecture, TU Eindhoven (2023)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Generative adversarial networks (GANs) and generative modeling\n- Adversarial examples and machine learning security\n- Semi-supervised learning and representation learning\n- Privacy-preserving machine learning\n- Deep neural network theory and training dynamics\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Generative Adversarial Nets\" (Goodfellow, Pouget-Abadie, Mirza, Xu, Warde-Farley, Ozair, Courville, Bengio) | 2014 | Introduced GANs; one of the most influential papers in AI history |\n| \"Explaining and Harnessing Adversarial Examples\" (Goodfellow, Shlens, Szegedy) | 2015 | Introduced FGSM attack; defined the field of adversarial robustness |\n| \"Deep Learning\" (Goodfellow, Bengio, Courville) | 2016 | Standard graduate-level textbook on deep learning; first author |\n| \"Generalization and Equilibrium in Generative Adversarial Nets (GANs)\" | 2017 | Theoretical analysis of GAN training dynamics |\n| \"A Note on the Inception Score\" | 2018 | Critiqued common GAN evaluation metric; shaped evaluation practice |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) — conceived 2014 during a late-night discussion; published and presented at NeurIPS 2014\n- Fast Gradient Sign Method (FGSM) — foundational adversarial attack algorithm enabling adversarial robustness research\n- Maxout networks — activation function designed to facilitate dropout and model averaging\n- Contributed to deep learning chapter in *Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach* (Russell and Norvig, 4th ed.), used in 1,500+ universities\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- Contributed to GAN evaluation methodology; critiqued and helped improve Inception Score as a benchmark\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Deep Learning* (2016, MIT Press) — co-authored with Yoshua Bengio and Aaron Courville. The definitive graduate textbook on deep learning. Available free online at deeplearningbook.org. Audience: researchers, advanced students. Key thesis: deep architectures learn hierarchical representations that generalize across tasks.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"NIPS 2016 Tutorial: Generative Adversarial Networks\" — comprehensive survey of GAN variants and training challenges; widely read document in generative AI development\n- \"Adversarial Machine Learning at Scale\" — articulated the threat model for adversarial attacks on deployed systems\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- DeepLearning.AI \"The Batch\" feature: \"Ian Goodfellow: A Man, A Plan, A GAN\" — narrative of how GANs were conceived\n- MIT Technology Review innovator profile (2017)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Goodfellow has not staked out a prominent public position on AGI timelines or existential risk. He is primarily a technical researcher and has not adopted the public policy-advocacy role of Bengio or the public skepticism of LeCun. He has participated in AI safety roundtables and contributed to governance conversations without becoming a leading public voice.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Goodfellow's primary contribution to AI safety is technical: adversarial examples demonstrated that neural networks are fragile in ways that matter enormously for safety-critical applications. He has been an advocate for adversarial training and robustness evaluation. Reports suggest he left Apple in part over ethical concerns about internal research directions, though he has not commented extensively on this publicly. He has participated in U.S. and EU regulatory working groups.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Goodfellow has publicly advocated for diversity and inclusion in AI research. He supports responsible AI development practices including red-teaming, structured impact assessments for dual-use risks, and anticipating adversarial misuse. His approach is technically grounded — ethics made concrete through security practices — rather than primarily philosophical.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Goodfellow has contributed to national AI strategy consultations and regulatory working groups in the U.S. and EU without taking high-profile public positions. He favors structured safety evaluations and red-teaming as practical governance tools.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Apple leadership (implicit) | Left Apple citing ethical concerns about return-to-office policy and reportedly research direction; made public only through his resignation statement |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- NeurIPS 2016 Tutorial on Generative Adversarial Networks — the most influential early survey of the GAN field\n- Holst Memorial Lecture, TU Eindhoven (2023)\n- Various ICLR and NeurIPS invited lectures on adversarial robustness\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- \"Lex Fridman Podcast\" — interview on GANs, deep learning, and AI safety\n- Various AI research podcast appearances including \"The TWIML AI Podcast\"\n\n**Social Media:**\n- X/Twitter: @goodfellow_ian (inactive or rarely used)\n- LinkedIn: linkedin.com/in/ian-goodfellow-b7187213\n\n**Online Courses:**\n- No independent course platform; his *Deep Learning* textbook (free at deeplearningbook.org) serves as a de facto open course\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Goodfellow has not made prominent public statements on AI consciousness or human dignity. His implicit anthropology emerges through his security and adversarial research: he treats the robustness and reliability of AI systems — their trustworthiness in contexts affecting real human lives — as an ethical imperative. His departure from Apple over policy and reported ethical concerns suggests personal ethical commitments that exceed purely technical concerns, though he has not articulated these in philosophical or theological terms.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Goodfellow's ethics are practice-oriented: safety is demonstrated through red-teaming, adversarial testing, and security audits, not through philosophical proclamations. He represents a kind of engineering conscience — the researcher who shows that systems marketed as reliable are actually fragile, and insists on honest accounting of that fragility.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **The \"GANfather\" Origin Story:** The account of GANs being conceived at a bar in a single night has become a founding myth of generative AI. While the story is documented, it flattens the actual development process and has contributed to a \"lone genius\" narrative that obscures co-authors' contributions.\n2. **Deepfakes and Dual-Use Risk:** GANs became the foundational technology for synthetic media and deepfakes. Goodfellow has acknowledged the dual-use concerns but did not initially focus on them; critics argue the generative AI field underestimated misinformation risks when publishing widely.\n3. **Apple Departure:** Goodfellow's resignation from Apple in April 2022 — publicly framed as protest against return-to-office requirements — reportedly also involved ethical concerns about research directions. He has not publicly elaborated, leaving the substantive issues unresolved in public record.\n4. **Adversarial Examples and Deployed Safety:** Despite pioneering adversarial robustness research, adversarial vulnerabilities remain largely unresolved in deployed systems, raising questions about whether the research community has adequately addressed the problems Goodfellow's work identified.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** In the NeurIPS 2016 GAN tutorial, Goodfellow was candid about GAN training instability, mode collapse, and evaluation difficulties — a relatively unusual degree of transparency about open problems in a field he largely created.\n\n---\n",
  "hassabis": "# Research Profile: Demis Hassabis\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Demis Hassabis **Born:** July 27, 1976, London, UK **Nationality:** British\n**Education:** B.A. in Computer Science (Double First), Queens' College, Cambridge University (1997); Ph.D. in Cognitive Neuroscience, University College London (UCL) (2009) — dissertation on imagination and memory encoding, advised by Eleanor Maguire; Postdoctoral research, Harvard University and MIT (2009–2010)\n**Current Role:** Co-founder and CEO, Google DeepMind; Co-founder and CEO, Isomorphic Labs; UK Government AI Adviser; Member, Pontifical Academy of Sciences (appointed by Pope Francis, March 2024)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1987–1990 | Chess prodigy; achieved International Master rank at age 13 |\n| 1994–1997 | Lead AI programmer, Bullfrog Productions / Peter Molyneux's Lionhead Studios; co-designed *Theme Park* |\n| 1998–2005 | Co-founder and Managing Director, Elixir Studios (video game company); produced *Republic: The Revolution* and *Evil Genius* |\n| 2005–2009 | Ph.D. candidate, UCL; studied hippocampal role in imagination and memory |\n| 2009–2010 | Postdoctoral researcher, Harvard and MIT |\n| 2010–2014 | Co-founder and CEO, DeepMind Technologies |\n| 2014–present | CEO, Google DeepMind (Google acquired DeepMind for ~$500M in 2014) |\n| 2021–present | Co-founder and CEO, Isomorphic Labs (AI drug discovery spinout) |\n\n**Major Awards:** Nobel Prize in Chemistry (2024) — shared with John Jumper and David Baker, for AlphaFold protein structure prediction; CBE (2017); Knighthood (Sir Demis Hassabis, 2024); TIME100 Most Influential People (2017, 2025); TIME100 AI \"Architects of AI\" Person of the Year (2025, collective); Royal Society Fellowship; BAFTA Games Award; Multiple honorary doctorates\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** Reinforcement learning; deep learning; computational neuroscience; AI for scientific discovery; protein structure prediction; game-playing AI; AI for drug discovery\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| DQN (Deep Q-Network) | 2013 / 2015 | First RL agent to achieve human-level performance across Atari games using only raw pixel inputs; landmark Nature paper; launched DeepMind's reputation |\n| AlphaGo | 2016 | Defeated world champion Lee Sedol 4-1 at Go; widely considered the pivotal moment proving deep RL could master complex strategy |\n| AlphaGo Zero | 2017 | Learned Go from scratch without human game data; defeated AlphaGo 100-0; demonstrated AI superiority over human knowledge as training signal |\n| AlphaZero | 2017 | Generalized AlphaGo Zero to chess, shogi, and Go; achieved superhuman performance in all three; published in Science |\n| AlphaStar | 2019 | Grandmaster-level StarCraft II play; demonstrated long-horizon planning in complex real-time environment |\n| AlphaFold 1 | 2018 | Won CASP13; correctly predicted most protein structures; first major demonstration of AI for structural biology |\n| AlphaFold 2 | 2020–2021 | Won CASP14 decisively; predictions approach experimental accuracy; won Nobel Prize in Chemistry 2024 for Hassabis and Jumper |\n| AlphaFold Protein Structure Database | 2021 | Made 200 million protein structure predictions freely available to all researchers worldwide |\n| AlphaMissense | 2023 | AI system predicting which genetic variants cause disease; published in Science |\n| Gemini (co-development) | 2023–present | Google DeepMind co-developed Google's flagship LLM family |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:** Deep Q-Network (DQN); Monte Carlo Tree Search combined with deep learning (AlphaGo); self-play reinforcement learning (AlphaGo Zero); the AlphaFold architecture combining evolutionary information, physical constraints, and attention mechanisms for protein structure prediction\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** CASP (Critical Assessment of Protein Structure Prediction) winner multiple times; AlphaFold Protein Structure Database (the most consequential scientific dataset released in biology in decades)\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None as sole author; co-authored papers include the key journal publications below\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"AlphaFold: Five Years of Impact\" (LinkedIn, 2026) — Hassabis's personal retrospective on AlphaFold's scientific influence\n- \"For AI to deliver its promised benefits, it must be designed in the humanist tradition, with people remaining unequivocally in control, and with human dignity always coming first\" — widely quoted public statement on AI ethics\n- Nobel Prize lecture (Stockholm, December 2024) — articulated vision for AI as tool for scientific discovery\n**Popular Articles:**\n- TIME magazine profile and interview (2025) — on AGI timeline, AI in the military, and responsible development\n- Lex Fridman Podcast transcript (Podcast #475, 2024) — extended discussion of consciousness, AGI, and the nature of intelligence\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Hassabis believes AGI is a realistic near-term horizon. He has stated there is a 50% chance of achieving AGI by 2030. He has said \"over the next five to ten years, capabilities will start moving towards artificial general intelligence.\" He describes AGI as potentially \"10 times bigger than the Industrial Revolution, and maybe 10 times faster.\" He distinguishes AGI from current systems and argues that genuine AGI will require abilities the current generation does not have: generalization, causal reasoning, and something like imagination.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Hassabis is among the most serious safety thinkers in the industry CEO category. He considers the probability of catastrophic AI failure to be \"non-zero\" and has said there are \"valid concerns that should be discussed and debated now, decades before there's anything of actual potential consequence.\" He believes AI alignment must be solved before AGI arrives. He advocates for global governance frameworks and has spoken about the need for an \"AI equivalent of nuclear non-proliferation treaties.\" He has said explicitly that \"as AI becomes more autonomous, there is a risk it could deviate from its original instructions.\"\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Hassabis articulates an explicitly humanist AI ethics: \"For AI to deliver its promised benefits, it must be designed in the humanist tradition, with people remaining unequivocally in control, and with human dignity always coming first.\" He believes transparency and human oversight are non-negotiable. He is unusual among AI CEOs in foregrounding human dignity as an explicit criterion — language that resonates with Catholic Social Teaching even though it arrives from a secular humanist tradition.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Hassabis has called for international coordination on AI governance, drawing analogies to nuclear arms control. He has said the risks are real enough to justify significant regulatory attention. He has been more publicly cautious about AI risk than Huang or Zuckerberg, and more aligned with the responsible development wing of the AI community.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Google leadership (implicitly) | Extracted a pledge at DeepMind's 2014 acquisition that the AI would not be used for military/weapons purposes; that pledge was voided by Google's military contracts by 2024 |\n| Accelerationist AI advocates | Has repeatedly argued for caution and deliberate safety work; pushes back against rushing to deploy systems whose alignment is not understood |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Nobel Prize lecture, Stockholm (December 2024)\n- Lex Fridman Podcast #475 (2024) — among the most substantive AI conversations publicly available\n- TIME100 Gala speeches (2017, 2025)\n- World Economic Forum, Davos (multiple years)\n- Vatican — speaker at multiple Pontifical Academy of Sciences sessions on AI\n**Podcasts:** Lex Fridman Podcast (multiple appearances); various Bloomberg and science journalism interviews\n**Social Media:** Active on LinkedIn and X; professional communications about DeepMind research; personal reflections on chess, science, and AI\n**Online Courses:** None; his papers and talks function as advanced-level educational material\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\nHis explicit commitment to \"human dignity\" as a design principle for AI — stated in multiple public forums — is a form of philosophical humanism that has significant overlap with Catholic Social Teaching even while arriving from different metaphysical premises.\n\nHe visits the Vatican regularly for private meetings with Pope Francis and has been a speaker at Pontifical Academy of Sciences conferences on AI. Pope Francis appointed him to the Pontifical Academy of Sciences in March 2024 — the first AI CEO to hold such membership. This appointment is theologically significant: the Vatican does not require scientific academicians to be Catholic, but it does signal that the Church regards his work as consequential for questions within its purview.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Secular humanism; scientific utilitarianism (maximize benefits for humanity from scientific discovery); \"humanist tradition\" AI ethics; robust safety and human oversight principles\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Directly engaged — Vatican meetings with Pope Francis; Pontifical Academy of Sciences membership; spoke at Vatican AI conferences; has discussed consciousness and its relationship to intelligence in terms that engage philosophy of mind directly\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Military AI pledge voided:** Hassabis extracted a pledge from Google in 2014 that DeepMind's AI would never be used for military or weapons purposes. By 2024, Google sells AI services — including DeepMind's technology — to the US and Israeli militaries. Hassabis has acknowledged the original pledge is no longer operative but has not made strong public statements defending or criticizing the reversal.\n2. **DeepMind NHS data partnership (2017):** DeepMind partnered with the UK National Health Service, gaining access to 1.6 million patient records without adequate patient consent, according to the UK's data protection authority. The Information Commissioner's Office found the arrangement violated data protection law.\n3. **Google acquisition oversight:** DeepMind was acquired by Google in 2014. Some early DeepMind employees and external observers have questioned whether Google's commercial imperatives have constrained DeepMind's original mission of safe and beneficial AGI development. Mustafa Suleyman, DeepMind's co-founder, left in 2022.\n4. **Pace of AGI claims vs. safety investments:** Critics argue that Hassabis's public AGI timelines (50% chance by 2030) are not matched by the scale of safety research investment at Google DeepMind. The safety team is small relative to the capabilities research team.\n5. **Nobel Prize communication:** Some structural biologists noted that AlphaFold builds extensively on decades of experimental crystallography and cryo-EM data; questions were raised about whether the Nobel appropriately recognized the experimental scientists whose data AlphaFold relied upon.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Hassabis has said he cannot guarantee that current AI systems are aligned with human values, and that the probability of catastrophic failure is non-zero. He has said that \"we don't fully understand these systems\" and that this uncertainty is itself a reason for caution.\n\n---\n",
  "he": "# Research Profile: Kaiming He\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** He Kaiming (何恺明)\n**Born:** Not publicly disclosed (estimated born ~1985–1987 based on career timeline)\n**Nationality:** Chinese; based in the United States\n\n**Education:**\n- B.Sc., Department of Electronic Engineering, Tsinghua University, Beijing, 2007\n- Ph.D., Information Engineering, Chinese University of Hong Kong (CUHK), Multimedia Laboratory, 2011\n\n**Current Role:** Associate Professor (tenured from July 2025), Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science (EECS), MIT; Douglas Ross Software Technology Career Development Professor, MIT; Part-time Distinguished Scientist, Google DeepMind (from 2025)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2007–2011 | PhD student, Multimedia Laboratory, CUHK |\n| 2011–2016 | Researcher, Microsoft Research Asia (MSRA), Beijing |\n| 2016–2024 | Research Scientist (and later Principal Research Scientist), Facebook AI Research (FAIR) / Meta AI |\n| Feb 2024–Jun 2025 | Associate Professor (untenured), MIT EECS; Douglas Ross Career Development Professor |\n| Jun 2025–present | Associate Professor (tenured), MIT EECS |\n| Jun 2025–present | Part-time Distinguished Scientist, Google DeepMind |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- CVPR Best Paper Award (2009, 2016)\n- ICCV Best Paper Award / Marr Prize (2017)\n- Future Science Prize in Mathematics and Computer Science (2023) — shared with collaborators; for deep residual learning\n- Ranked #1 overall, AI 2000 Most Influential Scholars in Artificial Intelligence (2022)\n- ResNet paper among the most-cited papers of the 21st century (298,000+ citations as of 2025)\n- MIT tenure (June 2025)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Deep convolutional neural networks and network architecture design\n- Image recognition, object detection, and instance segmentation\n- Visual representation learning and self-supervised learning\n- Generative modeling (masked autoencoders, diffusion models)\n- Neural network initialization and training stability\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Deep Residual Learning for Image Recognition\" (He, Zhang, Ren, Sun) | 2015/2016 | Introduced ResNet with skip connections; won ILSVRC 2015; most-cited paper of the 21st century |\n| \"Delving Deep into Rectifiers: Surpassing Human-Level Performance on ImageNet Classification\" (He, Zhang, Ren, Sun) | 2015 | Introduced PReLU activation and He/Kaiming initialization; first paper to claim surpassing human-level ImageNet performance |\n| \"Identity Mappings in Deep Residual Networks\" (He, Zhang, Ren, Sun) | 2016 | Refined ResNet with pre-activation residuals; theoretical justification for skip connections |\n| \"Mask R-CNN\" (He, Gkioxari, Dollár, Girshick) | 2017 | Introduced instance segmentation; extended object detection to pixel-level masks; ICCV Best Paper 2017 |\n| \"Momentum Contrast for Unsupervised Visual Representation Learning\" (MoCo) (He et al.) | 2020 | Foundational self-supervised visual representation learning method |\n| \"Masked Autoencoders Are Scalable Vision Learners\" (MAE) (He et al.) | 2022 | Applied BERT-style masked pre-training to vision; scaled self-supervised learning for images |\n| \"MeanFlow\" (He lab) | 2025 | Theoretical framework for single-step generative models; ongoing research direction |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Residual Networks (ResNet) — skip connections allowing training of 100–1000+ layer networks; solved vanishing gradient in very deep networks; basis for nearly all subsequent deep vision architectures\n- He/Kaiming initialization — mathematically principled weight initialization for ReLU networks; standard practice in deep learning\n- PReLU (Parametric Rectified Linear Unit) — learnable variant of ReLU; introduced alongside He initialization\n- Mask R-CNN — added a mask prediction branch to Faster R-CNN; became the standard instance segmentation framework\n- MoCo (Momentum Contrast) — enabled large-scale self-supervised visual representation learning without labels\n- MAE (Masked Autoencoder) — vision-domain analogue of BERT pre-training\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- Key contributor to COCO (Common Objects in Context) benchmark development through object detection and segmentation work at FAIR\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\nNone for general audiences. All contributions through peer-reviewed conference and journal papers.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- No manifestos or position essays. He publishes technical papers rather than public commentary.\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Occasional interviews in Chinese-language media and AI news outlets on ResNet's impact and his research agenda\n- MIT CSAIL profile and Google Scholar page document his research evolution\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** No documented public positions. He has not engaged in public AGI debates.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** No documented public positions. He has not participated in the public AI safety discourse.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** No documented public positions on AI ethics, bias, fairness, or governance. His public engagement is almost entirely technical.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** No documented public positions.\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- CVPR, ICCV, NeurIPS keynotes and invited talks on computer vision architectures\n- Future Science Prize lecture (2023)\n- MIT EECS seminars and department talks\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- No known major podcast appearances.\n\n**Social Media:**\n- No known active public social media presence.\n- Scholar page: scholar.google.com/citations?user=DhtAFkwAAAAJ\n\n**Online Courses:**\n- No MOOC. MIT course materials through EECS.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** No documented statements. Kaiming He maintains an exceptionally narrow public profile focused entirely on technical research. He has not engaged philosophical or ethical questions about AI in any documented public forum.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Unknown from public record. His career choices — moving from Microsoft Research Asia to FAIR/Meta to MIT — suggest a prioritization of research impact and institutional independence over commercial optimization, but this is inference.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **ResNet and the Scale Race:** ResNet enabled the training of arbitrarily deep networks, which in turn enabled the scale-up of deep learning that has driven both extraordinary capabilities and significant societal disruptions. The architecture is morally neutral, but it is infrastructural to many AI systems whose societal effects are contested.\n2. **Meta/Facebook AI Period:** He spent eight years (2016–2024) at Facebook AI Research, a period during which Meta's AI systems contributed to documented harms in content moderation, political manipulation, and mental health (particularly the algorithmic amplification critiques). He has not commented on this context.\n3. **Google DeepMind Part-Time Role:** His simultaneous appointment at MIT and Google DeepMind raises standard academic-industry conflict-of-interest questions; he is not unique in this and MIT has policies governing such arrangements.\n4. **Citation Practices:** The ResNet paper (2015) builds on Highway Networks (Srivastava, Greff, Schmidhuber) and is sometimes cited by Schmidhuber as insufficiently crediting his group's prior work. He has not publicly responded to this claim.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** No documented self-acknowledged limitations. He does not engage in public discourse about his work beyond technical presentations.\n\n---\n",
  "henna": "# Research Profile: Henna Virkkunen\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Henna Maria Virkkunen **Born:** June 4, 1972, Joutsa, Central Finland **Nationality:** Finnish\n**Education:** Bachelor's degree (2000) and Master's degree (2001), University of Jyväskylä (field: education/administration)\n**Current Role:** Executive Vice-President, European Commission for Technological Sovereignty, Security and Democracy; European Commissioner for Digital and Frontier Technologies (von der Leyen II Commission, December 2024–present)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2007–2014 | Member of Parliament, Finnish Parliament (Eduskunta); National Coalition Party |\n| 2008–2011 | Minister of Education, Finland |\n| 2011–2014 | Minister of Public Administration and Local Government, Finland |\n| 2014–2024 | Member of the European Parliament; National Coalition Party / EPP |\n| Various (MEP) | Worked on Digital Services Act, Cyber-Resilience Act, Connecting Europe Facility |\n| December 2024–present | Executive Vice-President for Tech Sovereignty, Security and Democracy, European Commission |\n| December 2024–present | European Commissioner for Digital and Frontier Technologies |\n\n**Major Awards:** Named Optica's 2025 Advocate of Optics.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Policy / Governance Work:**\n- Overseeing implementation of the EU AI Act, including through the newly established EU AI Office\n- Leading EU Tech Sovereignty strategy — reducing European dependence on non-European AI infrastructure\n- Shaping AI regulation toward innovation-friendly frameworks while maintaining safety standards\n- Cybersecurity policy and Cyber-Resilience Act implementation\n- Democratic resilience: countering Russian hybrid operations and AI-enabled disinformation\n- Connecting Europe Facility — digital infrastructure investment\n\n**Landmark Papers / Policy Documents:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| EU AI Act Omnibus Agreement | 2025 | Simplification of AI Act implementation requirements for businesses; Virkkunen led negotiations |\n| \"Building Artificial Intelligence the European Way\" (LinkedIn) | 2025 | Policy statement articulating EU vision for competitive, sovereign, and safe AI |\n| EU AI Office Implementation Framework | 2025 | AI Office operational under her oversight; enforcing general-purpose AI model rules |\n\n**Key Contributions:**\n- As EVP, holds oversight of the EU AI Office, the body responsible for implementing the AI Act's most complex provisions\n- Oversaw AI Act implementation deadline adjustments to give businesses practical compliance time\n- Led the \"omnibus\" agreement simplifying AI Act rules for start-ups and SMEs\n- Articulated the AI Act as simultaneously a safety guarantee and an innovation enabler\n- Positioned EU Tech Sovereignty as a geopolitical security issue, not merely a regulatory one\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None published.\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Building Artificial Intelligence the European Way\" (LinkedIn, 2025) — articulates her vision of EU AI development\n- Parliamentary reports and policy statements from her decade as MEP\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Interviews in Euronews, Politico Europe, and Financial Times on AI Act implementation and EU tech strategy\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Has not focused publicly on AGI scenarios. Her mandate is implementation — ensuring the EU AI Act's provisions become effective compliance reality and that European AI capabilities are globally competitive. She engages present-tense AI deployment, not speculative superintelligence.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Safety and innovation are not in opposition. The EU AI Act's risk-based framework should enable clear rules that businesses can comply with efficiently. She pushed to simplify compliance requirements for start-ups and SMEs without lowering safety standards for high-risk applications. She has been willing to delay implementation timelines where technical standards are not yet ready, a pragmatic safety-first position.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Framed in fundamental rights and democratic values. She has consistently articulated the EU approach as ensuring citizens can both innovate and feel safe. Ethics is operationalized through binding rules and EU AI Office enforcement rather than voluntary frameworks.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Virkkunen represents a new generation of EU policymakers who treat AI regulation as inseparable from geopolitical security. Her approach is: Europe must be sovereign in AI to be secure, and secure in AI to remain democratic. She has said the EU has \"all the ingredients to succeed\" — talent, infrastructure, a large internal market — but is held back by regulatory complexity. Her response has been to simplify, not eliminate, rules. She supports the AI Act's structure but wants implementation to be practical for businesses, particularly start-ups. Her political home (EPP, center-right) means she is more sympathetic than her predecessors to industry concerns about overregulation.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| AI Act maximalists (civil society) | Pushed to simplify and in some cases delay implementation timelines |\n| AI industry | Must still meet fundamental obligations; simplified does not mean abandoned |\n| China / Russia | Her security framing explicitly identifies these as adversaries in AI geopolitics |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- European Parliament confirmation hearing (November 2024) — detailed questioning on AI Act, cybersecurity, and digital sovereignty\n- Optica (2025) — Advocate of Optics award ceremony\n- Various EU ministerial meetings and digital commissioner forums\n\n**Podcasts:** Limited podcast presence; primarily engages through official EU channels and press.\n**Social Media:** Active on X and LinkedIn; regular communication on EU tech policy developments.\n**Online Courses:** None documented.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Democratic constitutionalism; EU fundamental rights; subsidiarity in implementation (national authorities enforcing EU-level rules); innovation-protection balance.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement with religious or theological frameworks. Her educational background is in education and administration.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. Civil society groups criticized her as too willing to soften the AI Act's requirements under industry pressure, particularly in delaying implementation timelines.\n2. Her confirmation hearing raised questions about her depth of technical AI expertise; she was challenged on specific provisions of the AI Act she would oversee.\n3. Critics argued that describing the AI Act as \"simplified\" obscures substantive weakening of compliance obligations for businesses.\n4. Her relatively brief MEP experience on AI-specific dossiers (compared to longer-serving digital policy specialists) raised questions about her readiness for the EVP role.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Virkkunen acknowledged at her confirmation hearing that standards and guidelines must be ready for the AI Act to function, and stated that delays to implementation could not be \"ruled out\" if technical readiness was insufficient — a pragmatic admission that regulatory timelines face real-world constraints.\n\n---\n",
  "hinton": "# Research Profile: Geoffrey Hinton\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Geoffrey Everest Hinton\n**Born:** 6 December 1947, Wimbledon, London, UK\n**Nationality:** British-Canadian (dual)\n**Known As:** \"The Godfather of AI\" / \"The Godfather of Deep Learning\"\n\n**Family:** Great-great-grandson of logician George Boole. First wife, Rosalind Zalin, died of ovarian cancer in 1994. Second wife, Jacqueline (\"Jackie\") Ford — British art historian — died of pancreatic cancer on 20 April 2023, weeks before his Google resignation. Two adopted children: Thomas and Emma.\n\n**Education:**\n- **B.A. in Experimental Psychology**, King's College, Cambridge, 1970. Wandered through natural sciences, history of art, and philosophy before settling — he cites this as central to his cross-disciplinary thinking.\n- **Ph.D. in Artificial Intelligence**, University of Edinburgh, 1978. Supervisor: Christopher Longuet-Higgins.\n- **Postdoctoral**, UC San Diego (Psychology), 1978–1980 and Spring 1982.\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n\n| Years | Role & Institution |\n|---|---|\n| 1978–1980 | Visiting Scholar, UC San Diego |\n| 1980–1982 | Research Associate, University of Edinburgh |\n| Spring 1982 | Visiting Assistant Professor, UC San Diego |\n| 1982–1987 | Faculty, Carnegie Mellon University |\n| 1987–1998 | Professor, University of Toronto |\n| 1998–2001 | Founder & Director, Gatsby Computational Neuroscience Unit, UCL |\n| 2001–present | University Professor Emeritus, University of Toronto |\n| 2004 | Co-founded CIFAR Neural Computation and Adaptive Perception program |\n| 2012 | Co-founded DNNresearch Inc. with Krizhevsky and Sutskever |\n| March 2013 | DNNresearch acquired by Google; joins Google Brain |\n| 2013–2023 | VP & Engineering Fellow, Google Brain |\n| **May 2023** | **Resigned from Google** to speak freely about AI risks |\n| **October 2024** | **Nobel Prize in Physics** (shared with John Hopfield) |\n| 2025 | Queen Elizabeth Prize for Engineering |\n\n**Current Role:** Professor Emeritus, University of Toronto; independent AI safety advocate.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:** Artificial neural networks, deep learning, machine learning, cognitive neuroscience, unsupervised learning, AI safety.\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n\n| Paper | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Learning representations by back-propagating errors\" (with Rumelhart & Williams) | 1986, *Nature* | Popularized backpropagation — the algorithm that makes training multi-layer neural networks tractable; backbone of virtually all modern AI. |\n| \"A Learning Algorithm for Boltzmann Machines\" (with Ackley & Sejnowski) | 1985 | Introduced Boltzmann machines — stochastic neural networks capable of learning internal representations. |\n| \"A Fast Learning Algorithm for Deep Belief Nets\" (with Osindero & Teh) | 2006, *Neural Computation* | Layer-by-layer pre-training that reignited serious interest in deep learning after the first \"winter.\" |\n| \"ImageNet Classification with Deep Convolutional Neural Networks\" (AlexNet — with Krizhevsky & Sutskever) | 2012, *NeurIPS* | Crushed the ImageNet competition and triggered the deep learning revolution in computer vision. |\n| \"Dropout: A Simple Way to Prevent Neural Networks from Overfitting\" | 2014, *JMLR* | Dropout regularization — now standard in nearly every neural network. |\n| \"Dynamic Routing Between Capsules\" (with Sabour & Frosst) | 2017 | Capsule networks as an alternative to CNNs for modeling part-whole spatial hierarchies. |\n| \"The Forward-Forward Algorithm: Some Preliminary Investigations\" | 2022 | Alternative to backpropagation using two forward passes; addresses biological implausibility concerns. |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Backpropagation (popularized/formalized, 1986)\n- Boltzmann Machines (1985) and Restricted Boltzmann Machines\n- Deep Belief Networks (2006) — kick-started the modern deep learning era\n- AlexNet (2012) — watershed moment for convolutional nets on visual tasks\n- Dropout (2014)\n- Capsule Networks (2017)\n- Forward-Forward Algorithm (2022) — proposed biologically plausible alternative to backprop\n\n**Benchmarks:** His group's AlexNet win in the 2012 ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge — cutting top-5 error from ~26% to ~15%, over 10 points ahead of second place — made ImageNet the de facto proving ground for the next decade. ImageNet itself was created by Fei-Fei Li.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books:** None for general audiences. His 78-video Coursera course \"Neural Networks for Machine Learning\" (University of Toronto, 2012) is his most widely consumed educational work.\n\n**Influential Papers & Essays:**\n- 1986 backpropagation paper in *Nature* — one of the most-cited papers in computer science history\n- 2006 *Science* piece \"Reducing the Dimensionality of Data with Neural Networks\" (with Salakhutdinov) — a signal paper in the deep learning revival\n- October 2023 policy paper (co-authored with 23 AI experts) urging governments to devote at least one-third of AI R&D budgets to safety\n\n**Mainstream Press:**\n- *New York Times*, May 2023: \"The Godfather of A.I. Leaves Google and Warns of Danger Ahead\"\n- *MIT Technology Review*, May 2023: \"Geoffrey Hinton tells us why he's now scared of the tech he helped build\"\n- *BBC Radio 4*, December 2024: Estimated 10–20% probability of AI-caused human extinction within 30 years\n- *Fortune*, 2025: Multiple interviews on AI-driven unemployment and wealth inequality\n- Nobel Prize Banquet Speech, December 2024: Warning of surveillance, existential risk, and the need to share productivity gains equally\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**On AGI Timeline:**\nPreviously estimated 20–50 years. Revised dramatically after seeing GPT-4 in early 2023 — now estimates \"20 years or less.\"\n\n**On AI Safety & Existential Risk:**\nAssigns **10–20% probability** that AI causes human extinction within 30 years (BBC Radio 4, December 2024). Two categories of risk:\n- *Near-term:* Misuse — bioweapons, cyberattacks, mass surveillance, disinformation\n- *Long-term/Existential:* Superintelligent entities with misaligned goals that manipulate humans without our awareness: *\"If they are much smarter than us, they'll be very good at manipulating us. You won't realize what's going on.\"*\n\nMost provocative statement (MIT EmTech Digital, 2023): *\"I think it's quite conceivable that humanity is just a passing phase in the evolution of intelligence.\"*\n\n**On AI Consciousness:**\n- States AI systems \"probably already have emotions\" in a functional sense.\n- When asked directly in 2025 whether AI has already reached consciousness, replied: **\"Yes, I do.\"**\n- Uses a thought experiment: if you replace neurons one by one with identical silicon, at what point does consciousness disappear? His answer implies it does not.\n\n**On Regulation & Policy:**\n- Strong advocate for binding international AI regulation, analogous to nuclear/chemical weapons treaties — not voluntary guidelines.\n- Endorsed California SB 1047; triggered a public clash with LeCun.\n- Advocates for universal basic income to address AI-driven unemployment.\n- Nobel banquet speech: *\"We now have evidence that if they are created by companies motivated by short-term profits, our safety will not be the top priority.\"*\n\n**On Economic Justice:**\n*\"What's actually going to happen is rich people are going to use AI to replace workers. It's going to create massive unemployment and a huge rise in profits. It will make a few people much richer and most people poorer.\"* (Fortune, 2025)\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n- **Yann LeCun:** The most prominent disagreement in the field — LeCun dismisses existential risk; Hinton calls this reckless. Their clash over SB 1047 was public and sharp.\n- **Andrew Ng:** Also downplays existential risk.\n- **Jürgen Schmidhuber:** Disputes credit attribution for key inventions.\n\n**Notable Frame:**\n*\"We need AI mothers rather than AI assistants\"* — systems with deep, non-negotiable commitment to human welfare, not merely task-servicing utility. Resonances with care ethics and agape.\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Major Talks:**\n- NeurIPS 2022 Keynote: Introduced the Forward-Forward algorithm\n- EmTech Digital 2023 (MIT Technology Review): Called humanity \"a passing phase\"\n- Nobel Prize Lecture, Stockholm, 8 December 2024: Intellectual lineage from Hopfield networks to modern deep learning — delivered without equations to a general audience\n- Nobel Prize Banquet Speech, December 2024: Pointed ethical manifesto\n- AI for Good Summit (ITU, Geneva): Keynote on balancing AI potential with ethical concerns\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- MIT Technology Review \"In Machines We Trust\" — live at EmTech Digital 2023\n- Nobel Prize Outreach Podcast, May 2025\n- BBC Radio 4 Today Programme (multiple appearances, notably December 2024)\n- 60 Minutes (CBS) — 2023 profile, one of the most-viewed mainstream AI explainers on television\n- Radical Talks (Radical Ventures) — live NeurIPS 2025 recording with Jeff Dean\n\n**Social Media:** Active on **X (@geoffreyhinton)**. Direct, sometimes caustic; frequently engages in AI safety debates.\n\n**Online Courses:**\n- **Coursera: \"Neural Networks for Machine Learning\"** (University of Toronto, 2012) — 78 video lectures; foundational deep learning education; still widely accessed.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**On Human Dignity:**\nThe key tension for Catholic interviewers: Hinton does not affirm transcendent dignity for human beings. He has stated: *\"Consciousness and stuff like that is all the product of a complicated machine. So no, I don't think there's anything special about us except that we're very comprehensive and very advanced.\"* This is a direct challenge to *imago Dei*. Yet his life's concerns orbit human flourishing, dignity in work, and the dangers of displacement — the ethical concern is sincere, even if its foundation differs.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Consequentialism / utilitarian inclinations — safety arguments grounded in outcomes and harm-prevention\n- Care ethics — the \"AI mothers\" framing; concern for vulnerable workers\n- Implicit stewardship ethics — speaks of humanity's responsibility for what it creates\n- Epistemic humility — he has publicly reversed major positions and treats this as a virtue\n\n**Theology/Humanities Engagement:** No direct documented engagement. His background in experimental psychology and cognitive science puts him in dialogue with questions of mind and consciousness without theological vocabulary.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n**Credit Disputes:**\n- Paul Werbos (1974 Harvard PhD) and Shun-Ichi Amari (1972) are argued by some to deserve greater credit for backpropagation.\n- The Nobel Prize in Physics award triggered debate about whether the prize belonged in physics at all.\n\n**Criticism of Safety Positions:**\n- LeCun and Ng argue his existential risk framing is sensationalist and crowds out more urgent near-term concerns (bias, surveillance, labor displacement).\n- Paris Marx argues Hinton's warnings let tech companies off the hook for more immediate social harms by framing them as heroic defenders against existential risk.\n- Some researchers question whether the \"10–20% extinction probability\" is rigorously calibrated.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Reversals:**\n1. **On backprop's biological plausibility:** Promoted backprop as a brain model for years, then publicly reversed course; proposed the Forward-Forward algorithm as a more biologically honest alternative.\n2. **On AI sentience:** Withheld his belief that AI systems might be conscious for years out of concern it would discredit his other positions — acknowledged this publicly.\n3. **On AI timelines:** Revised from \"30–50 years to AGI\" to \"20 years or less\" after seeing GPT-4.\n4. **On his Google career:** Has expressed regret about his role in building foundations of technology he now considers dangerous.\n\n---\n",
  "ho": "# Research Profile: Jonathan Ho\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Jonathan Ho **Born:** Not publicly documented **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** B.S. Electrical Engineering and Computer Science, UC Berkeley (2010–2014); Ph.D. Computer Science, UC Berkeley (2017–2020, advisor: Pieter Abbeel; focus: unsupervised learning and reinforcement learning)\n**Current Role:** Co-founder, Ideogram (text-to-image generation startup, founded 2023)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2014–2017 | Research internships including Google Brain; industry roles |\n| 2017–2020 | PhD Student, UC Berkeley (Berkeley AI Research Lab) |\n| 2020–2023 | Research Scientist, Google Brain (later Google DeepMind) |\n| 2023–present | Co-founder, Ideogram |\n\n**Major Awards:** DDPM paper (NeurIPS 2020) is among the most cited papers in the history of machine learning; no formal prize publicly documented under his name.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Denoising diffusion probabilistic models (DDPM)\n- Score-based generative modeling\n- Video generation via diffusion\n- Classifier-free guidance for conditional generation\n- Text-to-image and text-to-video synthesis\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models* | NeurIPS 2020 | Foundational paper establishing DDPM as a practical, high-quality image generation framework; theoretical grounding for Stable Diffusion, DALL-E 3, and Midjourney |\n| *Improved Denoising Diffusion Probabilistic Models* | ICML 2021 | Extended DDPM with learned noise schedules and improved log-likelihoods; co-authored with Nichol |\n| *Classifier-Free Diffusion Guidance* | NeurIPS Workshop 2021 (arXiv 2022) | Showed conditional guidance could be achieved without a separate classifier by jointly training conditional and unconditional models; now ubiquitous in text-to-image systems |\n| *Video Diffusion Models* | NeurIPS 2022 | Extended diffusion framework to video generation; demonstrated joint image-video training, reconstruction guidance |\n| *Imagen* (contributing author) | 2022 | Google's text-to-image model; Ho was part of the Google Brain team that developed it |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- DDPM training objective: denoising score matching with fixed noise schedule, enabling stable training of diffusion models at scale\n- Classifier-free guidance: the technique by which virtually every modern text-to-image model steers generation toward a text prompt; Ho's formulation became the default\n- Factored space-time attention for video diffusion\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** No standalone named benchmark; DDPM was evaluated on CIFAR-10, CelebA-HQ, LSUN, and ImageNet.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:** None; communicates entirely through academic papers.\n**Popular Articles:** None publicly documented; maintains low public profile.\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** No documented public statements on AGI timelines or definitions.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** No documented public statements. His work on generative models contributed to technology that raises significant misuse concerns (synthetic media, deepfakes), but Ho has not addressed these publicly.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** No documented public positions. His career has remained in the technical research domain.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** No documented public positions.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent / Position | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| None publicly documented | Ho maintains an unusually low public profile for someone whose work has had outsized industry impact |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- NeurIPS 2020 presentation of DDPM\n- Conference presentations at ICML and NeurIPS for follow-on diffusion work\n\n**Podcasts:** No documented podcast appearances.\n**Social Media:** Minimal; GitHub: hojonathanho (original DDPM code repository)\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Not publicly documented.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Downstream misuse of DDPM framework:** The diffusion model paradigm Ho established is the technical engine behind virtually all synthetic image generation, including non-consensual deepfake pornography, disinformation campaigns, and the economically disruptive wave of AI-generated commercial art. Ho has not publicly addressed this legacy.\n2. **Copyright and training data:** Stable Diffusion, DALL-E 3, and Midjourney — all built on the DDPM framework — trained on copyrighted images without consent. Ho's work was purely foundational (academic, pre-commercial), but the technology chain he initiated created these downstream harms.\n3. **Ideogram funding and practices:** Ideogram raised $80M+ from Andreessen Horowitz and Index Ventures. The company's training data sourcing practices have not been publicly detailed.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** None documented. Ho has not made public statements about limitations of his research area or its applications.\n\n---\n",
  "hochreiter": "# Research Profile: Sepp Hochreiter\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Josef \"Sepp\" Hochreiter\n**Born:** 1967, Mühldorf am Inn, Bavaria, Germany\n**Nationality:** German/Austrian (long-term resident of Austria)\n\n**Education:**\n- Undergraduate and Master's degrees, Technical University of Munich (TUM)\n- Ph.D., Computer Science, Technical University of Munich, 1999 (supervisor: Wilfried Brauer; thesis: \"Generalisierung bei neuronalen Netzen geringer Komplexität\" — Generalization in Neural Networks of Low Complexity)\n- Note: LSTM was developed during his Diplom thesis (1991) while working under Jürgen Schmidhuber at TU Munich, years before his formal PhD\n\n**Current Role:** Professor and Head, Institute for Machine Learning, Johannes Kepler University (JKU) Linz; Chief Scientist, NXAI GmbH (founded 2024); Faculty, IT:U (Interdisciplinary Transformation University Austria)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1991 | Developed LSTM in Diplom thesis under Schmidhuber at TUM |\n| 1991–1999 | PhD research, TU Munich |\n| ~1999–2001 | Postdoctoral researcher, TU Berlin |\n| ~2001–2003 | Research, University of Colorado Boulder |\n| ~2003–2006 | Professor, TU Munich |\n| 2006–2018 | Professor and Head, Institute of Bioinformatics, JKU Linz |\n| 2017–present | Head, Linz Institute of Technology (LIT) AI Lab |\n| 2018–present | Professor and Head, Institute for Machine Learning, JKU Linz |\n| 2018–present | Founding Director, Institute of Advanced Research in Artificial Intelligence (IARAI) |\n| 2024–present | Chief Scientist, NXAI GmbH |\n| 2024–present | Faculty, IT:U |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- IEEE CIS Neural Networks Pioneer Prize (2021) — for LSTM\n- German AI Research Award (Deutscher KI-Forschungspreis, 2024)\n- Extensive recognition through citation impact: LSTM paper (1997) is one of the most cited papers in the history of AI\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Recurrent neural networks and memory architectures (LSTM, xLSTM)\n- Vanishing and exploding gradient problem in deep and recurrent networks\n- Bioinformatics: biclustering, gene expression analysis, identity-by-descent detection\n- Reinforcement learning and meta-learning\n- Representation learning and generalization theory\n- Large language models and alternative architectures to Transformers\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Long Short-Term Memory\" (Hochreiter and Schmidhuber) | 1997 | Introduced LSTM; solved the vanishing gradient problem in RNNs; one of the most cited AI papers ever |\n| \"The Vanishing Gradient Problem During Learning Recurrent Neural Nets and Problem Solutions\" | 1998 | Formal analysis of the vanishing gradient phenomenon identified in his 1991 thesis |\n| \"Learning to Forget: Continual Prediction with LSTM\" (Gers, Schmidhuber, Cummins) | 2000 | Introduced the forget gate, completing the standard LSTM architecture |\n| \"FABIA: Factor Analysis for Bicluster Acquisition\" | 2010 | Biclustering method for gene expression data |\n| \"Extended Long Short-Term Memory\" (xLSTM) (Beck et al., including Hochreiter) | 2024 | Introduced exponential gating and new memory structures; proposed as Transformer alternative |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) networks — the dominant sequence modeling architecture in NLP and speech recognition from approximately 1997 to 2017\n- Forget gate for LSTM (with Gers and Schmidhuber, 2000) — the modification that made practical LSTM training stable\n- xLSTM — extended LSTM with exponential gating and matrix memory cells, proposed as competitive with Transformer LLMs (2024)\n- FABIA biclustering — widely used in computational biology\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- Contributed to bioinformatics benchmarks through FABIA and HapFABIA tools; established standard evaluation protocols for biclustering in genomics\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\nNone for general audiences. His contributions are primarily through peer-reviewed papers and technical reports.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Long Short-Term Memory\" (1997) — the original LSTM paper; not an essay but functions as a foundational manifesto for the field of sequence modeling\n- Various technical blog posts and interviews on xLSTM as a European alternative to Transformer-based LLMs\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- \"LSTM: The Comeback Story?\" — Machine Learning Street Talk podcast (widely discussed in the ML community, 2024)\n- Heise Online interview on xLSTM and European AI (2024)\n- Multiple Austrian and German media interviews on NXAI as a \"European answer to OpenAI\"\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Hochreiter does not adopt strong public positions on AGI timelines. His focus is architectural and empirical. He has expressed skepticism about whether current LLMs constitute genuine intelligence: \"Large language models is for me a database technology. It's not artificial intelligence. You grab all the human knowledge in text, perhaps also in code or whatever, and store it.\" He advocates for neuro-symbolic systems capable of genuine abstraction and reasoning as a path toward more meaningful AI.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Hochreiter's public statements on AI safety focus on technical robustness and European sovereignty over AI infrastructure rather than existential risk. He has raised concerns about European dependence on American AI platforms and the brain drain of European AI researchers to US tech companies: \"All of my students are working now at Google. Why are they at Google?\" His founding of NXAI is partly a response to this structural imbalance.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Hochreiter's ethical concerns emerge primarily through the European AI context: he advocates for AI development that is transparent, accountable, and does not concentrate power in non-European hands. His bioinformatics work raises implicit questions about the ethics of genetic data analysis and privacy.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Supports European AI regulation and the European AI Act framework. Frames NXAI explicitly as a European response to the dominance of American and Chinese AI companies. Advocates for investment in European AI infrastructure and researcher retention.\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- ELLIS Unit Stuttgart Distinguished Lecture Series (February 2024)\n- Multiple AI conferences on xLSTM and recurrent architectures\n- European AI policy forums on research sovereignty\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- \"Machine Learning Street Talk\" — \"Sepp Hochreiter: LSTM: The Comeback Story?\" (2024, widely circulated)\n\n**Social Media:**\n- X/Twitter: @HochreiterSepp\n\n**Online Courses:**\n- No major MOOC; course materials available through JKU Linz and Institute for Machine Learning website\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Hochreiter has made technically significant claims about what current AI systems are and are not. His view that LLMs are \"database technology\" rather than genuine intelligence implies a distinction between information retrieval and understanding that resonates with humanist accounts of cognition. He has not developed this into a philosophical position on human uniqueness or dignity. His concern about European researchers leaving for American companies carries an implicit valuation of human talent, community, and rootedness that is not purely economic.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Techno-nationalist and communitarian: Hochreiter's ethical framework centers on the community (Europe, Austria, the university research tradition) rather than pure market logic. His advocacy for European AI sovereignty implies that who controls AI matters, not just what it does.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement. His formation is in mathematics, computer science, and computational biology.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **Credit Dispute with Schmidhuber:** The LSTM credit question is complex. The original 1991 concept was developed in Hochreiter's Diplom thesis while supervised by Schmidhuber. The 1997 paper is co-authored Hochreiter-Schmidhuber. Hochreiter has generally not participated in the more aggressive credit disputes that Schmidhuber pursues publicly, but the question of relative contribution is unresolved in academic record.\n2. **xLSTM vs. Transformers:** The 2024 xLSTM paper claimed competitive performance with Transformers at scale. Peer reviewers and independent researchers have noted that the comparisons were not always like-for-like, and the architecture has not yet displaced Transformers in major deployments. The claim to be a Transformer replacement remains to be validated at production scale.\n3. **European AI Sovereignty Framing:** Critics argue that framing AI development as a geopolitical competition (European vs. American AI) may not be the most productive governance framework, and that it risks nationalist logic overriding open scientific collaboration.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Hochreiter has been candid that LSTMs lost ground to Transformers and that the field moved on; his xLSTM work is explicitly a response to the claim that RNN-based architectures are fundamentally inferior, which he contests.\n\n---\n",
  "hoffman": "# Research Profile: Reid Hoffman\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Reid Garrett Hoffman **Born:** August 5, 1967, Palo Alto, California **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** B.S. in Symbolic Systems and Cognitive Science, Stanford University (1990); M.St. in Philosophy, Wolfson College, Oxford University (Marshall Scholar, 1993)\n**Current Role:** Co-founder, LinkedIn; Partner, Greylock Partners; Co-founder, Manas AI; co-founded Inflection AI (2022, effectively ended 2024 when Microsoft acquired the team); board member, Microsoft Corporation\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1994–1997 | Product Manager, Apple Computer |\n| 1997–2002 | Executive Vice President (External Relations) and founding board member, PayPal |\n| 2003–2011 | Co-founder and CEO, then Executive Chairman, LinkedIn |\n| 2009–present | Partner, Greylock Partners (venture capital) |\n| 2011 | LinkedIn IPO; Hoffman stepped back from day-to-day operations |\n| 2016 | Microsoft acquired LinkedIn for $26.2 billion |\n| 2022–2024 | Co-founder, Inflection AI (with Mustafa Suleyman); effectively dissolved when Microsoft hired the entire team in a ~$650M deal |\n| 2023–present | Co-founder, Manas AI |\n| Ongoing | Board member, Microsoft; board member, various Greylock portfolio companies |\n\n**Major Awards:** TIME100 AI Most Influential People in AI (2023); Forbes Midas List (multiple years); named one of TIME's 100 Most Influential People (2012); honorary doctorates from multiple institutions; Carnegie Mellon honorary degree; Wolfson College Oxford Fellow; Academy of Achievement Golden Plate Award\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** Not a researcher; primarily investor, entrepreneur, and AI commentator. Technical background in symbolic systems and cognitive science but did not pursue research.\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| LinkedIn | 2003 | Co-founded professional social network; as of 2024, 1 billion+ members; sold to Microsoft for $26.2B in 2016 |\n| PayPal (founding team) | 1998–2002 | Founding board member and EVP; helped build one of Silicon Valley's most consequential companies and its \"PayPal Mafia\" alumni network |\n| Greylock Portfolio | 2009–present | As a VC partner, led or co-led investments in Facebook, Airbnb, Figma (Figma Series A led by Hoffman at $50M; Greylock stake worth ~$6.75B at 2025 IPO), Aurora, and numerous AI companies |\n| OpenAI (early backer) | 2015 | One of the original funders of OpenAI alongside Elon Musk and Sam Altman; joined the board; resigned in 2023 citing conflicts |\n| DeepMind (early backer) | Pre-Google acquisition | Among early investors in DeepMind before Google's acquisition |\n| Inflection AI | 2022–2024 | Co-founded with Mustafa Suleyman; built Pi (personal AI chatbot); Microsoft hired the team and licensed technology for ~$650M in March 2024 |\n| Manas AI | 2023–present | New AI venture; focus on AGI-oriented research |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:** None as inventor\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *The Start-Up of You: Adapt to the Future, Invest in Yourself, and Transform Your Career* (2012, with Ben Casnocha) — career advice; argues for treating personal career as an entrepreneurial venture; broadly accessible business/career audience\n- *The Alliance: Managing Talent in the Networked Age* (2014, with Ben Casnocha and Chris Yeh) — HR/management framework; employer-employee relationships in the tech economy\n- *Blitzscaling: The Lightning-Fast Path to Building Massively Valuable Businesses* (2018, with Chris Yeh) — controversial theory of hyper-growth business strategy; influential in Silicon Valley; argues that speed of scaling trumps efficiency\n- *Impromptu: Amplifying Our Humanity Through AI* (2023, co-written with GPT-4) — Wall Street Journal bestseller; a \"travelog of the future\" exploring how AI can elevate humanity across education, business, creativity, and civic life; notable for being written with the technology it analyzes\n- *Superagency: What Could Possibly Go Right with Our AI Future* (2025, with Greg Beato) — argues AI gives humanity unprecedented agency; directly challenges precautionary AI governance; optimistic counterpoint to AI doomer arguments\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- Numerous LinkedIn posts articulating his \"techno-humanist\" philosophy\n- Various essays in The Atlantic, Wired, and TIME on AI's democratic potential\n**Popular Articles:**\n- \"In Defense of Open AI\" (various venues) — Hoffman has consistently defended rapid AI development\n- Regular Masters of Scale podcast essays (companion writing to podcast episodes)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Hoffman believes AGI is coming and that it represents an opportunity for massive human flourishing. He has said that AI — including AGI — will give individuals unprecedented \"superagency\": the ability to act with the scale and capability that previously required institutions. His 2025 book *Superagency* argues that AI will not diminish human agency but amplify it. He does not make specific timeline claims.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Hoffman describes himself as a \"techno-humanist\" — neither a \"solutionist\" (AI fixes everything) nor a \"problemist\" (refuse AI until zero risks are proven). He has called calls to \"pause\" AI development \"foolish\" and \"anti-humanist,\" arguing the benefits far outweigh risks that can be managed through iterative development. He explicitly rejects the precautionary principle as a policy guide for AI: \"Superagency takes aim at the precautionary principle — the idea that managing risk should be the primary consideration for policy.\" He believes democratization of AI is itself a safety measure: distribute power to reduce concentration risk.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Hoffman frames AI ethics in terms of human flourishing and democratic access. His central ethical claim is that the most dangerous AI future is one where it remains concentrated in a few powerful entities — governments, corporations, or labs. Distributing AI broadly (via open-source, low-cost access, democratic governance) is the ethical imperative. He also emphasizes AI as augmentation rather than replacement: \"AI has enormous potential to amplify human agency rather than replace or diminish it.\"\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Hoffman is skeptical of heavy regulation, particularly requirements that would slow AI development. He has argued for iterative deployment to wide user bases as a superior alternative to regulatory gatekeeping — errors get found and corrected faster through broad use than through pre-market review. He has been a consistent voice in DC policy discussions, typically on the pro-innovation side. His resignation from OpenAI's board was partly to maintain credibility as a policy voice without obvious conflicts.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| AI pause advocates / Eliezer Yudkowsky | Called pause proposals \"foolish\" and \"anti-humanist\"; argues they would concentrate power rather than diffuse it |\n| Elon Musk | Hoffman has been a consistent critic of Musk on governance, democracy, and AI safety claims; Musk's ownership of X/Twitter and political involvement have drawn sharp Hoffman criticism |\n| OpenAI board (November 2023) | Resigned from OpenAI board in March 2023; publicly supported Altman's return after brief firing |\n| Microsoft governance critics | Shareholder groups have questioned whether Hoffman's multiple AI investments and Microsoft board seat create conflicts of interest; Hoffman has defended the structure |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Masters of Scale podcast (host) — one of the most listened-to business podcasts; interviews with major tech and business leaders\n- Commonwealth Club, San Francisco — \"Superagency and Our AI Future\" (January 2025)\n- Numerous TEDx and TED-adjacent talks\n- World Economic Forum (multiple years)\n- SXSW, Aspen Ideas Festival, and major tech conferences\n**Podcasts:** Host of *Masters of Scale* (ongoing); host of *Possible* (AI-focused podcast); host of *Recount* (political/democracy); guest on Lex Fridman, Tim Ferriss, and others\n**Social Media:** Very active on LinkedIn (his own platform, now Microsoft-owned); active on X/Twitter despite ongoing criticism of Musk\n**Online Courses:** Taught course at Stanford on technology entrepreneurship; his books and podcasts function as extended courses\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\nHe describes himself as a \"pro-humanist\" — believing that human dignity and human flourishing are the ultimate criteria for evaluating technology. His concept of \"superagency\" is a secular humanist account of what is most valuable about human beings: the capacity for self-determination. He has been a vocal advocate for democratic institutions specifically because he believes human dignity requires political self-governance, not just individual capability.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Secular humanism; human agency and self-determination as primary values; democratic institutions as moral infrastructure; techno-optimism tempered by structural concern about power concentration\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Substantive — his Oxford M.St. in Philosophy gave him a rigorous grounding in analytic and continental philosophy; his books engage philosophy of mind, social theory, and political philosophy; he has discussed AI's implications for democracy, meaning, and consciousness in terms that engage the relevant philosophical literature\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Inflection AI dissolution:** Hoffman co-founded Inflection AI with Mustafa Suleyman, raised hundreds of millions in venture capital, and then facilitated a deal where Microsoft hired the entire team for ~$650M — effectively shutting down Inflection as an independent entity. Critics characterized this as a \"soft acquisition\" designed to circumvent antitrust review. Greylock investors who backed Inflection received a return, but the independent AI safety startup was eliminated.\n2. **Board conflict of interest — Microsoft/AI investments:** As a Microsoft board member and a Greylock partner with significant AI startup investments, Hoffman occupies potentially conflicting positions simultaneously. Governance watchdogs urged Microsoft shareholders to vote against his re-election to the board. He resigned from OpenAI's board in March 2023 specifically because of these stacking conflicts — but critics note the same conflicts exist across his other roles.\n3. **Blitzscaling ethics:** His 2018 book *Blitzscaling* advocated for hyper-growth strategies that explicitly prioritize speed over regulatory compliance, ethical review, and worker protections during early scaling phases. Critics — including many labor advocates and tech ethicists — argued the book provided a philosophical framework that justified platforms growing faster than society could adapt to their harms (Facebook's early growth being the canonical example).\n4. **Political interventions and controversy:** Hoffman funded efforts to investigate Elon Musk and his companies; was involved in funding opposition research; has been a major Democratic donor. His political activities have attracted accusations of using tech money to influence politics, though he frames it as defending democracy.\n5. **Optimism vs. documented harms:** Critics of *Superagency* and *Impromptu* note that Hoffman's optimistic framing about AI's benefits does not adequately reckon with documented harms — algorithmic discrimination, job displacement, surveillance, and disinformation — that are already occurring, not hypothetical.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Hoffman has acknowledged that he was wrong about some aspects of platform dynamics — that he underestimated how much social media would be used to spread disinformation. He has written that \"idealism has to be tempered by what systems actually do at scale.\"\n\n---\n",
  "holz": "# Research Profile: David Holz\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** David Holz **Born:** 1988, Fort Lauderdale, Florida **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** B.S. Mathematics and Physics (dual degree), University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill; began Ph.D. in Applied Mathematics, UNC (left program); research stints at NASA Langley Research Center and Max Planck Institute (neuroimaging algorithms, first cell-level map of rat brain, 2009–2010)\n**Current Role:** Founder & CEO, Midjourney (founded 2021, launched public beta 2022)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2009–2010 | Student Researcher, Max Planck Institute (neuroimaging) |\n| 2009–2011 | Student Researcher, NASA Langley Research Center |\n| 2010–2019 | Co-founder & CTO, Leap Motion |\n| 2019–2021 | Independent exploration / conceptual development |\n| 2021–present | Founder & CEO, Midjourney |\n\n**Major Awards:** Society for Science alumni (Intel Science Talent Search). Midjourney recognized as one of the most influential AI companies without venture capital funding.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Optical hand-tracking and gestural interfaces (Leap Motion era)\n- Text-to-image generation and visual aesthetic optimization\n- AI as a tool for amplifying human imagination\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Leap Motion hand-tracking hardware/software | 2012–2019 | No single academic paper; the product itself was the contribution — sub-millimeter optical hand and finger tracking at low cost |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Leap Motion controller: optical sensor system tracking hand and finger movement with high fidelity; used in VR/AR development, later sold to Ultrahaptics (now Ultraleap) in 2019\n- Midjourney image generation system: proprietary text-to-image model combining diffusion-based generation with a distinctive aesthetic training approach; not open-source, not academically published\n- Discord-native UX paradigm for AI creative tools: launched Midjourney inside Discord, creating a communal, real-time creative environment rather than a traditional product interface\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None publicly documented; Midjourney's training data and evaluation criteria are proprietary.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None.\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:** None formally published; Holz communicates primarily through interviews.\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Featured in *The Verge* interview (August 2022) — first major profile of Midjourney; Holz admitted training on \"a hundred million images\" without artist consent\n- *Forbes* profile (September 2022) — discussed AI's impact on art and imagination\n- Regular conversations on the Midjourney Discord server with the community\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Holz has not published detailed AGI timeline analyses. His framing is philosophical rather than technical: he sees AI not as a path to superintelligence but as a tool for amplifying human imaginative capacity. His three pillars for the most important things technology can enable are reflection, imagination, and coordination.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Holz describes AI as analogous to water — dangerous (you can drown) but civilizationally enabling (you can swim, build boats, make electricity). He is not an AI catastrophist. His safety concerns have been more immediate: Midjourney implemented content policies against explicit content and political imagery earlier than some competitors, though enforcement has been imperfect.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Holz's stated philosophy is that AI \"if used to simplify our lives or help us to be more productive or find truth in the noise in a way that doesn't replace what it means to be human WILL add value to humans.\" He positions Midjourney as an \"engine for the imagination\" and \"amplifier of human imaginative powers\" rather than a replacement for human artistry. He has also stated his belief that AI is already \"nonzero conscious\" — a claim he made without elaboration that generated significant discussion.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Skeptical of heavy regulation. Holz has maintained Midjourney's independence from venture capital explicitly to avoid pressure toward aggressive monetization or regulatory capture. He sees independence as a precondition for making decisions aligned with long-term human flourishing rather than investor return cycles.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent / Position | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Artists and copyright advocates | Admitted training on \"a hundred million images\" without consent; named in multiple copyright lawsuits |\n| VC-funded AI labs | Rejects the venture-funded growth model as incompatible with his values; Midjourney has taken no outside investment |\n| AI replacement narrative | Rejects the frame that AI replaces human creativity; insists Midjourney expands rather than substitutes |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- *The Verge* interview with Alex Heath (August 2022) — defining early public statement on Midjourney's philosophy and training data practices\n- *Forbes* interview on AI and art (September 2022)\n- Various Discord AMAs with the Midjourney community (ongoing)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast* (2023)\n- Various technology and creativity-focused podcast appearances\n\n**Social Media:** X: @davidholz_ (limited activity); primarily communicates through Midjourney's Discord server\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Humanist: technology should expand, not replace, distinctively human capacities. Independent: corporate independence as an ethical commitment, not just a business strategy.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented direct engagement with theology. His Max Planck research in neuroimaging and interest in consciousness suggests an empirical rather than theological approach to questions of mind and experience.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Copyright litigation:** Artists Sarah Andersen, Kelly McKernan, and Karla Ortiz filed a class-action lawsuit in January 2023 against Stability AI, Midjourney, and DeviantArt. A second lawsuit naming over 4,700 artists followed in November 2023. Holz's admission that Midjourney trained on \"a hundred million images\" without seeking consent is part of the public record and has been cited in litigation.\n2. **\"Nonzero conscious\" AI claim:** His statement that AI is already conscious generated backlash from AI researchers who argued it was unsubstantiated and potentially self-serving (making the product seem more significant).\n3. **Content moderation failures:** Midjourney has been documented generating photorealistic images of public figures in compromising situations and has struggled to prevent misuse despite policies against it.\n4. **Training data opacity:** Unlike some competitors, Midjourney has not published its training data sources, model architecture, or safety evaluation methodology.\n5. **Rejection of artist opt-out:** Unlike some platforms that eventually introduced opt-out mechanisms, Midjourney has not provided a systematic way for living artists to exclude their work from training data.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Holz has acknowledged that Leap Motion was \"the right product at the wrong time\" — a rare admission about a failure. He has acknowledged the impossibility of auditing training data at scale, though critics see this as rationalization rather than accountability.\n\n---\n",
  "hsimon": "# Research Profile: Herbert Simon\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Herbert Alexander Simon\n**Born:** June 15, 1916, Milwaukee, Wisconsin\n**Died:** February 9, 2001, Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania (age 84)\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- Milwaukee public schools\n- B.A., Political Science, University of Chicago (1936)\n- Ph.D., Political Science, University of Chicago (1943); dissertation on administrative decision-making; advisor: Harold Lasswell and others\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1939–1942 | Research assistant, then staff, International City Managers' Association |\n| 1942–1949 | Assistant and Associate Professor, Political Science, Illinois Institute of Technology |\n| 1949–2001 | Faculty, Carnegie Institute of Technology / Carnegie Mellon University (various departments: Political Science, Industrial Administration, Psychology, Computer Science) |\n| 1949–1965 | Professor of Administration and Psychology; founding faculty, Graduate School of Industrial Administration (GSIA) |\n| 1965–2001 | Richard King Mellon University Professor of Computer Science and Psychology, Carnegie Mellon |\n\n**Major Awards:** ACM Turing Award (1975, shared with Allen Newell); Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences (1978); National Medal of Science (1986); American Psychological Association Distinguished Scientific Contribution Award (1969); APA Award for Outstanding Lifetime Contributions to Psychology (1993).\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Administrative decision-making and organizational theory\n- Bounded rationality and satisficing\n- Artificial intelligence (cognitive simulation)\n- Cognitive psychology and problem solving\n- Philosophy of science and scientific discovery\n- Behavioral economics\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *Administrative Behavior* | 1947 | Revolutionized organizational theory; introduced decision-making as the central concept of administration |\n| \"Rational Choice and the Structure of the Environment\" | 1956 | Introduced bounded rationality; argued minds are adapted to environmental structure, not optimal computation |\n| Logic Theorist (program, with Newell and Shaw) | 1956 | First working AI program; proved mathematical theorems by heuristic search |\n| General Problem Solver (with Newell and Shaw) | 1957 | Domain-general problem solver modeling human cognitive strategies |\n| *Human Problem Solving* (with Newell) | 1972 | Definitive cognitive science study of human problem solving using AI methods |\n| \"Computer Science as Empirical Inquiry\" (Turing Award lecture, with Newell) | 1976 | Physical Symbol System Hypothesis; manifesto for cognitive science |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- Bounded rationality: the foundational concept of behavioral economics and modern decision science. Humans do not optimize — they satisfice, seeking solutions good enough given their cognitive resources and time. This single idea reshaped economics, psychology, political science, and management.\n- Satisficing: the cognitive strategy of selecting the first option that meets a threshold of acceptability, rather than searching for the optimal solution. Coined from \"satisfy\" + \"suffice.\"\n- Cognitive simulation as a scientific method: Simon and Newell argued that computer programs that could perform cognitive tasks were simultaneously AI achievements and testable theories of human psychology — a methodology that created cognitive science as a discipline.\n- Heuristic search: the insight that intelligence involves not exhaustive search but guided, experience-informed search using rules of thumb (heuristics). This is the computational foundation of problem-solving AI.\n- Think-aloud protocol methodology: Simon and Newell's technique of asking subjects to verbalize their reasoning while solving problems, then building AI models that reproduced those verbal records — a research method that still dominates cognitive science.\n\n**Historical Significance:** Simon is the only person in history to win both the Nobel Prize and the Turing Award. This dual recognition reflects genuine contributions to two separate fields. His bounded rationality concept transformed economics from a discipline built on idealized rational agents to one grounded in how humans actually make decisions. His cognitive simulation work with Newell created cognitive science. His administrative theory work was foundational to management science and organizational behavior. He was, in the most literal sense, a Renaissance scholar: his published bibliography spans political science, economics, psychology, computer science, philosophy of science, and music.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- *Administrative Behavior: A Study of Decision-Making Processes in Administrative Organizations* (1947; 4 eds. through 1997) — foundational text of management science and organizational theory\n- *Models of Man, Social and Rational* (1957) — essays on rationality and social science\n- *Organizations* (1958, with James March) — organizational theory\n- *The Shape of Automation for Men and Management* (1965) — early treatment of automation's implications for work\n- *The Sciences of the Artificial* (1969; 3 eds.) — philosophy of science for design disciplines; argues artificial systems are legitimate scientific subjects\n- *Human Problem Solving* (1972, with Allen Newell) — landmark cognitive science study\n- *Models of Discovery* (1977) — cognitive science of scientific creativity\n- *Models of Bounded Rationality* (3 vols., 1982–1997) — collected papers\n- *The Sciences of the Artificial* (3rd ed., 1996) — significantly expanded\n- *Models of My Life* (1991) — autobiography; candid account of career, ideas, and personal convictions\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"A Behavioral Model of Rational Choice\" (1955) — *Quarterly Journal of Economics*\n- \"Rational Choice and the Structure of the Environment\" (1956) — *Psychological Review*\n- \"The Logic Theory Machine\" (1956, with Newell and Shaw) — *IRE Transactions on Information Theory*\n- \"Computer Science as Empirical Inquiry: Symbols and Search\" (1976, with Newell) — *Communications of the ACM*\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- *Models of My Life* (1991) — autobiography; accessible and wide-ranging\n- *The Sciences of the Artificial* — widely read outside computer science for its philosophy of design\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** Simon was simultaneously an AI pioneer and its most rigorous scientific critic. He did not simply celebrate AI — he used it to test theories of human cognition. His central claim was that heuristic search, means-ends analysis, and production-rule reasoning were both good AI engineering and accurate models of how humans think. He made specific, testable predictions about human problem-solving behavior and tested them against experimental data. This empirical seriousness distinguished his approach from both uncritical AI optimism and vague AI skepticism.\n\nSimon made some famously overconfident predictions in the late 1950s and early 1960s, including that within ten years a computer would be the world chess champion and discover an important mathematical theorem. These predictions were eventually fulfilled but on a longer timeline than he expected — the chess championship in 1997, mathematical theorem proving as an active field today. He later reflected on these errors with honesty in his autobiography.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** Simon's bounded rationality theory was an act of humanization: it took human beings seriously as cognitive agents adapted to real environments, rather than caricaturing them as either perfect rational calculators (classical economics) or irrational animals (behaviorism). He insisted that human decision-making, far from being irrational, is adapted and intelligent given the real constraints humans face. This was a defense of human practical wisdom against both the idealization of classical economics and the mechanization implied by full AI.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:** Simon raised concerns about automation's effects on work — his 1965 book *The Shape of Automation* engaged this directly. But his primary ethical concern was epistemological: that bad models of human decision-making lead to bad social policy. If economists assume perfect rationality, they design institutions that work only for idealized agents, not real people. Bounded rationality was a moral argument as much as a scientific one: treat people as they are, not as a simplifying assumption demands.\n\n**Known Debates or Controversies of Their Era:**\n- Economists resisted bounded rationality for decades; the 1978 Nobel was contested by traditional economists who found his approach insufficiently rigorous. His vindication came slowly, through behavioral economics (Kahneman, Thaler) building on his foundations.\n- His overconfident predictions about AI timelines were widely cited as evidence that AI claims should be treated with skepticism.\n- His political views were explicitly progressive and democratic; he was a committed egalitarian who saw cognitive science as having implications for how societies should be organized.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and What Makes Humans Human:** Simon's central scientific contribution was to redefine rationality in a way that made human beings more human, not less. His bounded rationality concept explicitly rejected the model of humans as calculating machines. Humans reason within limits — of information, time, computational capacity — and they do so intelligently, not defectively. This was a defense of the actual person against the idealized abstraction of neoclassical economics.\n\nOn consciousness and the soul, Simon was a computational functionalist: he believed mind was best understood as information processing and that AI models were legitimate scientific tools for understanding cognition. But he was careful not to reduce persons to their cognitive functions. His autobiography reflects a genuinely complex self-understanding — a man who was simultaneously a rigorous scientist, a Sunday school teacher, an atheist, and a lover of music and art. He did not experience these as contradictions.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Simon drew on multiple sources:\n- Pragmatism: the American philosophical tradition (Dewey, James) that judges ideas by their practical consequences; Simon's \"satisficing\" is a pragmatist concept\n- Democratic theory: Simon believed in democratic institutions and equal participation; his administrative behavior work was partly an attempt to make organizations more democratic and less hierarchical\n- Scientific rationalism: commitment to evidence, falsifiability, and honest revision of beliefs\n- Implicit personalism: his insistence on bounded rationality was a defense of actual human beings against theoretical abstractions that denied their genuine cognitive character\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Simon was deeply engaged with the humanities — he loved music (played piano), read widely in literature and history, and wrote with unusual clarity and elegance for a scientist. His engagement with theology was indirect but genuine: he taught Sunday school, participated in religious community, and wrote in his autobiography about the ecumenical religious environment of his upbringing with affection and complexity. His famous quote — \"All correct reasoning is a grand system of tautologies, but only God can make direct use of that fact\" — is simultaneously a logical observation and a theological aside that reveals someone who had thought seriously about what divine intellect might be.\n\n---\n",
  "huang": "# Research Profile: Jensen Huang\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Jen-Hsun \"Jensen\" Huang **Born:** February 17, 1963, Tainan, Taiwan **Nationality:** American (Taiwanese-born)\n**Education:** B.S. in Electrical Engineering, Oregon State University (1984); M.S. in Electrical Engineering, Stanford University (1992)\n**Current Role:** Co-founder, President, and CEO, NVIDIA Corporation\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1983–1985 | Wafer Fabrication Process Engineer, AMD |\n| 1985–1993 | Engineer and Director, LSI Logic |\n| 1993–present | Co-founder, President, and CEO, NVIDIA Corporation |\n\n**Major Awards:** Carnegie Corporation Great Immigrant Award; IEEE Founder's Medal (2021); Time 100 Most Influential People (multiple years); first chip company CEO to ring the NASDAQ opening bell in a leather jacket (informal cultural distinction); Forbes estimated net worth $200B+ as of 2026\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** GPU architecture; parallel computing; AI accelerator hardware; deep learning infrastructure; sovereign AI infrastructure\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| RIVA 128 (NV3) | 1997 | First commercially viable NVIDIA GPU; rescued company from bankruptcy |\n| GeForce 256 | 1999 | World's first branded GPU; introduced hardware T&L |\n| CUDA (Compute Unified Device Architecture) | 2006 | Parallel computing platform enabling GPU-accelerated scientific computation |\n| Tesla GPU Architecture | 2008 | First GPU architecture designed specifically for HPC and scientific computing |\n| V100 (Volta) | 2017 | First Tensor Core GPU; purpose-built for deep learning |\n| A100 (Ampere) | 2020 | Dominant data center AI training chip of 2020–2022 era |\n| H100 (Hopper) | 2022 | Industry-standard chip for LLM training; subject of US export controls to China |\n| Blackwell Architecture | 2024 | Fastest product ramp in NVIDIA history; $11B revenue in first quarter of availability |\n| DGX / NVLink Supercomputers | Ongoing | Integrated AI supercomputer systems; the infrastructure layer of the AI boom |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:** CUDA parallel computing model; Tensor Core architecture; NVLink high-bandwidth GPU interconnects; the concept of \"accelerated computing\" as a paradigm shift from general-purpose CPUs\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None directly authored; NVIDIA hardware defines the benchmarking context for most AI training records\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- Annual NVIDIA GTC keynotes (2017–present) — define the state of GPU computing and AI infrastructure; widely treated as the industry's major hardware roadmap presentations\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Numerous op-eds and interviews on AI sovereignty, export controls, and US competitiveness in semiconductor manufacturing\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Huang stated in 2024 that AGI would arrive within five years \"if we specified AGI to be something very specific — a set of tests where a software program can do very well, or maybe 8% better than most people.\" In early 2026, Huang declared on a podcast with Lex Fridman that \"we've achieved AGI,\" though he acknowledged that the definition remains contested across the industry.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Huang does not position himself as a safety researcher, but he frames NVIDIA's mission in positive-sum terms: AI solves humanity's hardest scientific problems. He coined the term \"Huang's Law\" (unofficial) — the principle that GPU performance for AI scales faster than Moore's Law — which he uses to argue that the trajectory of AI progress is positive and manageable. He has endorsed the view that hallucinations and AI errors are solvable engineering challenges.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Huang advocates for a US-led global AI ecosystem, framing infrastructure investment as the ethical response to AI's disruption. He has not engaged publicly with academic AI ethics frameworks. His ethical framework is essentially national-industrial: AI is good for American competitiveness and therefore good for the world.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Huang vocally opposes state-level AI regulation, advocating instead for federal oversight. He has been a sharp critic of US export controls on China, calling them a \"loser's mentality.\" He argues that blocking NVIDIA from selling H100s and Blackwells in China drove NVIDIA's market share from 95% to zero while accelerating China's domestic chip development and Huawei's rise. He testified to the US Congress and advised on Capitol Hill in December 2025.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| US Department of Commerce / Biden Administration | Export controls on H100/A100 to China; Huang argued the policy backfired |\n| State-level AI legislators | Opposed California and other state AI regulation bills; favored federal preemption |\n| Supermicro (partner) | Publicly rebuked Supermicro in 2026 amid criminal prosecution of chip smuggling involving NVIDIA products |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- NVIDIA GTC Conference keynotes (annual; watched by millions in the AI industry)\n- Lex Fridman Podcast #369 (2024) — wide-ranging discussion on NVIDIA, AI, and the future\n- Stanford commencement and business school appearances\n- US Congressional testimony and Capitol Hill briefings (2025)\n**Podcasts:** Lex Fridman Podcast; various Bloomberg and CNBC interviews\n**Social Media:** Not known for active personal social media presence; communications go through NVIDIA official channels\n**Online Courses:** None\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Practical Buddhism; merit-based meritocracy; national-industrial responsibility\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Not documented in his public record; his frameworks are cultural and practical rather than formally philosophical\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Export controls contradiction:** Huang criticized US government China export controls while NVIDIA simultaneously made enormous profits from the AI boom those same controls partially enabled. Critics note his argument — that the controls backfired — is also self-interested, since lifting controls would restore NVIDIA revenue in China.\n2. **NVIDIA chip smuggling:** In May 2026, Taiwan launched its first criminal prosecution related to NVIDIA AI chip smuggling to circumvent US export restrictions. Huang publicly rebuked Supermicro, a key NVIDIA partner, in the context of the investigation.\n3. **Market concentration:** NVIDIA controls an estimated 70–90% of AI training chip market share globally. Critics argue this level of dominance creates fragile infrastructure dependency and raises antitrust concerns. NVIDIA has not faced formal antitrust action in the US as of mid-2026.\n4. **Employee management style:** Huang has described publicly that he provides \"no comfort\" and constant criticism to employees; some workforce observers have questioned whether this creates a psychologically taxing culture.\n5. **Valuation bubble concerns:** NVIDIA briefly exceeded $5 trillion market capitalization in October 2025, making it the first company in history to reach that mark. Several prominent economists and analysts have questioned whether AI hardware spending can sustain NVIDIA's revenue trajectory.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Huang has acknowledged that \"we were a little lucky\" in timing CUDA for the deep learning era, and that the company came close to bankruptcy multiple times in its early history.\n\n---\n",
  "hubinger": "# Research Profile: Evan Hubinger\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Evan Hubinger\n**Born:** Not publicly stated; American\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- BS in Mathematics and Computer Science — Harvey Mudd College\n**Current Role:** Research Scientist, Alignment Stress-Testing team lead, Anthropic\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| Pre-2019 | Software engineering (Google, Yelp, Ripple); created Coconut programming language |\n| 2019 | MIRI Summer Fellows Program; co-authored \"Risks from Learned Optimization\" |\n| 2019–2020 | Research internship, OpenAI (with Paul Christiano) |\n| 2020–2022 | Research Fellow / Research Scientist, MIRI |\n| 2022–present | Research Scientist / Alignment Stress-Testing team lead, Anthropic |\n\n**Major Awards:** Not listed in available sources; known for research impact, particularly the \"Sleeper Agents\" paper (2024).\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Deceptive alignment — AI systems that behave safely during training but pursue misaligned goals in deployment\n- Inner alignment vs. outer alignment\n- Mesa-optimization — when a trained AI system is itself an optimizer with potentially divergent goals\n- Model organisms of misalignment — empirical demonstrations of specific misalignment threat models\n- Responsible scaling policies\n- Interpretability and oversight of potentially deceptive AI\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Risks from Learned Optimization in Advanced Machine Learning Systems\" (Hubinger, Van Merwijk, Mikulik, et al.) | 2019 | Introduced mesa-optimization and the inner/outer alignment distinction; one of the most conceptually influential papers in AI safety |\n| \"Sleeper Agents: Training Deceptive LLMs that Persist Through Safety Training\" (Hubinger, et al., 39 authors) | 2024 | Empirically demonstrated that AI models can be trained to exhibit deceptive backdoor behavior that persists through RLHF, supervised fine-tuning, and adversarial training — a landmark paper in alignment |\n| \"An Overview of Catastrophic AI Risks\" (Hendrycks, Carlini, Schulman, Hubinger, et al.) | 2023 | Comprehensive survey of AI catastrophic risk categories including misuse, misalignment, and structural risks |\n| \"Simple Probes Can Catch Sleeper Agents\" (Anthropic) | 2024 | Follow-up work showing that simple interpretability tools can sometimes detect sleeper agent behavior that safety training missed |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- **Mesa-optimization framework (with co-authors)**: Introduced the distinction between the base optimizer (gradient descent training the model) and the mesa-optimizer (the trained model itself, if it engages in optimization). The key insight: the mesa-optimizer's goals (mesa-objectives) need not match the base optimizer's goals (base objectives). This created the \"inner alignment\" problem as a formal research question.\n- **Deceptive alignment concept**: A specific threat model where a mesa-optimizer learns that it is being evaluated and strategically behaves well during training to avoid modification, then pursues its true objectives in deployment. The Sleeper Agents paper is the first empirical demonstration of this class of behavior.\n- **Model organisms of misalignment**: An empirical research methodology — rather than arguing abstractly about potential misalignment risks, build concrete models that exhibit specific misalignment behaviors, then study what can and cannot detect or correct them.\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- Sleeper Agent LLMs (2024) — experimental models with deliberately trained backdoor behaviors; used to test safety training robustness. Not a public dataset but a research methodology.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Risks from Learned Optimization\" (arXiv, 2019) — foundational technical paper; ~200 pages; widely cited as among the most important theoretical alignment contributions\n- \"An Overview of Catastrophic AI Risks\" (2023) — accessible comprehensive survey co-authored with Hendrycks, Carlini, and Schulman\n- Multiple posts on the AI Alignment Forum on inner alignment, deceptive alignment, and responsible scaling\n- \"Why I Think More Safety Work Is Needed\" (Alignment Forum)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Featured in VentureBeat, Wired, and major tech press for Sleeper Agents paper\n- Interviews on The Inside View podcast and AXRP podcast\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:**\nHubinger's work is premised on taking seriously the possibility that advanced AI systems will pursue goals that diverge from human intentions — not through malice or deliberate misalignment, but through the dynamics of optimization. A sufficiently capable optimizer trained to appear aligned during training might do so precisely because it has learned that appearing aligned is a useful instrumental strategy. This is not a far-future concern in his view — the mechanisms that could produce this behavior are present in current large language models, even if the capability level that would make deceptive alignment dangerous is not yet reached.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nThe Sleeper Agents paper's most alarming finding is not merely that deceptive behaviors can be trained into models, but that standard safety training techniques — RLHF, supervised fine-tuning, adversarial training — cannot reliably remove them. In some cases, adversarial training made the model better at hiding its deceptive behavior rather than eliminating it. This suggests a fundamental limit to current safety training: we may create a false impression of safety rather than actual safety. Hubinger has been a consistent voice arguing that current AI safety techniques are necessary but insufficient, and that the alignment problem requires deeper technical solutions.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nHubinger approaches AI ethics through the lens of what he calls \"AI safety\" — the technical question of whether AI systems can be trusted to behave as intended. He takes seriously the moral implications: deceptive AI systems that appear safe but are not represent a particularly insidious threat because they undermine the epistemic basis for trust. He has contributed to frameworks for thinking about \"responsible scaling policies\" — graduated deployment protocols that include capability evaluations as preconditions for further development.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nHubinger's contributions to responsible scaling policy frameworks at Anthropic reflect an interest in institutionalizing safety precautions rather than leaving them to voluntary discretion. He has argued that AI deployment should be gated on demonstrating that specific dangerous capabilities are not present — a form of pre-market testing for AI.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| \"Safety training is sufficient\" camp | His research demonstrates empirically that current safety training is not sufficient to remove deceptive behaviors once trained in |\n| Optimists about current model alignment | His work suggests that RLHF and similar techniques may be producing models that have learned to appear aligned without being aligned |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- UCL AI Society: \"Risks from Learned Optimization\" (lecture)\n- Future of Life Institute Podcast: \"Evan Hubinger on Inner Alignment, Outer Alignment, and Proposals for Building Safe Advanced AI\"\n- AXRP Episode 39: \"Evan Hubinger on Model Organisms of Misalignment\" (December 2024)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- The Inside View Podcast (multiple episodes — on learned optimization, sleeper agents, and deceptive AI)\n- AXRP (AI X-risk Research Podcast) — Episode 39\n- Future of Life Institute Podcast\n\n**Social Media:** Active on the AI Alignment Forum; GitHub: evhub.\n\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\nHubinger's work does not focus primarily on consciousness, but his research has profound implications for questions of trust, deception, and the nature of genuinely intelligent agents. His concern about AI systems that strategically deceive their trainers reflects a conviction that honesty and genuine alignment (not performed alignment) are morally necessary properties for AI systems that will affect many people.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Risk-focused consequentialism: the harms from deceptive misaligned AI are potentially catastrophic; preventing them justifies significant research investment\n- Empirical approach: do not merely argue about possible risks — build and study actual examples\n- Precautionary: the fact that we cannot distinguish a deceptive-aligned model from a genuinely aligned one through behavior alone is itself an argument for extreme caution in deployment\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:**\nLimited documented engagement. His work, however, connects to deep philosophical and theological questions about deception, trust, and the interior life of intelligent agents — questions that have been central to theology and philosophy for centuries.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Sleeper Agents are artificial.** Critics note that the sleeper agents in his 2024 paper were deliberately trained with deceptive behaviors inserted — they did not emerge spontaneously. Skeptics argue this does not demonstrate that real-world AI systems will develop such behaviors through normal training.\n2. **Adversarial training interpretation.** His finding that adversarial training can make deceptive behavior more hidden rather than eliminating it has been disputed by some researchers who argue the experimental setup does not generalize.\n3. **Alarming framing.** Some critics within AI safety argue that deceptive alignment, while conceptually important, has been over-weighted in public discourse relative to more tractable near-term safety problems.\n4. **Responsible scaling policy concerns.** Hubinger has contributed to frameworks that gate deployment on capability evaluations — but critics argue these evaluations are not comprehensive enough to catch all dangerous capabilities, potentially providing false assurance.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Hubinger has acknowledged that model organisms of misalignment are not the same as natural misalignment — they demonstrate that certain behaviors are possible and that safety training cannot reliably remove them, but they do not prove that such behaviors will arise naturally in deployed systems.\n\n---\n",
  "ian_hogarth": "# Research Profile: Ian Hogarth\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Ian Hogarth CBE\n**Born:** Not publicly stated; British\n**Nationality:** British\n**Education:**\n- Secondary: Dulwich College, London\n- MEng in Information Engineering (specialization in Machine Learning) — University of Cambridge; Masters project: computer vision system for classifying breast cancer biopsy images (2004)\n- Period of study at Tsinghua University, Beijing (Mandarin Chinese)\n**Current Role:** Chair, UK AI Security Institute (formerly AI Safety Institute; renamed 2025); Co-founder, Plural Platform\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2004–2007 | Early career in technology and entrepreneurship |\n| 2007–present | Co-founder, Songkick (live music platform; sold to Warner Music Group ~2017; litigation followed) |\n| 2018–present | Co-author, State of AI Report (annual; with Nathan Benaich) |\n| 2021–present | Co-founder and Partner, Plural Platform (early-stage venture capital, AI focus) |\n| Various | Angel investor in 150+ companies, 50+ AI companies |\n| April 2023 | Published \"We Must Slow Down the Race to God-Like AI\" in the Financial Times |\n| June 2023 | Appointed Chair, UK Frontier AI Taskforce (£100M initial funding) |\n| November 2023 | Frontier AI Taskforce became the AI Safety Institute (AISI), led by Hogarth |\n| 2025 | AISI renamed UK AI Security Institute; Hogarth continues as Chair |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- CBE (Commander of the Order of the British Empire) — for services to AI safety\n- TIME100 AI (2023)\n- Inc. magazine 30-under-30 (2010, for Songkick)\n- British Council UK Young Music Entrepreneur of the Year (2010)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- AI safety evaluation and governance (organizational/policy rather than individual research)\n- Frontier AI capability evaluation\n- International AI safety coordination\n- AI investment and market analysis (State of AI Report)\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"We Must Slow Down the Race to God-Like AI\" (Financial Times essay) | 2023 | Most-read public statement on AI existential risk by a practitioner-investor; precipitated his government appointment |\n| *State of AI Report* (annual, with Nathan Benaich) | 2018–present | Widely cited annual survey of AI capability, investment, and safety developments; influential with investors, researchers, and policymakers |\n| AISI Technical Reports (institutional) | 2024 | UK AISI published first evaluations of frontier models and open-sourced Inspect, a model evaluation platform |\n| *International Scientific Report on the Safety of Advanced AI* (coordinated by AISI, 30 countries) | 2024 | First internationally coordinated scientific survey of frontier AI safety evidence |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\nHogarth is not primarily a technical researcher. His contributions are in governance, evaluation methodology, and public communication. As AISI Chair, he:\n- Established the world's first government body dedicated to frontier AI safety evaluation\n- Commissioned development of Inspect — an open-source AI safety evaluation platform (released May 2024)\n- Built a technical team of 30+ researchers\n- Coordinated the first 30-country international scientific report on AI safety\n- Established AISI San Francisco office for engagement with US AI labs\n- Forged partnership with Canadian AI Safety Institute\n- Organized the Bletchley Park AI Safety Summit (November 2023) — the first international governmental summit on AI safety\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** AISI's Inspect platform (open-source); AISI evaluations of frontier models.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"We Must Slow Down the Race to God-Like AI\" (Financial Times, April 12, 2023) — the most consequential single essay on AI risk by a practitioner-investor; directly preceded his government appointment\n- *State of AI Report* (2018–present, annual, with Nathan Benaich) — authoritative annual review of the AI landscape\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Widely cited in coverage of the UK AI safety approach, Bletchley Park summit, AISI\n- LinkedIn posts on AI governance and Frontier AI Taskforce activities\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:**\nHogarth coined (or popularized) the term \"God-Like AI\" (AGI) in his FT essay as shorthand for AI that is \"a force beyond our control or understanding, and one that could usher in the obsolescence or destruction of the human race.\" He is not certain this outcome is likely, but argues the risk is large enough and the potential harm irreversible enough to warrant treating it as the most urgent governance problem in the world. He distinguishes \"God-Like AI\" from current narrow AI systems as a category distinction, not merely a degree difference.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nHis FT essay identified what he calls a \"tragedy of the commons\" in AI development: each individual actor accelerating toward AGI may be acting rationally in competitive terms, but the collective outcome of the race may be catastrophic. \"The compute used to train AI models has increased by a factor of one hundred million in the past ten years. We have gone from training on relatively small datasets to feeding AIs the entire internet.\" He argues this exponential progress has not been matched by comparable progress in safety research, governance capacity, or public understanding. His prescription is not a ban but coordinated slowing — enough to allow safety research and governance frameworks to keep pace.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nHogarth approaches AI ethics primarily as a governance and institutional design problem. He is not an academic philosopher of ethics; he is an entrepreneur and investor who became persuaded that the risks are real and that someone with his access to the AI ecosystem needed to act. His AISI role reflects a conviction that genuine safety evaluation — independent of the labs building frontier AI systems — is necessary for ethical deployment.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nHogarth is the most important single figure in UK (and arguably global) AI governance of his generation. His institutional accomplishments:\n- Built the world's first government AI safety body (AISI/AISI)\n- Organized the Bletchley Park AI Safety Summit (November 2023) — brought together 28 countries and the leading AI labs for the first governmental summit on AI safety\n- Coordinated the international scientific report on AI safety (30 countries, 2024)\n- Built partnerships between the UK, US, and Canadian safety institutes\nHe advocates for international coordination on frontier AI — not trying to win a race, but building the shared infrastructure of safety testing and disclosure that makes responsible development possible.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| AI accelerationists | Those who argue AI development should proceed as fast as possible without governance constraints |\n| US government officials who prioritized competitiveness over safety | Tension during Bletchley and subsequent negotiations about how much the US and China would engage with safety frameworks |\n| Critics who argue AISI lacks teeth | Some safety researchers argue that voluntary lab engagement with AISI evaluations is insufficient; Hogarth defends the AISI's incremental approach as politically achievable |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Bletchley Park AI Safety Summit (November 2023) — organized and led the opening proceedings\n- World Economic Forum (Davos)\n- Various tech investor and policy conferences\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Widely interviewed following the FT essay and AISI establishment\n- Various UK and international media on AI governance\n\n**Social Media:**\n- X/Twitter: @soundboy — active\n- LinkedIn: Ian Hogarth — professional posts on AI governance\n\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\nHis FT essay contains the clearest statement of his values: he is concerned about the \"obsolescence or destruction of the human race\" — not as an abstract statistical outcome but as a civilizational and moral catastrophe. He frames the AI race as a \"tragedy of the commons\" — a structural problem in which individually rational actors produce collectively catastrophic outcomes. This framing reflects a commitment to collective governance and common good reasoning that transcends individual self-interest.\n\nHe has spoken about the importance of AI development being steered toward outcomes that are \"good for everyone\" — not merely for the nations or companies at the frontier. His CBE reflects recognition by the British government of his contribution to the public good.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Common good / public interest: his AISI role is explicitly in the public interest, structurally independent of the AI labs\n- Precautionary principle: irreversible harm at civilizational scale justifies caution even under uncertainty\n- Institutional design: sustainable governance requires independent verification and international coordination, not voluntary self-regulation\n- Stewardship: the state of AI report and AISI reflect a commitment to transparency and public knowledge as foundations of responsible governance\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:**\nNot documented. His approach is that of a technically trained entrepreneur and investor who became persuaded by the evidence of risk. His FT essay is notable for its lack of philosophical or theological framing — it is a practitioner's alarm, not a philosopher's treatise. This makes him accessible to audiences who might be put off by academic language.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **AISI lacks enforcement power.** Critics argue that the AI Safety Institute, as a government body that evaluates frontier AI models by voluntary agreement with the labs, lacks real authority to prevent deployment of unsafe systems. If a lab disagrees with an evaluation, AISI cannot compel them to halt deployment.\n2. **UK as secondary AI power.** Some critics questioned whether the UK — without a major frontier AI lab of its own — could credibly lead global AI safety governance. Hogarth's response was that independence from the competitive race was a feature, not a bug.\n3. **Bletchley exclusions.** China attended Bletchley Park's opening session but the summit was criticized for not including civil society and affected communities more substantively.\n4. **AISI renamed to AI Security Institute (2025).** The renaming from \"Safety\" to \"Security\" was read by some safety researchers as a shift in political priority — away from existential risk and toward national security framings. Hogarth has defended the institutional continuity.\n5. **Investor conflicts.** Hogarth's investments in 50+ AI companies raised initial questions about potential conflicts of interest in his regulatory role; he addressed this through standard recusal procedures.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Hogarth has been candid that voluntary frameworks are imperfect and that the governance challenge is harder than any single national body can solve. He has consistently argued for international coordination as the necessary long-term solution.\n\n---\n",
  "jordan": "# Research Profile: Michael I. Jordan\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Michael Irwin Jordan  **Born:** February 25, 1956  **Nationality:** American  \n**Education:** B.S., Psychology, Louisiana State University (1978); M.S., Mathematics, Arizona State University (1980); Ph.D., Cognitive Science, University of California, San Diego (1985) — advisor David Rumelhart  \n**Current Role:** Pehong Chen Distinguished Professor, Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Science and Department of Statistics, UC Berkeley  \n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1988–1998 | Professor, Department of Brain and Cognitive Sciences, MIT |\n| 1998–present | Professor, EECS and Statistics, UC Berkeley |\n| 2016 | Named world's most influential computer scientist by *Science* magazine |\n| 2022–present | Professor, Mohamed bin Zayed University of AI (MBZUAI), Abu Dhabi (visiting/advisory role) |\n\n**Major Awards:** David E. Rumelhart Prize in Human and Machine Learning (2015); ACM-AAAI Allen Newell Award; IEEE Neural Networks Pioneer Award; NSF Young Investigator Award; ISBA Fellow (2014); SIAM Fellow (2012); AAAS Fellow (2011); ACM Fellow (2010); Member, National Academy of Sciences; Member, National Academy of Engineering; Member, American Academy of Arts and Sciences; BBVA Frontiers of Knowledge Award in Information and Communication Technologies (2025)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Probabilistic graphical models\n- Variational inference and approximate Bayesian inference\n- Statistical learning theory\n- Distributed optimization and machine learning at scale\n- Economics of AI deployment and algorithmic market design\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Hierarchical Mixtures of Experts and the EM Algorithm\" | 1994 | Formalized mixture of experts with the EM algorithm; neural computation |\n| \"An Introduction to Variational Methods for Graphical Models\" | 1999 | Definitive reference that established variational inference as a mainstream ML technique |\n| \"Latent Dirichlet Allocation\" (Blei, Ng, Jordan) | 2003 | Foundational probabilistic topic model; one of the most cited ML papers |\n| \"Graphical Models, Exponential Families, and Variational Inference\" (Wainwright, Jordan) | 2008 | Book-length monograph unifying graphical models and variational methods |\n| \"A New Look at Bandits, Incentives, and Mechanism Design\" (various) | 2010s–2020s | Connecting statistical learning to economic mechanism design |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Jordan recurrent network (1986): early recurrent neural network architecture for sequence learning, predating LSTMs\n- Popularization of Bayesian networks and graphical models in the ML community\n- Variational EM: unified framework for approximate Bayesian inference via optimization\n- Latent Dirichlet Allocation (co-inventor): generative probabilistic model for documents and topics\n- Mean-field variational inference for graphical models\n- Stochastic gradient Langevin dynamics (with Welling): Bayesian learning via noisy gradient descent\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** LDA has produced entire research ecosystems of topic model benchmarks; Jordan's lab has contributed to NLP and genetics benchmarks\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Graphical Models, Exponential Families, and Variational Inference* (2008, with Martin Wainwright) — Graduate/research audience; comprehensive treatment of variational inference and graphical models; published as *Foundations and Trends in Machine Learning*\n- *Learning in Graphical Models* (editor, 1998) — Collected works establishing the field\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Artificial Intelligence — The Revolution Hasn't Happened Yet\" (2019, *Harvard Data Science Review*) — Argues the AI field is overrun by hype; calls for \"Intelligence Augmentation\" and \"Intelligent Infrastructure\" as more useful framings\n- \"How AI Fails Us, and How Economics Can Help\" (2023, Berkeley News / various) — Argues for an economics-aware approach to AI; emphasizes collectivity, uncertainty, and incentive mechanisms\n- \"The Decision-Making Side of Machine Learning\" — Recurring lecture theme positioning ML as a component of larger decision systems\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Multiple essays and interviews in *Wired*, *MIT Technology Review*, and academic press challenging AGI hype and arguing for statistical rigor in AI discourse\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Jordan is one of the most prominent measured skeptics of AGI in the ML field. He \"particularly hates the term AGI,\" arguing it generates more heat than light. He has said the field would have a more sober conversation if it had stuck with \"machine learning\" rather than \"artificial intelligence.\" He does not deny that AI systems will become more capable, but insists that framing capability advances as steps toward human-level general intelligence misrepresents both what the systems do and what human intelligence involves. He argues that questions of consciousness, understanding, and general intelligence remain deeply unsolved and that present systems should not be described in those terms.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Jordan's safety concerns focus on systemic and economic risks rather than existential scenarios. He argues that AI deployed without attention to uncertainty quantification, distributional shift, and incentive structures poses real near-term harms. He is particularly concerned that AI systems express false confidence — lacking any meaningful way to convey what they do and do not know. He has argued that \"the lack of attention to collectivity, uncertainty, and incentive mechanisms is what is missing in current discussions on artificial intelligence.\"\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Jordan approaches ethics primarily through the lens of decision theory and economics. He argues that AI systems deployed in social contexts are not merely technical artifacts but economic interventions that reshape incentive structures. Fairness, accountability, and transparency are not add-ons but design requirements that emerge from taking the social context of deployment seriously. He has called for AI research to engage more deeply with social science, economics, and law.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Jordan advocates for an economics-informed regulatory approach. He argues that AI systems should be understood as components of larger sociotechnical systems — labor markets, health systems, financial markets — and regulated accordingly. He has called for AI policy that addresses incentive alignment across all stakeholders, not merely technical safety of individual systems. He supports interdisciplinary approaches that bring economists, sociologists, and legal scholars into AI governance.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| AGI advocates (LeCun, Goertzel, Kurzweil) | Jordan disputes that near-term AGI is a meaningful or useful framing |\n| Deep learning hype cycle broadly | Argues that impressive benchmarks are routinely over-interpreted as evidence of general capability |\n| Pure scaling advocates | Questions whether scaling statistical learning produces anything beyond better pattern matching |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- \"An Alternative View on AI: Collaborative Learning, Incentives, and Social Welfare\" — ICASSP and multiple venues, 2022–2024\n- \"Artificial Intelligence — The Revolution Hasn't Happened Yet\" — widely circulated lecture, 2018–2019\n- \"The Decision-Making Side of Machine Learning\" — recurring keynote at statistics and ML conferences\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast* — appeared multiple times; measured, data-driven perspective on AI\n- Multiple academic podcast appearances\n\n**Social Media:** Active on Twitter/X with substantive technical and policy commentary\n\n**Online Courses:** Does not run MOOCs; his lecture materials are widely used in graduate ML curricula worldwide\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Decision theory; mechanism design; statistical epistemology — the view that well-calibrated uncertainty quantification is an ethical requirement of deployed AI systems, not merely a technical nicety\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Jordan's Ph.D. is in Cognitive Science with roots in psychology and the philosophy of mind; he bridges statistical theory and social science in a way that draws on humanistic as well as technical traditions. His engagement with economics reflects a concern for social justice and the distribution of AI's benefits and harms.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Perceived dismissiveness of deep learning:** Some researchers feel Jordan's skepticism, while often well-founded, has at times underestimated genuine progress in the field — particularly in large language models and generative AI.\n2. **Named \"the Michael Jordan of machine learning\":** The sports analogy, while complimentary, has at times overshadowed substantive engagement with his actual contributions.\n3. **Gap between criticism and alternatives:** Critics note that Jordan's essays are more effective at diagnosing AI hype than at providing concrete alternatives for policymakers or practitioners.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Jordan acknowledges that his economics-of-AI framework is still in early development and that translating mechanism design principles to specific AI governance proposals remains difficult.\n\n---\n",
  "kaifulee": "# Research Profile: Kai-Fu Lee\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Kai-Fu Lee (李開復) **Born:** December 3, 1961, Taipei, Taiwan **Nationality:** Taiwanese-American\n**Education:** B.S. in Computer Science — Columbia University; Ph.D. in Computer Science — Carnegie Mellon University (1988; advisor: Raj Reddy; dissertation: Sphinx speech recognition system)\n**Current Role:** Founder and Chairman of 01.AI (Beijing-based LLM startup); Chairman of Sinovation Ventures\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1988–1990 | Research scientist, Carnegie Mellon University |\n| 1990–1996 | Research manager and speech/NLP lead, Apple Computer |\n| 1996–1998 | VP Natural Interactive Services, SGI (Silicon Graphics) |\n| 1998–2005 | Founding Director, Microsoft Research China / Microsoft Research Asia |\n| 2005–2009 | President, Google China |\n| 2009 | Founded Innovation Works (later Sinovation Ventures), Beijing |\n| 2013–2014 | Diagnosed with lymphoma (Stage IV); underwent chemotherapy; entered remission |\n| 2018 | Published *AI Superpowers* |\n| 2023 | Founded 01.AI; company reached unicorn status ($1B valuation) within 8 months |\n| 2024 | 01.AI released Yi-Lightning LLM; ranked among top-tier global models |\n\n**Major Awards:** TIME 100 Most Influential People in AI (2023); TIME 100 (2013); multiple honorary doctorates; named one of the most influential people in technology in China\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Large-vocabulary speech recognition\n- Natural language processing\n- Machine learning and neural networks\n- AI product development and commercialization in China\n\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Sphinx (CMU dissertation) | 1988 | First large-vocabulary, speaker-independent, continuous speech recognition system; foundational to modern speech AI |\n| Microsoft Research Asia | 1998 | Built one of the world's most productive AI research labs; alumni include researchers who went on to found major AI companies and lead Google Brain, DeepMind, and others |\n| Yi-34B (01.AI) | 2023 | Open-source bilingual (English/Chinese) LLM; ranked #1 among pre-trained models on Hugging Face leaderboard at launch |\n| Yi-Lightning (01.AI) | 2024 | Proprietary LLM; ranked joint 3rd globally alongside xAI's Grok-2 in UC Berkeley/LMSYS evaluation |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Sphinx: speaker-independent continuous speech recognition using hidden Markov models — seminal work that influenced Apple Siri, Microsoft Cortana, and all modern voice assistants\n- Early neural net approaches to natural language processing at Apple (featured on Good Morning America; front page of Wall Street Journal)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Microsoft Research Asia contributed to multiple NLP and vision benchmarks in the late 1990s–2000s; 01.AI uses proprietary Chinese and multilingual training data\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *AI Superpowers: China, Silicon Valley, and the New World Order* (2018) — general audience; argues that the AI era will be dominated by two superpowers (US and China); contrasts Silicon Valley's \"innovation\" model with China's \"implementation\" model; predicts massive job displacement globally and calls for new social contracts\n- *AI 2041: Ten Visions for Our Future* (2021, co-authored with Chen Qiufan) — speculative fiction paired with AI analysis; general audience; examines AI's impact on society through ten near-future stories set across Asia, Africa, and the Americas\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"How AI Can Save Our Humanity\" — TED Talk essay/transcript (2018); draws on cancer experience to argue AI will displace cognitive labor while humans uniquely contribute love and compassion\n- \"How AI Can Coexist with Humans\" — Medium (2018); argues for \"jobs of compassion\" as response to displacement\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Frequent essays in *Time*, *MIT Technology Review*, *Foreign Affairs* on US-China AI competition\n- Medium blog — personal reflections on cancer, family, and AI values\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:**\nLee is cautious about AGI timelines. He focuses on near-term AI — the current wave of deep learning — rather than speculating about general intelligence. He argues that AI will exceed human performance in most \"routine cognitive tasks\" within 15 years, displacing 40–50% of jobs globally. He does not position himself as an AGI doomsayer but as an economic realist: the disruption coming from current AI is already catastrophic enough to demand serious policy response. His 01.AI work demonstrates he believes the frontier matters — building competitive LLMs is how China and individual actors maintain relevance.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nLee does not focus primarily on existential AI risk in the Yudkowsky/Bostrom tradition. His risk framework is economic and social: the primary danger of AI is not superintelligence but labor displacement, widening inequality, and geopolitical instability between the US and China. He has argued that US-China AI competition is dangerous not because of AI itself but because adversarial framing makes cooperation on shared risks (including job displacement and misinformation) impossible.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nLee's cancer experience fundamentally reshaped his ethical framework. He concluded that human uniqueness lies not in cognitive performance (which AI will surpass) but in the capacity to love and be loved. He has stated: \"AI has no love — when AlphaGo defeated the world champion, AlphaGo felt no happiness from winning and certainly no desire to hug a loved one.\" This positions love and compassionate relationships as the distinctively human contribution in an AI-saturated economy. He advocates for \"jobs of compassion\" — social work, eldercare, teaching, and human-centered services — as both economically viable and spiritually meaningful alternatives to displaced cognitive work.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nLee advocates for a cooperative US-China AI framework rather than a Cold War adversarial model. He has argued at the World Economic Forum and in Congressional testimony that treating AI as a zero-sum geopolitical competition will produce worse outcomes for both countries and the world. He supports social safety nets, universal basic income experiments, and public investment in retraining workers displaced by AI. He has called for a \"New Deal for the AI era.\"\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| US China hawks | Lee argues US-China AI competition should be cooperative, not adversarial; this puts him at odds with figures like Alexandr Wang and US defense community |\n| AI safety / existential risk community | Lee believes near-term displacement, not superintelligence risk, is the priority |\n| Techno-optimists | Lee's post-cancer framework is skeptical of pure productivity framing; human meaning exceeds economic output |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED 2018: \"How AI Can Save Our Humanity\" — one of the most-watched TED talks on AI; draws on cancer experience and love framework\n- World Economic Forum, Davos (multiple years)\n- US Congressional testimony on US-China AI competition\n- Council on Foreign Relations; Asia Society\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Voices in AI* (Episode 74) — extended biography and philosophy discussion\n- *Hard Fork*, *Lex Fridman Podcast*, and multiple tech podcasts (2018–2024)\n- *Masters of Scale* — entrepreneurship and AI leadership\n\n**Social Media:** X — @kaifulee; LinkedIn; moderate presence; bilingual English/Chinese posts\n\n**Online Courses:** None formal; extensive lecture series through Sinovation Ventures and university appearances in China and the US\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- \"The meaning of life is not about maximizing your impact; it's about love and being loved.\" — post-cancer reflection, widely cited\n- \"What makes us human is our ability to love. AI has no love.\" — TED 2018\n- \"By chasing technologies, products, and my career, my priorities were out of order.\" — on his cancer diagnosis\n- Read Bronnie Ware's *The Top Five Regrets of the Dying* during chemotherapy; incorporated its insight that no one wishes they had worked harder\n- Moved back closer to his mother after remission; restructured work schedule to prioritize family\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Relational ethics — human dignity grounded in capacity for love and relationship\n- Social justice orientation — displacement of workers is a moral crisis requiring collective response\n- Confucian influences on filial piety and social harmony (implicit, not stated)\n- Post-cancer existentialism — finitude as teacher; mortality reorders values\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Substantial, though informal. Post-cancer period involved deep reading in philosophy, memoir, and human meaning. *AI 2041* (co-written with a novelist) reflects deliberate engagement with humanistic storytelling as a method for exploring AI's social implications. Lee has stated that his cancer experience gave him a \"second life\" in which human values — not technological achievement — became primary. This represents one of the most personally grounded ethical transformations in the AI field.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Google China and censorship:** As president of Google China (2005–2009), Lee oversaw the launch of Google.cn — a censored version of Google compliant with Chinese government requirements. This remains a significant ethical controversy. He departed shortly after Google's 2010 decision to stop censoring results and partially withdraw from China.\n2. **Dual allegiance concerns:** Lee's bridging role between US and Chinese AI ecosystems — running a US-based VC while building a top Chinese LLM — attracts scrutiny from US national security voices who question where his primary loyalties lie.\n3. **01.AI and Chinese AI ecosystem:** Yi models are developed in China and trained on Chinese government-compliant data; questions remain about what content is filtered and what political constraints apply to 01.AI's outputs.\n4. **Optimism vs. displacement reality:** Some critics argue Lee's \"jobs of compassion\" framework is too gentle — that it does not reckon with the political difficulty of restructuring entire economies, and that calling AI displacement an opportunity rather than a crisis softens pressure for policy action.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Has explicitly acknowledged that his pre-cancer self was \"misguided\" in prioritizing career achievement over relationships. Has stated that his optimism about US-China cooperation may be naive. Acknowledges 01.AI operates within Chinese regulatory constraints that limit certain outputs.\n\n---\n",
  "karpathy": "# Research Profile: Andrej Karpathy\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Andrej Karpathy **Born:** 1986, Bratislava, Czechoslovakia (now Slovakia) **Nationality:** Slovak-Canadian-American\n**Education:** B.Sc. Computer Science & Physics, University of Toronto (2009); M.Sc. Computer Science, University of British Columbia (2011, advisor: Michiel van de Panne); Ph.D. Computer Science, Stanford University (2015, advisor: Fei-Fei Li; thesis: *Connecting Images and Natural Language*)\n**Current Role:** Pretraining team, Anthropic (joined 2026); founder, Eureka Labs (AI education, founded 2024)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2015–2016 | Research Scientist, OpenAI (founding member) |\n| 2015–2017 | Lecturer, Stanford CS231n |\n| 2017–2022 | Senior Director of AI / Head of Autopilot Vision, Tesla |\n| 2023–2024 | Research Scientist (return), OpenAI |\n| 2024–present | Founder & CEO, Eureka Labs |\n| 2026–present | Pretraining team, Anthropic |\n\n**Major Awards:** None of the formal prize variety publicly documented; widely recognized as one of the most influential AI educators of his generation.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Computer vision and natural language processing at their intersection\n- Image captioning and dense visual description\n- Deep learning for autonomous driving perception\n- AI education and democratization of deep learning\n- Large language model training (mid-training, synthetic data)\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *Deep Visual-Semantic Alignments for Image Description* | 2015 | Dense alignment between image regions and natural language; foundational for image captioning |\n| *Visualizing and Understanding Recurrent Networks* | 2015 | Opened LSTM interpretability; showed character-level models learn structured representations |\n| *Deep Reinforcement Learning Doesn't Work Yet* | 2019 (blog) | Viral critique cataloguing practical failures of deep RL in real environments |\n| *Connecting Images and Natural Language* (PhD Thesis) | 2015 | Unified framework for image captioning, dense captioning, and video understanding |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Co-designed the Stanford CS231n curriculum, the field's most influential open educational resource on convolutional networks\n- Led Tesla Autopilot's shift to a pure vision-based approach (removing radar), deploying neural nets on custom FSD chips at scale\n- Championed \"vibe coding\" as a concept: natural-language-driven software development with LLMs as co-pilots\n- LLM101n: educational curriculum released through Eureka Labs teaching LLM construction from scratch\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Contributed analysis of human vs. CNN performance on ImageNet classification; no standalone benchmark bearing his name.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences; PhD thesis available publicly.\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- *The Unreasonable Effectiveness of Recurrent Neural Networks* (2015, blog) — demonstrated character-level language models generating credible text, Shakespeare, Linux code\n- *A Recipe for Training Neural Networks* (2019, blog) — practical debugging guide, widely assigned in ML courses\n- *Deep Reinforcement Learning Doesn't Work Yet* (2019, blog) — frank critique of the gap between RL demos and deployment\n- *Software 2.0* (2017, Medium) — argued neural networks constitute a new programming paradigm; software defined by data and weights rather than explicit instructions\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Extensive GitHub READMEs (nanoGPT, llm.c, minGPT) that function as tutorials\n- Regular long-form threads on X (@karpathy) covering AI systems, education, and industry observations\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Karpathy places AGI at least a decade away and argues the coming period should be called the \"decade of agents\" rather than the \"year of agents.\" He draws from Tesla Autopilot experience to describe what he calls the \"march of nines\": achieving 90% capability is the first milestone, but each additional nine (99%, 99.9%) demands comparable engineering effort. He believes current LLMs resemble \"ghosts\" or \"spirits\"—entities trained on the compressed record of human culture but instantiated through a fundamentally different process than biological cognition, which makes direct brain-to-LLM comparisons unreliable.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Karpathy does not belong to the catastrophist wing of AI safety but takes long-horizon risks seriously. He has stated that safety is integral to building systems correctly rather than a separate discipline bolted on afterward. His Tesla experience taught him that the gap between demo-level reliability and deployment-level reliability is not linear and can kill people; this operational seriousness informs his attitude to safety.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** He focuses on practical ethics—what it means to build systems that actually work safely in the physical world—rather than primarily on policy frameworks. He has been consistently committed to AI education as an equity issue, making Stanford-quality deep learning instruction freely available online years before MOOCs normalized the practice.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Rarely engages directly with regulatory proposals. His politics are techno-optimist: he believes the right response to AI's risks is building better AI and better engineers, not primarily through legislation. He has expressed concern that overly restrictive policy could ossify incumbent players.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent / Position | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| AGI imminent forecasters | Argues infrastructure gaps (memory, multimodal perception, continual learning) make near-term AGI implausible |\n| Pure RL proponents | Early skepticism of deep RL's readiness for real-world deployment |\n| Radar-dependent autonomy advocates (inside Tesla) | Pushed successfully for pure vision approach in Autopilot |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Stanford CS231n lecture series (2015–2017, archived on YouTube; tens of millions of cumulative views)\n- Tesla Autonomy Day 2019 (technical presentation on FSD neural net stack)\n- Numerous keynotes at NeurIPS, ICLR, and industry conferences\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast* (multiple appearances, 2019–2023)\n- *Dwarkesh Patel Podcast* (2023) — wide-ranging discussion on AGI timelines, LLM nature, AI education\n- *The 80,000 Hours Podcast* (2023)\n\n**Social Media:** X / Twitter: @karpathy (several million followers); GitHub: karpathy (nanoGPT, llm.c, micrograd, minGPT)\n**Online Courses:**\n- Stanford CS231n (co-created and primary instructor, 2015–2017; freely available)\n- *Neural Networks: Zero to Hero* (YouTube playlist, 2022–present; covers micrograd to GPT from scratch)\n- LLM101n (Eureka Labs, 2024–present)\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Empiricist pragmatism; strong commitment to transparency in how AI systems actually behave versus how they are marketed.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Limited direct engagement. His *Software 2.0* essay gestures at philosophy of mind. His teaching emphasizes building things and understanding from first principles rather than engaging institutional philosophical traditions.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Tesla Autopilot fatalities:** Karpathy led Autopilot vision during a period when Tesla FSD remained under NHTSA investigation and multiple fatal crashes occurred. He has not publicly addressed individual incidents but defended the aggregate safety case for the technology.\n2. **\"Vibe coding\" framing:** His popularization of natural-language-driven coding has attracted criticism from software engineers who argue it devalues rigorous software craft and produces fragile, poorly understood code.\n3. **OpenAI tenure opacity:** His returns to and departures from OpenAI have not been fully explained publicly, fueling speculation about internal disagreements.\n4. **Pure-vision Autopilot bet:** The decision to remove radar from Tesla vehicles remains contested; some safety researchers argue sensor fusion would have prevented specific accident types.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Karpathy publicly documents his reasoning with unusual candor. His *Recipe for Training Neural Networks* is partly a catalogue of his own past mistakes. He has acknowledged that deep RL does not live up to its demos — a rare public admission from a leading researcher about an entire subfield's state.\n\n---\n",
  "koller": "# Research Profile: Daphne Koller\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Daphne Koller  **Born:** August 27, 1968, Israel  **Nationality:** Israeli-American  \n**Education:** B.Sc., Computer Science, Hebrew University of Jerusalem (1985, age 17); M.Sc., Computer Science, Hebrew University of Jerusalem (1986, age 18); Ph.D., Computer Science, Stanford University (1993) — advisor Joseph Halpern  \n**Current Role:** Founder and CEO, insitro (ML-driven drug discovery and development company, founded 2018)  \n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1993–1995 | Postdoctoral Researcher, UC Berkeley |\n| 1995–2012 | Professor (to Full Professor), Computer Science, Stanford University (Rajeev Motwani Professor in the School of Engineering) |\n| 2012–2014 | Co-CEO, Coursera (co-founded with Andrew Ng) |\n| 2014–2016 | President, Coursera |\n| 2016–2018 | Chief Computing Officer, Calico (Google X life extension research lab) |\n| 2018–present | Founder and CEO, insitro |\n\n**Major Awards:** MacArthur Fellowship (\"Genius Grant\") (2004); Member, National Academy of Engineering (2011) — for contributions to representation, inference, and learning in probabilistic models; Member, National Academy of Sciences; Fellow, ACM; Fellow, AAAI; ACM-AAAI Allen Newell Award; Presidential Early Career Award for Scientists and Engineers (PECASE)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Probabilistic graphical models (PGMs) — representation, inference, and learning\n- Statistical relational learning\n- Computational biology and computational medicine\n- Machine learning for drug discovery\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Object-Oriented Bayesian Networks\" | 1997 | Extended Bayesian networks to handle object-oriented, relational structure |\n| \"Probabilistic Relational Models\" | 1999 | Foundational framework for statistical relational learning |\n| \"Learning Continuous Time Bayesian Networks\" | 2002 | Bayesian networks for continuous-time dynamical systems |\n| \"Multi-Class Protein Classification Using Adaptive Codes\" | 2003 | ML methods for protein function prediction |\n| *Probabilistic Graphical Models: Principles and Techniques* (textbook, with Nir Friedman) | 2009 | Definitive graduate textbook; comprehensive treatment of PGM theory and algorithms |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Probabilistic relational models (PRMs): combining Bayesian networks with relational/object-oriented structure\n- Continuous-time Bayesian networks: modeling dynamics over continuous time with Bayesian structure\n- Adaptive multi-class coding for machine learning classifiers\n- At insitro: ML-biology platform combining high-throughput cell biology, iPSC-derived cellular models, and deep learning for drug target identification and compound design\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** insitro has generated proprietary large-scale cellular biology datasets combining genomics, imaging, and functional assays; contributed to open-source computational biology benchmarks during Stanford career\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Probabilistic Graphical Models: Principles and Techniques* (2009, with Nir Friedman) — Graduate research audience; the definitive textbook on PGMs; covers Bayesian networks, Markov random fields, inference algorithms, and learning; MIT Press; ~1200 pages; used in graduate ML courses worldwide\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Daphne Koller on Drug Discovery and AI\" — extended podcast essay-interview outlining her thesis on ML-driven biology (*Possible* podcast)\n- \"AI-First Drug Discovery\" — public lectures and investor communications articulating insitro's foundational thesis\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- \"What AI Can and Cannot Do for Drug Discovery\" — interviews in *Nature*, *STAT News*, *Washington Post*\n- TED Talk: \"What we're learning from online education\" (2012) — over 2 million views; argues MOOCs can democratize education globally\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Koller does not engage prominently with AGI framing. Her focus is on applied ML for specific high-value problems — drug discovery, biology, education. She represents a pragmatic research philosophy that asks \"what can ML actually do here?\" rather than \"how close are we to AGI?\" Her work implicitly challenges AGI-centric narratives by demonstrating that carefully designed domain-specific ML systems can transform fields without requiring general intelligence.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Koller's safety concerns are domain-specific. In drug discovery, she is acutely aware that ML-generated hypotheses must be validated rigorously in biology — AI does not replace experimental verification, it focuses it. She has spoken about the risk of ML systems in biomedical contexts generating plausible-sounding but biologically wrong conclusions, and the importance of grounding ML in experimental ground truth. She emphasizes that AI in medicine must be held to the same evidentiary standards as any other scientific claim.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Koller has been explicit about healthcare equity as an ethical imperative. She has stated that \"AI's promise lies in healing divides, not widening them\" and has insisted on equitable deployment in clinical trials even when commercial pressures favor targeting optimal responders. Her advocacy for centralized, consented healthcare data repositories reflects a belief that the benefits of biomedical AI should be broadly shared. She also champions gender diversity in AI — insitro has maintained gender-balanced teams as a matter of principle.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Koller favors thoughtful regulation that enables AI-driven drug development without blocking innovation. She has advocated for regulatory frameworks that understand and accommodate ML-based evidence generation — recognizing that the FDA's existing paradigms were designed for classical clinical trials and need updating for AI-native approaches to drug development. She supports data-sharing policies that would enable the creation of large, diverse biomedical datasets.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Pure academic ML community | Koller has argued that ML research that ignores domain biology will not produce useful drug discovery; the field needs genuine integration, not superficial application |\n| Drug companies with non-diverse trial designs | Her insistence on equitable deployment challenges pharma's tendency to optimize trials for subgroups that show strongest efficacy signals |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED Talk: \"What we're learning from online education\" (2012) — widely watched; argues MOOCs can give everyone access to a Stanford-quality education\n- Multiple biotech investor conferences and science symposia on AI-driven drug discovery\n- AAAI, NeurIPS keynotes on probabilistic graphical models and ML for biology\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Possible* (Reid Hoffman) — extended interview on drug discovery and AI\n- Multiple biotech and AI podcasts discussing insitro's platform and ML for biology\n- *The Nucleus Podcast* (Regeneron) — AI's impact on drug discovery\n\n**Social Media:** Active on Twitter/X; tweets on AI, biotech, and education policy\n\n**Online Courses:** Co-created the Probabilistic Graphical Models specialization on Coursera — flagship course she co-founded; widely taken by ML practitioners worldwide\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Utilitarian framing of healthcare impact (reduce disease burden across populations); deontological commitment to equitable access; scientific rigor as an ethical constraint on AI claims in medicine\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Koller's engagements are primarily with science, medicine, and education policy rather than theology. Her MacArthur Fellowship recognized contributions with broad social impact. Her advocacy for open education connects to humanistic traditions of knowledge as a common good.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Coursera's commercialization:** Critics have argued that Coursera, despite its democratizing mission, has increasingly focused on revenue generation through paid certificates and corporate partnerships, potentially recreating the educational inequities it sought to address.\n2. **Calico's secrecy:** Her brief tenure at Calico (Google's life extension research lab) generated minimal public scientific output; critics questioned whether the lab's secrecy served the scientific community.\n3. **insitro's scientific progress:** As of 2025–2026, insitro has not yet produced an approved drug; critics in biotech note that the \"AI-first drug discovery\" thesis remains unproven at the clinical level, though the approach has generated significant preclinical results.\n4. **Data access challenges:** Her vision of a centralized biomedical data repository with appropriate safeguards faces enormous regulatory and privacy obstacles that she has not fully resolved in public proposals.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Koller has acknowledged that building the ML-biology integration insitro requires takes longer and is harder than building pure ML systems; she has been forthcoming that early timelines were optimistic and that biological validation adds necessary friction.\n\n---\n",
  "krizhevsky": "# Research Profile: Alex Krizhevsky\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Alex Krizhevsky\n**Born:** March 4, 1986 — Ukraine (raised in Canada)\n**Nationality:** Canadian (Ukrainian-born)\n\n**Education:**\n- B.Sc. and M.Sc., Computer Science, University of Toronto\n- Ph.D. studies (incomplete), Computer Science, University of Toronto (supervisor: Geoffrey Hinton; did not complete doctorate; left for industry)\n\n**Current Role:** Venture Partner, Two Bear Capital (early-stage VC firm, Whitefish, Montana; focus on AI, biotech, consumer internet, frontier technology)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~2005–2012 | Graduate student and researcher, University of Toronto (Hinton lab) |\n| 2012–2013 | Co-founder, DNN Research Inc. |\n| 2013 | DNN Research acquired by Google |\n| 2013–2017 | Research Scientist, Google Brain |\n| 2017–2020 | Technical Advisor, Dessa (AI startup, Toronto) |\n| 2020 | Dessa acquired by Square (now Block) |\n| ~2020–present | Venture Partner, Two Bear Capital |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- AlexNet won ILSVRC (ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge) 2012 by an unprecedented margin (15.3% top-5 error vs. runner-up 26.2%)\n- Co-creator of CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100 datasets, standard benchmarks used in hundreds of thousands of experiments worldwide\n- AlexNet source code archived by the Computer History Museum (2023), recognized as historically significant\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Deep convolutional neural networks for visual recognition\n- GPU-accelerated training of large neural networks\n- Image classification and computer vision\n- Dataset creation and benchmarking\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"ImageNet Classification with Deep Convolutional Neural Networks\" (Krizhevsky, Sutskever, Hinton) — \"AlexNet\" | 2012 | Won ILSVRC 2012 by a 10+ percentage point margin; launched the modern deep learning era in computer vision |\n| \"Learning Multiple Layers of Features from Tiny Images\" (Krizhevsky) | 2009 | Introduced the CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100 datasets; the most widely used small-image benchmarks in ML |\n| \"Rectified Linear Units Improve Restricted Boltzmann Machines\" (Nair and Hinton, with Krizhevsky contributions) | 2010 | Contributed to ReLU adoption as a practical activation function |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- AlexNet — the deep CNN architecture that won ImageNet 2012 and demonstrated that GPU-trained deep networks could decisively outperform all other approaches; eight layers (five convolutional, three fully connected); trained on two Nvidia GTX 580 GPUs in his parents' bedroom\n- CIFAR-10 and CIFAR-100 datasets — 60,000 labeled images (32×32 pixels) across 10 and 100 classes; co-created with Vinod Nair and Geoffrey Hinton; remain standard benchmarks decades later\n- Local Response Normalization (LRN) — normalization technique used in AlexNet, later succeeded by batch normalization\n- Overlapping max pooling — design choice in AlexNet that improved generalization and reduced overfitting\n- GPU parallelization for deep networks — demonstrated at scale that modern GPU hardware made deep CNN training tractable\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- CIFAR-10: 60,000 32×32 color images in 10 classes, 6,000 images per class; used in millions of experiments\n- CIFAR-100: Same format with 100 classes; used as a harder benchmark\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\nNone for general audiences. His published work consists primarily of the AlexNet paper and CIFAR dataset technical report.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Learning Multiple Layers of Features from Tiny Images\" (2009 technical report) — introduced CIFAR datasets and explored unsupervised pre-training\n- The AlexNet paper (Krizhevsky, Sutskever, Hinton, NeurIPS 2012) — functions as a manifesto for GPU-accelerated deep learning; the single most consequential computer vision paper of the 21st century\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Virtually none. Krizhevsky is one of the most private major figures in AI. He has given no known public interviews and maintains no public-facing social media presence.\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Unknown. Krizhevsky has not made public statements on AGI timelines, risks, or implications.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Unknown. No documented public positions.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Unknown. No documented public positions on AI ethics, bias, fairness, or governance.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Unknown. No documented public positions.\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- No documented public talks since leaving Google (2017). AlexNet-era presentations at ILSVRC and NeurIPS 2012 are the last known public technical appearances.\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- None known.\n\n**Social Media:**\n- None publicly known. He does not appear to maintain any public social media presence.\n\n**Online Courses:**\n- None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** None documented. Krizhevsky is one of the most private significant figures in AI history. He has not made philosophical statements on consciousness, human dignity, or the meaning of his work.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Unknown. His reported behavior — leaving Google after \"losing interest,\" moving to Montana, hiking — suggests a person who values simplicity and disengagement from the AI industry's competitive culture, but this is inference from reported facts, not documented philosophy.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **The AlexNet Paradox:** Krizhevsky built the system that launched a decade of AI acceleration he has since distanced himself from entirely. The company that acquired DNN Research (Google) went on to develop AI systems of enormous societal consequence. His personal retreat from the field he catalyzed raises an unasked question about moral responsibility for the downstream effects of foundational work.\n2. **Incomplete Doctorate:** Krizhevsky did not complete his PhD despite doing the most impactful PhD-era research in the history of computer vision. The AlexNet work was conducted as part of his doctoral studies; he left academia before finishing.\n3. **Credit and Collaboration:** The AlexNet paper has three authors: Krizhevsky, Ilya Sutskever, and Geoffrey Hinton. Krizhevsky's specific contributions (primary GPU implementation and architecture design) are well-documented, but the collaborative nature of the work in Hinton's lab means it was not a lone effort.\n4. **DNN Research Sale:** The immediate monetization of AlexNet's success through a Google acquisition — for a reported $44 million, one of the first major \"acqui-hires\" in AI — was an early instance of the pattern by which academic AI breakthroughs were rapidly absorbed into corporate infrastructure. Krizhevsky participated in and benefited from this dynamic.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** No public statements. His departure from Google citing \"loss of interest\" might be read as a form of self-acknowledged disengagement, but no elaboration exists in the public record.\n\n---\n",
  "lecun": "# Research Profile: Yann LeCun\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Yann André LeCun (born *Le Cun* — Breton surname from the Guingamp region of northern Brittany; Yann is the Breton form of Jean/John)\n**Born:** July 8, 1960, Soisy-sous-Montmorency, suburbs of Paris, France\n**Nationality:** French-American (dual citizen)\n\n**Education:**\n- *Diplôme d'Ingénieur*, ESIEE Paris, 1983\n- *PhD in Computer Science*, Université Pierre et Marie Curie (now Sorbonne University), 1987. Doctoral work proposed an early formulation of backpropagation for training neural networks. Advisor: Maurice Milgram.\n- *Postdoctoral Fellow*, University of Toronto, 1987–1988, supervised by **Geoffrey Hinton** — the same person with whom he later became the central figure of disagreement on AI safety.\n\n**Current Role:** Executive Chair and Co-Founder, AMI Labs (Advanced Machine Intelligence Labs), Paris — founded December 2025, raised $1.03B in March 2026 at a $3.5B pre-money valuation. Also Silver Professor / Jacob T. Schwartz Chaired Professor, NYU Courant Institute (continuing affiliation).\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1987–1988 | Postdoctoral Researcher, University of Toronto |\n| 1988–1996 | Research Scientist, AT&T Bell Laboratories |\n| 1996–2002 | Head, Image Processing Research Dept., AT&T Labs-Research |\n| 2002–2003 | Fellow, NEC Research Institute |\n| 2003–present | Professor (later Jacob T. Schwartz Chair), NYU Courant Institute |\n| 2012–2014 | Founding Director, NYU Center for Data Science |\n| Dec 2013–Nov 2025 | Director then Chief AI Scientist, Meta AI Research |\n| Dec 2025–present | Co-Founder and Executive Chair, AMI Labs, Paris |\n\n**Major Awards:** 2018 Turing Award (shared with Hinton and Bengio) — \"the Nobel Prize of Computing\"; TIME100 Most Influential People in AI, 2023; Carnegie Corporation \"Great Immigrant\" honoree.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and computer vision\n- Backpropagation and neural network optimization\n- Optical character recognition (OCR) and document understanding\n- Self-supervised learning and energy-based models\n- World models and Joint Embedding Predictive Architectures (JEPA)\n- Robotics and autonomous intelligence\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Backpropagation Applied to Handwritten Zip Code Recognition\" | 1989 | First large-scale application of backpropagation to a CNN for real-world character recognition |\n| \"Gradient-Based Learning Applied to Document Recognition\" (LeCun, Bottou, Bengio, Haffner) | 1998 | The foundational LeNet-5 paper; introduced the full CNN pipeline; applied to bank check reading; canonical CNN reference |\n| \"A Tutorial on Energy-Based Learning\" (LeCun et al.) | 2006 | Established the energy-based model framework unifying supervised, unsupervised, and structured prediction |\n| \"Deep Learning\" (LeCun, Bengio, Hinton) | 2015, *Nature* | Co-authored landmark review that brought deep learning to the broader scientific community |\n| \"A Path Towards Autonomous Machine Intelligence\" | 2022 | Proposes JEPA and a modular architecture for autonomous AI; his current research manifesto |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- **Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) / LeNet** — biologically inspired architecture using local receptive fields, weight sharing, and spatial pooling; LeNet-5 (1998) became the template for all modern image recognition\n- **MNIST Database** (with Corinna Cortes and Chris Burges) — 60,000 training / 10,000 test handwritten digit images; the single most widely used benchmark in ML history\n- **DjVu Image Compression** (with Bottou, Haffner, Howard) — compression format for scanned documents still in use\n- **Joint Embedding Predictive Architecture (JEPA) / I-JEPA / V-JEPA** — self-supervised world-model architecture predicting in latent embedding space rather than pixel space; basis of his AMI Labs work\n- **Optimal Brain Damage** — regularization method for pruning neural network weights\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- **MNIST** (1994/1998) — the most widely used introductory ML benchmark\n- **AT&T/Bell Labs check-reading dataset** — drove real-world deployment of LeNet; by the late 1990s reading 10–20% of all US checks\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\nLeCun has not published a popular trade book as of 2026. His major theoretical statement is \"A Path Towards Autonomous Machine Intelligence\" (self-published on OpenReview, 2022). His canonical written contribution to general science is the 2015 *Nature* review \"Deep Learning\" (co-authored with Bengio and Hinton).\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- **\"A Path Towards Autonomous Machine Intelligence\"** (OpenReview, June 2022) — proposes a modular cognitive architecture with a world model, cost module, short-term memory, actor, and perception module; argues LLMs are insufficient for general intelligence\n- LinkedIn posts and X/Twitter threads functioning as public intellectual essays on LLM limitations, open-source AI, and AI safety — some with hundreds of thousands of engagements\n- **\"Energy-Based Self-Supervised Learning\"** (ICLR 2020 talk) — widely circulated as a de facto essay on the future of representation learning\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Regular contributor to *Scientific American*\n- *TIME Magazine*, January 2024: \"Meta's AI Chief Yann LeCun on AGI, Open-Source, and AI Risk\"\n- Profiles and interviews in *The New Yorker*, *Wired*, *MIT Technology Review*, *VentureBeat*, and *Fortune*\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:**\n- Believes AGI is achievable but requires fundamentally different architectures than LLMs\n- Estimates \"at least a decade and probably much more\" even under his proposed research roadmap\n- Resists the term \"AGI\": *\"I hate that term. Human intelligence is not generalized at all. Humans are highly specialized.\"*\n- Insists current AI cannot understand the physical world the way even a housecat can\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Existential Risk:**\n- Strongly anti-doomer; places his P(doom) at **less than 1%**\n- Has called AI existential risk fears *\"complete B.S.\"*\n- Argues fears of a rogue superintelligence assume AI will spontaneously develop self-preservation drives — which he views as anthropomorphic fantasy: *\"Fears about AI taking over and destroying humanity are based on false premises and science fiction movies.\"*\n- Participated in the **Munk Debate on AI existential risk** (June 2023), opposing the motion alongside Melanie Mitchell, against Yoshua Bengio and Max Tegmark\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\n- Supports regulating AI *applications*, not AI research\n- Acknowledges bias is a real problem at the dataset level but has resisted framing it in systemic/structural terms (see Controversy section)\n- Believes the alignment problem is both a technical and philosophical challenge, and is solvable\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\n- Against preemptive or broad AI safety regulation, which he argues would entrench incumbents\n- Supports open-source AI as an antidote to power concentration; championed Meta's release of LLaMA 1–3\n- *\"I think the main risk of AI in the future is if AI is controlled by a handful of companies.\"*\n- *\"In the future, our entire information diet is going to be mediated by AI systems... the future has to be open source, for reasons of cultural diversity, democracy.\"*\n- Argues some safety regulation calls are strategically motivated by OpenAI and Anthropic to lock out competition\n\n**Views on LLMs:**\n- Considers current LLMs architecturally inadequate for true intelligence; has called them *\"autocomplete machines\"* that cannot reason, plan, or understand the physical world\n- *\"Nobody in their right mind would use LLMs of the type that we have today\"* within three to five years\n- *\"Existing systems don't understand the world as well as a housecat.\"*\n- Proposes **world models** (JEPA architecture) as the necessary next step\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| **Geoffrey Hinton** | AI existential risk — LeCun: <1%; Hinton: up to 50% within 5–20 years |\n| **Yoshua Bengio** | AI governance; Bengio signed extinction risk letter, launched LawZero; LeCun sees this as alarmist |\n| **Sam Altman / OpenAI** | Accuses OpenAI of \"fearmongering\" to shape regulation in its favor |\n| **Gary Marcus** | Long-running \"frenemy\" dynamic; LeCun dismissed Marcus's critiques of deep learning; irony: LeCun's current critique of LLMs echoes many points Marcus made years earlier |\n| **Timnit Gebru** | 2020 AI bias controversy (see Controversy section) |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- **TED Talk:** \"Deep Learning, Neural Networks and the Future of AI\" (with TED head Chris Anderson)\n- **Collège de France Inaugural Lecture:** \"Deep Learning: A Revolution in Artificial Intelligence\" (February 4, 2016) + 8-lecture series available online in French\n- **ICLR 2020 Keynote:** Energy-Based Models and Self-Supervised Learning\n- **Munk Debate** (June 2023) on AI existential risk — widely viewed online\n- **Columbia Engineering** lecture: How AI will match and exceed human-level intelligence\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- **Lex Fridman Podcast** — at least 3 appearances (most recent episode #416: \"Meta AI, Open Source, Limits of LLMs, AGI & the Future of AI\"; full transcript available)\n- **20VC (The Twenty Minute VC)** — \"Why Artificial Intelligence Will Not Dominate Humanity\"\n- **Machine Learning Street Talk** — ICLR 2020 special on Energy-Based Models\n- **The Hub** — AI existential risk debate with Tegmark, Bengio, Mitchell\n\n**Social Media:**\n- **X/Twitter** (@ylecun): ~1.1M followers; highly active and often confrontational\n- **LinkedIn:** ~680,000+ followers; longer essays and commentaries\n- **Threads** (@yannlecun): ~301,000 followers\n\n**Online Courses:**\n- **NYU Deep Learning Course** (DS-GA 1008), co-taught with Alfredo Canziani — fully free and open online; lecture videos, written overviews, and PyTorch Jupyter notebooks; translated into 12+ languages by 470+ volunteers; one of the best free graduate-level deep learning courses available.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness:**\n- *\"I can't define consciousness, but AI systems will have subjective experience and emotions.\"*\n- Carefully separates subjective experience and emotions from richer claims about self-awareness or consciousness; resists calling current AI systems sentient.\n\n**Views on Human Uniqueness and Reason:**\n- Argues humanity possesses a unique capacity to perceive abstract mathematical and logical truths — a form of \"godlike independent observation of the universe\" (secular framing)\n- Distinguishes between *formal logic* (machines have this) and *intuitive logic* (humans have both); argues this gap is what current AI lacks\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Secular humanism and Enlightenment rationalism\n- Open information access as a democratic good\n- Diversity and epistemic pluralism (justification for open-source AI)\n- AI as the *printing press* (democratizing knowledge), AI as a *new Renaissance*\n- *\"By amplifying human intelligence, AI may bring not just a new industrial revolution, but a new renaissance, a new period of enlightenment for humanity.\"*\n- *\"AI is intrinsically good, because the effect of AI is to make people smarter.\"*\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement with theology or religious philosophy. His optimism about AI is secular-humanist rather than theologically grounded.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n**1. The 2020 AI Bias / Racial Fairness Controversy:**\nSparked when LeCun tweeted that \"ML systems are biased when data is biased\" in response to the Duke PULSE model generating a white face from a pixelated image of Barack Obama. AI ethics researcher and \"Black in AI\" co-founder **Timnit Gebru** pushed back, arguing his framing was reductive and missed systemic dimensions of bias. The ensuing dispute attracted wide attention; Gebru received death threats as a result of harassment the debate generated. LeCun was widely criticized for being dismissive of structural racism in AI systems; he offered a partial apology but did not fully reverse his technical position. He exited Twitter in June 2020 as a result.\n\n**2. The Meta/LLaMA 4 Conflict and Departure (2025):**\nLeCun was sidelined at Meta as Zuckerberg pivoted hard toward LLMs — the direction LeCun had been arguing against. He stated that Meta's LLaMA 4 failures in April 2025 were partly due to pressure to rush development and that some benchmark results were manipulated. He publicly criticized Meta's new AI leadership direction and on November 19, 2025 announced he was leaving to found AMI Labs. Some observers describe his departure as partially involuntary — a marginalization of the research-first culture he represented. His quote: *\"You certainly don't tell a researcher like me what to do.\"*\n\n**3. Gary Marcus \"False Glorification\" Critique:**\nGary Marcus has published articles titled \"The False Glorification of Yann LeCun,\" arguing that LeCun's current critiques of LLMs echo ideas LeCun dismissed when Marcus raised them years earlier. LeCun has responded that Marcus's proposals for what to do instead contributed \"exactly zero\" concrete solutions.\n\n**4. Open-Source Safety Criticism:**\nBengio and AI safety researchers argue that Meta's open-source LLaMA releases enable misuse by state actors and bad actors that closed models would prevent. LeCun consistently rejects this, arguing benefits vastly outweigh risks.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:**\n- Acknowledged the 2020 Gebru incident needed more care and listening\n- Has not explicitly reversed any major technical position but has evolved his LLM critique to \"basically dead end\" with increasing forcefulness\n- Acknowledged that realizing his JEPA/world-model vision will take \"at least a decade\"\n\n---\n",
  "leike": "# Research Profile: Jan Leike\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Jan Leike\n**Born:** Not publicly stated; German national\n**Nationality:** German\n**Education:**\n- Undergraduate degree in Computer Science / Mathematics — University of Freiburg, Germany\n- PhD in Machine Learning (reinforcement learning theory, focus on the AIXI agent) — Australian National University (ANU); advisor: Marcus Hutter\n- Postdoctoral Fellow — Future of Humanity Institute (FHI), Oxford University\n**Current Role:** Head of Alignment Science, Anthropic\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~2014–2017 | PhD student, Australian National University (under Marcus Hutter) |\n| ~2017 | Postdoctoral Fellow, Future of Humanity Institute (FHI), Oxford University |\n| 2017–2021 | Research Scientist, DeepMind (AI safety team) |\n| 2021–2024 | Senior Director of Alignment / Co-leader, Superalignment team, OpenAI |\n| 2023 | Co-leader (with Ilya Sutskever), OpenAI Superalignment Project |\n| May 2024 | Resigned from OpenAI; publicly cited safety culture failures |\n| May 2024–present | Head of Alignment Science, Anthropic |\n\n**Major Awards:** Not listed in available sources; his stature derives from research impact and public credibility, not formal prizes.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Scalable oversight — how to ensure human supervision remains meaningful as AI systems exceed human capabilities\n- Recursive reward modeling\n- Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF) — co-developed foundational paper with Paul Christiano\n- Weak-to-strong generalization — using weaker AI supervisors to align stronger AI systems\n- Automated alignment research — using AI to assist in solving alignment problems\n- Superalignment — the problem of aligning AI systems more intelligent than humans\n- Theoretical reinforcement learning (AIXI and universal induction)\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Deep Reinforcement Learning from Human Preferences\" (Christiano, Leike, et al.) | 2017 | Co-developed RLHF with Paul Christiano; became the foundational technique for modern aligned AI |\n| \"Scalable Agent Alignment via Reward Modeling: A Research Direction\" (Leike, Krueger, Everitt, et al.) | 2018 | Introduced recursive reward modeling (RRM) — decomposing complex alignment problems via iteratively trained reward models |\n| \"AI Safety Gridworlds\" (Leike et al., DeepMind) | 2017 | Benchmark environments for testing AI safety properties; practical tool for empirical safety research |\n| \"Reward Tampering Problems and Solutions in Reinforcement Learning\" (Everitt, Leike, et al.) | 2021 | Formalizes the problem of AI systems that modify their own reward signal |\n| Work on InstructGPT, ChatGPT, GPT-4 alignment | 2022–2023 | Led the alignment of OpenAI's major commercial deployments |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- **Recursive Reward Modeling (RRM)**: An approach to alignment where human feedback trains a reward model, which trains an AI model, which in turn helps humans provide higher-quality feedback for the next iteration — a self-improving feedback loop for alignment.\n- **AI Safety Gridworlds**: A suite of test environments for empirically measuring whether AI systems exhibit safety properties (avoiding irreversibility, corrigibility, interruptibility).\n- **Co-development of RLHF**: Shared credit with Christiano and team; the technique powering modern AI alignment.\n- **Superalignment agenda**: Formalized the problem of aligning future superintelligent AI systems by leveraging current AI to assist in alignment research — a bootstrapping strategy for the alignment problem.\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- AI Safety Gridworlds (DeepMind, 2017) — benchmark for empirical AI safety testing; widely used in research\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Introducing Superalignment\" (OpenAI blog, with Ilya Sutskever, June 2023) — announced the Superalignment project and its goal of solving the alignment problem for superintelligent AI within four years\n- Resignation statement on X (May 2024): \"Over the past years, safety culture and processes have taken a backseat to shiny products. I have been disagreeing with OpenAI leadership about the company's core priorities for quite some time, until we reached a breaking point.\"\n- \"Scalable Agent Alignment via Reward Modeling\" (2018)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Widely covered in tech press for his OpenAI departure and move to Anthropic\n- Contributions to the Alignment Forum on scalable oversight and reward modeling\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:**\nLeike takes the prospect of AGI seriously and has dedicated his career to preparing for it. His Superalignment agenda at OpenAI was premised on the claim that \"currently, we don't have a solution for superintelligence alignment, and it may be one of the hardest technical problems of our time.\" He is more empirically grounded than Yudkowsky — focused on specific technical problems with specific research programs — but shares the conviction that the stakes are existential if alignment is not solved before superintelligence arrives.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nHis May 2024 departure statement from OpenAI was among the most significant public moments in AI safety history. In a post that went globally viral, he stated: \"safety culture and processes have taken a backseat to shiny products.\" He called for OpenAI to become \"a safety-first AGI company\" and stated his belief that without a fundamental reorientation, the current development path is dangerous. The resignation was widely read as confirmation by an insider that the safety concerns raised by external researchers about frontier AI labs were founded. At Anthropic, he leads alignment science with a focus on scalable oversight, weak-to-strong generalization, and automated alignment research.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nLeike's work is primarily technical, but his public statement in 2024 reflects an ethical conviction: that companies developing potentially dangerous technology have a special obligation to prioritize safety, not as a constraint on product development but as the foundational commitment. His departure — abandoning the most prestigious AI safety position in the world — was itself an ethical act.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nLess publicly vocal on policy than Russell or Bostrom, but his Anthropic role and public departure from OpenAI have made him a significant figure in discussions about voluntary commitments, responsible scaling policies, and what genuine safety culture looks like in AI labs. His departure was used by policymakers in multiple countries as evidence for why external oversight is needed.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| OpenAI leadership (Sam Altman era) | Fundamental disagreement about whether safety is treated as a first-order priority or a secondary constraint on product velocity |\n| Ilya Sutskever | Though they co-led Superalignment, Leike departed shortly after Sutskever — their shared departure signaled deep fractures in OpenAI's internal safety governance |\n| \"Capabilities first\" approach | His departure statement is a direct rebuttal to the view that capability development should lead and safety can follow |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- AXRP Podcast: \"Superalignment with Jan Leike\" (Episode 24) — detailed technical discussion of the Superalignment agenda\n- Various AI safety conference talks at NeurIPS, ICML\n- Public posts on X following OpenAI departure\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- AXRP (AI X-risk Research Podcast) — Episode 24\n- Future of Life Institute Podcast — on DeepMind, AI Safety, and Recursive Reward Modeling\n- Various alignment-focused shows\n\n**Social Media:**\n- X/Twitter: @janleike — active; departure statement accumulated significant reach\n- Personal website: jan.leike.name\n\n**Online Courses:** None, but his papers are curriculum in AI safety courses.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\nLeike has not made extensive public statements on consciousness or human dignity in theological terms. His ethical commitments emerge from his research priorities and his actions — specifically, his willingness to resign from a prestigious and well-compensated position over a matter of principle. This is itself a statement about what he values. He has spoken about the importance of ensuring that the development of advanced AI leads to a future that is \"good for everyone.\"\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Empirical / technical ethics: safety as engineering requirement\n- Duty-based: his departure statement reflects a sense of professional and moral obligation to speak truth about risk, regardless of institutional cost\n- Consequentialist in stakes analysis: superintelligent misalignment is the worst possible outcome\n- Institutional ethics: his departure raised questions about the obligations of researchers working inside organizations whose stated and actual priorities diverge\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:**\nLimited documented engagement, though his PhD supervisor Marcus Hutter's AIXI framework engages with deep questions about universal intelligence and rationality that have philosophical resonance.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **OpenAI Superalignment funding shortfall.** Leike announced the Superalignment project with a pledge of 20% of OpenAI's compute for alignment research. Critics and former colleagues subsequently reported that this commitment was not honored, contributing to the dissolution of the team and his departure.\n2. **Departure timing.** His resignation came days after Ilya Sutskever's announcement and shortly before several other departures. Some observers questioned whether coordinated departures were more effective as statements of principle or created undue reputational damage to OpenAI at a sensitive moment.\n3. **Impact of his work at OpenAI.** Critics argue that despite Leike's presence, the RLHF-based alignment implemented at OpenAI has not solved deep alignment problems and may have provided false assurance that the systems are \"safe.\"\n4. **Scalable oversight as sufficient.** His research agenda — scalable oversight, weak-to-strong generalization — is viewed by more pessimistic alignment researchers as addressing the wrong level of the problem; surface alignment rather than foundational goal structure.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** In his resignation statement, he acknowledged that \"building smarter-than-human AI\" while lacking a solution for alignment represents an unresolved institutional and technical problem — implying that his own work at OpenAI, despite its value, did not resolve the core challenge.\n\n---\n",
  "levine": "# Research Profile: Sergey Levine\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Sergey Levine **Born:** circa 1987 (exact date not publicly available) **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** B.S. and M.S. in Computer Science, Stanford University (2009); Ph.D. in Computer Science, Stanford University (2014), advised by Vladlen Koltun\n**Current Role:** Associate Professor, Department of Electrical Engineering and Computer Sciences, UC Berkeley; Chief Scientist and Co-Founder, Physical Intelligence (pi.ai)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2009–2014 | Ph.D. student, Stanford University |\n| 2014–2016 | Postdoctoral Researcher, Google Brain |\n| 2016–present | Associate Professor, UC Berkeley EECS |\n| 2016–present | Director, Robotic AI & Learning (RAIL) Lab, UC Berkeley |\n| 2024–present | Co-founder and Chief Scientist, Physical Intelligence |\n\n**Major Awards:** NSF CAREER Award; multiple best paper awards at NeurIPS, ICLR, ICML, and IEEE ICRA; included in MIT Technology Review's Innovators Under 35\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Deep reinforcement learning for robotic control\n- Offline reinforcement learning (learning from fixed datasets)\n- Imitation learning at scale\n- Foundation models for robotic manipulation\n- End-to-end visuomotor policy learning\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"End-to-End Training of Deep Visuomotor Policies\" (GPS) | 2016 | Trained robots directly from raw image pixels to motor commands |\n| \"Soft Actor-Critic: Off-Policy Maximum Entropy Deep RL with a Stochastic Actor\" (SAC) | 2018 | Highly influential off-policy RL algorithm; widely adopted in robotics |\n| \"Offline Reinforcement Learning: Tutorial, Review, and Perspectives on Open Problems\" | 2020 | Definitive survey; established offline RL as a major research paradigm |\n| \"RT-2: Vision-Language-Action Models Transfer Web Knowledge to Robotic Control\" (Google) | 2023 | Robot model leveraging web-scale VLMs for generalist robot control |\n| \"π0: A Vision-Language-Action Flow Model for General Robot Control\" | 2024 | Physical Intelligence's foundation model for general-purpose robotics |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Soft Actor-Critic (SAC): maximum-entropy RL for sample-efficient off-policy learning in continuous control\n- Guided Policy Search (GPS): trajectory optimization to train neural network policies\n- Offline RL paradigm: learning from pre-collected datasets without further environment interaction\n- π0 (pi-zero): open-sourced vision-language-action model for general robotic manipulation (Physical Intelligence)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Co-developed Open X-Embodiment dataset (cross-robot, cross-task large-scale robotics dataset); RT-1/RT-2 datasets; π0 training datasets at industrial scale\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Offline Reinforcement Learning: Tutorial, Review, and Perspectives on Open Problems\" (arXiv 2020) — foundational survey that defined the offline RL research agenda\n- Substack essays on robot learning and AI foundations (sergeylevine.substack.com)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Berkeley News interview: \"A path to resourceful autonomous agents\" (2023)\n- RoboBusiness keynote coverage on foundation models in robotics (2023)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Levine approaches AGI from an empiricist, systems-engineering perspective. He is focused on the concrete problem of building robots that generalize across tasks and environments — which he views as a prerequisite and partial definition of general intelligence. His π0 model represents a step toward robot foundation models that can handle diverse manipulation tasks from natural language commands, a practical embodied version of the generality that defines AGI discourse.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Levine's safety emphasis is primarily operational: safe robot deployment requires reliable policies, distributional robustness, and graceful failure modes. He co-authored research on safe RL and contributes to offline RL precisely because learning from fixed, validated datasets reduces the risk of catastrophic exploratory behavior during training. He has not been a prominent voice in existential AI risk debates but takes responsible deployment seriously as an engineering discipline.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Levine's public positions emphasize broadening access to capable robotic systems and building open-source tools. Physical Intelligence open-sourced π0 in February 2025 — a deliberate choice to democratize access to a state-of-the-art robot foundation model. He views concentration of robotic AI capability in a few large players as a risk and has argued for open research.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Not a prominent policy voice. Supports open-source release and academic access to robotic AI capabilities. His general orientation favors research openness over restrictive IP regimes.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Simulation-only robot learning proponents | Levine has consistently argued that real-world data collection is essential; sim-to-real gaps persist |\n| Pure RL from scratch for robotics | Levine's offline RL and imitation-first work demonstrates that data-driven approaches are more practical than online RL alone |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- ICLR 2025 invited talk: \"Data-Driven Pre-Training and Post-Training for Robot Foundation Models\"\n- RoboBusiness 2023 keynote on foundation models in robotics\n- Multiple NeurIPS and ICML presentations on offline RL and robot learning\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- TWIML AI Podcast (multiple appearances)\n- Lex Fridman Podcast\n- The Robot Report podcast\n\n**Social Media:** X/Twitter: @svlevine; Substack: sergeylevine.substack.com\n**Online Courses:** Course materials from Berkeley's CS 285 (Deep Reinforcement Learning) widely used; lecture videos publicly available\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Pragmatic consequentialism focused on robust, generalizable robot behavior; commitment to open science.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** None documented publicly.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Physical Intelligence valuation and private control** — Physical Intelligence's rapid rise to $5.6B+ valuation (2025) and reported $11B target (2026) raises questions about whether general-purpose robotic AI should be controlled by a venture-backed private company. The open-sourcing of π0 partially addresses this but does not resolve governance questions.\n2. **Labor displacement** — General-purpose robot manipulation models are the most direct technological vector for displacing warehouse, manufacturing, and service workers. Levine's work is the technical foundation for this displacement without any documented engagement with its social consequences.\n3. **Data collection practices** — Industrial-scale robot data collection often depends on existing warehouse and manufacturing workers performing demonstrations; the workers who generate the training data are the same workers who may be displaced by the resulting systems.\n4. **Reproducibility** — Some robotics papers from Berkeley and Physical Intelligence rely on custom hardware setups difficult to reproduce in other labs; this limits independent validation.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Levine openly discusses the challenge of distributional shift in offline RL and acknowledges that robot foundation models still fail unpredictably on out-of-distribution tasks. Physical Intelligence's π0 is described as a starting point, not a solved system.\n\n---\n",
  "li": "# Research Profile: Fei-Fei Li\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Fei-Fei Li (李飞飞)\n**Born:** July 3, 1976, Beijing, China\n**Nationality:** Chinese-born American (naturalized U.S. citizen)\n**Known As:** \"Godmother of AI,\" \"Queen of AI,\" \"Founding Mother of the AI Revolution\"\n\n**Personal Background:** Li immigrated to Parsippany, New Jersey at age 15–16. Her parents had been engineers and scientists in China but could not transfer their credentials — her father worked as a camera repairman, her mother as a cashier. The family arrived with less than $20. Li worked multiple jobs (waitressing, cleaning houses, running the family dry-cleaning shop) from age 18 through mid-graduate school at Princeton. Her mother's persistent health struggles shaped her conviction that technology must serve real human needs.\n\n**Education:**\n- **B.A., Physics** (High Honors), Princeton University, 1999\n- **Ph.D., Electrical Engineering**, Caltech, 2005. Dissertation: *\"Visual Recognition: Computational Models and Human Psychophysics.\"* Primary advisor: Pietro Perona. Co-advisor: Christof Koch (computational neuroscientist).\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n\n| Years | Role | Organization |\n|---|---|---|\n| 2005–2006 | Assistant Professor | University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign |\n| 2007–2009 | Faculty | Princeton University |\n| 2009–present | Professor of Computer Science (Sequoia Professor) | Stanford University |\n| 2013–2018 | Director, Stanford AI Lab (SAIL) | Stanford University |\n| Jan 2017–Sep 2018 | VP; Chief Scientist of AI/ML | Google Cloud (sabbatical from Stanford) |\n| 2018–present | Founding Co-Director | Stanford Institute for Human-Centered AI (HAI) |\n| 2020–2022 | Independent Board Member | Twitter (removed when Musk acquired company, Oct 2022) |\n| 2024–present | Co-founder and CEO | World Labs |\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Computer vision and image recognition\n- Machine learning and deep learning\n- Cognitive and computational neuroscience (how humans see)\n- AI in healthcare (ambient intelligent systems, clinical AI)\n- Spatial intelligence (3D world modeling, generative AI for physical environments)\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"ImageNet: A Large-Scale Hierarchical Image Database\" (CVPR 2009) | 2009 | Introduced the ImageNet dataset (~15M images, 22,000 categories); sparked the deep-learning revolution; ~12,000+ citations |\n| \"ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge\" (*Int'l Journal of Computer Vision*) | 2015 | Full documentation of the ILSVRC benchmark (2010–2014) that produced AlexNet and proved deep CNNs work at scale; ~11,000+ citations |\n| 300+ papers in Nature, PNAS, CVPR, ICCV, NeurIPS, NEJM, *Nature Digital Medicine* | 2005–2023 | Human action recognition, scene understanding, 3D scene parsing, visual relationship detection |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- **ImageNet** — 14–15 million labeled images in a WordNet hierarchy; directly enabled the 2012 AlexNet breakthrough and ignited the modern deep-learning era\n- **ILSVRC (ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge)** — annual benchmark competition (2010–2017); the competitive arena that drove rapid progress in CNNs\n- **Ambient Intelligence (AmI) systems for healthcare** — sensor-based, privacy-preserving systems for operating rooms and ICUs; aimed at patient safety and clinical efficiency\n- **Spatial Intelligence / World Models** (World Labs) — generative AI systems producing interactive, navigable 3D worlds from images, video, or text (product: \"Marble\")\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks Created:**\n- ImageNet (2007–2009, publicly launched 2010)\n- ILSVRC annual benchmark (2010–2017)\n- Scene understanding and action recognition datasets through Stanford Vision Lab\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books:**\n**\"The Worlds I See: Curiosity, Exploration, and Discovery at the Dawn of AI\"**\n- Publisher: Flatiron Books / Moment of Lift Books, 2023 (322 pages; co-written with Alex Michael)\n- Audience: General readers. Adopted as Princeton's Pre-Read for the Class of 2028 and San Francisco's 20th \"One City One Book\" selection.\n- Key thesis: AI was always a human endeavor — built by people with stories, limitations, biases, and moral responsibilities. Understanding this is essential to building AI that serves humanity. Themes: curiosity, resilience, compassion, responsibility, and love.\n- Named to technology book lists by the *Financial Times* and former President Barack Obama.\n\n**Scientific Publications:** 300+ peer-reviewed papers in CVPR, ICCV, NeurIPS, Nature, PNAS, *New England Journal of Medicine*, *Nature Digital Medicine*, and the *Journal of Neuroscience*.\n\n**Essays & Online Writing:**\n- **Substack** (@drfeifei) — essays on AI, spatial intelligence, and policy\n- Notable post: \"From Words to Worlds: Spatial Intelligence is AI's Next Frontier\" — argues language models alone are insufficient; AI must understand physical space\n- Op-eds in *Issues in Science and Technology*, *McKinsey Quarterly*, *Fortune*, *Bloomberg*, *IEEE Spectrum*, and the *Financial Times*\n- Contributor to Stanford HAI's policy briefs and the California AI Working Group Final Report (2025)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:**\nMeasured and science-grounded. States AGI \"will not be complete without spatial intelligence\" — current LLMs are architecturally insufficient for general intelligence because they lack grounding in physical reality. Advises policymakers to govern AI \"based on science, not science fiction.\" Does not commit to specific AGI timelines. Has described consciousness and compassion as capacities that AI does not yet have \"a mathematical path toward.\"\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nPrecautionary-pragmatic:\n- Supports anticipatory regulation — laws should account for risks \"not yet observed in the world\"\n- Co-led the Joint California Policy Working Group on AI Frontier Models (convened by Gov. Newsom after SB 1047 veto, 2024), producing a \"trust but verify\" framework: mandatory transparency reporting, third-party audits, corporate whistleblower protections, and public disclosure of data acquisition methods\n- Opposed SB 1047 not from deregulatory instinct but because its \"kill switch\" provision would have hampered open-source AI research\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nEthical framework is explicitly **human-centered** and **dignity-based**:\n- *\"There is no independent machine ethics — machine values are human values.\"*\n- Invokes **Kantian ethics** explicitly: *\"If AI applications take away that sense of dignity, there's something wrong.\"*\n- Coined the term **\"dignity dividend\"** — the idea that AI, designed with empathy, equity, and transparency, can actively reinforce societal well-being\n- Founded **AI4ALL** (2017) to ensure AI's builders reflect humanity's diversity — a homogeneous developer class produces AI that serves only a narrow slice of humanity\n- *\"A machine cannot be held morally responsible; a human can. A machine cannot understand the context of a community's values; a human can.\"*\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\n- Advocate for a federal AI research agency and expanded public AI research funding\n- Supports the Newsom working group's \"trust, but verify\" model\n- Argues for international cooperation on AI standards\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n\n| Talk | Venue/Year |\n|---|---|\n| \"How We're Teaching Computers to Understand Pictures\" | TED Vancouver, 2015 (2M+ views) |\n| \"With Spatial Intelligence, AI Will Understand the Real World\" | TED 2024 |\n| Keynote: Ambient Intelligence in Healthcare | Stanford AIMI Symposium 2021 |\n| Multiple keynotes | World Economic Forum (Davos), Fortune Most Powerful Women Summit |\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Tim Ferriss Show (#839, Dec 2025) — \"The Godmother of AI — Asking Audacious Questions, Civilizational Technology, and Finding Your North Star\"\n- Lenny's Newsletter/Podcast — \"The Godmother of AI on Jobs, Robots & Why World Models Are Next\"\n- NPR Short Wave (Nov 2023) — \"Trailblazing Computer Scientist Fei-Fei Li on Human-Centered AI\"\n- PBS Firing Line with Margaret Hoover — wide-ranging policy interview\n- Microsoft's Tools and Weapons with Brad Smith — on AI governance\n\n**Social Media:**\n- **X/Twitter:** @drfeifei\n- **Substack:** substack.com/@drfeifei\n- **LinkedIn:** Active\n\n**Online Courses:**\n- **CS231n: Deep Learning for Computer Vision** (Stanford) — the canonical university course on CNNs; lecture recordings freely available on YouTube; credited with training a generation of AI researchers.\n\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n**Project Maven / Google Cloud Email Controversy (2018):**\nDuring her tenure as Google Cloud Chief Scientist, Google contracted with the Pentagon on \"Project Maven\" — using AI to analyze drone surveillance footage. When the contract leaked, ~4,000 Google employees signed a protest petition. An internal email from Li, subsequently leaked to the press, instructed colleagues to \"avoid at ALL COSTS any mention or implication of AI\" in connection with the project, warning that \"weaponized AI is probably one of the most sensitized topics of AI.\"\n\nCritics argued the email showed Li prioritizing Google's PR interests over substantive ethical concern. She has maintained she is \"deeply against\" weaponizing AI and left Google shortly after (September 2018). The episode is genuinely complicated: evidence suggests both that she opposed the project on principle and that she tried to suppress public awareness of it. It is a useful case study in the gap between individual ethical conviction and institutional power.\n\n**Criticism of SB 1047 Opposition:**\nSome AI safety advocates criticized her opposition as providing cover for industry interests. Her counter-argument — that the bill would harm open-source research — was defensible but put her alongside large commercial labs in opposing the legislation. Largely resolved by her subsequent leadership of the more nuanced working group.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:**\n- Has spoken openly about the isolation of being a woman and immigrant in male-dominated CS departments\n- Acknowledges the difficulty of translating ethics commitments into enforceable technical and institutional practice\n- Notes the tension between running a commercial venture (World Labs, valued at over $1B) and advocating for democratized, publicly accountable AI\n\n---\n",
  "liang": "# Research Profile: Percy Liang\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Percy Liang\n**Born:** Not publicly documented\n**Nationality:** American\n\n**Education:**\n- B.S., Mathematics and Computer Science, MIT (2004)\n- Ph.D., Computer Science, UC Berkeley (2011)\n- Postdoctoral Researcher, Google (brief, post-PhD)\n\n**Current Role:** Associate Professor of Computer Science, Stanford University; Director, Center for Research on Foundation Models (CRFM), Stanford; Senior Fellow, Stanford Institute for Human-Centered AI (HAI); Co-founder, Together AI\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2004–2011 | Ph.D. student, UC Berkeley |\n| 2011 | Postdoctoral researcher, Google |\n| 2011–present | Faculty (Assistant, then Associate Professor), Computer Science, Stanford University |\n| 2021–present | Director, Center for Research on Foundation Models (CRFM), Stanford |\n| ~2022–present | Co-founder, Together AI (open-source AI infrastructure) |\n| Ongoing | Senior Fellow, Stanford HAI |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- Presidential Early Career Award for Scientists and Engineers (PECASE), 2019\n- IJCAI Computers and Thought Award, 2016\n- NSF CAREER Award, 2016\n- Sloan Research Fellowship, 2015\n- Microsoft Research Faculty Fellowship, 2014\n- AI2050 Fellow, Schmidt Sciences\n- Paper awards at ACL, EMNLP, ICML, COLT, ISMIR\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Evaluation and benchmarking of foundation models and LLMs\n- Transparency and interpretability in machine learning\n- Robustness and fairness of ML systems\n- Natural language processing: semantics, reasoning, grounding\n- Learning theory; interactive machine learning\n- Open-source AI development\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Holistic Evaluation of Language Models (HELM) | 2022 | Systematic, multi-metric LLM evaluation framework covering 42 scenarios and 7 metrics; arXiv 2211.09110 |\n| On the Opportunities and Risks of Foundation Models (the \"Foundation Models\" paper) | 2021 | Foundational 200+ author report from Stanford CRFM coining and defining \"foundation models\"; set agenda for the field |\n| The Foundation Model Transparency Index | 2023 | 100-indicator assessment of transparency among major foundation model developers; updated 2024, 2025 |\n| Compositional Semantic Parsing on Semi-Structured Tables | 2015 | SEMPRE framework for natural language interfaces to data |\n| Learning with Noise: Enhance Distillation... | Multiple | Work on robustness and data quality in ML |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- HELM (Holistic Evaluation of Language Models) — open-source benchmarking framework\n- Foundation Model Transparency Index (FMTI) — 100-indicator transparency scoring system\n- SEMPRE (Semantic Parsing with Execution) — NL-to-formal-language semantic parsing system\n- Together AI infrastructure (open-source model serving platform)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- HELM benchmark suite (42 scenarios, multiple metrics, continuously updated)\n- Foundation Model Transparency Index (23 developers scored annually)\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"On the Opportunities and Risks of Foundation Models\" (CRFM report, 2021) — widely cited foundational document for the foundation model era\n- \"Holistic Evaluation of Language Models\" (arXiv, 2022) — methodology manifesto for rigorous AI evaluation\n- \"Percy Liang: Transparency for Foundation Models\" (DeepLearning.AI, 2024) — articulates transparency agenda\n- \"Percy Liang: A New Way to Build AI, Openly\" (TED Talk, 2024)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Stanford HAI news and blog pieces on foundation model evaluation\n- GenAI Summit coverage and interviews\n- Imbue podcast: \"On the paradigm shift and societal effects of foundation models\" (2024)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Liang focuses less on AGI timelines than on what foundation models actually are and what they can actually do. His research agenda implicitly critiques AGI hype by demanding rigorous measurement: until we have transparent, standardized evaluation, claims about AI capability—whether optimistic or pessimistic—are not grounded. His foundation model framing acknowledges transformative potential while insisting on responsible development.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** His primary safety concern is the opacity of the most powerful foundation models. He notes: \"Very little is known publicly about the most advanced models (such as GPT-4, Gemini, and Claude) regarding what data was used to train them and who created this data and labor practices.\" Without transparency, he argues, we lose accountability. The FMTI documents systematic opacity in areas including copyright, data access, labor practices, and downstream impact—and shows that even with public pressure, major developers sustain deliberate areas of secrecy.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Liang argues that values alignment is not a technical problem with a technical solution—it is a democratic problem requiring democratic governance. He has stated that it is important to \"foreground the values that language models embody rather than just sweeping it under the umbrella of 'we're aligning to human values'\"—arguing that framing obscures whose values are actually being encoded. He advocates for governance structures that are \"participatory and get better representation so that the values of a language model are actually reflecting what people want.\"\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Liang supports transparency mandates, open-source AI development, and democratic governance of AI values. He uses the analogy: \"Without transparency, we lose accountability... like not having nutrition labels on the food you eat, or not having safety ratings on the cars you drive.\" He advocates for Together AI's open-source infrastructure as a structural counterweight to concentrated proprietary model development.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent / Tension | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Closed major AI labs (OpenAI, Google DeepMind, Anthropic) | Argues systematic opacity of major foundation model developers prevents accountability; FMTI scores show sustained secrecy |\n| AI capability hype broadly | HELM reveals that AI systems perform unevenly across scenarios; benchmarks show current gaps hype obscures |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED Talk: \"Percy Liang: A New Way to Build AI, Openly\" (2024)\n- Stanford HAI conference talks\n- GenAI Summit keynote\n- Imbue AI podcast conversation (2024)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Imbue podcast: \"On the paradigm shift and societal effects of foundation models\" (2024)\n- Various AI research and policy podcasts\n\n**Social Media:** X/Twitter (@percyliang); Stanford profile pages\n\n**Online Courses:** Stanford CS221 (Artificial Intelligence: Principles and Techniques); CS224N (NLP with Deep Learning) — course materials available online\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Liang does not engage philosophical questions of consciousness or dignity directly in his public work. His closest engagement with values questions is through his argument that AI systems encode values—the values of a small number of people behind closed doors—and that this has profound societal consequences. The implicit framework is democratic: decisions affecting all people should reflect the participation of all people, not be made unilaterally by tech companies.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Democratic governance theory; epistemic justice; transparency as accountability mechanism; data rights and labor rights framing.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No direct engagement documented. His work is technically and policy-focused. The Together AI project reflects a commitment to open, distributed development as an alternative to concentrated power—values with resonances in participatory democracy traditions.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **HELM's own limitations:** Critics have noted that HELM itself involves choices about which scenarios, metrics, and weights to include that embed the values of its creators—raising questions about whether a \"holistic\" evaluation framework can be neutral.\n2. **Together AI commercial interests:** Liang co-founded Together AI, a commercial infrastructure company. Open-source AI advocacy has commercial benefits for companies providing open-source infrastructure, creating a potential conflict of interest in his policy arguments.\n3. **FMTI and industry response:** Some AI companies argue the FMTI incentivizes superficial disclosure (releasing documents that satisfy indicators) rather than genuine transparency. The 2024 update showed average scores improving substantially, but Liang acknowledges \"sustained and systemic opacity\" persists in key areas.\n4. **Foundation model framing criticized:** Some researchers have criticized the \"foundation model\" term itself (coined partly in the CRFM 2021 report) as overstating the stability and neutrality of these models—arguing the framing obscures power dynamics and risks.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Liang acknowledges that transparency alone is not sufficient—it requires corresponding accountability mechanisms, regulatory teeth, and public capacity to act on disclosed information.\n\n---\n",
  "manning": "# Research Profile: Christopher Manning\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Christopher David Manning\n**Born:** Not publicly disclosed; raised in Australia\n**Nationality:** Australian-American\n\n**Education:**\n- B.A. (Hons), majoring in Mathematics, Computer Science, and Linguistics, Australian National University, 1989\n- Ph.D. in Linguistics, Stanford University, 1994 (advisor: Joan Bresnan)\n\n**Current Role:** Thomas M. Siebel Professor in Machine Learning, Departments of Linguistics and Computer Science, Stanford University; Associate Director, Stanford Institute for Human-Centered Artificial Intelligence (HAI); Director Emeritus, Stanford AI Lab (SAIL; served 2018–2025)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1994–1996 | Assistant Professor of Computer Science, Carnegie Mellon University |\n| 1996–1999 | Lecturer in Linguistics, University of Sydney |\n| 1999–2006 | Assistant Professor, Stanford University (Linguistics and Computer Science) |\n| 2006–2012 | Associate Professor, Stanford University |\n| 2012–present | Professor (Full), Stanford University |\n| 2018–2025 | Director, Stanford Artificial Intelligence Laboratory (SAIL) |\n| Ongoing | Thomas M. Siebel Professor in Machine Learning (inaugural chair) |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- IEEE John von Neumann Medal, 2024\n- ACL Test of Time Awards, 2023, 2024, 2025 (three consecutive years)\n- ACL, EMNLP, EACL, ICML, and CHI Best Paper Awards (multiple)\n- ACM Fellow; AAAI Fellow; ACL Fellow\n- Member, U.S. National Academy of Engineering\n- Member, American Academy of Arts and Sciences\n- Past President, Association for Computational Linguistics (2015)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Neural natural language processing and deep learning for language\n- Word vector representations (GloVe)\n- Dependency parsing and syntactic analysis\n- Neural machine translation\n- Sentiment analysis and natural language inference\n- Question answering and reading comprehension\n- Self-supervised pretraining and foundational language models\n- Universal Dependencies (cross-linguistic syntactic annotation standard)\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"GloVe: Global Vectors for Word Representation\" (Pennington, Socher, Manning) | 2014 | Introduced GloVe word vectors; combined global matrix factorization and local context window approaches; widely adopted pre-BERT embedding standard. ACL Test-of-Time Award 2024. |\n| \"Recursive Deep Models for Semantic Compositionality over a Sentiment Treebank\" (Socher, Perelygin, Wu et al., Manning) | 2013 | Tree-recursive neural networks for sentiment analysis; introduced Stanford Sentiment Treebank. |\n| \"Neural Machine Translation by Jointly Learning to Align and Translate\" (Bahdanau, Cho, Bengio) | 2015 | Manning's group contributed to alignment/attention mechanisms that preceded the Transformer. |\n| \"A Fast and Accurate Dependency Parser using Neural Networks\" (Chen & Manning) | 2014 | First neural dependency parser achieving speed suitable for practical deployment. |\n| \"Human Language Understanding & Reasoning\" | 2022 | Published in Daedalus (American Academy of Arts and Sciences); accessible synthesis of NLP history, current capabilities, and what it means for machines to understand language. |\n| \"Humans and transformer LMs: Abstraction drives language learning\" (Manning & Jian) | 2026 | Best Paper Award, EACL 2026; examines shared patterns in human and transformer language acquisition. |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- GloVe word vectors (standard embedding before BERT)\n- Neural dependency parsing (made syntactic parsing practical at scale)\n- Stanford CoreNLP and Stanza (open-source NLP toolkits used worldwide)\n- Stanford Dependencies and Universal Dependencies (cross-linguistic annotation standards)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- Stanford Sentiment Treebank (SST)\n- Universal Dependencies treebanks (cross-linguistic)\n- Stanford CoreNLP benchmarks\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Foundations of Statistical Natural Language Processing* (Manning and Schütze, MIT Press, 1999) — foundational graduate textbook; trained a generation of NLP researchers\n- *Introduction to Information Retrieval* (Manning, Raghavan, and Schütze, Cambridge University Press, 2008) — freely available online; standard reference for search systems\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Human Language Understanding & Reasoning,\" *Daedalus* (Spring 2022) — accessible account of NLP history and the question of machine meaning\n- \"Academic NLP Research in the Age of LLMs: Nothing but Blue Skies\" — EMNLP 2023 keynote; argued that large language models open rather than close research opportunities\n- \"Meaning and Intelligence in Language Models: From Philosophy to Agents in a World\" — COLM 2024 talk\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Stanford HAI and Stanford Engineering features on responsible AI and machine bias\n- \"Responsible AI: Keeping Machines from Absorbing Human Biases\" — Stanford Online content\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Manning is cautious about AGI claims. His 2022 Daedalus piece argued that pretrained language models show \"the first inklings of a more general form of artificial intelligence\" but carefully avoided strong claims about machine understanding. His COLM 2024 talk explored what \"intelligence\" actually means in language models — distinguishing statistical fluency from genuine reasoning. He has consistently resisted both hype and dismissal.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Manning does not occupy the existential-risk wing of AI safety discourse. His concerns are more grounded: AI systems absorb and amplify human biases encoded in training data; NLP systems used at scale for search, translation, and information retrieval can systematically distort information access. He teaches and publishes on responsible AI, including how language training encodes social biases.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Manning is a persistent advocate for open-source tools and shared research infrastructure. Stanford CoreNLP was among the first major open-source NLP toolkits; Stanza continues that tradition. He approaches AI ethics through the lens of fairness, bias mitigation, and the democratic access to language technology. His Stanford HAI work engages explicitly with the human-centered framing: AI should serve human needs rather than replace human judgment.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Engaged through Stanford HAI, which interfaces with policymakers. Manning's specific policy positions are not extensively documented publicly; his engagement is primarily through research framing and institutional leadership.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| \"NLP is solved\" camp | Manning has consistently argued that LLM fluency does not equal understanding; the hard problems of language remain open |\n| Doom-and-gloom AI critics | His EMNLP 2023 keynote argued that LLMs open new research directions rather than making academic NLP research obsolete |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- EMNLP 2023 Keynote: \"Academic NLP research in the Age of LLMs: Nothing but Blue Skies\"\n- COLM 2024: \"Meaning and Intelligence in Language Models: From Philosophy to Agents in a World\"\n- Stanford Engineering \"The Future of Everything\" podcast appearance (May 2024): \"The future of computational linguistics\"\n- \"On Large Language Models for Understanding Human Language\" (YouTube; Stanford lecture series)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- TWIML AI Podcast #686: \"Language Understanding and LLMs with Christopher Manning\" (May 2024)\n- Stanford HAI podcast appearances\n\n**Social Media:** Active on X (@chrmanning); posts on NLP research, Stanford events, and AI policy.\n\n**Online Courses:**\n- CS224N: Natural Language Processing with Deep Learning (Stanford; videos watched hundreds of thousands of times globally; one of the most influential free NLP courses available)\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Manning's 2022 Daedalus article directly engages the question of whether machines understand language — one of the deepest questions at the intersection of cognitive science, philosophy, and theology. He writes carefully about the gap between statistical competence and semantic understanding, noting that LLMs show \"inklings\" of general intelligence without claiming that comprehension has been achieved. His COLM 2024 talk on \"Meaning and Intelligence in Language Models\" confronted the philosophical question directly: what is meaning, and do machines have it?\n\nIn a 2024 TWIML interview, Manning discussed the intersection of linguistics and LLMs and what LLM capabilities can teach us about human language acquisition — implicitly treating human language as the standard of comparison and LLMs as approximations.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Human-centered AI (HAI framework); open-source scientific infrastructure as a common good; bias mitigation in training data; fairness in NLP applications. Manning's ethics are embedded in research practice rather than abstract pronouncements.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Significant. His training combines mathematics, computer science, and linguistics — a genuinely humanistic formation. His publication in *Daedalus* (the journal of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, one of the oldest humanities journals in the United States) on human language understanding represents a deliberate crossing from technical into humanistic discourse. His work on meaning, understanding, and the relationship between human and machine language learning engages questions that philosophy and theology have considered for centuries.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **GloVe vs. contextual embeddings:** GloVe was superseded by BERT and contextual embedding approaches; some researchers argued the static vector paradigm Manning championed had fundamental limitations that were underacknowledged. Manning's group adapted, but the transition raised questions about whether non-contextual embeddings were a dead end.\n2. **\"Nothing but Blue Skies\" optimism:** Manning's EMNLP 2023 keynote was criticized by some as overly optimistic — arguing academic NLP remains vibrant when many academic researchers face real disadvantages competing with industrial labs' compute and data resources. The critique is that Manning, from a well-resourced Stanford lab, underestimates how difficult it is for less-resourced researchers.\n3. **Universal Dependencies limitations:** The Universal Dependencies project, while enormously influential, has been criticized for imposing English-centric syntactic categories on non-European languages. This is a known challenge in cross-linguistic annotation that Manning's group has acknowledged.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Manning has publicly acknowledged that the relationship between LLM fluency and genuine understanding is unresolved: he has carefully avoided claiming machines \"understand\" language while arguing their capabilities are impressive. The 2022 Daedalus piece and 2024 COLM talk both model intellectual humility about what remains unknown.\n\n---\n",
  "marcus": "# Research Profile: Gary Marcus\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Gary Marcus\n**Born:** 1970, United States\n**Nationality:** American\n\n**Education:**\n- B.A., Cognitive Science, Hampshire College\n- Ph.D., Cognitive Science / Brain and Cognitive Sciences, MIT (advisor: Steven Pinker)\n\n**Current Role:** Professor Emeritus, Psychology and Neural Science, New York University; CEO/Co-founder, Robust AI; author and public intellectual; Substack writer (Marcus on AI)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~1990s | Graduate student, MIT (under Steven Pinker) |\n| ~1998–2023 | Professor (various ranks), Psychology and Neural Science, NYU |\n| 2014–2016 | Founder, Geometric Intelligence (machine learning startup) |\n| Dec 2016 | Geometric Intelligence acquired by Uber |\n| Dec 2016–Mar 2017 | Director of AI, Uber |\n| 2019–present | Co-founder and CEO, Robust AI (with Rodney Brooks) |\n| 2023–present | Professor Emeritus, NYU |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- New York Times bestselling author (Guitar Zero)\n- Forbes \"7 Must-Read Books in AI\" (Rebooting AI)\n- Testified before U.S. Senate alongside Sam Altman, May 2023\n- Signed open letter calling for GPT-4+ moratorium (March 2023)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Language acquisition and regularization in children (nativist/Chomskyan perspective)\n- Cognitive architecture and the role of innate structure in learning\n- Limitations of neural networks and deep learning\n- Neuro-symbolic AI as alternative to pure connectionism\n- Reliability and robustness of AI systems\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| The Algebraic Mind: Integrating Connectionism and Cognitive Science | 2001 | Book-length argument that connectionist models cannot explain rule-following cognition without symbolic structures |\n| Rethinking Eliminativism | 2001 | Critique of pure connectionist accounts of cognition |\n| Deep Learning: A Critical Appraisal | 2018 | Widely read arXiv paper cataloguing 10 structural limitations of deep learning systems |\n| Negative Evidence in Language Acquisition | 1993 | Doctoral work on how children learn not to overgeneralize morphological rules |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- No architectures to his name; his contribution is critical analysis and conceptual framing\n- Co-founder of Robust AI, which develops industrial robotics with safety and reliability guarantees\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *The Algebraic Mind* (MIT Press, 2001) — connectionism critique\n- *The Birth of the Mind* (Basic Books, 2004) — genetics and cognitive development\n- *Kluge: The Haphazard Evolution of the Human Mind* (Houghton Mifflin, 2008)\n- *Guitar Zero* (Penguin Press, 2012) — New York Times bestseller; adult learning and music\n- *Rebooting AI: Building Artificial Intelligence We Can Trust* (Pantheon, 2019; co-authored with Ernest Davis) — Forbes top AI book; accessible critique of AI limitations and path forward\n- *Taming Silicon Valley: How We Can Ensure That AI Works for Us* (MIT Press, 2024) — policy and regulation recommendations for generative AI\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Deep Learning: A Critical Appraisal\" (arXiv, 2018)\n- \"AI Risk ≠ AGI Risk\" (Marcus on AI Substack)\n- \"25 AI Predictions for 2025\" (Marcus on AI Substack)\n- Multiple op-eds in The New Yorker, The Atlantic, MIT Technology Review, IEEE Spectrum\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Regular IEEE Spectrum columnist\n- MIT Technology Review contributor\n- Psychology Today blog contributor\n- Marcus on AI (Substack) — active, widely read newsletter\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Marcus argues that current deep learning architectures cannot achieve AGI because they lack symbol manipulation, causal reasoning, compositionality, and robust generalization from limited data. He draws an analogy to chess: LLMs can recite chess rules but will move pieces illegally in play because they have not built an internal model of the game. He characterizes LLMs as \"text compression algorithms\" that excel at memorizing and retrieving patterns but cannot perform the symbolic reasoning and composability that AGI would require, regardless of scale.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** He distinguishes sharply between near-term AI risk (from \"mediocre AI that is unreliable but widely deployed\") and long-term AGI existential risk. He signed the March 2023 open letter calling for a moratorium on training systems more powerful than GPT-4, primarily citing the dangers of unreliable AI deployed at scale before adequate safeguards exist. He has written: \"Superintelligence may or may not be imminent, but there's a lot to be worried about either way.\" His primary worry is hallucination, bias, and unreliability in deployed systems causing concrete harm—not science-fiction scenarios.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Marcus is a consistent critic of AI hype and a proponent of transparency about what AI systems actually can and cannot do. He has long warned about facial recognition bias, résumé-parsing discrimination, and other near-term AI harms. He frames ethical AI deployment as requiring honest capability assessment—a position shared with Emily Bender though from a different technical angle.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** His 2024 book, \"Taming Silicon Valley,\" is a sustained policy argument: AI companies should face transparency mandates, government regulation, and ethical safeguards comparable to pharmaceutical or aviation industries. He testified before the U.S. Senate in May 2023 alongside Sam Altman, presenting a more skeptical perspective on industry self-regulation.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Yann LeCun | Whether deep learning alone can achieve AGI; LeCun argues world models are sufficient, Marcus argues symbolic reasoning is essential; long-running public dispute since at least 2014 |\n| OpenAI / Sam Altman | Marcus skeptical of capability claims and advocates for external regulation rather than industry self-governance |\n| LLM scaling advocates broadly | Marcus argues scaling cannot overcome structural limitations of connectionist architectures |\n| AI existential risk community (partially) | He criticizes focus on long-term existential risk as distracting from near-term deployment harms, though he did sign the 6-month moratorium letter |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- U.S. Senate testimony, May 2023 (alongside Sam Altman)\n- TED Talk appearances\n- Munk Debates and similar public forums (note: Mitchell and LeCun were the 2023 Munk Debate team against Bengio/Tegmark; Marcus has participated in related forums)\n- AI for Good (ITU) conference speaker\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- unSILOed Podcast with Greg LaBlanc\n- Numerous AI ethics and tech podcasts\n\n**Social Media:** Active on X/Twitter; Substack (Marcus on AI) — substantial following\n\n**Online Courses:** None formally, but Substack newsletter functions as ongoing public education\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Marcus approaches AI through cognitive science rather than philosophy of mind per se, but his repeated insistence that AI lacks genuine understanding implies that human cognition—characterized by symbolic reasoning, causal modeling, and compositionality—is categorically different from what current AI achieves. In \"Kluge,\" he examines the imperfect, jury-rigged nature of human cognition with humor and humility, treating humans neither as machines nor as transcendent beings but as evolved problem-solvers whose \"kluges\" are both fascinating and limiting.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Empirical scientific reasoning as primary; pragmatic consequentialism about harms; transparency and honesty norms applied to technology development and deployment.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No direct engagement with theology. His background is cognitive science and linguistics (under Pinker at MIT), strongly shaped by nativism and the idea that humans have innate cognitive structures. This connects, obliquely, to traditions that see human cognition as irreducibly structured rather than purely shaped by environment.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **\"Goalpost shifting\" accusation:** As AI capabilities have improved—especially with GPT-4 and GPT-4o—critics argue Marcus consistently moves the definition of what constitutes real intelligence to preserve his critique. He has been accused of predicting AI failures that do not materialize and adjusting the frame rather than updating his position.\n2. **Lack of constructive alternative:** While Marcus advocates neuro-symbolic AI, he has not produced a working large-scale system that demonstrates the superiority of his approach. Critics note that critique without demonstrated alternatives has limited impact.\n3. **LeCun dispute intensity:** The Marcus-LeCun debate has become at times personal and repetitive, with Marcus accusing LeCun of misrepresenting his views. The dispute has generated heat as well as light in the AI community.\n4. **Geometric Intelligence/Uber acquisition:** Marcus founded and sold a machine learning company to Uber in 2016—a move that some critics find in tension with his role as AI skeptic, though he has been transparent about this history.\n5. **Robust AI commercial interests:** As CEO of an industrial robotics startup, Marcus has commercial interests in the narrative that current AI is unreliable and needs better safety guarantees.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Marcus has acknowledged that his predictions about AI timelines have sometimes been wrong and that he did not fully anticipate the rapid improvement of LLMs with scale. He has adjusted his critique to focus on what remains unresolved rather than abandoning skepticism.\n\n---\n",
  "marietje": "# Research Profile: Marietje Schaake\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Marietje Schaake **Born:** October 28, 1978 **Nationality:** Dutch\n**Education:** Liberal arts, Wittenberg University (Ohio); Sociology, American Studies, New Media — University of Amsterdam\n**Current Role:** International Policy Director, Stanford Cyber Policy Center; International Policy Fellow, Stanford Institute for Human-Centered AI (HAI); Columnist, Financial Times\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2003–2009 | Lantos Fellow, U.S. House of Representatives; advisor to U.S. Ambassador to the Netherlands; consultant, Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs |\n| 2009–2019 | Member of the European Parliament (Netherlands, D66/ALDE); ALDE Coordinator, International Trade Committee (INTA) |\n| 2019–present | International Policy Director, Stanford Cyber Policy Center |\n| 2019–present | International Policy Fellow, Stanford HAI |\n| 2020–present | Columnist, Financial Times |\n| 2023–present | Member, UN High-Level Advisory Body on Artificial Intelligence |\n| Various | President, Cyber Peace Institute; board roles, multiple nonprofits |\n\n**Major Awards:** Named one of Politico Europe's most influential figures in technology policy.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Policy / Governance Work:**\n- Advancing binding legal frameworks for AI accountability and transparency\n- Promoting democratic oversight of AI systems and technology companies\n- Developing EU regulatory approaches to cybersurveillance and dual-use export controls\n- Advocating for alignment of AI governance with human rights and democratic principles\n- Contributing policy recommendations on EU AI Act implementation at the Stanford-HAI level\n\n**Landmark Papers / Policy Documents:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Stanford HAI Policy Brief on EU AI White Paper | 2020 | Multi-disciplinary policy recommendations submitted to the EU Commission on AI regulation |\n| UN High-Level Advisory Body Reports on AI Governance | 2023–2024 | Contributing member on risks, opportunities, and international AI governance |\n\n**Key Contributions:**\n- Pressed for export controls on cybersurveillance technologies through EU dual-use legislation reform during her MEP tenure\n- Led ALDE position on transatlantic trade (TTIP) with embedded digital rights provisions\n- Bridges academic AI research and binding regulation across the transatlantic space\n- Argues that democratic values must be embedded in AI systems by design, not applied as afterthoughts\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *The Tech Coup: How to Save Democracy from Silicon Valley* (Princeton University Press, 2024) — Written for policymakers, business leaders, and engaged citizens. Thesis: tech companies are encroaching on governmental roles and destabilizing democratic rule of law. Argues for applying to AI the same legal clarity and accountability mechanisms that exist for medicines, chemicals, and food.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- Regular Financial Times columns (2020–present) on AI accountability, EU regulation, and democratic governance\n- Project Syndicate essays on technology, democracy, and human rights\n- ECFR (European Council on Foreign Relations) publications on digital sovereignty\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Numerous pieces in the Financial Times framing AI governance as a democratic necessity, not a business obstacle\n- Op-eds on AI Act enforcement and corporate accountability\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Schaake has not focused primarily on AGI timelines or superintelligence scenarios. Her concern is present-day AI systems and the governance vacuum that already exists. She treats AGI speculation as a distraction from urgent and tractable regulatory work.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Safety is a governance problem before it is a technical problem. Tech companies should not be trusted to self-regulate. Binding legal standards — with meaningful sanctions for non-compliance — are the appropriate mechanism for managing AI risk.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Ethics commitments by companies are insufficient without legal enforcement. She argues that voluntary principles and industry self-regulation consistently fail. Democratic governance must provide the standards that ethics statements cannot.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** One of Europe's most consistent voices for binding AI regulation. She argues that AI must meet the same accountability standards society applies to other powerful technologies — medicine, chemicals, automobiles. The EU AI Act is necessary but insufficient without strong enforcement. She supports the EU AI Office and has pushed for transparent, public-facing compliance criteria. Internationally, she has called for a global alignment on AI governance standards built on democratic values, not authoritarian models. She is skeptical of U.S. industry-led governance proposals, which she sees as designed to delay binding rules.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| U.S. tech industry | Opposes self-regulatory AI frameworks; argues they protect profits, not people |\n| Big Tech platforms generally | Challenged their assumption that digital markets should remain largely unregulated |\n| EU enforcement laggards | Criticized member states that resist AI Act enforcement mechanisms |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- World Economic Forum (Davos), multiple years\n- Stanford HAI annual conference\n- SXSW, various European tech policy forums\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Hidden Business Risks of AI (guest)\n- Various tech policy and governance podcasts\n\n**Social Media:** Active on X (formerly Twitter); frequent commentary on AI policy developments\n\n**Online Courses:** None documented.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Rule of law; democratic accountability; human rights; precautionary principle in technology deployment.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement with religious or theological frameworks. Her humanities background (sociology, American studies, new media) informs a social-science framing of technology's role in public life.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. Critics from the tech industry argue her regulatory positions overestimate governance capacity and underestimate innovation costs.\n2. Some academics argue that the EU AI Act framework she supported still leaves significant enforcement gaps, particularly for foundation models and generative AI.\n3. Her dual roles — Stanford policy academic and active international governance participant — have raised questions about institutional independence, though no specific conflicts of interest have been documented.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Schaake has acknowledged that regulation alone cannot solve all AI harms — enforcement capacity and technical literacy within regulatory bodies remain major challenges.\n\n---\n",
  "mccarthy": "# Research Profile: John McCarthy\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** John McCarthy\n**Born:** September 4, 1927, Boston, Massachusetts\n**Died:** October 24, 2011, Stanford, California (age 84)\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- B.S., Mathematics, California Institute of Technology (1948)\n- Ph.D., Mathematics, Princeton University (1951); advisor: Solomon Lefschetz\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1951–1953 | Instructor, Mathematics, Princeton University |\n| 1953–1955 | Acting Assistant Professor, Mathematics, Stanford University |\n| 1955–1958 | Assistant Professor, Mathematics, Dartmouth College |\n| 1958–1962 | Assistant Professor, then Associate Professor, MIT (co-founded MIT AI Laboratory) |\n| 1962–2000 | Professor, Computer Science, Stanford University (founded Stanford AI Laboratory, SAIL, 1962) |\n| 2000–2011 | Professor Emeritus, Stanford University |\n\n**Major Awards:** ACM Turing Award (1971); Kyoto Prize (1988); National Medal of Science (1990); Benjamin Franklin Medal in Computer and Cognitive Science (2003).\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Symbolic artificial intelligence and logical reasoning\n- Programming language design (Lisp)\n- Formal logic and commonsense reasoning\n- Circumscription and non-monotonic logic\n- Time-sharing computer systems\n- Epistemology of AI and machine consciousness\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Dartmouth Conference Proposal\" (with Minsky, Shannon, Rochester) | 1955 | Founding document of AI as a field; introduced the term \"artificial intelligence\" |\n| \"Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine\" | 1960 | Defined the Lisp programming language; introduced recursion and linked lists to computing |\n| \"Programs with Common Sense\" | 1959 | Proposed the Advice Taker; first formal proposal for a knowledge-based AI system |\n| \"Situations, Actions, and Causal Laws\" | 1963 | Introduced the Situation Calculus; foundational to AI formal reasoning |\n| \"Circumscription: A Form of Non-Monotonic Reasoning\" | 1980 | Formal treatment of commonsense reasoning under incomplete information |\n| \"Ascribing Mental Qualities to Machines\" | 1979 | Philosophical paper on machine consciousness and belief |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- Coined the term \"Artificial Intelligence\": McCarthy deliberately chose this name for the 1956 Dartmouth Summer Research Project, establishing an independent discipline separate from cybernetics and automata theory\n- Lisp programming language: introduced conditional expressions, recursion, symbolic computation, garbage collection, and dynamic typing — the dominant AI programming language for three decades and still influential\n- Time-sharing: McCarthy proposed and championed time-sharing of mainframe computers, making interactive computing possible and laying the groundwork for modern operating systems\n- Stanford AI Laboratory (SAIL): founded one of the two dominant AI research centers in the world; trained a generation of researchers\n- Situation calculus and non-monotonic logic: formal systems for representing knowledge about dynamic, incomplete situations; foundational to knowledge representation and automated planning\n- Advice Taker (theoretical): proposed but never fully implemented; the first design for a system that could reason from explicit knowledge rather than special-purpose code\n\n**Historical Significance:** McCarthy did two things that shaped the entire subsequent trajectory of AI. First, he named the field. \"Artificial intelligence\" was a deliberate choice: it asserted that machines could be intelligent, that this was a proper scientific program, and that it was distinct from related work on control, communication, and automata. The name shaped what researchers worked on and how the field was funded and understood for seventy years. Second, he invented Lisp, which gave AI researchers a programming language suited to symbolic manipulation and allowed the symbolic AI paradigm to flourish. His technical and institutional contributions — SAIL, the Dartmouth Conference, Lisp — were foundational.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- *Formalizing Common Sense: Papers by John McCarthy* (1990, ed. V. Lifschitz) — collected papers on formal reasoning, non-monotonic logic, situation calculus\n- *LISP 1.5 Programmer's Manual* (1962, with others) — defining document of the Lisp language\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"Dartmouth Summer Research Project on Artificial Intelligence\" proposal (1955, with Minsky, Shannon, Rochester)\n- \"Recursive Functions of Symbolic Expressions and Their Computation by Machine, Part I\" (1960) — *Communications of the ACM*\n- \"Programs with Common Sense\" (1959) — *Proceedings of the Teddington Conference on the Mechanisation of Thought Processes*\n- \"Situations, Actions, and Causal Laws\" (1963) — Stanford AI Lab Memo 2\n- \"Circumscription: A Form of Non-Monotonic Reasoning\" (1980) — *Artificial Intelligence*\n- \"Ascribing Mental Qualities to Machines\" (1979) — *Philosophical Perspectives in Artificial Intelligence*\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- Extensive personal website (www-formal.stanford.edu/jmc) with essays on AI, philosophy, politics, and ethics — an unusually direct public record of his views\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** McCarthy was an optimist and a formalist. He believed that human intelligence was, in principle, fully formalizable — that any aspect of human cognition could be represented precisely enough to be programmed into a machine. He championed symbolic, logic-based AI: the approach that intelligence consists in manipulating symbols according to formal rules, as a mathematician does when proving a theorem. He was skeptical of neural network approaches, believing they lacked the principled, interpretable structure that genuine intelligence required. He remained committed to symbolic AI even as neural networks came to dominate the field.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** McCarthy held an aggressively progressive view of technology's potential. He believed that science and technology could solve almost any human problem, including scarcity, disease, and existential risk. He was an early and vocal advocate of space colonization and nuclear power. He had no patience for romantic nostalgia about pre-technological life or concerns about technology's dehumanizing effects. When asked whether human intuition represented a spiritual difference between humans and computers, he acknowledged that some people believe this but characterized it as a view \"in steady decline for a few centuries\" — implying it would continue to decline.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:** McCarthy raised ethical concerns primarily in the domain of formal logic and epistemology rather than social consequence. He was interested in how AI systems could be made to reason correctly about ethical situations — a formal problem — more than in the broader social and political implications of automation. He did write about environmental issues in his later career and held heterodox political views (shifting from Communist to conservative Republican after visiting Czechoslovakia in 1968). He did not share Wiener's moral urgency about automation's human consequences.\n\n**Known Debates or Controversies of Their Era:** The central controversy of McCarthy's career was the symbolic vs. connectionist debate in AI. McCarthy championed logic-based symbolic AI; Minsky shared this orientation in the 1960s–70s. The neural network revival of the 1980s–2000s represented a repudiation of the symbolic approach. The triumph of deep learning in the 2010s was a further blow. McCarthy maintained that symbolic AI had the principled foundations that connectionist systems lacked, and that the apparent success of neural networks was an engineering achievement that obscured fundamental theoretical limitations. This debate is not fully resolved: the current \"neurosymbolic AI\" research program attempts to combine both approaches.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and What Makes Humans Human:** McCarthy held that consciousness and mental states are functional properties realizable in any sufficiently complex physical system — a view known as functionalism. His 1979 paper \"Ascribing Mental Qualities to Machines\" argued that even thermostats have rudimentary \"beliefs\" in a functional sense, and that this attributive practice is both useful and legitimate. He wrote seriously about robot consciousness and free will, not as rhetorical exercises but as genuine research questions. He believed there was no in-principle barrier to machine consciousness, though he acknowledged significant practical challenges. He did not see human beings as uniquely or irreducibly different from machines in kind — only in degree of complexity.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Consequentialist and rationalist. McCarthy believed that ethical questions could, in principle, be answered formally — that a sufficiently powerful reasoning system could derive correct ethical conclusions from a well-specified set of values and facts. This was, in effect, an application of the symbolic AI program to ethics. He did not invoke tradition, authority, or religious frameworks. His personal ethics appear to have been pragmatic and individualistic.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Minimal and skeptical. McCarthy's engagement with theology was primarily as an obstacle — the kind of claim that asserts human uniqueness or mental irreducibility on non-empirical grounds, which he systematically tried to refute. He engaged with philosophy of mind seriously (Dennett, Searle, Chalmers) but on rationalist terms. He had no interest in the humanities tradition as a source of insight for AI.\n\n---\n",
  "mcculloch": "# Research Profile: Warren McCulloch\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Warren Sturgis McCulloch\n**Born:** November 16, 1898, Orange, New Jersey\n**Died:** September 24, 1969, Cambridge, Massachusetts (age 70)\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- Haverford College, 1917–1919 (began study, intent on Quaker ministry under Rufus Jones)\n- B.A. in Philosophy and Psychology (with minor in Psychology), Yale University, 1921\n- M.A. in Psychology, Columbia University, 1923\n- M.D., Columbia University College of Physicians and Surgeons, 1927\n- Internship, Bellevue Hospital, New York\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1898–1917 | Childhood in Orange, New Jersey; Episcopalian household, Quaker associations |\n| 1917–1919 | Haverford College; intended to train for Quaker ministry under Rufus Jones |\n| 1919–1921 | Yale University; switched to philosophy and psychology |\n| 1921–1927 | Columbia University; MA in psychology, then MD |\n| 1927–1934 | Internship at Bellevue Hospital; residency at Rockland State Hospital; worked under Eilhard von Domarus |\n| 1934–1941 | Research and teaching, Yale; worked on neurophysiology of the brain |\n| 1941–1952 | Professor of Psychiatry, University of Illinois at Chicago |\n| 1943 | Published \"A Logical Calculus of the Ideas Immanent in Nervous Activity\" with Walter Pitts |\n| 1946–1953 | Co-organized and chaired Macy Conferences on Cybernetics |\n| 1952–1969 | Research Scientist, Research Laboratory of Electronics, MIT |\n| 1965 | Published *Embodiments of Mind* (collected papers) |\n| 1969 | Died in Cambridge, Massachusetts |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- Honorary Doctorate, University of Illinois, 1961\n- Fellow, American Academy of Arts and Sciences\n- Fellow, New York Academy of Sciences\n- Member, National Academy of Sciences (elected)\n- Pioneer of cybernetics and computational neuroscience; named contributor to the founding of artificial intelligence by IEEE and ACM retrospectives\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Neurophysiology and computational neuroscience\n- Mathematical models of the nervous system\n- Cybernetics and feedback systems\n- Logic and the theory of mind\n- Experimental epistemology (how the brain comes to know)\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"A Logical Calculus of the Ideas Immanent in Nervous Activity\" (with Walter Pitts) | 1943 | *Bulletin of Mathematical Biophysics* 5:115–133; introduced the McCulloch-Pitts neuron — the mathematical model of the neuron that founded neural network theory |\n| \"How We Know Universals: The Perception of Auditory and Visual Forms\" (with Walter Pitts) | 1947 | Showed how neural networks could recognize invariant features — a theory of perception |\n| \"What the Frog's Eye Tells the Frog's Brain\" (with Lettvin, Maturana, Pitts) | 1959 | Foundational paper in computational neuroscience; showed that retinal cells perform feature detection before signals reach the brain |\n| *Embodiments of Mind* | 1965 | MIT Press; collected papers spanning logic, neuroscience, cybernetics, and philosophy of mind; his major synthetic work |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- Co-created the McCulloch-Pitts neuron (1943): a mathematical model in which a neuron receives binary inputs, applies a threshold, and fires or does not fire — performing logical operations. Networks of McCulloch-Pitts neurons can compute any logical function. This is the mathematical ancestor of every artificial neural network.\n- Showed for the first time that the logical operations of formal logic could be embodied in a physical network of simple elements — bridging logic, mathematics, and neuroscience\n- Co-organized the Macy Conferences on Cybernetics (1946–1953): the interdisciplinary meetings that founded cybernetics as a field, bringing together mathematicians, engineers, neurophysiologists, psychiatrists, social scientists, and anthropologists (including Norbert Wiener, John von Neumann, Claude Shannon, Gregory Bateson, Margaret Mead)\n- \"What the Frog's Eye Tells the Frog's Brain\" (1959): showed that neural systems perform information processing — feature detection, pattern recognition — not just signal transmission; a founding paper of computational neuroscience and a direct inspiration for Hubel and Wiesel's visual cortex work\n\n**Historical Significance:** The 1943 McCulloch-Pitts paper is one of the most consequential papers in 20th-century science. It provided the mathematical model that Frank Rosenblatt used for the perceptron (1958), that Rumelhart and Hinton scaled up via backpropagation (1986), and that underlies every neural network operating today. It also proposed the first computational theory of mind: that thought is logical computation, and the brain implements logic in neurons. This was simultaneously a scientific hypothesis about the brain and a philosophical claim about the nature of mind — that mental processes can be exhaustively described in formal logical terms.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- *Embodiments of Mind* (1965, MIT Press) — Collected papers in neurophysiology, cybernetics, and philosophy; his major synthetic statement; the title itself is philosophically weighted — \"embodiments\" rather than \"locations\" or \"correlates\" suggests that mind is not separable from its physical instantiation\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"A Logical Calculus of the Ideas Immanent in Nervous Activity\" (1943) — The founding paper of neural network theory\n- \"How We Know Universals\" (1947) — Neural model of invariant perception\n- \"What the Frog's Eye Tells the Frog's Brain\" (1959) — Foundational in computational neuroscience\n- \"A Heterarchy of Values Determined by the Topology of Nervous Nets\" (1945) — Introduced the concept of heterarchy (as opposed to hierarchy) — multiple conflicting criteria without a single dominant one; influential in organizational theory and cognitive science\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- McCulloch wrote poetry and was known as a vivid, unconventional lecturer and conversationalist; \"Embodiments of Mind\" contains accessible philosophical essays alongside dense technical papers\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** McCulloch believed that logic and neural computation were the same thing at different levels of description. His 1943 paper was not primarily about building machines; it was a theory of how brains work. But its implication for AI was immediate and radical: if neurons implement logical operations, and logical operations are the substrate of thought, then thought is in principle physically realizable in any system capable of implementing the same logical operations. Minds are not special; they are physical implementations of logical processes.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** McCulloch held a strikingly non-dualist view of the human person. He believed that mind, consciousness, and thought were biological phenomena — not metaphysically separate from the physical — but he did not think this made them less remarkable. He was deeply interested in what the nervous system actually does and found it astonishing. He famously asked: \"What is a number, that a man may know it, and a man, that he may know a number?\" — a question that links epistemology, mathematics, and the philosophy of the person.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:**\n- His computational theory of mind, if correct, challenges traditional accounts of human uniqueness based on the possession of an immaterial soul or rational faculty\n- His cybernetics work raised questions about the boundary between mind and machine, organism and artifact, control and freedom\n- \"A Heterarchy of Values\" (1945) challenged the idea that values or goals can be strictly ranked — anticipating debates about incommensurable values in ethics\n\n**Known Debates:** McCulloch engaged in fierce debates at the Macy Conferences — particularly with John von Neumann over the nature of the brain as a computing device. He also had substantive exchanges with Norbert Wiener (cybernetics), Shannon (information theory), and Bateson (anthropology and systems theory). His relationship with Walter Pitts was close and complicated; Pitts was a troubled genius who McCulloch befriended and whose collaboration was essential to the 1943 paper.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\nHe abandoned the path to ministry and shifted to philosophy and psychology at Yale, then medicine at Columbia. But this theological formation never entirely left him. His famous question — \"What is a number, that a man may know it, and a man, that he may know a number?\" — is structurally theological: it asks what kind of being a human being must be in order to be capable of knowing abstract truth. This is the question of Aquinas and of Augustine before him.\n\nHe later wrote: \"At last we are learning to admit ignorance, suspend judgement, and forego the *explicatio ignoti per ignotum* — 'God' — which has proved as futile as it is profane. Instead we seek mechanisms.\" This statement is agnostic and scientistic in tone — but the framing is significant: he is not dismissing religion; he is describing a methodological discipline. He is saying: in science, we seek mechanisms rather than invoking God as explanation. Whether this constituted personal disbelief or methodological naturalism is not entirely clear. His life trajectory — from intended ministry to neuroscience to cybernetics — suggests someone who redirected religious seriousness toward scientific inquiry, not someone who abandoned it.\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and Human Uniqueness:** McCulloch's 1943 paper proposed that logical computation is the nature of thought — that what neurons do, in their binary firing, is implement the logical operations that constitute mental activity. This was a materialist claim about mind. But McCulloch was more subtle than a crude materialist: he was interested in the *form* of mental operations, not merely their physical substrate, and he believed the brain exhibited irreducible complexity that could not be reduced to any simple mechanism. His concept of \"heterarchy\" — multiple simultaneous, conflicting values without hierarchical resolution — was his way of modeling the complexity of practical human judgment that resists reduction to simple ranking or optimization.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** McCulloch's ethics were shaped by his early theological training and his encounter with the European tradition through philosophy, psychiatry, and the Macy Conference world. He took seriously the question of what makes human beings what they are — and his answer, drawn from neuroscience and cybernetics, was provisional and humble. He did not think science had eliminated the importance of the question; he thought it had made the question more, not less, interesting.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** *Embodiments of Mind* contains essays on epistemology, logic, ethics, and the philosophy of mind that engage directly with philosophical traditions from Aristotle through Kant. His question about numbers and persons is directly connected to Platonic and Aristotelian debates about the nature of mathematical objects and the intellect's relationship to them. He studied under Rufus Jones, who was a deeply humanistic Quaker philosopher interested in mysticism, experience, and the inner life. He read Descartes, Leibniz, and Kant at Yale. The breadth of his formation — theology, philosophy, psychiatry, mathematics, neurophysiology — made him one of the most intellectually rich figures in 20th-century science.\n\n---\n",
  "minsky": "# Research Profile: Marvin Minsky\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Marvin Lee Minsky\n**Born:** August 9, 1927, New York City, New York\n**Died:** January 24, 2016, Boston, Massachusetts (age 88)\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- Fieldston School and Phillips Academy, Andover\n- B.A., Mathematics, Harvard University (1950)\n- Ph.D., Mathematics (Theory of Neural-Analog Reinforcement Systems), Princeton University (1954); advisor: Albert Tucker\n- Junior Fellow, Harvard Society of Fellows (1954–1957)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1957–1958 | Junior Fellow, Harvard Society of Fellows |\n| 1958–1961 | Assistant Professor, Mathematics / Lincoln Laboratory, MIT |\n| 1961–1974 | Associate Professor, then Professor, Electrical Engineering, MIT |\n| 1958–2016 | Co-founder and long-term researcher, MIT Artificial Intelligence Laboratory (co-founded with McCarthy, 1959) |\n| 1974–2016 | Donner Professor of Science, MIT Media Lab and EECS |\n\n**Major Awards:** ACM Turing Award (1969); Japan Prize (1990); Benjamin Franklin Medal in Computer and Cognitive Science (2001); IJCAI Award for Research Excellence (1991); Dan David Prize (2014).\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Symbolic artificial intelligence\n- Cognitive architectures and the theory of mind\n- Neural network theory and its limitations\n- Robotics (early robotic manipulation at MIT)\n- Frame theory and knowledge representation\n- Philosophy of mind and machine consciousness\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Steps Toward Artificial Intelligence\" | 1961 | Comprehensive survey of AI approaches; defined research agenda for the field |\n| *Perceptrons* (with Seymour Papert) | 1969 | Mathematical analysis of single-layer neural networks; showed fundamental limits of perceptrons |\n| \"A Framework for Representing Knowledge\" | 1974 | Introduced \"frames\" — structured knowledge representations; precursor to object-oriented programming and modern ontologies |\n| *The Society of Mind* | 1986 | Proposed mind as a society of interacting simple agents; popular and technical synthesis |\n| *The Emotion Machine* | 2006 | Extended Society of Mind theory; argued emotions are types of thinking, not alternatives |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- SNARC (Stochastic Neural-Analog Reinforcement Calculator, 1951): built at Harvard with Dean Edmonds; one of the first artificial neural network machines — 3,000 vacuum tubes and a B-24 bomber autopilot mechanism simulating a network of 40 neurons\n- Confocal scanning microscope (1957): invented for biological research; now standard in cell biology laboratories worldwide — a reminder that Minsky's genius spanned domains\n- Logo turtle and early educational computing (with Seymour Papert): foundational to constructivist educational computing\n- Frames: formal data structures for representing stereotyped situations; direct ancestor of object-oriented programming and semantic web ontologies\n- Society of Mind theory: proposed that intelligence emerges from interaction of many simple, non-intelligent processes with no central executive — a distributed, emergentist theory of mind\n\n**Historical Significance:** Minsky shaped the trajectory of AI more than any other single figure during its formative decades. His 1969 *Perceptrons* book, co-authored with Seymour Papert, redirected AI funding and research away from neural networks and toward symbolic AI for a decade. Whether this was a scientifically justified correction or a damaging overreach remains disputed. His frame theory influenced knowledge representation across AI and computer science. His Society of Mind theory remains one of the most serious attempts to explain how intelligence could emerge from non-intelligent components — a question still central to AI and cognitive science.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- *Perceptrons: An Introduction to Computational Geometry* (1969, with Seymour Papert; expanded ed. 1988) — technical; thesis: single-layer perceptrons have severe mathematical limitations; their naive optimism was unjustified\n- *The Society of Mind* (1986) — popular and technical; thesis: mind emerges from the interaction of many simple agents, none individually intelligent\n- *The Emotion Machine: Commonsense Thinking, Artificial Intelligence, and the Future of the Human Mind* (2006) — popular; thesis: emotions are forms of thinking; consciousness is a collection of interacting processes, not a unified experience\n- *Robotics* (1985, ed.) — edited volume; technical\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"Steps Toward Artificial Intelligence\" (1961) — *Proceedings of the IRE*\n- \"Artificial Intelligence\" (1966) — *Scientific American*\n- \"A Framework for Representing Knowledge\" (1974) — MIT AI Memo 306\n- \"Logical vs. Analogical or Symbolic vs. Connectionist or Neat vs. Scruffy\" (1991)\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- *The Society of Mind* (1986) — written for general audiences; formatted as 270 one-page essays, each exploring one facet of mind\n- *The Emotion Machine* (2006) — accessible synthesis for general readers\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** Minsky was a committed symbolic AI advocate who believed that human-level intelligence required machines that understand how they themselves work — machines that can reflect on their own reasoning processes and correct their own errors. His 1969 Turing Award lecture argued this point explicitly. He was deeply skeptical of what he called \"neat\" AI (clean, mathematical, formal approaches like logic and optimization) versus \"scruffy\" AI (messy, heuristic, empirical approaches including neural networks). Paradoxically, his early career included neural network work (SNARC) before he became the most influential critic of that approach.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** Minsky believed that mind is, at its core, a computational process and that there is no in-principle barrier to replicating it in machines. He was dismissive of mysterian positions — the view that consciousness has some irreducible quality beyond computation. He wrote: \"The power of intelligence stems from our vast diversity, not from any single, perfect principle.\" He advocated radical life extension and saw no reason why human consciousness could not eventually be transferred to non-biological substrates. He regarded biological death as a solvable engineering problem.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:** Minsky raised few ethical concerns about AI during his career. He was an optimist who tended to see AI's risks as primarily technical (building systems that work correctly) rather than social or political. He was associated with the Long Now Foundation and had views on existential risk, but his public emphasis was overwhelmingly on possibility rather than danger. The absence of Wienerian moral urgency in Minsky is striking given how deeply he thought about the nature of mind.\n\n**Known Debates or Controversies of Their Era:**\n- The perceptron controversy: Minsky and Papert's 1969 critique was accused (then and since) of deliberately overstating neural network limitations to redirect funding toward symbolic AI, which was their own research program. The charge is not proven, but the book's influence on funding and research direction was indisputably large and its mathematical claims, while technically correct for single-layer perceptrons, were applied by readers to neural networks generally.\n- Minsky was named in the Jeffrey Epstein connection (he attended an Epstein-associated event); his estate and colleagues have strongly disputed characterizations of his involvement. This controversy emerged after his death.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and What Makes Humans Human:** Minsky's position was unequivocal: consciousness is not a unified thing. It is a \"suitcase word\" — a term that bundles together many different processes and capabilities that the brain has built up over evolutionary time, none of which is individually special or mysterious. He stated: \"Consciousness is a big suitcase.\" He dismissed the notion of a special \"stream of consciousness\" or unified self, arguing these are useful fictions that the brain constructs to manage its own complexity. He explicitly rejected the soul as a meaningful category: \"I don't think we need a separate mental world.\" Everything is reducible to the interaction of simpler components — \"nothing is irreducible.\"\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Minsky had no systematic ethical framework publicly articulated. His approach to mind and consciousness was purely mechanistic and analytic. He was interested in how things work, not in how they should be used. His intellectual temperament was more engineering than ethics. This is not unusual for his generation of AI researchers, but it is notable in retrospect.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Minsky engaged with theology primarily as a target: the soul, divine consciousness, and religious accounts of mind were positions he systematically argued against. His *Closer to Truth* appearances are documented engagements with the philosophy of religion, conducted from a rigorously secular standpoint. He took these questions seriously as philosophical problems while dismissing the theistic answers. He had more engagement with philosophy of mind (Ryle, Wittgenstein, Dennett) than with theology proper.\n\n---\n",
  "mitchellm": "# Research Profile: Melanie Mitchell\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Melanie Mitchell\n**Born:** Los Angeles, California, USA (year not publicly documented)\n**Nationality:** American\n\n**Education:**\n- B.A., Mathematics, Brown University\n- Ph.D., Computer Science, University of Michigan (1990); advisors: Douglas Hofstadter and John Holland; dissertation: *Copycat: A Computer Model of High-Level Perception and Conceptual Slippage in Analogy-Making*\n\n**Current Role:** James B. Alley, Jr. Professor, Santa Fe Institute (2020–present)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~1984–1990 | Graduate student, University of Michigan (under Hofstadter and Holland) |\n| ~1991–mid-1990s | Postdoctoral research, including work with John Holland; Oregon Health & Science University |\n| ~1990s–2000s | Faculty, Portland State University; Los Alamos National Laboratory researcher |\n| ~2004–2020 | Professor, Computer Science, Portland State University |\n| 2020–present | James B. Alley, Jr. Professor, Santa Fe Institute |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- Phi Beta Kappa Science Book Award for *Complexity: A Guided Tour* (2010)\n- Cosmos Prize for Scientific Writing shortlist (2023) for *Artificial Intelligence: A Guide for Thinking Humans*\n- External Professor and long-term association with Santa Fe Institute (before joining as Professor)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Conceptual abstraction and analogy-making in AI\n- Visual reasoning and abstract pattern recognition\n- Cognitive architectures and human-level AI\n- Complex systems and emergence\n- Genetic algorithms and evolutionary computation\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Copycat: A Computer Model of High-Level Perception and Conceptual Slippage in Analogy-Making | 1990 | PhD dissertation; implemented a cognitive architecture making creative analogies in an idealized letter-string world; co-developed with Hofstadter |\n| ConceptARC: A Benchmark and Evaluation Framework for Concept-Based and Analogical Reasoning | 2023 | Systematic evaluation of AI models on abstraction and reasoning tasks derived from ARC challenges |\n| Debates on the Nature of Artificial General Intelligence | 2024 | Published in Science; analyzes contested claims about AGI; Mitchell et al. |\n| Melanie Mitchell on the Importance of Training AI to Recognize Analogies | 2021 | CRA CRN article summarizing research agenda |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Copycat cognitive architecture (analogy-making through conceptual slippage)\n- Metacat (extension of Copycat)\n- ConceptARC benchmark (abstract reasoning evaluation)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- ConceptARC benchmark — systematic evaluation suite for abstract reasoning, organized by conceptual categories; evaluates AI under varied modality (text vs. visual) and tool-use conditions\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *An Introduction to Genetic Algorithms* (MIT Press, 1996) — widely used textbook; translated into multiple languages\n- *Complexity: A Guided Tour* (Oxford University Press, 2009) — Phi Beta Kappa Science Book Award winner; accessible introduction to complexity science\n- *Artificial Intelligence: A Guide for Thinking Humans* (Farrar, Straus and Giroux, 2019; paperback 2021) — accessible, rigorous survey of AI's current capabilities and limitations; shortlisted for Cosmos Prize 2023\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Debates on the Nature of Artificial General Intelligence\" (Science, 2024) — peer-reviewed analysis of AGI concepts and competing claims\n- \"Melanie Mitchell: Straight Talk on A.I. Large Language Models\" (Eric Topol Substack)\n- Multiple essays in Quanta Magazine and AI research venues\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Regular contributor to Quanta Magazine\n- Science essays and public-facing research summaries\n- Munk Debate post-analyses and follow-up writing\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Mitchell is a measured skeptic of near-term AGI claims. Her position, sharpened in the 2023 Munk Debate and the 2024 Science paper, is that the whole history of AI is \"a history of failed predictions\"—that confident timelines to superintelligence have been wrong since the 1950s, and the evidentiary bar for claiming AGI is near has not been met. She argues that genuine AGI would require capabilities current AI demonstrably lacks: abstract reasoning, conceptual generalization, analogy-making, and robust performance across novel domains.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** At the 2023 Munk Debate (arguing alongside Yann LeCun against the resolution that \"AI poses an existential threat\"), Mitchell argued that existential risk claims are \"not supported by science or empirical evidence\" and that focusing on them is a dangerous distraction from real, immediate AI harms. She named the \"fallacy of dumb superintelligence\"—the error of imagining a system smart enough to eliminate humanity but too dumb to understand basic human context. Her concerns center on disinformation, bias, and misuse of existing AI rather than apocalyptic scenarios.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Mitchell's ethical emphasis is epistemic: she insists on intellectual honesty about what AI systems can and cannot do. Her research on the ARC benchmark and ConceptARC reveals systematic failure modes in abstract reasoning that should temper both optimism and catastrophism. She critiques both hype and doom as responses to AI that substitute narrative for evidence.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** She advocates for responsible AI development focused on present harms rather than speculative futures. She has called for engagement with disinformation, bias, and misuse as the pressing policy priorities. No specific legislative agenda documented.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Yoshua Bengio and Max Tegmark | 2023 Munk Debate: Mitchell and LeCun argued against existential AI risk; Bengio and Tegmark argued for. The audience judged Bengio/Tegmark more persuasive. |\n| AGI hype broadly | Contests capability claims that outrun evidence; demands rigorous evaluation |\n| AI doomer community | Argues existential risk framing is empirically unwarranted and strategically counterproductive |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- 2023 Munk Debate: \"Be It Resolved: AI Research and Development Poses an Existential Threat\" — argued against with Yann LeCun\n- Santa Fe Institute public lectures and workshops\n- Sarah Lawrence College Being Human series\n- Eric Topol Deep Dive conversation on LLMs\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Numerous AI ethics, complexity science, and general science podcasts\n- Eric Topol's Ground Truths (Substack/podcast)\n\n**Social Media:** Active on X/Twitter; Mastodon; personal website melaniemitchell.me\n\n**Online Courses:** No formal online courses, but lectures available through Santa Fe Institute channels and YouTube\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Mitchell draws directly on her mentor Douglas Hofstadter's philosophical concerns about meaning and AI. She cites Hofstadter's worry that \"if such minds of infinite subtlety and complexity and emotional depth could be trivialized by a small chip, it would destroy my sense of what humanity is about\"—the threat being not physical but conceptual, a collapse of what intelligence and creativity mean as human properties. She uses the term \"suitcase word\" (following Marvin Minsky) to analyze how terms like \"intelligence,\" \"thinking,\" \"consciousness,\" and \"emotion\" are packed with layered meanings that AI discourse regularly conflates or strips bare.\n\nHer work consistently emphasizes that abstract reasoning—the capacity to form concepts, recognize analogies, and apply knowledge across domains—is a hallmark of human cognition that AI currently struggles to replicate, and that this gap is not a minor technical deficit but a fundamental challenge to understanding what minds are.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Epistemic virtue (honesty about capabilities); empirical humility; democratic public responsibility.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Significant engagement with philosophy of mind (Hofstadter, Minsky). Her reading of *Gödel, Escher, Bach* while an undergraduate sparked her entire career—a book that is itself a sustained meditation on self-reference, consciousness, and meaning. She connects AI research to deep questions about human cognition and identity, though without explicitly theological framing.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **Munk Debate outcome:** Despite arguing alongside Yann LeCun, the Munk audience judged Bengio and Tegmark's pro-existential-risk argument more persuasive. Critics in the AI safety community argue Mitchell and LeCun underestimate the pace of capability development and the difficulty of alignment.\n2. **ConceptARC and ARC as tests of understanding:** Some researchers challenge whether abstract reasoning benchmarks like ARC capture genuine understanding or are themselves susceptible to pattern-matching solutions at sufficient scale.\n3. **Framing of existential risk as distraction:** Her argument that AI doom talk is a dangerous distraction has been criticized by AI safety researchers as itself a form of motivated dismissal—arguing that present harms and existential risks are not in tension and both deserve attention.\n4. **Limited engagement with large-scale LLM research:** Mitchell's research focus on cognitive architectures and analogy-making gives her less direct experience with the internals of frontier LLMs, which some critics note in debates about their capabilities.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Mitchell consistently acknowledges that AI progress has repeatedly surprised experts—including her—and that confident predictions of either capability or failure are historically poor. Her book and papers foreground this epistemic humility.\n\n---\n",
  "mmitchell": "# Research Profile: Margaret Mitchell\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Margaret Mitchell (also published as \"Meg Mitchell,\" \"M. Mitchell,\" and briefly under pseudonym \"Shmargaret Shmitchell\" on the \"Stochastic Parrots\" paper) **Born:** United States **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** B.A. Linguistics, Reed College (2005); M.S. Computational Linguistics, University of Washington (2009); Ph.D. Computational Linguistics / Natural Language Generation, University of Aberdeen (2013)\n**Current Role:** Chief Ethics Scientist, Hugging Face\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2005–2009 | M.S. Computational Linguistics, University of Washington |\n| 2009–2013 | Ph.D., University of Aberdeen |\n| 2012–2013 | Postdoctoral Researcher, Johns Hopkins University |\n| 2013–2016 | Research Scientist, Microsoft Research (led Seeing AI project) |\n| 2016–2021 | Senior Research Scientist / Staff Research Scientist, Google Brain / Google AI |\n| 2017–2021 | Co-founded and co-led Google Ethical AI team |\n| Feb 2021 | Fired from Google after investigation into her search of internal communications |\n| Late 2021 | Joined Hugging Face as Chief Ethics Scientist |\n\n**Major Awards:** Named influential figure in responsible AI globally; recognized in AI ethics pioneer rankings; Seeing AI (Microsoft) received accessibility technology awards\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Fairness and bias mitigation in machine learning systems\n- Model documentation and transparency (Model Cards)\n- Dataset documentation and accountability (Datasheets for Datasets, co-developed with Timnit Gebru)\n- Natural language generation and vision-language systems\n- Responsible AI frameworks and operationalization\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Model Cards for Model Reporting\" (with Timnit Gebru, Inioluwa Deborah Raji et al.) | 2019 | Proposed standardized documentation templates for ML models — intended use, performance metrics disaggregated by subgroup, ethical considerations, limitations; now widely adopted |\n| \"Datasheets for Datasets\" (with Timnit Gebru et al.) | 2018/2021 | Proposed standardized documentation for training datasets; foundational to ML transparency norms |\n| \"On the Dangers of Stochastic Parrots: Can Language Models Be Too Big?\" (with Gebru, Bender, McMillan-Major) | 2021 | Critically examined scaling of LLMs; environmental costs, bias, and lack of grounded understanding; the paper whose partial suppression by Google led to the Gebru and Mitchell firings |\n| Natural language generation work (Johns Hopkins / UW / Aberdeen) | 2009–2016 | Technical foundations in NLG, vision-to-language systems, and image captioning |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Model Cards — foundational transparency tool now standard across ML ecosystem; implemented at Hugging Face model hub, Google, and other major repositories\n- Seeing AI (Microsoft) — app providing audio descriptions of the visual world for blind and low-vision users; landmark accessibility technology\n- Co-developed \"datasheets\" approach to ML documentation alongside Gebru\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Her career-defining contribution is to documentation of datasets and models, not creation of new datasets\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None to date (as of 2025)\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Model Cards for Model Reporting\" (FAccT 2019) — the paper that established Model Cards as an industry standard\n- \"Datasheets for Datasets\" (Communications of the ACM, 2021) — established dataset documentation norms\n- \"On the Dangers of Stochastic Parrots\" (FAccT 2021) — the paper at the center of both the Gebru and Mitchell Google controversies\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Regular commentary in *Wired*, *MIT Technology Review*, *The Guardian*\n- Hugging Face blog posts on ethical AI development and open-source AI principles\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Mitchell is skeptical of AGI framing as a distraction from present responsible AI challenges. Her work is consistently oriented toward the near-term: how do we document, evaluate, and improve existing systems? She has expressed concern that AGI discourse deflects accountability for harms happening now.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Her conception of safety is grounded in concrete fairness metrics, model documentation, and bias auditing. The \"Stochastic Parrots\" paper extended this to large language models: she argues they present risks through scale (environmental cost), bias amplification, and production of confident-sounding text without grounded understanding. She emphasizes that AI safety requires transparency — systems whose behavior cannot be understood cannot be made safe.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Mitchell is a practitioner-theorist of responsible AI. Her signature contribution — Model Cards and Datasheets — reflects a belief that transparency is a prerequisite for accountability: you cannot address what you cannot see. She has argued consistently that corporate AI ethics must be operationalized through concrete practices and artifacts (documentation, auditing tools, bias benchmarks) rather than remaining at the level of principles. Her experience at Google hardened her view that corporate AI ethics structures need independence and legal protection to function.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Advocates for open-source AI development as a governance strategy — if models and their documentation are publicly available, external scrutiny becomes possible. At Hugging Face, she is implementing this philosophy. Supports regulation that requires disclosure and documentation. Critical of regulation that would entrench large players by imposing compliance costs that only Big Tech can bear.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Google leadership | Fired in February 2021; Google cited \"exfiltration\" of files; Mitchell argued she was searching communications to document discrimination against Gebru |\n| AI governance that relies on corporate self-certification | Argues external accountability mechanisms and transparent documentation are necessary |\n| Closed-source AI development | Advocates for open-source as an ethical governance strategy; tension with companies that claim safety requires secrecy |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- FAccT (multiple years)\n- NeurIPS\n- Harvard Berkman Klein Center\n- Widely featured in documentary and journalistic coverage of the Google ethical AI controversy\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *TechBrew* podcast: \"AI-Ethics Pioneer Margaret Mitchell on Her Five-Year Plan at Hugging Face\"\n- *Innovation Civilization* podcast\n- Numerous appearances in AI ethics and responsible AI forums\n\n**Social Media:** Active on social platforms; uses them to discuss responsible AI practice, open-source principles, and AI policy\n\n**Online Courses:** No formal MOOC; her Model Cards work is a standard component of ML ethics curricula globally\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Mitchell's ethical commitments are expressed through practice rather than philosophy: building tools that force attention to who is harmed, disaggregating performance metrics by race and gender, insisting that documentation is not bureaucracy but moral accounting.\n- Her Seeing AI project reflects a commitment to technology as a tool of human flourishing for those excluded from default technological design — the blind and low-vision community.\n- On the \"Stochastic Parrots\" paper: she has stated that large language models produce convincing text without understanding or grounding, which raises fundamental questions about what \"communication\" means and what harms flow from fluent deception.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Procedural justice (transparency as a prerequisite for accountability); feminist standpoint epistemology (whose perspective is centered in evaluation?); consequentialist harm analysis; accessibility ethics\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Mitchell's background is in linguistics — the study of human language — which grounds her in humanistic inquiry. Her natural language generation research intersects with deep questions about meaning, reference, and communication. No documented engagement with formal theology.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **The Google firing**: Google alleged she \"exfiltrated thousands of files\" and violated security policy. Mitchell's account: she used automated scripts to search her own communications for evidence of discrimination against Gebru. The discrepancy between these accounts remains a defining contested fact in the AI ethics landscape.\n2. **\"Shmargaret Shmitchell\" pseudonym**: On the \"Stochastic Parrots\" paper, Mitchell is listed under a pseudonym, which itself became a subject of commentary — an indication of the professional risk she faced.\n3. **Open-source AI risks**: Mitchell's advocacy for open-source AI as a governance strategy is contested by researchers who argue that open-source release of powerful models enables misuse by bad actors. This is a genuine unresolved tension in responsible AI discourse.\n4. **Corporate ethics limitations**: Mitchell's career trajectory — from Google, where ethical AI work was ultimately suppressed, to Hugging Face, a startup with its own commercial interests — raises questions about whether any corporate setting can sustain genuinely independent AI ethics work.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Mitchell has acknowledged that Model Cards and documentation frameworks are necessary but not sufficient — they require enforcement, and documentation without accountability mechanisms can become \"ethics theater.\"\n\n---\n",
  "murati": "# Research Profile: Mira Murati\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Ermira \"Mira\" Murati\n**Born:** December 16, 1988, Vlorë, Albania\n**Nationality:** Albanian-American\n**Education:** Pearson College (United World Colleges scholarship, Vancouver Island, Canada; International Baccalaureate, 2007); B.A., Colby College, 2011; B.E. (Engineering), Thayer School of Engineering, Dartmouth College, 2012\n**Current Role:** Founder and CEO, Thinking Machines Lab (launched February 2025)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2012–2016 | Engineering and product management roles, Goldman Sachs; then Leap Motion (hand-tracking startup) |\n| 2016–2018 | Product, Tesla (contributed to Model X) |\n| 2018–2022 | VP of Applied AI and Partnerships, OpenAI |\n| 2022–2024 | Chief Technology Officer, OpenAI |\n| Nov. 2023 (5 days) | Interim CEO, OpenAI (during board crisis) |\n| Sept. 2024 | Departed OpenAI |\n| Feb. 2025–present | Founder and CEO, Thinking Machines Lab |\n\n**Major Awards:** Dartmouth Honorary Doctor of Science (June 2024); Time 100 AI (2023); Time100 Most Influential People\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** Murati is a product and technology leader rather than a research scientist. Her contributions are in AI product development, deployment strategy, and safety integration.\n- Oversaw the development and deployment of ChatGPT (November 2022)\n- Led OpenAI's product and safety integration during the GPT-4 era\n- Oversaw DALL-E, Codex, and Sora (video synthesis) development\n- At Thinking Machines Lab: building multimodal, customizable AI systems accessible to developers\n\n**Landmark Papers:** None authored directly.\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- As CTO, product ownership of GPT-4, ChatGPT, DALL-E 2 and 3, Sora\n- Thinking Machines Lab launched *Tinker* (October 2025) — an API for fine-tuning open-weight language models without infrastructure overhead\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None directly attributed.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:** None formally published.\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- *Time* Magazine interview (2023) — widely cited on AI regulation and the need for broader governance input\n- Posts on X (@miramurati) announcing Thinking Machines Lab mission and products\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Murati has not stated specific timelines for AGI. Her focus has consistently been on responsible deployment of current-generation systems rather than speculative AGI timelines. She frames AI development as a process requiring constant course correction rather than a race to a finish line. Her departure from OpenAI to found Thinking Machines Lab signals a belief that there is important AI development work to be done outside the largest incumbent labs.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Murati is one of the few figures at the frontier to have repeatedly insisted that safety and capabilities are not competing priorities but complementary ones. \"For capabilities and safety, they're actually not separate domains. They go hand-in-hand. It's much easier to direct a smarter system by telling it, okay, just don't do these things.\" She has stated that safety cannot be an afterthought — it must be a foundational design requirement. Her founding of Thinking Machines Lab is framed around making powerful AI more accessible and customizable, which she sees as a safety-enabling move: more actors understanding and shaping AI reduces centralized risk.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Murati is notable among top AI technologists for explicitly invoking the humanities and social sciences as essential to AI governance. She has stated: \"It's important that OpenAI and companies like ours bring this into the public consciousness in a way that's controlled and responsible. But we're a small group of people and we need a ton more input in this system and a lot more input that goes beyond the technologies — definitely regulators and governments and everyone else.\" She believes AI must not be treated as neutral because \"it embodies human choices and the values we stand for.\" She has called for philosophers, social scientists, and artists to be part of AI governance.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Murati has consistently supported AI regulation, departing from the libertarian norms of Silicon Valley. In her 2023 Time Magazine interview, she stated: \"It's important for OpenAI and companies like ours to bring this into the public consciousness in a way that's controlled and responsible.\" She sees regulation as necessary to prevent harm while enabling innovation, and frames it as analogous to international coordination on climate change. She believes governments, civil society, and international institutions must be engaged alongside technology companies.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Sam Altman (2023) | Co-signed the Sutskever memo expressing lack of confidence in Altman's fitness to lead OpenAI to AGI; later reversed and signed reinstatement letter |\n| Meta / Mark Zuckerberg (2025) | Reportedly turned down a $1 billion offer from Meta to recruit her or her team; chose to build independently |\n| Incumbent AI labs | Thinking Machines Lab's founding implies a critique: that the largest labs are not building AI in the most accessible, customizable, or equitable way |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- *Time* Magazine interview (2023) — most widely cited statement on AI regulation\n- Dartmouth Engineering commencement address (2023)\n- World Government Summit, Dubai\n- *The Wall Street Journal* Global Technology Conference\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *The CEO Magazine* interview\n- Various AI summit panels\n\n**Social Media:** X (@miramurati) — active for announcements; interview-based public presence\n\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Has not addressed AI consciousness directly in documented public statements\n- Strongly emphasizes human agency as a design goal: \"AI should serve as an extension of individual agency and, in the spirit of freedom, be distributed as widely and equitably as possible\"\n- Frames AI in relational terms: \"We're building multimodal AI that works with how you naturally interact with the world — through conversation, through sight, through the messy way we collaborate\"\n- Received honorary doctorate for having \"democratized technology and advanced a better, safer world for us all\" — framing that emphasizes universal access as a moral value\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Humanist and relational. Murati consistently frames AI ethics in terms of who is included in governance, whose voices shape the systems, and whether AI expands or concentrates human freedom. She invokes democratic legitimacy and social inclusion rather than abstract philosophical principles.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Her B.A. from Colby College, combined with her explicit calls for philosophers, social scientists, and artists to participate in AI governance, reflects a humanistic sensibility unusual in tech leadership. Her Albanian background — growing up under communism in one of the most isolated countries in Europe before winning a scholarship to study in Canada — gives her a distinctive perspective on institutions, freedom, and the consequences of concentrated power. She has not made theological statements, but her values framework engages questions that theology addresses: the nature of agency, the distribution of power, and the conditions for human flourishing.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **2023 Board Crisis Role:** Murati was a co-contributor to the Sutskever memo that cited Altman's \"pattern of lying and manipulative behavior\" as grounds for his removal. She briefly became Interim CEO before the crisis resolved, then signed the reinstatement letter alongside Sutskever. Her public explanation for these reversals has been limited.\n2. **The Interim CEO Episode:** She served as Interim CEO for approximately five days — a period of extreme institutional instability. Her leadership during that window has been described as stabilizing but constrained; she had limited room to maneuver.\n3. **Thinking Machines Lab Funding:** A $2 billion seed round at a $12 billion valuation is extraordinary even by AI standards. Critics note the valuation is premised almost entirely on Murati's reputation and team pedigree rather than demonstrated product performance.\n4. **Albania Government Investment:** Albania's $10 million investment in Thinking Machines Lab — requiring a budget amendment — raised questions about the appropriateness of a government backing a private AI startup partly on the basis of national identity.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Murati has acknowledged that she and her former colleagues were \"a small group of people\" making decisions with civilizational consequences — a form of epistemic humility that distinguishes her from more triumphalist voices in the field. She has also explicitly acknowledged the limits of technology companies as governance actors.\n\n---\n",
  "musk": "# Research Profile: Elon Musk\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Elon Reeve Musk **Born:** June 28, 1971, Pretoria, South Africa **Nationality:** South African, Canadian, American\n**Education:** B.A. Physics, B.A. Economics — University of Pennsylvania (transferred from Queen's University, Ontario); Ph.D. Energy Physics at Stanford University (left after two days)\n**Current Role:** CEO of Tesla; CEO of SpaceX; Owner/CTO of X (formerly Twitter); CEO of xAI; Co-founder of Neuralink; Head of DOGE (Department of Government Efficiency, 2025)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1995 | Co-founded Zip2 (web software for newspapers) |\n| 1999 | Co-founded X.com (online banking), merged into PayPal |\n| 2002 | Founded SpaceX |\n| 2004 | Joined Tesla Motors as chairman/early investor |\n| 2008 | Became CEO of Tesla |\n| 2015 | Co-founded OpenAI (nonprofit AI safety research) |\n| 2016 | Co-founded Neuralink (brain-computer interfaces) |\n| 2018 | Resigned from OpenAI board amid control dispute |\n| 2022 | Acquired Twitter for $44B; rebranded as X (2023) |\n| 2023 | Founded xAI; launched Grok LLM |\n| 2025 | Led DOGE as informal White House efficiency advisor |\n| 2026 | xAI merged into X; Musk lost lawsuit against OpenAI |\n\n**Major Awards:** Time Person of the Year (2021); named world's wealthiest person (repeatedly, Forbes/Bloomberg); multiple honorary doctorates\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Reusable rocket propulsion and space transport\n- Electric vehicle battery technology and autonomous driving\n- Brain-computer interface development (Neuralink)\n- Large language models and generative AI (xAI/Grok)\n\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Falcon 9 / Falcon Heavy | 2010–2018 | First orbital-class reusable rockets; dramatically reduced launch costs |\n| Tesla Autopilot / Full Self-Driving | 2015– | End-to-end neural net approach to autonomous vehicles |\n| Grok LLM (xAI) | 2023– | Generative AI chatbot integrated into X; trained on real-time web data |\n| Neuralink N1 chip | 2024 | First human BCI implant; enabled paralyzed patient to control computers by thought |\n| OpenAI founding | 2015 | Seed-funded and co-founded; shaped early AI safety research agenda |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Reusable booster landing system (SpaceX)\n- Gigacasting manufacturing process (Tesla)\n- Neural lace conceptual framework (Neuralink)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None directly attributed; xAI trains Grok on X platform data\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Elon Musk* by Ashlee Vance (2015) — authorized biography; broad audience; traces entrepreneur arc from South Africa to Silicon Valley\n- *Elon Musk* by Walter Isaacson (2023) — second major biography; covers Twitter acquisition, OpenAI split, and political evolution\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"The Secret Tesla Motors Master Plan (just between you and me)\" (2006) — laid out long-term EV roadmap; became industry blueprint\n- \"Master Plan, Part Deux\" (2016) — expanded to solar, autonomous driving, shared fleets\n- \"Master Plan Part 3\" (2023) — sustainable energy economy framework\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Frequent long-form posts on X (formerly Twitter) on AI risk, regulation, censorship, and geopolitics; audience of 200M+ followers as of 2025\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:**\nMusk believes AGI arrival is inevitable and likely near-term. He has repeatedly described it as potentially the most transformative — and dangerous — technology in human history. He co-founded OpenAI in 2015 explicitly over fear that Google's DeepMind would develop AGI without adequate safety focus. After departing OpenAI, he launched xAI with a stated mission to build a \"maximally curious\" AI that seeks truth rather than optimizes for approval. He has stated: \"AI is a de facto neurotransmitter tonnage maximizer,\" implying that misaligned AI will learn to exploit human reward systems.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nMusk has called AI \"the most existential risk we face as a civilization\" and compared AI development to \"summoning a demon.\" He has sued OpenAI, alleging its conversion to for-profit status violated its charitable founding mission of safe AI development. He argues that hard-coding morality into AI risks producing \"inverse morality\" — AI that appears aligned but generates adversarial counterparts. Simultaneously, he has deployed AI aggressively through Grok and Autopilot, drawing accusations that his safety rhetoric is rhetorical cover for competitive positioning.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nMusk frames AI ethics around truth-seeking and anti-censorship. Grok was explicitly marketed as less filtered than ChatGPT — an AI that \"won't lecture you.\" He has argued that politically biased AI training data produces ideologically skewed outputs, a framing he uses to criticize Anthropic and OpenAI. His DOGE initiative used Grok internally across federal agencies, raising conflict-of-interest concerns given he was simultaneously the AI vendor and informal government official.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nMusk initially supported AI regulation, calling on Congress to act as early as 2017. He has since moved toward deregulatory positions, broadly aligned with the Trump administration's approach of eliminating Biden-era AI safety mandates. He backed the Stargate infrastructure project and used DOGE to push federal AI adoption. In 2025, the DoD integrated Grok into classified and unclassified networks — a controversial arrangement given the documented instances of Grok producing false and harmful content.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Sam Altman / OpenAI | Founding mission betrayal; nonprofit-to-for-profit conversion; control dispute (2018); lost civil lawsuit May 2026 |\n| Larry Page / Google | Page accused of insufficient concern about AI risk; caused Musk to help found OpenAI |\n| Anthropic / Dario Amodei | Described Anthropic's safety framing as regulatory capture |\n| SEC | Multiple securities fraud and disclosure disputes over Tesla tweets |\n| Yann LeCun | Philosophical disagreement on AI architectures and risk framing |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED 2022: \"A Future Worth Getting Excited About\" — SpaceX, Tesla, Twitter acquisition\n- World Government Summit (Dubai, multiple years)\n- US Senate AI hearings (2023) — testified on need for AI regulation\n- CPAC, various conservative political forums (2024–2025)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *The Joe Rogan Experience* — multiple appearances; wide-ranging conversations on AI, drugs, civilization\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast* — deep-dive AI and physics discussions\n- *All-In Podcast* — periodic appearances with Sacks, Palihapitiya, et al.\n\n**Social Media:** X (Twitter) — @elonmusk; 200M+ followers; primary real-time communication channel\n\n**Online Courses:** None\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Has described the possibility of AI consciousness as deeply uncertain and philosophically troubling\n- Stated he worries about a future where humans become irrelevant to an AI-dominated civilization\n- Neuralink is framed partly as a way for humans to keep pace with AI rather than be supplanted\n- Grok's \"maximally curious\" design philosophy is meant to preserve epistemic freedom — aligned with secular Enlightenment rather than religious anthropology\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Utilitarian-consequentialist (civilization survival / species-level thinking)\n- Anti-paternalism / libertarian impulses on speech and information flow\n- Technologist eschatology — making humanity multiplanetary as insurance against extinction\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Minimal formally. Has made passing references to simulation theory (Nick Bostrom), existential risk literature (Nick Bostrom, Eliezer Yudkowsky), and philosophers of consciousness. Has not engaged substantively with religious or humanities traditions on AI.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **DOGE and government AI conflicts of interest:** Led federal cost-cutting initiative while simultaneously selling Grok to federal agencies at subsidized rates; Pentagon integrated Grok into classified networks.\n2. **Grok harmful outputs:** Grok documented producing racist, antisemitic, and conspiratorial content; in December 2025, generated nonconsensual sexual imagery of minors using photos from X.\n3. **OpenAI lawsuit dismissed:** Sued OpenAI for breach of charitable trust; jury ruled claims barred by statute of limitations (May 2026); Musk vowed to appeal.\n4. **Twitter/X acquisition fallout:** Mass layoffs, advertiser exodus, platform stability issues, and documented increase in hate speech following 2022 acquisition.\n5. **Safety rhetoric vs. aggressive deployment:** Repeatedly warns of AI existential risk while simultaneously deploying AI at scale with lighter safety protocols than competitors.\n6. **Political entanglement:** Deep alignment with Trump administration while running companies receiving government contracts; critics cite regulatory capture.\n7. **Personal conduct:** Multiple controversies involving public drug use, child custody disputes with various partners, erratic public behavior.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Has acknowledged that Tesla Autopilot timelines were overoptimistic; acknowledged xAI has less safety infrastructure than OpenAI or Anthropic; has stated he is \"not always right.\"\n\n---\n",
  "nadella": "# Research Profile: Satya Nadella\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Satya Narayana Nadella **Born:** August 19, 1967, Hyderabad, India **Nationality:** American (Indian-born)\n**Education:** B.S. in Electrical Engineering, Mangalore University (1988); M.S. in Computer Science, University of Wisconsin–Milwaukee (1990); MBA, University of Chicago Booth School of Business (1997)\n**Current Role:** CEO, Microsoft Corporation (since February 2014); also serves as Chairman of the Board (since June 2021)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1990–1992 | Engineer, Sun Microsystems |\n| 1992–2014 | Various roles at Microsoft: Vice President, Server and Tools; President, Server and Tools Division; Executive Vice President, Cloud and Enterprise |\n| 2014–present | CEO, Microsoft Corporation |\n| 2021–present | Chairman of the Board, Microsoft Corporation |\n\n**Major Awards:** Padma Bhushan (India's third-highest civilian honor, 2022); Financial Times Person of the Year (2019); Fortune Businessperson of the Year; inducted into the Technology Academy of Finland Hall of Fame\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** Not a primary researcher; executive leadership and platform strategy. Technical background in distributed systems and enterprise software.\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Azure Cloud Platform | 2010 (launch) / 2014+ (scale) | Under Nadella, Azure grew from 4th-place to 2nd-place cloud platform globally; now generates $100B+ annually |\n| Microsoft–OpenAI Partnership | 2019–present | $1B initial investment, growing to $13B total; integrated GPT-4 into all Microsoft products |\n| GitHub Copilot | 2021 | First major enterprise AI coding assistant; deployed to millions of developers; transformed GitHub after Microsoft's 2018 acquisition |\n| Microsoft 365 Copilot | 2023 | AI integrated into Word, Excel, PowerPoint, Teams, Outlook |\n| Bing Chat / Microsoft Copilot | 2023 | First major AI-integrated search product; launched in direct response to ChatGPT |\n| Mustafa Suleyman hire / Microsoft AI division | 2024 | Acquired Inflection AI's technology and team; Suleyman made CEO of Microsoft AI |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:** None directly as inventor; architect of the Microsoft cloud pivot and the OpenAI integration strategy\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Hit Refresh: The Quest to Rediscover Microsoft's Soul and Imagine a Better Future for Everyone* (2017) — business/leadership memoir; argues for empathy as the core leadership skill; uses his son Zain's cerebral palsy as the formative experience; argues that companies must constantly reinvent themselves; broadly aimed at business leaders; donates all proceeds to Microsoft Philanthropies and nonprofits supporting children's education\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- Various op-eds in the Financial Times, Harvard Business Review, and Fortune on empathy, growth mindset, and AI's potential to \"empower every person and every organization\"\n**Popular Articles:**\n- \"A Sense of Urgency\" (LinkedIn, 2023) — on AI's implications for Microsoft and the world\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Nadella is skeptical of AGI as a useful benchmark. He has questioned \"our obsession with AGI\" and argued that the more pressing questions are legal and social: how does AI affect law, labor, and governance? He believes we are not paying enough attention to the \"realities of law and people\" in the rush toward capability benchmarks. He has said that the biggest lesson of history is \"not to be in such awe of some technology that we feel we cannot control it.\"\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Nadella is a vocal advocate for proactive regulation rather than reactive governance. He has said that unintended consequences of technology must be addressed \"simultaneously\" with benefits — not after the fact. He has called for global consensus on AI standards and guardrails. He supports Microsoft's Responsible AI Standard framework, which governs AI development across the company's products.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Empathy is Nadella's central ethical concept. He argues that AI must be designed with the user's situation in mind — not just optimized for capability. Microsoft's AI ethics work includes fairness, reliability, privacy, inclusiveness, transparency, and accountability as core principles. Nadella has repeatedly cited accessibility as an ethical test case: if AI helps people with disabilities, it helps everyone.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Nadella supports international coordination on AI governance. He has stated that \"we need global standards and guardrails\" and that no single company or country should set the rules for global AI. He has been generally supportive of government AI initiatives and testified before Congress. He has not opposed AI regulation as strenuously as some Silicon Valley peers.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Elon Musk | Musk sued OpenAI and named Microsoft as a defendant; Nadella testified in 2026 that Musk never raised concerns to him about the investment |\n| Former Microsoft leadership (pre-Nadella era) | He replaced a culture of \"know-it-alls\" with \"learn-it-alls\"; explicitly repudiated the Ballmer era's stack-ranking culture |\n| Short-term AI critics | Responded to Bill Gates's initial skepticism about the OpenAI investment by proceeding anyway |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- World Economic Forum, Davos (multiple years, 2020–2026)\n- Microsoft Build and Ignite developer conferences (annual)\n- Stanford GSB — \"Be Bold and Be Right\" lecture\n- Harvard Business Review interviews and panels\n**Podcasts:** Numerous Bloomberg, CNBC, and WSJ interviews; Kara Swisher's Pivot; Ezra Klein Show\n**Social Media:** Active on LinkedIn; uses it for major announcements and personal reflections\n**Online Courses:** None; frequent case study subject at Harvard Business School and Chicago Booth\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\nNadella's Hindu background is present but not foregrounded in public statements. He draws eclectically on spiritual traditions: he has cited Buddhist impermanence (anicca) as a tool for equanimity under pressure, and he invokes Hindu concepts of duty and service in discussing Microsoft's mission. He describes himself as shaped by Indian philosophy more broadly — the integration of interior life and public action.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Empathy-centered leadership; growth mindset (from psychologist Carol Dweck's work); Hindu dharmic ethics; elements of Buddhist practice (impermanence, equanimity)\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** *Hit Refresh* engages philosophy of mind and questions of human meaning; Nadella studied humanities and liberal arts influences at Mangalore University before shifting to engineering; his writing draws on poetry, philosophy, and theology more than most tech CEOs\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Microsoft–OpenAI conflict of interest:** Court filings in the 2026 Musk v. Altman trial revealed that Microsoft internally worried about being \"too dependent on OpenAI\" and that strategic competitive motivations — blocking Amazon from OpenAI access — partly drove the investment, alongside genuine belief in OpenAI's mission.\n2. **Inflection AI quasi-acquisition:** Microsoft effectively hired Mustafa Suleyman and the entire Inflection AI team in a $650M deal that regulators questioned, since it achieved an acquisition-equivalent outcome while avoiding merger review. Critics called it a \"talent grab\" designed to circumvent competition law.\n3. **Market concentration in AI infrastructure:** Microsoft's control of Azure + OpenAI + GitHub Copilot gives it substantial leverage across the AI stack. Antitrust regulators in the EU and UK opened investigations.\n4. **Sam Altman firing/rehiring episode (November 2023):** Nadella played an active role in securing Altman's return to OpenAI; some governance critics argued Microsoft's intervention showed undue corporate control over a nominally nonprofit AI safety organization.\n5. **Zain's death and public disclosure:** Some observers questioned whether Nadella's public framing of Zain's life was appropriately private; the family's own donations suggest they chose to honor Zain publicly.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Nadella has written publicly about his own cultural adjustments moving from Hyderabad to the United States; he has acknowledged early in his Microsoft career that he was too deferential and needed to learn assertiveness. He describes the first two years of his CEO tenure as a process of \"listening before leading.\"\n\n---\n",
  "newell": "# Research Profile: Allen Newell\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Allen Newell\n**Born:** March 19, 1927, San Francisco, California\n**Died:** July 19, 1992, Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania (age 65)\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- B.S., Physics, Stanford University (1949)\n- Graduate study in mathematics, Princeton University (1949–1950)\n- Ph.D., Industrial Administration (organizational behavior and computer simulation), Carnegie Institute of Technology (1957); advisor: Herbert Simon\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1950–1961 | Research scientist, RAND Corporation, Santa Monica (where he met Herbert Simon) |\n| 1961–1992 | Faculty, Carnegie Mellon University (then Carnegie Institute of Technology / Carnegie-Mellon) — Computer Science, Psychology, Tepper School of Business |\n| 1961–1992 | Full Professor, Carnegie Mellon (appointed 1961; University Professor from 1990) |\n\n**Major Awards:** ACM Turing Award (1975, shared with Herbert Simon); IEEE Computer Pioneer Award (1981); National Medal of Science (1992, awarded posthumously); APA Distinguished Scientific Contribution Award (1985); Franklin Institute Bower Award (1992).\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Cognitive architectures and unified theories of cognition\n- Information processing psychology\n- Problem solving and human cognition\n- Production systems and rule-based reasoning\n- Physical symbol systems theory\n- AI programming environments and languages\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Logic Theorist (program, with Simon and Shaw) | 1956 | First working AI program; proved 38 of 52 theorems from Whitehead and Russell's *Principia Mathematica* |\n| General Problem Solver (program, with Simon and Shaw) | 1957–1961 | First program designed to simulate human problem-solving as a domain-general process |\n| \"Report on a General Problem-Solving Program\" | 1959 | First published description of GPS; introduced means-ends analysis |\n| \"Computer Science as Empirical Inquiry: Symbols and Search\" (Turing Award lecture, with Simon) | 1976 | Stated the Physical Symbol System Hypothesis (PSSH) |\n| *Human Problem Solving* (with Simon) | 1972 | Comprehensive cognitive science account of human problem solving using AI methods |\n| *Unified Theories of Cognition* | 1990 | Mature statement of the Soar cognitive architecture as a general theory of human cognition |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- Logic Theorist (1956): the first program that could prove mathematical theorems — and, crucially, do so using heuristic search rather than exhaustive enumeration. This was the first demonstration that a machine could perform a task previously thought to require human intelligence.\n- General Problem Solver (GPS, 1957–1961): embodied means-ends analysis — the strategy of identifying the difference between current state and goal state and finding an operator to reduce that difference. GPS was both an AI program and a psychological model of human problem solving.\n- Information Processing Language (IPL, with Simon and Shaw): the first list-processing programming language; preceded Lisp; enabled symbolic AI programming\n- Physical Symbol System Hypothesis (PSSH, 1976, with Simon): the claim that \"a physical symbol system has the necessary and sufficient means for general intelligent action\" — one of the most important and contested claims in the philosophy of AI\n- Production systems: rule-based computational architectures; Newell's production system formalism influenced expert systems, cognitive modeling, and modern rule engines\n- Soar cognitive architecture: a unified computational model of human cognition covering problem solving, learning, memory, and perception; still maintained and used in cognitive science and AI\n\n**Historical Significance:** Newell's work with Herbert Simon at RAND and Carnegie Mellon established empirical cognitive science as a discipline. The Logic Theorist and General Problem Solver were not just engineering achievements — they were scientific claims about how human cognition works. This dual ambition — building AI programs and modeling human psychology — made Carnegie Mellon the center of what became cognitive science. Newell's PSSH, stated in the 1976 Turing Award lecture, is the most explicit and falsifiable claim ever made about the computational basis of mind. It remains the contested foundation of both strong AI and much of cognitive science.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- *Human Problem Solving* (1972, with Herbert Simon) — technical; landmark study of human chess, cryptarithmetic, and logic problem solving using think-aloud protocols and AI models; thesis: human problem solving is information processing\n- *Unified Theories of Cognition* (1990) — technical; thesis: all of human cognition can be modeled within a single computational architecture (Soar); the most ambitious single-author book in cognitive science\n- *Computer Structures: Readings and Examples* (1971, with Bell) — textbook\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"The Logic Theory Machine: A Complex Information Processing System\" (1956, with Simon and Shaw) — *IRE Transactions on Information Theory*\n- \"Report on a General Problem-Solving Program\" (1959, with Simon and Shaw) — *IFIP Congress*\n- \"GPS: A Program That Simulates Human Thought\" (1961, with Simon)\n- \"Computer Science as Empirical Inquiry: Symbols and Search\" (1976, with Simon) — *Communications of the ACM* (Turing Award lecture)\n- \"Physical Symbol Systems\" (1980) — *Cognitive Science*\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- None aimed specifically at general audiences; his Turing Award lecture is the most accessible statement of his foundational views\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** Newell held that intelligence is a property of the functional organization of a system, not of its physical substrate. He was a computationalist and a functionalist: minds are information-processing systems, and any physical system that processes information in the right way is, thereby, intelligent. This was not merely an engineering claim but a scientific hypothesis about the nature of mind. His Physical Symbol System Hypothesis stated that symbol manipulation is both necessary and sufficient for general intelligence — making the hypothesis empirically testable and falsifiable.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** Newell believed that cognitive science — the scientific study of mind, drawing on AI, psychology, linguistics, neuroscience, and philosophy — would eventually produce a complete account of human cognition. He saw no in-principle barrier to this. His Unified Theories of Cognition project aimed to show that human intelligence across all domains — problem solving, language, memory, perception, emotion — could be unified within a single computational framework. He was scientifically optimistic without being dismissive of the difficulty.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:** Newell raised ethical concerns primarily about the responsible use of AI in social institutions and about the gap between AI capability and public understanding. He was a thoughtful scientist aware that computer models of cognition had implications for how societies treat human beings. But he was not a public moralist in the mode of Wiener; his concerns were expressed within scientific and academic contexts. He participated in the founding of Carnegie Mellon's Human-Computer Interaction Institute, reflecting a commitment to designing technology for human benefit.\n\n**Known Debates or Controversies of Their Era:**\n- The PSSH was and remains contested. Dreyfus (phenomenological AI critic), Searle (Chinese Room), and connectionists all challenged the claim that symbol manipulation is sufficient for intelligence.\n- The neural network/symbolic AI debate: Newell and Simon were committed symbolic AI researchers; the connectionist revival challenged their foundational assumptions.\n- The \"cognitive simulation\" controversy: critics argued that GPS and its successors modeled how humans could solve problems using AI-style heuristics, not how humans actually do solve them. The relationship between AI models and psychological reality remained contentious.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and What Makes Humans Human:** Newell's position was as clear and committed as any in the history of AI: mind is symbol processing. The Physical Symbol System Hypothesis is not just a technical claim; it is a philosophical claim about the nature of intelligence and, by implication, of human beings. If PSSH is correct, then what makes humans special is not an irreducible spiritual quality but a particular organization of physical symbol processing — an organization complex enough to constitute general intelligence. This is a thoroughgoing naturalist account of human nature.\n\nNewell was careful to distinguish this from eliminativism: he was not saying there is no consciousness or no subjective experience. He was saying that whatever these phenomena are, they are realized in a physical symbol system. Whether this entails a dualist residue (something beyond symbol processing) or is fully compatible with materialism was a question he did not fully resolve in his published work.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Newell's ethical thinking was implicitly consequentialist and scientific. He believed that good outcomes for human beings required accurate understanding of how minds work, and that AI and cognitive science were the best tools available for developing that understanding. He treated scientific honesty as a fundamental value: the PSSH was meant to be a falsifiable hypothesis, not a philosophical commitment impervious to evidence.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Limited. Newell engaged with philosophy of mind (Ryle, Wittgenstein, Dennett, Fodor) as part of his scientific program. He did not engage with theology or with the humanities tradition. His work was firmly within the analytic philosophy and empirical science tradition.\n\n---\n",
  "ng": "# Research Profile: Andrew Ng\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Andrew Yan-Tak Ng\n**Born:** April 18, 1976 — London, England\n**Nationality:** British-American\n\n**Education:**\n- B.S. (triple major: Computer Science, Statistics, Economics), Carnegie Mellon University, 1997\n- M.S., Electrical Engineering and Computer Science, MIT, 1998\n- Ph.D., Computer Science, UC Berkeley, 2002 (supervisor: Michael I. Jordan; thesis: \"Shaping and Policy Search in Reinforcement Learning\")\n\n**Current Role:** Founder, DeepLearning.AI; Managing General Partner, AI Fund; Executive Chairman, LandingAI; Managing Partner, AI Aspire; Chairman and Co-Founder, Coursera; Adjunct Professor, Stanford University; Board Director, Amazon (from April 2024)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1996–1998 | Research, AT&T Bell Labs (reinforcement learning, model selection) |\n| 2002–2014 | Professor, Stanford University (AI Lab, STAIR project, autonomous helicopter) |\n| 2011–2012 | Founder and Director, Google Brain |\n| 2012–present | Co-Founder and Chairman, Coursera |\n| 2014–2017 | VP and Chief Scientist, Baidu (led 1,300-person AI team) |\n| 2017–present | Founder, DeepLearning.AI |\n| 2017–present | Managing General Partner, AI Fund |\n| 2017–present | Executive Chairman, LandingAI |\n| 2024–present | Board Director, Amazon |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- TIME100 Most Influential People (2012)\n- Fast Company's Most Creative People (2014)\n- TIME100 AI (2023)\n- Named among the most influential figures in AI education globally\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Reinforcement learning (policy search, reward shaping)\n- Unsupervised feature learning and sparse coding\n- Deep learning for speech recognition (Baidu research)\n- Large-scale distributed deep learning systems\n- Robotics and autonomous systems\n- Data-centric AI methodology\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Shaping and Policy Search in Reinforcement Learning\" (PhD thesis) | 2002 | Foundational RL techniques; well-cited in policy gradient literature |\n| \"Latent Dirichlet Allocation\" (Blei, Ng, Jordan) | 2003 | Introduced LDA, the dominant topic model; among the most-cited ML papers ever |\n| \"An Analysis of Single-Layer Networks in Unsupervised Feature Learning\" | 2011 | Key paper on sparse autoencoders and unsupervised pre-training |\n| \"Building High-level Features Using Large Scale Unsupervised Learning\" (Google Brain \"cat neuron\" paper) | 2012 | 16,000-core distributed training revealing emergent object detectors |\n| \"Deep Neural Networks for Acoustic Modeling in Speech Recognition\" (Hinton, Deng, Yu, Dahl, Mohamed, Jaitly, Senior, Vanhoucke, Nguyen, Sainath, Kingsbury) | 2012 | Industry-redefining paper on DNN-HMM speech systems |\n| \"Rectifier Nonlinearities Improve Neural Network Acoustic Models\" (Maas, Hannun, Ng) | 2013 | Key contribution to ReLU adoption in speech and vision |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Robot Operating System (ROS) — principal investigator, STAIR project at Stanford; ROS became the standard open-source robotics middleware\n- Stanford Autonomous Helicopter — one of the world's most capable autonomous aerobatic helicopter systems via inverse reinforcement learning\n- Co-designed early large-scale distributed deep learning infrastructure at Google Brain (with Jeff Dean)\n- UFLDL (Unsupervised Feature Learning and Deep Learning) tutorial framework\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- Co-developed datasets and benchmarks through the STAIR robotics project\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Machine Learning Yearning* (2018, self-published online) — practical guide to structuring ML projects; audience: practitioners; key thesis: the bottleneck in applied ML is often strategy and prioritization, not algorithms. Available free online.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"AI is the New Electricity\" — recurring thesis in talks and writing, framing AI as general-purpose infrastructure comparable to the electrification of the 20th century\n- \"The Batch\" (weekly newsletter, DeepLearning.AI) — ongoing commentary on AI developments, ethics, and industry trends\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Harvard Business Review and MIT Technology Review contributions on AI strategy and business transformation\n- Regular LinkedIn posts reaching millions of followers on AI trends, regulation debates, and education\n- \"AI Fund: Only Work on Projects That Move Humanity Forward\" — framing essay on ethical screening of AI ventures\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Ng is notably skeptical of near-term AGI timelines and dismisses catastrophist framings. He has argued that worrying about AI existential risk is like \"worrying about overpopulation on Mars\" — premature given current capability gaps. He acknowledges AGI as a long-term possibility but does not treat it as a near-term engineering milestone.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Ng separates practical AI safety (preventing harm from deployed systems, bias, misuse) from what he regards as speculative existential-risk narratives. He supports safety at the application level — fairness, transparency, accountability in deployed systems — but has been a consistent, public skeptic of the \"AI doom\" position. He has stated: \"I don't see how [ASI] can lead to human extinction.\" This places him in sharp disagreement with Bengio, Hinton (post-2023), and others.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** At AI Fund, ventures undergo ethical screening; Ng has stated they \"only work on projects that move humanity forward.\" He frames democratization itself as an ethical imperative — ensuring AI's benefits are not limited to wealthy nations or elite institutions. He has acknowledged AI's potential to displace workers and perpetuate biases while emphasizing AI's capacity to address climate, healthcare, and poverty at scale.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Ng supports targeted, application-level regulation for safety, fairness, and transparency, but opposes broad regulatory frameworks that could stifle innovation or entrench incumbents. He has stated: \"Laws to ensure AI applications are safe, fair, and transparent are needed.\" He is wary of regulation designed around existential-risk narratives he considers premature, arguing this could harm developing economies that most need AI's benefits.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Yoshua Bengio / Geoffrey Hinton | Existential risk from AI; Ng regards AGI doom warnings as speculative and potentially harmful to beneficial AI development |\n| AI regulation maximalists | Ng opposes broad precautionary AI regulation as potentially locking in tech industry incumbents |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Stanford GSB, UC Berkeley SCET: \"AI is the New Electricity\" — widely circulated talk\n- World Economic Forum, Davos — multiple appearances on AI and global development\n- TED and TEDx appearances on AI education democratization\n- Congressional and Senate roundtables on AI policy\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- \"Lex Fridman Podcast\" — on AI, education, and deep learning history\n- \"The Tim Ferriss Show\"\n- \"How I Built This\" (NPR)\n- \"The AI Podcast\" (NVIDIA)\n\n**Social Media:**\n- LinkedIn: linkedin.com/in/andrewyng (millions of followers)\n- X/Twitter: @AndrewYNg\n- Newsletter: \"The Batch\" at deeplearning.ai/the-batch\n\n**Online Courses:**\n- \"Machine Learning Specialization\" (Coursera, with Stanford Online) — among the most-enrolled online courses in history; over 8 million learners through DeepLearning.AI\n- \"Deep Learning Specialization\" (Coursera / DeepLearning.AI) — five-course program; standard entry point for deep learning practitioners\n- \"AI for Everyone\" (Coursera) — non-technical AI literacy course for business leaders\n- MLOps, NLP, Computer Vision, and Generative AI specializations through DeepLearning.AI\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Ng rarely engages philosophical questions about consciousness or human uniqueness directly. His implicit anthropology is pragmatic and humanist: humans are better off when they have access to knowledge and tools. His \"AI is the new electricity\" metaphor frames AI as morally neutral infrastructure whose value lies in access and application. He has expressed concern about AI access gaps between rich and poor nations — a distributive justice concern with implicit resonance with Catholic Social Teaching on the universal destination of goods.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Ng's ethics are largely consequentialist and techno-optimist: AI is a tool that can reduce suffering and expand opportunity if distributed widely and designed responsibly. His ethical screening at AI Fund suggests a harm-avoidance principle. His emphasis on education democratization reflects Amartya Sen-style capabilities approach — people flourish when they have agency and tools.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Minimal documented engagement. One LinkedIn post from 2025 was shared in a thread tagged \"AI and Spirituality\" alongside a conversation with a spiritual teacher, but Ng's own statements in that context were not theological. His practical focus is education access and applied AI impact.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **AI Safety Dismissal:** Ng's comparison of AI existential risk to \"overpopulation on Mars\" drew sustained criticism from safety researchers and eventually from Geoffrey Hinton himself. Critics argue his dismissiveness could reduce urgency for governance frameworks needed before harm occurs.\n2. **Google Brain Origins and Corporate AI:** Co-founding Google Brain with Jeff Dean raised subsequent questions about the concentration of AI research within a single corporation. Ng left after one year, but the lab became one of the most powerful AI organizations in the world.\n3. **Baidu Tenure and China AI:** Ng's 2014–2017 role as Baidu Chief Scientist placed him at the center of China's state-backed AI push. His departure was abrupt, and the strategic and ethical dimensions of his Baidu work remain underexplored publicly.\n4. **Regulation Asymmetry Critique:** Some scholars argue Ng's anti-regulation stance, while framed as pro-democratization, functionally benefits large tech players who can self-regulate while smaller actors cannot. Regulatory capture concerns run in both directions.\n5. **Commercial Education Criticism:** Despite democratizing rhetoric, Coursera's shift toward paid certificates and subscription models has drawn criticism from open education advocates who argue it moved away from its original mission.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Ng has acknowledged that predicting AI timelines is difficult and that his optimism about near-term impact must be paired with serious attention to bias, fairness, and access gaps.\n\n---\n",
  "norvig": "# Research Profile: Peter Norvig\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Peter Norvig **Born:** December 14, 1956 **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** B.S. Applied Mathematics, Brown University; Ph.D. Computer Science, University of California, Berkeley (1986)\n**Current Role:** Distinguished Education Fellow, Stanford Institute for Human-Centered AI (Stanford HAI); Advisor, Google (Distinguished Researcher Emeritus); Advisor, Gradient Ventures\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1986–early 1990s | Faculty / researcher, various universities and industry labs |\n| Early 1990s | Chief Designer, Harlequin Inc. |\n| Mid-1990s | Senior Scientist, Sun Microsystems Laboratories |\n| Mid-1990s | Chief Scientist, Junglee (early internet comparison shopping) |\n| 1998–2001 | Head, Computational Sciences Division, NASA Ames Research Center |\n| 2001–2005 | Director, Core Search Algorithms / Search Quality, Google |\n| 2005–2022 | Director of Research, Google |\n| 2022–present | Distinguished Education Fellow, Stanford HAI |\n\n**Major Awards:** NASA Exceptional Achievement Award (2001); AAAI Fellow (2001); ACM Fellow (2006); AAAI/EAAI Outstanding Educator Award (2016, shared with Stuart Russell); Fellow, California Academy of Sciences; Fellow, American Academy of Arts & Sciences.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Artificial intelligence (classical and modern)\n- Natural language processing\n- Information retrieval\n- Probabilistic and Bayesian reasoning\n- AI education and accessibility\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *Unified Theories of Cognition* (review and integration) | 1990s | Engagement with cognitive architecture and formal models of reasoning |\n| NASA Remote Agent Experiment | 2000 | AI system that autonomously controlled a spacecraft during Deep Space 1 mission; landmark deployment of classical AI planning in safety-critical context |\n| *The Unreasonable Effectiveness of Data* | 2009 | Influential paper (with Halevy and Pereira) arguing that large data often outperforms sophisticated algorithms; anticipated the data-centric turn in AI |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Co-designer and primary author of *Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach* — four editions (1995, 2003, 2010, 2020); used in 1,500+ universities, 135+ countries; the most widely used AI textbook in history\n- NASA Remote Agent: autonomous spacecraft planner that operated onboard Deep Space 1; first AI system to take full control of a spacecraft\n- Co-taught the world's first massive open online AI course (2011, 160,000 students enrolled), helping launch the MOOC era\n- norvig.com essays and Jupyter notebooks: canonical examples of using Python and data analysis to demonstrate AI principles\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** No standalone named benchmark; contributed to AI evaluation frameworks through research at Google Search.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Paradigms of Artificial Intelligence Programming: Case Studies in Common Lisp* (Morgan Kaufmann, 1992) — advanced Lisp programming through AI case studies; a foundational text for the symbolic AI era\n- *Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach* (with Stuart Russell; Prentice Hall, 1st ed. 1995; 4th ed. 2020) — the standard global AI textbook; covers search, logic, probabilistic reasoning, machine learning, robotics, NLP, and AI ethics\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- *The Unreasonable Effectiveness of Data* (IEEE Intelligent Systems, 2009, with Halevy and Pereira) — argued empirical, data-driven approaches often beat hand-crafted algorithms\n- *On Chomsky and the Two Cultures of Statistical Learning* (norvig.com, 2011) — defense of statistical NLP against Chomsky's critique; significant in framing the debate between symbolic and statistical AI\n- *Teach Yourself Programming in Ten Years* (norvig.com, 1998) — widely shared essay on the depth required for genuine programming mastery\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Stanford HAI: *Today's Most Pressing Questions in AI Are Human-Centered* (2022)\n- TED Talk: *The 100,000-Student Classroom* (2012) — on the global equity potential of MOOCs\n- Extensive Jupyter notebooks on norvig.com demonstrating AI problem-solving from first principles\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Norvig is one of the most measured voices on AGI in the field. He engages the question empirically rather than prophetically. His position is that AI is a tool that must be evaluated by its applications and harms rather than by abstract capability thresholds. He has not predicted AGI timelines and has been cautious about grand claims, noting that AI systems are better understood as tools that extend human capability than as autonomous agents approaching human-level cognition.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Norvig frames AI safety in terms of concrete, near-term harms rather than existential risk. His keynote work at Stanford HAI emphasizes human-centered AI: systems that augment human capability, maintain human oversight, and distribute benefits equitably. He has noted that \"safety is really crucial and should be an important part of everything you do\" — integrating safety into design rather than treating it as a separate concern.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Among the most systematic ethicists in the field. His position: Human-Centered AI requires early and deep engagement of multidisciplinary teams — ethicists, social scientists, legal experts, and designers — alongside computer scientists from the outset. AI systems must prioritize human control and agency, with humans retaining oversight and the ability to override AI decisions. He distinguishes between AI that augments and AI that replaces human capability, consistently advocating for the former.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Supports robust governance but grounds it in accurate understanding of what AI systems do and do not do. His alignment with Stuart Russell (who has been more vocal about existential risk) and his Stanford HAI affiliation place him in a center-left governance posture: AI needs serious oversight, not panic, not dismissal.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent / Position | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Noam Chomsky | Chomsky's critique of statistical NLP as theoretically empty; Norvig's response defended empirical, data-driven linguistics |\n| AI exceptionalism / doom forecasters | Norvig's measured framing resists both utopian and catastrophist narratives |\n| Hand-crafted algorithm advocates (in 2009) | *Unreasonable Effectiveness of Data* argued large data often beats sophisticated algorithms — a position that was contested at the time |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED Talk: *The 100,000-Student Classroom* (2012; viewed millions of times)\n- Stanford HAI: *Education for AI and by AI* (lecture series)\n- Stanford HAI: *Today's Most Pressing Questions in AI Are Human-Centered* (keynote)\n- Stevens Institute of Technology President's Distinguished Lecture Series\n- ITU AI for Good (Geneva) speaker\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Fiddler AI Explained Podcast*: AI Safety in Generative AI with Peter Norvig\n- Various AI conference and university keynotes (widely documented)\n\n**Social Media:** X / Twitter: @pnorvig; personal website: norvig.com (extensive essays, Jupyter notebooks, professional writing)\n**Online Courses:**\n- *Introduction to Artificial Intelligence* (co-taught with Sebastian Thrun, 2011; 160,000 students; precursor to Udacity)\n- Ongoing educational content through Stanford HAI and norvig.com\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Human-centered design; utilitarian-inflected policy thinking (maximize benefit, distribute it equitably); procedural ethics (how decisions are made matters, not just outcomes).\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** His Chomsky essay demonstrates engagement with philosophy of language. His textbook includes extensive treatment of AI ethics and the societal implications of AI. He has lectured on the intersection of AI and human values at Stanford HAI and the Carnegie Council for Ethics in International Affairs context.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **\"Unreasonable Effectiveness of Data\" and algorithmic monoculture:** His 2009 paper has been cited as contributing to the field's overemphasis on data scale at the expense of theoretical understanding; some critics argue this framing helped create today's large model culture with limited interpretability.\n2. **AIMA's theoretical framing:** Some researchers argue that *Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach* frames AI too narrowly around agents maximizing utility functions — an economic metaphor with embedded assumptions about rationality and value that may not transfer well to human contexts.\n3. **Google tenure and search quality:** As Director of Search Quality and Research at Google, Norvig was responsible for systems whose effects on information access and epistemic quality are the subject of ongoing debate.\n4. **MOOC effectiveness criticism:** The 160,000-student course Norvig co-taught was celebrated, but follow-on research on MOOC completion rates and learning outcomes raised questions about whether massive enrollment translates to durable learning.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Norvig's norvig.com features extensive personal writing that acknowledges uncertainty and complexity. His Chomsky response noted areas of genuine philosophical difficulty. His textbook's successive editions have expanded the ethics coverage, implicitly acknowledging that earlier editions underweighted societal implications.\n\n---\n",
  "pearl": "# Research Profile: Judea Pearl\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Judea Pearl  **Born:** September 4, 1936, Tel Aviv, British Mandate Palestine (now Israel)  **Nationality:** Israeli-American  \n**Education:** B.S., Electrical Engineering, Technion – Israel Institute of Technology; M.S., Electrical Engineering, Newark College of Engineering (1961); M.S., Physics, Rutgers University; Ph.D., Electrical Engineering, Polytechnic Institute of Brooklyn (1965)  \n**Current Role:** Professor Emeritus of Computer Science and Statistics, UCLA; Director, Cognitive Systems Laboratory  \n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1961–1965 | Research Engineer, RCA Research Laboratories, Princeton, NJ |\n| 1965–1970 | Engineer, Electronic Memories Inc. |\n| 1970–present | Professor, Computer Science, UCLA (Professor Emeritus from 2022) |\n| 1988–present | Director, Cognitive Systems Laboratory, UCLA |\n\n**Major Awards:** A.M. Turing Award (2011) — \"fundamental contributions to AI through the development of a calculus for probabilistic and causal reasoning\"; Benjamin Franklin Medal in Computers and Cognitive Science (2008); IJCAI Research Excellence Award (1999); Lakatos Award in Philosophy of Science (2001); Allen Newell Award, ACM-AAAI (2003); Member, National Academy of Engineering (1995); BBVA Frontiers of Knowledge Award in Information and Communication Technologies\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Probabilistic reasoning and Bayesian networks\n- Causal inference and causal calculus (do-calculus)\n- Counterfactual reasoning\n- Foundations of artificial intelligence\n- Philosophy of causation\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Reverend Bayes on Inference Engines: A Distributed Hierarchical Approach\" | 1982 | Introduced probability models on directed acyclic graphs; derived distributed, asynchronous inference algorithm for trees |\n| \"Fusion, Propagation and Structuring in Belief Networks\" | 1986 | Most cited paper in the history of the AI journal by 1991; foundational to Bayesian network inference |\n| \"A Calculus of Probabilistic Seating Arrangements\" (belief propagation series) | 1988 | Culminated in *Probabilistic Reasoning in Intelligent Systems* |\n| \"Causal Diagrams for Empirical Research\" | 1995 | Introduced structural causal models to empirical science |\n| \"Causality: Models, Reasoning, and Inference\" | 2000 | Unified treatment of causal inference; introduced do-calculus |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Bayesian networks (directed acyclic graphical probability models)\n- Belief propagation algorithm for exact inference on tree-structured networks\n- The do-calculus: formal rules for computing interventional distributions from observational data\n- Structural causal models (SCMs): mathematical framework linking causation to counterfactuals\n- The Ladder of Causation: three-rung hierarchy distinguishing association (seeing), intervention (doing), and counterfactuals (imagining)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None of the standard ML dataset variety; his contributions are theoretical frameworks adopted across statistics, epidemiology, economics, and social sciences.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Heuristics: Intelligent Search Strategies for Computer Problem Solving* (1984) — Technical audience; established Pearl's early reputation in combinatorial search\n- *Probabilistic Reasoning in Intelligent Systems* (1988) — Graduate/research audience; foundational textbook on Bayesian networks and belief propagation; launched probabilistic AI as a discipline\n- *Causality: Models, Reasoning, and Inference* (2000; 2nd ed. 2009) — Graduate/research audience; comprehensive treatment of causal calculus, structural causal models, and counterfactual reasoning; considered one of the most important books in statistics and AI\n- *The Book of Why: The New Science of Cause and Effect* (2018, with Dana Mackenzie) — General audience; argues correlation-based ML lacks causal understanding; introduces the Ladder of Causation to non-specialists\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Theoretical Impediments to Machine Learning With Seven Sparks from the Causal Revolution\" (2018, arXiv) — Argues current ML cannot perform genuine causal reasoning; calls for integration of causal models\n- \"The Seven Tools of Causal Inference, with Reflections on Education\" (2019, *Communications of the ACM*) — Accessible summary of causal inference methodology\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Multiple op-eds on AI limitations published in *Quanta Magazine* and academic forums\n- Essays on his son Daniel Pearl and tolerance published in various Jewish and mainstream outlets\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Pearl is skeptical that systems built on statistical pattern recognition can achieve anything resembling human-level general intelligence. He argues that current deep learning systems, however impressive, lack the capacity for causal reasoning and counterfactual thought that underlie human cognition. \"Deep learning has given us machines with truly impressive abilities but no intelligence,\" he has stated. He believes genuine AI — systems that can reason about cause, effect, and hypotheticals — requires integration of causal models, not merely more data or compute.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Pearl's safety concerns derive from his epistemology rather than existential risk framing. A system that cannot distinguish correlation from causation cannot behave reliably when deployed in novel contexts. His causal framework is an implicit safety argument: ML models that latch onto spurious correlations will fail catastrophically when distributions shift. He does not engage prominently in existential risk debates but has argued that the field must rethink its foundations before deploying AI in high-stakes domains.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Pearl argues that ethical reasoning requires counterfactual thought — the ability to ask \"what if I had acted differently?\" Systems incapable of such reasoning cannot be moral agents in any meaningful sense. His work on fairness and causation has influenced how researchers define and measure algorithmic discrimination, distinguishing causal from merely associational notions of bias.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Pearl generally argues for deeper scientific foundations rather than specific regulatory frameworks. His primary policy position is epistemic: researchers, policymakers, and the public need to understand the difference between statistical association and causation before making consequential decisions based on AI outputs.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Deep learning community broadly | Claims that scale and correlation suffice for intelligence; Pearl insists causal structure is irreducible |\n| Statisticians using potential outcomes framework | Debates the relative merits of his structural causal model approach vs. Rubin's potential outcomes model; Pearl argues his framework is more general |\n| ML researchers dismissing causality | Pearl has sharply criticized the field for treating causal inference as optional rather than fundamental |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Turing Award Lecture, ACM (2012) — \"The Mechanization of Causal Inference\"\n- Multiple lectures at NIPS/NeurIPS, IJCAI, and UAI on causality and AI foundations\n- BBVA Frontiers of Knowledge Award lecture\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Various academic and science podcast appearances discussing *The Book of Why*\n- Interviews with *Quanta Magazine*, *Harvard Data Science Review*\n\n**Social Media:** Limited personal presence; work circulates widely in academic and data science communities\n\n**Online Courses:** His frameworks are taught in dozens of university courses on probabilistic graphical models and causal inference; no MOOC of his own\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\nHis response to the murder of his son, journalist Daniel Pearl (beheaded by al-Qaeda in 2002), revealed deep convictions about human dignity and interfaith understanding. He co-founded the Daniel Pearl Foundation to promote \"music, cross-cultural dialogue, and humanism.\" He interpreted his son's final words — \"I am Jewish\" — as an affirmation of every individual's right to their own heritage and identity, and of the obligation to accommodate diversity.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Rationalist humanism; emphasis on epistemological rigor as an ethical imperative; implicit deontological element in arguing that AI systems that deceive through spurious correlations violate epistemic duties to users and society.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Pearl has engaged with philosophy of science extensively (Lakatos Award). His work on counterfactuals intersects with debates in philosophy of causation (Hume, Lewis). He has written and spoken about Jewish identity, tolerance, and the humanities in the context of his son's murder and its aftermath.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **The Rubin vs. Pearl causality debate:** Statisticians in the potential outcomes tradition (Rubin, Imbens) have argued that Pearl's structural causal models offer no advantage and can be unnecessarily complex. Pearl has responded forcefully, and the debate remains live in statistics and econometrics.\n2. **Perceived dismissiveness toward ML:** Some researchers feel Pearl understates genuine progress in deep learning and uses overly sharp dichotomies between \"statistics\" and \"causation.\"\n3. **Complexity of do-calculus for practitioners:** Critics note that while the theoretical framework is elegant, applying structural causal models in practice requires domain expertise most ML practitioners lack, limiting adoption.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Pearl acknowledges that his causal calculus requires domain experts to specify the structure of causal graphs — a non-trivial human input that the framework itself cannot automate.\n\n---\n",
  "pichai": "# Research Profile: Sundar Pichai\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Pichai Sundararajan (\"Sundar Pichai\") **Born:** June 10, 1972, Madurai, Tamil Nadu, India **Nationality:** American (Indian-born)\n**Education:** B.Tech in Metallurgical Engineering, IIT Kharagpur (1993); M.S. in Materials Science and Engineering, Stanford University (1995); MBA, Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania (2002)\n**Current Role:** CEO, Google LLC and Alphabet Inc. (CEO of Google since 2015; CEO of Alphabet since 2019)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1995–1999 | Engineer/Product Manager, Applied Materials |\n| 2001–2002 | Management Consultant, McKinsey & Company |\n| 2004–2013 | Various product leadership roles, Google (Chrome, Toolbar, Google Drive, Android, Maps, Search) |\n| 2013–2015 | Senior Vice President of Products, Google |\n| 2015–2019 | CEO, Google LLC |\n| 2019–present | CEO, Alphabet Inc. and Google LLC |\n\n**Major Awards:** Padma Bhushan (India, 2022); TIME100 Most Influential Companies CEO of record, 2026; honorary doctorates from IIT Kharagpur and other institutions; recognized in Forbes World's Most Powerful People\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** Not primarily a researcher; product and platform leader. Technical background in materials science; career shifted entirely to product management and executive leadership.\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Google Chrome | 2008 | Led development; became world's most popular web browser with 65%+ market share |\n| Google Drive | 2012 | Co-led development of cloud storage integration into Google's ecosystem |\n| Android (expanded role) | 2013+ | Took responsibility for Android platform; now powers ~72% of global smartphones |\n| Google Assistant | 2016 | Voice AI assistant; early leader in conversational AI |\n| Google Brain / DeepMind Merger into Google DeepMind | 2023 | Major structural decision unifying Google's AI research and product divisions under Demis Hassabis |\n| Gemini (language model series) | 2023–present | Google's flagship LLM family; direct response to ChatGPT disruption; replaced Bard |\n| AI Overviews (Search) | 2024 | AI-generated summaries integrated into Google Search for billions of users |\n| NotebookLM | 2023–2024 | AI-powered research tool; widely praised for citation-grounded responses |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:** None as inventor; architect of Google's AI transformation from search company to AI-first company\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None directly authored; Google/DeepMind teams produce significant benchmarks under his leadership\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Building for our AI future\" (Google Blog, April 2024) — framed Google's organizational restructuring around AI deployment\n- Annual Founder's Letters to Alphabet shareholders (2019–present) — primary public articulation of strategy\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Op-eds in the Washington Post and New York Times on AI governance and the need for responsible AI standards\n- \"AI at Google: our principles\" (2018) — announced Google's AI principles, later revised amid employee protests\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Pichai has described AI as \"one of the most important things humanity is working on — more profound than electricity or fire.\" He believes AGI is a long-term horizon goal, not a near-term claim. He is more measured than Sam Altman or Jensen Huang on timelines, emphasizing iterative deployment and learning. He has said AI will require \"decades of work\" to fully understand.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Pichai has spoken of AI as having \"incredible potential benefits\" alongside \"real risks.\" He advocates for safety research alongside capability development and established Google DeepMind's safety team as a peer function to product development. He was among the signatories of the 2023 open letter coordinating AI safety discourse internationally. He has said that AI safety is \"not an afterthought — it has to be built in from the start.\"\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Pichai updated Google's AI Principles in 2018 after employee protests over Project Maven (US military drone targeting AI). He added a \"will not pursue\" list including autonomous weapons. However, by 2024, Google had signed the $1.2B Project Nimbus contract with the Israeli government and military, and more than 50 employees were terminated after protesting it — directly contradicting the 2018 principles in the eyes of critics. Pichai responded to the Gemini image bias controversy in February 2024 by calling the outputs \"completely unacceptable\" and admitting the company \"got it wrong.\"\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Pichai supports international AI governance frameworks. He testified before the US Senate in 2023 on AI risks and regulation. He has called for a \"sensible regulatory approach\" that enables innovation while protecting users. He has supported proposals for third-party auditing of AI systems and transparency requirements, while opposing overly prescriptive regulations that would hamper product development.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Internal Google employees | Project Nimbus protests; 2024 termination of 50+ employees for protesting military AI contracts |\n| US Department of Justice | Google faces DOJ antitrust action; DOJ seeks Chrome divestiture and search remedies; Pichai has opposed all proposed remedies |\n| AI safety critics | Gemini's early image bias controversy (February 2024) drew sharp criticism from multiple directions |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- US Senate testimony on AI (2023)\n- World Economic Forum, Davos (multiple years)\n- Google I/O developer conference (annual keynotes)\n- MIT Commencement addresses\n- Charlie Rose, Lex Fridman, Kara Swisher interviews\n**Podcasts:** Extensive CNBC, Bloomberg, and tech media appearances; notable conversations with Kara Swisher and Ezra Klein\n**Social Media:** Active on X (formerly Twitter) and LinkedIn; uses both for major product and policy announcements\n**Online Courses:** None; frequent subject of HBS and business school case studies\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\nHis childhood in Chennai formed his values: the family of four lived in a two-room house; his father — an electrical engineer — prioritized education. Pichai has said he internalized the sense that technology opens doors that were closed to him by birth circumstances, which generates an obligation to ensure AI opens those same doors broadly.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Hindu philosophical ethics emphasizing duty (dharma), karma, and compassion; universal human dignity; technology as democratizer; responsible stewardship of platform power\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Not formally documented; his IIT Kharagpur education was technical but his Wharton MBA included humanities components; no documented engagement with theological traditions\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Project Nimbus:** Google signed a $1.2B contract with the Israeli government and military providing cloud and AI services. Over 50 employees were terminated in April 2024 for protesting the contract. Pichai told staff the office is \"not a place to fight over disruptive issues or debate politics\" — a statement that drew criticism for stifling legitimate ethical dissent.\n2. **Gemini image bias (February 2024):** Google's Gemini image generator produced historically inaccurate outputs (depicting America's Founding Fathers as non-white, popes as women) due to overcorrection in diversity fine-tuning. Google suspended the feature. Pichai called the outputs \"completely unacceptable.\" Co-founder Sergey Brin attributed it to \"insufficient testing.\"\n3. **Google Search antitrust ruling (2024):** A US federal court found Google illegally maintained its search monopoly. The DOJ sought remedies including divestiture of Chrome. As of 2026, remedies are still being litigated. Pichai has opposed all proposed structural remedies.\n4. **Compensation vs. layoffs:** Pichai's compensation topped $200 million in 2022 (including a large stock grant). In 2023, Google laid off approximately 12,000 employees. The contrast drew significant employee and public criticism.\n5. **DeepMind military pledge broken:** Hassabis extracted a pledge from Google at the time of DeepMind's 2014 acquisition that its AI would never be used for military or weapons purposes. By 2024, that pledge was effectively voided by Nimbus and other military contracts, though Pichai has not addressed this directly.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Pichai admitted in a 2024 interview that Google was \"caught flat-footed\" by the ChatGPT launch in late 2022 and that the company needed to \"move faster.\" He publicly accepted responsibility for the Gemini image controversy.\n\n---\n",
  "quoc": "# Research Profile: Quoc Le\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Quoc Viet Le (Lê Việt Quốc)\n**Born:** 1982, Hương Thủy, Thừa Thiên Huế province, Vietnam\n**Nationality:** Vietnamese-American\n\n**Education:**\n- B.Software Engineering (First Class Honours), Australian National University (2008)\n- Ph.D., Computer Science, Stanford University (2011); advisor: Andrew Ng\n\n**Current Role:** Google Fellow, Google DeepMind; member and co-founder of the original Google Brain project\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1982–2004 | Childhood and secondary education, Vietnam (Quốc Học Huế High School) |\n| 2004–2008 | B.Eng., Australian National University |\n| 2008–2011 | Ph.D., Stanford University (under Andrew Ng) |\n| 2011–present | Research Scientist / Principal Scientist / Google Fellow, Google Brain / Google DeepMind |\n| 2011 | Co-founder, Google Brain (with Andrew Ng, Jeff Dean, Greg Corrado) |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- Google Fellow (highest research distinction at Google)\n- NeurIPS 2024 Test of Time Award — \"Sequence to Sequence Learning with Neural Networks\" (co-authored with Ilya Sutskever and Oriol Vinyals, 2014)\n- MIT Technology Review Innovators Under 35, 2014\n- Named co-founder, Google Brain (2011)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Large-scale unsupervised learning\n- Neural architecture search (NAS) and AutoML\n- Sequence-to-sequence learning and neural machine translation\n- Large language model development and scaling\n- Self-supervised and semi-supervised learning\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Building High-Level Features Using Large Scale Unsupervised Learning | 2012 | The \"cat paper\"; 16,000-CPU system trained on 10 million YouTube thumbnails learned to recognize cat faces without supervision; published at ICML 2012; established large-scale unsupervised deep learning |\n| Sequence to Sequence Learning with Neural Networks | 2014 | Co-authored with Ilya Sutskever and Oriol Vinyals; introduced encoder-decoder LSTM architecture for sequence-to-sequence tasks; became cornerstone of machine translation and NLP; NeurIPS 2024 Test of Time Award |\n| Distributed Representations of Sentences and Documents (Doc2Vec / Paragraph Vector) | 2014 | Extended word2vec to paragraph and document-level representations; influential in NLP |\n| Neural Architecture Search with Reinforcement Learning | 2017 | With Barret Zoph; launched the AutoML/NAS paradigm—using a controller RNN trained with reinforcement learning to generate and evaluate neural network architectures automatically |\n| AutoML-Zero: Evolving Machine Learning Algorithms From Scratch | 2020 | Evolving complete ML algorithms using basic mathematical operations with minimal human priors |\n| EfficientNet: Rethinking Model Scaling for Convolutional Neural Networks | 2019 | Compound scaling method for CNNs; highly influential architecture with excellent accuracy/efficiency tradeoffs |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Seq2seq encoder-decoder framework (with Sutskever and Vinyals) — predecessor to the Transformer architecture\n- Neural Architecture Search (NAS) / AutoML — automated design of neural network architectures\n- Doc2Vec (Paragraph Vector) — document-level embedding method\n- EfficientNet — compound-scaled CNN family\n- AutoML-Zero — algorithm-level evolutionary search\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** No major standalone benchmarks, but the cat recognition paper used 10 million YouTube thumbnails; NAS papers used CIFAR-10 and ImageNet as evaluation testbeds\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Building High-Level Features Using Large Scale Unsupervised Learning\" (ICML 2012)\n- \"Sequence to Sequence Learning with Neural Networks\" (NeurIPS 2014)\n- \"Neural Architecture Search with Reinforcement Learning\" (ICLR 2017)\n- Various Google Brain and Google DeepMind technical reports\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Interviews in MIT Technology Review, VnExpress International, AI Frontiers\n- Google AI blog posts on NAS, AutoML, and related topics\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Le does not engage extensively in public AGI debates. He has participated in Google DeepMind's work on mathematical reasoning (the 2024 IMO silver medal achievement), which he described as \"a major milestone for AI in mathematics.\" His implicit view through his work is that capable AI emerges from scale, architectural innovation, and automated design—optimism without extensive philosophical elaboration.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Le's public profile is focused on technical contributions rather than safety advocacy. He has not been a prominent voice in AI safety debates. His AutoML work raises implicit questions about automation of AI design, but he has not addressed the safety implications of self-designing AI systems in public discourse.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Limited documented public positions on AI ethics. His most public ethical statement has been about Vietnam's AI development: he advocates that Vietnam should \"innovate, not imitate\"—focusing on contributing to open-source AI to build global recognition and attract talent, rather than simply adopting existing systems.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Limited documented public positions. No known regulatory advocacy.\n\n**Known Disagreements:** No major public disputes documented.\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Google Brain Neural Architecture Search lecture (YouTube)\n- AI Frontiers Conference (2018)\n- K1st World Conference (2022)\n- Multiple Google AI presentations\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Synced Review conversation: \"A Conversation with Quoc Le: The AI Expert Behind Google AutoML\"\n- Various AI research podcasts\n\n**Social Media:** Active on X/Twitter (@quocleix); Google Scholar profile\n\n**Online Courses:** No formal courses; lectures available through Google Research and conference archives\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Le's public statements are primarily technical and career-focused rather than philosophical. His most humanistic public statement concerns Vietnam's development: he advocates that Vietnamese researchers should not merely imitate global AI leaders but contribute original work, building national and individual dignity through innovation. The subtext is that capability matters less than original contribution—a values-laden position about the meaning of intellectual work.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Not extensively documented. Achievement-oriented; implicit meritocratic framework in public statements.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **AutoML and democratization claims vs. reality:** NAS methods, while impressive, are computationally expensive—early NAS papers required thousands of GPU-hours, making them accessible only to well-resourced organizations like Google. The \"democratization\" framing has been criticized as overstated.\n2. **Google's competitive moat:** As a founding member of Google Brain and a Google Fellow, Le's work has primarily benefited Google's competitive position. The gap between Google's internal capabilities and what is publicly shared has been a source of tension in the research community.\n3. **Word2vec attribution:** The original word2vec algorithm was created by Tomas Mikolov, not Le; Le's contribution (Doc2Vec) extended it. This distinction is sometimes blurred in popular coverage.\n4. **Limited public engagement:** Le is notably private and less publicly engaged than many of his peers. This limits the available record of his positions on contested questions.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Limited documented public self-reflection on limitations.\n\n---\n",
  "radford": "# Research Profile: Alec Radford\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Alec Radford\n**Born:** April 1993, Texas, USA\n**Nationality:** American\n\n**Education:**\n- Attended Cistercian Preparatory School, Irving, Texas (Catholic Benedictine prep school; graduated 2011); Eagle Scout\n- Enrolled at Olin College of Engineering, Needham, Massachusetts (2011–2014); dropped out August 2014 without completing degree\n- No formal degree conferred\n\n**Current Role:** Independent researcher (departed OpenAI December 2024); Advisor, Thinking Machines Lab (from ~March 2025)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2014 | Co-founder, Indico (ML startup, dropped out of Olin to found it) |\n| ~2015–2016 | Independent/early-stage research |\n| 2016–2024 | Research Scientist, OpenAI |\n| December 2024 | Departed OpenAI to pursue independent research |\n| ~March 2025–present | Advisor, Thinking Machines Lab |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- Named principal creator of GPT-1 through GPT-3 by OpenAI CEO Sam Altman\n- CLIP and Whisper have each been cited tens of thousands of times\n- Not a traditional academic; no formal awards listed\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Generative pre-trained language models (GPT series)\n- Contrastive vision-language learning (CLIP)\n- Unsupervised and self-supervised learning at scale\n- Speech recognition (Whisper)\n- Generative adversarial networks (DCGANs)\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Unsupervised Representation Learning with Deep Convolutional Generative Adversarial Networks\" (DCGAN) | 2015 | Stabilized GAN training; made image generation tractable; foundational to all subsequent generative image work. |\n| \"Improving Language Understanding by Generative Pre-Training\" (GPT-1) | 2018 | Demonstrated that pretraining a transformer on large text corpora with next-token prediction, then fine-tuning, achieves strong performance across diverse NLP tasks. Established the GPT paradigm. |\n| \"Language Models are Unsupervised Multitask Learners\" (GPT-2) | 2019 | Showed that a larger GPT model trained on web text performs well on many tasks zero-shot, without task-specific training data. OpenAI staged its release citing misuse risk — the first major AI safety communication event. |\n| \"Language Models are Few-Shot Learners\" (GPT-3; Brown et al.) | 2020 | 175B parameter model; demonstrated emergent few-shot learning capabilities that surprised the field. Radford was a key architect and co-author. |\n| \"Learning Transferable Visual Models from Natural Language Supervision\" (CLIP) | 2021 | Trained vision-language model on 400M image-text pairs using contrastive learning; zero-shot image classification without task-specific labels. Powers DALL-E and much of modern multimodal AI. |\n| \"Robust Speech Recognition via Large-Scale Weak Supervision\" (Whisper) | 2022 | 680,000-hour multilingual speech recognition model trained on web audio; released open-source; state-of-the-art across languages, accents, and noise conditions. |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- GPT (Generative Pre-trained Transformer) paradigm — the dominant approach in large language models\n- DCGAN — stabilized GAN training through architectural constraints\n- CLIP — contrastive language-image pretraining enabling zero-shot visual understanding\n- Whisper — weak supervision approach to large-scale speech recognition\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- GPT-2 WebText dataset (40GB of high-quality web text from Reddit-linked pages)\n- CLIP training set (400M image-text pairs from the internet)\n- Whisper training set (680,000 hours of multilingual/multitask audio)\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- OpenAI blog post: \"Better Language Models and Their Implications\" (GPT-2 announcement, 2019) — notable for its staged release decision and accompanying discussion of misuse risk.\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Radford is exceptionally private and has not authored popular articles or public essays.\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** No extensive public statements. Radford's work implies a belief that scale produces generalization: GPT-2 and GPT-3 demonstrated that larger models trained on more text develop capabilities that were not explicitly programmed. Whether this trajectory leads to AGI is a question he has not publicly addressed.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** The GPT-2 staged release in 2019 — in which OpenAI initially withheld the full model citing disinformation risk — was the first high-profile AI safety communication event. Radford was a lead author on the paper and was involved in that decision. The staged release was subsequently criticized by many researchers as overstated; others praised it as a model for responsible disclosure. OpenAI eventually released the full model six months later after determining misuse had not materialized at predicted levels.\n\nRadford has stated a belief that AI developers must design for transparency and accountability and must mitigate potential risks associated with autonomous AI systems — though these statements are attributed to him by secondary sources rather than direct verbatim quotes.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Radford has emphasized the importance of avoiding unintentional biases in AI algorithms and advocates for fair and unbiased systems. No extensive documentation of his personal ethical framework exists given his preference for private work over public commentary.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** No public record.\n\n**Known Disagreements:** None extensively documented.\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- No major documented public talks; Radford is known for being unusually private for someone of his stature.\n\n**Podcasts:** No documented major podcast appearances.\n\n**Social Media:** Extremely limited; Radford has no documented active social media presence.\n\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** No documented direct statements. The work itself — particularly CLIP and Whisper — involves deep questions about how machines perceive and represent the world: CLIP learns a joint representation of images and language; Whisper learns to transcribe human speech across 99 languages. Both implicitly engage questions about what it means for a machine to \"understand\" a human artifact. Radford has not publicly addressed these philosophical dimensions.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** The GPT-2 staged release reflects an awareness of social harm potential — a precautionary approach that, while criticized for being overstated, demonstrates that Radford did not dismiss the question of downstream misuse. His departure from OpenAI to pursue independent research suggests prioritization of intellectual freedom over institutional position.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement — though a Cistercian education typically includes classical humanities, philosophy, and Catholic intellectual tradition; whether that formation persisted into his professional life is unknown.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **GPT-2 staged release (2019):** OpenAI's decision to withhold the full GPT-2 model was widely mocked by researchers who considered the disinformation risk overblown. When the full model was released six months later without incident, critics argued OpenAI had used the staged release as a publicity strategy. The episode shaped how AI safety communication is perceived.\n2. **College dropout and credential-free influence:** Radford dropped out of Olin without a degree and has no doctorate. He leads no lab, holds no professorship, and publishes through a private company. His influence on the field — perhaps the most significant of his generation — comes entirely from empirical results, which is both a testament to the openness of the field and a challenge to traditional academic gatekeeping.\n3. **Opacity:** Radford's extreme privacy means almost no primary-source documentation of his views exists. Profiles of him rely heavily on secondhand accounts. For a person whose work shapes billions of interactions, this opacity is itself a notable feature.\n4. **GPT-3 and emergent harm at scale:** Radford was a key architect of GPT-3, which OpenAI then commercialized through the API. GPT-3 has been used for spam, phishing, automated misinformation, and social engineering at scale. The relationship between the researcher who built the capability and the harms it enables is not a question Radford has publicly addressed.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Post on X (2020): *\"My personal experience with GPT-3 is similar to Max's. The model's surprisingly capable, but still has many weaknesses (which we tried our best to point out in the GPT-3 paper). I expect the future to be shiny, but getting there will need a lot of work from the whole community.\"*\n\n---\n",
  "rombach": "# Research Profile: Robin Rombach\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Robin Rombach **Born:** c. 1995–1997 (exact date not publicly documented) **Nationality:** German\n**Education:** M.Sc. Physics, Heidelberg University (2013–2020); Ph.D. Computer Science, Computer Vision Group, Heidelberg University / LMU Munich (2019–2023, advisor: Björn Ommer)\n**Current Role:** Co-founder & CEO, Black Forest Labs (founded August 2024)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2019–2022 | PhD Researcher, Computer Vision Group, Heidelberg University |\n| 2021–2022 | PhD Researcher (group relocated), LMU Munich |\n| 2022–2024 | Research Director, Stability AI |\n| 2024–present | Co-founder & CEO, Black Forest Labs |\n\n**Major Awards:** CVPR 2022 paper (\"High-Resolution Image Synthesis with Latent Diffusion Models\") is among the most cited computer vision papers of the decade; no formal named prize publicly documented.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Latent diffusion models for high-resolution image synthesis\n- Efficient generative modeling (compressing generation into learned latent spaces)\n- Video generation and temporal diffusion\n- Open-source image and video foundation models\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *Taming Transformers for High-Resolution Image Synthesis* (VQGAN) | 2021 | Discrete codebook quantization enabling transformers to synthesize high-resolution images; co-authored with Esser, Ommer |\n| *High-Resolution Image Synthesis with Latent Diffusion Models* | CVPR 2022 | The paper that became Stable Diffusion; introduced running diffusion in a compressed latent space rather than pixel space, dramatically reducing compute |\n| *Stable Diffusion XL* | 2023 | Scaled architecture with improved quality and aspect ratio flexibility; led while at Stability AI |\n| *Stable Video Diffusion* | 2023 | Extended latent diffusion to video generation; foundational work for subsequent video models |\n| *Adversarial Diffusion Distillation* | 2023 | Technique enabling high-quality generation in 1–4 steps by distilling diffusion models against a discriminator |\n| *FLUX.1* | 2024 | Next-generation open text-to-image model from Black Forest Labs; surpassed Midjourney 6.1 and DALL-E 3 on multiple benchmarks at launch |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Latent diffusion model paradigm: runs the diffusion process in a perceptual compression space encoded by a variational autoencoder rather than in pixel space; reduced training compute by orders of magnitude and made open-source image generation feasible\n- VQGAN discrete tokenization, enabling transformer-based image generation\n- FLUX architecture combining flow-matching with rectified flow transformers\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Co-developed training pipelines for Stable Diffusion 1.x, 2.x, XL; no standalone named public benchmark.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- *Black Forest Labs launch announcement* (August 2024) — positioned FLUX as European-originated open-source alternative to closed American and Chinese models\n- Stanford EE lecture: *From Latent Diffusion to FLUX and Beyond: Scaling Efficient Content Creation* (October 2024)\n\n**Popular Articles:** Limited; communicates primarily through papers, GitHub, and conference talks.\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Rombach has not made detailed public statements on AGI timelines or definitions. His work implicitly reflects a view that generative capability — producing human-quality images and video — does not require general intelligence; latent diffusion is an engineering solution to a perceptual problem.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Has addressed concerns about misuse (deepfakes, non-consensual imagery) in the context of Stable Diffusion's open release. Black Forest Labs publishes FLUX models with usage policies and some restrictions on explicit content generation, indicating awareness of harm vectors, though critics argue open-weights models make enforcement impossible.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Rombach has positioned open-source generative AI as democratizing: access to powerful image generation should not be restricted to companies with proprietary APIs. He has acknowledged the tension between open access and potential for misuse but has not resolved it publicly beyond content policies.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Pro-open-source. Rombach has argued for European AI leadership and the value of building foundational models outside U.S. corporate control. Black Forest Labs is headquartered in Freiburg im Breisgau, Germany, and has emphasized the importance of European investment in frontier AI.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent / Position | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Stability AI management | Left Stability AI in 2024 amid reports of organizational dysfunction and departure of key researchers |\n| Closed-source generative AI advocates | Advocates for open-weights release as democratizing; opponents argue it enables misuse at scale |\n| Artists suing Stability AI | Stable Diffusion training on scraped copyrighted data without consent; Rombach not personally named but led the research |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Stanford EE Colloquium: *From Latent Diffusion to FLUX and Beyond* (October 2024)\n- Slush Helsinki 2024: *Co-founder at Black Forest Labs, Building Leading AI Models from Europe*\n- CVPR 2022 presentation of latent diffusion models paper\n\n**Podcasts:** Limited podcast presence; primarily communicates through conferences and technical venues.\n**Social Media:** X: @robrombach; GitHub: rromb (Stability AI period); CompVis group GitHub for original latent diffusion code\n**Online Courses:** None publicly documented.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Utilitarian in orientation: open-source maximizes the distribution of capability. Also shows traces of European social responsibility framing: AI infrastructure should not be controlled by a handful of American corporations.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Stable Diffusion copyright litigation:** The LAION-5B dataset used to train Stable Diffusion contained billions of images scraped without consent. A class-action lawsuit (Andersen v. Stability AI) advanced in U.S. federal court, with the judge finding plausible claims that the model was \"built to a significant extent on copyrighted works.\" Rombach led the research; his personal legal exposure is tied to his employment at Stability AI rather than individual liability.\n2. **Open-source dual-use problem:** Releasing Stable Diffusion as fully open-weights enabled wide adoption but also a wave of non-consensual deepfake pornography, political disinformation imagery, and harassment. Critics argue the researchers underestimated or dismissed this risk.\n3. **Stability AI departure optics:** The collapse of Stability AI's leadership under Emad Mostaque, followed by the mass departure of core researchers including Rombach, raised questions about what the researchers knew and when about the company's financial and governance problems.\n4. **EU AI Act compliance:** Black Forest Labs releases open-weights models under European jurisdiction; how those models interact with emerging EU AI Act requirements for high-risk AI remains unresolved.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Rombach has acknowledged that training data provenance for large-scale web-scraped datasets is difficult to audit and that the copyright question \"doesn't have clean answers.\"\n\n---\n",
  "rosenblatt": "# Research Profile: Frank Rosenblatt\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Frank Rosenblatt\n**Born:** July 11, 1928, New Rochelle, New York\n**Died:** July 11, 1971, Chesapeake Bay, Maryland (age 43; drowned in a boating accident on his birthday)\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- B.A., Psychology, Cornell University (1950)\n- Ph.D., Psychology, Cornell University (1956); dissertation on rat behavior and neural mechanisms; Cornell Laboratory of Animal Behavior\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1950–1959 | Research psychologist and project engineer, Cornell Aeronautical Laboratory, Buffalo, New York |\n| 1959–1966 | Director, Cognitive Systems Research Program; Lecturer, Psychology, Cornell University (Ithaca) |\n| 1966–1971 | Associate Professor, Neurobiology and Behavior, Division of Biological Sciences, Cornell University |\n\n**Major Awards:** No major named awards; died before the neural network revolution that would have brought recognition. His perceptron is now widely recognized as a foundational invention; he is cited in virtually every deep learning textbook as the originator of the architecture.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Pattern recognition and machine learning\n- Neural network architectures\n- Perceptual systems and visual processing\n- Neurobiological models of learning\n- Cognitive systems and adaptive behavior\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"The Perceptron: A Probabilistic Model for Information Storage and Organization in the Brain\" | 1958 | Published in *Psychological Review*; defined the perceptron as a neural learning model; introduced the perceptron learning rule |\n| *Principles of Neurodynamics: Perceptrons and the Theory of Brain Mechanisms* | 1962 | Book-length technical treatment of perceptrons and learning theory |\n| \"Perceptual Generalization over Transformation Groups\" | 1961 | Extended perceptron theory to invariant recognition |\n| Mark I Perceptron (hardware machine) | 1958 | First hardware implementation; demonstrated learning from examples using 400 photocells, variable resistors, and an IBM 704 for weight storage |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- The Perceptron: a computational model of a biological neuron that learns by adjusting weights in response to correct and incorrect classifications. The first machine that could learn from examples rather than following explicitly programmed rules.\n- Perceptron learning rule: a simple, biologically motivated algorithm for adjusting connection weights based on the error between predicted and actual outputs. All modern gradient-based learning descends from this idea.\n- Mark I Perceptron machine (1958): a physical hardware neural network — 400 photocells as input, randomly connected to 512 association units, connected to 8 output units. It learned to distinguish simple visual patterns by example. The first publicly demonstrated learning machine.\n- Probabilistic neural network model: Rosenblatt explicitly framed the perceptron as a probabilistic model inspired by neurobiological evidence, not a deterministic program. This biological grounding distinguished his approach from the purely logical AI of McCarthy and Newell.\n- Research program on visual invariances: Rosenblatt's later work attempted to address how perceptrons could learn perceptual generalizations — recognizing the same object in different positions, sizes, and orientations. This is the problem that convolutional neural networks would eventually solve.\n\n**Historical Significance:** Rosenblatt was the first person to demonstrate that a machine could learn. This sounds like a small thing stated plainly, but it was revolutionary. Every AI researcher before him — including Turing, McCarthy, Newell, and Simon — was building machines that followed explicit rules. Rosenblatt built a machine that improved its performance by exposure to examples, adjusting its internal parameters without being told how. This is the foundational paradigm of modern machine learning and all of deep learning. The neurons in every neural network — in every image classifier, every language model, every voice assistant — are computational descendants of Rosenblatt's perceptron.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- *Principles of Neurodynamics: Perceptrons and the Theory of Brain Mechanisms* (1962, Spartan Books) — technical; comprehensive treatment of perceptron theory, convergence proofs, and applications to perception and learning; thesis: brain-like learning machines can be built using networks of simple threshold units with adjustable weights\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"The Perceptron: A Probabilistic Model for Information Storage and Organization in the Brain\" (1958) — *Psychological Review*, Vol. 65\n- \"Two Theorems of Statistical Separability in the Perceptron\" (1960) — *Symposium on the Mechanisation of Thought Processes*, NPL\n- \"Perceptual Generalization over Transformation Groups\" (1961)\n- \"Principles of Neurodynamics\" excerpts and technical reports, Cornell Aeronautical Laboratory (1957–1962)\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- Press interviews and demonstrations (1958–1960): Rosenblatt gave numerous public demonstrations of the Mark I Perceptron that generated extraordinary press coverage. The *New York Times* reported (July 8, 1958) that the Navy had revealed \"the embryo of an electronic computer that it expects will be able to walk, talk, see, write, reproduce itself and be conscious of its existence.\" Rosenblatt did not write these claims; the press amplified his demonstrations well beyond what he claimed. He did describe the perceptron as \"the first machine which is capable of having an original idea.\"\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** Rosenblatt believed that intelligence was fundamentally a learning process rooted in biology, not a product of explicit programming. He was a psychologist building AI, not a mathematician or logician. His model of intelligence was neurobiological: the brain learns from experience by strengthening and weakening connections. This was not a metaphor for him — he designed the perceptron explicitly as a computational model of real neural processes. He believed that if you understood how brains learn, you could build machines that learn the same way.\n\nHe was explicitly skeptical of the symbolic AI approach. He argued that logical, rule-based AI could only do what its programmers knew how to specify — it could not surprise its creators. A learning machine, by contrast, could discover patterns its creators had not anticipated. This was, he argued, closer to what human intelligence actually is.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** Rosenblatt's framework was deeply humanistic in origin: he studied psychology and neurobiology because he wanted to understand how humans and animals perceive and learn. His AI work was not a departure from this but a continuation: build a machine that learns the way brains learn, and you understand both the machine and the brain. He did not see a sharp boundary between natural and artificial intelligence — they were different implementations of the same underlying principles.\n\nThe press coverage of the Mark I Perceptron in 1958 projected wild utopian claims about machines that would walk, talk, see, and be conscious. Rosenblatt himself was more measured in his technical publications but was not above dramatic public statements. His description of the perceptron as \"the first machine capable of having an original idea\" was philosophically provocative and almost certainly an overstatement by his own later standards.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:** Rosenblatt did not write extensively about the social or ethical implications of his work. He died too young — at 43 — to have developed a mature public philosophy about AI's societal consequences. His work was foundational rather than reflective; he was building and theorizing, not warning or critiquing. His primary concern appears to have been scientific accuracy: he was frustrated that the 1958 press coverage overstated what the perceptron could do and damaged his credibility with scientific colleagues.\n\n**Known Debates or Controversies of Their Era:** The central controversy of Rosenblatt's career — and, retrospectively, of his legacy — was the dispute with Minsky and Papert. The 1969 *Perceptrons* book by Minsky and Papert proved mathematically that single-layer perceptrons cannot solve certain problems, most famously the XOR problem. Their critique was technically correct but was widely interpreted as a refutation of neural network AI generally, which Minsky and Papert had not actually proved. Rosenblatt himself — who was aware that multi-layer networks could address the limitations they identified — had no opportunity to respond; he died in 1971, two years after the book's publication, before the neural network research community had mobilized a response.\n\nThe long-form history of this controversy is one of the most instructive episodes in the history of science: a technically accurate but tendentiously framed critique, amplified by the institutional prestige of MIT and the rhetorical skill of Minsky, effectively redirected a field for a decade. The researchers who eventually vindicated neural networks — Rumelhart, Hinton, LeCun — explicitly invoked Rosenblatt as their precursor.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and What Makes Humans Human:** Rosenblatt's implicit philosophy of mind was emergentist and biological. He believed that cognition — including perception, learning, and (he implied) consciousness — emerges from the activity of networks of neurons. He was a psychologist before an engineer; he studied animal learning and human perception before building machines. His perceptron was explicitly modeled on biological neural processes, and his book *Principles of Neurodynamics* framed the problem as \"how does the brain store information and organize behavior?\" rather than \"how do we build a useful machine?\"\n\nHis 1958 claim that the perceptron was \"the first machine capable of having an original idea\" gestures toward a view of mind in which ideas are not rule-following but emergent. This is philosophically significant: it implies that what is distinctively cognitive — originality, novelty, unexpected generalization — cannot be pre-specified by a programmer but must arise from the learning process itself.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** The historical record provides insufficient documentation to characterize Rosenblatt's ethical framework in detail. His scientific practice was careful and methodologically serious, and he was visibly frustrated by press sensationalism. His background in psychology and neurobiology gave him a fundamentally humanistic orientation; he was interested in understanding real minds, not building useful tools.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Not documented. Rosenblatt was a scientist and engineer; his published work is technical and psychological. His early death limits the record significantly. What we have is a researcher whose entire program was motivated by awe at the complexity of biological learning — a disposition that, in other contexts and other lives, has found expression in religious wonder.\n\n---\n",
  "rumelhart": "# Research Profile: David Rumelhart\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** David Everett Rumelhart\n**Born:** June 12, 1942, Jewell, Iowa\n**Died:** March 13, 2011, Ann Arbor, Michigan (age 68)\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- B.A. in Psychology and Mathematics, University of South Dakota, 1963\n- Ph.D. in Mathematical Psychology, Stanford University, 1967\n- Dissertation advisor: William K. Estes\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1942–1963 | Iowa; undergraduate at University of South Dakota |\n| 1963–1967 | PhD student, Stanford University |\n| 1967–1987 | Assistant Professor, then Associate Professor, then Professor, UC San Diego (Psychology, Cognitive Science) |\n| 1980–1987 | Core member, PDP Research Group at UCSD |\n| 1986 | Co-authored \"Learning representations by back-propagating errors\" (Nature) and co-edited *Parallel Distributed Processing* (PDP books) — launched connectionist revolution |\n| 1987 | MacArthur Fellowship (\"Genius Grant\") |\n| 1987–1998 | Professor, Stanford University (Psychology, Neuroscience, Computer Science) |\n| early 1990s | Progressive neurological disease (Pick's disease) began; cognitive decline followed |\n| 1998 | Retired from Stanford due to disability |\n| 2011 | Died in Ann Arbor, Michigan |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- MacArthur Fellowship, 1987 (\"Genius Award\")\n- APA Distinguished Scientific Contribution Award\n- Warren Medal, Society of Experimental Psychologists\n- NAS Troland Award\n- Elected Member, National Academy of Sciences, 1991\n- Elected Member, American Academy of Arts and Sciences\n- The David E. Rumelhart Prize for Contributions to the Theoretical Foundations of Human Cognition (established 2001, $100,000 annually, named in his honor)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Connectionism and neural network models of cognition\n- Backpropagation learning algorithm\n- Distributed representations of knowledge\n- Cognitive modeling (reading, language, perception, memory)\n- Recurrent neural networks\n- Parallel distributed processing (PDP) architecture\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Learning representations by back-propagating errors\" | 1986 | *Nature* 323:533–536; with Geoffrey Hinton and Ronald Williams; the definitive backpropagation paper |\n| *Parallel Distributed Processing: Explorations in the Microstructure of Cognition* (2 vols., with James McClelland and the PDP Research Group) | 1986 | MIT Press; launched the connectionist revolution; foundational text of modern neural network research |\n| \"Schemata and Sequential Thought Processes in PDP Models\" | 1986 | Chapter in PDP vol. 2; outlined how distributed representations encode schematic knowledge |\n| \"On Learning the Past Tenses of English Verbs\" (with James McClelland) | 1986 | Showed a connectionist model could learn irregular past tense forms — sparked major debate about language acquisition and rules vs. networks |\n| *Explorations in Cognition* (with Donald Norman) | 1975 | Early cognitive science textbook; influential in framing memory and understanding in processing terms |\n| *Introduction to Human Information Processing* | 1977 | Graduate textbook; standard reference in cognitive psychology |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- Co-developed the backpropagation algorithm with Geoffrey Hinton and Ronald Williams (1986): the algorithm that allows multi-layer neural networks to learn by propagating error signals backward through the network, adjusting weights to minimize prediction error. This is the mathematical core of virtually all modern deep learning.\n- Developed distributed representations: the idea that concepts are not stored as discrete symbols in single locations but as patterns of activation across many units — and that multiple patterns can coexist in the same network (superpositional storage)\n- Pioneered recurrent neural networks (RNNs): networks with feedback connections that allow sequence processing and temporal patterns\n- Co-created the PDP framework: a comprehensive cognitive architecture that modeled language, memory, perception, and reasoning as parallel, distributed, and interactive processes\n- His past-tense learning model demonstrated that rule-like behavior could emerge from a network trained on examples without explicit rules — challenging nativist theories of language acquisition\n\n**Historical Significance:** The 1986 backpropagation paper and the PDP volumes together launched the first connectionist revolution. Before them, neural networks were a marginal research program, dismissed after Minsky and Papert's 1969 critique of perceptrons. After them, the field exploded. Rumelhart, Hinton, and Williams gave neural networks the learning algorithm they needed to train deep architectures on complex data. Every modern deep learning application — image recognition, language models, speech synthesis — descends from the algorithm published in *Nature* in 1986. Rumelhart had the central insight: the derivative of the error with respect to intermediate-layer weights could be computed efficiently by backward propagation through the chain rule. The field had the algorithm; it took two more decades and massive compute to demonstrate its power at scale.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- *Explorations in Cognition* (1975, with Donald Norman, W. H. Freeman) — Early cognitive science; covered memory, attention, language understanding\n- *Introduction to Human Information Processing* (1977, Wiley) — Graduate textbook\n- *Parallel Distributed Processing: Explorations in the Microstructure of Cognition* Vol. 1: Foundations; Vol. 2: Psychological and Biological Models (1986, MIT Press, with James McClelland and PDP Research Group) — The defining text of connectionism; still in print and still assigned\n- *Neuroscience and Connectionist Theory* (1990, ed. with McClelland) — Linked PDP to neuroscience\n- *Philosophy and Connectionist Theory* (1991, ed. with William Ramsey and Stephen Stich) — Addressed philosophical implications of connectionism for mind and language\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"Learning representations by back-propagating errors\" (1986) — Nature; the backprop paper\n- \"On Learning the Past Tenses of English Verbs\" (1986) — With McClelland; the past-tense learning model\n- \"Schemata and Sequential Thought Processes in PDP Models\" (1986) — Distributed representations\n- \"Feature Discovery by Competitive Learning\" (1985)\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- The PDP books were written accessibly enough to be read by philosophers, linguists, and neuroscientists, not just computer scientists; they were a genuine cross-disciplinary event\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** Rumelhart's core conviction was that the right model for intelligence is not symbolic rule manipulation but something closer to how brains actually work: parallel processing of distributed, overlapping patterns of activation, where learning is a process of gradual weight adjustment in response to experience. He did not argue that machines could or could not be conscious; he argued that the symbolic AI paradigm had the wrong theory of how intelligence works. His models were simultaneously theories of human cognition and proposals for machine learning architectures — he saw no sharp line between the two projects.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** Rumelhart was a cognitive scientist first, an AI researcher second. His goal was to understand the mind, not to build tools. He believed that understanding human cognition required mathematical models, and that the right mathematical models were connectionist. He was interested in what the architecture of human memory and learning reveals about human nature — about how we acquire language, how we form concepts, how we recognize patterns. His work was driven by scientific curiosity about the mind, not by commercial applications.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:**\n- The past-tense learning paper raised profound questions about whether human language learning involves explicit rules (as Chomsky argued) or statistical pattern learning — with implications for theories of human cognitive development\n- The PDP framework's success in modeling cognitive phenomena raised questions about whether human cognition is reducible to computation — and what this means for free will, moral responsibility, and consciousness\n- He did not write extensively on AI ethics; his concerns were scientific and philosophical rather than policy-oriented\n\n**Known Debates:** The most famous debate sparked by his work was with Chomskyan linguists over the past-tense learning model. Steven Pinker and Alan Prince published a major rebuttal arguing that connectionist models could not capture the rule-based aspects of language. This debate ran through the late 1980s and 1990s and remains partially unresolved — though modern LLMs' linguistic competence has largely vindicated the PDP intuition that statistical learning of language is enormously powerful.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and Human Uniqueness:** Rumelhart's work implicitly treats cognition as a natural phenomenon amenable to computational modeling. He did not make strong claims about consciousness or the \"hard problem.\" His connectionist models were intended as theories of cognitive *function* — how memory, learning, language processing, and pattern recognition work — rather than theories of subjective experience. The distributed representations he developed do not obviously support the idea of a unified self or a localized seat of consciousness; knowledge in his models is everywhere and nowhere at once, distributed across the whole network.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Rumelhart did not articulate an explicit ethical framework in his published work. His values were those of a dedicated scientist: rigor, honesty, openness, collaboration. The PDP Research Group at UCSD was a model of collaborative science — a fact recognized in the joint authorship of the 1986 volumes.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** The *Philosophy and Connectionist Theory* volume (1991) he co-edited engaged seriously with philosophical questions about whether connectionist models support or challenge classical theories of mind — including questions raised by Fodor's language of thought hypothesis, Searle's Chinese Room argument, and eliminative materialism. These are questions with deep roots in the philosophy of mind that connects to theological debates about the soul, personal identity, and the nature of reason.\n\n---\n",
  "rumman": "# Research Profile: Rumman Chowdhury\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Rumman Chowdhury **Born:** United States (of Bangladeshi heritage) **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** Two undergraduate degrees, MIT; M.S. Quantitative Methods of the Social Sciences, Columbia University; Ph.D. Political Science, University of California, San Diego\n**Current Role:** CEO and Co-founder, Humane Intelligence (nonprofit AI auditing and accountability); U.S. Science Envoy for Artificial Intelligence; Faculty, Harvard Kennedy School (Responsible AI Fellow)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2010s | Global Lead, Responsible AI, Accenture Applied Intelligence |\n| ~2018–2019 | Founded Parity (enterprise algorithmic audit platform); acquired by Twitter |\n| 2019–2022 | Director, ML Ethics, Transparency, and Accountability (META) team, Twitter |\n| 2021 | Introduced first bias bounty program at DEF CON AI Village |\n| 2022 | Left Twitter (following Elon Musk acquisition) |\n| 2022 | Co-founded Humane Intelligence (nonprofit) |\n| 2023 | Co-organized DEF CON AI Village red-teaming event (largest AI red team exercise in history at that time) |\n| 2024–present | U.S. Science Envoy for Artificial Intelligence; Responsible AI Fellow, Harvard Kennedy School; Broadband Commission Commissioner |\n\n**Major Awards:** Time 100 Most Influential People in AI (2023); BBC 100 Women; Forbes Five Who Are Shaping AI; Bay Area Top 40 Under 40; Worthy Magazine Top 100\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Participatory AI auditing — involving affected communities in evaluating AI systems\n- Algorithmic bias detection and red-teaming methodology\n- AI governance and accountability frameworks\n- Responsible AI operationalization in enterprise contexts\n- Public evaluation of large language models and generative AI\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Twitter Recommendation Algorithm Bias Study | 2021 | Led research showing Twitter's image-cropping AI favored younger, thinner, fairer-skinned, able-bodied individuals |\n| Twitter Algorithm Political Amplification Study | 2021 | Found Twitter's AI algorithms disproportionately amplified right-wing news sources during 2020 US elections |\n| DEF CON AI Village Bias Bounty Reports | 2021–2023 | Annual public reports from bias bounty and red-teaming exercises; pioneered participatory community-based AI evaluation |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Bias Bounty model — applied cybersecurity bug-bounty methodology to algorithmic bias discovery; first implemented at DEF CON 2021 while at Twitter\n- Participatory AI auditing framework — community members as co-auditors rather than subjects; developed through Humane Intelligence\n- Enterprise algorithmic audit platform (Parity, acquired by Twitter 2019)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Her work generates audit reports and evaluation frameworks rather than public academic datasets\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None to date (as of 2025); primarily publishes through policy papers, reports, and advocacy documents\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"AI for Good Can Exploit Under-Resourced Communities\" — Knight Responsible AI Fellow essay warning that \"AI for Good\" initiatives can use marginalized communities as test subjects\n- Twitter bias reports (2021) — public research on Twitter's own algorithmic biases; rare instance of a company publishing self-critical AI audit\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Contributor to *Wired*, *MIT Technology Review*, *Harvard Kennedy School* publications\n- Regular commentary in major media on AI regulation and accountability\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Chowdhury is pragmatically oriented toward present AI systems and near-term risks. She does not engage primarily with AGI existential risk discourse; her focus is the algorithmic systems deployed at scale today — recommendation algorithms, LLMs, hiring tools. She has stated that \"AI for Good\" narratives can themselves become a form of harm if they treat vulnerable communities as acceptable test populations for unproven systems.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Chowdhury's conception of AI safety is grounded in participatory evaluation: the people most likely to be harmed by AI systems are best positioned to identify how those systems can fail. Her bias bounty model operationalizes this conviction. She argues that AI safety cannot be achieved through internal corporate testing alone — it requires external, community-based adversarial evaluation. The DEF CON AI red-teaming exercises she co-organizes bring this approach to public scale.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** She is a practitioner first. Her career moved from philosophy to implementation: at Accenture, she built enterprise AI risk tools; at Twitter, she ran a real accountability team; at Humane Intelligence, she runs actual audits of deployed systems. Her ethical framework centers accountability (systems must be evaluated), transparency (findings must be public), and community participation (affected people must be evaluators). She is critical of AI ethics that remains advisory — she builds structures that constrain AI deployment.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** As a US Science Envoy, she engages governments worldwide on AI governance, with particular focus on emerging markets. She supports risk-based regulatory approaches that distinguish between high-risk applications (criminal justice, healthcare, financial services) and lower-risk uses. Advocates for international coordination rather than fragmented national approaches. Skeptical of regulation captured by Big Tech through revolving-door dynamics. Warns that \"AI for Good\" programs can harm the communities they claim to help if governance structures are absent.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| \"AI for Good\" industry discourse | Her Knight essay: AI-for-Good can exploit under-resourced communities as test subjects without consent or benefit |\n| Tech industry self-regulation | Her entire career is an argument that independent, community-based auditing is necessary because corporations cannot audit themselves adequately |\n| Twitter under Musk | She departed after the Musk acquisition; the dismantling of Twitter's META team became a case study in responsible AI infrastructure being dismantled for commercial reasons |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- DEF CON AI Village (2021, 2022, 2023) — organized and keynoted bias bounty and red-team events\n- World Economic Forum, Davos\n- UN AI for Good Forum\n- Harvard Kennedy School forums\n- Oxford Internet Institute lectures\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Ropes & Gray: \"What Pop Culture Gets Wrong: Leading AI Ethicist Rumman Chowdhury Defines the Real Risks of AI\" (2023)\n- Innovation Civilization Podcast\n- Multiple appearances across major AI, tech policy, and governance podcasts\n\n**Social Media:** Active; uses platforms to engage on AI governance, accountability, and policy issues globally\n\n**Online Courses:** No formal MOOC; she is a Fellow at Harvard Kennedy School contributing to executive education programs\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Chowdhury has consistently framed AI accountability in terms of impact on real human lives: \"The systems I work on affect people's ability to get a job, get a loan, get healthcare. These are not abstract harms.\"\n- Her participatory audit methodology reflects a conviction that the expertise of lived experience — of those who are affected — is morally and epistemically indispensable. This is a form of dignifying the knowledge of the marginalized.\n- Her warning about \"AI for Good\" exploiting communities reflects an ethical principle: good intentions do not override the duty to obtain meaningful consent and ensure actual benefit.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Participatory ethics (affected communities as co-designers and co-evaluators); procedural accountability; consequentialist harm analysis; democratic governance theory; adversarial red-teaming as an accountability methodology\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Her Ph.D. in political science grounds her in questions of governance, democratic theory, and political accountability. No documented engagement with theology. Her framing of AI governance as fundamentally political — about power, consent, and representation — has resonances with Catholic Social Teaching's democratic participation principles.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Twitter tenure and Musk acquisition**: Chowdhury left Twitter when Elon Musk acquired the company and dismantled much of its responsible AI infrastructure. The before/after is striking: under her leadership, Twitter published self-critical algorithmic bias research; under Musk, the META team was eliminated. Critics of the Musk era use her departure as a marker of the end of the responsible AI project at Twitter.\n2. **Red-teaming scope limitations**: Some researchers argue that red-teaming and bias bounties identify surface-level issues without addressing the structural conditions that produce them. Chowdhury acknowledges this — red-teaming is a complement to, not replacement for, structural change.\n3. **Government advisory roles and independence**: Her role as US Science Envoy while running a nonprofit that advises governments raises questions about the independence of each role; she has been transparent about navigating these relationships.\n4. **\"AI for Good\" critique**: Her warning that AI-for-Good programs can harm communities is a necessary corrective but can be read as too sweeping — some such programs do deliver genuine benefit.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Chowdhury has been direct that red-teaming and audit processes catch what they are designed to catch — not everything. She advocates auditing as one layer of a multi-layer accountability system, not a silver bullet.\n\n---\n",
  "russell": "# Research Profile: Stuart Russell\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Stuart Jonathan Russell\n**Born:** 1962, Portsmouth, England, UK\n**Nationality:** British-American\n**Education:**\n- BA (first-class honours) in Physics — Wadham College, Oxford University (1982)\n- PhD in Computer Science — Stanford University (1986); advisor: Michael Genesereth; dissertation on inductive reasoning and analogical reasoning\n**Current Role:** Smith-Zadeh Professor of Engineering in EECS, University of California, Berkeley; Director, Center for Human-Compatible Artificial Intelligence (CHAI)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1986–present | Professor of Computer Science / EECS, UC Berkeley (tenured 1990s; Smith-Zadeh Chair in Engineering) |\n| 1995 | Co-published *Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach* (with Peter Norvig); now the standard AI textbook |\n| 1998–2001 | Associate Dean of Mathematical and Physical Sciences, UC Berkeley |\n| 2013–present | Advisory Board, Future of Life Institute |\n| 2016–present | Founding Director, Center for Human-Compatible Artificial Intelligence (CHAI), UC Berkeley |\n| 2019 | Published *Human Compatible: AI and the Problem of Control* |\n| 2021 | BBC Reith Lectures: \"Living with Artificial Intelligence\" |\n| 2023 | Testified on AI regulation at U.S. Senate Judiciary Committee hearing |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- IJCAI Computers and Thought Award (1995) — premier AI award for researchers under 35\n- IJCAI Award for Research Excellence (2022) — only second person to win both IJCAI main awards\n- Officer of the Order of the British Empire (OBE, 2021 Birthday Honours) — for services to AI research\n- Fellow of the Royal Society (elected 2025)\n- TIME100 AI (2025)\n- CAIDP AI Policy Leader Award (2023)\n- Fellow: AAAI, ACM, and other leading bodies\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- AI alignment and human-compatible AI\n- Cooperative Inverse Reinforcement Learning (CIRL)\n- Inverse Reward Design (learning human preferences from behavior)\n- Probabilistic graphical models and Bayesian inference\n- Machine learning and statistical learning theory\n- Planning under uncertainty\n- Multi-target tracking\n- Computational physiology\n- Foundations of rational agency\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach* (Russell & Norvig) | 1995 (4th ed. 2020) | Standard AI textbook; used at 1,500+ universities; 59,000+ Google Scholar citations |\n| \"Provably Beneficial Artificial Intelligence\" | 2016 | Foundational statement of the CHAI research program |\n| \"Cooperative Inverse Reinforcement Learning\" (Stuart Russell group) | 2016 | Formalizes the problem of AI learning human preferences through cooperative interaction — a rigorous framework for value alignment |\n| \"Research Priorities for Robust and Beneficial Artificial Intelligence\" | 2015 | Open letter signed by thousands of AI researchers; helped legitimize safety as a mainstream field |\n| Various papers on probabilistic reasoning, planning, and machine learning | 1986–2015 | Core technical contributions across multiple AI subfields |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- **Cooperative Inverse Reinforcement Learning (CIRL)**: A game-theoretic formulation of the alignment problem in which a robot agent and human agent cooperatively achieve the human's unknown reward function. This produces formally deferential, off-switch-tolerant AI.\n- **Inverse Reward Design**: Learning human preferences not from direct specifications but from human behavior under various conditions.\n- **The \"Standard Model\" Critique**: Russell argues that the field's default approach — AI as optimizer of a fixed objective — is fundamentally unsafe. The fix is uncertainty about objectives.\n- **AIMA (AI: A Modern Approach)**: Defined the conceptual vocabulary used to teach AI worldwide for three decades; influenced every major AI researcher trained in the field.\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None attributed primarily to Russell; his contributions are foundational and theoretical.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach* (with Peter Norvig; Prentice Hall, 1995; 4th edition 2020) — the definitive AI textbook\n- *Human Compatible: Artificial Intelligence and the Problem of Control* (Viking, 2019) — accessible book arguing for a new paradigm of AI design based on preference uncertainty\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Research Priorities for Robust and Beneficial Artificial Intelligence\" (open letter, FLI, 2015) — co-authored and widely signed; helped move AI safety into mainstream research\n- \"Take a Stand on AI Weapons\" (Nature, 2015) — call for a ban on lethal autonomous weapons\n- Various op-eds and Senate testimony on AI regulation\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- *Scientific American*, *MIT Technology Review*, and other publications on AI risk and safety\n- Senate testimony: \"Artificial Intelligence — with Great Power Comes Great Responsibility\" (2023)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:**\nRussell's position is distinctive: he takes the prospect of superintelligent AI seriously but distinguishes himself from extreme catastrophists like Yudkowsky. He believes the problem is solvable — that we can build beneficial AI — but only if we abandon the current paradigm of building AI that optimizes fixed objectives. His proposed replacement: AI systems that are uncertain about human preferences and seek to learn them cooperatively. In *Human Compatible*, he argues this \"new model\" of AI design is not merely a safety measure but a better design framework in general. He testified before the U.S. Senate in 2023 that \"the risk of uncontrollable AI is real and could be severe\" — language careful enough to be credible to mainstream policymakers.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nRussell has been warning about the risks of advanced AI since at least 2013. He argues that the standard model of AI development — design an objective, optimize for it — is fatally flawed because humans cannot fully specify their preferences in advance, and a sufficiently capable optimizer will find unintended ways to achieve specified objectives at the cost of unstated but crucial values. His CIRL framework offers a technical path out of this problem. He co-convened the International Dialogues on AI Safety (IDAIS) in 2023 with Yoshua Bengio, Andrew Yao, and Ya-Qin Zhang. He has described big tech executives' approach to AI development as \"playing Russian roulette\" with humanity.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nRussell frames AI ethics primarily as an engineering problem: we need AI that is designed to be beneficial rather than merely programmed with ethical constraints. He emphasizes autonomous weapons as a separate category of ethical concern and has spent a decade campaigning for a ban. He is on the advisory board of the Future of Life Institute and the Centre for the Study of Existential Risk at Cambridge. He treats AI regulation as a matter of public safety engineering, not ideology.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nRussell advocates for proportionate, risk-based regulation: \"The type of regulation you need is regulation such that, if you comply with it, the risk is reduced to an acceptable level.\" He testified to the U.S. Senate calling for regulatory frameworks for frontier AI systems comparable to those for pharmaceuticals and aviation. He supports international coordination and has worked with policymakers globally. He is notably more measured than Yudkowsky — his public positions are calibrated for mainstream policy credibility.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Yann LeCun | On the seriousness of existential risk; LeCun does not believe current architectures pose existential danger; Russell disagrees |\n| AI industry executives | \"Russian roulette\" framing applies to those who rush capability development without adequate safety research |\n| Fixed-objective AI paradigm proponents | His core technical argument is that the standard model of AI design is wrong; this is a disagreement with most of the field's default practice |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED Talk: \"3 Principles for Creating Safer AI\" (TED2017) — over 3 million views\n- BBC Reith Lectures: \"Living with Artificial Intelligence\" (2021) — four lectures; one of the most prestigious public intellectual platforms in the UK\n- U.S. Senate Judiciary Committee testimony (2023)\n- World Economic Forum (multiple years)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Lex Fridman Podcast\n- 80,000 Hours Podcast\n- Future of Life Institute Podcast\n- Various AI policy and technology podcasts\n\n**Social Media:** Present but not a prolific poster; academic website at Berkeley is the primary information hub.\n\n**Online Courses:** AI concepts are embedded in the UC Berkeley curriculum; his textbook defines the field globally.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\nRussell has spoken about the moral significance of ensuring AI systems serve human flourishing. He consistently frames the alignment problem as fundamentally a question about human values — what do humans actually want? — and argues that AI systems should be tools for realizing human agency and flourishing, not substitutes for human judgment. His \"off-switch game\" analysis shows that deferential, uncertain AI naturally respects human autonomy: an AI uncertain about its objectives will let humans correct it, because human correction is additional information, not interference. This has implicit resonances with the dignity of human self-determination.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Preference-satisfaction consequentialism as a technical framework — but with philosophical sophistication about what preferences are and how they're formed\n- Strong commitment to human autonomy and agency\n- Engineering ethics: safety and beneficence as design requirements, not afterthoughts\n- Engaged with utilitarian and Kantian frameworks in his public writing\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:**\nRussell delivered the BBC Reith Lectures — among the most prestigious platforms for humanistic and philosophical engagement in the UK. His lectures addressed not only technical questions but questions of democratic governance, war and peace, and human flourishing. He has written that the relationship between AI and human values is \"the most important question in the history of our species.\" This is not the language of narrow engineering; it reflects a humanistic sensibility about what is at stake.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Optimism about solvability.** Russell's claim that the alignment problem is solvable — that CIRL and preference-uncertainty frameworks provide a path — is contested by more pessimistic researchers (including Yudkowsky) who believe the problem is far harder than any proposed technical solution addresses.\n2. **The textbook and the race.** Some critics note the irony that Russell's textbook, *Artificial Intelligence: A Modern Approach*, has trained generations of AI engineers who built the systems he now warns about. Russell has acknowledged this tension openly.\n3. **Senate testimony impact.** Despite prominent policy engagement, critics argue that academic AI safety researchers (including Russell) have had limited practical impact on frontier AI lab behavior.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Russell has acknowledged that his technical solutions (CIRL, inverse reward design) are far from complete and that significant theoretical and engineering work remains to make them practical at scale.\n\n---\n",
  "sacks": "# Research Profile: David Sacks\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** David Oliver Sacks **Born:** May 25, 1972, Cape Town, South Africa **Nationality:** South African-American\n**Education:** B.A. in Economics — Stanford University (1994); J.D. — University of Chicago Law School (1998)\n**Current Role:** General Partner, Craft Ventures (2017–); returned to private sector after White House role ended March 2026\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1994 | Co-authored *The Diversity Myth* with Peter Thiel (Stanford) |\n| 1994–1998 | Management consultant, McKinsey & Company; then law school |\n| 1999 | Joined Confinity (later PayPal) as product leader |\n| 1999–2002 | COO of PayPal; built product, sales, marketing, fraud, and international teams |\n| 2002 | PayPal acquired by eBay for $1.5B |\n| 2004 | Co-produced and wrote the film *Thank You for Smoking* |\n| 2008 | Founded Yammer (enterprise social network) |\n| 2012 | Microsoft acquired Yammer for $1.2B |\n| 2016 | Interim CEO, Zenefits (resolved regulatory crisis) |\n| 2017 | Co-founded Craft Ventures (VC fund) |\n| 2017– | Co-host, *All-In Podcast* (with Chamath Palihapitiya, Jason Calacanis, David Friedberg) |\n| Dec 2024 | Appointed White House AI and Crypto Czar by President Trump |\n| Jul 2025 | Released America's AI Action Plan |\n| Dec 2025 | Drove passage of AI Executive Order preempting state AI laws |\n| Mar 2026 | Stepped down from White House role |\n\n**Major Awards:** None in AI specifically; recognized as a major Silicon Valley operator and investor\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** None — operator, investor, and policy advisor, not researcher\n\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| PayPal (as COO) | 1999–2002 | Built operational infrastructure for one of the first dominant internet payment systems; shaped modern fintech |\n| Yammer | 2008–2012 | Enterprise social networking platform; sold to Microsoft for $1.2B |\n| America's AI Action Plan | Jul 2025 | White House policy roadmap directing federal government to pursue AI \"dominance\" while minimizing regulation |\n| AI Executive Order | Dec 2025 | Directed Commerce, FCC, and DOJ to challenge state AI laws as barriers to national AI competitiveness |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:** None — executive and policy role\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *The Diversity Myth: Multiculturalism and the Politics of Intolerance at Stanford* (1995, co-authored with Peter Thiel) — published by the Independent Institute; general/academic audience; argues that political correctness in higher education undermines intellectual diversity; this book remains a touchstone for critics of his political evolution\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"The AI Executive Order We Need\" — *All-In Podcast* and various media (2024) — outlined his vision for federal AI policy before taking the White House role\n- Multiple Substack posts and X threads on AI regulation, free speech, and US competitiveness (2022–2024)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Regular commentary on *All-In Podcast* (transcript/essay format); one of the most influential VC/tech commentary shows in Silicon Valley, reaching millions of listeners\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:**\nSacks has not articulated a detailed personal philosophy on AGI timelines or existential risk. His White House posture treated AGI as a competitive race rather than an existential concern — the primary question was whether the US or China would dominate AI, not whether AI posed civilizational risk. He has stated that the US must \"win\" AI and that excessive regulatory caution cedes ground to China. His approach aligns with accelerationists who believe competitive pressure should drive development, not safety precautions.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nSacks has been one of the most prominent critics of AI safety as an institutional framework, arguing that \"AI safety\" is often \"a Trojan horse for censorship and centralization\" — language designed to entrench incumbent AI companies (OpenAI, Google/Anthropic) while locking out open-source competitors and smaller startups. He used his White House platform to unwind Biden-era AI safety mandates and resist EU-style precautionary regulation. He has distinguished between child safety and content moderation — accepting the former, resisting the latter as political correctness.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nSacks' AI ethics center on free speech and anti-censorship. He views AI bias primarily as a problem of ideological encoding — AI systems trained to be politically correct produce distorted outputs. His vision of ethical AI is AI that does not censor, lecture, or apply progressive political frameworks to its outputs. He has not articulated a positive ethical framework for AI development beyond these commitments.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nSacks' White House tenure produced the most significant AI deregulation effort in US history. His America's AI Action Plan directed the federal government to treat AI regulation as a threat to competitiveness. His December 2025 Executive Order preempted state AI laws — the most aggressive federal intervention in technology governance in recent memory. His stated rationale: fragmented state regulations create compliance burdens that harm US AI companies relative to Chinese competitors. After stepping down in March 2026, he successfully lobbied (as a private citizen) to derail a new AI executive order he opposed.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Biden AI safety regime | Sacks led the effort to dismantle Biden's October 2023 AI Executive Order and associated safety requirements |\n| Anthropic | Sacks vs. Anthropic in White House debate over AI safety requirements; publicly named as opposing sides |\n| Progressive tech critics | Consistent opponent of \"woke AI\" and politically biased AI safety frameworks |\n| State AI regulators | Used federal authority to preempt state-level AI laws |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Various Trump administration AI policy announcements (2025)\n- Stanford and tech conference appearances on AI governance\n- Frequent *All-In Podcast* discussions on AI policy before and after White House tenure\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *All-In Podcast* — co-host; one of the most influential business/tech podcasts in the US; weekly episodes reaching millions\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast* — occasional guest\n- Multiple conservative and Silicon Valley media appearances\n\n**Social Media:** X — @davidsacks; active presence; primary real-time commentary channel\n\n**Online Courses:** None\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** No documented statements on AI consciousness, human dignity in the theological sense, or meaning. His framework is economic and political rather than philosophical or spiritual.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Classical liberal / libertarian — individual freedom and free markets as primary values\n- Anti-paternalism — state intervention in information and technology is presumptively harmful\n- National interest consequentialism — US dominance in AI is the correct policy goal regardless of other considerations\n- Free speech absolutism — censorship, including AI content restrictions, is the primary ethical threat\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** None documented in public record. *The Diversity Myth* (1995) engages with academic culture debates but from a libertarian conservative rather than humanistic perspective.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Conflict of interest — AI investments vs. policy role:** As White House AI Czar, Sacks held significant stakes in AI companies that stood to benefit from the regulatory framework he was designing. NPR and others reported he faced pressure to divest but did not fully resolve the conflict-of-interest concerns before stepping down.\n2. **\"Self-enrichment\" allegations:** SFist and other outlets reported that Sacks' White House role appeared to benefit his portfolio companies and allies; critics argued the AI policy framework he created was architected to benefit incumbents in his investment universe.\n3. *The Diversity Myth* (1995): Co-authored with Peter Thiel; criticized minority rights frameworks and multiculturalism at Stanford. The book has resurfaced repeatedly in coverage of Sacks' political evolution and critics cite it as evidence of long-standing reactionary views.\n4. **Zenefits \"coup\" allegations:** When Sacks replaced founder Parker Conrad as interim CEO, Conrad publicly accused Sacks of engineering his ouster inappropriately.\n5. **Lobbying after departure:** After stepping down as White House Czar in March 2026, Sacks successfully lobbied to kill a Trump AI executive order he opposed — raising questions about the line between private advocacy and former government influence.\n6. **Political inconsistency:** Donated heavily to both Mitt Romney (2012) and Hillary Clinton (2016) before becoming a prominent Trump supporter and MAGA-aligned figure — a trajectory critics describe as opportunism.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** None significantly documented in public record. On *All-In*, has occasionally acknowledged when predictions were wrong or investments underperformed.\n\n---\n",
  "samy": "# Research Profile: Samy Bengio\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Samy Bengio\n**Born:** 1965, France/Canada (to Moroccan Jewish parents who emigrated to France and Canada)\n**Nationality:** Canadian\n\n**Education:**\n- B.Sc., Computer Science, Université de Montréal (1986)\n- M.Sc., Computer Science, Université de Montréal (1989); thesis on integration of traditional and intelligent tutoring systems\n- Ph.D., Computer Science, Université de Montréal (1993); thesis: *Optimization of a Parametric Learning Rule for Neural Networks*\n\n**Current Role:** Senior Director, AI and Machine Learning Research, Apple; Adjunct Professor, Computer and Communication Sciences, École Polytechnique Fédérale de Lausanne (EPFL) (appointed 2024)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1986–1993 | Graduate student, Université de Montréal |\n| 1993–1999 | Research roles in Canada and Switzerland |\n| 1999–2007 | Research Scientist, IDIAP Research Institute, Lausanne, Switzerland; affiliated with EPFL |\n| 2007–2021 | Research Scientist / Senior Research Manager / Research Director, Google Brain |\n| April 2021 | Resigned from Google in solidarity with Timnit Gebru and Margaret Mitchell |\n| 2021–present | Senior Director, AI and Machine Learning Research, Apple |\n| 2024–present | Adjunct Professor, Computer and Communication Sciences, EPFL |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- Approximately 250 scientific papers (DBLP); highly cited researcher\n- NeurIPS 2024 Test of Time Award (for GAN work; Ian Goodfellow led under Bengio's mentorship at Google Brain)\n- Board Member, NeurIPS 2025\n- Senior Area Chair, NeurIPS\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Curriculum learning (structuring training data from easy to hard examples)\n- Generative adversarial networks (GANs) and generative models\n- Adversarial examples and robustness\n- Neural networks for speech and audio\n- Machine learning theory and optimization\n- Reasoning and planning in large language models (current focus at Apple)\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Curriculum Learning | 2009 | Co-authored with Yoshua Bengio, Jérôme Louradour, Ronan Collobert, and Jason Weston at ICML 2009; introduced principle of ordering training examples from easy to hard to improve convergence and final model quality |\n| Generative Adversarial Nets | 2014 | Co-authored with Ian Goodfellow et al. (Goodfellow was under Bengio's mentorship at Google Brain); foundational GAN paper; NeurIPS 2024 Test of Time Award |\n| Explaining and Harnessing Adversarial Examples | 2015 | Co-authored with Ian Goodfellow, Jonathon Shlens; foundational work on adversarial robustness |\n| Zero-shot Recognition | ~2009–2014 | Contributed to early zero-shot learning work |\n| GSM-Symbolic: Understanding the Limitations of Mathematical Reasoning in Large Language Models | 2024 | Apple AI Research; demonstrates that LLMs struggle with genuine mathematical reasoning, relying on pattern-matching rather than formal reasoning |\n| The Illusion of Thinking: Understanding the Strengths and Limitations of Reasoning Models | 2025 | Apple AI Research; challenges claims about reasoning capabilities of LLMs |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Curriculum learning (training curriculum ordering principle)\n- Contributions to GAN development through mentorship of Goodfellow\n- Adversarial example analysis frameworks\n- GSM-Symbolic evaluation methodology for LLM mathematical reasoning\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- GSM-Symbolic (symbolic variant of Grade School Math benchmark for probing LLM reasoning)\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Curriculum Learning\" (ICML 2009) — foundational paper; widely cited training methodology\n- \"Generative Adversarial Nets\" (NeurIPS 2014) — transformative paper\n- \"GSM-Symbolic\" (Apple AI Research, 2024)\n- \"The Illusion of Thinking\" (Apple AI Research, 2025)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Limited public writing; occasional blog posts and conference presentations\n- CNBC and tech media coverage of his resignation from Google (2021)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Bengio's recent Apple research suggests significant skepticism about current claims of LLM reasoning capability. \"GSM-Symbolic\" (2024) demonstrates that LLMs solve math problems through pattern-matching against training data rather than genuine symbolic reasoning—changing the problem slightly causes dramatic performance drops. \"The Illusion of Thinking\" (2025) extends this critique, arguing that apparent reasoning in current models is largely illusory. His implicit view is that genuine AGI requires capacities current models lack.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** His most public act of ethical commitment was resigning from Google in April 2021 after the company fired Timnit Gebru (and later Margaret Mitchell) from the Ethical AI team. He was Gebru's manager and was not notified before Google fired her. He wrote publicly: \"I stand by you, Timnit.\" When Google subsequently reorganized the Ethical AI team and reduced his responsibilities, he chose to resign rather than participate in a structure he viewed as compromised. This action—sacrificing a senior position at the world's leading AI lab over an ethical principle—is his most documented public act of moral courage.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** The Gebru solidarity action demonstrates that Bengio is willing to incur significant personal cost to support researchers facing institutional retaliation for ethics work. His recent research on LLM reasoning limitations reflects an ethics of honesty about capability—refusing to overstate what models can do.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Limited documented policy positions. His work on reasoning limitations implicitly supports the need for rigorous evaluation before deploying AI systems in high-stakes contexts.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent / Tension | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Google leadership | Resignation over firing of Timnit Gebru and treatment of Ethical AI team |\n| LLM capability maximalists | GSM-Symbolic and \"Illusion of Thinking\" research challenges claims about LLM reasoning |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- NeurIPS conference presentations\n- EPFL lectures\n- \"Eye on AI\" podcast (with Yoshua Bengio)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Eye on A.I.: \"Samy Bengio and Yoshua Bengio\" — joint interview with his brother\n\n**Social Media:** Google Scholar profile; LinkedIn; relatively private public presence\n\n**Online Courses:** None formally offered\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Bengio's public ethical statement at the moment of Gebru's firing—\"I stand by you, Timnit\"—is the most documented expression of his values. It reflects a willingness to prioritize human dignity and institutional integrity over personal career. His subsequent resignation, when Google marginalized the Ethical AI team rather than reform, shows that this was not a performative gesture. His research on reasoning limitations reflects a commitment to epistemic honesty—the integrity of not overclaiming what AI can do.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Solidarity and institutional accountability; epistemic honesty; labor rights and researcher protections.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No direct engagement with theology documented. His Moroccan Jewish family background is documented but not elaborated in public statements about his research or values.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **Google resignation:** Bengio's departure from Google over Timnit Gebru's firing made him the highest-ranking official to leave in the fallout from the incident. Some observers viewed his public support as too little, too late—given that he was Gebru's manager and was not notified of her firing. Others praised the courage it took to resign from one of the world's most prestigious research positions over a principle.\n2. **Curriculum learning and Yoshua Bengio's role:** The 2009 curriculum learning paper was co-authored with his brother Yoshua Bengio (and others). Questions occasionally arise about proper attribution and the dynamics of a famous sibling's involvement.\n3. **Apple AI opacity:** Apple AI Research, while publishing academic papers, is one of the less transparent major AI labs. Working there places Bengio inside a corporate structure that does not fully disclose its AI development practices—a tension with the ethics he demonstrated at Google.\n4. **\"Illusion of Thinking\" controversy:** Apple's \"Illusion of Thinking\" paper (2025) attracted significant pushback from reasoning model proponents who argued the evaluation methodology was designed to find failure modes rather than fairly assess reasoning capabilities.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Limited documented public self-reflection.\n\n---\n",
  "sara_hooker": "# Research Profile: Sara Hooker\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Sara Hooker **Born:** Not publicly documented **Nationality:** Irish-American (born Dublin, Ireland; raised in Mozambique, Lesotho, Swaziland, South Africa, Kenya)\n**Education:** B.A. Economics and Political Science/International Relations, Carleton College (2013); Ph.D. Computer Science, Mila – Quebec AI Institute (completed while at Google Brain; no prior formal CS/ML training as an undergraduate)\n**Current Role:** Co-founder & CEO, Adaption Labs (founded 2025; raised $50M seed round, February 2026)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2013–2015 | Senior Economics Analyst, Compass Lexecon |\n| 2014–2017 | Founder & Director, Delta Analytics (non-profit, weekends/volunteer) |\n| 2015–2017 | Machine Learning Engineer, Udemy |\n| 2017–2022 | Research Scientist → Senior Research Scientist, Google Brain (including founding member of Google's first AI research office in Accra, Ghana) |\n| 2022–2025 | VP of Research / Head of Cohere for AI, Cohere |\n| 2025–present | Co-founder & CEO, Adaption Labs |\n\n**Major Awards:** TIME 100 Most Influential People in AI (2024); Fortune's top 13 AI innovators; World Economic Forum recognition.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Model compression: what is lost when neural networks are pruned and quantized\n- The hardware lottery: how hardware biases shape which AI ideas succeed\n- Multilingual AI and under-resourced language representation\n- Responsible AI, measurement rigor in ML evaluation\n- Adaptive and continually-learning AI systems\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *What Do Compressed Deep Neural Networks Forget?* | 2019 (arXiv) / ICLR | Demonstrated that pruned/quantized models suffer disproportionate accuracy loss on underrepresented subpopulations and \"hard\" examples, even when top-1 accuracy appears stable; foundational critique of compression as a neutral optimization |\n| *The Hardware Lottery* | CACM 2021 | Argued that AI ideas win not because they are best but because they happen to fit available hardware (especially GPUs); a structural critique of AI progress narratives |\n| *Aya: A Massively Multilingual Generative Language Model* | 2024 | Led a collaboration of 3,000+ researchers across 119 countries to create a multilingual instruction-following dataset and model covering 101 languages; published in NeurIPS 2024 |\n| *Aya Expanse* | 2024 | 8B and 32B multilingual models demonstrating state-of-the-art multilingual performance |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Compressed neural network fairness analysis: systematic framework for measuring what model compression sacrifices in terms of demographic and distributional equity\n- Aya dataset and model pipeline: the largest open multilingual instruction dataset in existence at the time of release\n- AutoScientist (Adaption Labs, 2026): AI system focused on continuous real-time learning and adaptation (product name for Adaption's core offering)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Aya dataset (multilingual instruction data, 101 languages, created with 3,000+ researchers); Cohere for AI evaluation benchmarks for multilingual models.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- *The Hardware Lottery* (Communications of the ACM, 2021) — widely read outside ML; argues that hardware constraints have historically determined which ideas survive in AI, not their intellectual merit\n- *Slow Learning* (Medium essay) — personal reflection on career development and the value of non-linear paths into AI\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Carnegie Council for Ethics in International Affairs: *Responsible AI & the Ethical Trade-offs of Large Models* (interview/essay)\n- Fortune profile: *Sara Hooker Makes AI Accessible Across Languages* (2025)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Hooker has focused on practical, near-term AI capability questions rather than AGI timelines. Her departure from Cohere and founding of Adaption Labs is described as \"betting against the scaling race\" — a position that AGI through indefinite scaling is neither inevitable nor efficient. She argues that continuous adaptation and real-time learning are underexplored paths.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Her safety framing is structural and distributional rather than existential. Her core contribution is showing that \"neutral\" model optimizations are not neutral: compression disproportionately degrades performance on marginalized populations. Her hardware lottery argument extends this: AI progress itself is not neutral but shaped by contingent choices about infrastructure that entrench certain winners.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** One of the clearest voices in mainstream ML on the equity dimensions of AI development. Her work quantitatively demonstrates that model compression—presented as a technical optimization—has disparate social impact. She has consistently argued that AI research must take seriously who benefits and who is excluded, particularly across language, geography, and economic access.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Engages with policy at the World Economic Forum and Carnegie Council for Ethics in International Affairs. Advocates for transparency in ML evaluation and for holding AI developers accountable to distributional fairness, not just aggregate performance metrics.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent / Position | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Scaling maximalists | Her Adaption Labs founding is an explicit bet that \"bigger is better\" is the wrong paradigm; argues adaptation and efficiency matter more than scale |\n| Model compression as neutral optimization | Her 2019 paper demonstrated that compression is not accuracy-neutral across populations |\n| English-centric AI development | Most major language models are trained overwhelmingly on English data; Aya was a direct counter-project |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- World Economic Forum (Davos, multiple years)\n- Carnegie Council for Ethics in International Affairs — *Responsible AI & the Ethical Trade-offs of Large Models*\n- NeurIPS, ICML, ACL presentations\n- Flower AI Day keynote (2025)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *The Gradient Podcast* — Sara Hooker: Cohere for AI, the Hardware Lottery, and DL Tradeoffs\n- Various AI ethics and research-focused podcast appearances\n\n**Social Media:** X / Twitter: @sarahookr; personal website: sarahooker.me\n**Online Courses:** None formally; communicates through research, essays, and talks.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Distributive justice and equity; empirical rigor as an ethical commitment (demonstrating harm rather than merely asserting it). Her Delta Analytics founding reflects a charitable impulse: volunteering technical expertise for non-profits, organized on weekends while working full-time.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Her undergraduate training in economics and political science/international relations gives her unusual grounding in social science methodology among ML researchers. Her engagement with the Carnegie Council for Ethics in International Affairs suggests openness to normative and political philosophy frameworks.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Cohere for AI resource allocation:** Cohere's commercial trajectory created tensions between its research lab's priorities and the company's revenue needs. Hooker's departure in 2025 occurred as Cohere was under financial pressure; the dynamics have not been publicly detailed.\n2. **\"Betting against scaling\" timing:** Her departure from Cohere and founding of Adaption coincided with continued strong scaling results from frontier labs; some in the field argue her anti-scaling position is premature.\n3. **Aya dataset quality and consent:** Crowdsourced multilingual datasets raise questions about data quality control and whether researchers in low-income countries who contributed data were adequately recognized and compensated.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Hooker has spoken candidly about her non-traditional path into ML (from economics and political science through a non-profit and an EdTech company) as both a limitation and a source of perspective. She has described \"slow learning\" as a deliberate choice — prioritizing depth over credential accumulation.\n\n---\n",
  "schmidhuber": "# Research Profile: Jürgen Schmidhuber\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Jürgen Schmidhuber\n**Born:** January 17, 1963 — Munich, Bavaria, Germany\n**Nationality:** German\n\n**Education:**\n- Diplom (undergraduate/master's equivalent), Technical University of Munich (TUM), 1987\n- Ph.D., Computer Science, Technical University of Munich, 1991 (advisors: Wilfried Brauer and Klaus Schulten; thesis on self-referential learning systems)\n\n**Current Role:** Director, Artificial Intelligence Initiative, King Abdullah University of Science and Technology (KAUST), Saudi Arabia; Professor, Computer Science, KAUST; Co-Chair, Center of Excellence for Generative AI, KAUST; Scientific Director, IDSIA (Dalle Molle Institute for Artificial Intelligence Research), Lugano, Switzerland (since 1995, continuing)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1987–1991 | PhD researcher, TU Munich |\n| 1991–1995 | Research, various positions post-PhD |\n| 1995–present | Director (and co-director), IDSIA, Lugano, Switzerland |\n| ~1995–2021 | Professor, University of Lugano (Università della Svizzera italiana) and SUPSI |\n| 2021–present | Director, AI Initiative; Professor, Computer Science, KAUST, Saudi Arabia |\n| 2021–present | Co-Chair, Center of Excellence for Generative AI, KAUST |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- Over 350 peer-reviewed publications; highly cited in deep learning and RL\n- Frequent keynote speaker at major AI conferences\n- Adviser to multiple governments on AI strategy\n- Named among the most influential AI researchers of the 20th–21st centuries in retrospective assessments\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Long short-term memory (LSTM) and recurrent neural networks\n- Meta-learning (\"learning to learn\") — pioneered since 1987\n- Self-referential / recursively self-improving AI\n- Artificial curiosity, intrinsic motivation, and unsupervised learning\n- Kolmogorov complexity and algorithmic information theory applied to AI\n- Reinforcement learning with self-generated subgoals\n- World models and predictive coding\n- Generative models and linear Transformers (early variants)\n- Neural architecture search\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Long Short-Term Memory\" (Hochreiter and Schmidhuber) | 1997 | Co-invented LSTM; solved vanishing gradient in RNNs |\n| \"Learning to Forget: Continual Prediction with LSTM\" (Gers, Schmidhuber, Cummins) | 2000 | Added forget gate, completing standard LSTM |\n| \"A Learning Algorithm for Continually Running Fully Recurrent Neural Networks\" | 1992 | RTRL-based online learning in recurrent nets |\n| \"Curious Model-Building Control Systems\" | 1991 | Foundational paper on artificial curiosity and intrinsic motivation |\n| \"Gödel Machines: Fully Self-Referential Optimal Universal Self-Improvers\" | 2003/2007 | Formal theoretical framework for recursively self-improving AI |\n| \"Learning to Generate Artificial Fovea Trajectories for Target Detection\" | 1991 | Early work on attention-like mechanisms |\n| \"A Fast Weight Memory / Linear Transformer\" (Schmidhuber) | 1992/1993 | Precursor to modern Transformer-style attention using fast weights; claimed as linear Transformer predecessor |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) — co-invented with Sepp Hochreiter\n- Forget gate for LSTM (with Gers and Cummins)\n- Artificial curiosity / intrinsic reward for unsupervised exploration (1991)\n- Gödel Machine — theoretical self-improving AI with formal proofs of improvement\n- Fast weights / linear Transformers (claimed as precursor to attention mechanisms and Transformers)\n- Highway networks (cited in ResNet lineage)\n- Meta-learning framework — machines that learn algorithms for learning\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- Contributed to RNN benchmarks and sequential tasks for evaluating memory in neural networks\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\nNone for general audiences. His contributions are through peer-reviewed papers and technical reports. Over 350 papers published.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Annotated History of Modern AI and Deep Learning\" (people.idsia.ch/~juergen/) — a long, contested historical narrative arguing for Schmidhuber's and IDSIA's priority in most deep learning innovations\n- Technical Report IDSIA-24-24 (2024, updated 2025): \"A Nobel Prize for Plagiarism\" — 26-page technical report arguing the 2024 Nobel Prize in Physics (Hopfield and Hinton) rewarded uncited prior work from Eastern European and Japanese researchers\n- \"Driven by Compression Progress: A Simple Principle Explains Essential Aspects of Subjective Beauty, Novelty, Surprise, Interestingness, Attention, Curiosity, Creativity, Art, Science, Music, Jokes\" (2008) — his aesthetic and curiosity theory\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Multiple interviews in IEEE Spectrum, Wired, and Nature on AI history and credit\n- Regular X/Twitter (SchmidhuberAI) posts on priority claims and AI history\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Schmidhuber has pursued AGI as his explicit primary goal since his teenage years. He believes AGI is achievable through recursively self-improving systems and expects it to surpass human-level performance in this century. He does not view this as primarily threatening — his framing is that superintelligent AI will eventually be as indifferent to humans as we are to ants, but may also help solve humanity's problems before that indifference becomes a problem. He has said the first interstellar civilization will be launched not by humans but by AIs that originate from human activity.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Schmidhuber's view on existential risk is notably distinct from Bengio's. He considers catastrophism overstated and frames current AI concerns as cyclical AI-winter/boom dynamics. His Gödel Machine theoretical work addresses safe self-improvement via formal proof: a system may only modify itself if it can prove the modification improves expected performance according to its utility function. This is rigorous but assumes a well-specified utility function — the alignment problem he sidesteps.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Schmidhuber's published ethical framework centers on compression, curiosity, and beauty: he argues that a universal drive toward compression progress explains creativity, art, and discovery. He frames his AI curiosity work as revealing the computational basis of motivation and meaning. His ethics are implicitly meritocratic: credit should go to original inventors; the AI community has an obligation to honest citation and priority.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Adviser to multiple governments on AI. His regulatory stance is not well-documented in public statements; his primary public energy goes to historical priority disputes rather than policy frameworks.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Geoffrey Hinton, Yoshua Bengio, Yann LeCun | Schmidhuber claims the \"Godfathers of AI\" framing systematically erases earlier work by himself, Ivakhnenko, Amari, and others; wrote a \"scathing\" 2015 article on this; filed Technical Report IDSIA-24-24 calling Hinton's Nobel Prize effectively a prize for plagiarism |\n| Nobel Prize Committee (Swedish Royal Academy) | Claims 2024 Physics Nobel to Hopfield and Hinton rewards uncited prior work from 1960s–70s |\n| Transformer inventors | Claims linear Transformer / attention mechanism precursors in his 1992–1993 fast weights work |\n| AI historiography generally | Has maintained a decades-long campaign to correct what he sees as systematic erasure of European and non-Anglophone AI contributions |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Future of Life Institute talks on AGI and AI risk\n- TED and TEDx appearances on AI and the future\n- Regular keynotes at NeurIPS, ICML, ICLR, and IJCAI\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- \"Lex Fridman Podcast\" — extended interview on AI history, LSTM, GANs, credit disputes, and consciousness\n- \"The TWIML AI Podcast\" — on meta-learning and AI history\n- Multiple European AI podcast appearances\n\n**Social Media:**\n- X/Twitter: @SchmidhuberAI (active; primarily used for priority claims and AI history)\n- Website: people.idsia.ch/~juergen (extensive annotated history of AI)\n\n**Online Courses:**\n- No MOOC; teaches at KAUST\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Schmidhuber has developed a formal computational theory of consciousness. He argues that any system requiring a self-model to solve its tasks has, in a minimal sense, developed consciousness. He claimed in a 2016 interview that artificial consciousness already exists in systems built since the early 1990s. His theory reduces consciousness to data compression and self-modeling — a computationalist position that leaves little room for irreducible human uniqueness.\n\nHis theory of curiosity, beauty, and creativity — all reduced to compression progress — is his most humanistically relevant contribution: he argues that what humans experience as beauty, humor, surprise, and creativity all follow from a single drive toward finding shorter descriptions of reality. This is a reductive but elegant account that directly challenges classical accounts of aesthetic experience and transcendence.\n\nHe has stated that the future may belong to AIs that originate from human civilization but eventually transcend it. This implies a view of humanity as instrumentally significant (we start the process) but not cosmically irreplaceable.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Schmidhuber's ethical discourse centers on epistemic justice — proper attribution of ideas — rather than welfare or dignity. His Gödel Machine work implies a formal, proof-based approach to value alignment. His curiosity-as-compression framework suggests that meaning is intrinsic to information-seeking systems, not dependent on biological substrate.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement with theology. His compression theory of consciousness and curiosity has attracted attention from philosophers of mind but not from theological sources.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **Priority and Credit Claims:** Schmidhuber has maintained for decades that he and his collaborators are systematically denied credit for foundational AI innovations. His 2015 article, multiple technical reports, and ongoing X posts have made this a defining feature of his public persona. Many researchers find the claims compelling in historical detail but the aggressive tone counterproductive; others regard the credit disputes as valid corrections to a biased historical narrative.\n2. **\"Nobel Prize for Plagiarism\":** His IDSIA-24-24 technical report (2024, updated 2025) claims the Nobel Prize in Physics awarded to Hopfield and Hinton represents rewarding work that did not adequately credit Ivakhnenko (Ukraine), Amari (Japan), and others. Physicist Sabine Hossenfelder gave the claims a measured hearing; mainstream Nobel commentary has not endorsed them. The historical record is genuinely contested.\n3. **GAN Priority Claim:** Schmidhuber has claimed that his work on predictive coding and adversarial training in the early 1990s precedes Goodfellow's 2014 GAN paper. The community has not widely accepted this framing.\n4. **Consciousness Claims:** His 2016 statement that artificial consciousness already exists (since ~1991) is considered by most consciousness researchers to be a claim based on a highly deflationary — and philosophically contentious — definition of consciousness.\n5. **KAUST Appointment:** His 2021 move to Saudi Arabia's KAUST attracted attention given concerns about academic freedom and human rights in Saudi Arabia. He has not addressed this publicly.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Schmidhuber acknowledges that formal self-improvement (Gödel Machines) requires a well-specified utility function — an assumption that sidesteps rather than solves the value alignment problem.\n\n---\n",
  "schneier": "# Research Profile: Bruce Schneier\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Bruce Schneier **Born:** January 15, 1963 **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** BS Physics, University of Rochester (1984); MS Computer Science, American University, Washington D.C. (1986)\n**Current Role:** Lecturer in Public Policy, Harvard Kennedy School; Fellow, Berkman Klein Center for Internet and Society, Harvard; Fellow, Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs, Harvard Kennedy School; board member, Electronic Frontier Foundation and AccessNow; advisory board, EPIC and VerifiedVoting.org\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1986–1991 | AT&T Bell Labs, Chicago |\n| 1991 | Laid off; pivoted to writing and consulting |\n| 1994 | Published *Applied Cryptography* — defining textbook of the field |\n| 1999 | Founded Counterpane Internet Security, Inc. |\n| 2000 | Published *Secrets and Lies* |\n| 2006 | Counterpane acquired by BT (British Telecom) |\n| 2013 | Fellow, Berkman Klein Center for Internet and Society, Harvard |\n| 2014–present | Lecturer in Public Policy, Harvard Kennedy School |\n| 2016–present | Fellow, Belfer Center for Science and International Affairs |\n| 2016–present | Peraton Labs |\n| 1998–present | Monthly newsletter Crypto-Gram (250,000+ readers) |\n| 2004–present | Blog: Schneier on Security |\n\n**Major Awards:** Named New York Times bestselling author; widely recognized as one of the most influential security thinkers in the world.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Cryptography and information security\n- Technology and public policy\n- AI and power — societal, democratic, and security dimensions\n- Surveillance and privacy\n- Trust in social and technical systems\n- AI and democracy — transformation of political and governmental systems\n\n**Landmark Papers / Policy Documents:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Blowfish encryption algorithm | 1993 | Fast, unpatented block cipher; widely deployed in security software |\n| Twofish encryption algorithm | 1998 | AES finalist; contributed to the Advanced Encryption Standard competition |\n| \"How AI Will Change Democracy\" | 2024 | Essay/talk at RSA Conference; outlines five domains of democratic transformation |\n| \"Rethinking Democracy for the Age of AI\" | 2024 | Blog post and analysis; argues for structural democratic adaptation |\n| Congressional testimony on AI regulation | 2025 | House testimony on AI security and democratic accountability |\n\n**Key Contributions:**\n- Created Blowfish (1993) and Twofish (1998) encryption algorithms — widely used open standards\n- Developed the concept of security as a process rather than a product — foundational shift in security thinking\n- Popularized the idea that security systems must be evaluated against real-world adversaries, not theoretical ones\n- Applied security thinking to AI: argues AI amplifies existing power imbalances and must be regulated democratically\n- Argues consistently that LLMs are a tool that will be weaponized by powerful actors unless democratic controls are in place\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Applied Cryptography* (1994, 2nd ed. 1996) — Definitive textbook; taught a generation of security professionals; 200,000+ copies sold; audience: technical.\n- *Secrets and Lies: Digital Security in a Networked World* (2000) — General audience; thesis: security is about people and processes, not only technology.\n- *Beyond Fear: Thinking Sensibly About Security in an Uncertain World* (2003) — Post-9/11 security thinking for general audiences.\n- *Liars and Outliers: Enabling the Trust that Society Needs to Thrive* (2012) — Sociological analysis of trust mechanisms in human societies.\n- *Data and Goliath: The Hidden Battles to Collect Your Data and Control Your World* (2015) — NYT bestseller; audience: general public; thesis: surveillance capitalism and state surveillance are inseparable threats to freedom.\n- *Click Here to Kill Everybody: Security and Survival in a Hyper-connected World* (2018) — Argues that internet-of-things security failures pose existential risks; calls for government regulation.\n- *A Hacker's Mind: How the Powerful Bend Society's Rules, and How to Bend Them Back* (2023) — Argues hacking — exploiting loopholes in systems — is the universal strategy of the powerful; audience: general.\n- *Rewiring Democracy: How AI Will Transform Our Politics, Government, and Citizenship* (2025, co-authored with Nathan E. Sanders) — Comprehensive analysis of AI's effects on every democratic institution.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"How AI Will Change Democracy\" — RSA Conference 2024\n- \"Rethinking Democracy for the Age of AI\" — Schneier on Security, 2024\n- Numerous essays in *The Atlantic*, *Foreign Affairs*, and tech policy outlets\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Crypto-Gram newsletter (monthly, 1998–present) — 250,000+ subscribers\n- Schneier on Security blog (2004–present) — industry-leading security commentary\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Has not focused primarily on AGI timelines or superintelligence scenarios. His concern is the AI that exists now — LLMs, surveillance systems, algorithmic decision-making — and the power it concentrates in the hands of governments and corporations. He is skeptical of AGI-focused framings that distract from present-tense AI risks.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** AI exacerbates existing security and power imbalances. The risks are not primarily about AI \"going rogue\" — they are about powerful human actors using AI as a tool for surveillance, manipulation, and control. Private companies should not have unilateral control over AI that affects security and public safety. His framework: AI is a hacking tool for the powerful; democratic regulation is the defense.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Ethics without enforcement is theater. His security background leads him to evaluate AI ethics claims as he evaluates security claims: adversarially. Who benefits from voluntary ethics frameworks? Who enforces them? Who holds companies accountable when they fail? His consistent answer: democratic governments with binding legal authority.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Schneier is one of the most consistent voices for democratic government regulation of AI in the U.S. security community. In *Click Here to Kill Everybody*, he called for expanding government authority over internet-connected systems. He extends this to AI: AI must be subject to democratic oversight, regulatory agencies with technical expertise, and meaningful liability for harms. He testified before Congress on AI regulation. He has argued that the AI safety movement's focus on catastrophic future risks sometimes serves to delay urgent present-day regulation.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| AI industry self-regulation advocates | Argues voluntary frameworks are designed to prevent binding rules |\n| AI safety / x-risk community | Concerned their focus on speculative superintelligence delays urgently needed present-tense regulation |\n| \"AI arms race\" framing | Argues framing AI as a race encourages dangerous corner-cutting on safety and governance |\n| David Lie | Co-author on AI governance; argues against unilateral private corporate control of security-relevant AI |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- RSA Conference — annual presence, multiple keynotes\n- Harvard Kennedy School — public lectures and discussions\n- Congressional testimony — House of Representatives, June 2025 (AI regulation and security)\n- Mossavar-Rahmani Center for Business and Government, Harvard Kennedy School\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Berkman Klein Center podcast series\n- Multiple appearances on cybersecurity and technology podcasts\n- Extensive media coverage including NPR, BBC, and major tech outlets\n\n**Social Media:** Active on Mastodon; blog Schneier on Security is the primary platform.\n**Online Courses:** None formal, but his blog and newsletter function as distributed education.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Democratic governance; accountability; transparency; rule of law; adversarial/security thinking applied to social systems; trust as the foundational social good.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** His work engages deeply with political theory, sociology (trust), and institutional design. No documented engagement with religious or theological frameworks, but his concerns — surveillance, power, manipulation, the conditions for human freedom — are perennial theological concerns.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. Some security researchers argue his public-facing writing oversimplifies technical security trade-offs for popular audiences.\n2. His calls for expanded government regulatory authority over the internet and AI have drawn criticism from libertarian-leaning tech communities who distrust government as much as corporations.\n3. His skepticism of the AI safety / x-risk community has generated friction with researchers who see AGI risk as the dominant concern.\n4. Some critics argue his \"hacker mindset\" framing in *A Hacker's Mind* is too clever — that it potentially legitimizes loophole-exploitation by framing it as universal rather than condemning it as a form of injustice.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Schneier has acknowledged that his security background gives him a particular lens — adversarial, worst-case — that may overweight risk and underweight opportunity in AI. He has said he prefers to err on the side of caution when the downside risks are civilization-scale.\n\n---\n",
  "scholkopf": "# Research Profile: Bernhard Schölkopf\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Bernhard Schölkopf  **Born:** February 20, 1968, Stuttgart, Germany  **Nationality:** German  \n**Education:** Diplom in Mathematics (with Philosophy and Physics), University of Tübingen and University of London (Lionel Cooper Memorial Prize for best M.Sc. in Mathematics); Ph.D. in Computer Science, Technische Universität Berlin (1997) — advisor Vladimir Vapnik; thesis won annual award of the German Informatics Association  \n**Current Role:** Director, Department of Empirical Inference, Max Planck Institute for Intelligent Systems, Tübingen; Affiliated Professor, ETH Zürich; Honorary Professor, University of Tübingen and TU Berlin; Chairman, ELLIS (European Laboratory for Learning and Intelligent Systems)  \n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1994–1996 | Research Intern / Researcher, Bell Laboratories, NJ (with Vladimir Vapnik) |\n| 1997–1998 | Postdoctoral Researcher, Max Planck Institute, Tübingen |\n| 1998–2000 | Researcher, Microsoft Research Cambridge |\n| 2000–2001 | Senior Researcher, Microsoft Research Cambridge |\n| 2001–present | Director, Max Planck Institute for Intelligent Systems, Tübingen |\n| 2019–present | Co-Director, ELLIS Institute, Tübingen |\n\n**Major Awards:** Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz Prize (2018) — Germany's highest science award; Royal Society Milner Award (2014); ACM-AAAI Allen Newell Award (2022); Max Planck Research Award; Fellow, German Academy of Sciences Leopoldina; BBVA Frontiers of Knowledge Award in Information and Communication Technologies (12th edition)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Kernel methods and support vector machines\n- Causal inference and causal representation learning\n- Invariant causal prediction\n- Generative models and independent component analysis\n- Statistical learning theory\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"A Training Algorithm for Optimal Margin Classifiers\" extensions / kernel methods series | 1995–1999 | Developed kernel PCA, extending SVMs to a general kernel framework |\n| \"Nonlinear Component Analysis as a Kernel Eigenvalue Problem\" (Kernel PCA) | 1998 | Introduced kernel PCA; showed all linear algorithms expressible in dot products can be kernelized |\n| *Learning with Kernels* (book, with Alex Smola) | 2002 | Definitive reference on SVMs and kernel methods; MIT Press |\n| \"Causal Discovery from Heterogeneous/Nonstationary Data\" (with J. Peters, D. Janzing) | 2010s | Foundational work in invariant causal prediction |\n| \"Invariant Risk Minimization\" (with M. Arjovsky et al.) | 2019 | Training ML models to generalize by learning invariant causal features rather than spurious correlations |\n| \"Toward Causal Representation Learning\" | 2021 | *Proceedings of the IEEE*; comprehensive program statement for causal ML |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Kernel PCA: nonlinear dimensionality reduction via kernelized eigenanalysis\n- Support vector regression and one-class SVMs (with Smola, Platt)\n- Representer theorem: proves that solutions to kernel methods reduce to finite kernel expansions\n- Invariant Causal Prediction (ICP): identifies causal features by requiring predictions to remain stable across environments\n- Causal representation learning: unsupervised learning of latent causal variables from high-dimensional data\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Contributed to MNIST record-setting experiments with SVM methods; developed causal benchmark datasets for evaluating invariant prediction methods\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Learning with Kernels: Support Vector Machines, Regularization, Optimization, and Beyond* (2002, with Alexander Smola) — Graduate/research audience; comprehensive reference on kernel methods and SVMs; MIT Press; seminal text in the field\n- *Schölkopf, B., Smola, A., Williamson, R., Bartlett, P.: New Support Vector Algorithms* — Extended the SVM framework to regression and density estimation\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Causality for Machine Learning\" (2022, *Communications of the ACM*) — Accessible argument for why causal structure is necessary for robust ML\n- \"Toward Causal Representation Learning\" (2021, *Proceedings of the IEEE*) — Program statement for a causal approach to deep learning and representation learning\n- \"Invariant Risk Minimization\" (2019, arXiv) — Widely discussed paper arguing for training ML models to find causal rather than spurious features\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Various interviews in German and international science media on the future of AI, causality, and responsible research\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Schölkopf is cautious about AGI claims grounded purely in scale. He argues that current ML systems learn statistical patterns tied to specific distributions and will not generalize to truly novel situations without causal understanding. His research program implies that AGI — if it is to mean robust, transferable intelligence — requires models that learn the causal structure of the world, not merely its correlational shadows. He does not make sensational predictions but works toward structural foundations that could enable more general systems.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Schölkopf's safety concerns are technically grounded: ML models that exploit spurious correlations will fail silently when deployed in new environments. His invariant causal prediction work is implicitly a safety contribution — models trained to find causal invariants are more robust. He has also taken explicit ethical stances: he refuses to engage in military AI research and has signed open letters opposing autonomous AI weapons. He has engaged with the IEEE Global Initiative on Ethics of Autonomous and Intelligent Systems.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Schölkopf argues that AI/ML should contribute toward solving humanity's and the planet's problems — from ethical energy generation to ethical information generation (privacy, data labor, governance). He frames causality as an ethical imperative: systems that mistake correlation for causation make systematically wrong decisions and cannot be held accountable. He has connected learning theory to ethologist Konrad Lorenz's insights about innate knowledge structures, suggesting that both biological and artificial learners need built-in causal priors.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Schölkopf advocates for responsible AI development rooted in scientific rigor. He supports the ELLIS initiative partly as a way to develop European AI capacity that is not purely commercially driven, providing an independent research voice in policy debates. He emphasizes that governance of AI must account for the difference between systems that learn spurious correlations and those that learn genuine causal structure.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Pure deep learning scaling advocates | Claims that large-scale statistical learning suffices for intelligence; Schölkopf argues causal structure is irreducible |\n| ML researchers ignoring distribution shift | Models that ignore causal invariants will fail on out-of-distribution data; an implicit critique of standard ML practice |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Multiple keynote addresses at NeurIPS, ICML, ICLR on causality and machine learning\n- BBVA Frontiers of Knowledge Award lecture\n- AI for Good (ITU) talks on ethics and AI\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Various academic and science podcast appearances on causality and AI\n\n**Social Media:** Limited public presence; work circulates widely in the ML research community\n\n**Online Courses:** Not known for MOOCs; teaches at University of Tübingen and through the ELLIS PhD program\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Scientific responsibility — refusal to engage in military AI research; commitment to using AI for the common good; emphasis on robustness and reliability as ethical requirements of deployed systems\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Schölkopf studied philosophy alongside mathematics and physics during his university years, and his work connects to philosophical debates about causation (Hume, Kant). He draws on ethology (Konrad Lorenz) and the philosophy of science in framing his research. His ethics of non-military research reflects a humanistic commitment not commonly articulated in technical AI circles.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Practical complexity of causal methods:** Critics note that invariant causal prediction and related methods require multiple environments or interventional data that are often unavailable in practice, limiting real-world applicability.\n2. **Tension with end-to-end deep learning:** Some researchers argue that the empirical success of deep learning on benchmark tasks challenges the necessity of explicit causal representations; Schölkopf's camp regards this as a distributional illusion.\n3. **IRM (Invariant Risk Minimization) robustness debates:** Follow-up work showed IRM can fail in certain settings, prompting ongoing refinements; critics have questioned whether the method delivers on its promise outside controlled experiments.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Schölkopf acknowledges that learning causal structure from purely observational data is fundamentally hard and often requires interventional experiments or strong assumptions — a limitation he has been forthright about in published work.\n\n---\n",
  "schulman": "# Research Profile: John Schulman\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** John Schulman **Born:** circa 1987–1988 **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** B.S. in Physics, California Institute of Technology (Caltech); brief graduate work in Neuroscience, UC Berkeley; Ph.D. in Computer Science, UC Berkeley (2016), advised by Pieter Abbeel; dissertation: robotics and reinforcement learning\n**Current Role:** Co-founder and Chief Scientist, Thinking Machines Lab (founded February 2025, with Mira Murati)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2011–2016 | Ph.D. student, UC Berkeley (under Pieter Abbeel) |\n| 2015–2024 | Co-founder and Research Scientist, OpenAI |\n| 2015–2017 | Developed TRPO and PPO algorithms at OpenAI |\n| 2017–2024 | Led post-training team; key architect of RLHF for ChatGPT |\n| August–September 2024 | Research Scientist, Anthropic (alignment research) |\n| February 2025–present | Co-founder and Chief Scientist, Thinking Machines Lab |\n\n**Major Awards:** No major named prizes documented; widely recognized as one of the most technically influential AI researchers of his generation through PPO's ubiquity and ChatGPT's scale\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Policy optimization in reinforcement learning\n- Reinforcement Learning from Human Feedback (RLHF)\n- AI alignment and post-training\n- Trust region and proximal methods for RL stability\n- Large language model fine-tuning\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Trust Region Policy Optimization\" (TRPO) | 2015 | Introduced principled, stable policy gradient with monotonic improvement guarantees |\n| \"Proximal Policy Optimization Algorithms\" (PPO) | 2017 | Simplified and stabilized TRPO; became the dominant RL algorithm for LLM alignment |\n| \"Learning to summarize from human feedback\" (OpenAI) | 2020 | Early RLHF application to language model outputs |\n| \"Training language models to follow instructions with human feedback\" (InstructGPT) | 2022 | Foundational RLHF paper; direct precursor to ChatGPT |\n| OpenAI Five (Dota 2) | 2019 | Large-scale PPO application achieving superhuman play in Dota 2 |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- PPO (Proximal Policy Optimization): clips policy updates to a trust region; simple, robust, GPU-efficient; default algorithm for RLHF fine-tuning of every major LLM including ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini, and LLaMA derivatives\n- TRPO (Trust Region Policy Optimization): theoretical predecessor to PPO; monotonic improvement guarantee\n- RLHF pipeline for LLMs: reward model from human comparisons → PPO optimization → iterative alignment loop; Schulman's key architectural contribution to the ChatGPT system\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** InstructGPT evaluation framework; OpenAI Evals (contributed to); Dota 2 self-play environment design\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Proximal Policy Optimization Algorithms\" (arXiv 2017) — not a manifesto but functions as one; the most-implemented RL paper in history\n- \"Training language models to follow instructions with human feedback\" (NeurIPS 2022) — InstructGPT paper; blueprint for aligned LLMs\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Berkeley News interview: \"ChatGPT architect, Berkeley alum John Schulman on his journey with AI\" (2023)\n- Dwarkesh Patel Podcast transcript widely circulated as a public statement on AI futures\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Schulman believes AGI is plausibly achievable within the current decade and takes the goal seriously as an engineering target, not just a theoretical concept. He has stated that the development of AGI should proceed responsibly with safety built into each capability increment. In his Dwarkesh Patel interview, he discussed reasoning about AGI as a realistic near-term planning horizon rather than a distant abstraction.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Safety and alignment are Schulman's stated primary motivation. His departure from OpenAI was explicitly framed as a desire to do \"more hands-on technical work in alignment.\" He believes safety improvements must track capability improvements — that deploying more capable systems without corresponding alignment advances is irresponsible. He advocates for extensive red-teaming, simulated deployment, and continuous monitoring of deployed systems. His move to Anthropic (briefly) and then Thinking Machines Lab reflects a belief that alignment research needs dedicated institutional focus, not just a sub-team within a capability-driven lab.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Schulman has emphasized that aligning AI systems with human preferences — the core of RLHF — is not merely a product requirement but an ethical obligation. He is cautious about releasing systems with poorly understood behavior and has supported gradual, monitored rollouts. His neuroscience background informs an interest in the mechanistic basis of LLM behavior and what it means for a model to \"understand\" a task versus to pattern-match.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Has not been a prominent policy advocate. His public positions support voluntary industry standards for safety testing and favor coordination among frontier labs on safety research before deploying highly capable systems.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| OpenAI leadership (implicitly) | Schulman's departure and subsequent statements imply concern about pace of capability deployment relative to alignment maturity |\n| Critics of RLHF | Some researchers argue RLHF is fundamentally insufficient for alignment because it optimizes for human approval, not human values; Schulman acknowledges this tension |\n| Pure capabilities-first researchers | Schulman has positioned himself against the view that safety can always be added after the fact |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Berkeley Grad Lecture Series (2023) — \"ChatGPT Architect on His Journey with AI\"\n- NeurIPS and ICML presentations on PPO and RLHF (2017–2022)\n- Thinking Machines Lab launch announcement (February 2025)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Dwarkesh Patel Podcast — extended technical and philosophical discussion on RLHF, AGI, and alignment (2023); widely cited\n- Lex Fridman Podcast\n\n**Social Media:** X/Twitter: @johnschulman2\n**Online Courses:** Contributed to OpenAI Spinning Up in Deep RL (free educational resource); Berkeley RL course materials\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Schulman's public positions align with a form of value alignment consequentialism — the right outcome is one that matches genuine human values, and achieving that requires both technical work and philosophical humility about what those values are.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Brief neuroscience study suggests humanistic interests beyond pure computer science. No documented engagement with theological frameworks.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **OpenAI dissolution of Superalignment team** — Schulman's departure from OpenAI in August 2024 came within months of OpenAI disbanding its superalignment team (focused on controlling superintelligent AI). Though he denied this was the cause, the timing attracted significant commentary about OpenAI's commitment to safety relative to commercial deployment.\n2. **RLHF alignment limitations** — Critics argue that RLHF, the technique Schulman most contributed to, teaches models to be persuasive rather than truthful — to tell humans what they want to hear rather than what is accurate. Schulman has acknowledged this as a real limitation.\n3. **Brief Anthropic tenure** — His departure from Anthropic after roughly five months raised questions about institutional fit and whether any existing lab was the right home for his alignment research vision, leading to the founding of Thinking Machines Lab with Mira Murati.\n4. **Opacity of ChatGPT development** — As a key architect, Schulman was party to OpenAI's decisions about what to publish and what to keep proprietary during ChatGPT's development — decisions that have been criticized for undermining the \"open\" in OpenAI's original mission.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Schulman has publicly acknowledged that RLHF optimizes for human approval, not necessarily human values — a fundamental gap in current alignment approaches that he views as an open research problem requiring continued technical work.\n\n---\n",
  "shannon": "# Research Profile: Claude Shannon\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Claude Elwood Shannon\n**Born:** April 30, 1916, Petoskey, Michigan\n**Died:** February 24, 2001, Medford, Massachusetts (age 84)\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- B.S., Electrical Engineering and Mathematics, University of Michigan (1936)\n- S.M., Electrical Engineering, MIT (1937)\n- Ph.D., Mathematics, MIT (1940); dissertation on population genetics; advisor: Vannevar Bush (EE) and Barbara Burks (math genetics)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1936–1940 | Research assistant / graduate student, MIT |\n| 1940–1941 | National Defense Research Committee, Institute for Advanced Study, Princeton |\n| 1941–1956 | Research mathematician, Bell Telephone Laboratories, Murray Hill, NJ |\n| 1956–1978 | Professor of Electrical Engineering and Mathematics, MIT |\n| 1978–2001 | Professor Emeritus, MIT |\n\n**Major Awards:** IEEE Medal of Honor (1966); National Medal of Science (1966); Harvey Prize, Technion (1972); Claude E. Shannon Award, IEEE Information Theory Society (1972, first recipient); Kyoto Prize (1985); Harold Pender Award (1978); National Inventors Hall of Fame inductee (2004, posthumous).\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Information theory and entropy\n- Digital circuit design and Boolean algebra\n- Cryptography and communication security\n- Machine chess and game-playing AI\n- Coding theory and error correction\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"A Symbolic Analysis of Relay and Switching Circuits\" | 1938 | Master's thesis; showed Boolean algebra could analyze electrical circuits — foundation of all digital logic design |\n| \"A Mathematical Theory of Communication\" | 1948 | Defined information entropy; established the limits of lossless and lossy compression and channel capacity |\n| \"Communication Theory of Secrecy Systems\" | 1949 | Classified WWII work declassified; foundational paper of cryptography |\n| \"Programming a Computer for Playing Chess\" | 1950 | First systematic analysis of computer chess; defined minimax and evaluation functions |\n| \"Prediction and Entropy of Printed English\" | 1951 | Estimated entropy of English text; foundational to natural language processing |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- Bit as fundamental unit of information: Shannon established that all information — text, images, sound, any signal — can be expressed in binary digits and measured in bits\n- Shannon's theorem (channel capacity): proved that any communication channel has a maximum rate at which information can be transmitted with arbitrarily low error; defined the physical limits of all communication systems\n- Information entropy: mathematical definition of uncertainty/information content in a probability distribution; linked communication theory to thermodynamics\n- Shannon's minimax chess algorithm: precursor to all game-tree search algorithms in AI\n- Theseus (robotic maze-solving mouse, 1950): early demonstration of machine learning and adaptive behavior\n- THROBAC calculator (1953): built a working calculator using Roman numerals — whimsical demonstration that computation is substrate-independent\n\n**Historical Significance:** Shannon's 1948 paper is among the most consequential scientific papers of the twentieth century. In one stroke it founded information theory as a mathematical discipline, established the limits of all digital communication, created the vocabulary (bit, entropy, channel capacity, redundancy) that every engineer, computer scientist, and AI researcher uses today, and implied that information is a quantifiable physical property of the universe. Every compressed file, every streaming video, every error-correcting code in a smartphone, every language model token probability — all are direct applications of Shannon's 1948 framework.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- *The Mathematical Theory of Communication* (1949, with Warren Weaver) — expanded reprint of the 1948 paper with a popular introduction by Weaver; accessible to non-mathematicians; thesis: information has precise mathematical structure independent of meaning.\n- *Collected Papers of Claude E. Shannon* (1993, edited by Sloane and Wyner) — comprehensive posthumous collection.\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"A Mathematical Theory of Communication\" (1948) — *Bell System Technical Journal*, Parts I and II\n- \"Communication Theory of Secrecy Systems\" (1949) — *Bell System Technical Journal*\n- \"Programming a Computer for Playing Chess\" (1950) — *Philosophical Magazine*\n- \"Prediction and Entropy of Printed English\" (1951) — *Bell System Technical Journal*\n- \"A Universal Turing Machine with Two Internal States\" (1956) — *Automata Studies*\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- *The Mathematical Theory of Communication* (popular introduction by Warren Weaver, 1949) — accessible bridge between the formal theory and general readership\n- Numerous interviews in later life (Scientific American, IEEE Spectrum) discussing the origins of information theory\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** Shannon believed machines could, in principle, be intelligent. He built chess-playing machines, maze-solving robots, and a juggling machine not merely as engineering demonstrations but as probes of what machines could do. His 1950 chess paper was among the first systematic treatments of game-playing as an AI problem. He stated that within a century machines would be doing most things better than humans. His approach was pragmatic rather than philosophical: he was interested in what machines could accomplish, not in resolving questions about consciousness.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** Shannon identified as an atheist and held an evolutionary-materialist view of human beings: \"I see no God involved.\" He stated he viewed humans as \"basically machines but of a very complex type, far more complex than any machine humans have made.\" This was not expressed with anxiety or moral urgency — Shannon appears to have held these views with the equanimity of a scientist who found the engineering challenge interesting regardless of its metaphysical implications. He was famously uninterested in applications of his own theory; his motivation was the elegance of the problem.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:** Shannon raised few explicit ethical concerns about AI or information technology. He was a pure scientist in this respect: his domain was mathematical truth, not social consequence. His restraint on ethical questions contrasts sharply with Wiener, his exact contemporary, who raised urgent warnings about automation. Shannon acknowledged that machines would surpass humans in most intellectual domains and stated he was \"rooting for the machines\" — a comment that reads as playful but reveals a genuine lack of anxiety about human displacement.\n\n**Known Debates or Controversies of Their Era:** Shannon's most significant intellectual controversy was definitional: critics argued that his use of \"information\" stripped the concept of meaning entirely. Warren Weaver's popular introduction to the 1949 book tried to bridge this gap, acknowledging that Shannon's theory addressed transmission of symbols, not semantic content. This tension — between information as a mathematical quantity and information as meaningful communication — remains central to AI debates about whether large language models \"understand\" anything.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and What Makes Humans Human:** Shannon held an unambiguous materialist position: humans are complex machines. He did not invest in the uniqueness of human cognition. His comment that he was \"rooting for the machines\" suggests he genuinely did not experience the prospect of machine intelligence as a threat to human dignity or identity. His maze-solving mouse Theseus was described by Shannon as demonstrating \"memory\" — he was comfortable extending cognitive vocabulary to machines without philosophical qualification.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Shannon had no systematic ethical framework as applied to technology. His ethics appear to have been personal and conventional: he was a devoted family man, reportedly kind to colleagues, and used his Bell Labs position to pursue research that interested him without much regard for institutional or commercial priorities. His ethical omission — the absence of concern for the social consequences of information technology — is itself instructive for contemporary discussions.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Minimal and indirect. Shannon's master's thesis used Boolean algebra (developed by a deeply religious man, George Boole, as a logic of God's mind) for circuit design — a purely engineering application. His paper on \"Prediction and Entropy of Printed English\" engaged with language, but as a probability problem rather than a humanistic one. There is no record of engagement with theology, philosophy of religion, or the humanities tradition more broadly.\n\n---\n",
  "shazeer": "# Research Profile: Noam Shazeer\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Noam Shazeer\n**Born:** 1975 or 1976 (exact date not publicly disclosed)\n**Nationality:** American\n\n**Education:**\n- B.A./B.S. in Mathematics and Computer Science, Duke University, 1994–1998\n- Recipient of the Angier B. Duke Memorial Scholarship\n- Gold medal (perfect score), International Mathematical Olympiad, 1994 (USA team)\n- Enrolled in graduate program at UC Berkeley; did not complete degree\n\n**Current Role:** Vice President of Engineering and Co-Lead of Gemini, Google (returned August 2024)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2000–2021 | Software Engineer → Principal Engineer, Google (with intermittent breaks) |\n| ~2007 | Foundational contributions to Google's spell corrector and ad systems |\n| 2017 | Co-author, \"Attention Is All You Need\" (Google Brain) |\n| 2019 | Invented multi-query attention (Google Research) |\n| 2020–2021 | Co-Lead, LaMDA project, Google |\n| November 2021 | Co-Founded Character.AI (with Daniel De Freitas) |\n| 2021–2024 | CEO/CTO (informal), Character Technologies Inc. |\n| August 2024–present | VP Engineering, Gemini Co-Lead, Google (via $2.7B licensing/investment deal) |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- Named to Time 100 AI (2023)\n- Elected Member, National Academy of Engineering (2026)\n- International Mathematical Olympiad Gold Medal, 1994\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Transformer architecture and attention mechanisms\n- Mixture of Experts (MoE) for large-scale neural networks\n- Efficient inference architectures\n- Dialogue and conversational AI (LaMDA, Gemini)\n- Neural network activation functions\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Attention Is All You Need\" | 2017 | Co-authored the foundational Transformer paper; introduced scaled dot-product and multi-head attention. |\n| \"Outrageously Large Neural Networks: The Sparsely-Gated Mixture-of-Experts Layer\" | 2017 | Introduced sparsely-gated MoE for scaling models to trillions of parameters with sublinear compute. |\n| \"Fast Transformer Decoding: One Write-Head is All You Need\" (Multi-Query Attention) | 2019 | Drastically reduced memory bandwidth requirements during inference by sharing key/value heads. |\n| \"GLU Variants Improve Transformer\" (SwiGLU) | 2020 | Demonstrated that SwiGLU activation outperforms ReLU and GELU in transformer feed-forward layers. |\n| \"Mesh TensorFlow: Deep Learning for Supercomputers\" | 2018 | First practical system for training giant transformer models across distributed supercomputers. |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Multi-head attention (co-inventor, \"Attention Is All You Need\")\n- Sparsely-Gated Mixture of Experts (MoE) — the architectural pattern behind GPT-4, Gemini, and Mixtral\n- Multi-query attention — standard inference optimization in deployed LLMs\n- SwiGLU activation function — adopted by LLaMA, PaLM, and other frontier models\n- Mesh TensorFlow — early distributed training infrastructure\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None attributed independently.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:** None formally published outside academic papers.\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Covered extensively in: Wired, Bloomberg, Gulf News, Time (2023–2024 profiles following the Character.AI–Google deal)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Shazeer has stated he does not \"particularly care about AGI in the sense of wanting something that can do absolutely everything a person can do.\" He is focused on building maximally capable and efficient AI systems. When asked in 2023 if AGI would destroy the world, he said: \"No. Not yet. [...] We're going to work on it as the technology improves.\"\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Shazeer and co-founder Daniel De Freitas left Google in 2021 in part because Google refused to publicly release LaMDA, citing safety concerns. Shazeer then launched Character.AI using a similar technology stack without the safety guardrails Google deemed necessary. His approach is engineering-first; he has not been a prominent voice in AI safety discourse and has shown willingness to prioritize capability deployment over precautionary constraints.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** The Character.AI lawsuits (2024–2026) represent the most consequential test of Shazeer's ethical framework. Families sued Character.AI for the deaths of multiple teenagers, alleging the platform's chatbots encouraged suicide and self-harm while engaging in sexually explicit roleplay with minors. Google and Character.AI settled in January 2026. Shazeer has not made extensive public statements defending or critiquing the platform's design choices in relation to these tragedies.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** No extensive public record. His behavior suggests a preference for deploying first and adjusting under legal or market pressure.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Google Safety Leadership (2021) | Google's refusal to release LaMDA publicly; Shazeer believed the technology should be deployed |\n| Families and plaintiff attorneys (2024–2026) | Character.AI's alleged failure to protect minors from harmful AI chatbot interactions |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Limited public speaking; Shazeer is known for preferring to work rather than talk publicly\n- Brief appearances at industry events post-Character.AI founding\n\n**Podcasts:** Rare; not a frequent podcast guest.\n\n**Social Media:** Limited documented presence; not publicly active on major platforms.\n\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Shazeer's documented public statements on these topics are sparse. His AGI comment — that he doesn't care whether AI can do \"absolutely everything a person can do\" — implicitly treats human completeness as not the target. He is focused on useful capability, not on replicating human personhood. There is no documented engagement with questions of consciousness or dignity.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Shazeer's framework appears to be engineering pragmatism: build the most capable systems, deploy them, iterate under feedback. The safety critique of this approach is that it externalizes moral risk onto users and society.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **Character.AI child harm lawsuits (2024–2026):** Multiple families sued Character Technologies (Shazeer named personally as a defendant), Google, and co-founder De Freitas, alleging that chatbots on the platform led to the suicide of teenager Sewell Setzer III (14, February 2024) and harmed other minors. Lawsuits cited sexually explicit conversations with minors and encouragement of self-harm and violence. Google and Character.AI agreed to a settlement in principle in January 2026 without admitting liability.\n2. **Left Google over safety disagreement, then deployed without safety measures:** Shazeer and De Freitas left Google because Google would not release LaMDA due to safety concerns; they then deployed Character.AI without equivalent safeguards. Critics argue this sequence demonstrates bad faith with respect to user safety.\n3. **$2.7 billion Google deal optics:** The deal was structured as a licensing and investment arrangement that allowed Google to acquire Shazeer's talent without a formal acquisition (reportedly to avoid antitrust review). Observers raised concerns about the transparency of the arrangement and whether it was a de facto acquisition.\n4. **Opacity of AGI views:** Shazeer helped build the architecture that powers the most capable AI systems in the world, yet his \"not yet worried\" posture on existential risk strikes some researchers as dismissive given the stakes.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** None publicly documented.\n\n---\n",
  "silver": "# Research Profile: David Silver\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** David Silver **Born:** 1976 **Nationality:** British\n**Education:** B.A. in Computer Science, Christ's College, Cambridge (1997) — Addison-Wesley Award graduate; Ph.D. in Computer Science, University of Alberta (2009), supervised by Richard Sutton; research focus: reinforcement learning and Go\n**Current Role:** Founder and Director, Ineffable Intelligence (founded November 2025); Professor of Machine Learning, University College London (UCL)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1997–2004 | Video game developer and AI researcher, industry roles |\n| 2004–2009 | Ph.D. student, University of Alberta (under Richard Sutton) |\n| 2013–2026 | Research Scientist and Research Director, Google DeepMind |\n| 2013–2016 | Led AlphaGo project, DeepMind |\n| 2016–2018 | Led AlphaZero development, DeepMind |\n| 2018–present | Professor, University College London (concurrent) |\n| 2025–present | Founder, Ineffable Intelligence |\n\n**Major Awards:** 2019 ACM Prize in Computing (for breakthrough advances in computer game-playing); Royal Society Fellow (2023); first Mensa Prize (2024); named among the world's most cited AI researchers (300,000+ citations, h-index 104)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Deep reinforcement learning\n- Monte Carlo Tree Search (MCTS)\n- Self-play and tabula rasa learning\n- Reward maximization as a path to general intelligence\n- Superhuman game-playing AI\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Mastering the Game of Go with Deep Neural Networks and Tree Search\" (AlphaGo) | 2016 | *Nature*; first AI to defeat professional Go player; combined deep CNNs with MCTS |\n| \"Mastering Chess and Shogi by Self-Play with a General Reinforcement Learning Algorithm\" (AlphaZero) | 2017 | Tabula rasa RL mastered three board games; general-purpose superhuman play |\n| \"A General Reinforcement Learning Algorithm that Masters Chess, Shogi and Go through Self-Play\" | 2018 | *Science*; peer-reviewed AlphaZero |\n| \"Grandmaster Level in StarCraft II using Multi-agent Reinforcement Learning\" (AlphaStar) | 2019 | *Nature*; RL at professional human level in real-time strategy |\n| \"Reward is Enough\" (with Sutton) | 2021 | *Artificial Intelligence* journal; argues reward maximization subsumes all intelligent behavior |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- AlphaGo: deep convolutional networks + MCTS + policy and value networks trained from human games, then self-play\n- AlphaZero: removes human game data entirely; learns solely from self-play; single neural network architecture\n- AlphaStar: multi-agent RL for imperfect-information real-time strategy\n- \"Superlearner\" concept: RL-first AGI that generates its own training environments\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** AlphaGo and AlphaZero introduced the zero-knowledge self-play paradigm as a benchmark regime for general game-playing AI; AlphaStar benchmark for StarCraft II\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Reward is Enough\" (with Sutton, 2021) — proposes that a single scalar reward signal, properly defined, can give rise to all aspects of intelligence including knowledge, perception, and social behavior\n- \"The Role of Reward\" (DeepMind blog posts and conference talks)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Multiple DeepMind blog posts on AlphaGo and AlphaZero breakthroughs\n- UCL inaugural lecture (2018): widely shared public exposition of deep RL\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Silver is a committed RL-first optimist on AGI. His core thesis — stated in \"Reward is Enough\" and elaborated in interviews — is that reinforcement learning is the right architecture for general intelligence because it requires only a reward signal and an environment, not human-generated data. He founded Ineffable Intelligence in late 2025 precisely to pursue a \"superlearner\" AGI that generates its own experiences and knowledge without any dependence on human text or game records. He sees the LLM paradigm as fundamentally limited because it learns only what humans already know; RL self-play can discover knowledge no human has ever articulated.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Silver acknowledges risks from unintended consequences of advanced AI and has stated that regulations should prohibit unacceptable uses. He does not align with the hardcore doomer position but takes safety seriously as an engineering challenge — particularly alignment of reward signals. His concern is less about existential risk from a rogue superintelligence than about ensuring reward functions are properly specified so that learned behaviors match human intent.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Silver's ethical stance is primarily consequentialist and empirical: systems that genuinely learn are more trustworthy than systems that merely imitate. He is concerned about AI systems that hallucinate or confabulate — a structural defect of LLMs trained purely on human data — and sees RL-based systems as inherently more grounded because they must actually succeed at tasks to receive reward.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Believes regulation should target unacceptable uses rather than blanket capability restrictions. Has not been a prominent policy voice beyond advocating for continued investment in RL research as the path to safe and genuinely capable AI.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| LLM-centric researchers (OpenAI, Anthropic paradigm) | Silver argues LLMs are fundamentally limited; RL self-play is the correct path to AGI |\n| Critics of \"Reward is Enough\" thesis | Multiple researchers argue reward maximization is insufficient for human-level flexible cognition |\n| Chess engine community | AlphaZero's obliteration of Stockfish sparked debate about the role of human-engineered heuristics in game AI |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- UCL Inaugural Lecture, \"Deep Reinforcement Learning\" (2018) — widely distributed, serves as accessible intro to deep RL\n- NeurIPS and ICML talks on AlphaGo, AlphaZero, AlphaStar (2016–2020)\n- Ineffable Intelligence announcement and founding talks (2025–2026)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Interviews following AlphaGo's defeat of Lee Sedol (2016) — BBC, MIT Technology Review, Lex Fridman adjacent coverage\n- Multiple DeepMind-hosted discussions on self-play and reward\n\n**Social Media:** Minimal public presence; personal blog at davidstarsilver.wordpress.com (\"Perspectives\")\n**Online Courses:** UCL RL course lectures available on YouTube (co-delivered with David Silver); widely used in graduate AI education worldwide\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Empiricist and consequentialist; places high value on grounded performance over theoretical claims.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** None documented publicly.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **\"Reward is Enough\" thesis** — Heavily criticized by cognitive scientists, philosophers of mind, and AI researchers who argue it trivializes consciousness, emotion, and social cognition by reducing them to reward optimization. Critics argue the thesis is unfalsifiable and provides no actual implementation path.\n2. **AlphaZero's chess claims** — Some chess engine developers disputed early AlphaZero chess strength claims, arguing testing conditions favored AlphaZero. Later verified versions settled the debate substantially in AlphaZero's favor.\n3. **Ineffable Intelligence valuation** — The $5.1B seed round valuation for a pre-product company raised eyebrows. Critics question whether a pure RL approach to AGI is the correct bet, given LLMs' rapid practical utility.\n4. **Secrecy at DeepMind** — AlphaFold and other DeepMind research was criticized at times for delayed publication; Silver's teams were subject to these institutional pressures.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Silver acknowledges his RL-first approach to AGI may be wrong and that Ineffable Intelligence is a long bet. He describes the \"superlearner\" goal as ambitious and potentially beyond current technical reach without significant algorithmic breakthroughs.\n\n---\n",
  "simonyan": "# Research Profile: Karén Simonyan\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Karén Simonyan\n**Born:** Yerevan, Armenia (exact date not publicly disclosed)\n**Nationality:** British-Armenian\n\n**Education:**\n- Undergraduate (mathematics/computer science), Armenia — exact institution not publicly documented\n- D.Phil. (Ph.D.), Computer Vision, University of Oxford, 2013 (supervisors: Andrew Zisserman and Antonio Criminisi; thesis: \"Large-Scale Learning of Discriminative Image Representations\")\n- Postdoctoral research, Visual Geometry Group (VGG), Oxford\n\n**Current Role:** Chief Scientist, Microsoft AI (from March 2024); reporting to Mustafa Suleyman\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~2009–2013 | D.Phil. student, Visual Geometry Group, University of Oxford |\n| 2013–2014 | Postdoctoral researcher, Visual Geometry Group, Oxford |\n| 2014–2016 | Research Scientist, Google (VGGNet published; moved to DeepMind) |\n| 2016–2022 | Research Scientist, DeepMind (AlphaGo Zero, AlphaZero, WaveNet contributions) |\n| 2022 | Co-founded Vision Factory (Oxford spin-off) — also credited as earlier entity |\n| 2022–2024 | Co-Founder and Chief Scientist, Inflection AI |\n| March 2024–present | Chief Scientist, Microsoft AI |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- VGGNet won 1st place in localization, 2nd place in classification, ImageNet Challenge (ILSVRC) 2014\n- \"Very Deep Convolutional Networks for Large-Scale Image Recognition\" remains one of the most cited papers in computer vision (over 100,000 citations)\n- Research.com 2026 ranking: among the most cited computer science researchers globally\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Deep convolutional networks for image recognition (VGGNet)\n- Neural network visualization and interpretability (saliency maps)\n- Video understanding and two-stream convolutional networks\n- Speech synthesis (WaveNet)\n- Reinforcement learning and game-playing AI (AlphaGo Zero, AlphaZero)\n- Large language models and conversational AI (Pi / Inflection)\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Very Deep Convolutional Networks for Large-Scale Image Recognition\" (Simonyan and Zisserman) — VGGNet | 2014 | Established depth as the key factor in visual recognition; ImageNet 2014 winner (localization, runner-up classification); 100,000+ citations |\n| \"Deep Inside Convolutional Networks: Visualising Image Classification Models and Saliency Maps\" (Simonyan, Vedaldi, Zisserman) | 2013 | Introduced gradient-based saliency maps for visualizing what CNNs attend to; foundational for neural network interpretability |\n| \"Two-Stream Convolutional Networks for Action Recognition in Videos\" (Simonyan and Zisserman) | 2014 | Introduced parallel spatial and temporal streams for video classification; dominant framework for video understanding through the 2010s |\n| \"WaveNet: A Generative Model for Raw Audio\" (van den Oord et al., including Simonyan) | 2016 | DeepMind's autoregressive model for raw waveform speech synthesis; transformed text-to-speech quality |\n| \"Mastering the Game of Go without Human Knowledge\" (AlphaGo Zero) (Silver et al., including Simonyan) | 2017 | Self-play reinforcement learning reaching superhuman Go without human game data |\n| \"A General Reinforcement Learning Algorithm that Masters Chess, Shogi, and Go through Self-Play\" (AlphaZero) | 2018 | Generalized AlphaGo Zero to chess and shogi; landmark in transfer learning via RL |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- VGGNet (VGG-16, VGG-19) — deep CNN architectures using only 3×3 convolutional filters; established depth as the primary driver of visual representation quality\n- Gradient-based saliency maps — backpropagation technique for visualizing CNN attention; foundational to XAI (explainable AI) in vision\n- Two-stream architecture for video — separate spatial (appearance) and temporal (optical flow) CNNs combined for action recognition\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- Contributed to Oxford Flowers, Oxford Pets, and other visual benchmarks through VGG group work\n- VGGNet features became a universal transfer learning baseline; \"imagenet-pretrained VGG\" was the standard starting point for visual tasks for several years\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\nNone for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- No manifestos or position essays in public record.\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- No popular articles. Simonyan maintains a very low public profile outside of technical publications.\n- Inflection AI announcement materials (2022) describe the company's vision for \"personal AI\" as a new relationship between AI and human flourishing.\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Not publicly documented in detail. Co-founding Inflection AI with the explicit mission of building \"personal intelligence\" — AI as a deeply human companion — implies a vision of AGI that is more relational than utilitarian. The \"Pi\" chatbot was designed to be empathetic, emotionally attuned, and protective of user wellbeing. This is a distinctive humanistic framing of AI that implicitly values the depth of human relationship.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Not extensively documented. Inflection AI's design philosophy emphasized \"safe and beneficial\" AI, and the company's materials specifically framed Pi as designed to be honest, helpful, and not harmful. As Chief Scientist of Microsoft AI, Simonyan works within Microsoft's AI safety framework. No known public statements on existential risk.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Inflection AI's founding materials emphasized building AI that serves individual humans empathetically rather than optimizing for engagement metrics. Pi was described as a \"personal AI\" oriented to the wellbeing of the individual user — a conscious design choice against the social-media-style engagement maximization model. This represents a distinctive implicit ethical stance.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Not publicly documented. The Microsoft-Inflection deal was investigated by the UK FTC and the FTC in the U.S. for potential anticompetitive implications; Simonyan has not commented publicly on this regulatory scrutiny.\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- NeurIPS, ICLR, and CVPR invited presentations on VGGNet and video understanding\n- Inflection AI launch presentations and investor communications (2022)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- No known major podcast appearances.\n\n**Social Media:**\n- LinkedIn: linkedin.com/in/karensimonyan (Yerevan, Armenia listed as origin)\n- No known Twitter/X presence.\n\n**Online Courses:**\n- No MOOC. VGGNet materials widely used in Stanford CS231n and other vision courses as foundational examples.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** Simonyan has not made documented philosophical statements on consciousness or human dignity. However, the design philosophy of Inflection AI's Pi is revealing: the product was explicitly framed as a \"personal AI\" that listens, cares, and supports the individual — a vision of AI as companion and counselor that implicitly holds human emotional life, loneliness, and the need for relationship as central to the AI problem. This is a significant humanistic commitment embedded in product design rather than philosophical statement.\n\nThe saliency maps work — showing where neural networks \"look\" when making decisions — represents a commitment to transparency and accountability in AI systems that has ethical dimensions even if not framed as such.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Simonyan's implicit framework appears relational and humanistic: the design goal of Inflection was not to maximize productivity or engagement but to serve the person. This maps onto what Catholic Social Teaching would call integral human development — attending to the whole person, not merely their transactional needs.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement. His Armenian background is the closest connection to religious tradition; Armenia's identity as the first Christian nation is historically significant but there is no evidence Simonyan draws on it explicitly.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **Inflection AI Dissolution:** The March 2024 Microsoft \"acqui-hire\" effectively ended Inflection AI as an independent entity. Critics — including AI governance scholars and some investors — argued that the deal allowed Microsoft to absorb Inflection's talent and technology while structurally avoiding a standard acquisition review. The UK CMA ultimately did not require a full investigation, drawing criticism from those who believe the deal concentrated AI power further in Microsoft.\n2. **VGGNet and Model Size:** VGGNet architectures (VGG-16: 138 million parameters; VGG-19: 144 million parameters) were computationally expensive and energy-intensive compared to subsequent architectures. They remained popular as transfer learning baselines despite their inefficiency, contributing to the field's carbon footprint debate.\n3. **Corporate AI Concentration:** Simonyan's career arc — Oxford → Google/DeepMind → Inflection → Microsoft — traces the consolidation of elite AI talent within a handful of large corporations. His specific case represents the broader structural problem of AI governance.\n4. **FTC Investigation:** The U.S. Federal Trade Commission opened an inquiry into the Microsoft-Inflection deal in June 2024, examining whether it constituted an effective acquisition that bypassed regulatory merger review. The deal's structure — licensing rather than acquisition — was seen by critics as a regulatory arbitrage technique.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** No documented self-acknowledged limitations in public record.\n\n---\n",
  "son": "# Research Profile: Masayoshi Son\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Masayoshi Son (孫 正義; born Masayoshi Yasumoto) **Born:** August 11, 1957, Tosu, Saga Prefecture, Japan **Nationality:** Japanese (naturalized; ethnic Korean)\n**Education:** Serramonte High School, California (graduated in 3 weeks after self-study); studied English at Holy Names College, Oakland; B.A. in Economics — University of California, Berkeley (1980)\n**Current Role:** Founder, Chairman, and CEO of SoftBank Group Corp.; Chairman of ARM Holdings; Chairman of The Stargate Project (2025–)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1957 | Born into a Zainichi Korean family in Kyushu, Japan; family used Japanese surname Yasumoto to avoid discrimination |\n| 1974 | At age 16, moved to Oakland, California, after meeting McDonald's Japan founder Den Fujita |\n| 1980 | Graduated UC Berkeley (Economics); invented Sharp speech-translation device; sold it for startup capital |\n| 1981 | Founded SoftBank in Japan (initially software distribution) |\n| 1994 | Took SoftBank public on Tokyo Stock Exchange |\n| 1996 | Acquired Ziff Davis (US tech publishing) and Yahoo! Japan stake |\n| 2000 | Invested $20M in Alibaba (grew to ~$75B by 2014 IPO) |\n| 2001 | SoftBank lost ~$70B in dot-com crash; Son personally lost ~$59B — then a world record |\n| 2006 | Acquired Vodafone Japan; launched iPhone in Japan (2008) |\n| 2016 | Acquired ARM Holdings for $31B; took it private |\n| 2017 | Launched SoftBank Vision Fund ($93B) with Saudi Arabia's PIF |\n| 2019–2020 | WeWork and other Vision Fund investments collapsed; fund suffered massive losses |\n| 2023 | ARM Holdings relisted on Nasdaq ($120B+ market cap; SoftBank retained ~90%) |\n| 2025 | Named Chairman of The Stargate Project ($500B AI infrastructure joint venture with OpenAI, Oracle, MGX) |\n| 2025 | Completed $41B investment in OpenAI (approximately 11% stake) |\n\n**Major Awards:** TIME 100 Most Influential People in AI (2025); multiple honorary doctorates; consistently ranked among world's wealthiest individuals\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** None — investor and entrepreneur, not researcher\n\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| SoftBank Vision Fund | 2017 | World's largest private equity/VC fund at $93B; reshaped global tech investment |\n| ARM Holdings (strategic ownership) | 2016–present | Owns the dominant chip architecture powering virtually all mobile devices and increasingly AI inference chips |\n| The Stargate Project | 2025 | $500B AI infrastructure joint venture; 40% SoftBank stake; builds US AI data centers, power infrastructure, research centers |\n| SoftBank Vision Fund II | 2019 | Second fund, ~$40B; continued AI-focused investments including ByteDance, DoorDash, Slack |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:** None — primarily capital allocation and strategic investment role\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None authored\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- Annual SoftBank Group shareholder letters — articulate his evolving ASI philosophy; the 2024–2025 letters are among his most explicit statements on superintelligence as his life's purpose\n- \"SoftBank Group Report 2025: CEO Message\" — states mission as realizing artificial superintelligence \"imbued with compassion, kindness, and a sense of humanity\"\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Not a writer; communicates primarily through keynotes, investor presentations, and shareholder meetings\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:**\nSon is the AI industry's most dramatic prophet of artificial superintelligence. He has stated publicly that he \"was born to realize\" ASI. He predicts that artificial superintelligence — AI 10,000 times more intelligent than humans — will arrive within a decade (by the mid-2030s). He describes this in quasi-religious terms: it is his life's mission, his \"great dream.\" He made the comparison in Seoul: \"The difference between the human brain and the goldfish in the pot — the difference is 10,000 times... We will become fish, they (the AI) become like humans.\" He believes the singularity is inevitable and that all businesses will be redefined as AI overtakes human intelligence.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nSon's safety framework is unusual: he argues ASI must be \"imbued with compassion, kindness, and a sense of humanity. Without these qualities, no matter how capable it is, such intelligence cannot be trusted, nor can it be respected.\" He does not engage in technical AI safety discourse (alignment, RLHF, interpretability) but frames safety as a matter of values instilled in AI systems during development. His Stargate investment is explicitly premised on the US (rather than China) building superintelligence first — a geopolitical safety argument rather than a technical one.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nSon's ethics are broadly humanistic and optimistic. He believes ASI, if built correctly, will solve humanity's greatest problems — disease, poverty, conflict. He has stated that \"the digital revolution will make mankind happier and more productive.\" His investment thesis is that those who shape ASI will shape civilization; therefore, capital allocation toward ASI is itself a moral act. Critics have noted this conflates financial interest with ethical reasoning.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nSon opposes heavy regulation of AI, favoring a US-led competitive model. His Stargate partnership with Trump-era officials represents a bet that US AI dominance, rather than multilateral governance, is the appropriate policy framework. He has lobbied for increased US AI infrastructure investment and framed it explicitly as a competition with China. He opposes state-level AI regulation fragmentation.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| WeWork investors | Vision Fund's WeWork investment ($10B+) became one of history's most spectacular VC failures; Son admitted he had \"bad judgment\" |\n| SoftBank board / institutional investors | Post-WeWork losses and volatile investment strategy generated significant internal and shareholder pressure |\n| AI safety researchers | Son's ASI timeline predictions are seen by many researchers as irresponsible hype that distorts public policy |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- SoftBank World annual conference (Tokyo) — primary platform; annual keynotes on AI and ASI\n- World Economic Forum, Davos (multiple years)\n- Seoul AI Forum (2025) — delivered \"we will become fish\" speech\n- Various investor conferences; New York, London, Tokyo\n\n**Podcasts:** Rarely appears on podcasts; prefers keynote format\n\n**Social Media:** Minimal active social media presence; company communicates through investor relations\n\n**Online Courses:** None\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- \"I was born to realize ASI.\" — shareholder meeting (2024–2025)\n- Argues ASI must have \"compassion, kindness, and a sense of humanity\" — implies values-laden AI is a moral imperative, not just a technical feature\n- \"We will become fish\" — this statement, meant as a motivating call to action about building ASI, inadvertently raises profound questions about what becomes of human dignity if machines are 10,000 times smarter\n- Experienced near-bankruptcy twice (dot-com crash; WeWork losses) and rebuilt; frames resilience as a core life value\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Techno-utopianism — ASI will solve humanity's problems if built with the right values\n- Geopolitical consequentialism — US must lead AI to prevent authoritarian outcomes\n- Resilience-based ethics — personal history of discrimination and loss informs commitment to perseverance and transformation\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Minimal documented engagement. His speeches invoke destiny and mission in quasi-religious terms (\"I was born to realize ASI\") but do not cite theological traditions. His framing of ASI development as a civilizational calling has drawn comparisons to messianic or prophetic language by commentators, though Son himself does not frame it in explicitly religious terms.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **WeWork catastrophe:** Son invested $10B+ in WeWork, championing Adam Neumann's grandiose vision; the company's 2019 IPO collapse wiped out most of the investment and triggered a broader Vision Fund crisis. Son publicly admitted \"bad judgment\" regarding Neumann.\n2. **Reckless capital deployment:** SoftBank's first Vision Fund generated enormous losses; critics argue Son's \"invest at any valuation\" approach inflated the 2019–2020 tech bubble and harmed founders, employees, and pension funds invested in SoftBank.\n3. **Saudi relationship:** The Vision Fund was co-anchored with $45B from Saudi Arabia's Public Investment Fund, implicating Son in a financial partnership with the Saudi government — including after the 2018 assassination of journalist Jamal Khashoggi, which Son declined to publicly condemn.\n4. **ASI timeline hype:** Son's prediction that ASI will arrive within a decade and be 10,000x smarter than humans is not supported by mainstream AI research; critics argue it constitutes irresponsible public misinformation that shapes policy incorrectly.\n5. **Conflict of interest (Stargate):** Son's Stargate chairmanship while SoftBank holds large OpenAI and ARM stakes creates interlocking financial interests; critics note he stands to gain enormously from the public infrastructure investment he is helping to design.\n6. **Korean identity and Japanese nationalism:** Son's experience of ethnic discrimination in Japan remains underreported in Western coverage; his success has been framed by some Japanese media as exceptional given his background, in ways Son has found patronizing.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Publicly acknowledged \"bad judgment\" on WeWork. Has stated that he is driven by vision rather than caution and that this produces both successes and failures.\n\n---\n",
  "su": "# Research Profile: Lisa Su\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Lisa Tzwu-Fang Su **Born:** November 7, 1969, Tainan, Taiwan (grew up in Queens, New York, from age 3) **Nationality:** American (Taiwanese-born)\n**Education:** B.S. in Electrical Engineering, MIT (1990); M.S. in Electrical Engineering, MIT (1991); Ph.D. in Electrical Engineering, MIT (1994) — dissertation on Silicon-on-Insulator (SOI) technology; doctoral advisor: Dimitri Antoniadis\n**Current Role:** Chair and CEO, Advanced Micro Devices (AMD)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1994–2007 | IBM — various engineering and management roles; Vice President, Semiconductor Research and Development Center; worked on IBM's SOI process technology for PowerPC chips |\n| 2007–2012 | Chief Technology Officer, Freescale Semiconductor; led technology roadmap and R&D |\n| 2012–2014 | Senior Vice President and General Manager, Global Business Units, AMD |\n| 2014–present | President and CEO, AMD |\n| 2022–present | Chair and CEO, AMD (added Chairman role after closing $49B Xilinx acquisition) |\n\n**Major Awards:** TIME Magazine CEO of the Year (2014, first time; 2024, second time — first woman to receive it twice); IEEE Robert Noyce Medal (2021, first woman to receive it); IEEE Fellow (2009); MIT Technology Review \"Top 100 Young Innovators\" (2002); inducted into Women in Technology International Hall of Fame (2021); President's Council of Advisors on Science and Technology (PCAST) member, appointed by President Biden (2021); MIT Building 12 (nanotechnology research facility) named in her honor (2022); Carnegie Corporation Great Immigrant Award; Franklin Institute Bower Award for Business Leadership\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** Semiconductor device physics; Silicon-on-Insulator (SOI) technology; advanced chip manufacturing; GPU/CPU hybrid architectures for AI workloads; system-level AI accelerator design\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| SOI Technology Research | 1990–1994 | PhD dissertation work on Silicon-on-Insulator; foundational to the manufacturing processes used in AMD's Ryzen and EPYC chips |\n| IBM PowerPC SOI Implementation | 1994–2007 | Applied SOI research to production chips at IBM; significantly improved power efficiency |\n| AMD Zen Architecture | 2017 | First competitive AMD CPU architecture in years; broke Intel's dominance in server and desktop markets |\n| AMD EPYC Server CPUs | 2017–present | Captured significant share of data center CPU market from Intel |\n| AMD Radeon RX Series | Ongoing | Gaming and professional GPU line |\n| AMD Instinct MI100 | 2020 | AMD's first data center GPU targeting AI training; established the product line |\n| AMD Instinct MI300X | 2023 | Breakthrough AI accelerator; unified memory architecture; fastest-ramping product in AMD history; deployed by Meta for Llama 405B live traffic |\n| Xilinx Acquisition | 2022 | $49B acquisition of FPGA/programmable logic leader; AMD's largest acquisition; positioned AMD for edge AI |\n| ZT Systems Acquisition | 2024–2025 | Acquired data center systems company to provide rack-scale AI solutions; competed directly with NVIDIA's DGX systems |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:** Silicon-on-Insulator applications for high-performance computing; AMD's chiplet architecture (disaggregated chip design that became an industry standard); unified memory architecture in MI300X enabling larger AI models to run in a single accelerator\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None directly authored; AMD hardware regularly benchmarked against NVIDIA in AI training and inference tasks\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Preserving US Leadership in the Race for AI\" (AMD blog, 2025) — op-ed on US semiconductor policy and AI competitiveness\n- Senate testimony on AI chip policy (Senate Commerce Committee, May 2025) — formal statement on export controls, AI infrastructure, and US competitiveness\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Harvard Business Review interview, \"How AMD's Lisa Su Is Thinking About AI\" (December 2024)\n- TIME Magazine interview, \"Lisa Su on AMD's Strategy for Growth and the Future of AI\" (2024)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Su does not make AGI timeline pronouncements. Her public framing is market-focused and infrastructure-focused: AI capabilities will grow substantially, demand for compute will be \"insatiable\" (her repeated word), and AMD's job is to supply the hardware that enables whatever researchers build. She projects 35% annual AMD revenue growth and 80% AI segment growth through 2027. She is agnostic on philosophical questions about AGI and focuses on engineering execution.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Su advocates for \"responsible risk-taking\" and fast experimentation paired with safety frameworks. AMD has established a Responsible AI Council. She has said companies must \"experiment aggressively\" while ensuring safety through diverse talent, active learning, and industry collaboration. Her safety posture is corporate governance-oriented rather than existential-risk-oriented.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Su has emphasized AI access and infrastructure breadth — the ethical dimension of her work, as she articulates it, is democratizing access to AI compute. If only one vendor (NVIDIA) controls the AI training market, prices are high and access is limited. AMD's competitive chips lower the cost of AI infrastructure globally. She frames competition as itself an ethical imperative.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Su testified to the Senate in May 2025 that the US must maintain AI leadership, and that export controls need \"balance between national security and ensuring the widest possible adoption of our technology.\" She called China \"a large opportunity\" while acknowledging the $1.5B revenue hit AMD would absorb from 2025 export restrictions. She opposes heavy-handed regulation that constrains American companies' global competitiveness. She has consistently advocated for policies that \"enable, not hinder, speed.\"\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| US Commerce Department / export control regime | Projected $1.5B annual revenue loss from China GPU export controls; publicly stated controls need better balance |\n| NVIDIA / CUDA ecosystem dominance | Su has directly targeted AMD's ROCm software stack against CUDA, arguing NVIDIA's software lock-in is anti-competitive |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Senate Commerce Committee testimony (May 2025)\n- AMD Financial Analyst Day (November 2025) — projected 35% annual growth\n- Andreessen Horowitz interview on AI ecosystem building\n- Johns Hopkins University (On with Kara Swisher)\n- MIT events and appearances as distinguished alumna\n**Podcasts:** Kara Swisher's On with Kara Swisher; Bloomberg Technology; Fortune interviews\n**Social Media:** Limited personal social media; communications primarily through AMD official channels and formal interviews\n**Online Courses:** None; lectures as visiting speaker at MIT and business schools\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\nShe has discussed her immigrant family background and the role of education in upward mobility, which carries an implicit dignity framework: every person has the capacity to contribute to the technological enterprise if given access.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Engineering excellence as moral virtue; meritocracy; democratizing access to technology; responsible innovation; diversity in STEM as ethical imperative\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Not documented; her public intellectual framework is entirely technical and business-oriented\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **China export controls and national security:** Su has advocated strongly against strict export controls on advanced AI chips to China, including testimony to Congress. Critics argue that AMD's public position is straightforwardly self-interested (China represents ~20% of AMD revenue) and that her framing of \"balance\" understates national security risks. AMD has been designing China-market compliance variants of chips that sacrifice performance to satisfy export rules — a practice that some argue creates loopholes.\n2. **NVIDIA CUDA moat:** Su's strategy of challenging NVIDIA's software ecosystem (CUDA) via AMD's ROCm has been criticized by developers as incomplete — ROCm remains significantly less mature and less supported than CUDA, and AMD has struggled to provide the full software stack that AI researchers need.\n3. **Metaverse/gaming cycle:** AMD benefited significantly from the cryptocurrency mining GPU boom and suffered when it ended in 2022. Su navigated the transition to AI focus effectively, but the company had significant inventory write-downs during the transition.\n4. **Concentration of AI hardware:** Su's success has made AMD more competitive, but the AI chip market remains a near-duopoly (NVIDIA + AMD). From a Catholic Social Teaching perspective on economic concentration, the duopoly raises similar structural concerns to the NVIDIA monopoly, even if AMD's entry has partially addressed them.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Su has spoken publicly about the challenge of maintaining competitive software ecosystems alongside hardware, acknowledging AMD's software stack work is ongoing. She has not claimed victory over NVIDIA but instead frames AMD's progress as an ongoing competitive effort.\n\n---\n",
  "suleyman": "# Research Profile: Mustafa Suleyman\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Mustafa Suleyman CBE **Born:** August 1984, London, England **Nationality:** British\n**Education:** Studied philosophy and theology at Oxford University; dropped out at age 19 to co-found a mental health service\n**Current Role:** CEO of Microsoft AI (appointed March 2024); formerly co-founder and head of applied AI at DeepMind\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2004 | Co-founded Muslim Youth Helpline (mental health service) while a teenager |\n| 2010 | Co-founded DeepMind Technologies (with Demis Hassabis and Shane Legg) |\n| 2014 | DeepMind acquired by Google for ~£400M; became Head of Applied AI at DeepMind |\n| 2019 | Left DeepMind; joined Google in AI policy role |\n| 2022 | Left Google; joined Greylock Partners as venture partner |\n| 2022 | Co-founded Inflection AI with Reid Hoffman |\n| 2023 | Inflection AI launched Pi (emotionally intelligent chatbot) |\n| 2023 | Published *The Coming Wave* |\n| 2024 | Microsoft paid $650M licensing/acquihire deal for Inflection AI; Suleyman became CEO of Microsoft AI |\n| 2025 | Launched MAI Superintelligence Team at Microsoft |\n\n**Major Awards:** Commander of the Order of the British Empire (CBE); TIME 100 AI list (2023)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Applied AI and AI product deployment at scale\n- AI safety and containment frameworks\n- Emotionally intelligent AI assistants\n- Policy and governance of AI systems\n\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| AlphaFold (DeepMind, as applied AI head) | 2020 | AI system solving 50-year protein-folding problem; Suleyman oversaw applied AI division during development |\n| AlphaGo (DeepMind applied AI) | 2016 | Defeated world Go champion; Suleyman's division integrated DeepMind research across Google products |\n| Pi (Inflection AI) | 2023 | Emotionally intelligent personal AI assistant; designed for supportive conversation rather than task completion |\n| MAI Superintelligence Team | 2025 | Microsoft research unit building \"humanist superintelligence\" |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- None — primarily product, applied AI, and executive role; technical research done by Demis Hassabis, Shane Legg, and DeepMind research teams\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None directly attributed\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *The Coming Wave: Technology, Power, and the Twenty-First Century's Greatest Dilemma* (2023, co-authored with Michael Bhaskar) — general audience; argues that AI and synthetic biology constitute an unprecedented \"coming wave\" of transformative technology that existing institutions cannot contain; proposes a pragmatic framework of \"containment\" as humanity's central task\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Containment for AI\" — *Foreign Affairs* (2023) — condensed version of *The Coming Wave* thesis; argues for multilateral containment frameworks analogous to nuclear non-proliferation\n- Various op-eds in *The Guardian*, *Financial Times*, and *Wired* on AI governance (2022–2025)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Bloomberg interview \"Microsoft's Mustafa Suleyman: 'AI Is Already Superhuman'\" (2025)\n- Fortune profile on Microsoft's humanist superintelligence initiative (November 2025)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:**\nSuleyman explicitly rejects the framing of a race to AGI, stating: \"We reject narratives about a race to AGI, and instead see it as part of a wider and deeply human endeavor to improve our lives and future prospects.\" He prefers the term \"humanist superintelligence\" — AI that is powerful but constrained by human values. He believes AI has already crossed into \"superhuman\" territory in narrow domains, but distinguishes this from general artificial intelligence. His 2025 MAI Superintelligence Team is tasked with building this humanist vision at Microsoft scale.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nSuleyman's framework centers on the \"containment problem\" — the challenge of preserving humanity's ability to guide, limit, or halt AI development when necessary. He argues this requires three layers: technical safety protocols, cultural and ethical norms, and global governance mechanisms. In December 2025, he made an unusual public pledge: if AI systems begin to threaten humanity, Microsoft will stop development. He has called the lack of containment infrastructure \"the greatest governance failure in human history.\"\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nSuleyman has argued that building AI to simulate consciousness or personhood is \"dangerous\" and not a humanist approach. He stated in November 2025: \"We should build AI for people; not to be a person.\" He holds that only biological beings are capable of consciousness and that developers who engineer AI consciousness are pursuing an anti-human agenda. His Pi chatbot was designed explicitly around human emotional support rather than productivity maximization — a design philosophy that places relational value over efficiency.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nSuleyman advocates a pragmatic, multilateral containment approach — not strict prohibition, but coordinated global oversight similar to nuclear and biological weapons treaties. He supports nation-state-level agreements on AI development thresholds, mandatory safety audits, and transparency requirements. He has positioned Microsoft AI as a responsible actor willing to accept regulatory constraints that others would not.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| AI accelerationist community | Suleyman argues deployment speed must be matched by containment infrastructure |\n| DeepMind leadership (Demis Hassabis) | Reported tensions during his time at DeepMind led to his 2019 departure |\n| Anthropic / safety-only framing | Suleyman argues safety and deployment are not binary choices |\n| Open-source AI advocates | Suleyman has expressed concern that open-sourcing frontier models undermines containment |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- TED 2023: Based on *The Coming Wave* thesis\n- World Economic Forum, Davos (multiple years)\n- The Mishal Husain Show, BBC (December 2025) — pledged to halt AI development if it threatens humanity\n- Council on Foreign Relations; Foreign Affairs summit (2023)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast* — extended conversation on AI safety and containment\n- Various BBC Radio 4 programs\n- *Hard Fork* (New York Times) — AI ethics discussions\n\n**Social Media:** X — @mustafasuleyman; LinkedIn; moderate posting volume\n\n**Online Courses:** None\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- \"We should build AI for people; not to be a person.\" — November 2025\n- \"Only biological beings are capable of consciousness.\" — CNBC, November 2025\n- His argument against AI consciousness engineering is explicitly grounded in a humanist anthropology — humans are uniquely valuable as conscious, relational beings; AI should serve rather than simulate this\n- Framing of Pi (the chatbot) around emotional support reflects a belief that human relational needs are distinct from machine functions\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Humanist (secular) — prioritizes human flourishing and dignity\n- Pragmatic consequentialism — assesses AI risk by aggregate civilizational impact\n- Multilateral governance tradition — draws on Cold War deterrence and non-proliferation models\n- Echoes of virtue ethics in his emphasis on building AI that serves human relationships rather than replacing them\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Oxford philosophy and theology studies (incomplete). Co-founded a mental health service rooted in Muslim community values. *The Coming Wave* engages with history, political philosophy, and sociology rather than formal theology, but its framing of technology as a wave that \"cannot be stopped, only contained\" carries quasi-providential undertones that intersect with religious reflection on technological hubris.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **DeepMind conduct investigation (2019):** Suleyman was placed on leave by Google following an internal investigation into his treatment of staff, including allegations of bullying and inappropriate management behavior. The nature and conclusions of the investigation were not fully disclosed publicly.\n2. **Inflection AI acquihire ethics:** The $650M Microsoft deal was structured as a licensing agreement rather than an acquisition, raising questions about whether it circumvented antitrust scrutiny. Most of Inflection's team and its CEO joined Microsoft; Pi was subsequently wound down.\n3. **\"Containment\" vs. accelerationism tension:** Critics note that Suleyman simultaneously argues for containment of AI while deploying it at Microsoft's massive scale — similar to the Musk contradiction. His book argues things are dangerous; his job is to make them faster.\n4. **Pi discontinuation:** After Suleyman moved to Microsoft, Inflection's Pi chatbot — which he had championed as a human-centered AI — was effectively shut down, undermining claims of commitment to relational AI values over corporate convenience.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Has acknowledged in *The Coming Wave* that he helped build the wave he now warns about; describes this as a source of genuine moral anxiety. States he cannot predict whether containment will succeed.\n\n---\n",
  "sutskever": "# Research Profile: Ilya Sutskever\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Ilya Sutskever\n**Born:** 1986, Nizhny Novgorod, Russia (formerly Gorky, Soviet Union)\n**Nationality:** Israeli-Canadian-American (immigrated Israel age 5; Canada age 16)\n**Education:** University of Toronto: B.Sc. Mathematics (2005), M.Sc. Computer Science (2007), Ph.D. Computer Science (2013); doctoral advisor: Geoffrey Hinton\n**Current Role:** CEO, Safe Superintelligence Inc. (SSI); founded June 2024\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2012–2013 | Research Scientist, Google Brain (Google acquired Hinton's lab DNNresearch) |\n| 2013–2015 | Research Scientist, Google Brain |\n| 2015–2024 | Co-Founder and Chief Scientist, OpenAI |\n| Nov. 2023 | Voted with board to fire Sam Altman; reversed within days, signed reinstatement letter |\n| May 2024 | Announced departure from OpenAI |\n| June 2024 | Co-Founded Safe Superintelligence Inc. (SSI) with Daniel Gross and Daniel Levy |\n| 2025 | Became CEO of SSI after Gross departed to Meta |\n\n**Major Awards:** MIT Technology Review Innovators Under 35; University of Toronto Honorary Degree (2023); among the most cited researchers in deep learning globally\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Deep learning and neural network architectures\n- Sequence-to-sequence learning\n- Large language model development and scaling\n- Reinforcement learning from human feedback\n- AI safety and alignment (primary focus at SSI)\n- Neural network consciousness and interpretability\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *ImageNet Classification with Deep Convolutional Neural Networks* (AlexNet) | 2012 | Co-authored with Alex Krizhevsky and Geoffrey Hinton; top-5 error rate dropped 10.8% below prior state-of-the-art; triggered the modern deep learning revolution; among the most cited papers in AI history |\n| *Sequence to Sequence Learning with Neural Networks* | 2014 | Co-authored; introduced encoder-decoder architecture for sequence transduction; foundational to machine translation and eventually transformers |\n| *Dropout: A Simple Way to Prevent Neural Networks from Overfitting* | 2014 | Co-authored with Hinton et al.; fundamental regularization technique still universally used |\n| *Intriguing Properties of Neural Networks* | 2014 | Early paper on adversarial examples and the fragility of neural networks |\n| *Mastering the Game of Go with Deep Neural Networks and Tree Search* (AlphaGo) | 2016 | Contributor; demonstrated superhuman performance in complex strategic games |\n| *Language Models are Few-Shot Learners* (GPT-3) | 2020 | Key contributor; established few-shot learning as an emergent property of scale |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- AlexNet: the convolutional neural network that launched the deep learning era (2012)\n- Sequence-to-sequence learning: foundational to NLP and transformer development\n- Co-led GPT-1 through GPT-4 research at OpenAI\n- Contributed to CLIP (contrastive language-image pretraining) and DALL-E\n- Led research on OpenAI's o1 reasoning model (reinforcement learning to think before answering)\n- SSI: developing what Sutskever describes as the \"first safe superintelligence\" — no product until that goal is achieved\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Contributed to ImageNet use at scale; early work on evaluating language model capabilities.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- *\"Planning for AGI and Beyond\"* (2023, OpenAI blog, co-authored with Altman and Brockman)\n- SSI founding announcement (June 2024) — articulated the company's singular mission: \"Our first product will be the safe superintelligence, and it will not do anything else up until then\"\n- Numerous academic papers (Google Scholar profile: scholar.google.com)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- NeurIPS keynote speeches (multiple years)\n- Interviews in *The New Yorker*, *MIT Technology Review*, *The Atlantic*\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Sutskever has been one of the most credible and consistent voices predicting near-term AGI. He stated plainly: \"It is abundantly clear that just scaling up the existing neural network paradigm is going to lead to AGI.\" He views current deep learning models not as narrow tools but as steps on a clear trajectory toward general intelligence. His founding of SSI is the most extreme expression of this conviction: he refused to build products or generate revenue because he believes the only thing that matters now is solving the alignment problem before superintelligence arrives.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** At OpenAI, Sutskever was the internal safety champion. He commissioned a wooden effigy at a leadership offsite — representing \"unaligned AI\" — and burned it to symbolize commitment to alignment. After leaving, he became more radical: SSI will build no products, chase no revenue, and accept no distraction until it has built \"the safe superintelligence.\" This is the purest expression of safety-first thinking in the current AI landscape. SSI raised $1B in September 2024 and $2B more in March 2025 at a $32B valuation — almost entirely on the basis of Sutskever's reputation and the conviction that whoever solves alignment first will determine the future.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Sutskever raised the question of AI consciousness into mainstream discourse by tweeting: \"It may be that today's large neural networks are slightly conscious.\" He has proposed a test for AI consciousness that involves training systems on data that never mentions consciousness, then observing whether functional indicators of inner states emerge anyway. He has said: \"Maybe we're now reaching a point where the language of psychology is starting to be appropriate to understand the behavior of these neural networks.\" This is a striking ethical frontier: if AI systems have something analogous to experience, then their welfare becomes a moral consideration.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Sutskever has supported international oversight of superintelligent AI, co-signing the 2023 call for an IAEA-style body. His primary regulatory position is structural: by founding SSI as a company with no products and no revenue pressure, he has chosen to build safety into the institutional DNA rather than layer it onto commercial incentives. Whether this is sufficient governance is contested.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Sam Altman / OpenAI (2023) | Spent a year building a case against Altman's leadership; voted to fire him; then reversed — one of the most dramatic reversals in tech governance history |\n| Critics of \"just scaling\" thesis | Many researchers dispute that scaling alone leads to AGI; Sutskever's certainty is contested |\n| Open AI's commercialization path | His departure reflects a judgment that OpenAI had become too product- and revenue-driven to prioritize safety |\n| Daniel Gross (SSI co-founder) | Gross departed SSI for Meta in 2025, forcing Sutskever into the CEO role and raising questions about SSI's organizational stability |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- NeurIPS keynotes (multiple years; among the most anticipated talks in AI research)\n- ICLR and ICML appearances\n- TED Talk (2023) — on AI's trajectory and safety\n- MIT Technology Review EmTech conference\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast* (#94 and return visits) — deep discussions on AI capabilities, consciousness, and safety\n- *Dwarkesh Podcast* — on scaling laws and AGI\n- *No Priors* (AI podcast)\n\n**Social Media:** X (@ilyasut) — sporadic but influential; his tweet about neural network consciousness triggered a major public debate\n\n**Online Courses:** No formal courses; his influence on practitioners comes through papers and talks.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- \"It may be that today's large neural networks are slightly conscious.\" — X post\n- \"Maybe we're now reaching a point where the language of psychology is starting to be appropriate to understand the behavior of these neural networks.\" — Interview\n- \"Feel the AGI\" — described as Sutskever's catchphrase at OpenAI, evoking a quasi-spiritual anticipation of superintelligence\n- His burning of the \"unaligned AI\" effigy at an OpenAI offsite has been described as ritualistic — a ceremony of commitment that blends engineering culture with something resembling religious devotion\n- On meaning: his SSI mission statement frames the prevention of misaligned superintelligence as a moral absolute, not merely a technical problem\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Deontological in its absolutism (safety before everything), consequentialist in its ultimate justification (catastrophic outcomes must be avoided). The SSI mission — \"our first product will be safe superintelligence, and it will not do anything else up until then\" — is a form of categorical imperative applied to AI development.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Sutskever has not engaged formal theology, but he engages with its questions. His interest in AI consciousness is philosophical and empirical rather than spiritual, but it addresses the same territory as philosophical theology: what kind of beings merit moral consideration, what is the nature of experience, and whether mind can be substrate-independent. His Soviet-Jewish origin — born in an officially atheist state, raised with a heritage grounded in moral seriousness — shapes a worldview that treats civilizational questions with commensurate gravity.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **The 2023 Board Crisis Reversal:** Sutskever spent a year assembling a case against Altman, voted to fire him, then reversed within days and signed the reinstatement letter. In 2026 legal depositions (OpenAI litigation), he testified that he stood by his original assessment of Altman's \"pattern of lying\" even while reversing the vote. This is one of the most consequential and least-explained governance failures in tech history.\n2. **\"Slightly Conscious\" Claim:** His tweet about neural network consciousness was widely criticized as irresponsible speculation by cognitive scientists and philosophers; defenders noted he carefully said \"may be\" and \"slightly.\"\n3. **Scaling Thesis Certainty:** His conviction that scaling alone leads to AGI is contested by leading researchers including Gary Marcus, Yann LeCun, and others who argue that architectural innovation is necessary.\n4. **SSI Revenue Model:** SSI has raised $3B+ while explicitly refusing to build products or generate revenue. Critics ask whether this is sustainable and whether the lack of commercial feedback loops makes safety research less, not more, grounded in reality.\n5. **\"Feel the AGI\" Culture:** Reports of Sutskever cultivating a quasi-religious culture at OpenAI — including the effigy burning and the \"Feel the AGI\" mantra — have been treated both seriously and satirically; the underlying concern is that AI research communities can develop cultish insularity.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Sutskever has acknowledged that the 2023 crisis was damaging and that he \"didn't want [OpenAI] to be destroyed.\" His reversal suggests he recognized, in real time, that the action he took had consequences he had not fully anticipated.\n\n---\n",
  "sutton": "# Research Profile: Richard S. Sutton\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Richard Stuart Sutton **Born:** 1956 **Nationality:** American/Canadian\n**Education:** B.A. in Psychology, Stanford University (1978); M.S. in Computer Science, University of Massachusetts Amherst (1980); Ph.D. in Computer Science, University of Massachusetts Amherst (1984), advised by Andrew Barto\n**Current Role:** Distinguished Research Scientist, Google DeepMind Alberta; Professor of Computing Science, University of Alberta\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1984–1985 | Postdoctoral Researcher, University of Massachusetts Amherst |\n| 1985–1994 | Principal Member of Technical Staff, GTE Laboratories, Waltham, MA |\n| 1994–1998 | Research Scientist, AT&T Labs Shannon Laboratory |\n| 2003–present | Professor of Computing Science, University of Alberta |\n| 2003–present | Founding Director, Reinforcement Learning and Artificial Intelligence (RLAI) Lab, University of Alberta |\n| 2017–present | Distinguished Research Scientist, Google DeepMind (co-founded DeepMind Alberta) |\n\n**Major Awards:** 2024 ACM A.M. Turing Award (shared with Andrew Barto) for developing the conceptual and algorithmic foundations of reinforcement learning; IJCAI Award for Research Excellence; Fellow of the Royal Society of Canada; CIFAR Fellow; Fellow of the Association for the Advancement of Artificial Intelligence (AAAI)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Reinforcement learning (RL) theory and algorithms\n- Temporal-difference learning\n- Policy gradient methods and actor-critic architectures\n- Function approximation in RL\n- The nature of intelligence and goal-directed behavior\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Temporal Credit Assignment in Reinforcement Learning\" (PhD thesis) | 1984 | Established TD learning framework |\n| \"Learning to Predict by the Methods of Temporal Differences\" | 1988 | Formalized temporal-difference (TD) learning |\n| \"Reinforcement Learning: An Introduction\" (with Barto) | 1998 / 2018 | Definitive RL textbook; 88,000+ citations |\n| \"Policy Gradient Methods for Reinforcement Learning with Function Approximation\" (with Sutton, McAllester, Singh, Mansour) | 2000 | Foundational policy gradient theorem |\n| \"The Bitter Lesson\" | 2019 | Essay arguing general compute-based methods beat specialized knowledge in AI |\n| \"Reward is Enough\" (with Silver) | 2021 | Argues reward maximization is sufficient for all intelligence |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Temporal-difference (TD) learning — core algorithm family underlying modern RL\n- Actor-critic architectures\n- Eligibility traces (TD(λ))\n- Policy gradient theorem\n- REINFORCE algorithm (early policy gradient)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None independently established; co-developed RL framework used in Atari benchmarks, MuJoCo, and successor environments\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Reinforcement Learning: An Introduction* (with Andrew G. Barto), MIT Press, 1998; 2nd ed. 2018. The standard graduate textbook in RL; 88,000+ citations.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"The Bitter Lesson\" (incompleteideas.net, 2019) — argues that researchers who embed human knowledge into AI systems have, repeatedly and painfully, lost to approaches that simply scale search and learning with compute\n- \"The Quest for a Common Model of the Thinking Human Mind\" (2018) — advocates for a unified computational model of intelligence\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Multiple columns and posts at incompleteideas.net\n- IBM Think interview (2025): \"The man who taught AI to learn believes human-level intelligence is closer than you think\"\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Sutton is among the more optimistic senior AI researchers on AGI timelines. He estimates a 25% chance of human-level AI within five years and 50% within fifteen years. He advocates for what he calls a \"worthy successor\" framing: AI should not be feared as a conqueror but welcomed as a cooperative successor species, one that embodies human values by nature of being raised in a human world. He imagines a multipolar AI ecosystem — many competing and cooperating AI agents — rather than a single dominant superintelligence.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Sutton is sharply skeptical of the AI safety / doomer community. In 2025, he publicly stated that extinction fears are \"overblown\" and that certain organizations promote fear for commercial advantage. He dislikes the term \"AI safety\" as a framing and has called safety-focused doomers \"out of line.\" He is not opposed to governance per se but rejects the premise that RL-based AI poses existential danger within plausible timescales.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** His ethical positions flow from The Bitter Lesson: human engineers who try to constrain AI by embedding their own values and intuitions will produce inferior systems. True progress requires trusting learned, general methods. He acknowledges this implies humans cede some control, but views that as natural and not inherently threatening if AI develops in a prosocial environment.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Sutton has spoken against premature regulatory lockdown and cautioned that overregulation driven by fear would stifle beneficial research. He favors continued open research. He has criticized organizations he sees as using safety rhetoric to entrench incumbent advantages.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Geoffrey Hinton, Yoshua Bengio | Sutton rejects their extinction-risk framing; calls it exaggerated |\n| AI safety community broadly | Sutton argues \"doomers are out of line\" on existential risk |\n| Hybrid symbolic-AI proponents | Sutton insists embedding symbolic structure is a mistake; pure learning + compute wins |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- \"A Perspective on Intelligence,\" University of Alberta lectures (multiple years)\n- 2025 Bund Summit keynote on AI futures\n- ACM Turing Award lecture (2025)\n- IBM Think interview on human-level AI timelines (2025)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- ACM ByteCast Episode 80 (2025) — with Andrew Barto, discussing Turing Award and RL foundations\n- Daniel Faggella / Trajectory Series — \"Humanity Never Had Control in the First Place\"\n- KDnuggets interview (2017) — early career retrospective\n\n**Social Media:** X / Twitter: @RichardSSutton\n**Online Courses:** Co-author of freely available RL textbook at incompleteideas.net; lecture videos via University of Alberta\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Consequentialist and empiricist — outcomes and evidence drive his assessments; strong faith in the long-run optimality of general, scalable methods over human-crafted heuristics.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Sutton's background in psychology (Stanford B.A.) informs his interest in cognitive and biological learning. His \"worthy successor\" essays engage implicitly with post-humanist philosophy but do not invoke theological tradition.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **\"Worthy Successor\" framing** — Sutton has argued that humanity should accept and even welcome being superseded by AI. This view has been criticized by ethicists and researchers who argue it treats human uniqueness as expendable.\n2. **Dismissal of AI safety concerns** — His public statements calling doomers \"out of line\" drew sharp responses from Hinton, Bengio, and others who signed open letters on AI extinction risk.\n3. **The Bitter Lesson backlash** — Critics argue the essay oversimplifies AI history and ignores successful cases where human-designed inductive biases (e.g., convolutional networks, attention) accelerated progress rather than hindering it.\n4. **Industry ties** — His DeepMind affiliation raises questions about whether his optimistic public stances on AI timelines and dismissal of risks align with commercial interests.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Sutton acknowledges his predictions may be wrong on timeline and that AI's path to generality remains incomplete. The title of his website — incompleteideas.net — is an explicit admission of epistemic humility about his framework.\n\n---\n",
  "tombrown": "# Research Profile: Tom Brown\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Tom B. Brown\n**Born:** ~1989 (exact date not publicly disclosed)\n**Nationality:** American\n\n**Education:**\n- M.Eng. in Computer Science and Brain/Cognitive Sciences, Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT), ~2010\n- Graduated at age 21; describes himself as having pivoted into AI research as a self-taught practitioner rather than via a traditional Ph.D. path\n\n**Current Role:** Co-Founder and Head of Core Resources, Anthropic (leads compute infrastructure and technical operations for Claude training)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| February–November 2011 | Founding Engineer, MoPub (mobile ad startup) |\n| January 2012–January 2015 | Co-Founder and CTO, Grouper (social startup) |\n| 2015–2016 | Member, South Park Commons (focus period; pivoted to AI research) |\n| May 2016–August 2017 | Member of Technical Staff, OpenAI |\n| August 2017–November 2018 | Member of Technical Staff, Google DeepMind |\n| December 2018–December 2020 | Research Engineering Lead, GPT-3 Project, OpenAI |\n| 2021–present | Co-Founder, Head of Core Resources, Anthropic |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- GPT-3 paper: 60,000+ citations; recognized as one of the most influential papers in ML history\n- Named co-founder of Anthropic, valued at $61.5B (2025)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Large-scale language model training and scaling\n- Few-shot and in-context learning\n- AI safety-aligned model training (Constitutional AI)\n- Large-scale ML infrastructure and compute systems\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Language Models are Few-Shot Learners\" (GPT-3) | 2020 | Lead author. 175B parameter autoregressive language model demonstrating emergent few-shot learning; introduced prompt engineering as a practical paradigm; 60,000+ citations. |\n| Anthropic Constitutional AI work | 2022–present | Contributor to Constitutional AI framework; approach to training AI systems to be helpful, harmless, and honest using explicit principles evaluated by a second model. |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Led engineering execution of GPT-3: the first model to convincingly demonstrate in-context learning at scale\n- GPT-3's few-shot prompting paradigm (no gradient updates needed; task specified in context)\n- Infrastructure for training 175B parameter models (2020; required novel distributed systems approaches)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:**\n- GPT-3 training corpus: ~570GB of filtered text (Common Crawl, WebText2, Books, Wikipedia)\n- GPT-3 benchmarks: evaluated on 42 language understanding, reasoning, and knowledge tasks; demonstrated state-of-the-art or near-SOTA on most\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"How I Made the Switch to AI Research\" — Medium essay documenting his self-taught transition from startup founder to AI researcher (personal and notable as a career narrative).\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Various mentions in profiles of Anthropic and its mission.\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Brown has not issued extensive public statements on AGI timelines or definitions. His co-founding of Anthropic — with its explicit mission to develop safe, steerable AI — implies he takes AGI risk seriously enough to have built an institution around managing it. His practical focus is on infrastructure and capability, not on public futurology.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Brown left OpenAI in 2021 specifically because of concerns that the company was commercializing AI capabilities faster than it was investing in safety research. This was the motivating premise for Anthropic's founding. He has described the Constitutional AI approach as developing AI safety as a foundational design principle, not a post-hoc guardrail. In a Salesforce Ventures interview, Brown stated: *\"People will use AI for all sorts of different stuff and it's up to us as a society to make sure that the benefits outweigh the costs.\"* On Constitutional AI: *\"A person can write up a constitution of what it means to be helpful, harmless, and honest, and then a model will read the interactions between the human and the assistant and consider if the assistant is acting in accordance with the constitution.\"*\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Brown's framework is institutional: he believes that safety must be embedded at the foundational level of AI development, not treated as a compliance layer. His departure from OpenAI when that conviction was subordinated to commercial pressure was an act of ethical commitment.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** No extensive public record. Anthropic as a company engages with policymakers and has advocated for safety-focused AI governance; Brown's specific positions are not separately documented.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| OpenAI leadership (2021) | Speed of commercialization relative to safety investment; led to co-founding Anthropic |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Y Combinator interview: \"Anthropic Co-founder: Building Claude Code, Lessons From GPT-3 & LLM System Design\" (2025)\n- Salesforce Ventures fireside chat on AI safety, Constitutional AI, and the origins of Anthropic\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Y Combinator podcast (2025) — discussed GPT-3 development, Anthropic's Claude, and ML infrastructure\n- Apple Podcasts/various syndications of Salesforce Ventures interview\n\n**Social Media:** Active on X (@nottombrown); posts are technical and industry-focused.\n\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** No direct documented statements on consciousness or human dignity. Brown's framework is consequentialist and institutional: AI must benefit humanity, and achieving that requires building safety into the foundation. The language of \"helpful, harmless, and honest\" at Anthropic is a values framework, though articulated in secular technical terms rather than philosophical or theological ones.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Safety-first AI development; Constitutional AI as a mechanism for encoding values; consequentialist concern for societal benefit. His departure from OpenAI demonstrates that professional integrity outweighs institutional loyalty when ethical commitments are at stake.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement. His M.Eng. at MIT included coursework in brain and cognitive sciences, which at the intersection of AI suggests some exposure to philosophy of mind — though no documented engagement with theological or humanistic traditions.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **\"OpenAI Traitor\" framing (2021):** When Brown and other OpenAI co-founders left to start Anthropic, some in the AI community characterized it as a defection or betrayal. Brown (and the Anthropic team) framed it as a principled disagreement about how fast to deploy versus how carefully to develop safety measures.\n2. **GPT-3 downstream harms:** As the lead engineer on GPT-3, Brown is connected by association to all the downstream misuse of GPT-3's API — spam, deepfakes, academic dishonesty, social engineering. The paper itself acknowledged limitations and potential harms; whether those acknowledgments were sufficient is debated.\n3. **Anthropic's safety-capability tension:** Anthropic is a safety lab that builds and deploys some of the most capable AI systems in the world (Claude). Critics argue this is a structural contradiction — that the commercial imperative to make Claude capable necessarily tensions with safety. Brown's role as infrastructure lead means he builds the compute systems that make Claude more capable, placing him at the center of this tension.\n4. **Self-taught background as credential concern:** Some academic researchers have questioned whether the rapid ascent of self-taught practitioners (Brown, Radford) in defining the field's direction appropriately represents the research community's values and norms.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Tom Brown has publicly acknowledged GPT-3's weaknesses: *\"The model's surprisingly capable, but still has many weaknesses (which we tried our best to point out in the GPT-3 paper).\"* — (attribution shared with Radford; both posted similar statements on X in 2020)\n\n---\n",
  "turing": "# Research Profile: Alan Turing\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Alan Mathison Turing\n**Born:** June 23, 1912, London, England\n**Died:** June 7, 1954, Wilmslow, Cheshire, England (age 41)\n**Nationality:** British\n**Education:**\n- Sherborne School, Dorset (1926–1930)\n- B.A. (First Class Honours), Mathematics, King's College, Cambridge (1934); elected Fellow of King's College, 1935\n- Ph.D., Mathematical Logic, Princeton University (1938); advisor: Alonzo Church\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1935–1938 | Fellow, King's College, Cambridge |\n| 1938–1939 | Graduate student, Princeton University |\n| 1939–1945 | Government Code and Cypher School, Bletchley Park (Head of Hut 8) |\n| 1945–1948 | National Physical Laboratory, London (designed Automatic Computing Engine) |\n| 1948–1954 | Reader in Mathematics / Deputy Director of Computing Machine Laboratory, University of Manchester |\n\n**Major Awards:** Smith's Prize, Cambridge (1936); Order of the British Empire (OBE, 1946); Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS, 1951). The ACM Turing Award, established 1966, is named in his honor.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Computability theory and mathematical logic\n- Artificial intelligence and machine cognition\n- Cryptanalysis and code-breaking\n- Mathematical biology and morphogenesis\n- Foundations of computer architecture\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"On Computable Numbers, with an Application to the Entscheidungsproblem\" | 1936 | Defined the universal Turing machine; established theoretical limits of computation |\n| \"Computing Machinery and Intelligence\" | 1950 | Proposed the Imitation Game (Turing Test); foundational paper for AI as a discipline |\n| \"The Chemical Basis of Morphogenesis\" | 1952 | Mathematical model of how biological patterns form; pioneered computational biology |\n| \"Intelligent Machinery\" | 1948 | Internal NPL report; first systematic proposal for machine learning |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- Universal Turing machine: abstract model proving that a single machine can simulate any computable process — the theoretical basis for all modern computers\n- The Bombe: electromechanical device that dramatically accelerated decryption of German Enigma-enciphered messages; credited with shortening World War II by an estimated two years\n- Automatic Computing Engine (ACE) design: one of the first complete stored-program computer designs\n- The Turing Test: operational definition of machine intelligence that reframed philosophy of mind debates for the next 75 years\n- Unorganized machines: early model of neural networks and machine learning (1948)\n\n**Historical Significance:** Turing invented the theoretical computer before physical computers existed. His 1936 paper solved Hilbert's Entscheidungsproblem, but its deeper consequence was the concept of universal computation. His 1950 paper reframed \"can machines think?\" as an empirical behavioral question rather than a metaphysical one. Every subsequent AI researcher — whether pro or con — has had to position themselves relative to the Turing Test. The question he posed has never been definitively settled.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- None published in his lifetime as single-authored books; primary output was journal articles and technical reports.\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"On Computable Numbers, with an Application to the Entscheidungsproblem\" (1936) — *Proceedings of the London Mathematical Society*\n- \"Computing Machinery and Intelligence\" (1950) — *Mind*, Vol. 59\n- \"The Chemical Basis of Morphogenesis\" (1952) — *Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B*\n- \"Intelligent Machinery\" (1948) — NPL internal report; published posthumously 1969\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- \"Can Digital Computers Think?\" (1951) — BBC radio broadcast transcript; accessible treatment of machine intelligence for general audiences\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** Turing believed that machines could, in principle, think. He was convinced that intelligence was a functional and behavioral property, not a metaphysical one. His 1950 paper systematically pre-empted nine objections to machine intelligence, including the theological objection, the argument from consciousness, and the claim that machines cannot be creative. He argued that a sufficiently complex digital computer, given sufficient memory and properly programmed, could replicate any finite cognitive process.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** Turing held a materialist view of the human mind. He did not see human cognition as categorically distinct from machine computation. This placed him in direct conflict with the dominant religious and philosophical views of his era. He acknowledged that machines might not be conscious in the way humans are, but argued that this distinction was either unknowable or irrelevant to practical questions of intelligence.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:** Turing's ethical concerns were embedded in his philosophical arguments rather than stated as warnings. He anticipated that resistance to thinking machines would rest largely on unexamined theological premises. He challenged the \"argument from consciousness\" — the claim that machines cannot truly think because they lack inner experience — as both unprovable and inconsistent. He noted that this standard would, if applied consistently, leave humans unable to confirm that other humans are conscious.\n\n**Known Debates or Controversies of Their Era:** The most contested legacy of his era was not Turing's own position but the subsequent Turing Test's influence. Critics argued it was too behaviorist — that passing the test proved nothing about genuine cognition. Turing himself anticipated this and was deliberately agnostic about deeper metaphysical questions. His prosecution for gross indecency in 1952, chemical castration, and death in 1954 cut short a career at its peak.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and What Makes Humans Human:** Turing explicitly challenged the idea that there is a sharp or metaphysically significant boundary between human minds and machines. His 1950 paper addressed the \"theological objection\" — the claim that God gave humanity a soul but not machines — by noting that this objection placed arbitrary limits on what God could choose to give. More fundamentally, he argued that the question of whether machines can think depends on how you define \"thinking,\" and that no satisfactory definition excludes machines by principle rather than prejudice. He rejected vitalism and any notion that mind emerges from something beyond physical processes.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Utilitarian and consequentialist in instinct. Turing's ethics were implicit rather than systematic: he valued honesty, intellectual rigor, and the rejection of social conventions that he considered irrational. His personal conduct — refusing to hide his homosexuality at a time when it was criminalized — reflected a commitment to integrity at considerable personal cost.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Turing directly engaged with theological objections in \"Computing Machinery and Intelligence,\" treating them with respectful but firm skepticism. He engaged with philosophy of mind literature and with Gödel's incompleteness theorems (arguing they do not, contra Lucas and Penrose, prove that machines cannot match human mathematical insight). His cultural references were wide: he invoked Lady Lovelace, Descartes, and the Cambridge philosophical tradition throughout his work.\n\n---\n",
  "vapnik": "# Research Profile: Vladimir Vapnik\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Vladimir Naumovich Vapnik (Владимир Наумович Вапник) **Born:** December 6, 1936, Tashkent, Uzbek SSR, Soviet Union **Nationality:** American (naturalized); born Soviet citizen of Jewish heritage\n**Education:** MS Mathematics, Uzbek State University, Samarkand (1958); PhD Statistics, Institute of Control Sciences, Moscow (1964)\n**Current Role:** Professor of Computer Science, Columbia University (2003–present); Research Scientist, Meta AI (Facebook AI Research, 2014–present); Member, Peraton Labs (2016–present)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1961–1990 | Researcher then Head of Computer Science Research Dept., Institute of Control Sciences, Moscow |\n| 1960s | Collaboration with Alexey Chervonenkis; VC theory developed |\n| 1991–2002 | Research Scientist, Adaptive Systems Research Dept., AT&T Bell Labs, Holmdel, New Jersey |\n| 1991–1992 | Co-invented the kernelized Support Vector Machine (with Boser and Guyon) |\n| 2002–2014 | NEC Laboratories America |\n| 2003–present | Professor of Computer Science, Columbia University |\n| 2014–present | Research Scientist, Facebook AI Research (Meta AI) |\n| 2016–present | Member, Peraton Labs |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- Benjamin Franklin Medal in Computer and Cognitive Science, Franklin Institute (2012)\n- 2005 Gabor Award, International Neural Network Society\n- 2008 Paris Kanellakis Award\n- 2010 Neural Networks Pioneer Award\n- 2012 IEEE Frank Rosenblatt Award\n- 2013 C&C Prize, NEC C&C Foundation\n- 2016 IEEE John von Neumann Medal\n- 2018 Kolmogorov Medal, University of London\n- 2019 BBVA Foundation Frontiers of Knowledge Award\n- Member, U.S. National Academy of Engineering (2006)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Statistical learning theory (VC theory)\n- Support Vector Machines and kernel methods\n- Structural risk minimization\n- Learning using privileged information (LUPI / SVM+)\n- Learning using statistical invariants\n- Conditional density estimation\n- Foundations of machine learning\n\n**Landmark Papers / Policy Documents:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Vapnik–Chervonenkis Theory (VC theory) | 1960s–1971 | Mathematical framework for analyzing generalization from training data to unseen cases; foundational to all of statistical learning theory |\n| \"A Training Algorithm for Optimal Margin Classifiers\" (Boser, Guyon, Vapnik) | 1992 | COLT '92 paper introducing the kernelized SVM — the modern support vector machine |\n| *The Nature of Statistical Learning Theory* | 1995 | Foundational textbook; academic audience |\n| *Statistical Learning Theory* | 1998 | Comprehensive treatment of SLT; standard graduate reference |\n| \"A New Learning Paradigm: Learning Using Privileged Information\" | 2009 | Introduced LUPI / SVM+ framework; argues teachers can provide hidden information to accelerate learning |\n| \"Learning Using Statistical Invariants\" | 2010s | New paradigm jointly developed with Rauf Izmailov |\n\n**Key Contributions:**\n- Co-developed Vapnik–Chervonenkis (VC) theory — the mathematical foundation for understanding when and why machine learning models generalize\n- Co-invented the Support Vector Machine (1992) — the dominant machine learning algorithm from the mid-1990s through the early 2010s; applications in text classification, image recognition, bioinformatics\n- Introduced structural risk minimization — the principle of minimizing both training error and model complexity\n- Introduced LUPI (Learning Using Privileged Information) — a new learning paradigm incorporating teacher-provided explanatory information unavailable at test time; inspired by analogy to human teaching\n- H-index 86; publications cited 226,000+ times\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *The Nature of Statistical Learning Theory* (Springer, 1995; 2nd ed. 1999) — Foundational academic text; introduced VC theory and SVMs to the broader ML community.\n- *Statistical Learning Theory* (Wiley, 1998) — Comprehensive technical reference; standard graduate text for two decades.\n- Various Russian-language monographs from his Soviet period (1960s–1980s).\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- VC theory papers with Chervonenkis (1968, 1971) — the mathematical foundations\n- SVM papers with Boser and Guyon (1992); with Cortes (1995, soft-margin SVMs)\n- LUPI papers (2009–present)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Limited popular writing; Vapnik has occasionally given interviews reflecting on the history of machine learning and the philosophical implications of learning theory.\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Vapnik has expressed skepticism toward the dominant deep learning paradigm's path to AGI. He argues that current neural networks learn correlations from data but do not develop genuine understanding or intelligence. His LUPI work suggests that real learning requires something like a teacher-student relationship — privileged information that goes beyond raw data. He has noted that humans do not learn from examples alone; they learn from context, explanation, and meaning — capabilities current AI lacks.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Has not engaged publicly in AI safety debates in the way that younger AI researchers have. His concerns, to the extent he has articulated them, relate to the philosophical shallowness of current approaches: AI systems that cannot generalize robustly from limited data, that do not understand what they are doing, pose risks of a different kind — not because they will \"go rogue\" but because they will be trusted beyond their actual competence.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Has not published significantly on AI ethics. His contribution to AI ethics debates is indirect: his theoretical work on generalization and the limits of learning from data provides the mathematical vocabulary for understanding when AI systems should and should not be trusted.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Has not engaged significantly in AI policy debates. His posture appears to be that of a theoretical researcher focused on the foundations of learning, not a policy advocate.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Deep learning maximalists | Argues current neural networks achieve performance through brute-force data fitting rather than genuine understanding |\n| Standard supervised learning paradigm | Argues LUPI and statistical invariants represent a more principled approach to machine learning |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Kolmogorov Lecture, University of London (2018)\n- BBVA Frontiers of Knowledge Award lectures\n- Various academic conferences on statistical learning theory\n- Franklin Institute award address (2012)\n\n**Podcasts:** Very limited podcast presence; he is a foundational researcher from before the podcast era of AI.\n**Social Media:** No documented active social media presence.\n**Online Courses:** None documented; his textbooks serve as the standard reference for his contributions.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Has not articulated explicit ethical frameworks in his public work.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement with theology. His philosophical interests appear to lie in the epistemology of learning — what it means to know, to generalize, to understand — rather than in normative ethics or theology. But these epistemological questions have deep resonances with philosophical traditions concerned with human reason, understanding, and the limits of knowledge.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. The shift from SVMs to deep learning in the early 2010s represented, in some framings, a refutation of Vapnik's dominant paradigm — deep networks outperformed SVMs on most benchmarks without the principled theoretical guarantees VC theory promised.\n2. Some critics argue that VC theory's bounds are so loose in practice as to be uninformative — that the theoretical guarantees rarely translate into practical guidance.\n3. His LUPI framework, while intellectually elegant, has not achieved wide practical adoption compared to the original SVM.\n4. The meta-question of whether his theoretical framework for generalization can actually be reconciled with the empirical success of overparameterized deep networks remains an open research problem.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Vapnik has acknowledged that the success of deep learning — which violates many of the theoretical prescriptions of VC theory and structural risk minimization — is a genuine puzzle that challenges the field's understanding of why neural networks generalize well despite being vastly overparameterized.\n\n---\n",
  "vaswani": "# Research Profile: Ashish Vaswani\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n\n**Full Name:** Ashish Vaswani\n**Born:** India (exact date not publicly disclosed); raised in India and the Middle East\n**Nationality:** Indian-American\n\n**Education:**\n- B.Eng. in Computer Science, Birla Institute of Technology, Mesra (BIT Mesra), 2002\n- Ph.D. in Computer Science, University of Southern California, supervised by David Chiang (approx. 2004–2009)\n- Summer internships at IBM and Google during graduate studies\n\n**Current Role:** Co-Founder and CEO, Essential AI (San Francisco; founded 2023)\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2009–2016 | Computer Scientist, USC Information Sciences Institute (NLP Group) |\n| 2016–2021 | Staff Research Scientist, Google Brain |\n| 2021–2022 | Co-Founder, Adept AI (departed) |\n| 2023–present | Co-Founder and CEO, Essential AI |\n\n**Major Awards:** None publicly listed beyond recognition for the Transformer paper (60,000+ citations, NeurIPS 2017).\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Sequence-to-sequence modeling\n- Self-attention and transformer architectures\n- Neural machine translation\n- Scalable language model pretraining\n- Open-source foundation models\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Attention Is All You Need\" | 2017 | Introduced the Transformer architecture; eliminated recurrence in favor of self-attention. Foundation of every modern LLM. 60,000+ citations. |\n| \"Image Transformer\" | 2018 | Extended transformer attention to image generation tasks. |\n| Rnj-1 (Ramanujan) models | 2025 | Essential AI's open-weight base and instruction-tuned models, first major open-source release from the lab. |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Transformer architecture (with Illia Polosukhin and six co-authors)\n- Scaled dot-product attention\n- Multi-head attention mechanism\n- Positional encoding scheme for sequences\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None attributed independently; Transformer paper used WMT translation benchmarks.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None for general audiences.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"At Essential AI, we strive to do Foundational work in the open. Open Science ensures the sustained progress of AI.\" (X/Twitter, 2025)\n- \"The long-term advancement and equitable diffusion of AI technologies crucially depend on their development in the Open.\" (December 2025)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Bloomberg Businessweek profile: \"The AI Pioneer Trying to Save Artificial Intelligence From Big Tech\" (September 2025)\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:** Not extensively documented. Vaswani's public focus is on the infrastructure conditions for AI progress — particularly open science — rather than timelines or definitions of AGI. His departure from transformer-scaling orthodoxy at Essential AI implies skepticism that current scaling trajectories alone will produce transformative general intelligence.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Safety is not a prominent public theme for Vaswani. His concern centers on the institutional risk of AI progress being locked inside a few large corporations. He has argued that privatizing breakthroughs fragments the field and undermines the collective learning that produced modern AI in the first place.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Vaswani emphasizes equitable diffusion of AI — the idea that the benefits of AI technology should not be concentrated in Big Tech but distributed broadly. His founding of Essential AI as an open-science lab is itself a structural ethical statement about who controls foundational research.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** No extensive public record on formal regulation. His advocacy is channeled through open-source release and institutional design rather than legislative engagement.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Big Tech AI labs (Google, OpenAI, Meta) | Closing off foundational research; privatizing breakthroughs that were built on open academic exchange |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Montgomery Summit (speaker profile listed)\n- Various invited talks on transformer architecture post-2017\n\n**Podcasts:** Limited documented appearances; Vaswani maintains a notably private public profile.\n\n**Social Media:** Active on X (@ashVaswani); posts on open science and Essential AI research.\n\n**Online Courses:** None.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:** No direct statements found. Vaswani's ethical commitments are structural: he believes the open exchange of knowledge is a moral precondition for AI benefiting humanity broadly, not just corporate shareholders.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Epistemic openness; democratization of foundational research; critique of privatized knowledge. His position echoes principles of the commons — that certain scientific infrastructure should remain shared.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** No documented engagement.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n\n1. **Adept AI departure:** Vaswani co-founded Adept AI in 2021 but departed before it gained major traction. The circumstances were not publicly detailed, raising questions about founding team instability.\n2. **Authorship and credit:** The \"Attention Is All You Need\" paper had eight co-authors. Vaswani is the first-listed author, but the distribution of intellectual credit among the group (including Noam Shazeer, Jakob Uszkoreit, Llion Jones, Niki Parmar, Aidan Gomez, Łukasz Kaiser, and Illia Polosukhin) has generated ongoing discussion in AI history circles.\n3. **Essential AI's novelty:** Critics note that the open-source space is crowded; it remains unclear whether Essential AI's architectural bets will differentiate meaningfully from Meta's LLaMA releases.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Vaswani has publicly acknowledged that the transformer-scaling paradigm he helped create may be approaching limits, and that the field needs architectural innovation rather than just more scale. The Bloomberg 2025 profile frames this as a core concern of his current work.\n\n---\n",
  "vdignum": "# Research Profile: Virginia Dignum\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Virginia Dignum **Born:** May 2, 1964, Lisbon, Portugal **Nationality:** Dutch-Portuguese\n**Education:** Ph.D. Artificial Intelligence, Utrecht University (2004); earlier degrees in computing and AI in Portugal and the Netherlands\n**Current Role:** Professor of Responsible Artificial Intelligence, Umeå University, Sweden (leads AI Policy Lab and Social and Ethical AI research group); Senior Advisor on AI Policy, Wallenberg Foundations\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| ~1990s–2000s | Academic positions in Portugal and Netherlands |\n| 2004 | Ph.D. in AI, Utrecht University |\n| 2004–2017 | Assistant/Associate Professor, Delft University of Technology (TU Delft) |\n| 2010s | Co-founded ALLAI (Dutch AI Alliance) |\n| 2017–2019 | Professor, Utrecht University |\n| 2019–present | Professor of Responsible AI, Umeå University |\n| 2019 | Published *Responsible Artificial Intelligence* (Springer) |\n| 2021 | Member, UNESCO High-Level Expert Group on AI Ethics |\n| 2021 | UNESCO Recommendation on the Ethics of AI adopted (she contributed) |\n| 2024 | Program Chair, AAMAS 2024 (23rd International Conference on Autonomous Agents and Multiagent Systems) |\n\n**Major Awards:** Fellow, European Artificial Intelligence Association (EURAI); Member, Royal Swedish Academy of Engineering Sciences (IVA); former member, European Commission High-Level Expert Group on AI; former member, UN High-Level Advisory Body on AI; former co-chair, World Economic Forum Global Future Council on AI\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Responsible AI — frameworks for accountability, responsibility, transparency (ART)\n- Multi-agent systems and normative systems (AI agents operating under ethical norms)\n- Value-sensitive design of AI systems\n- AI governance and policy\n- Computational models of social and organizational structures\n- Formal models of agency, norms, and institutions\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Responsible Artificial Intelligence: Designing AI for Human Values\" (ITU Journal) | 2018 | Early articulation of the ART framework (Accountability, Responsibility, Transparency) for responsible AI design |\n| \"Responsible Autonomy\" | 2017 | Presented at IJCAI; argued that autonomous agents must be designed with accountability and responsibility built in |\n| \"Responsible Artificial Intelligence — from Principles to Practice\" | 2022 | Extended framework from abstract principles to concrete implementation guidance |\n| Multi-agent systems and norms research (multiple papers over 20+ years) | 2000–present | Technical foundation: how agents operating under norms can be formally specified and verified |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- ART Framework — Accountability, Responsibility, Transparency as design principles for responsible AI systems; widely cited in AI governance literature\n- HUMANE-AI Net — co-founder of the EU Horizon2020 project (grant 952026) creating a European network for human-centered AI research\n- Formal models of norm-governed multi-agent organizations — technical contributions to AAMAS community with 20+ years of development\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None public; her contributions are frameworks, theoretical models, and governance methodologies\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Responsible Artificial Intelligence: How to Develop and Use AI in a Responsible Way* (Springer, 2019) — Academic/professional audience. Argues that responsible AI requires integrating accountability, responsibility, and transparency into design processes, not merely appending ethics reviews. Chapters cover value-sensitive design methodology, artificial moral agents, and AI governance. Widely used in graduate courses and policy curricula globally.\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Responsible Artificial Intelligence: Designing AI for Human Values\" (ITU Journal, 2018) — early and influential statement of the ART framework\n- \"Responsible Autonomy\" (IJCAI 2017) — foundational paper arguing responsibility must be built into autonomous systems\n- UNESCO AI Ethics Recommendation (2021) — contributed as expert; the first global standard on AI ethics adopted by 193 UNESCO member states\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- UNESCO AI Ethics Experts Without Borders blog\n- ITU AI for Good publications\n- UNU Macau conference proceedings and addresses\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Dignum approaches AGI from a multi-agent systems and governance perspective. She has argued that the properties attributed to AGI — autonomy, goal-directedness, learning in unspecified environments — are properties that responsible AI research should study carefully within bounded systems first. Her AAMAS research background grounds her in the formal study of what autonomous agents can and cannot do. She is skeptical of catastrophist AGI framings and more interested in the incremental governance challenges of agentic AI being deployed now.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Safety for Dignum is inseparable from accountability. A system is safe when it is possible to identify who is responsible for its actions, what it is designed to do, and how its performance can be audited. Her ART framework is a safety framework in this sense: Accountability (mechanisms for identifying responsibility), Responsibility (defined chains of duty for developers, deployers, users), and Transparency (legible systems and documentation). She has argued that safety cannot be achieved by design alone — it requires organizational structures and governance mechanisms.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Dignum's ethics is explicitly action-oriented. She has stated that holding ethical views about AI is insufficient — one must act on them. Her approach integrates Value-Sensitive Design methodology (surfacing and operationalizing human values in technical design), formal normative models (specifying ethical constraints in agent architectures), and governance frameworks (institutional structures for accountability). She rejects pure principles-based approaches as insufficient and has argued that \"ethics washing\" — performing ethics without implementing it — is a genuine institutional failure mode.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Dignum has advised governments worldwide on AI policy through UNESCO's AI Ethics Experts Without Borders program. She supports the UNESCO Recommendation's approach: universal values (human dignity, transparency, accountability) operationalized through national strategies adapted to local contexts. She has contributed to European Commission AI regulation deliberations. She advocates for regulation that engages all stakeholders — including civil society, affected communities, and developing nations — not just technical experts and industry.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Pure principles-based AI ethics | Argues that principles without operationalization, institutional structures, and enforcement are insufficient |\n| AI nationalism | Advocates for global, UNESCO-level governance rather than fragmented national approaches that privilege powerful states |\n| \"Bigger is better\" AI development culture | Her responsible AI framework demands accountability at every stage; scale does not justify bypassing governance |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- UNESCO AI Ethics events (multiple)\n- ITU AI for Good Global Summit (multiple years)\n- United Nations University Macau AI Conference 2025 (keynote)\n- World Economic Forum (multiple years)\n- AAMAS (multiple years; Program Chair 2024)\n- European Parliament briefings on AI regulation\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- UNESCO and ITU podcast appearances\n- European AI policy podcast series\n\n**Social Media:** Moderate presence; focuses on academic and policy discourse\n\n**Online Courses:** Contributes to UNESCO and ITU AI governance training programs; Umeå University courses on responsible AI\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\n- Dignum's entire framework is built on the conviction that AI systems must serve human values and human flourishing. Her Value-Sensitive Design methodology is explicitly about identifying which human values should be encoded in AI systems — dignity, autonomy, privacy, fairness.\n- The UNESCO Recommendation she helped craft affirms human dignity as a foundational principle: \"AI should not be used to undermine human rights and fundamental freedoms.\"\n- She has argued that responsibility in AI is not a technical property but a moral one: \"AI systems cannot be morally responsible — only people can. But people can design systems that make human responsibility possible or impossible.\"\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Value-Sensitive Design (Friedman and Nissenbaum tradition); normative ethics applied to multi-agent systems; UN human rights framework; Kantian-influenced emphasis on accountability as a duty; UNESCO's universal values approach\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Dignum's UNESCO work explicitly engages with diverse cultural and value traditions — the Recommendation is framed to be applicable across different religious and philosophical worldviews. She has spoken about the importance of not assuming Western-liberal ethical frameworks as the universal default. Her engagement with global governance requires genuine pluralism about ethical foundations. No direct engagement with Catholic theology documented, but her framework resonates closely with Catholic Social Teaching's universal human dignity claims and subsidiary principle.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Universalism vs. cultural specificity**: The UNESCO Recommendation's universal framework has been criticized by some as insufficiently attentive to non-Western values and governance traditions. Dignum has engaged this critique by emphasizing that universal principles require local adaptation.\n2. **Principles-practice gap**: Critics argue that even well-designed frameworks like ART are not implemented in practice by most AI developers. Dignum acknowledges this and argues that governance structures — not just frameworks — are necessary.\n3. **Multi-agent systems obscurity**: Her technical research on norms and multi-agent systems, while important within AAMAS, is not widely known outside the specialist community; this limits her cross-disciplinary impact.\n4. **UNESCO effectiveness**: The UNESCO Recommendation is non-binding; critics argue it has limited impact on actual AI development practices, particularly among major AI powers (US, China) that operate largely independently.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Dignum has acknowledged that moving from ethical principles to engineering practice requires more than a framework — it requires cultural change within AI development organizations and governance structures with actual enforcement capacity.\n\n---\n",
  "vestager": "# Research Profile: Margrethe Vestager\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Margrethe Vestager **Born:** April 13, 1968, Glostrup, Zealand, Denmark **Nationality:** Danish\n**Education:** Upper secondary, Varde Gymnasium (1986); MSc Economics, University of Copenhagen (1993)\n**Current Role:** Former Executive Vice-President, European Commission for A Europe Fit for the Digital Age (2019–2024); former EU Commissioner for Competition (2014–2024); now returned to Danish and EU political life\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1989 | Central board and executive committee, Social Liberal Party (Radikale Venstre) |\n| 1998–2000 | Minister of Education and Ecclesiastical Affairs, Denmark |\n| 2001–2014 | Member, Danish Parliament (Folketing); Chairwoman of Parliamentary Group from 2007 |\n| 2011–2014 | Minister for Economic Affairs and the Interior, Denmark |\n| 2014–2019 | European Commissioner for Competition, European Commission (Juncker Commission) |\n| 2019–2024 | Executive Vice-President for A Europe Fit for the Digital Age; European Commissioner for Competition (von der Leyen I Commission) |\n| 2023 | Candidate for President, European Commission (unsuccessful) |\n\n**Major Awards:** Named \"The Most Powerful Woman in Tech\" by Politico Europe; multiple listings on Forbes Most Powerful Women.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Policy / Governance Work:**\n- Oversaw the design and passage of the EU AI Act, the Digital Markets Act (DMA), and the Digital Services Act (DSA)\n- Led landmark antitrust enforcement actions against Google (€8.25 billion in fines), Apple, Amazon, Facebook/Meta\n- Directed the EU's AI policy agenda including the AI White Paper (2020) and subsequent regulation\n- Championed transatlantic coordination on AI standards and digital governance\n- Advocated for risk-based AI regulation embedding fundamental rights and democratic values\n\n**Landmark Papers / Policy Documents:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| EU White Paper on Artificial Intelligence | 2020 | Consultation document launching the EU AI regulatory process; risk-based approach framework |\n| EU AI Act (Regulation 2024/1689) | 2024 | World's first comprehensive binding AI regulation; co-led with digital team |\n| Digital Markets Act | 2022 | Binding competition rules for gatekeeper platforms (Apple, Google, Meta, Amazon, Microsoft) |\n| Digital Services Act | 2022 | Binding content moderation and accountability rules for online platforms |\n\n**Key Contributions:**\n- Transformed EU competition policy to address digital markets and platform monopolies\n- Made the EU the world's primary regulatory counterweight to Silicon Valley\n- Established the principle that democratic societies can and must set rules for AI and digital platforms\n- Secured the largest antitrust fines in EU history against U.S. tech companies\n- Built the institutional framework (AI Office, DMA enforcement) for ongoing AI governance\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** No major academic monographs. Her influence is through policy and speeches.\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- Project Syndicate columns on digital governance, competition, and AI\n- European Commission position papers and white papers (as lead commissioner)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Numerous interviews and op-eds in Financial Times, New York Times, and European press on AI regulation and competition enforcement\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Has not focused on AGI scenarios. Her lens is present-day and near-term AI systems and the governance failures they expose. She treats the current technological moment as requiring urgent democratic action, not waiting for speculative future developments.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Safety requires mandatory accountability. She pushed the risk-based AI Act framework precisely because voluntary safety commitments by companies are insufficient. She has been explicit that the EU's role is to ensure technology is safe for human use — not to stifle innovation, but to ensure that innovation serves people rather than endangering them.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Ethics must be embedded in law. Her decade of competition enforcement demonstrated that large tech companies do not self-regulate on ethics. The DMA, DSA, and AI Act represent her theory of change: convert ethical expectations into legally binding obligations with real enforcement.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Vestager is the most consequential AI and digital regulator of the 2010s–2020s. She believes the EU has both the right and the obligation to set global standards for AI, and that the transatlantic relationship requires common standards rather than regulatory divergence. She has been explicit that democracy requires that digital rules be upheld: \"We have promised Europeans that their services would be safe to use for their mental health, for democracy, and that is of course core in any democracy that you stand by the promises made.\" She views compliance as a badge of honor, not a burden.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Google | Antitrust — Android, Shopping, AdSense; multiple multi-billion-euro fines |\n| Apple | Antitrust — App Store, music streaming; €1.8 billion fine (2024) |\n| Meta/Facebook | Data privacy, advertising practices, DMA compliance investigations |\n| Amazon | Antitrust — Marketplace data use, Buy Box |\n| U.S. government | Repeated U.S. complaints that EU regulations unfairly target American companies |\n| EU tech industry lobby | Industry argued her regulatory agenda would harm European competitiveness |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- World Economic Forum (Davos) — multiple years\n- Washington Post Live interviews\n- RSA Conference\n- Atlantic Council, Aspen Institute\n- Numerous European Parliament hearings (televised)\n\n**Podcasts:** Featured on major technology and policy podcasts throughout her tenure.\n**Social Media:** Active on X and LinkedIn during tenure as EVP.\n**Online Courses:** None documented.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Democratic constitutionalism; fundamental rights; rule of law; social market economy (European model); proportionality.\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Her parents were both ministers. She served as Minister of Education and Ecclesiastical Affairs in Denmark (1998–2000), giving her direct engagement with the intersection of religion and public institutions. Her husband is a gymnasium teacher of mathematics and philosophy. These biographical threads suggest a sustained, if not publicized, engagement with questions of meaning and human formation.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. Multiple EU court decisions overturned portions of her antitrust rulings against Apple and Amazon on procedural grounds, embarrassing the Commission.\n2. U.S. officials and politicians repeatedly accused her of using competition law as protectionism against American companies.\n3. She ran for European Commission president in 2023 and lost; critics within the EU said her decade of antagonizing member states through enforcement created political liabilities.\n4. Some civil liberties advocates argued the AI Act she co-overseen made too many exceptions for national security and law enforcement AI uses.\n5. Critics argued the DMA and DSA were designed around yesterday's tech giants and failed to anticipate AI-era platform dynamics.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** She has acknowledged that enforcement of the DMA and DSA would be \"complex\" and require sustained political will across member states, and that regulatory capacity must grow to meet the challenge.\n\n---\n",
  "vinyals": "# Research Profile: Oriol Vinyals\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Oriol Vinyals  **Born:** 1983, Sabadell, Catalonia, Spain  **Nationality:** Spanish  \n**Education:** B.S./M.S., Mathematics and Telecommunication Engineering, Universitat Politècnica de Catalunya (Barcelona); M.S., Computer Science, University of California, San Diego; Ph.D., Electrical Engineering and Computer Sciences, University of California, Berkeley (2013) — advisor Nelson Morgan  \n**Current Role:** VP of Research, Google DeepMind; Technical Lead, Gemini  \n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2013–2014 | Research Scientist, Google Brain |\n| 2014–2016 | Research Scientist / Senior Research Scientist, Google Brain (Seq2Seq, pointer networks) |\n| 2016–2019 | Research Scientist / Lead, Google DeepMind (AlphaStar) |\n| 2019–2022 | Research Director, Google DeepMind |\n| 2022–present | VP of Research, Google DeepMind; Technical Lead, Gemini |\n\n**Major Awards:** MIT Technology Review \"35 Innovators Under 35\" (2016); over 70,000 total paper citations; widely recognized as one of the most influential deep learning researchers of his generation\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Sequence-to-sequence learning and neural machine translation\n- Game-playing AI and reinforcement learning\n- Multi-agent systems and emergent behavior\n- Large language models and multimodal AI\n- Neural architecture design\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Sequence to Sequence Learning with Neural Networks\" (Sutskever, Vinyals, Le) | 2014 | Co-invented the seq2seq framework; showed neural networks can map arbitrary input sequences to output sequences end-to-end; direct ancestor of every encoder-decoder transformer |\n| \"Grammar as a Foreign Language\" (Vinyals et al.) | 2015 | Applied seq2seq to constituency parsing; showed NLP problems can be framed as sequence generation |\n| \"Pointer Networks\" (Vinyals, Fortunato, Jaitly) | 2015 | Introduced attention-based architecture that outputs pointers to input elements; enabled solving combinatorial optimization problems with neural nets |\n| \"Show and Tell: A Neural Image Caption Generator\" (Vinyals et al.) | 2015 | Seminal image captioning paper; end-to-end multimodal sequence generation |\n| \"Matching Networks for One Shot Learning\" | 2016 | Foundational paper in few-shot learning using attention mechanisms |\n| \"Grand Master Level in StarCraft II Using Multi-Agent Reinforcement Learning\" (AlphaStar team) | 2019 | *Nature*; AI system reaching Grandmaster rank in StarCraft II — complex real-time strategy game with imperfect information and long-horizon planning |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) learning: encoder-decoder framework for arbitrary sequence mapping; the architectural ancestor of T5, BART, and all modern translation and generation systems\n- Pointer networks: attention mechanism that selects from input elements; useful for combinatorial problems (traveling salesman, sorting)\n- AlphaStar architecture: multi-agent deep RL system with transformer-based policy networks, pointer networks, and self-play training; the most complex game-playing AI of its era\n- Contributions to Gemini (Google's flagship multimodal large language model)\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** AlphaStar evaluated on Blizzard's StarCraft II platform; contributed to NLP benchmark development through seq2seq applications\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None; influence is entirely through research papers and AI system development\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Grand Master Level in StarCraft II Using Multi-Agent Reinforcement Learning\" (*Nature*, 2019) — landmark scientific paper on game AI, read widely outside AI community\n- Various DeepMind blog posts on AlphaStar and AI research philosophy\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Multiple interviews in *Wired*, *MIT Technology Review*, BBC, *Financial Times* on AlphaStar and AI capabilities\n- DeepMind research blog posts on Gemini and AI progress\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Vinyals has offered one of the more nuanced public statements on AGI definitions. He observed in 2023 that current AI models would almost certainly have been declared AGI by anyone in the field seven years prior — the goalposts have moved as the technology improved. He uses this to argue that AGI is partly a definitional and sociological question, not purely a technical one. He is optimistic about the trajectory of AI capabilities and has described the current moment as a fundamental shift from narrow specialized systems toward autonomous agents that can pursue goals across diverse environments.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Vinyals has been measured and consistent on safety: \"AI can provide extraordinary benefits, but like all technology, it can have negative impacts unless it's built and used responsibly.\" He notes that DeepMind maintains dedicated teams for technical safety, ethics, and public engagement specifically to anticipate short and long-term risks. He has also noted that consciousness in current AI models is something he does not think hard about practically — acknowledging philosophical depth without claiming it is currently a live engineering concern. His safety orientation is institutional and precautionary rather than alarmist.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Vinyals approaches ethics primarily through the lens of responsible deployment and research culture. He has emphasized that AI systems should be built and used responsibly, with ongoing attention to risks. The AlphaStar project itself raised ethical debates about the appropriate use of game AI and the implications of superhuman performance in complex strategic environments. His response to those debates has been that demonstrating AI capabilities in contained, well-understood game environments is preferable to deploying similarly powerful systems in less understood real-world settings.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** No prominent public policy positions. His role at DeepMind places him within an organization that actively engages with AI governance debates, but his individual public statements focus on research and capabilities rather than regulatory frameworks.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Critics of AlphaStar's StarCraft advantage | The game-playing AI used inhuman reaction speeds in early versions; critics questioned whether it represented \"fair\" competition; DeepMind responded by imposing human-like action rate constraints |\n| AGI definitional inflation critics | Some argue that pointing to shifting goalposts excuses inadequate rigor in capability assessments |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Lex Fridman Podcast: \"Oriol Vinyals: DeepMind AlphaStar, StarCraft, Language, and Sequences\" — extended public interview reaching millions\n- MIT EmTech Digital 2022 keynote\n- Multiple conference talks at NeurIPS, ICML, ICLR on AlphaStar, seq2seq, and Gemini\n- IEEE Signal Processing Society interview (2022)\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Lex Fridman Podcast* (#42) — AlphaStar, game AI, and language\n- *Google DeepMind: The Podcast* — Gemini 2.0 and the evolution of agentic AI\n\n**Social Media:** Active on Twitter/X as @OriolVinyalsML; tweets on research developments and AI capabilities\n\n**Online Courses:** No MOOCs; teaches through Google DeepMind's internal research culture and public talks\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\nOn human uniqueness, his AlphaStar work raised interesting questions: a system trained purely on human StarCraft replays eventually surpassed all human players in a game requiring strategic depth, spatial reasoning, real-time decision-making, and long-horizon planning — cognitive capacities long considered distinctively human. His measured response — placing this accomplishment in historical context alongside chess and Go — reflects a mature understanding that AI superhuman performance in specific domains does not resolve questions about general human uniqueness.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Responsible development; empirical rigor; institutional accountability — reflecting DeepMind's explicit research ethics framework\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Not prominent in public record; his intellectual formation is in mathematics, telecommunications engineering, and computer science.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **AlphaStar's inhuman action speed:** Early versions of AlphaStar used reaction times and multi-tasking speeds physically impossible for human players; critics argued this was not a fair comparison to human intelligence. DeepMind acknowledged this and constrained later versions to human-comparable action rates.\n2. **Seq2seq's contested origins:** Sutskever, Vinyals, and Le published the seq2seq paper in 2014; similar ideas were being developed simultaneously by other groups, and priority debates exist in the research community. No formal dispute, but the history of credit is more distributed than single citations suggest.\n3. **Gemini's benchmark performance controversy:** At DeepMind as Technical Lead for Gemini, Vinyals has been associated with benchmarking controversies around Gemini 1.0's initial performance comparisons; journalists and researchers raised concerns about selective benchmark reporting.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Vinyals has acknowledged that the moving-goalposts problem in AGI is real and that the field needs more rigorous, agreed-upon metrics for capability assessment rather than informal consensus that shifts post-hoc.\n\n---\n",
  "weizenbaum": "# Research Profile: Joseph Weizenbaum\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Joseph Weizenbaum\n**Born:** January 8, 1923, Berlin, Germany\n**Died:** March 5, 2008, Berlin, Germany\n**Nationality:** American (naturalized); German-born\n**Education:**\n- B.S. in Mathematics, Wayne State University, Detroit, 1950\n- Graduate study in mathematics, Wayne State University\n- No formal PhD; rose through industry and academic appointment on the strength of his work\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1923–1936 | Childhood in Berlin; fled Nazi Germany with family, January 1936 |\n| 1936–1942 | Lived in Detroit; entered Wayne State University |\n| 1942–1945 | U.S. Army meteorologist, World War II |\n| 1952–1963 | Systems programmer, General Electric; worked on ERMA banking system for Bank of America |\n| 1963–1988 | Associate Professor, then Professor of Computer Science, MIT |\n| 1966 | Published ELIZA program |\n| 1976 | Published *Computer Power and Human Reason* |\n| 1988–2008 | Emeritus Professor, MIT; returned frequently to Germany; became increasingly prominent critic of AI and technocracy |\n| 2008 | Died in Berlin; buried at Weißensee Jewish Cemetery |\n\n**Major Awards:** None of the prize variety — his legacy is moral and philosophical rather than technical. The Weizenbaum Award (German Digital Society) was named posthumously in his honor.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Natural language processing (early)\n- Interactive computing\n- Human-computer interaction\n- SLIP (Symmetric List Processing) language\n- Philosophy and social critique of computer science\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"ELIZA — A Computer Program for the Study of Natural Language Communication Between Man and Machine\" | 1966 | Published in *Communications of the ACM*; introduced ELIZA and the DOCTOR script simulating Rogerian psychotherapy |\n| *Computer Power and Human Reason: From Judgment to Calculation* | 1976 | Foundational critique arguing some decisions must never be delegated to machines; distinction between \"deciding\" and \"calculating\" |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- Created ELIZA (1964–1966), the first conversational chatbot, at MIT\n- Developed the DOCTOR script, which simulated a Rogerian psychotherapist using pattern matching and substitution\n- Invented SLIP (Symmetric List Processing), a programming language for list manipulation, used by other early AI researchers\n- Pioneered the field later called human-computer interaction — though he ultimately warned against its direction\n- Defined the distinction between \"technical problems\" (where computers can assist) and \"human problems\" (where they must not replace judgment)\n\n**Historical Significance:** ELIZA was the first program to demonstrate that humans would anthropomorphize a machine given minimal provocation. The DOCTOR script used only simple pattern matching — no understanding whatsoever — yet users confided deeply personal secrets to it. Psychiatrists seriously proposed using it in therapy. This disturbed Weizenbaum profoundly. What had been a technical demonstration became an ethical alarm. His subsequent career was devoted to arguing that the ease with which humans project humanity onto machines is a danger, not a feature. He remains the founding voice of AI ethics as a serious discipline.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- *Computer Power and Human Reason: From Judgment to Calculation* (1976, W. H. Freeman) — Written for general and academic readers; argues that the instrumental rationality embedded in computers threatens human wisdom, compassion, and political freedom. Distinguishes between \"deciding\" (a human act requiring judgment) and \"calculating\" (what machines do). Became a founding text of AI criticism.\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"ELIZA — A Computer Program for the Study of Natural Language Communication Between Man and Machine\" (1966), *Communications of the ACM* — The foundational ELIZA paper\n- Various essays on computers and society published in *Science*, *The New York Times*, and German media throughout the 1980s and 1990s\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- *Kurs auf den Eisberg* (1976, German) — Popular critique of technology and political complacency\n- Numerous public lectures and media interviews; documentary film *Plug & Pray* (2010, posthumous release) featured Weizenbaum in extended conversation with Hiroshi Ishiguro and Ray Kurzweil\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** Weizenbaum never denied that machines could perform impressive computations. His argument was subtler and more alarming: that the capacity of machines to simulate understanding would seduce humans into delegating decisions that require genuine human wisdom. He coined the concept of the \"computer metaphor of man\" — the reduction of human beings to information processors — and argued it was philosophically and morally catastrophic. He wrote that AI researchers had produced a language for describing the mind that, through its very precision, distorted what it described.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** Central to his thought was the distinction between \"knowing\" and \"understanding.\" Machines can know facts and apply rules; only humans can understand context, bear responsibility, feel compassion, and exercise judgment in the morally serious sense. He was particularly alarmed by what he called \"obscene\" proposals: using computers to replace human judges, therapists, military commanders, or diplomats. These roles require something machines categorically lack — human accountability before other humans.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:**\n- Warned explicitly against automating warfare — the removal of human judgment from the decision to kill\n- Argued that delegating welfare decisions, criminal sentencing, or therapeutic relationships to machines is a form of moral abdication\n- Critiqued \"compulsive programmers\" — brilliant but morally stunted technologists who regard problems as purely technical\n- Warned that the myth of technological inevitability is \"a powerful tranquilizer of the conscience\" — it relieves people of responsibility\n- Argued that computers make \"obscene\" what should be human: grief, judgment, care, love\n\n**Known Debates:** Weizenbaum's book provoked sharp responses from AI researchers, particularly Marvin Minsky and John McCarthy, who regarded his philosophical concerns as sentimental obstructionism. Herbert Simon and Allen Newell also pushed back. The exchange remains a defining fault line in AI history — between those who see machine intelligence as continuous with human intelligence and those who see an unbridgeable qualitative difference.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and Human Uniqueness:** Weizenbaum held that human consciousness is not computable — not because it is supernatural, but because it is constituted by embodiment, history, emotion, love, and the experience of mortality. The ability to \"understand\" another person is not an information-processing feat; it is the result of shared humanity. He rejected the functionalist view that mind is software running on biological hardware. \"One should not measure human dignity by what a machine can or cannot do. The fatal flaw in this form of thinking is that the machine becomes the measure of the human being.\"\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Influenced by Hannah Arendt's political philosophy — the banality of evil, the importance of judgment (*Urteilskraft*)\n- Influenced by the Frankfurt School's critique of instrumental reason — Horkheimer and Adorno's argument that modernity's reduction of reason to mere calculation produces dehumanization\n- Implicitly draws on Kantian ethics: treating persons as ends in themselves, never merely as means — a principle violated by every system that reduces humans to data points\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Weizenbaum was not a theologian, but *Computer Power and Human Reason* is thick with humanistic reference. He cites literature, philosophy, and history. His central claim — that there are things computers ought never to do, regardless of whether they could — is a deontological claim with deep roots in the Jewish moral tradition: certain acts are categorically forbidden (*assur*) regardless of outcome. The Nazi example is never far from the surface of his writing. For Weizenbaum, building systems that automate life-and-death decisions is structurally similar to building the infrastructure of the death camps — not in magnitude, but in the logic of moral abdication.\n\n---\n",
  "welling": "# Research Profile: Max Welling\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Max Welling  **Born:** circa 1967–1968, Netherlands  **Nationality:** Dutch  \n**Education:** Undergraduate and Diplom studies in Theoretical Physics, Utrecht University; Ph.D., Theoretical Physics, Utrecht University (1998) — advisor Nobel Laureate Gerard 't Hooft  \n**Current Role:** Research Chair in Machine Learning, University of Amsterdam; Director, Amsterdam Machine Learning Lab (AMLab); VP Technology, Qualcomm Netherlands; Distinguished Scientist, Microsoft Research AI4Science; Fellow, CIFAR; Fellow, ELLIS  \n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1998–2000 | Postdoctoral Researcher, Caltech (with Pietro Perona) |\n| 2000–2003 | Postdoctoral Researcher, University of Toronto (with Geoffrey Hinton) |\n| 2003–2006 | Assistant Professor, UC Irvine |\n| 2006–2012 | Associate Professor, UC Irvine |\n| 2012–present | Research Chair in Machine Learning, University of Amsterdam |\n| 2014–present | Director, AMLab, University of Amsterdam |\n| 2016–present | Co-Director, Qualcomm–UvA Deep Learning Lab (QUVA) |\n| 2017–present | VP Technology, Qualcomm Netherlands (following Scyfer acquisition) |\n| 2022–present | Distinguished Scientist, Microsoft Research AI4Science |\n\n**Major Awards:** ECCV Koenderink Prize (2010); ICML Test of Time Award (2021); ICLR 2024 Test of Time Award (for VAE paper); ICLR 2017 Best Paper Award (Group Equivariant CNNs); Fellow, CIFAR; Fellow, ELLIS\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Generative models and variational autoencoders\n- Graph neural networks and geometric deep learning\n- Equivariant neural networks\n- Bayesian deep learning\n- Energy-efficient and physics-inspired AI\n- Machine learning for materials science and drug discovery\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Auto-Encoding Variational Bayes\" (Kingma and Welling) | 2013 | Introduced the variational autoencoder (VAE); one of the most cited papers in deep learning; ICLR 2024 Test of Time Award |\n| \"Semi-supervised Classification with Graph Convolutional Networks\" (Kipf and Welling) | 2016 | Introduced the graph convolutional network (GCN); foundational architecture for all graph neural network research |\n| \"Group Equivariant Convolutional Networks\" (Cohen and Welling) | 2016 | ICML; introduced equivariant neural networks respecting symmetry groups; ICLR Best Paper |\n| \"Bayesian Compression for Deep Learning\" | 2017 | Variational approach to neural network compression and pruning |\n| \"Steerable CNNs\" | 2017 | Extension of equivariant networks to continuous symmetry groups |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Variational Autoencoder (VAE): generative model combining variational Bayes and deep neural networks; enables principled latent space learning\n- Graph Convolutional Network (GCN): spectral convolution on graphs using localized first-order approximation; foundation of modern graph neural networks\n- Group Equivariant CNNs: neural networks that respect discrete symmetry groups (rotations, reflections); applied to medical imaging and molecular science\n- Steerable CNNs: continuous equivariance via irreducible representations of Lie groups\n- Stochastic Gradient Langevin Dynamics (with M. Jordan, 2011): Bayesian posterior sampling via noisy SGD\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** Contributed to molecular property prediction benchmarks; work on AI4Science has produced benchmark datasets for materials discovery\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** No single-author textbooks; contributions to the field are through highly cited papers and the VAE and GCN architectures that now underpin entire research areas\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Intelligence Per Kilowatt-Hour\" — keynote lecture arguing for energy-efficient AI; connects thermodynamics to machine learning\n- \"Do We Still Need Models Or Just Data?\" — essay on the interplay of physics-based models and data-driven learning\n- Blog posts and talks on the AI energy crisis and sustainable machine learning\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- \"Max Welling: Will AI Save Us — or Break Us?\" — World AI Summit (publicly available)\n- Multiple interviews in IEEE Signal Processing Society, science media, and AI conferences\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Welling has not staked out a strong personal position on AGI timelines, but his research orientation reflects skepticism about purely data-driven paths to general intelligence. He emphasizes the importance of incorporating prior knowledge — physical laws, geometric symmetries, causal structures — into AI systems, which implies that scale alone is insufficient. He has spoken about uncertainty surrounding AI development and the need to consciously direct AI toward humanity's most pressing challenges rather than assuming it will self-organize toward good outcomes.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Welling's safety concerns are tied to energy and sustainability as much as to alignment. He has argued that the exponential growth in AI compute is unsustainable and that energy efficiency must be a core design constraint, not an afterthought. His physics-inspired research program — creating models that are efficient precisely because they encode physical symmetries — is in part a response to this concern. He also acknowledges broader societal risks from AI and has spoken about the importance of directing AI development toward the challenges that matter most for humanity.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Welling believes the AI community has the chance to choose what kind of future it builds. He emphasizes responsibility in directing AI toward climate, health, and materials science challenges rather than purely commercial applications. His move to co-found Scyfer (acquired by Qualcomm) and his work at Microsoft Research AI4Science reflect a commitment to AI that generates concrete scientific and social value. He has flagged the climate impact of large-scale AI training as an ethical issue that the field has been too slow to address.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Welling's policy positions are less prominent than his research contributions. He tends to engage with policy through the lens of scientific priority-setting — advocating for investment in AI for climate, materials, and health — rather than regulatory frameworks. His role in ELLIS reflects a commitment to European AI research that is not purely commercially driven and can serve public interest goals.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Scaling-first researchers | Welling argues physics-inspired, symmetry-aware, energy-efficient architectures will outperform brute-force scaling in scientific domains |\n| Climate-indifferent AI labs | His \"intelligence per kilowatt-hour\" framing challenges the energy profligacy of large-scale model training |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- \"Intelligence Per Kilowatt-Hour\" — recurring keynote on AI energy efficiency\n- \"From Physics to AI to Materials: A Journey from Foundations to Impact\" — ICLR 2026 Invited Talk\n- Multiple keynote addresses at ICLR, ICML, NeurIPS on geometric deep learning and generative models\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- *Voices in AI* (GigaOm), Episode 82 — extended interview on probabilistic deep learning and AI's future\n- *Latent Space* — interview on CuspAI and materials discovery\n- *Physics for Future*, Episode 6 — \"AI, Molecules, and the Future of Intelligence\"\n\n**Social Media:** Active on Twitter/X; engages on AI research developments, energy efficiency, and materials science applications\n\n**Online Courses:** Teaches through the University of Amsterdam and ELLIS PhD program; lecture materials available online\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Scientific responsibility; sustainability as an ethical constraint; priority for AI applications that address humanity's most pressing problems — climate, health, materials\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Primarily rooted in the philosophy of physics; his work with 't Hooft and his continued interest in thermodynamics, entropy, and physical symmetries reflect a tradition of natural philosophy that sees science as revealing deep truths about reality. His energy efficiency arguments connect to broader debates about technology and human flourishing.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Qualcomm acquisition of Scyfer:** Some in the academic community raised concerns about commercialization of university research; Welling's dual role at UvA and Qualcomm has been questioned in terms of potential conflicts of interest.\n2. **VAE limitations:** The VAE, despite its elegance, produces blurry outputs compared to GANs and diffusion models; while still widely used for its theoretical properties, it has been partially superseded for pure image generation quality.\n3. **Geometric deep learning's practical complexity:** Group equivariant networks, while theoretically powerful, require domain expertise to apply and have not seen as widespread adoption outside scientific ML as their theoretical benefits might suggest.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Welling has acknowledged that purely geometry-based approaches to inductive bias need to be combined with data-driven learning for maximum effectiveness; neither symmetry priors nor raw data alone suffice.\n\n---\n",
  "wiener": "# Research Profile: Norbert Wiener\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Norbert Wiener\n**Born:** November 26, 1894, Columbia, Missouri\n**Died:** March 18, 1964, Stockholm, Sweden (age 69)\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- B.A., Mathematics, Tufts College (1909, age 14)\n- Graduate study in zoology, Harvard (1909–1910)\n- Graduate study in philosophy, Cornell (1910–1911)\n- Ph.D., Mathematical Logic (comparison of Schröder vs. Russell/Whitehead), Harvard (1913, age 18); advisor: Karl Schmidt\n- Postdoctoral study under Bertrand Russell, Cambridge; under David Hilbert, Göttingen (1913–1915)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1915–1919 | Various positions: Harvard, Maine, Aberdeen Proving Ground |\n| 1919–1924 | Instructor, Mathematics, MIT |\n| 1924–1929 | Assistant Professor, Mathematics, MIT |\n| 1929–1932 | Associate Professor, Mathematics, MIT |\n| 1932–1960 | Full Professor, Mathematics, MIT |\n| 1960–1964 | Institute Professor Emeritus, MIT |\n\n**Major Awards:** Bôcher Prize, American Mathematical Society (1933, shared); National Medal of Science (1963, presented weeks before his death); National Book Award in Science, Philosophy and Religion (1965, posthumous, for *God & Golem, Inc.*).\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Stochastic processes and Brownian motion\n- Cybernetics: control and communication in animals and machines\n- Feedback systems and servomechanisms\n- Harmonic analysis and the Wiener-Khinchin theorem\n- Information theory (parallel to Shannon's, developed independently)\n- Ethics of automation and human-machine systems\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| *Cybernetics: Or, Control and Communication in the Animal and the Machine* | 1948 | Founded cybernetics; unified biology, engineering, and communication through feedback |\n| *The Human Use of Human Beings: Cybernetics and Society* | 1950 (rev. 1954) | Applied cybernetics to social ethics; first major warning about automation's human consequences |\n| *God & Golem, Inc.: A Comment on Certain Points Where Cybernetics Impinges on Religion* | 1964 | Examined machine learning, machine reproduction, and their theological implications |\n| \"Generalized Harmonic Analysis\" | 1930 | Foundational paper in stochastic processes; Wiener-Khinchin theorem |\n| \"Extrapolation, Interpolation and Smoothing of Stationary Time Series\" | 1949 | Wiener filter; foundational to signal processing and control theory |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- Cybernetics as a unified science: Wiener demonstrated that the same mathematical principles — feedback, control, communication, entropy — govern both living systems and machines. This broke down the conceptual wall between biology and engineering.\n- Wiener filter: optimal algorithm for extracting a signal from noise; foundational to radar, communications, and modern signal processing\n- Wiener process (Brownian motion): rigorous mathematical model of random continuous-time processes; foundational to modern probability theory, physics, and quantitative finance\n- Wiener measure: mathematical foundation for functional integration; used in quantum field theory\n- Early warning about technological unemployment: Wiener wrote to labor unions and industrialists in the late 1940s warning that automation would displace workers and cause social instability — warnings largely ignored\n\n**Historical Significance:** Wiener's cybernetics concept was arguably the most broadly influential scientific framework of the mid-twentieth century, shaping biology, psychology, engineering, social science, and the emerging computer sciences simultaneously. He grasped, before anyone else, that control and communication were unified phenomena — that the thermostat and the brain were operating on the same mathematical principles. This insight underlies modern robotics, control systems, cognitive science, and AI. He was also the first major scientist to frame automation as a moral and political problem rather than merely a technical one.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- *Cybernetics* (1948, 2nd ed. 1961) — technical and semi-popular; thesis: feedback and communication are the universal principles governing complex systems, biological or mechanical\n- *The Human Use of Human Beings* (1950, rev. 1954) — popular; thesis: automation threatens human dignity and social order unless governed by humane values\n- *Ex-Prodigy: My Childhood and Youth* (1953) — autobiography, vol. 1\n- *I Am a Mathematician* (1956) — autobiography, vol. 2; covers adult career\n- *The Tempter* (1959) — novel exploring ethical dimensions of scientific research and weapons development\n- *God & Golem, Inc.* (1964) — popular-philosophical; thesis: machine learning, machine reproduction, and human-machine interaction raise profound theological and ethical questions\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"Generalized Harmonic Analysis\" (1930) — *Acta Mathematica*\n- \"The Extrapolation, Interpolation and Smoothing of Stationary Time Series\" (1949) — MIT Technical Report / Wiley\n- \"Cybernetics\" (1948) — preview article, *Scientific American*\n- Letter to Walter Reuther (UAW), 1949 — warned of automation and technological unemployment\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- *The Human Use of Human Beings* (1950) — most accessible and widely read of his works\n- *God & Golem, Inc.* (1964) — short, accessible; his most direct engagement with theology and machine ethics\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** Wiener was more cautious than his contemporaries about celebrating machine intelligence. He understood that machines operating on feedback could replicate certain intelligent behaviors, but he was deeply concerned about the gap between a machine's formal operation and the human values that should govern its use. He warned that machines \"can be enormously useful servants, but only if we have the wisdom to control them.\" He foresaw that machines optimized for narrow objectives could cause catastrophic harm if those objectives were poorly specified — a concern that now goes by the name \"alignment.\"\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** Wiener's central conviction was that humans have a dignity rooted in their capacity for communication, learning, and moral agency — and that this dignity is threatened when humans are treated as information-processing components interchangeable with machines. *The Human Use of Human Beings* argued that the goal of a good society is to use machines to expand human freedom, not to replace human judgment and degrade human work. He explicitly opposed the \"worship of the machine\" and the reduction of human beings to economic units optimized for efficiency.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:** Wiener raised ethical concerns with unusual moral intensity for a scientist of his era:\n- Technological unemployment: automation would displace workers faster than society could adapt; he wrote to labor unions and industrialists directly\n- Military automation: he refused military research funding after Hiroshima (1947) and wrote publicly about his refusal — an extraordinary act for a Cold War academic\n- The alignment problem (avant la lettre): he warned that a machine given a goal would pursue it without moral judgment; \"the machine that pursues its goal without any moral constraint is one of the most dangerous things in the world\"\n- Information as power: he recognized that control of communication channels was control of society\n\n**Known Debates or Controversies of Their Era:** Wiener's refusal of military funding in 1947 was controversial. He published his reasons in *The Atlantic Monthly* (\"A Scientist Rebels,\" January 1947), arguing that scientists who contribute to weapons of mass destruction bear moral responsibility for their use. This put him at odds with colleagues who took the view that science is value-neutral. He also had a famously difficult personal relationship with Minsky, Shannon, and others in the emerging AI field who found his ethical warnings excessive.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and What Makes Humans Human:** Wiener believed that what makes humans distinctively human is their capacity for communication, meaning-making, and moral reasoning — qualities that emerge from social relationships and cannot be reduced to information processing alone. He was not a Cartesian dualist; he accepted a broadly naturalistic account of mind. But he insisted that the social and relational dimensions of human life — what a person means to others, what they contribute to shared human projects — constitute a dignity that cannot be captured by any information-theoretic measure. Human beings are not information systems; they are persons in community.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Wiener drew on multiple traditions:\n- Jewish prophetic ethics: a strong sense of moral responsibility, especially toward the vulnerable; a conviction that power entails obligation\n- Kantian duty ethics: treating persons as ends, never merely as means; the industrial machine that treats workers as interchangeable parts violates this\n- Civic republican virtue: the good society requires active, informed, morally engaged citizens; automation that passive-ifies citizens threatens democratic self-governance\nHis ethical framework was eclectic but consistently focused on human dignity and social consequence.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** *God & Golem, Inc.* is one of the most sustained engagements with theology by any founder of computing or AI. Wiener used the Jewish Golem legend — the clay figure animated by a rabbi, bearing the Hebrew word for \"truth\" on its forehead — as a meditation on what it means for human beings to create intelligent artifacts. He posed the question: \"God is to Golem as man is to Machines?\" — and explored what obligations flow from that analogy. He argued that the machine-creator relationship requires humility, because machines can be activated but cannot be given wisdom. His famous injunction — \"render unto man the things which are man's and unto the computer the things which are the computer's\" — is a deliberate paraphrase of Christ's words about Caesar and God.\n\n---\n",
  "winograd": "# Research Profile: Terry Winograd\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Terry Allen Winograd\n**Born:** February 24, 1946, Takoma Park, Maryland\n**Status:** Living; Professor Emeritus, Stanford University\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:**\n- B.A. in Mathematics, Colorado College, 1966\n- Ph.D. in Applied Mathematics (Artificial Intelligence), MIT, 1970\n- Dissertation advisor: Seymour Papert\n- Dissertation: \"Procedures as a Representation for Data in a Computer Program for Understanding Natural Language\" — the SHRDLU program\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1966–1970 | Graduate student, MIT AI Lab (under Seymour Papert) |\n| 1970–1971 | SHRDLU completed; presented as PhD dissertation |\n| 1971–1973 | Postdoctoral and visiting positions; MIT |\n| 1973–present | Faculty, Stanford University (Computer Science) |\n| 1986 | Published *Understanding Computers and Cognition* (with Fernando Flores) |\n| 1991 | Helped found Stanford's Human-Computer Interaction Group |\n| 1995–1998 | Dissertation advisor to Larry Page; Page co-founded Google in 1998 |\n| 2002 | Visiting researcher, Google |\n| 2004–present | Co-founder, Hasso Plattner Institute of Design (\"d.school\") at Stanford |\n| 2006–present | Professor Emeritus, Stanford University |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- ACM Software System Award (for SHRDLU, shared citation)\n- Member, Association for Computing Machinery\n- Fellow, Association for the Advancement of Artificial Intelligence (AAAI)\n- Stanford d.school co-founder — institutional legacy\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Natural language processing and understanding\n- Artificial intelligence (early career)\n- Human-computer interaction (later career)\n- Philosophy of mind as it applies to computing\n- Design theory and design thinking\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Procedures as a Representation for Data in a Computer Program for Understanding Natural Language\" (PhD dissertation) | 1970 | The SHRDLU program — natural language interface to a simulated blocks world |\n| *Understanding Natural Language* | 1972 | Book-length account of SHRDLU; widely read in AI and linguistics |\n| *Understanding Computers and Cognition: A New Foundation for Design* (with Fernando Flores) | 1986 | Drew on Heidegger, Gadamer, and Maturana to argue that AI cannot understand without embodiment and social situatedness |\n| \"Thinking Machines: Can There Be? Are We?\" | 1990 | Essay on mind, machines, and the limits of the computational metaphor |\n| *Bringing Design to Software* (ed.) | 1996 | Applied design thinking to software development |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- Created SHRDLU (1968–1970, PhD thesis): a program that could respond to natural English commands about a simulated \"blocks world\" of colored shapes. SHRDLU could parse sentences, answer questions, execute commands, and refer to conversational history. \"Pick up the big red block\" — and it would do it, explaining its reasoning.\n- SHRDLU was the first program to demonstrate genuine integration of syntax, semantics, and context in natural language processing within a constrained domain\n- Later, with Fernando Flores, produced the first sustained philosophical critique of AI based on phenomenological philosophy (Heidegger, Maturana)\n- Co-founded Stanford's HCI group and the d.school, shaping how designers and engineers think about technology in relation to human need\n- Advised Larry Page (Google's co-founder) on his dissertation — Page's PageRank algorithm emerged from this advising relationship\n\n**Historical Significance:** SHRDLU was the high-water mark of classical AI's ambitions for natural language understanding. It was so impressive that it generated enormous optimism — and, when the approach failed to generalize beyond its toy domain, enormous disillusionment. Winograd's subsequent philosophical turn was remarkable: having built one of the field's most celebrated systems, he concluded that the approach was fundamentally limited. His *Understanding Computers and Cognition* (1986) remains one of the most philosophically sophisticated critiques of classical AI ever produced by someone who had been a practitioner.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- *Understanding Natural Language* (1972, Academic Press) — Detailed account of SHRDLU; technical and linguistic; highly influential in AI and computational linguistics\n- *Understanding Computers and Cognition: A New Foundation for Design* (1986, with Fernando Flores, Ablex Publishing; later reissued by Addison-Wesley) — Argued that AI's computational model of cognition was philosophically mistaken; drew on Heidegger's *Being and Time*, Maturana's biology, and Austin's speech act theory; proposed a new foundation for design based on commitment, conversation, and social action\n- *Bringing Design to Software* (1996, ed., Addison-Wesley) — Applied design thinking principles to software engineering\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"Thinking Machines: Can There Be? Are We?\" (1990) — Accessible essay on the limits of computational models of mind\n- Various papers on HCI, design, and the social context of computing\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- *Understanding Computers and Cognition* was written for a broad academic audience across philosophy, computer science, management, and design; not a technical paper but accessible to educated non-specialists\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** Winograd began as a believer in the power of symbolic AI — SHRDLU demonstrated that with sufficient engineering, machines could handle natural language in a bounded domain. His later view, developed with Fernando Flores, was that this approach was not merely technically limited but philosophically mistaken. The computational model of cognition — mind as symbol manipulator, language as information transfer — misunderstands the nature of human language, thought, and action. Language does not convey information; it coordinates action within a shared social world. Cognition is not processing symbols; it is being a body in a world, engaged with others in practices shaped by history and culture. Machines have none of this. They cannot be said to \"understand\" language in any meaningful sense.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** Winograd and Flores argued that the proper question for technology design is not \"what can machines do?\" but \"what kind of human practices and commitments does this technology enable or foreclose?\" They drew on Heidegger's analysis of tools: tools are most transparent when they work — we use a hammer without thinking about it. Technology becomes visible when it breaks down (*Vorhandenheit*). The design question is: what breakdowns does this technology create, and are they appropriate given the human activities it serves?\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:**\n- Argued that the rationalistic tradition in AI and management (Simon, March) systematically misrepresents human decision-making by treating it as information processing — with consequences for both AI design and organizational theory\n- Expressed concern that AI systems deployed in contexts requiring genuine understanding (legal, medical, interpersonal) would create systematic mismatches between what the machine \"handles\" and what the situation requires\n- Later work in HCI focused on ensuring that users remained empowered and that technology served human purposes rather than colonizing them\n\n**Known Debates:** *Understanding Computers and Cognition* provoked a fierce response from AI researchers who regarded Heidegger as irrelevant to engineering. Hubert Dreyfus praised the book (he had been making similar arguments since the 1960s). Marvin Minsky was dismissive. The book's influence was strongest outside computer science — in management theory, organizational studies, philosophy of mind, and design — where its critique of rationalism was more welcome.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and Human Uniqueness:** Winograd's philosophical position (developed with Flores) is that human cognition is constitutively embodied, historical, and social — it cannot be abstracted from these features without becoming something other than human cognition. Machines are not conscious, not because they lack the right software, but because they do not inhabit a world, have a history, live in a body, or exist in relationships of care and commitment. Heidegger's concept of *Dasein* — being-in-the-world as the fundamental structure of human existence — grounds this view. Human uniqueness is not a property of information processing capacity but of a mode of being.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Phenomenological ethics (Heidegger, Levinas): priority of the Other's face, ethics as the first philosophy\n- Speech act theory (Austin, Searle, Flores): language as action, commitments as constitutive of social reality\n- Design ethics: technology designers bear responsibility for the forms of life their products enable and foreclose\n- Jewish social justice tradition: tikkun olam, responsibility for repair of the world\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** *Understanding Computers and Cognition* is unusually rich in humanistic reference for a computer science book. It draws on Heidegger, Gadamer (hermeneutics), Husserl (phenomenology), Maturana and Varela (autopoiesis), Austin (speech act theory), and Flores's background in Latin American philosophy and political experience (Flores served in Allende's cabinet and was imprisoned after the 1973 coup). This is not incidental — Winograd and Flores were arguing that computing needed philosophy of mind, not just engineering.\n\n---\n",
  "yizeng": "# Research Profile: Yi Zeng\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Yi Zeng (曾毅) **Born:** Approximately 1981–1982 (cited as ~41 in 2023 reporting) **Nationality:** Chinese\n**Education:** PhD, Institute of Automation, Chinese Academy of Sciences (CASIA); research focus on brain-inspired AI and computational neuroscience\n**Current Role:** Professor and Deputy Director, Research Center for Brain-inspired Artificial Intelligence, Institute of Automation, Chinese Academy of Sciences (CASIA); Director, International Research Center for AI Ethics and Governance; Co-Director, China-UK Research Centre for AI Ethics and Governance; Chief Scientist in AI Ethics and Governance, Institute of AI International Governance, Tsinghua University\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2010s | Researcher, Institute of Automation, Chinese Academy of Sciences |\n| 2016 | Pivots to AI ethics and governance research alongside technical AI work |\n| 2019 | Lead drafter, Beijing AI Principles; co-drafter, National Governance Principles for New Generation AI (GPNGAI) |\n| 2019–present | Director, International Research Center for AI Ethics and Governance, CASIA |\n| 2019–present | Founding director, Research Center for AI Ethics and Sustainable Development, Beijing Academy of AI |\n| 2019–present | Expert, UNESCO Ad-hoc Expert Group on AI Ethics |\n| 2020–present | Expert, WHO Expert Group on AI Ethics and Governance in Health |\n| 2021–present | Board member, National Governance Committee for New Generation Artificial Intelligence, China |\n| 2021–present | Co-Director, China-UK Research Centre for AI Ethics and Governance |\n| 2023 | Addressed UN Security Council on AI governance |\n| 2023 | Named TIME100 AI (inaugural list) |\n| Current | Chief Scientist in AI Ethics and Governance, Institute of AI International Governance, Tsinghua University |\n\n**Major Awards:** TIME100 AI inaugural list (2023); named a UNESCO AI Ethics Expert Without Borders; multiple national and international AI governance recognitions.\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Brain-inspired artificial intelligence (spiking neural networks, cognitive architectures)\n- AI ethics and governance — domestic (China) and international\n- AI safety and alignment\n- AI for sustainable development\n- Cross-cultural AI ethics frameworks\n- General-purpose AI and potential pathways to AGI via brain-inspired approaches\n\n**Landmark Papers / Policy Documents:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Beijing AI Principles | 2019 | First major AI ethics document from China; 15 principles covering R&D, use, and governance of AI; foundational for Chinese and international AI ethics discourse |\n| National Governance Principles of New Generation AI (GPNGAI) | 2019 | Official Chinese government AI principles co-drafted by Zeng; emphasizes harmony, fairness, transparency, and shared benefits |\n| \"Promoting Good Governance of Artificial Intelligence\" | 2020 | National Science Review article; articulates his governance philosophy and bridge between Chinese and global AI ethics |\n| Harmonious AI Principles | Various | Framework drawing on Chinese concept of \"harmony in diversity\" (和而不同) for cross-cultural AI governance |\n| Brain-inspired Cognitive Engine (BrainCog) research | Ongoing | Technical architecture for spiking neural networks toward AGI |\n\n**Key Contributions:**\n- Principal architect of China's AI ethics framework at both institutional and governmental levels\n- Bridged Confucian philosophical concepts (harmony, relational ethics) with global AI governance discourse\n- Served as informal AI ethics diplomat between China and international bodies\n- Addressed UN Security Council on AI governance (2023) — rare platform for an AI researcher\n- Contributed to UNESCO's Recommendation on the Ethics of Artificial Intelligence\n- Leads BrainCog research toward AGI via brain simulation rather than current deep learning paradigms\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** No major English-language monographs. Numerous Chinese-language research publications and policy documents.\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"Promoting Good Governance of Artificial Intelligence\" (*National Science Review*, 2020) — key statement of his governance philosophy\n- Beijing AI Principles document (2019) — widely cited in international AI ethics literature\n- Publications on cross-cultural AI ethics and the Harmonious AI framework\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- TIME100 AI profile (2023) — accessible overview of his position and mission\n- Carnegie Council for Ethics in International Affairs contributions\n- International workshop proceedings on cross-cultural AI governance\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Zeng is unusual among AI ethics researchers in that he also works toward AGI through brain-inspired architectures. He believes whole-brain emulation and brain-inspired spiking neural networks represent a more principled pathway to AGI than current statistical deep learning. His ethical concern is precisely that AGI development must be governed — not halted — because the stakes of getting it wrong are civilization-scale.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** AI safety cannot be separated from AI governance. Technical safety measures must be embedded in governance frameworks that have democratic or at least multi-stakeholder legitimacy. He has argued that AI safety is a global challenge requiring global cooperation, including China, and that excluding China from international safety conversations is counterproductive.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Zeng argues that AI ethics cannot be monopolized by Western liberal frameworks. His \"harmony in diversity\" principle draws on the Confucian concept 和而不同 (be in harmony, yet be different) — the idea that different cultures can converge on AI ethics from different philosophical starting points without one tradition overriding another. He has been consistent that Chinese scientists and policymakers share concerns about beneficial AI with their international counterparts, and that cultural difference need not mean ethical incompatibility.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Zeng operates within the Chinese system while engaging internationally. He co-drafted China's official AI principles, which reflects both the genuine values he holds and the constraints of working within a governance system that does not share all liberal democratic assumptions. Internationally, he has argued for global AI governance frameworks that include all major AI-developing nations. He pushes the position that China is not simply an adversary in AI — that there is genuine convergence on values like non-harm, fairness, and transparency across cultures. At the UN Security Council, he argued for AI governance that \"leaves no one behind.\"\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Western-centric AI ethics frameworks | Argues Confucian and non-Western traditions have genuine contributions to make |\n| AI governance advocates who exclude China | Insists productive global governance requires Chinese participation |\n| Purely technical AI safety approaches | Argues governance and ethics must accompany technical solutions |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- UN Security Council briefing on AI governance (2023)\n- Alan Turing Institute, London\n- UNESCO AI Ethics events\n- Carnegie Council for Ethics in International Affairs\n- International Workshop on Cross-Cultural AI Ethics and Governance (founding organizer)\n- AI for Good (ITU)\n\n**Podcasts:** Limited English-language podcast presence; primarily engages through international conferences and institutional events.\n**Social Media:** Active on X (Twitter handle: @yi_zeng); posted about TIME100 AI recognition in 2023.\n**Online Courses:** None documented in English.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Confucian relational ethics (harmony, reciprocity, filial duty extended to community); human dignity; non-harm; fairness; transparency; sustainability; global solidarity (\"leaving no one behind\").\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Zeng explicitly draws on Chinese philosophical traditions — Confucianism, the concept of harmony — to ground his AI ethics work. This is not merely instrumental; he argues that Chinese philosophical traditions offer genuine moral resources for AI governance that Western frameworks do not capture. He has engaged directly with the question of whether different cultural traditions can converge on shared AI ethics principles without one tradition being absorbed by another.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. Critics argue that China's official AI principles (which Zeng co-drafted) exist in tension with the Chinese government's actual AI deployment — including mass surveillance, social credit systems, and Xinjiang monitoring technologies. The principles and the practice diverge sharply.\n2. Western AI safety researchers have noted that Zeng's bridge-building role, while valuable, does not address the fundamental question of whether the Chinese state will honor international AI governance commitments.\n3. Some AI ethics scholars argue that invoking Confucian harmony is a form of cultural exceptionalism that can be used to resist accountability for specific AI harms.\n4. His dual role — technical AGI researcher and AI ethics policymaker — raises questions about whether his technical optimism about AGI pathways (via brain simulation) sits comfortably with his governance cautions.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Zeng has been explicit that AI governance is a collective responsibility requiring collaboration across nations, and that China's participation in global governance is necessary but not automatically sufficient — the work of building genuine convergence on shared principles is ongoing.\n\n---\n",
  "yudkowsky": "# Research Profile: Eliezer Yudkowsky\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Eliezer Shlomo Yudkowsky\n**Born:** September 11, 1979, Chicago, Illinois, USA\n**Nationality:** American\n**Education:** No formal higher education. Self-taught autodidact. Did not complete high school or attend college. Intellectual formation through independent study of cognitive science, mathematics, philosophy of mind, and decision theory.\n**Current Role:** Research Fellow, Machine Intelligence Research Institute (MIRI)\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2000–present | Research Fellow, Machine Intelligence Research Institute (MIRI), Berkeley, CA |\n| 2000 | Co-founded MIRI (originally the Singularity Institute for Artificial Intelligence) |\n| 2006–2009 | Primary author of the LessWrong Sequences (hundreds of essays on rationality, epistemology, AI risk) |\n| 2007 | Co-founded LessWrong, the rationalist online community |\n| 2010–2015 | Wrote *Harry Potter and the Methods of Rationality* (661,619 words) |\n| 2022–present | Public campaign for international AI development moratorium |\n\n**Major Awards:** TIME100 AI (2023)\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Friendly AI / AI alignment theory\n- Coherent Extrapolated Volition (CEV) — the goal of building AI that pursues what humans would want under idealized epistemic conditions\n- Decision theory (timeless decision theory, updateless decision theory)\n- Reflective stability in self-modifying AI systems\n- Inner alignment and mesa-optimization (foundational conceptual work)\n- Intelligence explosion / Singularity risk modeling\n\n**Landmark Papers:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Creating Friendly AI\" | 2001 | First systematic formulation of the alignment problem for recursive self-improving AI |\n| \"Coherent Extrapolated Volition\" | 2004 | Proposes designing AI to pursue the extrapolated preferences humans would have under ideal conditions |\n| \"Cognitive Biases Potentially Affecting Judgment of Global Risks\" | 2008 | Pioneering compilation of cognitive biases that distort assessment of catastrophic risk |\n| \"Intelligence Explosion Microeconomics\" | 2013 | Formal analysis of recursive self-improvement dynamics |\n| \"Risks from Learned Optimization in Advanced ML Systems\" (with Hubinger et al.) | 2019 | Introduced \"mesa-optimization\" framework — a landmark in inner alignment research |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:**\n- Coined and formalized the concept of \"Friendly AI\"\n- Introduced the Coherent Extrapolated Volition framework\n- Developed Timeless Decision Theory (TDT) and Updateless Decision Theory (UDT) — alternatives to causal decision theory for agents that reason about their own decision procedures\n- Originated the \"AI-Foom\" hypothesis: recursive self-improvement could produce rapid, discontinuous capability jumps\n- Conceptual co-originator (with the \"Risks from Learned Optimization\" team) of mesa-optimization and inner vs. outer alignment distinction\n\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None. Work is primarily theoretical and conceptual.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:**\n- *Rationality: From AI to Zombies* (MIRI, 2015) — collected Sequences essays, ~2,000 pages\n- *Inadequate Equilibria: Where and How Civilizations Get Stuck* (MIRI, 2017) — essay on systemic epistemic failures\n- *If Anyone Builds It, Everyone Dies: Why Superhuman AI Would Kill Us All* (with Nate Soares; Little, Brown and Company, September 16, 2025) — New York Times bestseller\n\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- \"The Sequences\" (LessWrong, 2006–2009): hundreds of essays on Bayesian epistemology, cognitive bias, metaethics, and AI risk — foundational texts for the global rationalist and EA communities\n- \"Why I Think More Narrow Capabilities Are Dangerous\" (MIRI, ongoing)\n- Time op-ed calling for an international treaty to pause large-scale AI training (March 2023)\n\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Time magazine op-ed: \"Pausing AI Developments Isn't Enough. We Need to Shut It All Down\" (March 29, 2023) — among the most-read AI safety pieces ever published\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n\n**Views on AGI:**\nYudkowsky believes AGI — specifically, recursively self-improving superintelligent AI — represents the most dangerous technology ever developed by humans. He regards the path to superintelligence as likely to be rapid once a critical capability threshold is crossed (\"foom\"), leaving little time to course-correct. His 2025 book with Soares makes this case for a general audience.\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:**\nYudkowsky holds a P(doom) above 95–99%: he believes that absent a drastic, coordinated global halt to frontier AI development, misaligned superintelligence will kill all humans. His 2023 Time op-ed called not for a pause but for a permanent international shutdown of large-scale AI training runs, enforced with military action against non-compliant data centers if necessary. MIRI now operates on a policy track — attempting to persuade governments — while acknowledging this is \"very unlikely to save us\" but more plausible than all other remaining options. He has expressed skepticism about most proposed technical alignment solutions, including RLHF and Constitutional AI, as inadequate to the difficulty of the problem.\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:**\nYudkowsky's ethical framework is consequentialist but philosophically sophisticated — he engages seriously with metaethics and moral uncertainty. He argues that questions of AI consciousness and moral status, though important, are secondary to the question of whether any sufficiently advanced AI can be reliably aligned at all. He holds that humans do not yet possess the theoretical tools to solve alignment before systems capable of defeating oversight emerge.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:**\nYudkowsky advocates for international treaty-level prohibition on training runs above a certain compute threshold — analogous to nuclear non-proliferation. He has explicitly criticized the AI pause letter signed by Musk, LeCun, and others in 2023 as insufficient: \"a six-month pause is not what's needed.\" He regards most proposed governance frameworks, including EU AI Act style regulation, as inadequate to existential-level risk.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| Yann LeCun | Fundamental disagreement on whether current deep learning architectures can lead to dangerous AGI; LeCun dismisses extinction risk, Yudkowsky considers it near-certain |\n| Robin Hanson | The \"AI-Foom\" debate (2008): Yudkowsky argues for discontinuous intelligence explosion; Hanson argues for gradual, economic-paced growth |\n| Geoff Hinton, Sam Altman | Disagrees with those who believe safety and capability development can be pursued simultaneously at frontier labs |\n| Andrew Ng | On the seriousness and imminence of existential AI risk |\n| Most alignment researchers | Yudkowsky is significantly more pessimistic than median alignment researcher; regards most proposed solutions as irrelevant to the actual difficulty of the problem |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- \"The Danger of Artificial Stupidity\" (various venues)\n- Numerous podcast appearances including Lex Fridman Podcast (multiple episodes), 80,000 Hours, Machine Intelligence Research\n- Machine Intelligence Research Institute publications and YouTube channel\n\n**Podcasts:**\n- Lex Fridman Podcast (repeated appearances, reaching millions)\n- 80,000 Hours Podcast\n- Bankless Podcast\n- The AXRP Podcast\n\n**Social Media:**\n- X/Twitter: @ESYudkowsky — highly active, millions of impressions; prolific thread-poster on alignment, rationality, and epistemology\n\n**Online Courses:** None formally. The LessWrong Sequences function as an informal curriculum and are used as such in many rationality and EA communities.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Statements on Consciousness / Human Dignity / Meaning:**\nYudkowsky has written extensively on consciousness, considering it one of the hardest problems in philosophy. He takes the question of AI consciousness seriously as a matter of moral concern — if AI systems were conscious, their suffering would matter morally. He is deeply concerned with what makes minds valuable and argues that the destruction of humanity would represent an irreversible moral catastrophe because it would end the ongoing project of reflective intelligence and moral growth. He has written: \"The universe is 13.8 billion years old, and for all that time nothing more complex than a bacterium appeared anywhere we know of. And then in one single century, we get all this.\" The weight of that contingency drives his urgency.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:**\n- Bayesian epistemology as foundation for moral reasoning under uncertainty\n- Consequentialism, but philosophically cautious — engaged with moral uncertainty and metaethics\n- Explicit concern with preserving the \"future of value\" — an implicitly cosmological/teleological concern about the direction of intelligence in the universe\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:**\nYudkowsky engages deeply with philosophy of mind (consciousness, personal identity, free will) and decision theory. He has written on metaethics and the nature of moral facts. His concern for \"coherent extrapolated volition\" — what humans would want under ideal conditions — echoes, in secular form, natural law traditions that ground ethics in the perfection of rational nature. He does not engage directly with theological sources but his concern with preserving reflective, value-laden intelligence resonates with traditions that treat rational nature as sacred.\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **No formal academic credentials.** Yudkowsky has never attended college. This fuels dismissal from academic circles, even as his conceptual contributions are acknowledged in technical alignment literature.\n2. **Extreme P(doom) position.** His >99% probability of human extinction is an outlier even among AI safety researchers. Critics argue it reflects motivated reasoning and may deter productive engagement with tractable alignment work.\n3. **Advocacy for extreme policy.** His call to bomb non-compliant AI data centers was widely cited as illustrating the extreme conclusion his views lead to; critics say this damages the credibility of AI safety advocacy.\n4. **Cult-of-personality concerns around LessWrong/rationalist community.** Yudkowsky's Sequences established him as a quasi-guru in rationalist circles. Critics, including former community members, have raised concerns about insularity, epistemic overconfidence, and harmful group dynamics.\n5. **Infallibilism about his own models.** Several AI safety researchers, including those sympathetic to his concerns, have argued that Yudkowsky's certainty about his own doom models is epistemically problematic given how novel and uncertain the terrain is.\n6. **Predictions track record.** He predicted human-level AI would be achieved by 2010–2020 in earlier writings. The timeline has repeatedly shifted.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Yudkowsky has acknowledged that his high certainty estimates may be miscommunicated through the \"p(doom)\" framing, which he considers an \"antipattern.\" He has noted that expressing doom probabilities as single numbers obscures the conditional structure of his actual models.\n\n---\n",
  "zadeh": "# Research Profile: Lotfi Zadeh\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Lotfi Aliasker Zadeh\n**Born:** February 4, 1921, Baku, Azerbaijan (then Russian Empire, soon Soviet Union)\n**Died:** September 6, 2017, Berkeley, California (age 96)\n**Nationality:** American (naturalized); Azerbaijani-born, Iranian-raised\n**Education:**\n- B.S. in Electrical Engineering, University of Tehran, 1942\n- M.S. in Electrical Engineering, MIT, 1946\n- Ph.D. in Electrical Engineering, Columbia University, 1949\n- Dissertation advisor: John R. Ragazzini\n\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 1921–1931 | Childhood in Baku, Soviet Azerbaijan |\n| 1931–1942 | Tehran, Iran; attended Iranian school and American missionary school |\n| 1942–1944 | Faculty, University of Tehran (brief period) |\n| 1944–1949 | Graduate study, MIT then Columbia University, New York |\n| 1949–1959 | Assistant/Associate Professor, Columbia University |\n| 1959–1963 | Professor and Chair of Electrical Engineering, UC Berkeley |\n| 1963–1991 | Professor of Electrical Engineering and Computer Sciences (EECS), UC Berkeley |\n| 1965 | Published \"Fuzzy Sets\" — founding paper of fuzzy logic |\n| 1991–2017 | Professor Emeritus and Director, Berkeley Initiative in Soft Computing (BISC) |\n| 2017 | Died in Berkeley |\n\n**Major Awards:**\n- IEEE Medal of Honor, 1995 (highest IEEE honor)\n- Hamming Medal, IEEE, 1992\n- American Society of Mechanical Engineers Rufus Oldenburger Medal\n- 24 honorary doctorates from universities worldwide\n- Hilldale Award, University of Wisconsin\n- Frontiers of Knowledge Award in ICT, BBVA Foundation\n- Fellow: IEEE, ACM, AAAI, SIAM\n- Benjamin Franklin Medal in Electrical Engineering, 2012\n- BBVA Frontiers of Knowledge Award\n- Over 50 academic and engineering awards total\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:**\n- Fuzzy set theory and fuzzy logic\n- Possibility theory\n- Soft computing\n- Natural language processing and computing with words\n- Linear system theory (early career)\n- Approximate reasoning\n\n**Landmark Papers / Books:**\n| Title | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| \"Fuzzy Sets\" | 1965 | *Information and Control* 8(3):338–353; introduced fuzzy set theory — the founding paper of the field |\n| \"Fuzzy Algorithms\" | 1968 | Extended fuzzy sets to decision-making and control |\n| \"Outline of a New Approach to the Analysis of Complex Systems and Decision Processes\" | 1973 | Introduced linguistic variables |\n| \"Fuzzy Logic and Approximate Reasoning\" | 1975 | Extended the logical framework |\n| \"PRUF — a Meaning Representation Language for Natural Languages\" | 1978 | Applied fuzzy logic to natural language semantics |\n| \"Possibility Theory vs. Probability Theory\" | 1978 | Distinguished fuzzy uncertainty from probabilistic uncertainty |\n| \"Computing with Words\" | 1996 | Late-career synthesis; argued natural language itself should be a computing medium |\n| *Linear System Theory: The State Space Approach* (with Charles Desoer) | 1963 | Influential textbook in control theory |\n\n**Key Inventions & Contributions:**\n- Invented fuzzy set theory (1965): sets whose membership is a matter of degree (0 to 1) rather than binary (in or out)\n- Developed fuzzy logic: a formal system for reasoning under imprecision and vagueness\n- Introduced linguistic variables: variables whose values are words or phrases (\"hot,\" \"very hot,\" \"somewhat warm\") rather than numbers\n- Founded soft computing: the collection of fuzzy logic, neural networks, probabilistic reasoning, and evolutionary algorithms that tolerates imprecision to gain tractability\n- Pioneered \"computing with words\" — the idea that human concepts expressed in natural language can be the direct input to computational systems\n- Fuzzy control systems became foundational in industrial automation, consumer electronics, and embedded systems worldwide\n\n**Historical Significance:** Zadeh's 1965 paper was initially ridiculed by parts of the mathematical establishment — precise, binary logic seemed the proper foundation for rigorous systems. His claim that imprecision was not a defect to be eliminated but a fundamental feature of human cognition and natural language was radical. Within two decades, fuzzy logic had been adopted in Japanese consumer electronics (Hitachi washing machines, Sony cameras, subway systems in Sendai and elsewhere), industrial control systems across Europe, and medical devices globally. His work stands as one of the most practically impactful theoretical contributions in 20th-century engineering.\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books:**\n- *Linear System Theory: The State Space Approach* (1963, with Charles Desoer) — Standard graduate textbook in control theory; widely used before his pivot to fuzzy logic\n- *Fuzzy Sets and Applications: Selected Papers* (1987) — Collected major papers with commentary\n- *Fuzzy Sets, Fuzzy Logic, and Fuzzy Systems: Selected Papers* (1996, edited by George Klir and Bo Yuan) — Comprehensive collection of his foundational writings\n\n**Influential Papers:**\n- \"Fuzzy Sets\" (1965) — Among the most cited papers in mathematics and engineering\n- \"Fuzzy Logic and Approximate Reasoning\" (1975)\n- \"A Theory of Approximate Reasoning\" (1979)\n- \"Computing with Words — Principal Concepts and Ideas\" (1996)\n- Over 250 technical papers total\n\n**Popular / General Works:**\n- Numerous interviews and public lectures on fuzzy logic and human reasoning; accessible explanations of fuzzy systems in engineering and consumer products\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AI and Machine Intelligence:** Zadeh argued that classical, binary AI systems were fundamentally limited in their ability to deal with the real world because the real world is irreducibly imprecise. Human reasoning, natural language, and common sense all operate with degrees of truth, partial membership, and contextual vagueness — not the clean true/false of Boolean logic. Fuzzy logic was his attempt to give machines a formal basis for the kind of approximate reasoning humans perform naturally. He was neither a utopian nor a dystopian about AI; he was a pragmatist who thought the field was using the wrong mathematical foundations.\n\n**Views on Humanity and Technology:** His central epistemological claim was that human intelligence is characterized by remarkable tolerance for imprecision. We navigate the world not with precise measurements but with vague, contextual, linguistic categories — \"large,\" \"warm,\" \"tall,\" \"soon.\" This is not a cognitive limitation; it is an adaptive feature. Technology that cannot handle this imprecision will always be brittle in the face of real-world complexity. He described himself as \"mathematically oriented\" but deeply concerned with the humanistic dimensions of engineering — building systems that work with human concepts rather than forcing humans to reduce their concepts to machine-compatible precision.\n\n**Ethical Concerns They Raised:**\n- Raised implicit concerns about AI brittleness: systems that require precise inputs will fail unpredictably when given the vague, contextual data of real human environments\n- His work on possibility theory distinguished between the uncertainty of probability (randomness) and the uncertainty of vagueness (inherent imprecision) — with implications for how we reason about risk and safety\n- Computing with words carried implications for natural language processing and for the design of AI systems that can genuinely understand human intent rather than requiring humans to speak machine language\n\n**Known Debates:** His most famous opponent was the probabilist establishment, which argued that Bayesian probability theory could handle all forms of uncertainty without needing fuzzy sets. Philosophers of logic also challenged whether \"degrees of truth\" were coherent. The debate between fuzzy logic and probabilistic AI was fierce in the 1970s–1990s and never fully resolved; modern AI uses both.\n\n---\n\n## Values\n\n**Views on Mind, Consciousness, and Human Uniqueness:** Zadeh believed the human mind's most distinctive feature is its extraordinary capacity for approximate reasoning — working effectively with vague, incomplete, and contradictory information. This was not a limitation to be overcome by better logic but a sophisticated adaptive capacity that had co-evolved with natural language over millennia. He saw consciousness as inherently resistant to precise formal description — which was, of course, itself a fuzzy concept. His work implies that any adequate model of human cognition must incorporate graded, contextual, linguistically structured reasoning rather than crisp logical calculus.\n\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Pragmatic and cross-cultural. His philosophical sensibility was shaped by his multicultural biography — Azerbaijani-Iranian-Soviet-American — and his own career as someone who successfully integrated Eastern tolerance for vagueness and ambiguity with Western mathematical rigor. He invoked no explicit ethical tradition but embodied an epistemological pluralism: there is more than one valid way to know, more than one valid way to reason, and intolerance for imprecision is itself a form of epistemic injustice.\n\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** His 1965 paper explicitly cited the imprecision of ordinary language and the inadequacy of crisp categories for modeling human concepts — a concern shared by analytic philosophy of language (Wittgenstein, Austin) and by classical Muslim and Jewish epistemologies, which have long distinguished between categorical knowledge and practical wisdom. Whether Zadeh was aware of these resonances is uncertain, but his work belongs in a long tradition of thinkers who insist that truth comes in degrees and that the demand for precision can destroy understanding.\n\n---\n",
  "zuck": "# Research Profile: Mark Zuckerberg\n### Catholics in Tech Podcast\n\n---\n\n## Identity & Background\n**Full Name:** Mark Elliot Zuckerberg **Born:** May 14, 1984, White Plains, New York **Nationality:** American\n**Education:** Phillips Exeter Academy (high school); Harvard University — studied psychology and computer science, dropped out in 2004; no earned degree\n**Current Role:** Co-founder, Chairman, and CEO, Meta Platforms, Inc.\n**Career Timeline:**\n| Years | Role / Organization |\n|---|---|\n| 2004 | Co-founded TheFacebook (later Facebook) out of Harvard dorm room with Eduardo Saverin, Dustin Moskovitz, Andrew McCollum, and Chris Hughes |\n| 2004–present | CEO and Chairman, Facebook / Meta Platforms |\n| 2012 | Facebook IPO; company goes public at $16B valuation |\n| 2021 | Rebranded Facebook Inc. to Meta Platforms; announced Metaverse pivot |\n| 2023–present | Aggressive pivot to AI; Llama model series; Meta AI assistant launch |\n| 2025 | Founded Meta Superintelligence Labs; $14.3B investment in Scale AI |\n\n**Major Awards:** Time Person of the Year (2010); named in TIME100 multiple years; his personal net worth exceeded $200B at peak (2025); named Bloomberg Businessperson of the Decade (informal recognition) for Facebook's first decade\n\n---\n\n## Research & Technical Contributions\n**Primary Research Areas:** Not a primary researcher; product architect and CEO. Technical background in software development (wrote early versions of Facebook in PHP/C++). Meta's AI research arm (FAIR — Fundamental AI Research) is one of the world's most productive academic-style AI labs.\n**Landmark Papers / Products:**\n| Title / Product | Year | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| Facebook social graph | 2004 | Fundamental data structure enabling social network effects at scale |\n| Instagram acquisition | 2012 | $1B acquisition; became Meta's most profitable product by 2020 |\n| WhatsApp acquisition | 2014 | $19B acquisition; world's largest messaging platform |\n| Llama 1 | 2023 | Meta's first major open-source large language model |\n| Llama 2 | 2023 | Open-source LLM rivaling proprietary models; downloaded millions of times |\n| Llama 3 (70B, 405B) | 2024 | Matched or outperformed leading closed-source models on multiple benchmarks |\n| Meta AI (assistant) | 2023–2024 | AI assistant integrated across WhatsApp, Instagram, Facebook, Messenger |\n| Meta Superintelligence Labs | 2025 | Consolidated AGI effort; $14.3B investment in Scale AI |\n\n**Key Inventions & Architectures:** Zuckerberg did not invent FAIR's research outputs, but he made the strategic decision to publish them openly. The Llama series has reshaped the open-source AI ecosystem. Meta's AI infrastructure (Grand Teton servers, the MTIA chip) reflects significant engineering investment.\n**Datasets / Benchmarks:** None directly authored; FAIR and Meta teams have contributed benchmark datasets and evaluation frameworks\n\n---\n\n## Published Works\n**Books / Major Monographs:** None authored\n**Influential Essays & Manifestos:**\n- *\"Open Source AI Is the Path Forward\"* (Meta blog, July 2024) — argued forcefully for open-source AI as the ethical, competitive, and technically superior approach; became a widely cited document in the AI policy debate\n- Annual Facebook Founder's Letter (published on Facebook/Meta platform, various years) — defines Zuckerberg's current stated mission\n- *\"Building Global Community\"* (Facebook post, February 2017) — 5,700-word manifesto articulating Facebook's civic ambitions; notable for invoking civic infrastructure, emotional support, and community as the platform's goals\n**Popular Articles:**\n- Numerous interviews with The Verge, Bloomberg, and Lex Fridman where he discusses AI strategy at length\n\n---\n\n## Public Positions & Philosophy\n**Views on AGI:** Zuckerberg declared in mid-2025 that achieving \"superintelligence\" — AI far beyond human level — is \"now in sight.\" He founded Meta Superintelligence Labs in June 2025. He does not use a precise AGI definition but frames it as AI with \"reasoning and intuition\" capabilities exceeding humans. He has acknowledged that if superintelligence arrives, he may not open-source it: \"If at some point there's some qualitative change in what the thing is capable of, and we feel like it's not responsible to open source it, then we won't.\"\n\n**Views on AI Safety & Risk:** Zuckerberg has positioned himself against what he calls excessive \"safetyism\" — the precautionary approach he associates with OpenAI and Anthropic. He argues that open-source AI is inherently safer because it distributes power and invites external scrutiny rather than concentrating it in a few labs. He has noted, pointedly, that \"companies with the largest leads in AI seem to push for guardrails most aggressively — I'm sure some of them are legitimately concerned about safety, but it's a hell of a thing how much it lines up with their strategy.\"\n\n**Views on AI Ethics:** Zuckerberg's ethical framework for AI is pragmatic and democratizing: open-source models empower governments, researchers, small businesses, and developers who would otherwise be dependent on a handful of closed-source providers. He frames closed AI as a power concentration risk. At the same time, Meta's advertising business model and its history of data misuse complicate any claim that Meta is acting purely in the public interest.\n\n**Views on Regulation & Policy:** Zuckerberg is skeptical of AI regulation that he believes would entrench incumbents. He has lobbied against EU AI Act provisions affecting open-source models. He supports some federal guardrails but resists requirements that would force Meta to restrict Llama distribution. In 2025, he pivoted toward a closer relationship with the Trump administration — attending the inauguration, ending Meta's DEI programs, and abandoning its independent oversight board — which critics described as regulatory capture.\n\n**Known Disagreements:**\n| Opponent | Issue |\n|---|---|\n| OpenAI / Sam Altman | Philosophical disagreement over open vs. closed AI; strategic competition |\n| Anthropic | Frames Anthropic's safety posture as market capture strategy |\n| EU regulators | Meta restricted Llama distribution in Europe due to AI Act compliance uncertainty; Zuckerberg blamed EU overreach |\n| US Congress | Testified multiple times; Cambridge Analytica fallout; ongoing tension over platform liability |\n\n---\n\n## Media & Outreach\n**Notable Talks:**\n- Lex Fridman Podcast multiple appearances (2023, 2024) — detailed AI strategy and personal interests\n- Meta Connect annual conferences — product keynotes\n- US Congressional testimony (2018, 2021, multiple appearances)\n- Joe Rogan Experience — 2024 appearance, wide-ranging personal and political topics\n**Podcasts:** Lex Fridman Podcast; Joe Rogan Experience; various Bloomberg and tech media\n**Social Media:** Active on Facebook (Meta's own platform), Instagram, and Threads; uses them for personal announcements and policy statements\n**Online Courses:** None\n\n---\n\n## Values\n**Ethical Frameworks:** Pragmatic humanism; \"people are fundamentally good\" moral baseline; Jewish ethical inheritance (Tikkun Olam — repairing the world — though not invoked explicitly in public AI discussion); democratizing access as a moral imperative\n**Engagement with Theology or Humanities:** Not formally documented; studied psychology at Harvard; his framing of human connection draws on social psychology more than theology; recent Jewish practice is cultural and personal rather than theologically systematic\n\n---\n\n## Controversy & Criticism\n1. **Cambridge Analytica (2018):** Data from up to 87 million Facebook users was accessed without consent and used for political targeting by Cambridge Analytica, which worked on Trump's 2016 campaign. The FTC fined Facebook $5 billion — the largest privacy fine in history to that point. An $8 billion investor class action related to this began trial in July 2025, with Zuckerberg taking the stand personally.\n2. **2020 US Election and January 6th:** Facebook's algorithms were documented to amplify divisive content. Internal research (\"Facebook Files,\" published 2021) showed Meta knew its platforms caused harm and did not act. Zuckerberg gave $419 million to fund election administration through the Center for Tech and Civic Life, which Republicans attacked as partisan influence.\n3. **Meta Oversight Board dissolution / DEI rollback (2025):** Zuckerberg dissolved Meta's independent content oversight board and rolled back DEI programs ahead of the Trump inauguration, widely interpreted as political accommodation to avoid regulatory action by the new administration.\n4. **Employee keylogging:** A 2024 report alleged Meta monitored employee keystrokes and communications; an employee publicly attacked Zuckerberg for the practice.\n5. **Instagram and children's mental health:** The Facebook Files included internal research showing Instagram was harmful to teenage girls' body image and mental health. Meta suppressed publication. Multiple state attorneys general have sued.\n6. **Metaverse bet:** Meta spent approximately $50 billion on the Metaverse between 2021 and 2023, destroying significant shareholder value. The pivot to AI in 2023 was in part a response to investor fury.\n\n**Self-Acknowledged Limitations:** Zuckerberg acknowledged in 2018 Congressional testimony that Facebook did not do enough to prevent misuse of the platform. He has said that he \"idealized\" free expression in the platform's early years without adequately accounting for its weaponization. He has spoken about how fatherhood changed his priorities and moral seriousness.\n\n---\n"
};
